<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2570 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-SPURS-HNS &LR;      05-19 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SPURS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ Get ready.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's the unspoken warning from the Lakers' locker room as they
get ready to rumble with the Spurs tonight in Game 2 of the Western
Conference semifinals at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   After all, if the Lake Show can be pre-empted by a night of live
tag-team wrestling, as it was Monday, then the Spurs should brace
themselves for the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs manhandled the Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal in San
Antonio's 87-81 victory in Game 1, and O'Neal isn't happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   So expect the sequel to be different when the best-of-seven
series resumes.
</P>
<P>
   Who are these new-look Spurs, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The league's wallflowers looked more like clinging vines Monday,
throwing O'Neal into the mother of all funks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to guard Shaq is to break the rules that the NBA
is supposed to enforce,'' O'Neal said. ``But they never enforce
them, which is fine. I've been getting played like that for seven
years. But nobody's going to break me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Spurs didn't try. With David Robinson, Tim Duncan,
Will Perdue and Malik Rose tag-teaming O'Neal into submission, or
at least as close as teams come to subduing the 7-1, 335-pound
center, the slaps on the big man's arms were so frequent it sounded
like applause.
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy worked because O'Neal was held _ and he'll tell
you that's the word _ to 21 points, far below the 29.5-point
average he had in four games against the Rockets in the opening
round.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Shaq Daddy'' intends to show the Spurs just who their
daddy is tonight, especially because O'Neal thinks the officials
didn't give him his due Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew what their plan was when I get it down low _ foul.
So?'' said O'Neal of the Spurs' tactics. ``But it didn't work out
like that (referees calling fouls). I think that's going to be more
to my favor because that's my style of ball.''
</P>
<P>
   So expect tonight to be something along the lines of ``Daddy
Dearest,'' with O'Neal meting out the punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson didn't see how the Lakers could get O'Neal any more
involved than he was Monday night, when he attempted 19 field goals
(making six) and 14 free throws (making nine).
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll adjust some,'' Robinson said. ``They're definitely
going to get some other players involved. It's hard to say. Shaq
posted up really hard in that game. I thought he was very
aggressive, and I thought that he came down and got low-post
position and they went to him a lot. I don't know what their
philosophy (will be in Game 2), but they definitely went to Shaq
(Monday).''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was irritated that referees Steve Javie, Ron Garretson
and Joe DeRosa didn't go to him more often, as in sending him to
the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal stalked Javie after the game spewing his gripes (almost
everyone's story) or holding his tongue (O'Neal's version).
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get a chance to say anything to him,'' O'Neal said.
``I didn't have to say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Besides, the Lakers spent most of Tuesday saying it
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see on the tapes where Shaq is getting fouled, but
they (the referees) didn't do anything about it,'' said the Lakers'
Robert Horry. ``Those two (Robinson and Duncan) are the `Golden
Boys,' though.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Spurs are going to get physical, the Lakers _ and
O'Neal in particular _ will respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to have to play (the same way),'' O'Neal said.
``Hopefully they (the refs) will let both teams play physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (Monday's game) was not physical. Where I've been,
they're more physical. That's not physical at all. It was just
another day at the office for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is funny hearing the Lakers complain about rough play,
because guys like O'Neal, J.R. Reid and Derek Harper are among the
more physical players at their positions. But they discovered the
Spurs can play that way, too.
</P>
<P>
   And so did the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can play physical ball,'' Mario Elie said. ``We can get up
and play defense against the best of them. Against Shaq (Monday),
we threw everything but the kitchen sink at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect the kitchen sink to be next.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it goes on, I think it will get more physical,'' Robinson
said. ``That's just the nature of the playoffs, especially as you
get to Games 4, 5, 6 and 7. That (more physical play) is what is
going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you still have to play basketball. You have to play. The
defense has to be good, the rotations have to be good, and
offensively we're going to have to execute. That first game is
always that feeling-out game. You have to get a feel for what
they're going to do and what you want to do. We saw some good
things that worked, so we're going to try and improve upon those.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game plan was to make him work a little bit, and then when
he puts it on the floor, to try and help out. But he has good
quickness and he makes some pretty good, quick moves into the
middle and toward the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were more fortunate than anything else. Like I
said, it's just a real feeling-out process right now. We're trying
to get a feel for what we want to do, and (Monday) wasn't exactly
how it's going to end up, but we saw some good things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
