<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREWERS DEFEAT METS, 4-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Armando Benitez was not going to give in and throw
his second-best pitch. He surely remembered the devastating home
run Marquis Grissom had hit off him in the 1997 American League
Championship Series, when Benitez was with Baltimore and Grissom
was with Cleveland, and Grissom hit a slider for a home run to win
Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, the stakes were not nearly so high, and the
teams were different. But Benitez, now a New York Mets reliever,
was facing Grissom, a Milwaukee Brewer, with a game on the line.
And if Grissom was going to beat him this time, he was going to
have to hit a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Grissom did, hammering a 95-mile-an-hour fastball over the fence
in left field for a three-run home run with two out in the eighth
inning. It enabled the Brewers to rally for a 4-2 victory over the
Mets at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   This home run and third straight loss did not cost the Mets
(21-18) a pennant, but they were costly nonetheless. Before Dennis
Cook (5-1) had come on to begin the eighth with a 2-1 lead, Rick
Reed had turned in a beleaguered rotation's strongest starting
performance in 10 days. In the process, Reed had been exonerated of
the assertion by Milwaukee Manager Phil Garner and right fielder
Jeromy Burnitz that he was doctoring the ball.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Reed's best outing of the season _ one run in seven
innings _ went for naught.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud's run-scoring single in the fifth was still holding
up when the turnaround came. Brian Banks beat out a bunt single to
open the eighth off Cook. Burnitz followed by singling up the
middle just past a diving Edgardo Alfonzo, giving the Brewers men
on first and third and nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine called for Benitez, who had struck out
29 batters in 19 innings. And the Mets badly needed a strikeout.
Benitez responded with not one, but two, as he mixed up his pitches
and fanned both Jeff Cirillo and Dave Nilsson on three pitches
each. But then came Grissom's turn. Benitez threw five pitches, all
fastballs. And on a 3-1 count, Grissom _ who nearly had to be
removed from the game after crashing into the center field fence on
Alfonzo's fifth-inning double _ blasted the game-winning home run,
his third of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Since they ran off six straight victories from April 28 to May
3, the Mets have lost 9 of 13 games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
