<HEADER>
A2576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT &LR;      05-19 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX DEFEAT YANKEES, 6-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Before returning as the New York Yankees' manager on
Tuesday, Joe Torre missed his time in the dugout. He missed hearing
the voices of his players, watching their reactions closely,
analyzing their body language, all of those ways a manager measures
his team.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre had no idea that on his first night back, the Yankees
would provide enough body language to fill a semester's worth of
Psychology 101 _ from David Cone's self-loathing grimace to Scott
Brosius' monumental bat slam to Jorge Posada's woe-is-me amble.
Stranding 15 runners in a 6-3 loss to Pedro Martinez and the Boston
Red Sox would cause contortions in any player, or principal owner.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting next to the Yankees' dugout, George Steinbrenner waved
his arms disgustedly after the slumping Chuck Knoblauch committed
his seventh error.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who fell half a game behind Boston in the American
League East, have scored 11 runs in their last 54 innings, and on
Tuesday night, they were 3 for 19 with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle innings, Torre lowered his cap so that his eyes
were almost completely hidden and leaned his head back against the
dugout wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very calm,'' he said later, plaintively. ``I wish the
result was better.''
</P>
<P>
   In losing for the sixth time in their last seven games, the
Yankees failed to capitalize on an evening when Martinez wasn't
dominating. The Boston right-hander's stuff had been electric
recently; he'd thrown nasty fastballs, changeups, curveballs, all
for strikes. But against the Yankees, he struggled to command his
curve, and his changeup sometimes drifted over the middle of the
plate. Martinez allowed 10 hits and 4 walks in his 7 innings, or 5
more base runners than he had allowed in any of his first 8 starts.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees could not finish him off. First and third, two
out in the first inning: No runs. Lead-off double in the second: No
runs. Bases loaded, one out, one run in during the fifth: No more
runs. Lead-off single in the sixth: No runs. Lead-off double in the
seventh: No runs. ``We had our hits,'' said Brosius, ``but boy,
when there were runners on base, he just seemed to take it to
another level.''
</P>
<P>
   He struck out 11, nine of those with runners in scoring
position. When Brosius struck out to close the seventh, he turned
and flung down his bat.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did muster a 2-0 lead through the top of the fifth
inning, with Cone breezing. But when Martinez labored through a
36-pitch inning in the fifth, Cone had to wait and watch and wait,
and after returning to the mound, he just didn't have the same
quality of breaking ball or split-fingered fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanley led off by slamming a hanging slider into the left
field screen. It was this hit, Cone said, that rattled him, turning
him into a tentative pitcher. Reggie Jefferson singled home the
tying run in the same inning. Nomar Garciaparra blasted a double
off the center field wall to start the sixth, and with one out,
Cone threw a splitter that bounced off the glove of Posada, a wild
pitch; Garciaparra raced home with the go-ahead run. Cone scowled,
blaming himself, Posada hung his head and blamed himself, and Torre
saw it all.
</P>
<P>
   Torre surprised everyone other than his wife, Ali Torre, with
his decision to return on Tuesday. They went to dinner Monday
evening and discussed the possibilities, how strong he's felt
recently. ``Are you ready to do it?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I am,'' he answered directly, and on Tuesday morning, he
called the interim manager Don Zimmer at 8 a.m. and asked his own
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you ready to do the job we hired you to do?'' Torre
queried. Zimmer immediately understood the implication of what
Torre was saying, two months to the day after undergoing surgery
for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Torre flew here with Steinbrenner, and after he arrived at the
ball park and surprised his players, Derek Jeter, the Yankees'
shortstop, plopped down in his office grinning and called him Mr.
Torre; others shook his hand. Torre, who met with his stunned
players in March to tell them about his forthcoming operation,
gathered them again on Tuesday, under far different circumstances,
telling them he was back for good, jokingly mentioning the movie
``Halloween 3'' _ ``I'm back.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre is not fully recovered. When asked on Tuesday if he will
undergo radiation for his cancer, Torre declined to be specific,
saying only that he will continue to be treated and that the
particulars are a private matter, so long as it does not cause him
to leave the team.
</P>
<P>
   Torre added that he did not anticipate missing any games as he
underwent further tests and treatment. He repeated that he felt
great, that he'd been ``champing at the bit'' to manage the Yankees
again. ``This is what I want,'' Torre said. ``I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were 21-15 (.538) under Zimmer, Torre's hand-picked
replacement. It appears the 68-year-old Zimmer will stay with the
team as Torre's bench coach, rather than return to New York to rest
his aching knees. ``I'm just glad he's back,'' said Zimmer. ``I'm
just tickled to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre came out of his office and sat next to Zimmer, speaking
quietly into his left ear, placing his arm on Zimmer's shoulder.
When Torre met with the players, he decided against thanking Zimmer
in front of them; he knew Zimmer would break down.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, who scrapped publicly with Zimmer over Hideki
Irabu at the end of spring training and barely spoke to his interim
manager since, wouldn't speak directly of Zimmer's performance.
``I'm not in a position to sit here and judge these guys,''
Steinbrenner said. ``He's got them in first place, doesn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   Torre had no intention of taking the lineup card to the field
before Tuesdasy night's game; rather, he wanted the hitting coach
Chris Chambliss go to the plate, as he usually does.
</P>
<P>
   But Zimmer suggested to Torre that he do so, and Torre joined
the umpires at home plate. Fans at Fenway Park stood and applauded,
and kept on cheering, for perhaps two minutes, and Torre raised his
cap. ``Welcome back,'' the giant screen above center field read.
</P>
<P>
   And then Torre went about the business of analyzing the body
language of a slumping, frustrated team. As Torre spoke to
reporters and the players ate silently after the loss, Steinbrenner
stood against a wall stiffly, his mouth turned downward. Welcome
back, indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
