<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-AFTERMATH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING AT AFFLUENT HIGH SCHOOL EXPOSES VULNERABILITY OF CAMPUSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Parents and students at Palisades High School said
Tuesday they thought their ocean-view campus in an affluent
neighborhood was safe from violence that is plaguing schools
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Now they say they know better, after a coach and student were
wounded in a drive-by shooting Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it happens here you realize there's no safe place to
be,'' said Sandy Mizrahi, whose daughters attend the school, which
draws children from across Los Angeles to one of the nation's most
wealthy communities. ``We're so sequestered here on this oasis.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the Colorado high school massacre, the shooting Monday
underscored for many students and parents the vulnerability of all
campuses _ even one of the safest in the Los Angeles Unified School
District by any measure.
</P>
<P>
   The drive-by attack occurred when a carload of young men fired
several times into a group of students, grazing the head football
coach in the calf and hitting a teen-ager in the thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Vontray Gardner, 18, was treated and released from Santa
Monica-UCLA Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, 62-year-old Ron Price, returned to the math, science
and technology magnet school Tuesday and tried to calm jittery
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about anyone shooting at us,'' said Price, a
teacher and coach for 33 years. ``I know what gang activity is all
about. There's just not gang activity around here.''
</P>
<P>
   While counselors talked with students and staff, detectives and
campus police were trying to determine whether the shooting was
fueled by gang rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting conflicting reports,'' said Detective Ron
Phillips of the Los Angeles Police Department's West Los Angeles
Division. ``We don't know the whole story.''
</P>
<P>
   Four suspects, including an adult, two Palisades High students
and a student from another school, were arrested on suspicion of
assault with a deadly weapon, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Pearce, 20, of South Central Los Angeles, is scheduled
to be arraigned today, Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   The three others _ two 15-year-olds and a 16-year-old _ were not
identified by police because of their ages. They were booked and
released to their parents, pending a juvenile court date.
</P>
<P>
   School officials told detectives they had heard the shooting
resulted from an argument over a girl.
</P>
<P>
   Palisades High School administrators plan to beef up security
throughout the week, said Linda Hosford, the acting principal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly are a quiet campus. We certainly are a safe
campus. But we have to realize that we are on the same planet and
in the same society and these things can happen,'' Hosford said.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting is scheduled for parents at 7 p.m. Monday to address
their concerns, Hosford said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Carrillo, a freshman who lives in Koreatown, said he
decided to attend Palisades High to get away from the violence that
infests schools in his own neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when something like this happens here, you're shocked,''
Carrillo said in between classes.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack across the street from the school at 15777
Bowdoin St., students said they heard young men yell that they were
part of the ``Jamaican Mafia,'' a gang whose members speak with
Jamaican accents.
</P>
<P>
   Police said witnesses gave them the account, but they have no
evidence to the claim.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred during the last class of the day as about
three dozen students who do not have a sixth period waited for a
ride home, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Price noticed people gathering near a green car and went to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone started running. I started to run also,'' Price said.
``I ducked behind the handball court out of the line of fire.''
</P>
<P>
   As he hid, he recalled hearing a ``pop, pop, pop'' noise and
felt a sting below his calf, he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
