<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY DEPARTMENT CONTRACTORS SPENT $250 MILLION ON BUSINESS TRIPS
IN '98 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Private contractors for the Department of Energy
crisscrossed America and the world last year on more than 210,000
taxpayer-financed business trips that critics say are getting way
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The $250 million in travel spending included a $300 hotel room
and a $1,600 airline ticket that could have been bought for a
fourth of that amount, says a recent audit by the General
Accounting Office.
</P>
<P>
   Spending by the 34 contractors, including two from Kansas City,
was up $27 million from two years earlier despite an Energy
Department goal to cut spending by $30 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unconscionable; it's unacceptable,'' said Rep. Ron
Packard, a California Republican. ``They think there's an unending
supply of money. There isn't. This simply takes money away from
projects and research and programs that are crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   The department took similar heat several years ago after
then-Secretary Hazel O'Leary spent $4.58 million on 16 overseas
trips from 1993 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may have permeated the entire agency because we now see
those same problems widespread,'' said Packard, chairman of the
House Appropriations Subcommittee on Energy and Water Development,
which requested the audit.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the audit, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson wrote
a letter to his staff April 14 telling it to ``act quickly and
decisively'' to reduce contractor trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``In times of limited budgets and electronic alternatives to
travel, we cannot continue such practices,'' Richardson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The audit did point out that although the department was not
meeting its contractor travel cost reduction goals, it had exceeded
goals for cutting travel of its own employees. Its costs have
dropped by 32 percent, or about $15 million, since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The travel by private contractors is part of their duties
managing plants and supplying materials to the department. Travel
and all costs are supposed to be monitored by the department.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, O'Leary announced a downsizing plan. One goal was to
cut contractor travel costs of $261 million in 1995 by $30 million
annually. The first year, costs dropped to $222 million but then
increased to $240 million the next year and to $249 million last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to have gone back to the old ways, and I think that
it's because there are no consistent guidelines,'' Packard said.
</P>
<P>
   The rising costs have come despite a 33 percent decline in
contractor employees since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Contractors said inflation, especially in airfares, partly
accounts for the recent rise in travel spending. Another factor is
more foreign travel, especially to Russia, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City companies operate two Energy Department plants.
Midwest Research Institute oversees the National Renewable Energy
Laboratory in Colorado. In Kansas City, AlliedSignal Federal
Manufacturing and Technologies makes non-nuclear energy components.
</P>
<P>
   Midwest Research Institute spent $4.9 million on travel last
year, up from $4.8 million in 1996. AlliedSignal spent $5.4
million, up from $4.7 million 1996. Both companies say they are
aiming to cut costs. Midwest Research Institute set a goal of $4.4
million this year.
</P>
<P>
   At AlliedSignal, travel spending has dropped this year, a
spokeswoman said. It was down by about 15 percent for February and
March, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The 34 energy contractors took 213,213 trips by air, road and
rail in the fiscal year that ended Sept. 30, 1998. About 96 percent
were domestic and about 11 percent were from contractor sites to
Washington, the audit found.
</P>
<P>
   Some contractors said many Washington trips are at the request
of the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want reports, they want presentation, they want
interaction,'' said David Schwoegler, spokesman for the Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory, operated by the University of
California for the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   Some travel spending at Lawrence Livermore was specifically
cited in the report as excessive, including $303 for a hotel room
in Monterey, Calif., and $1,602 for an airline ticket that another
person got for $414.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Lawrence Livermore employees' hotel rooms are
obtained at discounted rates, and 75 percent of airline tickets are
bought as advance fare purchases, Schwoegler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report picks out the most flagrant expenses,'' Schwoegler
said. ``It's not like we're spending flagrantly.''
</P>
<P>
   The audit is especially critical of the preference some
contractors have to buy refundable airline tickets, which are the
most expensive. Although the tickets can be refunded or changed at
no cost, nonrefundable tickets can be much cheaper and usually can
be changed by paying a $75 fee to the airline.
</P>
<P>
   Among other findings:
</P>
<P>
   Expenses were paid for some employees at Los Alamos, N.M., to
make trips related to obtaining master's degrees. In all, 24
employees made 380 trips to the University of New Mexico, about 100
miles from Los Alamos. The Energy Department later said the trips
were not justified.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent of all trips from 1996 to 1998 were to
conferences that cost $59 million. One trip alone, to a conference
in Vancouver, British Columbia, was attended by 520 contractor
employees at a cost of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, about 800 contractor employees were assigned to
Washington at a cost of $76 million in salary, living allowance and
relocation costs. That number was excessive, the department found,
and the number has been cut by almost 300.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have problems,'' said Michael L. Telson, chief
financial officer for the department. ``But when you look at the
historical sweep, we are really making progress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
