<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DEVIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS GROUND INTO FIVE DOUBLE PLAYS, FALL TO DEVIL RAYS
</HEADLINE>
 RAYS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Twenty-two of the Texas Rangers' 43 batters
reached safely.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' lineup collected 14 hits, and designated hitter
Rafael Palmeiro drove in four runs. Right-hander Mike Morgan
pitched into the sixth inning, and the bullpen provided 3 2/3
scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   And it all went for naught.
</P>
<P>
   The double-play ground ball remains the pitcher's best friend
and the Rangers' worst enemy. Tuesday night's 5-4 loss to the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays at The Ballpark in Arlington only reinforced that
fact.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who entered yesterday's games having grounded into
a major-league-worst 41 double plays, padded their total with a
season-high five.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hit into a lot of double plays this year,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``And tonight was the most noticeable of
any game we've had.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Rangers stranded 13 runners _ nine in scoring
position _ in the one-run loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't control the ball after you hit it,'' said catcher
Ivan Rodriguez, who grounded into his American League-high 10th and
11th double plays. ``If it goes right at them, it's going to be a
double play. There's nothing you can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing except watch as the double play sucks the life from an
inning once filled with potential.
</P>
<P>
   Devil Rays right-hander Rolando Arrojo (2-4) induced first-,
third- and fifth-inning double-play ground balls from Rodriguez,
Rusty Greer and Lee Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-inning ground ball from Stevens kept the Rangers from
a potential big inning after Palmeiro's two-run single. Palmeiro
advanced 90 feet after Todd Zeile drew a walk, and the Devil Rays'
4-3 lead appeared in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, though, bounced into a 6-4-3 double play, and Arrojo
retired Roberto Kelly on strikes to strand Palmeiro at third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``In situations when there are runners on, I like to throw the
two-seam sinker and try to keep the ball low, and hope they hit it
on the ground,'' Arrojo said.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Esteban Yan slammed the door shut when the Rangers
threatened in the seventh inning. The Rangers scored once off
left-hander Scott Aldred, who failed to retire any of the three
batters he faced, but Yan induced a double-play ground ball from
Zeile to preserve the Devil Rays' 5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa closer Roberto Hernandez, who pitched a scoreless ninth
inning for his 14th save, also escaped trouble by inducing the
fifth and final double-play ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   Greer opened the inning with a single, but Rodriguez bounced
into his second double play of the night. It became more painful
after Palmeiro and Zeile delivered consecutive two-out singles.
Stevens drew a walk to load the bases, but Kelly popped Hernandez's
first pitch to the mound to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any one reason,'' Oates said of the
Rangers' penchant for double-play ground balls. ``I think at times
we swing at pitchers' pitches and press with runners in scoring
position. We've also got about five guys in the lineup who don't
run very well.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
