A2592 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-KAN-KAN &LR;      05-19 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS PROSPERITY BYPASSING 9 MILLION U.S. CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ While many American families cheer the Dow
and move up to bigger homes and nicer cars, more than 9 million
children are being left behind, according to a national report
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Kids Count report says that 13 percent of the country's
children, one in seven, are at serious risk because they are
growing up in homes where parents are poor and jobless and lack a
high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Ten percent of Missouri children fall into that ``high risk''
category. In Kansas, the rate is 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pocket of kids who will face tough odds the rest of
their lives. These are children being sidestepped by the booming
economy,'' Gary Brunk, executive director of Kansas Action for
Children, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Nelson, president of the Annie E. Casey Foundation, the
Baltimore-based child advocacy group that produces Kids Count, said
that although success is never guaranteed for anyone, America must
do more to see that more children have an honest chance to achieve
it.
</P>
<P>
   Kids Count used six criteria to determine these ``high-risk''
children: The head of household is a high school dropout; the
children have no health insurance; the family lives in poverty;
only one parent lives in the home; no parent works full time; or
the family receives welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   A child whose family meets four of the six factors was deemed
``high-risk.'' Statistics show that those household conditions
raise the likelihood that young people will drop out of school,
become teen parents or abuse drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Utah had the lowest rate of high-risk children, 5 percent.
Louisiana, at 22 percent, had the highest.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Berta Sailer, director of St. Vincent's child-care center
in Kansas City, sees some of Kansas City's share every day at 6
a.m. when she opens the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 200 children at St. Vincent's would be considered
``high risk,'' Sailer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no economic boom around here,'' she said. ``I can get
in a car and travel 10 minutes and see more disparity than if I'd
flown in a plane for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what a luxury is to our families? Utilities _ and
some of them don't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   And contrary to what she believes to be a wide perception about
impoverished families, most of her parents have jobs. But it's no
longer true that vocational training and a full-time job are a
ticket to a better life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting into the work force doesn't mean getting out of
poverty,'' Sailer said. ``Sometimes, it's only enough to keep you
from sliding back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill O'Hare, national Kids Count coordinator, said the study's
``high-risk'' findings were likely to surprise those who believe
prosperity has occurred across the demographic board.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a concentration of people in this country that the
middle-class and the well-to-do don't see,'' O'Hare said.
</P>
<P>
   Karla Myers, 36, is a mother of four who once was homeless and
recently began working at St. Vincent's as a receptionist.
</P>
<P>
   At times, she has hit all six of the high-risk factors. Her two
oldest children have dropped out of school.
</P>
<P>
   She said many high-risk parents are products of their own
upbringing, such as growing up in welfare families with parents who
didn't finish school and abused alcohol and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not using that as an excuse, because everybody can do
better if they try,'' Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's gotten lost here is that the best way to help
kids is to help parents. Times are great and wonderful for a lot of
people, but there is another part of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare said research shows that children do better when parents
do better.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 26 percent of teens with four of the six high-risk
factors were high school dropouts in 1998 compared with 1 percent
of teens with none of the risks.
</P>
<P>
   Also, 16 percent of high-risk females age 15 to 19 were teen-age
mothers, compared with only one-tenth of 1 percent of those girls
with none of the risk factors.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show that race plays a key role in determining who is
``high-risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty percent of black children and 25 percent of Hispanic
children grow up in ``high-risk'' families, compared with 6 percent
of white children.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of ``high risk'' children live in poor areas of
central cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving jobs to suburbs creates distressed inner-city
neighborhoods,'' O'Hare said. ``The tax base is in the suburbs, so
that's where the better schools are.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year that Kids Count had compiled
``high-risk'' findings. Since 1990, the annual study has used 10
health, economic and social indicators to determine child
well-being in the various states.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire ranked best nationally this year in that study.
Mississippi ranked 50th. The District of Columbia was 51, getting
the lowest score in nine of the 10 areas.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, which fell from 31st to 32nd since last year, scored
improvements in teen pregnancy and infant mortality but showed a
big jump in high school dropouts. While the national dropout rate
dropped 9 percent from 1985 to 1996, Missouri's increased by 50
percent. The dropout rate has risen to 12 percent, from 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, a lot of our teens don't see high school
as being a part of their road map to the future,'' said Ruth
Ehresman of Citizens for Missouri's Children.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, which fell from 15th to 18th overall, improved in the
dropout rate but registered a 69 percent increase from 1985 to 1996
in the share of children living in single-parent households, a jump
three times the national rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
