r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-19 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIERKER   GETS THE LAST LAUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Houston Astros are on their way to a third
consecutive National League Central title under Larry Dierker, and
you know what this means, don't you?
</P>
<P>
   Next Los Angeles Dodgers manager: Rick Monday.
</P>
<P>
   You laugh?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, you laughed when Dierker _ long-ago ballplayer and
long-time broadcaster _ was asked to trade in his familiar Hawaiian
shirts for an Astros jersey and his scoresheet for a lineup card
after the team finished its 10th season in a row without a division
title in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But who's laughing now?
</P>
<P>
   If the '98 NL Manager of the Year award and the affection of his
players are proof, Dierker has arrived in his first attempt at
being somebody's boss, proving a good baseball man doesn't lose his
feel for the game just because he spends 17 years watching it from
the press box.
</P>
<P>
   Most nights, Dierker even feels at home in the dugout now, much
as the old Taft High pitching and basketball star has come to feel
like a ``hybrid Texan'' after drawing an Astros paycheck for 33 of
the past 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a slow progression,'' said Dierker, who's not afraid
to admit the occasional tactical error, the admission itself
suggesting he's not fully a manager yet. ``Before this I was always
performing _ pitching or broadcasting. I didn't have people working
for me or have control over people's lives. This is a weighty
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, 52, sat at the desk in the visiting manager's office at
Dodger Stadium three hours before the Astros' series-opening, 11-3
victory over the Dodgers on Tuesday night. A Hawaiian shirt hung in
the closet behind him.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Reseda and Woodland Hills and was a delivery boy
for the Daily News when it was called the Green Sheet. He quit that
job after two weeks when he found out how much money was to be
earned in handing out what was then a free-of-charge newspaper. His
mother, Marilyn, lives in Woodland Hills and Dierker is staying
with her this week.
</P>
<P>
   He was still a kid when he signed with the Astros and still a
kid when he pitched his first major-league game on his 18th
birthday, striking out Willie Mays in the first inning on Sept. 22,
1964. He went on to win 20 games in '69, no-hit the Montreal Expos
in '76 and set five Astros career records that still stand.
</P>
<P>
   But his playing career ended in '77, and by the time he was
appointed manager, to his and everybody else's surprise, he was no
longer an Astros ex-pitcher, he was an Astros ex-broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   Astros management thought it had to do something different to
compete with better-financed clubs, wanted an unorthodox manager,
and got one. And the team wanted a calming influence after three
seasons of Terry Collins' intensity, and got it.
</P>
<P>
   In Dierker's let-'em-play style, starting pitchers work into the
late innings, ``lefty-righty'' bullpen and pinch-hitting moves are
rare and slumping regulars know they'll get a chance to work
through their problems on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the main thing is the trust he has in all of his
players,'' said Jack Howell, the former Angel who is the Astros'
busiest pinch-hitter. ``If I'm not swinging the bat well, he
continues to throw me out there, and that makes me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker speaks of treating players as something more than ``game
pieces,'' personifications of statistical tendencies. He prefers
``dealing with the human element,'' of ``care and nurturing,'' of
occasionally ignoring the percentages to make the ``emotionally
stabilizing'' move.
</P>
<P>
   From the perspective of the broadcasting booth, Dierker had
observed that the majority of managers live lives of quiet
desperation. Unproven young men afraid to blow their big chances.
Tired old men worried that patience would be interpreted as
slow-wittedness.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker watched insecure managers make changes for the sake of
making changes _ to impress owners for whom the financial stakes
were rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I saw happening was that as the game changed and the
salaries grew, the managers would be armed with all these stats and
reports, and if there was any opportunity to make a move, even if
it might give you very little advantage, they'd do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make a move and it doesn't work, then the players
failed,'' Dierker said of the way these things are viewed. ``If you
don't make a move and it doesn't work, you should have made a
move.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker learned from the surprising success of notably patient
Expos manager Buck Rodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like when we would go into Montreal, (the Expos)
always had a lefty and a righty available in the seventh, eighth,
ninth innings, and we were always out of pitchers by then,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he became a manager, having never asked for the job
in the first place, Dierker literally could afford to follow his
own unique approach. He can draw on his major league pension or
fall back on broadcasting if this doesn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the sense of desperation that some guys bring to
this job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he'd better not get too comfortable. The Astros' division
titles the past two years were pleasant surprises. Now, after a
franchise-best 102 victories in '98, they're expected to run away
with the division.
</P>
<P>
   With first baseman Jeff Bagwell, second baseman Craig Biggio and
most of the pitching staff among the league leaders, the Astros are
doing it, their NL-best 24-13 record giving them a four-game lead
in the NL Central.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate, Dierker won't get kicked back upstairs anytime
soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
