<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2597 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-1STL     05-19 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS DEFEAT HAWKS, 100-92
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On Sunday, Allan Houston sprinted defiantly down the
Miami Arena floor and punched his fist into the air after his
dramatic shot that eliminated the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the player labeled as too passive and nice, the New
York Knick who walked too slump-shouldered and unassuming, was
flaunting a confident edge and exuding an extrovert's ability to
take over a party. Just 48 hours later, without breaking his bold
stride, Houston took over the Atlanta Hawks' home and made himself
comfortable as he delivered a playoff career-high 34 points to give
the Knicks Game 1 of their four-of-seven-game second-round series,
a 100-92 victory on Tuesday night at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get paid to shoot, make or miss,'' said Houston, who was 13
of 20 from the floor. ``Over all, as far as confidence, if people
want to consider the Miami shot the one that propelled me, that's
fine. But I want to think of it as one of many more to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his 10-foot jumper in Miami was a defining shot for
Houston, one that set his confidence up for a night like Tuesday
night. His assertiveness was contagious as the team formed a line
behind him and followed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of overindulging on their victory in Miami, the Knicks
came out crisp and sharp at the beginning. There was no letdown, as
Coach Jeff Van Gundy had feared. There was no sign of a team that
seemed uninterested in the Hawks or less energetic in the face of
an opponent they did not loathe as much as they did the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried, too,'' Chris Childs said. ``When we got out
there, I was shocked at how ready we were. I didn't know if we'd
have the same attitude we had when we played in Miami. But we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   They had that aggressive air about them even with the gallant
Patrick Ewing in foul trouble most of the night. Without him for
all but 17 minutes in the game, Houston and his running partner,
Latrell Sprewell, filled the offensive void.
</P>
<P>
   The two of them set out on a torrid transition game that defied
the plodding, halfcourt style that seemed inevitable when the
matchup between these two defensive-minded teams developed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of walking the ball up the floor and allowing the aging
and worn Hawks to take a breath and set up their defense, the
Knicks seized any missed shot and pushed the ball up the floor. It
was a situation made for Sprewell in the first half, when he scored
17 of playoff career-high 31 points. In the third quarter, it was
Houston's turn. Delivering smooth, silky jumpers and also darting
to the hoop, he collected 15 points and helped turn an 8-point
deficit into an 80-73 Knick lead entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``To attack before their defense is set, you have to get stops
and rebound,'' said Van Gundy, whose team outrebounded the Hawks,
40-32. ``And rebounding has been the hardest part against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The ominous Dikembe Mutombo has had a lot to do with that. But
when Ewing was on the floor, he was able to pull Mutombo away from
the basket with an uncanny baseline jumper. When Ewing, who made 6
of 7 shots, kept collecting fouls, there was Chris Dudley. He
didn't have the offense to draw Mutombo, but he had fouls to give
and a brawny body to put in front of the elbow-throwing
shot-blocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dudley gave us great minutes,'' said Van Gundy, who didn't
play Dudley in Game 5 against Miami. ``He hadn't been playing, but
to his credit, he kept himself ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing kept himself in the right frame of mind as well. He had
been exasperated all night, and even picked up a technical foul
with 11 minutes 25 seconds left in the third quarter, popping off
when he picked up his fifth foul. But upon his return, Ewing
rediscovered his touch.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief moment, the Knicks eased their foot off the pedal.
After the Knicks built a gaudy 17-point lead with 6:53 left in the
game on a massive two-handed dunk by Sprewell, the Hawks went on a
12-4 run to cut the Knicks' lead to 7 points with 1:59 left. That
was when Ewing, who loped back onto the floor just two minutes
earlier, came up with a 10-foot jumper to spell some relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating sitting,'' said Ewing, whose injury-riddled
body probably benefited from his 17 minutes of playing time, during
which he scored 12 points. ``I'm just happy we got the win. If I
knew I wasn't going to play, I would have sat out.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the night, Ewing had a good seat for Houston's
performance. Houston worked in tandem with Sprewell, whose
explosive night offensively was tempered only by the shaky defense
he played. Just after Sprewell had scored 9 points in the first
quarter to send the Knicks to a 38-27 lead in the second quarter,
he inexplicably left the mild-mannered Chris Crawford open for two
straight 3-pointers. Crawford, who scored a team-high 26 points,
had 17 in the second quarter to give the Hawks a 50-48 halftime
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks had made up this ground without Steve Smith, who
scored 25 points, but was saddled with foul trouble through the
game. Smith has been an irritant to the Knicks and has often got
the best of Houston. This time was different. This time, Smith was
facing a player who burst out of his shell in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you hit a shot like he did, your confidence
skyrockets,'' Childs said. `'I've told him, he's the future here.''
</P>
<P>
   He played like it. He played as if the Miami shot had been a
turning point for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be a stretch,'' Van Gundy said. ``But let's stay with
that if he can come out and give us 34 every night. I do know this:
He's always been confident. Obviously, making a shot like he did
just expands that confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
