<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLEAN-AIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BAD DECISION ON CLEAN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 19:
</P>
<P>
   In a bizarre and tortured decision, a three-judge federal
appeals panel last week invalidated air-quality regulations imposed
by the Clinton administration to ease the suffering of millions of
Americans with asthma and lung disease. If upheld, the decision
would repudiate one of the administration's main environmental
achievements and award victory to a coalition of industries and
state governments that have fought the regulations in Congress and
in the courts. It could threaten a series of other clean-air
initiatives as well, and overturn a half-century of jurisprudence
that has allowed Congress to delegate important rule-making powers
to federal agencies. For all these reasons, the administration is
obliged to appeal this decision _ first to the full Court of
Appeals, and, if that fails, to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   At issue were two administrative rulings by the Environmental
Protection Agency in 1997. One tightened the standards for
ground-level ozone, a major contributor to smog. The other set new
limits on microscopic dust-like specks called particulates.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings were controversial. Though they would clearly bring
health benefits, they would also force many industrialized states
to find new ways to reduce pollution. That in turn would mean big
investments in cleaner power plants, fuels and cars. This page
supported the rulings, as did the governors of New York, New Jersey
and other Northeastern states that suffer from dirty air
``imported'' from coal-fired plants in the Midwest. But they were
bitterly opposed by several Midwestern state governments, many big
utilities and industry.
</P>
<P>
   The two judges who voted to overturn the rulings were Stephen F.
Williams and Donald H. Ginsburg, both Reagan appointees. David S.
Tatel, a Clinton appointee, dissented. In explaining their
decision, the majority dusted off the ``nondelegation doctrine,''
which says that Congress cannot delegate legislative-like powers to
the executive branch. The doctrine was twice upheld in the 1930s.
Since then the Supreme Court has shown no appetite for reviving it,
and has consistently upheld delegations of power from Congress to
agencies like the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from its shaky constitutional underpinnings, the decision
was confusing as to which branch of government had in fact violated
the nondelegation doctrine. Some parts of the opinion blamed
Congress for writing a vague clean-air law and giving away too much
authority. Other parts blamed the EPA for exceeding its authority
and imposing ``arbitrary'' standards. Either way, there are
problems. To tell Congress that it can no longer broadly delegate
authority is to say that Congress must henceforth write detailed
regulations _ an executive function it does not want and cannot
effectively perform. To fault the EPA is to say that it cannot make
the choices it must make to institute broad congressional mandates.
</P>
<P>
   To some people, especially opponents, agency choices will always
seem ``arbitrary.'' But as Tatel noted, that does not mean the new
standards for soot and ozone were arbitrarily arrived at. On the
contrary, he noted, the EPA had ``adhered to a disciplined
decisionmaking process,'' including four years of scientific and
medical studies and extensive peer review. In addition, the agency
gave the states up to 15 years to meet these standards.
</P>
<P>
   The court has now sent the rulings back to the EPA for review
and, presumably, revision. But the question that leaps to mind is
whether any new standards will satisfy Judge Williams and Judge
Ginsburg. The administration's obvious course is to challenge their
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
