<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEXICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A PRESIDENTIAL PRIMARY FOR MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Timees said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 19:
</P>
<P>
   Mexico was already headed toward a lively three-party
presidential contest next year. Now the contest will begin even
earlier, with this week's welcome decision by the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, to choose its nominee through a
national primary election open to all voters.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the PRI reflected the undemocratic circumstances
of its birth some 70 years ago. The victorious veterans of Mexico's
revolution organized the party as an instrument for keeping power
in their own hands, and those of their chosen political heirs,
indefinitely. The PRI has controlled Mexico's presidency and most
other high offices ever since. In the past, its presidential
nominees were hand-picked by the outgoing president. That helped
turn Mexico's political leadership into a closed, self-perpetuating
club.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to a broad-based national primary will contribute to a
healthy opening of Mexican political life. It may also help
reinvigorate a party that has grown complacent and out of touch
with the modern Mexican electorate.
</P>
<P>
   The new primary system will allow prospective PRI nominees to
sharpen their appeal to voters. Victory will go to the contender
who wins the largest number of electoral districts, a rule designed
to encourage campaigning outside urban centers like Mexico City.
Candidates will have to resign any government offices, participate
in debates and abide by campaign spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Credit for the new system goes mainly to President Ernesto
Zedillo, who pressed ahead with changes far bolder and more
resistant to high-level tampering than most Mexican analysts
expected. Having earlier pushed through legislation to assure
fairer campaigning and impartial election supervision, Zedillo is
well on his way to building a legacy as the president who brought
real democracy to Mexico after decades of manipulated candidacies
and fraudulent elections. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2609 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-CHECKS-2ndTAK     05-19 0306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-CHECKS-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES:personnel and employee relations.
</P>
<P>
   Broadhurst said the Police Department also is investigating
claims of similar incidents in Los Angeles public libraries, where
Smith has been employed intermittently since 1990 _ although city
officials said he has not worked for the city in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's confronted about these bizarre behaviors, he claims
to have had a seizure, which is identical to what occurred at El
Sereno,'' Broadhurst said. ``That's why people were calling me even
before the name was published.''
</P>
<P>
   The LAUSD is experiencing a shortage of teachers and is
struggling to fill thousands of vacant positions, and last week's
incident was the latest symptom of the teacher crunch, said school
board member David Tokofsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are short thousands of teachers and hundreds of
substitutes,'' Tokofsky said. ``Issues of selectivity are not high
on L.A. Unified's radar screen when we're in that deep of a
shortage.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to fingerprinting, the LAUSD background check
includes a written agreement requiring disclosure of any criminal
convictions or pending court cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if individuals do not have convictions, then it becomes
rather difficult to deny them their credentials,'' said Santiago
Jackson, assistant superintendent of the district's Office of
Legislation.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said there are no immediate plans to seek
expansion of their access to employees' background information.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where we sit as a school district, we'd like to have all
of the information and pursue all of the information, but with
everything in place right now as far as privacy laws, employee
records, it is hard to get information unless there has been a
conviction of an individual,'' Jackson said.
</P>
