<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FED EDGES TOWARD ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 19:
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's decision on Tuesday to leave interest
rates unchanged but to warn that it was thinking of raising them in
the future reaffirms how unsure the policy makers are about the
state of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed cut rates three times late last year when it believed
that the financial panic following the Russian default would slow
American growth and might bring on a world recession. In retrospect
the Fed seems to have overreacted, although the cuts appeared
prudent at the time. Now, with the United States' economy growing
far more rapidly than expected, a world recession seemingly
unlikely and with some signs of a rebirth of inflation, a modest
increase in rates could easily be justified.
</P>
<P>
   That the Fed did not dictate such an increase, but instead
announced a ``bias'' in favor of raising rates in the future,
probably reflects a continued argument within the Fed's open market
committee about the extent to which inflation is a threat. Some
believe that thanks to increases in productivity brought on by
computers, the economy is now able to grow much faster than in the
past without any appreciable threat of inflation. But it is also
possible that inflation has been held down by overseas weakness
that is now reversing. The Fed should be vigilant about inflation,
and may rightly conclude next month that a rate increase is wise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
