r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-CHECKS-2TAKES     05-19 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-CHECKS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER'S ARREST SHOWS HIRING FLAWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A substitute teacher accused of taking off his
pants in front of fourth-graders last week had a history of alleged
sexual battery or harassment against co-workers at area libraries,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   And even after the incident at El Sereno Elementary School,
teacher Wendell Smith got a job substituting the next day at a
second Los Angeles school, Yorkdale Elementary School in Eagle
Rock, when rules were bypassed, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not go through the substitute office when they hired
him,'' said Los Angeles Unified School District spokesman Pat
Spencer, adding that a memo is being sent to all principals
reminding them of proper substitute hiring procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 46, was arrested Thursday at his Highland Park home. He
has pleaded not guilty to four counts of forcible lewd acts with a
child and was being held on $750,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's case is not unique.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a former deputy state labor commissioner without
teaching credentials was hired to work at a Los Angeles elementary
school even though he was under federal investigation and
eventually indicted on suspicion of collecting more than $60,000 in
bribes in his previous post.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases and others, officials said the privacy rights of
prospective employees collided with the need to provide for the
safety of children _ and that safety lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a parent, my gut instinct is to say always err on the side
of caution to protect children,'' said Kathleen Dixon, a San Pedro
attorney who serves as chairwoman of the LAUSD Parent
Collaborative. ``But as an attorney, I know how badly that can be
abused.''
</P>
<P>
   Eadie Gieb of Sylmar, president of Parents and Students United
of the San Fernando Valley, took a less compromising view and
suggested making release of full employment records a condition of
working as a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We entrust our children to go to school, and we believe that
somehow they're going to be safe there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that there are some sexual predators out there
that need to be weeded out of the system, and they threaten all
children's safety.''
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD officials said they have little access to negative
information unless a person is convicted of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   In the Smith case, incidents at libraries in Glendale, Inglewood
and Los Angeles where he worked part time did not lead to criminal
prosecution or convictions and were never reported to the school
district, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we known of any of this, he would not have been hired,''
said LAUSD spokesman Brad Sales. ``We have a reference on file from
Inglewood that doesn't mention any of this. It said everything was
hunky-dory.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials for the cities of Inglewood, Glendale and Los Angeles
said that because of recent lawsuits, records of employee
misconduct remain confidential _ inaccessible to even other
prospective employers.
</P>
<P>
   The school district conducts background checks of job
applicants, including a fingerprint check, but state law allows
access to information about criminal convictions only _ not
arrests, Sales said.
</P>
<P>
   Arrests that occur after an employee is hired would be reported
to the school district only if the employee reveals to the
arresting agency that he or she works for a school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concern to the parents, and it's a concern to us
also,'' said LAPD Inspector Detective Larry Broadhurst, who is
supervising the investigation of Smith. ``Maybe there's a flaw in
the system that needs to be looked at.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Smith, of Highland Park, had worked as a
substitute teacher for the LAUSD for two years with no incidents
until last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On April 27, 1998, the Inglewood Police Department filed a
sexual battery report against Smith after a co-worker at Inglewood
Public Library complained that he entered her office, suddenly
reached down, grabbed her hand and placed it on his groin. The city
attorney did not prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   Inglewood Library Director Miguel Alaniz said he knew that Smith
worked for the LAUSD but officials would not say whether anyone
notified the school district of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is we don't volunteer information without a
release,'' said Inglewood Personnel Director Robert Wilson. A
release is a statement signed by the individual, authorizing
disclosure of information.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, Smith began working as an intermittent librarian
at the Glendale Public Library but was fired just six months later
in February 1999 as the result of a sexual harassment complaint by
a female librarian, said Jack Hoffman, director of personnel and
employee relations.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
