A2617 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-DRIVERS-LADN     05-19 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-DRIVERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTLINE HELPS PARENTS MONITOR TEEN DRIVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Do you know how your teen-ager is driving?
</P>
<P>
   Now if teen drivers misbehave on the road, there's a way to find
out. An emergency room nurse, tired of treating child car-crash
victims, has set up a hotline to report bad drivers whose cars have
``1 (888)-TELL DAD'' bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   The service costs $14.95 for the bumper sticker and $5 per month
for monitoring, including notification of parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times you can have a really good kid, and when
they're with their friends they get a little reckless, careless, a
little daring,'' said Wendy Petta, 26. ``This will make them think:
Oh, yeah, I have a sticker on my bumper.''
</P>
<P>
   Petta recently began distributing the stickers. Each carries a
large-print identification number so motorists can lodge a specific
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   So far she has four customers, including Lisette Perez, who made
her 19-year-old daughter put it on the bumper of her Honda Civic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will give me a little more peace of mind to know someone is
keeping an eye on her and she's not driving recklessly,'' said
Perez, 40, who said she has reported truck drivers for bad driving.
``It's just one more deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristell Perez said she had little choice but to accept the
sticker because she is still living at home and the car is in her
parents' name.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said as long as I keep having the sticker on, I can take
the car wherever I want to go,'' she said. ``I have a feeling that
if they do get called, I'd probably get my car taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Police welcome the idea but question how effective it will be
for kids who might remove the sticker or who face little prospect
of being punished if they are caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, how are you going to get the kids to keep it on
their car?'' said Officer Dwight McDonald of the California Highway
Patrol's West Valley station. He said the one who doesn't mind
having the sticker on the car is probably the one more likely to
obey traffic laws, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said the CHP regularly receives complaints about bad
driving and, using the license plate as an identifier, follows up
with a letter warning that the alleged violator's actions were
observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get enough complaints, we take it to the city
attorney,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Petta said she started the business out of her home after a
close call with a teen-age driver on Angeles Crest Highway about
two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was coming home from my mom's with my two kids in the car,
and this young kid came by in his Mustang and cut me off, and I had
to swerve,'' she said. ``I thought: I wish his mom knew how he was
driving because if she did he wouldn't be driving like that.''
</P>
<P>
   As an emergency room nurse at Verdugo Hills Hospital north of
Los Angeles, Petta said she often sees the injuries that teen-agers
and others suffer in traffic crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they know their parents are going to find out about
reckless driving, they're going to drive safer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When phoning in a complaint to her service, a person should give
the identification number on the bumper sticker and the time, date
and location of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Petta said she will then call the parents and relay the
information.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-year-old Melissa La Joice said she is glad to drive the
family Dodge Caravan when she is allowed, although it carries one
of the bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a burden,'' said Melissa, who has a
learner's permit. ``It's a protective measure. If someone has that
on, they'll have that responsibility on their shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Jan La Joice, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard some people say, oh, it's Big Brother watching, but
I don't think that's what it was intended for,'' she said. ``It's
more of a reminder that you need to be aware and need to be safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Jan La Joice also drives the Caravan, she knows she must
live up to the standard she expects of her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could just as easily report me as my daughter,'' she
said. ``So the parents have to set an example.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
