<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-STARWARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BEFORE THE BEGINNING, AFTER THE END 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most viewers will recall the chronological discontinuity at the
beginning of the first ``Star Wars'' film, which appeared in 1977.
In the opening text that scrolled up the screen, ushering audiences
into the unknown, there were two puzzles. ``Star Wars,'' subtitled
``A New Hope,'' was a science-fiction movie set in the remote past,
and it was also called ``Episode IV.'' The old Horatian advice to
poets is to begin ``in medias res,'' in the middle of things. That
adage still applies, but for a different reason than Horace had in
mind. If you call the first ``Star Wars'' film ``Episode IV,'' you
enclose the audience, as Horace understood, in an already onrushing
vehicle. But if your story is as entertaining as ``Star Wars'' was,
you also build demand for the missing episodes, for what is now
called the prequel, a word unknown until the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   So far, George Lucas' new film, ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace,'' which opens today, has been prequel only to
itself. The soundtrack was released early, and so was the
novelization. ``Phantom Menace'' merchandise went on sale
nationwide two weeks ago. Hype is too small a word for the sales
pressure that has been building up behind this movie, which is only
appropriate, since the original ``Star Wars'' trilogy set a
precedent not only in the use of special effects and the fervor the
films inspired among fans but also in the development of retail
licensing. All in all, it seems a little disingenuous for Fox,
which is releasing the movie, to complain about reviews that jumped
the release date. If they had been glowing, perhaps Fox executives
would never have complained. As it is, advance reviews suggest that
there are few harder tasks than making a really good prequel.
</P>
<P>
   The business of America is business, said a man not half as wise
as Obi-Wan Kenobi. But the entertainment of America is also
business, which, as George Lucas has proved many times over, can be
entertaining in itself. Whatever the final verdict on ``The Phantom
Menace,'' yea or nay, Lucas will go down in cinematic history as
the greatest director of licensed properties yet, a brilliant
commodifier of the movies. It would have been hard enough for ``The
Phantom Menace'' to compete with the original ``Star Wars''
trilogy. To compete with what is expected of it may prove nearly
impossible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
