A2623 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASA-ASTROBIOLOGY-SFC     05-19 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-ASTROBIOLOGY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE ASTROBIOLOGY INSTITUTE: NASA'S METAPHYSICAL MISSION  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. _ Nobel prize-winning biochemist Baruch S.
Blumberg has been named to head NASA's new Astrobiology Institute,
a bold project to seek evidence for the origin and evolution of
life in the universe, space agency administrator Daniel S. Goldin
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at eleven major universities and research centers are
already linked together and collaborating by computer to form the
``virtual'' institute, with its headquarters at the Ames Research
Center in Mountain View.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin made the announcement of Blumberg's appointment during a
talk to the Ames staff that clearly displayed his own excitement
over the institute's future. Among the extraordinary scientific
advances envisioned by the NASA chief are:
</P>
<P>
   _Intelligent DNA-based computer chips and ``biologically
inspired electronics'' aboard miniature space vehicles may seek
signs of life among comet clouds beyond the solar system, he
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   _Submarines may one day probe the frigid oceans that most
probably underlie the cracked and icy crust of Jupiter's moon
Europa.
</P>
<P>
   _``Simulation chambers'' will exploit new knowledge of
Earth-bound microorganisms living in extreme environments to model
the earliest life on Earth and beneath the Martian surface _ and
even predict entire ecosystems of planets around distant stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new field of study,'' Goldin said, ``will bring a new
understanding of fundamental life processes on Earth and throughout
our universe, if it exists.'' But it will demand a ``revolution in
communications, networking, information technology, computing and
scientific thinking,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has asked Congress to increase the institute's annual
budget from $10 million to $25 million, and Goldin projected that
the institute would eventually need $100 million a year to achieve
its goals.
</P>
<P>
   To Goldin, astrobiology involves ventures ``so vast and with
goals so staggering'' that it may well enable science to ``capture
and develop the universal fingerprints of life processes.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching those goals, he said, will involve finding answers to
such questions as: How does life begin and evolve? Does life exist
elsewhere in the universe? And what is the possibility of life on
Earth and beyond?
</P>
<P>
   There may be more than a touch of metaphysics in such questions,
but scientists around the world have long been trying to answer
them. America's own National Science Foundation, as well as NASA,
is already financing major research into the first two mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   A new Exobiology Institute, Goldin said, will try to create
artificial cells that mimic the metabolic processes of living
organisms ``and search for the complex chain of interactions that
may determine how life originates and evolves.''
</P>
<P>
   And if submarines do probe Europa's ocean on missions inspired
by the Astrobiology Institute, they could carry newly conceived
machines to ``discover, analyze and automatically sequence the
genome of any microbes found there,'' Goldin said. ``Just imagine
how finding even single-cell life forms on other planets may add to
our understanding of the biodiversity of our universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumberg, the Institute's new director, is both a physician and
biochemist. He won his Nobel laurels in 1976 for isolating the
unique protein that led to a vaccine against hepatitis B, a liver
disease that once afflicted more than 200 million people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   A cancer specialist and frequent visiting professor of biology
at Stanford, Blumberg has been a research chief at the Fox Chase
Cancer Center in Philadelphia and is a professor of medicine and
anthropology at the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the Ames Research Center staff yesterday, Blumberg
said the Institute will ``answer some of the most fundamental
questions of biology, unencumbered by previous hypotheses.''
Scientists at all the Institute's component centers will focus
their energies on ``curiosity-driven research'' rather than
specific space missions, he said, which will mean ``a whole new
universe is opening before us.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Goldin and Blumberg stressed that they cannot begin to
predict what life may be like and how it originated elsewhere in
the universe. When a reporter asked Blumberg, ``How do you look for
something if you don't even know what it is,'' he replied _ to
appreciative laughter from the scientists in his audience _
``That's just what basic research is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of NASA19 (77726 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
