<HEADER>
A2626 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILLY-MAYORAL-NYT &LR;      05-19 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-MAYORAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-COUNCILMAN WINS PHILADELPHIA PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ A long and often nasty Democratic primary
campaign ended Tuesday when John F. Street, the former City Council
president and Mayor Edward G. Rendell's chosen successor, defeated
five other candidates to win the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Street will oppose Sam Katz, a financial consultant
who is seeking to become the city's first Republican elected mayor
since 1947. Katz, who lost a mayoral primary bid in 1991 and a 1994
bid to become Pennsylvania governor, faced no opposition in
Tuesday's Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell, a Democrat who is is barred by law from seeking a third
four-year term, has been credited with revitalizing Philadelphia's
finances and spirit. His strong support and early endorsement of
Street, along with that of the city's three main newspapers, helped
Street keep atop of most polls.
</P>
<P>
   With 97 percent of the ballots counted, Street had 100,308
votes, or 35 percent, to defeat Marty Weinberg, a former high-level
aide to the late Mayor Frank Rizzo. Weinberg had 88,297 votes, or
31 percent, better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   While the campaign began with thoughtful discourses on issues
like crime, education and economic development it became dominated
by attack advertising as the candidates spent record amounts, more
than $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg, who is white, made no secret of the fact he was
counting heavily upon a high turnout among white voters, especially
those from the working-class and middle-class neighborhoods where
Rizzo enjoyed widespread support during his divisive tenure as
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of advertisements, Weinberg showed 18-year-old film
footage of Street, who is black, as a young, boisterous member of
the City Council, shoving a television reporter in one instance and
throwing water in someone's face in another.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg also ran advertisements that cited Street's history of
personal financial problems, including two bankruptcy filings, as a
way to raise questions about his ability to manage the city
government.
</P>
<P>
   Street, who served seven years as council president through last
December, vowed throughout his campaign to continue the progress of
the Rendell administration and avoided the mud slinging.
</P>
<P>
   But he was finally drawn in last week, running commercials that
condemned Weinberg for injecting race as an issue. The Street
advertisements quoted newspaper endorsements of Street that chided
Weinberg for exploiting racial tensions.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it was probably Street's working partnership
with Rendell that cemented victory. Over the years, they worked
closely to turn around Philadelphia's financial status, from near
bankrupt in 1992 to robust in more recent times. In particular, the
downtown area has enjoyed a surge in economic development as
Philadelphia enhances its attractiveness to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   In the rest of the primary field, John F. White Jr., the city's
former public housing director, received 22 percent of the vote,
followed by Happy Fernandez, a former member of the City Council;
Dwight Evans, a state legislator for the last 18 years, Queena R.
Bass.
</P>
<P>
   While Street will undoubtedly be considered the front-runner in
the fall campaign, owing in large measure to the greater number of
registered Democrats over Republicans, about 7 to 2, in the city,
Katz has an unusually large pool of Democrats to approach _ the
majority of those who voted Tuesday for candidates other than
Street. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 0150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2628 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASA-ASTROBIOLOGY-SFC     05-19 1009
