<P>
   PAPILLOTE (Undated) _ The cooking method known as en papillote _
after the parchment paper that encloses the food in an envelope _
has held its own through any number of culinary fashions. It was
especially favored in the days when haute cuisine was more
ceremonious than it is now, allowing the server to open the package
at the table in a show of erupting aromatic steam. Now, it still
maintains its place, mostly in restaurants, thanks to what is
perhaps a purer, more esthetic reason: a dish cooked in this way is
intensely yet harmoniously flavored. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
