<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-TREATMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HERB MIXTURE AS PROSTATE CANCER TREATMENT PRAISED  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A traditional blend of eight Chinese herbs is starting to show
promise as a treatment for advanced prostate cancer, researchers
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The herbal concoction, called ``PC-SPES'' and sold in health
food stores as a dietary supplement, achieved results by one
measure even in men who had failed conventional hormonal therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how the mixture might work, which of the eight
ingredients may be the most beneficial or harmful, and whether side
effects will prove acceptable after long-term use.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors warned cancer patients that supplements fall outside the
standard regulatory system for drugs and may vary in purity and
potency. And while early studies often seem promising, further
research could lead to different conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the caveats, cancer specialists said they are intrigued
by the potential benefits of PC-SPES, which derives its English
name from the abbreviation for ``prostate cancer'' and the Latin
word for ``hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The mixture includes saw palmetto, a supplement used by some men
to achieve shrinkage of an enlarged prostate. Other ingredients
include indigotica (da qing ye), glycyrrhiza glabra and glycyrrhiza
(gan cao), Panax Pseudo Ginseng (san qi) and Ganoderma Iucidum
Karst (ling zhi). Only one company makes it, a Southern California
firm that based the mix on a traditional Chinese recipe. It costs
$200 to $400 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary results of an ongoing two-year study of PC-SPES were
reported at a meeting of cancer specialists in Atlanta Tuesday.
Authors included Dr. Eric Small and colleagues at the University of
California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The study is one of the first to subject the herbal compound to
rigorous clinical testing. Results reported Tuesday involved 61
men, out of a total of 70 enrolled in the clinical study, including
34 patients whose cancer was no longer responding to hormonal
therapy and 27 men who had not been treated with hormones.
</P>
<P>
   All the men received a standard dose of nine capsules daily of
PC-SPES. Researchers then measured circulating levels of prostate
specific antigen (PSA), a blood marker commonly used to track
cancer patients although by no means a perfect indicator of
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Reductions of PSA levels exceeding 50 percent were observed in
all 27 ``hormone-naive'' patients. But experts were most impressed
by Small's report that PSA levels also plummeted in 19 of the 34
hormone-resistant patients.
</P>
<P>
   That suggests PC-SPES may have effects that go beyond simply
reducing male hormones that act on the prostate. There were also
hints of tumor shrinkage in some men, though details were not yet
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's clearly showing an effect,'' said Dr. Robert DiPaola at
the Robert Wood Johnson Medical School in New Brunswick, N.J. ``But
to really know its usefulness, we need to do further studies.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Wu, a researcher at New York Medical College in Valhalla,
N.Y., also emphasized the need for caution when interpreting the
limited study results.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the fundamental idea behind PC-SPES _ throwing
multiple weapons against a disease _ makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cocktails work much better than single agents alone,`` Wu
said, noting the recent experience in using multiple drug
combinations to fight HIV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
