<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN REAL LIFE, THE MOVIE WAS BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Razzing the nerds, that wasn't invented at
Columbine High School, and it's not new.
<P>
   We all knew a Ronnie Gebron. Or we were him.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Jackson, local business and political figure, is a
compassionate champion of the underdog. It's his life. But recently
Arthur has been haunted by the memory of a kid from his high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronnie Gebron,'' Jackson says. ``He was fat, had red hair and
freckles and wore glasses. That's the grand slam of nerdiness,
isn't it? We were never kind to him in four years. He must have
been angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur was a high school jock, a soccer star. The scariest thing
he and his pals could imagine was to be seen being nice to a Ronnie
Gebron. And sweet Jesus, what if Ronnie somehow showed up at a
party?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why was I like that?'' Jackson says. ``I wasn't brought up
that way. And it was a Quaker school. But they never once told us,
`You've got to be nice.' We have to teach that.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Billy Madison,'' a '95 Adam Sandler movie, Billy (Adam) has
a similar delayed attack of conscience. Billy remembers the nerd he
tormented in high school. He phones the nerd and sincerely
apologizes.
</P>
<P>
   The nerd, still nerdy, is taken aback but graciously accepts the
apology. He hangs up, reaches over to a long list of names taped to
his wall, labeled ``People to kill,'' and crosses off Billy
Madison.
</P>
<P>
   It was funnier before Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   BULLY.COM: The online book behemoths are trying to crush your
local bookstore by slashing prices on best-sellers. But what about
the speed of delivery?
</P>
<P>
   History buff Jerry Matters ordered a book on the Berlin airlift
from Amazon.com. He placed the order on Christmas day of '97. The
book arrived Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry says, ``I hope they stay out of the mail-order-bride
business.''
</P>
<P>
   WWWWW...: We're lucky that when Tim Berners-Lee invented the
World Wide Web he didn't name it the Wondrous World Wide Web Window
to the Whole Wide Weird Wacky World. But even at a mere three Ws,
it's a lot to say.
</P>
<P>
   Why not fix it? The WWW is supposed to make our lives more
efficient, so why such a ponderous mouthful o' wordage? Why not say
``dub'' instead of dubbaya-dubbaya-dubbaya? Save eight syllables
every time.
</P>
<P>
   MANNY 4 SALE: Bill Babbitt, brother of the recently executed
Manny, is in Hollywood, shopping Manny's life story. Bill and San
Francisco PR whiz Lee Housekeeper are camped out at the Sportsman's
Lodge, entertaining bidders, and there are many.
</P>
<P>
   Free advice to Bill: Make the movie guys promise not to
Hollywoodize the story. Their favorite thing is to buy the rights
to a compelling real-life story, then invent key facts to punch it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you were on Manny's side or not, you don't want to watch
the movie and say, ``I didn't know Manny Babbitt was married
briefly to Marilyn Monroe.''
</P>
<P>
   PACKING HEAT: Having survived the Bay to Breakers, Carolyne
Zinko and a friend boarded an N-Judah train heading back downtown.
It was packed solid and stiflingly hot.
</P>
<P>
   A rider pressed the intercom and begged the operator to turn on
the air conditioning. The operator explained that the AC was on the
blink, and so was the switch to shut off the heater. He told the
passengers he had begged the Muni mechanics to turn on the AC,
``but they didn't know how.''
</P>
<P>
   Added the operator, ``That's a $3 million-dollar train for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened to this state's tough lemon laws?
</P>
<P>
   THE ANSWER, MY FRIEND: Annoyed by those loose ad cards that
clutter up your magazines? Use your gas-powered leaf-blower to
remove 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Another tip you won't get from Martha Stewart: Trimming nasal
hair with your W &LR; weed W &LR; whacker.
</P>
<P>
   DIG THIS: The Postal Service printed a batch of 60-cent stamps
honoring ``Grand Canyon, Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   Please take note if you were planning to visit the Grand Canyon
at its previous location, Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But I can understand the mistake. I've often flown over that
area of the country and noticed that the map boundary lines tend to
get obscured by drifting sand.
</P>
<P>
   RUMOR KILL: Although Bill Clinton's West Coast fund-raising
weekend was highlighted by a Beverly Hills party hosted by David
Geffen, whose DreamWorks produced ``Saving Private Ryan,'' it's not
true that Clinton named the event ``Privately Saving Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL WARS: Last week the Mark Hopkins Hotel announced a huge
$34 million renovation project. And wow, that's got to be the
biggest hotel face-lift in city history!
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, when the Fairmont announced a $72 million
overhaul. In fairness, the Fairmont has more rooms, 594 to the
Mark's 362.
</P>
<P>
   Both hotels announced they will cover the cost of the remodeling
by raising the price of a room-service cheeseburger to $372.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
