<HEADER>
A2639 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BOS &LR;      05-19 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SOX GET DROP ON YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-YANKEES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe there are better ways to spend $450 million, after all.
</P>
<P>
   On splendid May nights like this, when Yawkey Way trembles with
the chants of fans from Brighton and the Bronx, the Yankees are in
the third-base dugout and Boss Steinbrenner is strolling through
the stands, Pedro Martinez and David Cone are dueling on the hill,
and Derek Jeter and Nomar Garciaparra are comparing All-Star
pedigrees at short, perhaps it's best to quietly put away all the
pretty models of the future Fenway and savor the crusty antique,
just as it is.
</P>
<P>
   While Tuesday night's outcome could not diminish the poignancy
of Yankee manager Joe Torre's return from prostate cancer, the Red
Sox moved into sole possession of first place in the American
League East with a 6-3 win over New York, which dropped a half-game
back. The Sox, who have not been alone in first place this late in
a season since winning the division in 1995, have won 10 of their
last 12; the Yankees have lost 7 of 9.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez gave up hits (10) and racked up strikeouts (11) in
nearly equal measure Tuesday night, but drew a Maginot Line in the
sand when it came to giving up runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like all great pitchers, Pedro turns it up with runners in
scoring position,'' pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said of Martinez,
who stranded 13 Yankees in seven innings while permitting just two
New Yorkers safe passage home. ``It's just a quality that a great
starting pitcher has. Sabes (Bret Saberhagen) is like that, Ramon
(Martinez) is like that. They just reach down a little deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the statmeisters sort through the strikeout numbers: seven
straight games of 10 strikeouts or more, at least one strikeout in
31 consecutive innings, and 102 K's this season, or more strikeouts
than any two other pitchers in the American League combined. The
poets will marvel at the soul of the slender Dominican who stranded
four Yankees on third base and ended five innings with strikeouts,
before leaving to a deafening ovation from a sellout crowd of
33,620.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been that way for a long time,'' said second baseman Jose
Offerman, whose shared history with Martinez extends through their
time together with the Dodgers and back to the Dominican Republic.
``He's just a tough guy when he's out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got something hard for us, to keep the game that way. But
he was able to do the job, which was exciting for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who leads the majors in wins with eight after strong
relief work by Rheal Cormier and Tom Gordon (save No. 5), struck
out the side and left with a 3-2 lead in the seventh, which ended
with World Series MVP Scott Brosius flinging his bat in frustration
after whiffing with runners on first and third.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get that many opportunities against a pitcher like
him,'' said Torre, whose 1999 debut was shrouded in secrecy until
he arrived here yesterday afternoon. ``We let him off the hook, but
you've got to give him credit. He reached back and did the job.''
</P>
<P>
   And had fun doing it, even though he required 36 pitches just to
get through the fifth inning, when the Yankees scored once and
might have had more except for Darren Lewis's head-banging catch of
O'Neill's drive to the wall in center. ``They put him through the
wringer there,'' Kerrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   But he came out intact on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a game and I enjoy the game,'' Martinez said. ``It
was a great opportunity for me to face those guys. If I retire
tomorrow, I have a chance to say, `I beat those guys.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my job. I enjoy every part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, held to Jason Varitek's swinging-bunt single
through the first four innings, trailed, 2-0, before finally
breaking through against Cone in the fifth. Mike Stanley, twice a
Yankee, twice a Red Sox, led off with his third home run, a
377-foot drive that was aided by a 10-mile-an-hour east wind to the
top of the wall in left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Lewis singled to left. Trot Nixon flied deep to
center, but Offerman walked and both runners moved up on a passed
ball. Jeff Frye walked to load the bases and Reggie Jefferson
followed with a line single to right, scoring Lewis with the tying
run.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman tried to score the go-ahead run from second, but was
gunned down by O'Neill, the second time in two nights Offerman has
been erased on a play at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra led off the sixth with a double high off the
left-center field wall, took third as Troy O'Leary grounded out to
the right side, and scored on a wild pitch by Cone, the type of
imperfections the Yankees rarely showed en route to winning a
record 125 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch's throwing error in the eighth was another, as
the second baseman tried to do too much with Varitek's bases-loaded
grounder. Knoblauch, who was going to his left, reversed direction
and went airborne with his throw to second in an attempt to turn
two, but his throw rolled into short left field as two runs scored.
Nixon's ground ball brought home the final run, making it 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a little bit of fun in the middle of the season,''
Martinez said. ``To us, we're realistic. It's too early to compare
ourselves to them. They're the best team in the last 30 years. We
have to keep battling and hope to sneak by.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
