<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2640 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  HKN-BRUINS-SABRES-BOS &LR;      05-19 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES BEAT BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
 HKN-BRUINS-SABRES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden said his
team's failure to beat the Sabres in the Eastern Conference
semifinals, which ended Tuesday night in a 3-2 loss in Game 6 at
Marine Midland Arena, boiled down to exactly one thing: His best
players, with the notable exception of captain Ray Bourque, were
simply not up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden singled out Jason Allison, who held out for a significant
pay increase last fall, and Dmitri Khristich, who took the club to
arbitration last summer, as the two most disappointing members of
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a sixth game tonight and our best player was Ray
Bourque,'' said Sinden. ``Where the hell are all our young players?
When you have an inspiration like Ray Bourque, and you can't
respond to that inspiration, then as a young player, you've got to
look at yourself and say, `Wait a minute, am I good enough to be a
star player or a good player?' It's not talent. It's a Ray Bourque
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's a lack of experience, or a lack of understanding of
the price that has to be paid in the playoffs, but whatever it is,
Sinden said too few had what the 38-year-old Bourque had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy, they booed him every time he touched the puck
and he was the best player on the ice,'' said Sinden. ``He was
fantastic. Do I get the response from my young players to his
performance? I don't get it. I'm not sure they get it. They have to
know what I'm trying to tell you. Until they understand what that
means, they will never ever, ever be a great team. You have to be
what Ray Bourque is, in your own level. We have some, but we don't
have enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden thought his team was mediocre Tuesday night and through
too much of the series. He thinks part of the reason Khristich and
Allison struggled was because of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a sixth game comes and you're going to be eliminated,
there's no room for just a mediocre display,'' he said. ``We paid a
few players this year and I don't think it helped them. As a matter
of fact, they were reduced in their capabilities. I don't think
Allison was the player he was last year, he wasn't the player he
should've been for one of our top-priced players in tonight's game.
That's his problem, not mine. I paid him. If you want it and you
get it, earn it. Earn it, baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say things like that. I like Allison,
he's a terrific talent, but you've got to perform. You can't just
come out and say, `Here's a game in Buffalo, it's over, let's go
home.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden was even more pointed on Khristich, who once again is up
for a contract when July 1 rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Khristich was a total, total disappointment,'' he said. ``All
he does is give the puck to the other team. He passes it to the
other team every time he gets it. He wants all this money because
he gets a few goals that are meaningless, really. Meaningless
goals. I need him in the playoffs. You need these high-priced
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not mad at either of them. I'm saying they want big money
_ I want it now. I want it now. In the four games we lost, we had
very few good players. Very few, and that was disappointing that we
should go up and down on the roller coaster like that. Most of them
worked their butts off, but some of our higher-priced players were
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden thought coach Pat Burns and assistants Jacques Laperriere
and Bob Francis employed every possible tactic in an effort to make
the team competitive. They just didn't have enough help from their
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaching staff did a great job,'' said Sinden. ``They
tried traps, they tried forechecking, they tried everything. I
think it was a player issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden thinks management is going to have a good amount of work
ahead of it this summer to shore up the roster. It is likely the
brass will go out and get some experienced players to complement
their young talent. It was patently obvious throughout the playoffs
they didn't have enough depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to come to grips with the fact that Buffalo outplayed
us,'' said Sinden. ``We have to face it and we have to get better.
This team is improving, we need some help. We have to do a little
better than we've done. We have to have some players who are a
little bit better than what we've got at some positions, no
question. Obviously, we're not good enough to go to the Stanley Cup
finals, which is our goal. But we're getting there. We have really
good young talent, we don't have enough maybe. This is a big,
difficult problem, these playoffs; you have to be on top of your
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo in general and this rink in particular have proven to be
dark places for the Bruins, and not just in the middle of winter.
The Bruins are 1-9-1 here since the arena opened, and they lost all
three postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Peca gave Buffalo the lead with a goal on the power play
at 5:15 of the first period. Steve Heinze answered for Boston, also
on the man advantage, at 12:49. Wayne Primeau made it 2-1 at 17:29,
a goal that really hurt the Bruins. Early in the second, Curtis
Brown made it a two-goal cushion at 1:08. In the third, Boston
pulled goalie Byron Dafoe for an extra attacker late and the move
paid off, with Joe Thornton beating Dominik Hasek at 18:57. But it
wasn't enough, and the series was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost four games and in the four games we lost, we played
terrible,'' said Sinden. ``We did not play well. If you don't play
well, you're going to lose, and Buffalo played really well. We
weren't able to counteract their forechecking, never, and so we got
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is good news, Sinden said it's that the Bruins are a
much better team than two years ago, when they missed the playoffs,
and better than last year, when they were eliminated in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that really has a chance to be something,'' he
said. ``They got beat by a team that really forechecked them, they
weren't ready for it and didn't know how to counteract it and
didn't counteract it. It had a lot to do with experience. I think
(Burns) knew exactly what he wanted them to do and they weren't
prepared to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team and they just ran into a team that was a
little better. Most of these guys gave a great effort, but I'm
disappointed that the people who are supposed to win you playoff
series didn't win us the playoff series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
