<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2643 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZEDILLO-CALIFORNIA-SF     05-19 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZEDILLO-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S ZEDILLO, CALIFORNIA'S DAVIS STRESS CORDIAL RELATIONS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ROBERT B. GUNNISON and CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ Opening a historic three-day trip to California,
President Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico proclaimed ``a new
understanding'' Tuesday with his northern neighbor and new era of
democracy in his own nation.
<P>
   It was a day of contrasts _ a warm official welcome from
Governor Gray Davis and cheers of ``Viva Mexico'' in the
Legislature, and angry protests against Mexican government policies
in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Zedillo nor California politicians in their official
remarks mentioned Proposition 187, the 1994 anti-illegal immigrant
measure that irked Mexico. Instead, they used the coded language of
politics to try to put the issue behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new understanding to continue our path toward the
21st century with a productive, fruitful relationship for all, a
productive and fruitful relationship of friends and trade
partners,'' Zedillo told the Legislature in Spanish, which was
translated for his audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come to California to reassure you, to reassure the
Mexican-origin population and all inhabitants of California, that
we are working very hard in Mexico to build a future of prosperity
and justice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction, Davis, who met with Zedillo in Mexico City
in January, said California's antagonistic attitude toward Mexico
is a thing of the past. ``Those days are gone forever,'' he said.
``You do the state of California and the people of California a
great honor with your presence.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco Tuesday night, Zedillo explained to a packed
audience his long absence from California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a coincidence that for more than four years I
couldn't come here,'' he told the crowd of 2,000 at a meeting of
the Commonwealth Club of California and the World Affairs Council.
</P>
<P>
   There were, he said, ``certain circumstances'' _ his way of
saying that former Gov. Pete Wilson made him unwelcome because of
the Proposition 187 campaign and the Republican governor's attacks
on illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``And besides,'' he said, ``I was not invited.'' The Fairmont
Hotel audience roared with laughter.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, a questioner in the audience asked Zedillo
what steps he was taking to counter the ``anti-Mexican backlash''
sponsored by the previous administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sentiment was ill-founded,'' the president said, ``and
probably it was not right to feed that sentiment. We have the will
to take very concrete steps to show people it is better to work
together than to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The only time the words ``Proposition 187'' were actually
mentioned came in a reporter's question _ during the first press
conference Zedillo has given since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   While Mexico bitterly condemned Wilson for his support of
Proposition 187, Zedillo was careful not to criticize Davis for his
decision to appeal a federal court ruling against the measure,
which halts government services, including education, for illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust Gray Davis, and I hope and trust and know there will
be in the end a good solution regarding this issue,'' he said in
response to the question.
</P>
<P>
   While California politicians used Zedillo's visit to try to show
themselves friends of Mexico and of the state's large Latino
population, Zedillo had a message of his own _ that his nation is
becoming more democratic and more stable for economic investment.
Mexico is now the state's No. 1 trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived one day after his Institutional Revolutionary Party,
which has held power for seven decades, agreed to the first
nationwide presidential primary later in November.
</P>
<P>
   The primary will end the tradition of Mexican presidents
selecting their successors and will allow voters to pick their
nominee for the general election in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in English to a luncheon audience of several hundred
local business and political leaders, Zedillo said his nation has
``a new kind of political stability that will make it more
realistic to reach our economic targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo also may have been speaking to potential voters. Some
Latino activists want legislation in Mexico that would allow more
than 3 million Mexican citizens living in California to vote in the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   As Zedillo arrived at the Capitol, California Highway Patrol
officers on horseback efficiently swept dozens of chanting
protesters out of the president's view.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators, many of them supporters of the Zapatista
movement in Chiapas, carried effigies of the Mexican president,
with blistering signs reading: ``Why does Zedillo kill families in
Chiapas?'' and ``Why does Zedillo kill Mexico's poor?''
</P>
<P>
   After the police did their work, the protesters were quickly
replaced by a line of enthusiastic students, carrying ``Welcome to
California'' signs. A smattering of boos was drowned out by the
students directly in front, who cheered lustily for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should know that there is a problem,'' said Marianna
Rivera, a member of the Zapatista Solidarity Coalition. ``The
Mexican government abuses its own people. They have been the party
in power for 70 years. They are totally corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatista movement began in January 1994 in southern Chiapas
state in the name of greater rights for indigenous people. The
conflict, especially a 1997 massacre of 45 Indians in the Chiapas
village of Acteal, has received international attention.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people spent the morning in front of the Capitol,
several holding aloft a large papier-mache figure of Zedillo with a
sign denouncing him as a puppet of the rich. Blocked behind metal
barriers, the protesters faced the red carpet that Zedillo and
Davis had used to enter the Capitol and prayed and performed an
Aztec dance.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner, the fourth annual immigrant lobby day was
taking place. The timing was coincidental but appropriate, said
Angie Wei of the California Immigrant Welfare Collaborative, which
coordinated the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are glad President Zedillo could be here to join in our
efforts for better treatment of immigrants,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the protest was Davis' decision to seek federal
appellate court mediation of Proposition 187. Davis, although
opposed to the measure, said he was obligated to continue the
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Zedillo plans to travel to Los Angeles for more
speeches, a town hall meeting and a state dinner in Beverly Hills.
Thursday, he will read to a bilingual elementary school in Los
Angeles, then travel to San Diego for another speech before
returning to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Lynda Gledhill contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 0223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
