<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2644 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  HKN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-19 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BRUINS TEAM HAS A FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
 HKN-RYAN COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Here's what you should remember about the 1998-99
Boston Bruins:
</P>
<P>
   That with a minute and change left, and with a two-goal deficit
that had been sitting up there for more than a period and with the
sellout Marine Midland Arena crowd of more than 18,000 chanting
``We Want The Leafs!'' while waving thousands of white pom-poms,
and with the cumulative effect of a lot of hits and a lot of
hard-skating shifts and with the thought of a nice hot shower
almost impossible to suppress, Joe Thornton _ the now fully-minted
Hope of the Future _ redirected a Mattias Timander six-on-five slap
shot past the almighty goaltender Dominik Hasek and suddenly those
18,000-plus people were in bad need of a wee-wee.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the final was Buffalo 3, Boston 2. Both the series and the
season are over. Buffalo now will play Toronto in an Eastern
Conference final made in newspaper beancounters heaven. (Wow! 60
miles apart. No hotel stays! Um, you think you guys could car
pool?) The Bruins didn't win because they weren't quite good enough
to win, but they did what all the beloved Bruins teams of yore
would have done, which was to let the Sabres know that a 60-minute
hockey game is a 60-minute hockey game. ``We played hard right to
the buzzer,'' said coach Pat Burns. ``You have to be proud of those
guys, and I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The night had ``celebration'' written all over it. The Sabres
had the 3-2 series lead, they had the home ice, and they had the
Great Hasek. Then they even got the first goal, which, according to
conventional wisdom, should have decided things right there. But it
didn't, because Steve Heinze tied it up before the first period was
over.
</P>
<P>
   But Wayne Primeau made it 2-1 before the period's end, and the
pesky Curtis Brown (3-2_5 in this series) took advantage of a
fairly complete Bruins breakdown to make it 3-1 after two periods,
and for the Bruins, the third period would be like trying to run up
Mt. Washington while carrying a Hammond organ. The crowd was
getting whoopier and whoopier, and why not? Buffalo in the winter
and spring is a one-sport town. Sabres rule. And for the second
year in a row, they are going to the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are going home. They now can admit it: They are
whipped, physically, mentally, and perhaps even emotionally. They
have just played 12 grueling playoff games, and I mean grueling.
Bruins hockey ain't no Ice Chips, pal. Bruins hockey ain't pretty;
no how, no way. Bruins hockey is body-sacrificing, gut-check
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love coming to games this time of the year,'' said Anson
Carter. ``The sun is out. You wear shorts to practice. But then you
lose and it's like a punch in the face. Tired? Yes, I'm tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody but everybody had said before the playoffs began that
the East was a thoroughly unpredictable hodgepodge in which
seedings meant nothing. Sure enough, only one of the top four seeds
(Toronto) remained after the first round. This series was a battle
between No. 6 (Boston) and No. 7 (Buffalo). Everything that
everybody had said was the gospel truth. And that's why this will
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be watching the Toronto-Buffalo series,'' vowed
Heinze, who came up awfully big in the playoffs. ``We thought we
could go farther. We believe we have something special here. It was
just a matter of a bounce, one way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A few shifts here and a few shifts there in their favor,''
agreed Rob DiMaio. ``That was the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   That might have been an oversimplification, but Heinze and
DiMaio can be forgiven. Like everyone else in the room, they had
given everything there was to give, and now they were hurting
inside, completely firm in the belief that the Buffalo team
advancing to play Toronto isn't a damn bit better than they are,
starting with the goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   Dominik Hasek may be Dominik Hasek, but he did not win this
series for the Sabres. ``That was never even a question,''
maintained Carter. ``We knew from our experience and from watching
the tapes that Buffalo was not a one-man team. One individual
wasn't going to beat us _ and he didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading Byron Dafoe for Hasek wouldn't have improved the Bruins'
chances. Trading just about anybody for Michael Peca would have.
The nasty forward with the angelic face (and amazingly tiny body)
did everything he was supposed to do, including scoring the game's
first goal Tuesday night. One thing that might improve the Bruins'
chances of continuing this step-by-step march to the Stanley Cup
would be to study tapes of Peca's six-game series in the hopes of
figuring out just how this wonderful player does what he does.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins didn't leave anything in reserve. What they had to
give was what we got to see, and that includes every trick Burns
could think of. The mentor railed about physical play throughout,
accusing Peca of ``getting away with murder'' and moaning that Ken
Belanger constantly was being targeted by officials with ``radar''
trained on No. 18, and No. 18 alone. I would say the chances of an
``I told ya' so'' tumbling out of Burns's lips when Belanger was
sent off for roughing in the second period were pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff shrugged it all off, often answering
with playful jests of his own. ``What Pat said didn't anger me,''
Ruff declared. ``He was just doing his best to disrupt my thought
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns did what he did because all is fair in love, war, and
Stanley Cup series. You prod and push and jolt your own team. You
make public appeals to the referees. You do whatever it takes,
especially when you know in your heart of hearts that the other
team is more experienced and just plain savvier in the whys and
wherefores of playoff hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 3-1, the season a little more than a minute away from
its conclusion, the Bruins put a smile on the crusty coach's face.
They ensured that Buffalo would stagger, not swagger, its way to
the finals.
</P>
<P>
   They may be tired and frustrated today, but we know one thing
for sure. Their pride is intact. The Bruins will be back.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
