<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S TREAT TWINS TO THREE-MARTINEZ LAUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On a night against the Twins, Edgar Martinez provided
triplets.
</P>
<P>
   Over 24 hours, he threw a party of five.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it was a birth announcement people won't soon
forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I played the last two days, I think I'm better than
ever,'' the 36-year-old Martinez said. ``I feel like 21.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking batting practice at the expense of Minnesota for the
second consecutive night, the Mariners designated hitter launched
three home runs to help punish the visitors 10-1 at the Kingdome
Tuesday _ giving him five long balls in two games and the second
hat trick of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's two-game outburst tied a major league record, making
him the 21st player to pull this feat.
</P>
<P>
   He hit one to each field in the fifth, sixth and eighth innings,
giving him seven homers for the season.
</P>
<P>
   And people said he was in a batting slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have occasional power, but five in two days?'' said
Martinez, who has been on a tear since sitting out Sunday's
contest. ``You see guys like Junior (Ken Griffey Jr.) do it. I
guess it amazes me.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's efforts meshed nicely with another superb outing by
rookie pitcher Freddy Garcia, who was back after a 10-day injury
layoff, prompted by a Chili Davis liner that tattooed his right
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia didn't leave until he said so this time. So fluid and
poised for his 22 years, he allowed just the one run on seven hits,
walking one and striking out three.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Garcia a team-leading fifth victory in six
decisions, the Mariners a season-best-tying third win in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The home club (18-21) will try pull off its first series sweep
of the season against the Twins Wednesday night, concluding a
six-game homestand before touring Kansas City and Minnesota.
Long-suffering M's lefty Jeff Fassero will face the Twins' Mike
Lincoln. The way things have been reversing themselves lately,
Fassero might find some solace.
</P>
<P>
   When Garcia went down in New York, the big right-hander was one
of the few good things the Mariners had going. He's just one of the
guys now.
</P>
<P>
   Another would be Ken Griffey Jr., who smacked his
major-league-leading 15th homer into the right-field seats in the
first inning, getting the onslaught rolling. With a nice easy
swing, Griffey reached for a low delivery on the first offering
from Dan Perkins and sent it into a tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   And now Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time AL batting champ was slumping, his average at an
unEdgar-like .277, hearing the same subtle digs he's been hearing
for the past couple years _ that he finally might be slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   All that makes him do is shrug. And start hitting like an
absolute mad man.
</P>
<P>
   After grounding out and flying out, the Martinez rampage got
started in the sixth. He led off with a homer to right, the ball
slicing away from him for a 6-1 Mariner lead.
</P>
<P>
   He said the pitch was high in the strike zone, a little outside.
Swat.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, Martinez pulled one to left with Alex Rodriguez
aboard, putting his club up 9-1.
</P>
<P>
   He saw a slider down the middle of the plate. Boom.
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, Martinez led off the eighth with a blast to
straightaway center, putting a final exclamation mark on a
power-filled evening.
</P>
<P>
   High and down the middle. Gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a joke,'' Mariner backup catcher Tom Lampkin said.
``That was unbelievable. It didn't even look like he was swinging
at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Lou Piniella, ``One of Edgar's strengths his whole
career is he can use (the field) line to line. That's why you see
him with a .320 career batting average.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, his homer exploits themselves awe-inspiring, presented
Martinez with three cigars, one for each long ball. Moments before,
he had teased his teammate, asking him what time they were going to
eat?
</P>
<P>
   Providing a translation, Martinez said, ``He wants to know what
I've been eating these last few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's other three-homer night came in July 1996 at Texas.
This one was better, because he supposedly wasn't swinging as well.
</P>
<P>
   As he wrapped up his interviews, Martinez was asked if he would
sit for an ESPN radio interview, a little national exposure. He
said he would if there was time.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was headed for a postgame workout.
</P>
<P>
   Don't all 21-year-olds do that?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
