r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE-VALUES-SFCHRON     05-19 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-VALUES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE NO LONGER ALONE ON `FAMILY VALUES' PLATFORM
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Exactly seven years ago, Vice President Dan
Quayle blasted America's cultural landscape by attacking the
hippest feminist and single mom on television _ Murphy Brown.
</P>
<P>
   His now-famous ``Poverty of Values'' speech in San Francisco, in
which he lambasted the popular TV character for choosing to be a
single mom, put Quayle on the front lines of the family values
debate and made him the punch line of late-night TV talk shows
across America.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Quayle will mark the anniversary of the ``Murphy
Brown'' speech with another address to the Commonwealth Club of
California as he attempts to move from dark horse to front-runner
in the race for the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But this year he is hardly a lone voice on family values. A pack
of presidential hopefuls _ Republicans and Democrats alike _ are
rushing to champion the issue.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of incidents of youth violence, including the
Littleton massacre, the question of family values resonates with
more voters and politicians, experts say. If the 1996 election was
about ``the economy, stupid,'' some pundits suggest next year's
vote will be about what's close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Baby Boomers have kids, and they're starting to get
grandkids ... but while there's a sense that the economy's doing
great, it's not enough,'' said Karl Rove, chief strategist to the
campaign of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who has stressed issues like
juvenile crime, welfare reform and family health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government plays a role in that _ encouraging a society of
responsibility, in which people attempt to do their best,'' Rove
said.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing dialogue on the issue by a host of presidential
hopefuls underscores both the enduring appeal of family values as a
political theme and its evolution as America heads into the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle kicked off the debate in 1992 when he delivered the
speech in San Francisco that vilified one of America's most popular
TV characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help matters when prime-time TV has Murphy Brown, a
character who supposedly epitomizes today's intelligent, highly
paid professional women, mocking the importance of fathers by
bearing a child alone and calling it just another `lifestyle
choice,''' Quayle told the Commonwealth Club of California in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle spokesman Jonathan Baron says the former vice president
``clearly won the debate on the debate over values. ... (He) made
it safe for the political leaders to confront the decline in the
culture that threatens so much of our society.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that was the beginning,'' Baron said. ``Now he is on a
mission to achieve a restoration of values.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle is hardly alone in that quest.
</P>
<P>
   These days, ``Republicans, Democrats, you name it _ everyone
wants family values. ... Everyone agrees they're important,'' said
GOP analyst Dan Schnur. ``The partisan debate is now over the role
of government in the family values arena.''
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, the discussion of family values encompasses
topics like violence prevention, mental health services and even
old-fashioned parental controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to give a kid a rule to break than no rule at
all,'' said Tipper Gore, wife of Vice President and Democratic
front-runner Al Gore, in a recent interview with The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, that's what I do as a parent,'' she said. ``I'm not
saying my kids are perfect. But it is up to us to teach our
children values.''
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore has discussed her own bout with depression and the
need for more counseling services while pushing her husband's
proposals on education, guns and youth violence. For Republicans,
family values can range from Pat Buchanan's emphasis on religious
values to Elizabeth Dole's support for gun control to Gary Bauer's
critique of homosexuality to the parental responsibility issues
raised by Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I have five daughters. If that's not a reality
check (on family values), I don't know what is,'' said Forbes, in
an interview in Sacramento last week.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the Littleton tragedy, Forbes said it isn't a
question of gun control but a return to the high expectations and
strict guidelines that many Baby Boomer parents like himself recall
from their own youth.
</P>
<P>
   Among the presidential hopefuls lining up to stake their claim
to the issue:
</P>
<P>
   -- Gore, who unveiled a detailed educational plan this week,
calling for increased school discipline, including
``second-chance'' schools to help at-risk kids and a host of other
proposals that he said would improve the prospects for both kids
and families in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   -- Senator John McCain, R-Ariz., who was part of the original
V-chip coalition. He joined Democratic Senator Joseph Lieberman, of
Connecticut, in introducing a resolution calling for the surgeon
general to study the impact of media violence on children.
</P>
<P>
   -- Elizabeth Dole, who has argued passionately for gun control
in recent weeks and has called for programs for at-risk youth and
educational reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah DiVito Hardman, former president of the California
Christian Coalition and now grassroots state coordinator for
Forbes, said voters are now as concerned with their families'
spiritual well-being as they are with their economic health.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are starting to look at the big picture, and they're
seeing things here and there,'' Hardman said. ``It's not just
Littleton ... (but Littleton) creates a fear _ and fear is a
terribly motiving factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have been out front on the family values issue haven't
necessarily found it easy to be pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan Quayle ... set off a match in a gas can when he delivered
the Murphy Brown speech,'' said Leslie Goodman, a GOP consultant
and editor of politicalaccess.com, a leading political Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a crusader for something he's felt strongly about,''
and should have been applauded, not ridiculed, she said. ``Tipper
Gore has been a leader of another crusade, and she talks about
mental health and the availability of counseling. ... That's
another piece of the puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Gray Davis' wife, Sharon, who is outspoken on
family issues, recalled that ``people ridiculed (Tipper Gore) and
said she should be minding her own business ... (but) I admire her
for being right at the cutting edge at a time when it wasn't
popular. It's so easy to get on the bandwagon after you've had a
huge tragedy like Littleton.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Quayle is hoping to position himself at the center of
the values debate for the year 2000. ``Remember, Murphy Brown is
gone, and I'm still here fighting for the American people,'' Quayle
said, in announcing his presidential run earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Reprising that theme _ and the speech is San Francisco _ is a
savvy but risky idea, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``By coming back for the sequel, he's reminding people his
original point was a good one,'' said Schnur.
</P>
<P>
   But ``you cannot give an I-told-you-so speech,'' said one GOP
insider. ``(That) doesn't get us where we need to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, a Bush supporter, cited the Texas governor's successful
youth and volunteer programs as evidence of the family values that
Americans will demand in the next election. The successful
presidential candidate for the year 2000, she said, will be
``talking about what should be and will be. Lay out your game plan,
and tell us the solutions you propose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
