 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 431 - May 19, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 431 -- May 19, 1999 We are offering
the following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. RACHEL, RACHEL Rachel Weisz, 28, worked hard at not growing
up - until now. Although she earned a reputation for dating her
co-stars and appearing nude on screen, this English stage and film
actress may be getting ready to act like an adult. Responsibility
looms with three movies due out in the U.S: the $90 million remake
of ``The Mummy,'' Michael Winterbottom's dark sexual thriller ``I
Want You,'' and the historical epic ``The Taste of Sunshine,''
co-starring Ralph Fiennes and William Hurt. By James Fallon. W
Magazine. 1,500 words + photos.
</P>
<P>
   2. FOLK HEROES : PETER, PAUL AND MARY TUNE UP FOR THE
</P>
<P>
   NEXT MILLENNIUM It's been almost four decades since three folk
singers combined talents for a concert at Greenwich Village's
``Bitter End'' coffee house, and Peter, Paul and Mary are still
going strong. Their latest album, ``Songs of Conscience and
Concern'' is a collection of their lesser-known songs that they
feel deserve a wider audience, and one new song, ``Don't Laugh At
Me,'' whose message seems especially appropriate in the wake of the
tragedy in Littleton, Colorado. By Bonnie Siegler. 1,500 words +
photos.
</P>
<P>
   3. MOVIES AREN'T THE VILLAIN Gary Ross, a writer and director
whose films include ``Big,'' ``Dave'' and ``Pleasantville,'' writes
that it is absurd to blame the movie industry for a climat of
violence in which a tragedy such as the Littleton school massacre
can occur. New York Times Op-Ed. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   4. STAR WARS PACKAGE We are offering the following features to
celebrate the opening of the film ``The Phantom Menace'': A. The
Force Is With Samuel L. Jackson cf ENT. 429 B. The Man Who Would Be
Obi-Wan Kenobi cf ENT. 429 C. Fans in the Grip of 'Star Wars' Fever
cf ENT. 429 D. Force Field : A 'Star Wars Quiz' cf ENT. 429 E. The
Source Behind the Force : 'Star Wars' Producer Rick McCallum. F.
Liam Neeson interview cf ENT. 429 Art is available. Please contact
us for further details.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   5. THE GIRL WHO WOULD BE QUEEN : NATALIE PORTMAN TALKS
</P>
<P>
   'STAR WARS' Natalie Portman won't be waiting to see the film
``Star Wars : The Phantom Menace'' (in which she plays Queen
Amidala,) on its release day in the U.S. The 17-year-old will be
taking her biology final ... By Cindy Pearlman. 1,500 words.
________________________________________________________ 6.
EVERETT'S PEAK After an auspicious debut, Rupert Everett struggled
for years under his own notoriety as Hollywood's gay poster boy.
Now with three movies coming out, he's back on top. By Merle
Ginsberg. From W Magazine. 1,500 words + photo.
</P>
<P>
   7. MR. NICE GUY Capital punishment may be a divisive issue but
it has been very good to Alice Cooper. It's been a big part of the
singer's professional life as he has been ``executed'' night after
night on the concert stages of the world for more than a quarter of
a century. Cooper may die for his sins, but he always comes back
from the grave, prancing and preening. ``Always with the best of
taste,'' he adds. By Jim Sullivan. BPI. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
THE ROMANCE IS BACK FOR HUGH GRANT Hugh Grant's appeal has survived
several resounding box-office flops and even some Divine
intervention. He may soon be more popular than ever, as he returns
to romantic comedy - the genre most favoured by his fans - for
``Notting Hill,'' co-starring Julia Roberts. He admits that the
film's look at celebrity, the tabloid press and the paparazzi hit
home for him. By Ian Spelling. 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
T2 : 3D ONE OF A KIND SPECTACLE Universal Studios has developed the
ultimate attraction for movie fanatics. It's not just a 3D film,
its a multi-sensory ride that virtually delivers the audience
straight into the 1991 Arnold Schwarzenegger blockbuster
``Terminator 2.'' ``Terminator 2: 3D'' combines the most
sophisticated 3D imaging with live-action stunt work, blurring the
line between the silver screen and reality. By Tamara Conniff. BPI.
800 words + photos.
</P>
