<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Now the tough part
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The impressive election of Ehud Barak as prime minister of
Israel is, most agree, convivial to the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is a general and a national hero like his great
predecessor, Yitzhak Rabin. That gets him some initial respect.
(Like Rabin, he has only small reserves of charisma. The defeated
Benjamin Netanyahu had tons of charisma, and look where that got
him.)
</P>
<P>
   Barak will guard Israel's borders without giving away the store.
He can trade some West Bank land for time. The West Bank has always
been an overly hyped issue. More substantive matters _ security,
economics, water _ have never really been seriously visited. Then
there are the intransigents who have never been rendered placable
about anything _ Israel's vivacious far right, Hamas, Hezbollah,
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   New ideas are needed. Everyone stays busy verifying the old
ones. If Ehud Barak has any, now's the time.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
