</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Updating Your Little Black Book  
 By David Einstein   
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Question: &LR;  I often get e-mail from people whom I'd like to add
to my Address Book, but creating new contacts is time-consuming. Is
there an easy way in Outlook 98 to transfer e-mail addresses in
messages to the Address Book?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Indeed, there is. Open up the message. Now right-click
on the sender's e-mail address, which you'll see on the From: line
at the top of the window. Choose Add to Contacts from the menu that
pops up. This will bring up the Contact dialog box and
automatically insert the e-mail address. You also can use the box
to add other useful information you may have about the person, such
as a phone number. When you're done, click Save and Close.
</P>
<P>
   Browsing Solution
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am running Windows 98 on a fairly new computer. When I'm
using Internet Explorer 4, I often get ``frozen'' and can't escape
the program. As a result, I am forced to shut down by turning the
power off. Is there some way to get the computer to quit the
program without having to do that?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have an uncle who sometimes freezes, and we've found that
the best way to get him going again is to shout at him. But yelling
at your computer isn't going to help. There is something you can
try, however. Press one of the Control keys (they're probably
labeled Ctrl) and, at the same time, press one of the Alt keys and
the Delete key. This will display the Close Program box. In theory,
if you then click End Task, the program will close and you can get
back to business.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the Ctrl-Alt-Del combination sometimes doesn't
work. In which case you can do one of two things: Press
Ctrl-Alt-Del twice in a row, which should restart the computer, or
do what you've been doing and shut down the system.
</P>
<P>
   Because your problem seems to happen most often in Internet
Explorer 4, you also might try downloading the latest version of
the browser, IE 5, which may prove more stable for you. You can get
it for free at www.microsoft.com/ie.
</P>
<P>
   Font Frenzy
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there way to print out all the fonts in Word 97 for
comparative viewing? If not, is there another resource for doing
it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Windows only lets you print separate samples of each font. To
do that, go to Fonts in the Control Panel (Start
Button/Settings/Control Panel/Fonts), double-click a font and click
Print.
</P>
<P>
   That having been said, there are some good third-party programs
that can print the comparative lists for you. One that's gotten
high marks in reviews is FontLister, a $5 shareware program that
you can download from ZDNet's software library at www.hotfiles.com.
</P>
<P>
   At the same site, you also can download a free program that lets
you view a sample list of fonts right from the Word toolbar _ which
may save you the trouble of having to print them. This is a feature
that Microsoft has included in some other programs, notably
Publisher, but which for some reason hasn't been available in Word.
(It will be, however, with the arrival of Office 2000 next month.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the program you should try is called ``Enhanced
Drop-Down Font List for MS Word 97,'' which is about as descriptive
as a name can get.
</P>
<P>
   CD-ROM Facts
</P>
<P>
   Q: Currently my system has a 40x CD-ROM drive. I would like to
install a recordable CD-ROM drive (CDR) so I can record stuff on
CDs for backup purposes. But the CDR I have in mind has a slower
reading speed than the CD-ROM drive I already have. Is it possible
to have two CD drives at the same time?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure it's possible, but I don't know whether there's much
advantage to it. The CDR drive you're contemplating probably reads
at 24x, which is plenty fast. And since it can also read ordinary
CDs, it would make your existing CD-ROM drive redundant.
</P>
<P>
   One benefit of having two CD drives is that you could copy a CD
directly. But that's time consuming, and it's actually easier to
``rip'' information off a CD, store it temporarily on your hard
drive, then write it to a blank CD. And for that procedure, all you
need is the CDR.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Tired of the same old sounds that your computer emits when you
start Windows, shut down your system or perform other Windows
functions? You can easily customize your system with short audio
clips that you can record or download from the Web. Once you have
the sounds on your hard drive (they must be stored in ``.wav''
files), use the Sounds feature in the Windows Control Panel to
substitute them for the boring Windows sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-12-99 2051EDT &QL;
</P>
