<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2821 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-INTERNET-SURVIVAL     05-19 1846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-SURVIVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET'S TOP PLAYERS MIX STRATEGY, GRIT TO SURVIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ In December 1997, when the cappuccino
machine first appeared at the headquarters of Yahoo Inc., it didn't
deliver quite the jolt that executives had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were e-mails to me and everybody saying this is
rubbish,'' recalls company president Jeff Mallett. ``Why are we
wasting money on a cappuccino machine? Let's put it back into the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Only when workers learned that Yahoo founders David Filo and
Jerry Yang had paid for the machine from their own pockets did
their outrage subside.
</P>
<P>
   It's plainly one of Mallett's favorite stories, part of the
Yahoo mystique. Here's one of the Internet's premier firms, a
company with a stock market value of $30 billion, and it still
revels in its scrappy image.
</P>
<P>
   Just as well. Because Yahoo and other elite Internet firms can't
afford to forget that they're in the fight of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the high values the market has placed on Internet
stocks. Most of the high-flyers earn slim profits, if any. But the
stocks stay up thanks to investors who believe that some of these
hot companies will still be hot _ and profitable _ a few years down
the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully believe that many of the Web companies that we see
today will become mammoths of the next millennium. But many more
will cease to exist,'' says Bob Davis, chief executive of Waltham,
Mass. Web service Lycos Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Already there's a top tier of firms like Yahoo, Amazon.com and
America Online Inc., companies so well entrenched that only a drop
in the IQ of top managers could kill them. The eBay auction site
has established itself as the standard by which on-line auction
sites are judged. Other companies, like Lycos, have built huge
audiences but are still trying to lock down a position of industry
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Pay close attention, and it's clear that all of the hot Net
firms have bet on a set of basic strategies they think will assure
their survival and dominance over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  At first glance, the Web titans seem to face a simple
problem: Anybody can do what they do. Internet access and Web
technologies are available to all. In theory, any small-timer with
a good idea could knock Yahoo or eBay off its perch virtually
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, it's not that simple. Most of the leaders were among
the first in their niche _ Yahoo and Lycos in Web searching, eBay
in auctions, Amazon in retailing. In an infant industry, their head
start has helped establish them as recognized brand names. Now
they're spending millions to lock in their brands and freeze out
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's done it better than AOL. It was once dwarfed by firms
like Prodigy and CompuServe. But TV and print ads, and a tidal wave
of free AOL software disks have made the firm perhaps the
best-known name on the Internet. AOL's research claims that over
half of all Americans think of AOL when they think of the Internet,
while fewer than one-tenth think of Yahoo or Microsoft. Brags AOL
Interactive Services Group president Barry Schuler: ``America
Online, when it comes to on-line services, is the only company
that's a true national brand.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Internet companies are aiming to win superbrand status
for themselves. Amazon, for instance, is stifling a competitive
threat from rival on-line bookseller Barnes &AMP; Noble.com by using
aggressive pricing and heavy advertising. Amazon's first-quarter
revenue of $293.6 million far outstripped Barnes &AMP; Noble's $32.3
million. David Risher, Amazon's vice president of marketing, says
the power of the Amazon brand deserves much of the credit. ``You
talk to a lot of people, they don't tell you they bought a book or
a CD,'' says Risher. ``They tell you they bought it at
Amazon.com.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  And Amazon regulars find it's ridiculously simple to keep on
buying. That's because the company created a system that memorizes
address and credit card data the first time a customer buys. To buy
another book tomorrow, there's no need to retype the data.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of another vital leadership strategy _ keeping it
simple.
</P>
<P>
   Early commercial Web sites were saturated with color photos and
dancing animated images _ stuff that can take forever to download
on a home computer. Yahoo was having none of it. ``Users don't want
that,'' Mallett says. ``What users want is fast, clean and so
forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Yahoo has never strayed from its bland
blue-on-white graphics and near-total absence of graphics. And the
company still has a team of living, breathing humans at its Santa
Clara, Calif. campus who spend their days creating the Yahoo Web
index. Instead of overwhelming the searcher with millions of
``hits,'' Yahoo displays a list of categories that quickly guide
the user to the needed information. These days, practically every
search site on the Web emulates Yahoo's simple design.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  Simplicity has its downside, though. If a visitor finds what
he's looking for, and immediately leaves, it's hard to make money
off of him. Successful Internet sites must get people to visit
frequently and hang around _ the better to sell them things and
flash ads on their screens.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``stickiness,'' and it's a crucial measurement of an
Internet company's success.
</P>
<P>
   In the stickiness sweepstakes, AOL's the one with the tube of
superglue. The company claims its 17 million users stay on the
service for an average of 55 minutes a day, far and away the best
performance in the industry. But remember that AOL, unlike almost
every other Net business, is more than a Web site. It's an Internet
service provider as well.
</P>
<P>
   Web companies that don't have their own on-line services need
other ways to build user loyalty. They're doing it by letting
visitors personalize the site. With special software, visitors to
Yahoo or Lycos can create their own custom Web page, with the
information and features that matter to them.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants like Amazon build up a database of information about
everything the visitor has ever purchased. Return to the site and
you're greeted by name, and told about new products and services
you might want to buy. ``In a physical store, you can't be all
things to all people,'' says Amazon's Risher. ``In mine, you can do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more notable are efforts by Web leaders to create on-line
communities, where visitors become participants in electronic
subcultures. Yahoo is spending $3.6 billion to buy the GeoCities
Web hosting site, where 3.5 million subscribers build personal Web
sites and maintain hundreds of communities appealing to a vast
range of tastes and interests. Lycos has done the same by acquiring
the Tripod and Angelfire Web hosting services.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most surprising community site is eBay. People come
to the Internet auction house in search of bargains, but thousands
stick around to chat. ``That is what eBay is based on,'' says Steve
Westly, the company's marketing chief. ``We are about changing
lives here.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, eBay is one of the stickiest sites on the Web.
According to the research firm Media Metrix Inc., eBay's 6.5
million users in February spent an average of two hours a month on
the site. That's far behind AOL, but vastly better than most Web
properties. By comparison, Amazon holds its average visitor for a
mere 12 minutes a month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  Amazon is trying to find new ways to get visitors hooked.
Born as a bookstore, Amazon now sells recorded music, videos,
flowers and other gift items. In March the company launched a new
auction site to tap into eBay's market. Amazon even has a free
service for e-mailing electronic greeting cards. Risher says it's
just one more way to bring in visitors who might stay and shop.
</P>
<P>
   All the Web leaders figure that more is better, and they're
constantly adding new features. Search services like Yahoo, Lycos
and AOL's Web home page are now ``portals,'' with free e-mail and
Web page services, chat rooms, message boards _ anything that might
reel in more users.
</P>
<P>
   Not that this is a certain path to success. Yahoo's Mallett says
it's just too easy for Web firms to copy each others' innovations.
``We may have a 90-day advantage over some people . . . but that
would be a long time,'' he says. ``Most of the time, the next day,
AOL or Microsoft will pop up with a similar service.''
</P>
<P>
   But while flashy features may not give Web firms a lasting edge,
they do force competitors to play follow the leader. Fancy features
also screen out market newcomers. To take on a Yahoo or a AOL,
you've got to have at least as much to offer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  That was the daunting challenge that faced Lycos little more
than a year ago. One of the first search engines, it had become an
industry also-ran, its visitor count far behind Yahoo and AOL. Then
chief executive Davis got out his checkbook and bought several
major Web services, weaving them into a new Lycos Network.
</P>
<P>
   The push for eyeballs has paid off. Media Metrix recently found
that Lycos had edged past Yahoo in total visitors for the month of
March. ``I think what has proven to be the most challenging
issue,'' says Davis, ``is how to build and sustain a meaningful
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether an on-line company hopes to make money by selling goods
and services to consumers or advertising to businesses, the model
depends on drawing in millions of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   There's still a vast untapped Web audience in the United States,
where only about one-quarter of the population is regularly on
line. All the Web leaders are bombarding the masses with radio, TV
and print ads to tempt them to log on. But AOL is in the strongest
position to reach the unwired because it operates its own Internet
service, not just a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's Mallett says that in five years, half a billion people
will be on line. Most won't be American. No surprise then that
Yahoo and every other major Web company is making aggressive moves
overseas. Yahoo has 18 foreign subsidiaries providing custom Web
content in Europe, Asia and Latin America. AOL's purchase of the
struggling on-line service CompuServe has made it a major Internet
provider in Europe. Lycos has 10 foreign sites. Amazon's biggest
on-line bookstores are in Britain and Germany and eBay is running
on-line auctions in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about locking in dominant market position. AOL, backed
by billions in subscriber revenue, has already pulled it off. It's
the standard that the other Web-based companies aspire to.
</P>
<P>
   That's why even now the Yahoo people work in an anonymous
low-rise building with cheap gray plastic chairs, preferring to
pump every spare dime into efforts to dominate one of the world's
most competitive industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running a business,'' says Mallett. ``Everything
matters. Every single hire matters. Every single light bulb
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when you're already on top _ if you plan to stay there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-12-99 1351EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
