<HEADER>
A2824 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MILNER-COLUMN20     05-19 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MILNER-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wolfe was wrong; it is quite possible to go home again
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I think it was Tom Wolfe who said, ``You can't
go home again.'' That's not the Tom Wolfe who wrote ``The Right
Stuff'' and those other recent books, but the other one who wrote
those mammoth novels a generation or two ago.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe's declaration has been challenged many times in the
decades since he first came up with it. Some have agreed and some
haven't.
</P>
<P>
   I have just recently made a return trip to my old home town,
Lubbock, ``The Hub of the Plains and the Home of Texas'' and it was
indeed a trip. Make that A Trip!
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards I was somewhat dazzled by the experience. Felt a lot
like jet lag. I'm pretty sure I had fun, though.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing it was exhilarating to again, after more than 30
years, see how outrageously flat the country is out there on the
Texas High Plains. I remembered it being flat, of course, having
lived out there from babyhood until I went into the Navy to help
win WWII by teaching Waves how to swim at Waikiki Beach. But it is
flatter and the sky is bigger than I recalled. I love it!
</P>
<P>
   The occasion for this return to my home town was something
called ``Raising a Reader Book Festival'' put on by the Barnes and
Noble Bookstores and the Lubbock Area Coalition for Literacy. A
lady named Ann Boggs was the head honcho and did a marvelous job of
putting it together and keeping it rolling smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   I talked with some students at my old high school, the
magnificent Lubbock High School, built back when they really knew
how to build schools and the cost wasn't so high they could follow
through as they pleased, and at one of the ``new'' high schools
(meaning one built after I left town) Monterey High. Each session
was attended by students who were truly interested in books and
authors and such as that, and each session was an experience to be
remembered and cherished.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the real highlight: a book signing session at the
bookstore attended by several of my former teammates and classmates
at Lubbock High and their wives, children, and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   That's when I started feeling the jet lag.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the first comment by my former football teammates was
along the lines of ``Put on a little weight there, haven't you,
hoss.'' No question mark at the end of that sentence, you see. It
was a statement of fact.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they had put on some heft as well, but not as much as
I had. I allowed as how I am on a strict diet now and going to the
gym at least twice a week and will soon again be looking like the
slender racing animal I once was.
</P>
<P>
   The tidings passed along by my old friends included both happy
and sad things. A couple of old friends had died I hadn't heard
about and one former teammate, a co-captain my senior year, was
reported to have Alzheimers. But the remarkable aspect of this old
friends session for me was the fact that those who were there
didn't appear to be all that different than they were way back
before the big war. There was a lot more grey hair, of course, and
reports of bad knees and such as that, but beneath it all they
looked and sounded astonishingly similar to the way they looked and
sounded way back when.
</P>
<P>
   As my friend Joe Murray has written, I grind out a new book
every 35 or so years. But after that return home to autograph my
latest one (''Confessions of a Maddog'', University of North Texas
Press) I've decided it won't be that long before I grind out
another one and get to go back home again.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for The Lufkin Daily News, Lufkin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
