<HEADER>
A2825 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-WEBMD-COX &LR;      05-19 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEBMD-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
WebMD shifts gears, cancels plan for IPO 
By Michael E. Kanell  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WebMD, one of the hottest Internet plays in Atlanta,
has for the second time pulled back from the brink of an initial
public offering of stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company, which hopes to become the leading
site for health care information on the Net, filed a formal request
with the Securities and Exchange Commission to withdraw its
much-ballyhooed IPO.
</P>
<P>
   ``This request is made because the company has decided to pursue
a strategy that does not involve the offer and sale of its shares
to the public,'' wrote Jeffrey Arnold, WebMD chairman and chief
executive, in the SEC document, which was dated May 12.
``Therefore, the company has decided not to engage in an initial
public offering at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   An IPO had originally been slated for early May, then was
delayed before being shelved Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold was not available after filing the statement. Other
company officials, who have said nothing this week, said there
would be no comment beyond the written statement to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   But rumors about the company have been swirling for weeks, and
the retreat from a lucrative IPO can only feed still more frantic
speculation. A similar, if less well-publicized, IPO filing last
summer was withdrawn when the market turned suddenly chilly. But
since then, the climate has reversed, and numerous Net-related
companies have soared in sometimes-delirious trading.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, WebMD launched its Internet business and chalked up a
series of deals with large players. WebMD registered for an IPO in
February, hoping to raise up to $55 million.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the launch seems to have been canceled _ or at least
postponed _ not for lack of likely investment but the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Bloomberg News reported that Microsoft had committed
to paying $300 million in exchange for 27 percent of WebMD. That
report was never confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, CNBC's David Faber reported Microsoft had
failed to strike a deal, but that continued talks indicated the
market value for the young company was climbing past the $2.5
billion mark.
</P>
<P>
   And where Microsoft is sniffing, other investors may not be far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   An IPO is typically a way for a young and unproven company to
trade control for cash, raising money that can bankroll operations
and expansion until its budding business takes off. An IPO also
lets early investors and executives turn at least some of their
shares into hefty checks.
</P>
<P>
   But WebMD, whose business by most accounts is not near
profitability, has already turned its promise into some cash. Most
impressively, the company announced a five-year, $220 million
investment by DuPont, which will hold two seats on the WebMD board.
</P>
<P>
   And if WebMD is poised for an injection anywhere in the
neighborhood north of $300 million, an IPO right now seems
unneeded. The early investors can surely get whatever payoff they
need, while the company grows. Assuming WebMD succeeds, it can bide
its time for a still more lucrative IPO in the future.
</P>
<P>
   As for the chances of success, there's no guarantee. But what
better indicators than an aggressive business plan, piles of cash
and the imprimatur of Microsoft?
</P>
<P>
   WebMD at first conceived a two-pronged strategy, going after
consumers to be sure, but expecting to make its money serving
doctors and other professionals who would be charged for various
services and special professionals-only information.
</P>
<P>
   But over the months, that strategy seems to have morphed until
the emphasis has seemingly come to rest on consumers who will
access the free side of the site. That shift to the consumers
expecting free access means advertising is key, and that means that
brand recognition matters.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD has deals with Lycos and CNN, as well as various providers
of health care information. Each deal adds content to the WebMD
site, each adding reasons that a Net surfer would visit
www.WebMD.com. And the more visits and the more eyes that ``drill
down'' into the site, the more WebMD can charge advertisers for
space.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD is not entering an empty field. Scores of entrepreneurs
have noticed that health care, which accounts for 14 percent of the
nation's $6 trillion-a-year economy, could be a monstrous market on
the Net as well. Hundreds of sites have emerged as competitors for
that market, but thus far, none is dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Among a slew of rivals are Atlanta companies like ADAM.com and
Medcast.
</P>
<P>
   Other contenders have some brand recognition of their own,
including sites of the Mayo Clinic and former Surgeon General C.
Everett Koop.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
