<SLUG> BC-DOUBLE-DUTCH-JUMPROPE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Double dutch the game, catching on quickly the aim
 &HT;    By Cara Ann
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Smack-dab in this month's issue of
``Teen People'' is a fashion spread starring Stan's Pepper
Steppers, the reigning world champs of double-dutch rope jumping.
</P>
<P>
   Bring down the old clothesline from grandma's attic. This sport
is cool.
</P>
<P>
   Double-dutch jumping, first popular in New York City, involves
two ropes twirling in opposite directions and one or two jumpers
doing tricks _ flips, rolls, push-ups, all without stopping.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's just catching on around here, again. Palm Beach
County used to send a team to the national tournament every year.
Then the elementary school teachers who organized teams moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, one simply transferred. Felisa Miles wound up at Lake
Worth High, with no double-dutch team and the responsibility of
hosting last weekend's state tournament.
</P>
<P>
   She rustled up an old elementary student of hers _ Donald
Mundell, now 18 _ and two others who knew how to jump.
</P>
<P>
   They had months to prepare for the tournament. Pahokee Middle
School had just two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know the rules until Monday,'' says physical
education teacher Paula Yeater, who heard about the tournament and
organized students. They used flag football jerseys for uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Pahokee eighth-graders Joyetta Burgess, Brittney Godfrey and
Rochanna Geffare participated in speed-jumping, a two-minute
sprint-in-place measured by how many times a jumper's left foot
hits the floor.
</P>
<P>
   They jumped 35 times. More experienced teams from Broward County
jumped 265 and 285 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got another year before we get like this,'' says
Godfrey, watching the freestyle competition with its flips and
turns.
</P>
<P>
   But one young Palm Beach County team made it to nationals, after
just a year of jumping. Maggie Gonzalez and Meika and Brittany
Bodwell, third-graders with West Palm Beach Girl Scout Troop 14,
will compete in Hartford, Conn., in June.
</P>
<P>
   Troop sponsor Mary Dean thinks the school system should pick up
double-dutch as a competitive sport for girls, like softball.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people just don't know about it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet.
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
