A2827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-SPANDEX20-COX     05-19 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SPANDEX20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spandex gives clothing comfort, flexibility
 &HT;    (EDS: Art available.)
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ S-T-R-E-T-C-H out and relax _ it's going to be a
fluid-fit, wrinkle-free, comfy-as-can-be summer.
</P>
<P>
   Stretchy spandex and Lycra fibers are showing up in trace
amounts in everything from clingy dresses to plus-size shirts and
from trousers to tailored jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, these fibers, which can stretch up to six times their
original length, were found mostly in workout wear, swimwear and
under garments.
</P>
<P>
   Now manufacturers are using them in all kinds of clothing. Knit
shirts and sweaters sport a bit of the stretchy fiber. Suits and
capris offer some flexibility, as do shorts and skirts. Most of
these stretchy clothes can be found in the juniors and plus-size
departments, while only a few items with spandex or Lycra can be
found in women's.
</P>
<P>
   ``These clothes can be in dressy or casual, depending on where
you're going,'' said Cassandra Rayson, department manager at Stein
Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Spandex is the generic term for elastane, man-made elastic
fibers. Lycra is a registered brand of spandex made only by DuPont,
which developed the fiber in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Spandex or Lycra can be combined with just about any other
fiber, including cotton, rayon, polyester, acrylic, acetate, etc. A
little bit of it goes a long way, too. Spandex or Lycra is usually
found in small portions in garments _ from 1 percent to 8 percent _
which doesn't change the appearance of the fabric, yet offers a
smooth, fluid-form silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   Garments with these fibers are very ``wearable'' and have a
bounce-back stretching quality so they retain their shape better,
even when stretched and washed repeatedly, said Linda Dizmon, sales
manager for women's apparel at Sears.
</P>
<P>
   They also offer a lot of support and can help ``hold things in''
or smooth things out, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Probably spandex and Lycra's greatest attribute is the comfort
it offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in pants and things, to have that little bit of spandex
makes it so much more comfortable because it moves with you and
breaths with you,'' Dizmon said. ``It also helps the clothes kind
of keep their shape better.''
</P>
<P>
   Teens and college-age shoppers go crazy for anything with
spandex in it, Rayson reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it you really have to have the body for the little
skirts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But just because a clothing item has spandex in it doesn't mean
the garment has to fit tightly or is ``clingy,'' says Millisa
Herring, co-manager of Lane Bryant, which sells women's sizes 14
through 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of our items do have some type of spandex in them
to allow for stretch and comfort so it's not too tight,'' she said.
``About 75 percent of the capri pants we sell have stretch in them,
as well as the elbow-sleeve stretch shirts. That allows for a
little bit more freedom of movement and comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Store managers say they definitely have seen an increase in the
number of clothing items that contain spandex. Even though some of
this spring's clothing items are trendy, they said they don't see
the idea of adding spandex to clothes as a soon-to-fade fad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's something that will continue,'' Herring said.
</P>
<P>
   Dizmon sees the addition of spandex to clothing as a lifestyle
demand.
</P>
<P>
   Lifestyles are geared toward comfort and casual living now, she
said. ``But then people still want to look cute. To buy something
on sale that is cute and comfortable, that's the absolute
superlative to be able to get all that. I think that's a lot of
what the spandex offers.''
</P>
<P>
   Allyson McKee, 15, said she has a closet full of items that
contain either spandex or Lycra _ dresses, skirts, shirts and
pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels really good,'' she said as she sorted through some of
the stretchy styles at Sears. ``They're really comfortable to wear
to school and really cute and in style.''
</P>
<P>
   Clothing items with Lycra or spandex may require some special
attention when washing. Here are some of the fabric-care tips
listed on the DuPont Web site at www.dupont.com/lycra/facts
/care.0.html:
</P>
<P>
   _ Never use chlorine bleach on garments with Lycra. Bleach can
cause discoloration, growth and eventual breakage of Lycra.
All-fabric, nonchlorine bleach can be used for laundering Lycra
garments and may actually be beneficial in preventing graying.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the garment tags recommend washing and tumble drying, it's
probably for a good reason. The heat generated by the drier will
help recover any lost stretch that occurred while wearing the
garment and thorough washing, rinsing and drying in machines will
bring out the best in Lycra.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dry cleaning Lycra is no problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most fiber combinations can be cleaned by following simple
guidelines (listed on the clothing's tag). When mixed with cotton,
nylon, polyester or acrylic, Lycra can be hand or machine washed
and tumble or line dried.
</P>
<P>
   When mixed with rayon, silk, acetate or tri-acetate, fabrics
with Lycra should only be dry cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   _ When in doubt about the care of a fabric, always follow label
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Christi Mays writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
