</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-GARDENS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KITCHEN GARDENS: Books may plant seeds of inspiration
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's positively absolutely safe!
</P>
<P>
   Those who record such details remind us that as of last weekend,
it's OK to plant anything in the garden without fear of frost.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to rush right in, troweling in the tomatoes and basil,
and planting the beans. But if you're putting down the same old
crops in the same old place, this may be the time for a new
approach to the kitchen garden.
</P>
<P>
   A crop of new books provides inspiration that may motivate you
to pencil in a new plan, or just curl up on the porch and think
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Start with ``Country Home's new Kitchen Garden Planner''
(Meridith, $34.95), which offers plan sketches and gorgeous, though
somewhat repetitious, photos of herbs and their life-size flowers.
The book records plans of 13 gardens in various parts of the
country, and all are dedicated to a decorous kitchen garden. While
long on herbs, the plans also focus on vegetable gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Getting organized also is the focus of ``Country Living
Gardener: A Garden of Recipes'' (Hearst, $24.95). It's written and
illustrated with watercolors and pen-and-ink drawings by Cynthia
Gibson, who calls the book ``my personal approach to combining the
arts of gardening and cooking.'' Chapter headings bring the two
together in themes such as ``The Soup Garden,'' ``The Salad
Garden'' and ``The Edible Flower Garden.'' Chapters cover both the
growing and using of the edibles.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes Ronni Lundy with another approach in her ``Butter
Beans to Blackberries: Recipes from the Southern Garden'' (North
Point, $30). This is not really about the growing of the beans and
berries, but rather about enjoying the harvest of what she calls
``the whole garden of treasures that every Southerner remembers and
loves.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the ribs, fried chicken and biscuits usually
associated with the Southern table, it is the fruits and vegetables
that captured the author's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Lundy, who lives in Louisville, came to national attention with
her first book, ``Shuck Beans, Stack Cakes and Honest Fried
Chicken.'' Her second, ``The Festive Table,'' wandered too far from
her roots, but now she is back home in territory as comfortable as
a pair of garden clogs.
</P>
<P>
   Lundy is passionate about all the foods of the South, but in
particular those harvested from the fields, and the book and
recipes are laced with the recollections of where and when she ate
them, starting in her mountain home of Corbin, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   For Southern expatriates, the book may be a trip down memory
lane, even if they never step from the back porch to the garden.
The rest of us may just make our first acquaintance with lady cream
peas and ``greasy'' beans.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
