<HEADER>
A2830 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-LUYENDYK20-COX     05-19 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LUYENDYK20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Luyendyk drives towards retirement
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Through the years, it wasn't so unusual to see
Arie Luyendyk signing autographs. After all, he's a two-time
Indianapolis 500 winner.
</P>
<P>
   But Luyendyk had never been approached for his signature by a
fellow driver until 1998 Indy 500 Rookie of the Year Steve Knapp
asked him to sign his driving uniform last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought he was kidding, but he was serious,''
Luyendyk said. ``That was a first for me. I've signed underwear
(this week), bras and some flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk's writing hand is in overdrive because fans realize the
end is near for a racing legend. Late last year, Luyendyk announced
the Indianapolis 500 on May 30 would be his last open-wheel race.
It has led to a wave of well-wishing and reminiscing from fans,
sponsors and drivers.
</P>
<P>
   And it's made for a sentimental week for Luyendyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if I'm going to totally retire,'' Luyendyk said.
``It's going to be tough, because I want to be in a race car. But I
want to spend time with my family and do other things that life has
to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   But before he does that, in honor of his last Indy run there's
been public appearances, charity events and press conferences. In
between, the 45-year-old Holland native has found time to practice
at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, although practice was shortened
Tuesday because of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'm busier and there's been more requests for
interviews,'' Luyendyk said. ``I realize what this is all about,
but I also realize I'll be here in the future, probably still
working with Team Treadway and other sponsors we have.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I might broadcast next year. I live in the States
(Scottsdale, Ariz.) and I'm not moving anywhere else. So I'll be
around.''
</P>
<P>
   That Luyendyk will stay in racing comes as good news to the fans
who have followed his career as a Dutch Formula Vee series driver
in 1972 to the Indianapolis 500's all-time prize-money leader with
$5.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than his prize money that's made Luyendyk a
favorite in the racing community. It's his class, on the track and
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the two years I raced in America, I found Arie to be a
gentleman as well as a very professional driver,'' said Nigel
Mansell, who finished third in the 1993 Indy 500. ``When I did my
last race for the Newman/Haas team at Laguna Seca, Arie came by our
motorhome . . . to say goodbye and wish us well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That showed he is a true sportsman, and I'm certain that's one
reason why the public has been supportive of him throughout his
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the support stems from Luyendyk's success at Indy. He won
the race in 1990 and 1997, set the 500-mile average speed record
(185.981 mph) in 1990 and the one-lap qualifying mark (237.498) in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Said Indianapolis Motor Speedway president Tony George, ``I
think it's safe to say when his name comes up on the ballot for
induction into the Hall of Fame, he will most likely be elected on
the first ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   But will he be inducted as a two-time Indy champion or three?
Luyendyk likes his chances of winning the race, especially after
finishing with the fourth-highest speed on Monday (221.119).
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen here you can't foresee,'' Luyendyk said. ``You
hope your car handles good and you stay close to the lead. If you
stay close at lap 150 or 160, you have a shot at winning this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way, I'm not counting on (winning), but we're
working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Luyendyk is finished with the 500, he said he'll spend more
time with his son, Arie Jr., lending monetary support to the
Formula Ford 1600 class racer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay away and just try to get the money,'' Luyendyk said.
``I try not to be an overbearing dad. I'd like to see him here, but
now we want him to get the experience of all kinds of race
tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like his dad did.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Lance writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
