<SLUG> BC-MANIC-MOMS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Manic moms: Lazy days loom _ but first, there's a frantic end of
school frenzy
 &HT;    (With illustration.)
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Summertime, and the living is easy? Not for parents.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Christmas, there's no time of the year that keeps
families more frantic than May and June. School is wrapping up,
clubs are winding down and summer activities are beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you get into May and everything goes into
overdrive,'' says Melanie Payne, 39. ``I've got two kidsd with my
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fussell, owner of the home-organizing service Clutter
Coach, recommends keeping a weekly calendar on the refrigerator as
a reminder of family activities and responsibilities. Running
errands such as grocery shopping without children in tow can save
time, too, says Fussell, the mother of an 8-year-old and leader of
a Cub Scout troop.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the flip side of the coin. Kelly Burke, a high
school physics teacher, has her share of end-of-the-school-year
pressures _ finishing the curriculum, scheduling around a series of
special events. Katie, 6, is wrapping up Girl Scouts for the year,
and baseball season ends in late May for Adam, 7.
</P>
<P>
   But for Burke, there is an end in sight. Like her kids, she gets
a summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I pick them up at school now, the first two questions are
`How was your behavior at school?' and `Do you have any homework
tonight?' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the summertime we wake up and say, `Shall we go
swimming today or play golf? Do you want to go to the aquarium in
Tennessee or Callaway Gardens?' It's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
