<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Former orphan returns home to help others
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service DAYTON, Ohio _ The last thing Roy
<TEXT>
Sturgill wanted to do is to come back to Dayton. Too many toxic
memories.
<P>
   Progress is forward motion, after all, not backward. The only
way to prove you've transcended your past is to travel light-years
away from it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Sturgill's young clients at Montgomery County
Children Services have such a hard time buying his story. They find
it hard to believe their caseworker once lived at the orphanage at
Shawen Acres. Hard to believe he would came back on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think every caseworker is trained to give out the same
story _ about how they made it, and you can make it too,'' Sturgill
says with a wry smile.
</P>
<P>
   Disbelief aside, Sturgill, 43, has found that his past helps him
understand his clients, both children and parents. And working with
children on the very grounds where, a troubled adolescent, he once
lived, has exorcised some of his demons. ``I get a lot of memories,
walking around,'' Sturgill says.
</P>
<P>
   The memories, up to the day in '70 when he came to Shawen Acres,
are mostly bad. His mother married at 15 and had three children by
the time Roy came along. Overwhelmed, she sent the baby to live
with a great-aunt until he was 4 years old.
</P>
<P>
   When he came home, his parents were virtual strangers to him.
``My parents were constantly arguing,'' Sturgill recalls. ``I
thought they were arguing mainly because I was back. I carried that
blame for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents divorced shortly after Roy rejoined the family. His
mother contracted multiple sclerosis, and his father, an alcoholic,
had little to do with the family. When he was 14, his mother was
put in a nursing home. The children were told that none of their
family members could take care of them, and they went to live at
Shawen Acres.
</P>
<P>
   That stung. But after years of neglect and abuse, the orphanage
was a relief. A caseworker took them shopping for shoes and
clothes. ``It was the first time we'd had anybody invest that kind
of money in us,'' Sturgill says. ``It was nice to be able to go to
school and wear new clothes and shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   School was another matter. By ninth grade, Sturgill had a spotty
attendance record. His Shawen Acres caseworker informed him, ``Not
going to school is not an option.''
</P>
<P>
   Sturgill lived in Cottage 5 with 18 other boys from different
cultures and backgrounds, who came together as a family. For the
first time, he learned discipline through consequences, not fists
and broom handles. ``I had to make choices, with my choices
resulting in good or bad consequences,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the great-aunt who had raised him his first four
years sent for Sturgill. After graduating from high school, he
joined the Navy, well-prepared by the discipline and camaraderie of
life at Shawen Acres.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he tried to bury his past. It surprised him when he
cried at the funeraln a whole lot quicker. I have the benefit of
having been that teen-ager.''
</P>
<P>
   He can talk to children about forgiveness: ``I try to tell them,
'Look, I know your parents have done bad things to you, and you're
angry and upset. But eventually, if you both live long enough,
you'll forgive them _ or you should.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sturgill also believes no case is hopeless: ``With the right
intervention, you can take almost any situation that involves
children, and turn that around and improve their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   At first apprehensive, Sturgill now says, ``Kicking me off the
property is the only way I'll go out.'' He bought a home less than
a mile from his office.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, how he found his calling at the place where he started
out. Day by day, he strives to redeem childhoods at the place that
redeemed his.
</P>
<P>
   You can move forward, after all, by going back.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
