<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2835 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDLIFE-JOURNEY20-COX     05-19 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDLIFE-JOURNEY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Installment 9: Ron Wiggins' midlife journey to Mount McKinley
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few ways to tell you're in the Midwest:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fewer Mercedes and Volvos, more John Deere tractors. A lot
more.
</P>
<P>
   _ Business signs tend to be perky. ``If you can't stop, smile as
you go by.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rampant Bambicide. It's almost as if deer say, ``I came
through a long, cold winter in good shape, so now that it's spring,
I think I'll throw myself in front of a truck.''
</P>
<P>
   _ When you forget to move your slow vehicle into the right lane,
Midwestern drivers seem to take the attitude that inconsiderate
nitwits are God's creatures, too. Not once, when I forgot, did
Midwestern drivers lean on their horns or offer me instructive
gestures.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask for directions and you not only get directions, but you
are required to repeat them back, and then your foster angel waits
to see that you're going the right way.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coffee is 25 cents at gas marts. When I remarked on the price,
I got my only frown from an Iowan who said a trifle defensively,
``A quarter's a fair price for a cup of coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Midwesterners don't seem to understand that the yellow light
means speed up, and thus, have an unnerving tendency to slow down
when they see a caution light and then stop before it turns red.
</P>
<P>
   Official Iowa State Joke:
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did the disc harrow say to the tractor?
</P>
<P>
   A: Pull me closer, John Deere.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIANCE, Neb. _ As I drove to see ``Carhenge'' in Alliance,
Neb., I kept saying to myself: ``There has to be more to this than
I've been told.''
</P>
<P>
   A colleague told me what I'd see: ``It's unbelievable. You go
into this field off town and this farmer's got a bunch of cars set
up exactly like those mysterious stone formations at Stonehenge in
England.''
</P>
<P>
   Carhenge? Druid farmers in Nebraska?
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, you've got to see this.''
</P>
<P>
   When helpful reader Marsha Baker of West Palm Beach, Fla.
recommended Carhenge as well, I marked it on my map.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Stonehenge, except with cars,'' I kept saying to myself
as I drove west, making a slow go of it in a sustained headwind of
30 mph that held Max, my Toyota-powered RV, to 50 mph.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered how Max would fare if the winds sustained through the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   They sustained, and Max hated it. I never got the game little RV
up to 50 all the way to Alliance, often kicking into second gear
just to maintain headway.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, I was able to appreciate the rolling
Nebraska countryside pretty much at my leisure. And the country was
so beautiful in its rise and fall that I wondered why Rodgers and
Hammerstein didn't simply go with Nebraska!
</P>
<P>
   And then I understood. Oklahoma _ four syllables. Nebraska _
three. How are you going to sing Nebraska, without making it
``Nebraskaka,'' which I don't think the citizens of Nebraska would
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the musings of the newcomer struck by the blue-skied,
golden beauty of the country, the cloudless storms notwithstanding.
Would I ever get to Alliance bucking these headwinds? And if not,
who would help me? I drove hours without a car or truck passing me.
</P>
<P>
   I got my answer up the road at Red's Cafe in Mullen, Neb. _
population 728. Nebraskans, when they're spread thin, look out for
the other fellow as Sam Simonson demonstrated when he came over to
my table to refill my coffee.
</P>
<P>
   No, Simonson was not my waiter. Coffee is self-serve in these
parts and when you're helping yourself, you come around to the
other tables and top off cups. Simonson was a rancher, I was to
learn, and a fit, fiftyish man with crinkly blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   I thanked him and, thinking a compliment was in order, said
``Your Sand Hills countryside reminds me of the British Open.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Ben Crenshaw thought,'' smiled Simonson. ``South
of here a ways, he built Sand Hills Golf Club, fixing it up to look
like one of those British courses. He flies in folks to North
Platte and they shuttle 'em to the golf course. Celebrities like
it. The Gatlin Brothers and Glen Campbell come out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Ted Turner came in with a buffalo ranch. Now land
is up to $250 an acre, a shocker to folks around here. ``Six or
seven years ago it was $60 and $70 an acre.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him about how we rate in the nation,'' said the man
behind the counter who was Bill Neumeyer, the manager. He pointed
to a yellowing Associated Press clipping rating Hooker County as
the 13th least populated county in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 2,700 people in the whole county,'' Simonson said.
``You got to go 100 miles one way and 75 miles another to reach a
town of any size. Where you going?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To Alliance. To see Carhenge,'' I said. ``Have you seen it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' the rancher said evenly. ``Just some cars stuck in the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Post Script: Yes, by golly, that is exactly what Carhenge is,
some cars stuck in the ground, replicating the work of ancient
Druids who, having no access to junked Cadillacs and Fords, made do
with slabs of granite. I went, I saw, I bought post cards. As to
why anyone would bother, there was only this explanation at the
``attraction:''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Carhenge) was conceived by Jim Reinders who once lived on
this farm. Constructed during a family reunion, it was dedicated on
the summer solstice of 1987.''
</P>
<P>
   As to ``why,'' the artist declines comment, saying ``PLANE LOQUI
DEPREHENDI''
</P>
<P>
   Which loosely translates to ``If you have a flat place, do
something with it.''
</P>
<P>
   I left a half dollar donation in a lock box, saddled up Max, and
headed for the Colorado Springs gold country.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
