<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Do I worry? Yeah, but fears can't stifle joy
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ We parents today are struggling with a
set of worries so different from the worries of our past that it's
hard to know whether we should forge ahead, heads high, or build
ourselves a bunker.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose the answer lies somewhere in the middle. But that
middle is often so obscured by the news of bomb scares at our
proms, guns in our schools, hungry children in our midst that
sometimes we can't help but embrace all the fear, real or not.
</P>
<P>
   I started thinking about this, really thinking about it, Monday
when I was in the car, alone. There was a Columbine story on NPR,
then a car pulled up next to me and the guy in it stared at me and
made me feel so uncomfortable, so unnerved, that my heart thumped
wildly and my adrenaline fed my imagination.
</P>
<P>
   (ITAL)My God,(END ITAL) I thought, (ITALAL)what(END ITAL) is
keeping you awake? Sleeplessness is sleeplessness. Fear is fear.
</P>
<P>
   Worrying is worrying.
</P>
<P>
   Except lately. Lately we're all so skittish about the most
regular of things. School days. Prom nights. Even strangers at a
stoplight.
</P>
<P>
   So far, I've had to offer only cursory explanations of Columbine
and death by tornadoes and bomb scares to my 8-year-old, which is
good. I can barely comprehend it all myself. Except to say that,
whatever we do, however we fight what's happening around us, we
can't let ourselves be crippled by things we cannot control.
</P>
<P>
   We can't let the fear steal our joy.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
