<HEADER>
A2837 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS20-TAKE     05-19 1681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS20-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: What authority does Hillary Rodham Clinton have to run around
the world giving $20 million to whomever she wishes?
</P>
<P>
   A: This subject has come up before. The $21 million in aid funds
wasn't ``given'' by Clinton. She merely announced it during her
visit to Macedonia to meet with refugees and talk to international
aid workers. Designed to support ethnic Albanians who were forced
from Kosovo, and the Macedonian people who have taken them in, the
money was part of an aid package approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can you tell me about Project Adventure? I understand
that it operates homes for troubled youths.
</P>
<P>
   A: Described as an intervention program for those who are
``socially maladjusted,'' Project Adventure has as its premise the
concept that outdoor settings and adventure-based activities will
increase the students' enthusiasm and willingness to pay attention.
Based in Hamilton, Mass., it has four U.S. offices and a number of
workshop sites nationwide, and is expanding with outreaches in
Asia, Australia and New Zealand, and a worldwide network of
educators.
</P>
<P>
   If you're online, check www.pa.org for general information about
Project Adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that an expedition found a body on Mount
Everest that may be a man who reached the summit 29 years before
Sir Edmund Hillary. Do you have any details? Is Hillary still
alive? If so, what was his reaction?
</P>
<P>
   A: The reported discovery of the remains of British climber
George Mallory, who died on Mount Everest in 1924, has reopened a
debate on who was first to climb the world's highest mountain.
History books have credited Hillary and his guide, Tenzing Norgay,
for accomplishing the feat in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Expedition members found the body they believe to be Mallory's
on May 1 near the top of Everest, but they haven't been able to
prove that he reached the summit before falling to his death.
Mallory and his companion, Andrew Irvine, were last seen on June 8,
1924.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary indeed is still living. In Auckland, New Zealand, the
80-year-old explorer said he believed an ascent of Mount Everest
could only be described as a success if the climber returned alive.
``Despite that, it was a very remarkable effort by Mallory (and
Irvine) even to get as high as they did, and we don't know where
that was.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read a short article on an Alabama jury awarding $581
million to a family that claimed to have been overcharged for two
satellite dishes. There were no particulars about the case. What
was the big deal?
</P>
<P>
   A: The case involved finance charges by Whirlpool Financial
National Bank, a former subsidiary of Whirlpool Corp. now owned by
TransAmerica Bank. As reported by the Birmingham News, Barbara
Carlisle and her parents, George and Velma Merriweather of
Greensboro, Ala., bought two satellite dishes and financed $1,124
at an interest rate of 21.9 percent. They said they were told the
deal involved payments of $34 a month for three years, when in fact
the term was for four years and four months.
</P>
<P>
   Carlisle and the Merriweathers said the longer term caused them
to be overcharged $612. By paying on the contract for 4 1/2 years,
their attorney said, they were being charged 300 percent interest.
Their lawsuit alleged that Whirlpool targeted ``uneducated and
illiterate people.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hale County jury awarded $975,000 in compensatory damages and
$580 million in punitive damages. ``The jury sent a message that
they will not tolerate companies' going into people's homes and
robbing and stealing from them this way,'' said Tom Methvin of
Montgomery, one of the plaintiff's attorneys. He added that the
trial judge can reduce the verdict and the Alabama Supreme Court
can reduce it even further.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I send an e-mail comment about the NATO campaign in
Yugoslavia to President Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   A: Address your message to president(at)whitehouse.gov or call
up the White House web site _ www.whitehouse.gov _ and use the form
you'll find after clicking on The President &AMP; Vice President,
followed by The President.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is the numerical size of a man's hat determined? It can't
be the circumference of the head.
</P>
<P>
   A: Head size is based on the circumference of the head, but
you're right, it isn't the circumference. Casey Bush of the
Millinery Institute in New York cited information from the book
``Hat Life Directory,'' which uses this example in explaining how
hat size is determined. If a string is placed around a head and it
measures 21.8759 inches, and this circumference of the odd oval is
made into a circle, the diameter of the circle is 7 inches. The
equivalent hat size, then, is 7.
</P>
<P>
   This is for American hat sizes only; hatmakers in France, Italy
and other countries use different sizes and ways of measurement.
Even among American hatmakers there's not a complete
standardization in all factories, however, so buyers would be wise
to try hats on for correct fit, no matter what the number says.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the racial breakdown of people on death row in the
United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: The NAACP Legal and Educational Fund's Capital Punishment
Project says 3,565 inmates were on death row nationwide as of April
1. It listed these statistics: white, 1,657 (46.48 percent); black,
1,516 (42.53); Latin, 299 (8.39); Native American, 48 (1.35);
Asian, 28 (.79); and ``unknown,'' 17 (.48).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about the NATO military commander, Gen. Wesley
Clark. What is his educational and military background?
</P>
<P>
   A: Clark, who grew up in Little Rock, Ark., is a 1966 graduate
of the U.S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y., where he
graduated first in his class. He has a master's degree in
philosophy, politics and economics from Oxford University in
England, where he studied as a Rhodes scholar between 1966 and
1968. He also is a graduate of the National War College, Command
and General Staff College and Ranger and Airborne schools.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Clark has been a White House fellow and special
assistant to the director of the Office of Management and Budget.
He also taught at West Point and served in various Army positions
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He has been commander of the National Training Center at Fort
Irwin, Calif.; deputy chief of staff for concepts, doctrine and
development at the Army Training and Doctrine Command, Fort Monroe,
Va.; commander of the 1st Cavalry Division, Fort Hood, Texas; and
commander in chief of the U.S. Southern Command in Panama. Clark
also led the military negotiations for the Bosnian peace accords at
Dayton, Ohio, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He became commander in chief of the U.S. European Command on
July 11, 1997; he also is the supreme allied commander, Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that the woman in Boston who won the $197 million Big
Game jackpot in April couldn't claim her prize because she wasn't
an American citizen. Is that true? Why haven't we seen anything
more about her lately?
</P>
<P>
   A: Citizenship doesn't necessarily figure into the claiming of a
lottery prize, but in fact the woman you're inquiring about,
Chilean-born Maria Grasso, has been a U.S. citizen since 1984. On
April 6, she won the $197 million Big Game jackpot, the largest
single prize ever won by an individual in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The public hasn't seen her or heard much about Grasso since then
because, after claiming her windfall _ $70.2 million taken in a
lump-sum _ she dropped out of sight. She had quit her job as a
nanny for Boston millionaire and venture capitalist Chris Gabriele,
and hired a lawyer and public relations firm to deal with the
onslaught of media and other inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso's relatives in Chile also have dropped from view. Chilean
television coverage showed Grasso's mother scrambling down the
front walk of her Santiago home, luggage in hand. State television
editor Denis Jones said Grasso herself apparently told her family
to duck the media. ``We called the United States and were told that
she hired a security company that recommended that,'' Jones added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In one of his novels, Tom Clancy writes about the ``seven
sisters of women's colleges,'' but he doesn't list them. Then I
read an article that identified Radcliffe as a ``Seven Sisters''
school, saying it was to merge with Harvard. Can you fill me in on
the other six?
</P>
<P>
   A: In addition to Radcliffe, which is in Cambridge, Mass., these
are the others: Vassar, Poughkeepsie, N.Y.; Smith, Northampton,
Mass.; Mount Holyoke, South Hadley, Mass.; Barnard, New York City;
Bryn Mawr, Bryn Mawr, Pa.; and Wellesley, Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you print the poem read at the funeral of Rachel Scott,
one of the students killed last month at Columbine High School?
</P>
<P>
   A: A number of people spoke and gave readings at the April 24
service at Trinity Christian Center in Littleton, Colo. The only
poem in the CNN transcript is this, written by a cousin of Rachel
Scott identified only by her first name, Sara:
</P>
<P>
   Looking down, seeing despair / Only leaving a soul-searching for
air / Feeling the warmth, seeing the light / Reaching for wings of
eternal flight / Slipping away from this world today / Angel of
mine, you found your way / Let my love be the wind beneath your
wing / As you rejoice in heaven in seeing / Angel of mine, watch
over me always / Because I will need you in my heart in many ways /
You, my angel, I promise to you, to share your rhythm and rhyme to
them, you will show them what's true / Angel of mine, your face
will make the heavens so bright / With your beauty, grace and
loving spirit / Only God knows why you were shot / But I know I
shall never forget my beloved friend and cousin, Rachel Joy Scott.
</P>
<P>
   End/Take1
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
