<HEADER>
A2838 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS20-TAKE     05-19 1756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS20-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: The G-7 and G-8 countries are much in the news. But why does
the media refer to them by both numerical designations? What's the
difference?
</P>
<P>
   A: The name at first was Group of Seven (or G-7) for the seven
largest industrial countries in the world: the United States,
Germany, France, Japan, Canada, United Kingdom and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The organization originally came together in response to the
OPEC-induced oil crisis of the 1970s. The increases in oil prices
rocked the stability of the global monetary system, creating
massive deficits in balance of payments accounts. Representatives
of the seven nations met to discuss mutually agreeable
macroeconomic and monetary policies that, it was hoped, would
neutralize the effects of the imbalance. By 1997 the president of
Russia was being included, so G-7 became G-8.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Commission of the European Union also is
often included in economic summits for discussions of economic and
political issues, but as yet that hasn't created any momentum for
adding yet another number.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It is true, as I've heard, that Al Gore and Tommy Lee Jones,
the actor, were roommates at Yale?
</P>
<P>
   A: Right people, wrong school. They were roomates at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent item about the anniversary of the burning of the
German airship Hindenburg reminded me of something I've been
wondering about for years. When I was growing up in Washington,
D.C., in the 1930s, I once saw a very large dirigible. Did the
United States have any airships comparable in size to the
Hindenburg?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Hindenburg, which exploded and burned May 6, 1937, was
804 feet long and 135 feet wide, making it the largest rigid
airship ever constructed, according to Encyclopedia Britannica.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy experimented with airships in the 1920s and '30s, and
it's possible you might have seen one of them. The Navy's Akron and
Macon were large enough to carry fighter airplanes, both launching
and receiving them while in flight. While it didn't state their
exact dimensions, World Book Encyclopedia described the Akron and
Macon as ``giant.'' Or you may have seen Germany's Graf Zeppelin,
which flew more than 1 million miles between 1928 and 1937,
including many trans-Atlantic trips.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. construction of rigid airships was halted after the Akron
went down in a storm off the New Jersey coast in April 1933, and
the Macon was forced by bad weather into the sea off California in
February 1935. Some 75 people died in the two accidents.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison, today's nonrigid airships, such as the familiar
Goodyear blimp, average about 200 feet in length. Rigid airships,
which had a wood or metal frame, are no longer flown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article concerning a study by J.D. Power about automobile
defects mentioned a number of makes, but not Nissan. Were any
Nissan vehicles tested? If so, how did they do?
</P>
<P>
   A: Information about Nissan vehicles wasn't included in the
Associated Press article you saw, so it isn't known if any were
tested. In fact, the study on which the article was based was a
private report to automakers made by J.D. Power and Associates, a
global marketing information services firm based in Agoura Hills,
Calif. As reported, the findings came from a confidential executive
summary of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Information about Nissan vehicles is included, however, in the
Power firm's 1999 Initial Quality Study 2, which lists the top
three vehicles in various size categories in initial quality. In
the entry midsize segment, the U.S.-built Nissan Altima was listed
as ``best,'' followed by Plymouth Breeze and Dodge Stratus. Among
compact cars, Nissan Sentra placed third, after Toyota Corolla
(``best'') and Saturn SW (station wagon).
</P>
<P>
   Internet users can see this report at http://www.jdpower.com/
and clicking on ``Hot Off the Press,'' then on the May 5, 1999,
entry under ``What's New.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about Candlestick Park in San Francisco. Where
does the name come from, and is it the official name?
</P>
<P>
   A: The official name now is 3Com Park, but many people still use
the original Candlestick name. That comes from Candlestick Point, a
rocky outcropping into San Francisco Bay that was offered in 1958
by developer Charles Harney as the site for the Giants' new home.
The team previously had been playing at Seals Stadium. The names
Candlestick Point (and Park) came from the jagged rocks and trees
that rise from the tidelands like giant candlesticks.
</P>
<P>
   Candlestick Park opened April 12, 1960. In an effort to build up
recognition of its identity, 3Com Corp. paid $500,000 to the City
of San Francisco in 1995 to have its name attached to the stadium.
In 1996, the deal was extended to January 2000 for an additional
$3.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   3Com Corp., based in Santa Clara, Calif., makes hardware that
lets computers communicate with each other across networks. It's
the No. 2 company in its field after Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about decaffeinated coffee in one of the tabloids
stated that it's best to use a product prepared by steam
distillation or the Swiss water process. It indicated that coffee
decaffeinated by other means could contain dangerous chemicals. Do
you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Decaffeinated coffee is made by two methods, and the Food and
Drug Administration has determined that both are safe, said Chris
Rosenbloom, spokeswoman for the American Dietetic Association and a
professor in Georgia State University's department of nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   In one process, caffeine is removed from the green, unroasted
coffee beans by softening them with water, flushing them with a
solvent usually containing chlorine, and heating and blowing them
with steam to remove the solvent. To obtain a product that is 97
percent caffeine-free, this process must be repeated up to 24
times. In the other process, any of five or so decaffeination
agents is mixed directly with the coffee beans to remove the
caffeine. Either way, little or no trace of the solvent ends up in
the product.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbloom added that she isn't aware of any research currently
being done that shows any danger.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On a trip to London, I noticed a statue of Abraham Lincoln in
the center of the city. Do you know who sculpted it and why it's
there?
</P>
<P>
   A: The British chose to honor Lincoln because of his policies,
such as emancipation. In addition to Lincoln's statue in Parliament
Square, a bust of him is displayed in the Royal Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The bronze statue you saw was sculpted by Dublin, Ireland-born
Augustus Saint-Gaudens and was unveiled in 1920. A replica of a
monument in Chicago, it depicts Lincoln standing in front of an
elaborate chair with the design of an eagle on its back. Sculptor
Saint-Gaudens was taken to the United States as a child, so it's
likely he wanted to take a give a touch of Americana to London
years later. The British Tourist Authority had little information
about the bust of Lincoln, other than saying it was created out of
Indiana limestone by American sculptor Andrew O'Connor (date
unrecorded).
</P>
<P>
   Q: When the president flies into a city, where does his
motorcade come from? I'm told that vehicles in the motorcade are
bulletproof, so I'm sure there aren't such vehicles already in
place in every city he visits. Are they driven in advance to
wherever he goes?
</P>
<P>
   A: The president's armored limousine, and any other armored
vehicles required for a motorcade, come from Washington, said Jim
Cool of the Secret Service. They aren't driven to each location,
however; they're flown aboard military aircraft in advance of the
president's visit. Local non- armored vehicles, such as police and
highway patrol escorts, also are routinely part of a motorcade, as
you know.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My son is interested in joining the CIA when he completes his
Air Force service. What are the requirements, what is the procedure
for applying, and where can he get information?
</P>
<P>
   A: An applicant must be a U.S. citizen and must successfully
complete a thorough medical examination, a polygraph interview and
an extensive background investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A number of fields are open, both immediately (such as applied
research psychologists, biological scientists, computer scientists,
economists, energy analysts, information threat analysts, nurses
and polygraph examiners) and on an ongoing basis (computer and
electronic engineers, interpreters, language instructors, imagery
analysts, security protective officers and software development
engineers, among others).
</P>
<P>
   Those interested should send a resume and cover letter. The CIA
says it will respond within 45 days if there is further interest.
</P>
<P>
   The best source of information can be found on the Internet at
http://www.odci.gov/cia/ciahome.html and then clicking on How to
Apply. A Job Kit and Resume Guide shows how to format your resume
properly. Or call the CIA, 703-482-1100, and ask for the recruiting
center.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An obituary on Joe Adcock, first baseman for the Milwaukee
Braves, said he hit a home run on May 26, 1959, that didn't count
because he passed Hank Aaron on the bases. I don't understand what
that means. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: A runner who passes another runner on the basepaths is
automatically out. The incident in question occurred at Milwaukee's
County Stadium. Pittsburgh Pirates pitcher Harvey Haddix set down
the first 36 Braves he faced, throwing 12 perfect innings. But the
Pirates, too, were being shut out.
</P>
<P>
   In the 13th inning, the perfect game ended with Felix Mantilla
reaching base on an error. Mantilla moved to second base on a
sacrifice by Eddie Mathews. With the perfect game over and first
base open, the Pirates gave an intentional walk to Hank Aaron to
set up a possible double play. Adcock, the next batter, not only
broke up the no-hitter, but also won the game for Milwaukee when he
hit a hanging slider over the right center field fence. Aaron
didn't see the ball sail into the seats, but he did see Mantilla
cross the plate. Assuming the game was over, he ran from second
base straight to his dugout instead of continuing to third and
home.
</P>
<P>
   After a huddle, officials declared that Adcock was out for
passing Aaron on the bases, but would be credited with a double for
allowing the man on second base to score. Since Mantilla scored,
the game was over, with the Braves winning 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   End.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
