<HEADLINE>
THE NEW PAUL ALLEN  
 REAL NETWORKS TRIES TO DODGE A BULLET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hey _ didn't that used to be Paul Allen?
</P>
<P>
   Techies who are also professional basketball fans may have
noticed that Allen, a co-founder of Microsoft who owns the Portland
Trail Blazers, looks a lot more dapper these days as he takes his
accustomed seat courtside at Trail Blazers games.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on television frequently as the Trail Blazers are
having their best season in years, the 45-year-old billionaire
looks much more like a high-technology investor than the
guitar-playing, hacker geek that many recall. Gone are the rumpled
sport shirts and the beard, replaced by clean-shaven cheeks and
well-cut suits.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Allen's Vulcan Ventures investment firm,
which is based in Seattle, declined to discuss his makeover, though
one employee estimated that it began two years ago. That would be
around the time that Allen was said to be dating the tennis star
Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
   But the spotlight is shining even more brightly on him in the
current National Basketball Association playoff season. Last week,
his team swept the Phoenix Suns in three games to advance to the
next round _ the first time the Trail Blazers have won a playoff
series since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Curious techies and sports fans alike can get more details about
Allen at the Paul Allen Web site (www.paulallen.com). There, one
can read about his interest in music education and philanthropy,
his numerous telecommunications investments and his teams (he also
owns the Seattle Seahawks football team) _ and learn that one of
his favorite movies is ``La Dolce Vita.''
</P>
<P>
   Lessons in Not Blocking the Ads That Feed You
</P>
<P>
   Real Networks is trying to dodge a bullet, one that is headed
straight for its own foot.
</P>
<P>
   The software company, which is based in Seattle, produces
so-called streaming media technology that can be downloaded free
from the Web and enables personal computers to receive live audio
and video feeds on the Web. But Real Networks has also been selling
another company's program, called At Guard, that enables PC users
to block out Internet advertising. And that doesn't sit well with
Real Networks' paying customers _ operators of Web sites that
employ Real Networks technology and that in many cases depend on
advertising for their revenue.
</P>
<P>
   After Real Networks sent e-mail a few weeks ago to tens of
thousands of people offering At Guard for half the usual $29.99
price, some Web developers fired off e-mail of their own to Real
Networks and engaged in heated debates on industry bulletin boards.
Some have threatened boycotts or even defections to other brands of
streaming media, like Apple's or Microsoft's.
</P>
<P>
   Real Networks got the message. Last week, the company decided it
would stop selling At Guard altogether after June 15, Steve
Haworth, a spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Ad-blocking software like At Guard is intended to speed Web
viewing by stopping graphics-laden ads from downloading to a user's
PC. But many of Real Network's customers contend that widespread
use of ad-blocking software could seriously hurt their industry.
</P>
<P>
   Web viewers need to accept advertising if they want free
programming, said Scott Mathias, managing editor at ITVWorld.com, a
producer of online programming. ``If ad blocking is freely
available,'' he said, ``how will everyone's needs be met?''
</P>
<P>
   Although ad-blocking software has been available for several
years, it has been slow to catch on.
</P>
<P>
   But Anne Marshall, a product marketing manager at WRQ, the
Indianapolis company that produces At Guard, said the Real Networks
promotion had been generating strong sales for her company.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marshall said that regardless of what Real Networks had
decided, At Guard is a product that ``puts choice back in the hands
of Internet users.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-16-99 2216EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
