<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-BILLS-ONLINE-670&AMP;     05-19 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-BILLS-ONLINE-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE REPORT: THE BUSINESS OF PAYING BILLS ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeing opportunity in every crevice of the economy, a growing
number of Internet commerce companies now want to serve as the
bearers of bad news _ in this case, delivering bills online.
</P>
<P>
   And the idea seems to be catching on, with some of the nation's
biggest billers adopting online systems and one of the Internet's
most popular Web sites expected to offer similar billing services
by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is simple. A company sends e-mail to customers,
notifying them to check a Web site for new bills. Or, alternately,
customers simply know to check the site at regular intervals. In
either case, the billing agent charges merchants a small fee while
allowing them to save the $3 or so that it typically costs to print
and mail a paper bill. Customers pay their bills online without
incurring postage or check-processing fees. And banks save on
processing costs, because there is no paper to push.
</P>
<P>
   One key to the success of this approach, analysts and executives
say, is to aggregate the billers on a single site to make bill
delivery and payment as quick and painless as possible for
consumers. Unless enough large billers are willing to move to
online billing, though, the practice appears to have little chance
of proliferating.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies competing to bring more billers online are
the Checkfree Corporation, the industry leader so far, and
Transpoint, a joint venture of Microsoft, First Data and Citigroup.
As billing agents, Checkfree and Transpoint work with companies
like BellSouth and Consolidated Edison to deliver their bills
online and with banks to work out the online payment process.
</P>
<P>
   Transpoint and Checkfree are racing to create partnerships with
the biggest billers, such as electric utilities, credit card
companies and mortgage lenders. Checkfree's early lead in the field
comes in part from its having started sooner, in early 1997; the
company says it has signed up many of the nation's top billers,
including GTE, Chase Credit Card and MCI Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   Both Checkfree and Transpoint are also signing partnerships with
banks, so that a customer can visit his or her own bank's Web site
and view and pay the bills of every company signed up by either
billing agent.
</P>
<P>
   Since banks have offered various types of proprietary online
bill-payment services for years, consumers can be expected to
gravitate first toward bank Web sites to view and pay their bills.
But stiff competition for the banks is on the way from portal Web
sites, the gateways to the Internet that are visited by millions of
Internet users each month. Though no portal deals have been made
public, analysts say Checkfree and Yahoo have reached an agreement
for Yahoo visitors to receive and pay the bills issued by each of
Checkfree's merchant partners. (Yahoo and Checkfree declined to
comment on the deal.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology is unbelievably sticky,'' Robert Sterling, a
Jupiter Communications analyst, said, using industry jargon for
features that keep viewers coming back to a particular site.
Customers who pay bills on one site will not only return out of
habit, Sterling said, but will be reluctant to learn another site's
system. With tens of billions of bills mailed in the United States
each year, at least millions of repeat site visits could be at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is potentially a King Midas technology,'' Sterling said.
</P>
<P>
   But if online bill delivery can save customers time, save
merchants and banks money and provide Web sites with guaranteed
visitors, why are fewer than 1 percent of the nation's merchants
offering the service?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chicken-or-egg problem,'' said Lewis Levin, chief
executive of Transpoint. ``Billers have been saying that they'd do
something like this if there were billions of customers who were
dying to get their bills on the Internet. Customers say they'd love
to get their bills on the Internet if only billers would deliver
them. I think the billers have finally realized they're the
chickens and they have to invest in order to get this started.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The investment, however, is significant. It costs an average of
$150,000 to build a Web site with the technology to present bills
to customers and accept payments online, executives from Transpoint
and Checkfree said. Both companies provide the software that
enables consumers to view and pay their bills online, and they
charge merchants roughly the price of a stamp for each bill
processed.
</P>
<P>
   For AT&AMP;T, one of the nation's biggest billers, such an
investment was well worth the price, said Daniel H. Schulman,
executive vice president for consumer markets. AT&AMP;T introduced its
online billing service in March 1998, using a system designed
in-house, Schulman said. Hoping to gain broader exposure for this
service, AT&AMP;T is now negotiating to have its bills offered through
Checkfree, too.
</P>
<P>
   Schulman said the company had been aggressively promoting the
service. He would not disclose the number of customers using the
system, ``but we do well over a couple hundred million dollars in
electronic billing per year,'' which he said could save up to 60
percent of the cost of paper bills. The system, at www.att.com,
also enables customers to apply online for on-the-spot credit for
disputed long-distance charges and to learn about special pricing
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see if someone is making a slew of international
calls,'' Schulman said, ``and we could offer them a plan for that
when they're paying at our site.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the online billing service makes it easier
for customers to obtain a wealth of information about their
accounts _ such as the name of each person called rather than just
the phone number. In addition, customers who set up an online
billing account receive a discounted long-distance rate of 9 cents
a minute, with no monthly fee, as compared with 10 cents a minute
and a $4.95 monthly fee for AT&AMP;T's ``One Rate Plus'' calling plan.
</P>
<P>
   Banks are also offering incentives for consumers to pay their
bills online. The Union Bank of California, for example, offers
free banking and checking for a year when customers join its online
program. Analysts and executives say that creating such consumer
inducements is crucial to the success of online bill delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billers save money, but there aren't really enough incentives
yet for consumers,'' said Ullas Naik, senior vice president for
research at FAC Equities/First Albany, an investment banking firm.
``Only when they offer those incentives will we see a broad-based
migration.''
</P>
<P>
   Naik suggested one such incentive: ``Take a buck off each bill
if you receive and pay it online. That could save you $10 a
month.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-16-99 2154EDT &QL;
</P>
