<SLUG> BC-CPT-NORTHPOINT-DSL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
START-UP LEADS PHONE CAUSE IN BATTLE FOR INTERNET ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Michael W. Malaga, chairman of Northpoint
Communications Group Inc., stood at a whiteboard in his office here
recently and explained how his newly public company planned to
change the Internet business.
</P>
<P>
   Northpoint builds high-speed data networks using normal phone
lines _ an approach that could render the networks of most current
Internet service providers obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   He drew a box on his improvised map of the Bay area. ``So ISP's
have these big modems pools in every city,'' Malaga said, referring
to the conventional Internet service providers, ``and these access
points for dedicated services like T-1 lines,'' he continued,
drawing another box. ``And then they aggregate the traffic
somewhere else to transport to another city,'' he added, drawing a
third box and connecting them all with lines.
</P>
<P>
   After pausing, the 34-year-old executive erased the entire
schematic with three swift strokes. ``In the future,'' he said,
``they won't have to do any of this. We will allow ISPs to become
sales and marketing companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether by ``allow'' he really means ``force.''
Although it had revenue last year of only about $1 million,
Northpoint, which raised $360 million in an initial public stock
offering on Nasdaq on May 5, now has a stock market value of about
$5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company is perhaps the most advanced of a small cadre of
aggressive new players that are building high-speed Internet
networks based on a technology called digital subscriber line, or
DSL. It is a technology that, if widely embraced by computer users,
could do away with the dial-up modem access offered by the leading
Internet service providers, like the network-access portion of
America Online's business or Internet access provided by companies
like Mindspring Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   DSL is shaping up as the telephone network's main weapon against
the cable television industry's mounting campaign to offer
high-speed Internet access. That is why the Baby Bell local
telephone companies themselves are taking a hard look at DSL. But
so far, the smaller and nimbler DSL upstarts like Northpoint are
the ones having more success turning the technical concept into
commercial reality.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, if the Internet service providers really are
fated to obsolescence, they may be planting the seeds of their own
destruction: for those companies are Northpoint's main customers.
</P>
<P>
   Northpoint uses advanced DSL technology from Copper Mountain
Networks Inc., which itself went public on Thursday, raising $84
million and achieving a stock market value of $1.5 billion. The
technology, which combines software and hardware, enables
Northpoint to build networks that can deliver up to 1.5 million
bits of information a second _ or about 30 times as much Internet
data over a normal phone line as is possible with a conventional
56,000-bit-a-second modem. Rather than sell the use of those lines
directly to customers, Northpoint strikes deals with Internet
service providers to use its systems to resell the high-speed data
service to small and medium-sized business users and residential
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, computer users seeking high-speed access through the
telephone network have typically used a special kind of circuit
called a T-1 line. T-1 can deliver 1.5 million bits of information
a second, but it might cost the user $800 or more a month. A
comparable system based on Northpoint's DSL network might cost the
user as little as $350. As a result, an Internet service provider
can resell Northpoint's DSL lines more economically than providing
its own T-1 lines or leasing such lines from a telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   But the fundamental rules of communications economics mean that
the success of Northpoint and its initial DSL competitors, Covad
Communications Group Inc. and Rhythms Netconnections Inc., may very
well spell the end of broad profitability for traditional Internet
providers.
</P>
<P>
   But Northpoint cannot afford to be greedily gleeful about this
prospect. For if the Baby Bell local phone titans also expand into
DSL, those same economic rules could endanger the long-term success
of Northpoint and the other DSL upstarts.
</P>
<P>
   An essential economic characteristic of the communications
industry is that communications networks cost a lot to build but,
once built, relatively little to operate. While it may cost
billions to build a fiber optic link from New York to Los Angeles,
for instance, it costs only pennies, if that, to transmit a call
using that network.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the companies that control the assets _ the optical
fiber, the switches, the advanced gear for transmitting data from
one point to another _ control the pricing for communications
services. These companies also reap most of the profits. It is very
difficult to generate long-term success in the communications
business by leasing communications capacity from others.
</P>
<P>
   The quest to control physical communications assets, and thus to
control one's own costs and increase profitability, is the basic
rationale behind many of the billion-dollar deals that have become
so routine in the telecommunicatons business. That is why
Northpoint's business model may look so attractive to investors but
also so potentially dangerous for Internet providers.
</P>
<P>
   For everyday Internet providers, squeezed between America
Online's marketing juggernaut in the consumer market and the power
of international giants in the big-business segment, Northpoint
offers a compelling proposition. Northpoint can build the DSL
network, operate it and maintain it. That frees Internet providers
to concentrate on finding customers, operating e-mail and World
Wide Web server computers, selling the service at a markup and
answering the phone when something goes wrong.
</P>
<P>
   By using Northpoint, even the smallest Internet provider gets
access to a high-speed data system more advanced than just about
anything America Online is using _ and competitive with the cable
modems that are beginning to sprout around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But in one sense a deal with Northpoint is a Faustian bargain.
The sacrifice is profit margin, because Northpoint controls the
asset. An example illustrates the case: Northpoint generally sells
a 160-kilobit line to an Internet provider for $75 a month.
Flashcom, which is based in Westminster, Calif., and is one of
Northpoint's biggest customers, sells that same line to end users
for $79.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   With discounts for buying in bulk, Flashcom is probably paying
less than $75 _ but not much less. Because Northpoint controls the
asset, Northpoint controls most of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is pursuing much the same strategy, but using cable
television systems, rather than traditional phone lines. When
America Online and other Internet providers complain that AT&AMP;T will
not have to offer the use of its cable systems to other Internet
providers, what they really fear is the prospect that AT&AMP;T will
sell access to those systems at prices that keep the bulk of the
profits for itself.
</P>
<P>
   For Northpoint, the potential pitfall in its business plan is
that the very economic forces that could let it absorb most of the
profits from traditional Internet providers could eventually
undermine its own profitability. Northpoint, after all, has to
lease the actual copper phone lines to its customers from the Baby
Bell phone giants (though at rates that are regulated).
</P>
<P>
   The company connects to those circuits by installing its own
network equipment inside the Bell companies' central switching
offices. Northpoint buys this equipment from Copper Mountain and
hires Lucent Technologies Inc. to actually install it. Moreover,
Northpoint deals with the end-user customers only through its ISP
resellers. Given all this, what _ if anything _ is Northpoint's
long-term asset?
</P>
<P>
   ``The asset is really in the co-location,'' Malaga said,
referring to the deals Northpoint has struck to place equipment
inside the Bells' central offices. Northpoint has hundreds of such
deals, each of which can take months to negotiate. That has given
Northpoint a head start on many of its potential rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But in the long run, the Bells are compelled by regulation to
offer co-location to just about any company that asks for it. What
that means is that Northpoint might well end up being more valuable
as an acquisition target for a bigger company _ a Bell, say _
looking to make a quick DSL splash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-16-99 2021EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
