<SLUG> BC-CPT-GAME-FUTURE18-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
How to play the game at E3 
By Omar Gallaga  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What's the hardest part about the video game
business?
</P>
<P>
   Forget about bringing bloodthirsty aliens to life or building
virtual worlds.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part of the business may be convincing folks in the
real world to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   In today's competitive gaming world, game makers have got to
convince hard-core gamers that they're not just selling a shameless
rip-off (even if it is a sequel) or something that's as boring as a
modern-day Pong.
</P>
<P>
   You've also got to be at the right place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're George Lucas, the best place to sell the game hype
is at the Electronic Entertainment Expo in Los Angeles, which wraps
up today after three days. How's the game played at E3, as the expo
is known?
</P>
<P>
   Learn from the folks at Austin-based Iguana Entertainment and
its parent, Acclaim Entertainment, who let me spend some time with
them at E3:
</P>
<P>
   _Create the illusion of exclusivity.
</P>
<P>
   Acclaim's booth was a circular structure with a single entrance.
Anyone who wanted to see the inside, including its upcoming games,
had to get past security.
</P>
<P>
   _Throw a party, but keep people out of it.
</P>
<P>
   A party scheduled for after the show for Acclaim was restricted
to VIPs. Likewise, Eidos Interactive whetted attendees' appetites
by sending out hundreds of invitations in advance to a House of
Blues party that featured Everclear and David Bowie, then turned
away half the crowd when the place got too full. And a VERY private
party thrown by game developer Psygnosis at the Playboy Mansion was
a distant dream for hopeful E3 attendees _ it was booked up before
E3 began.
</P>
<P>
   _Get some celebrity endorse- ments.
</P>
<P>
   Acclaim brought in motocross racer Jeremy McGrath to sign
autographs. Electronic Arts hosted wrestlers from the WCW and Bowie
was guest of honor with Eidos. Acclaim makes the Jeremy McGrath
Supercross game.
</P>
<P>
   _Get some sexy celebrity endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Acclaim welcomed buxom personality ``Debra'' from the World
Wrestling Federation to sign autographs too. Strangely, her line
was longer than McGrath's. Acclaim produces WWF Attitude.
</P>
<P>
   _Announce important-sounding news.
</P>
<P>
   Acclaim announced Thursday that it was changing the names of the
companies it owns. So, after this week, Iguana will cease to exist.
It will be called Acclaim Austin. Releasing news during E3 gives
the appearance that a company is a mover and shaker. And it makes
it so much easier to distribute those pesky press releases.
</P>
<P>
   _Remember that floor space equals buzz.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest names at E3 had the biggest booths. Sony. Sega.
Nintendo. Microsoft and Electronic Arts. Acclaim claimed a huge
chunk of space for a relatively small area of game demonstrations.
But because of the security mentioned earlier, the general E3
public didn't know that, and had to wonder what kinds of goodies
were inside.
</P>
<P>
   _Give out free stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Acclaim and Iguana handed out stickers to publicize the new
Chef's Luv Shack game that Iguana produced in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   _Oh yeah, the games.
</P>
<P>
   Have at least some games available to players.
</P>
<P>
   If they're good, the players will come.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-05-15-99 0051E
</P>
