<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Wednesday, May 19, 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ALIEN-LIFE-SEARCHER (San Francisco) _ NASA's scientific search
for alien life now has a world-famous director _ a Nobel laureate.
Baruch Blumberg, who won the 1976 Nobel Prize for
physiology/medicine, will be the new head of the space agency's
Astrobiology Institute based at NASA's Ames Research Center in
Mountain View, Calif. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   UNSAFE-HUDSON-RIVER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Contaminated sediments will
continue to be a major source of PCBs in the upper Hudson River for
years to come, and fish in some areas will remain unsafe to eat for
at least a decade if nothing is done to clean up the problem,
according to a new study by the Environmental Protection Agency. By
ELIZABETH BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND-POLICE (Oakland, Calif.) _ To lead his campaign to
change his city's crime-ridden image, Mayor Jerry Brown tapped the
young captain in charge of East Oakland's toughest neighborhoods as
the new police chief. He's Capt. Richard Word, 37, a 15-year
department veteran who has reduced drug-related violence in the
flatlands near the Oakland Coliseum. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and
ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   MALCOLM-X-DIARY (San Francisco) _ The family of Malcolm X is
poised to sue to stop the sale of the slain civil rights leader's
diary by the Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield auction house here on May
27. New York attorney Joseph Fleming, representing the heirs of
Malcolm X and his late wife Betty Shabazz, says his inquiries so
far indicate the diary, worth up to $50,000, was stolen. By ERIC
BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   TAMOXIFEN (San Francisco) _ A leading group of cancer
specialists has recommended that doctors offer the widely debated
drug tamoxifen to tens of millions of healthy women worried about
developing breast cancer, a move that stunned some members of the
San Francisco Bay area's medical community and outraged activists
in the field. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSITY-EXPANSION (Albany, N.Y.) _ The State University of
New York at Albany's east campus was an abandoned site just four
years ago. Now it's undergoing explosive growth. Six new labs are
being added, a biotech firm there will grow by 50 percent, and a
center for gene studies will be established within the next month.
By CLAIRE HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   BERRY-UNION (San Francisco) _ Banking on a change of political
climate since its stunning defeat last summer, the United Farm
Workers Union is calling for a representation election at Coastal
Berry Inc., the nation's biggest strawberry grower, based in
Watsonville, Calif. The UFW has petitioned the state Agricultural
Labor Relations Board in Salinas, and the board must by law
schedule one on or before May 24. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CARE (San Francisco) _ As health insurance rates keep
rising, workers' benefits are sure to suffer, health care experts
say. Their assertion came in the wake of a vote Tuesday by the
California Public Employees' Retirement System (CalPERS) to allow
health maintenance organizations to raise rates for its members by
an average of 9.7 percent next year. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COSMETICS-FIRMS (San Francisco) _ Small cosmetics firms are
sprouting all over the place. Heavy Duty, a company in Carmel,
Calif., features a product called Hand Gear, a rich, hydrating hand
cream that the firm's owner, Alexandra Volkmann, says will fill a
niche. Market observers say there's an international explosion in
cutting-edge beauty and personal care products. By BETH HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-ONLINE (San Francisco) _ If you're you still dying for
an early viewing of Star Wars, relax, crank up the home computer
and start bidding on the hundreds of online offers for opening-week
tickets for ``The Phantom Menace.'' By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-STAR (San Francisco) _ At 26, Haile Gebrselassie, who grew
up in a hut in his native Ethiopia, has become a film star. Never
heard of Gebrselassie? Wave the white flag when it comes to its
pronunciation? (Geb-rah-sell-ah-see.) Don't feel bad. He's little
known, but he starred in a Walt Disney Pictures movie,
``Endurance,'' written and directed by the Englishman Leslie
Woodhead, that's both a documentary (in contemporary scenes), and a
drama. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Danny Piazza lives in a
middle-class suburb of Albany. He recently got a notice say that
there's a pedophile living in his neighborhood. But under New
York's version of Megan's Law _ which requires dislosure of
convicted sexual offenders _ he can get only limited details.
``It's ridiculous,'' he says. It is. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
