<HEADER>
A3026 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-SPRAWL-BOS &LR;      05-19 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SPRAWL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT ON SPRAWL RAISES HABITAT CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As Massachusetts loses 44 acres a day to development,
efforts to protect open space have accelerated recently, but barely
one-sixth of the state can be called truly protected wildlife
habitat, according to a new Massachusetts Audubon Society report.
</P>
<P>
   While the study reiterates now-common fears that Massachusetts
is losing swaths of countryside to sprawl, one of its more
innovative features is scrutinizing the quality of so-called
protected open space _ much of which turns out to include prison
yards, covered landfills, golf courses and other
less-than-truly-natural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is talking about the value of the land we're losing,''
said John J. Clarke, advocacy director for the society.
Environmentalists and state officials have perhaps been overly
focused on a ``numbers game'' of boosting acres of land publicly
owned, rather than focusing on protecting natural habitats, Clarke
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do a better job of convincing people that it's
important to buy land for functional wildlife habitats, not just
for soccer fields,'' Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the report found that 23.8 percent of the state's 3.76
million acres of land has been developed, up from 15 percent in
1971 and 20 percent in 1985. Most of the growth is coming from
demand for houses, malls and office parks on Cape Cod, in
southeastern Massachusetts and the lower Connecticut River Valley,
and booming exurban communities along Interstate 495.
</P>
<P>
   But while state and federal agencies count 40 percent of the
state as protected open space, the Audubon study contends that no
more than 17.3 percent should really be counted as what it calls
``truly protected wildlife habitat.''
</P>
<P>
   The 40 percent figure includes land that has been altered in
ways that may threaten native animals and plants, and includes
sections of military bases, covered landfills, school campuses,
prison yards, amusement parks, ski areas and golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes land subject to what the society considers
less-than-permanent protection, including nearly 270,000 acres
under Chapter 61 agriculture, conservation or forestry arrangements
that provide a temporary local tax break for the owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all open space is equally valuable or healthy habitat; not
all developed land is equally degraded,'' study author Jennifer
Steele wrote. ``Not all protection is equal or equally effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Clarke said, protected wildlife habitat areas tend to
be highly fragmented and ``in some areas like a museum inside a
fence,'' rather than continuous areas that can support a natural
ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   For conservation advocates, the report does show some positive
trends. The annual rate of conversion of land in the state has
dropped from 21,000 acres a year in the mid-1980s to about 16,000
acres per year recently.
</P>
<P>
   Also, from 1988 to 1997, land has been formally protected for
wildlife habitat 48 percent faster than it has been developed, a
rate the society acknowledged is ``high and should be lauded.''
</P>
<P>
   James C. Dougherty, president of the 15,000-member Massachusetts
Association of Realtors, said he was surprised that the Audubon
report found that less than a quarter of the state has been
developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us live in communities that are being built up faster
than we might like,'' Dougherty said, but the solution lies in
better local planning and land conservation efforts based on broad,
locally approved taxes rather than taxes only on home sales.
</P>
<P>
   However, given projections showing Massachusetts will continue
to gain population over the next 25 years, Dougherty said, ``If you
don't have new construction, you're going to have a lot of people
living in the street. . . . The key is managing growth so that it
is done intelligently and properly.''
</P>
<P>
   State Environmental Affairs Secretary Robert A. Durand has begun
developing ``build-out analyses'' for all 351 cities and towns in
Massachusetts to show local officials how much development could
occur under their current zoning codes, with more than 20 such
studies completed in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   After the state last year met a goal of preserving 100,000 acres
of land during the 1990s, Governor Paul Cellucci set as a state
goal preserving another 200,000 acres of open space by 2010.
Cellucci's new goal includes not just additions to state forests
and parks but nonprofit nature preserves and agreements by
landowners and farmers not to develop their land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
