<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3028 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN-AR     05-19 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
TORRE BEST OF NEW YORK STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-SHAUGHNESSY COLUMN-ART-BOS 
(ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Yankees are in town, but Don Zimmer isn't managing and Roger
Clemens isn't pitching. Those boys from the Bronx simply have no
sense of drama. None at all.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening farewell for a now-officially-moribund Fenway
Park, the Yanks Tuesday night lost to Pedro Martinez, 6-3, and fell
into second place behind the surging Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   It was especially painful for New Yorkers because the fall from
first came on the night of Joe Torre's return to the bench. It
seems poor Joe just can't keep the Bombers on top the way Zim did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very good, very calm,'' Torre said after the game, his
first since he was sidelined with prostate cancer during spring
training. ``There was no stress for me tonight. The only thing I
had to be careful of was my hands. I didn't want to reach up and
scratch something and all of a sudden there'd be some guy running
to second base.''
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner watched from his box next to the Yankee
dugout and was in Torre's office after the frustrating defeat. He
did not look particularly happy after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the loss, there was nonstop action on the visitors'
side of the field. Noble Torre was back in the corner office, Zim
was on the bench, holding a fungo bat, officially done as manager
(itals)for the last time.(unitals) Meanwhile, the Rocket was
meeting behind closed doors with Torre, general manager Brian
Cashman was again proving to be the exact opposite of Dan Duquette
(read: accessible), and Steinbrenner was sitting in Box 65-D of a
near-empty Fenway discussing Torre, Zimmer, Clemens, old Fenway,
new Fenway, and his days running track for Williams in the old
Boston Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Whew. All that and we hadn't even seen Pedro (11 more strikeouts
and 136 pitches) yet.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Torre qualifies as one of the feel-good stories of
the spring. The perfect manager for this near-perfect team, Torre
was diagnosed early in spring training and left the team for
surgery and recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   In Torre's absence, the Yankees turned to Zimmer, who honored
his friend by leaving the manager's office chair empty and refusing
the front-row seat on the team bus and airplane.
</P>
<P>
   All the Yankees had faith that Torre was coming back sometime
this summer, and the decision was made while the manager and his
wife had dinner at home Monday night. Torre called Steinbrenner
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``George kept saying, `Are you sure; are you sure?' '' said
Torre. ``He was flying today, getting in around two, so I asked him
if he could go a little earlier and we'd fly together.''
</P>
<P>
   They did. Torre was in the Yankee clubhouse by mid-afternoon.
The first players he saw were Jeff Nelson and Joe Girardi. And he
saw Zim. The infamous former Sox manager has been getting to the
park early for 51 years, and Tuesday was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer wasn't doing any formal interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done with that,'' said the man who steered the S.S.
Steinbrenner for two months. ``I'm just a bench coach.''
</P>
<P>
   There's speculation in Yankeeland that Zimmer might quit. He has
been hobbled by a bum knee and threatened to retire once Torre
returned. His threats are sometimes ignored because he's retired a
couple of times already. The lovable Zim has become like the
neighborhood barkeep who gets into a snit with management and quits
every other weekend, only to return on Monday. He might be serious
this time. His knee is a legitimate pain, and it's no secret that
he feels unappreciated by the Boss.
</P>
<P>
   Sox fans were denied the delicious prospect of watching Zim
march out with the lineup card, but that's not as regrettable as
the Yankees' decision to bring Clemens off the disabled list Friday
in Chicago rather than Thursday at Fenway. Torre took credit/blame
for the decision, just as John McNamara didn't take the blame for
removing Clemens from Game 6 in '86.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the Rocket was magnificently obtuse, even by the
lofty standards he set during his 12-year Boston career. As if
trained in the Duquette school of no-pulse nonspeak, Clemens said
it made no difference whether he pitched here or at the new
Comiskey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I badly want to pitch, but we're just looking at the big
picture,'' said Clemens. ``There's no more distractions here than I
have when I pitch in Texas. I'm sure I'll pitch here again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Rog. Does that mean you'll stare at the Jerry Reinsdorf
luxury box when you walk off the field after fanning 16 White Sox
Friday night?
</P>
<P>
   For New Yorkers, the bottom line is that the Yankees are whole
again. They have their trusty manager, they'll soon have another
ace, and Boston's flirtation with first should be brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Torre is a player's manager,'' said the respectful Derek
Jeter. ``There's a calmness when he's around. Nothing seems to faze
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a couple of months since things seemed normal,''
said Girardi. ``Joe's our leader, and we're accustomed to seeing
Joe in the leader's chair.''
</P>
<P>
   Proving that courage and class supersede even the polarizing
passion of the Red Sox-Yankee rivalry, many Fenway fans stood and
applauded madly when Torre brought out the lineup card before the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was moving,'' said the manager. ``I didn't want to take the
lineup card out, but I asked my bench coach (Zimmer) and he told me
I should take it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said his comeback had nothing to do with Boston and was
not expedited by New York's mid-May free-fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been taking my daughter to arts and crafts every
Tuesday,'' said Torre. ``My wife took her (yesterday), and I think
that was OK with her. I was happy to be going back to work. This is
where I want to be. We've created something special here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been ready for about a week. I'd been thinking about
coming back sometime during this series. So (Tuesday) morning I
called Zim and told him, `Are you ready to do the job you were
hired to do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer was ready. George was ready. Roger was (almost) ready.
And the Yankees should be ready to resume the dominance that marked
their 1999 season under the steady hand of Torre.
</P>
<P>
   Now they just have to get climb over the first-place Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
