<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3029 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENTURE-CAPITAL-BOS &LR;      05-19 1527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-CAPITAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURE CAPITAL: INTERNET SPEEDS MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pressure was on. The venture capitalists at Highland Capital
Partners were eyeing BeFree Inc., a promising Internet start-up in
Marlborough, Mass. that had come to their attention just three days
before. Normally, partners of the Boston venture firm would take up
to four weeks to check out the entrepreneur, his business plan and
his references, often in face-to-face meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But other venture capitalists were ready to rain money on
BeFree. So the four partners of Highland had to move quickly: They
canceled all their appointments and spent just a day on the phone
evaluating their prospect. Within 48 hours, Highland committed $10
million to BeFree and its founder, Gordon Hoffstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it `fire drill' due diligence,'' chuckles Paul A.
Maeder, managing general partner. ``If we didn't act quickly we
would have lost the deal. There's a frenzy out there with Internet
start-ups we have never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the frenetic new world of venture capital. The
financiers who have traditionally bankrolled promising technology
start-ups are throwing out many of the old rules of venture
investing to keep up with the Internet gold rush.
</P>
<P>
   With on-line ventures cropping up all over, the money men of
high tech are adopting a new code of behavior that matches what
some would call the ``irrational exuberance'' of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists are moving at warp speed, making decisions
in hours and days instead of weeks and months. Attention to profit
is being jettisoned in favor of fast growth for their portfolio
companies. Product technology, once the main reason for investing
in a young company, is taking a back seat to marketing and creating
a brand name for an Internet venture.
</P>
<P>
   The financiers are betting larger sums, up to $50 million on a
single Internet prospect, compared to less than $30 million for a
computer hardware firm just six years ago, for instance. Naturally,
with more money and higher risks, venture capitalists are looking
for quicker payoffs from their investments by either selling the
company or taking it public within 24 months instead of the
traditional three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Given Wall Street's fervor for Internet stocks, venture
capitalists, like many investors, are looking to strike while the
market is still hot. The scramble to get in on the most promising
deals has prompted some of the most daring venture capitalists to
commit $5 million or more to a single on-line company after a mere
two-hour meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet start-ups today are a once in a lifetime
opportunity,'' says Jonathan Flint, general partner of Polaris
Venture Partners, a three-year old Waltham, Mass. venture capital
that has invested in more than a dozen Internet-related companies.
``While Amazon.com, Netscape, e-Bay, and a few others have the
mother lode, there is still some adjoining acreage where you can
mine for gold _ and that's what we are after.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Internet is seizing a bigger and bigger share of the
venture capital pie. Overall, a whopping $13.7 billion was invested
last year in 2,023 high technology and biomedical companies
nationwide, according to Technologic Partners' Venture Finance, a
publication that tracks venture spending. Nearly half of the
companies were Internet-related. In 1997, 627 deals captured $2.5
billion in venture funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a a land grab and there are no signs of an
Internet investment slowdown,'' says Richard A. Shaffer, Venture
Finance editor and publisher. ``The Internet is so central to
investing that many venture capital firms have stopped doing life
science and health care deals. Why spend a decade going through
clinical trials and federal approvals when you can launch an
Internet company that the public may buy?''
</P>
<P>
   But some worry that venture capitalists may be throwing caution
to the winds. Their hefty bets in small companies that are years
from profitability could backfire, particularly if Internet stocks
tumble on Wall Street and dampen the overall market for on-line
ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ``.com'' fever that has struck the venture community
has made a big difference to entrepreneurs looking for money.
</P>
<P>
   Stig Leschly, founder of Exchange.com, for instance, raised
venture money in less than six weeks. Exchange.com, which runs Web
sites that bring buyers and sellers of antique books and old music
recordings together, got $12 million in venture capital, including
$4.5 million from Polaris.
</P>
<P>
   He and his investors found out how quickly they could hit the
jackpot. Just seven months after Leschly formed the Cambridge,
Mass. company, Exchange.com was snapped up by Amazon.com for more
than $200 million, even though Exchange.com in the first quarter
lost $1.2 million on revenues of only $173,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has happened very quickly,'' says Leschly, 29, who
will relocate his company to Amazon.com's Seattle headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   And with scores of Internet ventures being formed monthly, some
venture capitalists are quick to switch investments if they
perceive another on-line company can get to market first.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Polaris did after spending $250,000 to form
Netconnects, a start-up in Sunnyvale, Calif., that planned to put
classified advertisements on the World Wide Web. After learning
that another company, Classifieds 2000 of Santa Clara, Calif., had
the same idea but was about four months ahead in developing its
service, Polaris abandoned Netconnects and invested $1.5 million in
Classifieds 2000 instead. The payoff came in April 1998, when
Classified 2000 was acquired by Excite.com for nearly $50 million
in Excite.com stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Classified 2000 could get bigger very quickly and give us
branding _ name recognition _ plus we could also sell it very
quickly,'' explains Flint.
</P>
<P>
   Besides making decisions faster, venture capitalists have
adopted new rules for the Internet age. They used to nurture
start-ups through many years and rounds of financing, guiding a
company to profits before taking it public. Now, the Internet
corporate motto seems to be ``Get big fast; profits can wait.'' And
since most on-line companies provide a service rather than make a
product, technology is overshadowed by the marketing quest for ever
more ``eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   For Desh Deshpande, the founder of Cascade Communications Corp.,
one of the state's most successful telecommunications companies of
the 1990s, the rapid financing of electronic commerce companies is
strikingly different from the funding of high-tech manufacturing
companies like Cascade, which received venture financing in the
early 1990's before going public in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are used to building revenues and profits, so valuing a
company based on eyeballs . . . is a very different concept,'' says
Deshpande, who now runs Sycamore Networks Inc., a
telecommunications business in Chelmsford.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, venture capitalist firms are hustling to taking on
more deals. Polaris, for instance, has backed more than a dozen
electronic commerce and Internet software companies _ including
Exchange.com, Wrenchead.com of Armonk, N.Y., an on-line auto parts
business headed by Gus Conrales, and Crimson Solutions of Boston, a
Web-based job search service for college students and recent
graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when a venture partner launched two start-ups
a year, spending 60 to 90 days to evaluate deals. Several venture
capitalists said they each expect to finance and oversee a half
dozen Internet deals this year, making financing decisions in less
than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists are finding that the entrepreneur and his
management team are often far younger but more business-savvy than
some of the engineers who founded earlier generations of technology
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing founders of Internet companies who are very
bright, generally under 35, who are knowledgeable about consumer
marketing. We would not have seen that five years ago,'' says
Robert F. Higgins, a Highland managing general partner, noting that
the Internet has prompted young executive talent to forgo the
corporate ladder for a chance to become an entreprenuer.
</P>
<P>
   Among the youngest local entreprenurs is 23-year-old Wellie
Chao, who formed Crimson Solutions with two schoolmates while
attending Harvard College. His company's Web site,
``eRecruiting.com'' enables students and alumni of nearly 60
colleges to search on line for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   At 46, Gordon Hoffstein of BeFree is among the older leaders of
an Internet company. His ability to get a quick financial
commitment from Highland stemmed in large part from his successful
track record launching two previous companies: MicroAmerica, a
computer hardware distributor, and PCs Compleat, a mail-order
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1991, I got venture financing for PCs Compleat, but it took
about six months. Now with so much investment money available, not
only is it a lot easier . . . but the competition . . . favors the
entrepreneur, something we have not seen before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
