<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-MIGRANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG SEEKS CONSTITUTIONAL REVIEW IN MIGRANT CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In what critics are calling the worst threat to Hong
Kong's autonomy since the former British colony was returned to
China in 1997, the local government plans to ask Beijing to
reinterpret the territory's constitution to block a flood of
migrants from mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa and his Cabinet say they had no
choice but to ask China to override a Hong Kong supreme court
ruling granting residency to all mainland-born children of Hong
Kong residents _ including illegitimate children and children born
before their parents gained citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Tung will ask Beijing to throw out the court ruling and narrow
residency rights to children born after their parents became
residents, a move that the government says would cut those eligible
to 200,000, from 1.67 million. Tung's announcement followed a
three-week government drumbeat of doomsday predictions if Hong Kong
were forced to accommodate a tidal wave of new arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's legal community and opposition legislators decried
the decision, calling it a violation of Hong Kong's judicial
independence. Tung's request to Beijing makes a mockery of the
Court of Final Appeal, the supreme court, and opens the door for
the government to reject any court ruling it dislikes, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the government is doing is to teach the five judges a
lesson for not ruling in their favor,'' said Martin Lee, chairman
of the opposition Democratic Party and a prominent lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a move,'' he said, ``would cause untold damage to the
rule of law, the independence of the judiciary, the `one
country-two systems' arrangement and the so-called `high degree of
autonomy' Hong Kong is supposed to enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``one country-two systems'' model promises capitalist Hong
Kong autonomy from communist China on all matters other than
defense and foreign affairs. Under the Basic Law, Hong Kong's
postcolonial constitution, the former colony was allowed to retain
its British legal system, and its Court of Final Appeal was to be
the final arbiter of law.
</P>
<P>
   The government insists the request is an exceptional case and in
the best interest of Hong Kong, which could not afford a projected
25 percent increase in its 6.8 million population over the next 13
years. The government has said taxpayers would have to spend $92
billion for new infrastructure and $4 billion annually for social
services to accommodate the new arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only on such extraordinary issues that we take such
unusual steps,'' Tung said. ``Truly, Hong Kong cannot accept such a
huge population growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the government has inflated the figures of people
eligible for residency to scare the public. If the government's
survey is accurate, 692,000 people would be immediately eligible to
move here, but 20 percent of people surveyed said they did not
expect their mainland-born children to come.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong already accepts 150 mainland immigrants a day.
Accommodating all of the newly eligible people in a timely manner,
however, would require raising the quota to a number somewhere
between several hundred and 1,000 a day, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has repeatedly said in recent months that it would
prefer Hong Kong to settle the matter itself but would assist the
territory if asked for help. Under the Basic Law, the standing
committee of the National People's Congress _ China's rubber-stamp
parliament _ can ``reinterpret'' Hong Kong's constitution, or the
congress as a whole can vote to amend the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy advocates and lawyers say it would be preferable to
amend the Basic Law to limit residency rights rather than overturn
the court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials say it would take too long to amend the
constitution, since the congress as a whole will not meet again
till next March _ too late to block an expected wave of arrivals.
The standing committee of the National People's Congress meets next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of demonstrators on both sides of the issue chanted and
waved banners throughout the day outside the legislature. Polls
indicate most locals fear the arrival of migrants and disagree with
the court ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
