<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOT OF NEW AGE HOT AIR ABOUT OXYGEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This would make Chicken Little subscribe to Consumer Reports. In
our latest peril, the sky is not falling. It has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our atmosphere is severely depleted of oxygen!''
</P>
<P>
   ``As toxic levels on our planet increase and as oxygen levels
decrease, it becomes apparent we must do something!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bodies are now experiencing oxygen starvation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Without adequate supplies of oxygen, in effect, you are merely
rearranging the deck chairs on the Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   You do not have to suffer this dying world. Earth may be the
Titanic, but the new pushers of panic have your life preserver.
They say they have oxygen in tablets. They claim to have oxygen in
drops. You can drop into oxygen bars in California and abroad to
get a direct hit of oxygen from a tank.
</P>
<P>
   You can save your life, if you pay $29.95 for the bottle. This
is a typical price that several nutritional supplement companies
are charging in a racket that gives New Age a bad name. With the
paranoia of characters in a Woody Allen movie, company after
company tries to outdo the other in depicting the putrid state of
our air. Even though scientists say there is still quite sufficient
oxygen to maintain a healthy earth, one Internet ad for a product
called Oxy-Moxy said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Many years ago there was 30 to 35 percent oxygen in the air.
Generally there is now 18 to 20 percent. In certain industrial
cities (e.g. Gary, Ind.) oxygen levels in the air have fallen to 12
to 14 percent _ dangerously close to the minimum that's needed to
sustain human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the claims of how oxygen tablets and drops can
``sustain human life'' have caught the attention of the government.
Early in the spring, the Federal Trade Commission embarrassed two
particularly aggressive companies, Rose Creek Health Products and
the Staff of Life. The companies had advertised ``Vitamin O'' in
big ads in USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC said ``Vitamin O'' was just bottled salt water.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, because of the way our hemoglobin works,
physiologists say you get more oxygen out of one deep breath than
you can ever obtain with a full day of supplements. Furthermore,
the supplements that advertise oxygen in liquid drops are utterly
useless, since the only way you could absorb oxygen out of water is
if you had gills like a fish. ``It's a psych job,'' said Frank
Katch, exercise physiologist at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst. ``There's no physiological benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   That has not stopped many other companies from trying to psych
out consumers. Between the many companies and their products,
products with names like OxyToddy, OxyBody, Oxy-Gen, Oxy Cooler,
Oxyrich, and Oxygen Solution, the products claim to treat just
about anything imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling ugly? One company's doggerel for a skin moisturizer
claims, ``When superoxygenated minerals are formulated together
with natural pigments, they share their oxygen with these pigments,
turning this nourishing moisturizer into a skin-beautifying
treatment'' that ``protects your face from environmental
pollutants.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling sick? The oxygen products supposedly treat headaches,
asthma, high blood pressure, cancer, and AIDS. They claim to keep
the blood pure and the colon clean.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling mortal? One company, Life Extensions, posted on its Web
page: ``Oxygen capsules: Researchers find technique to resupply
critical nutrient and halt aging.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot air has long been used to sell air. In 1846, George Green,
in an ad endorsed by five US senators and four congressmen,
proclaimed that ``the celebrated oxygenated bitters'' were ``a sure
remedy for dyspepsia, asthma, and general debility.'' In 1887, a
product called Seven Barks claimed that ``The sixth layer of bark
acted upon the lungs, making the breathing healthy and natural, a
means by which the blood becomes oxydized while passing through the
organs of respiration.''
</P>
<P>
   You would think that by now, just as we are about to celebrate a
millennium when we will praise our progress in medicine and public
health, from sanitation to cutting the mortality rate from cancer,
the Federal Trade Commission would not have to be concerned with
such farcical products.
</P>
<P>
   But just when you thought the FTC was driving Rose Creek
underground, along comes another company with Cat and Dog Oxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oxy-Pet delivers more oxygen (and oxygen energy) into the
bloodstream from every breath,'' the ad said. ``Important for
animals, who are exposed to so much more pollution than humans are,
since most pollutants are heavier than air and their nostrils are
closer to the ground. Provides added energy and vitality, a better
coat and resistance to aging.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Little, holding his Consumer Reports, has to be clucking
at the quacks who claim even Fido can have eternal youth. As for
me, I will continue to take my chances with exhaling and inhaling.
The New Age of oxygen pills and drops returns us to the old age of
selling you nothing for something.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
