<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPA AND PRIVACY; FUN WITH `PHANTOM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a cartoon on the contributor's page of this week's New
Yorker, Robert Mankoff drops a real photo of J. D. Salinger into a
sketch of a TV news show. The caption reads: ``And, in literary
news, J. D. Salinger's privacy has been violated once again by his
appearance in this cartoon.'' It's funny to rib Salinger about his
famous reclusiveness, particularly in the magazine that was once
his home, and it's even funnier to upend the media that manufacture
their own ``news.'' Just about everyone looks silly in the
cartoon's perspective, including the viewer with his nose sticking
into the inane TV report.
</P>
<P>
   But violation of privacy is more than just a joke in this issue
of The New Yorker, for it contains an excerpt from Ernest
Hemingway's forthcoming ``unpublished novel,'' or ``fictionalized
memoir,'' which has been given the title ``True at First Light.''
The book has been edited by Hemingway's son Patrick, who cut the
850-page manuscript in half, but it's hard to forget that his
father did not intend to release it for publication. See how you
feel reading the piece, which will find its way into the author's
oeuvre despite his wishes. There are a few moments of descriptive
grace, but it is clearly unfinished and lacking in Hemingway
polish. Set in East Africa, the excerpt revolves around the
shooting of a troublesome lion and a pair of eagles, as well as the
shooting of the horse that became the bait for the lion and the
eagles. Somehow all that predatory activity seems fitting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of predators . . . Sometimes it looks as though the
more that's written around a piece of entertainment _ interviews
with stars, articles on budget and special effects _ the less we
can expect from the entertainment itself. I'm talking ``Phantom
Menace,'' of course, the prequel that appears to be classier than
your everyday average money-grubbing sequel only because of its
``Star Wars'' ancestry, an ancestry whose reputation has become
inflated now that sci-fi event movies are a way of life. Unable to
leave the ``Star Wars'' series alone, particularly after its
lucrative return as a ``Special Edition,'' George Lucas has opted
to forget about restraint and unleash on us not only prequels 4, 5,
and 6 but a seemingly unending torrent of promotional blather.
</P>
<P>
   Of the bazillion ``Phantom Menace'' pieces on newsstands these
days, the only one I could read was in Movieline, thinking it was
probably the one movie magazine able to resist all the glee.
Indeed, the June issue has a Joe Queenan piece in which the always
sour writer puts on a Yoda mask and makes his way around New York
speaking lines like ``Have will I your largest caffe latte, yes,
um.'' Guess what? No one seems to care much about Yoda, although
Queenan does manage to put his annoying Yoda persona to practical
use with telephone marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Movieline also features a list of ``100 Questions We Honestly
Want to Ask Hollywood,'' beginning with ``Where is Roberto
Benigni's `off' button?'' Other pressing questions include ``Do
Joseph Fiennes and Ralph Fiennes really share any DNA?'' and ``How
did God let Keanu Reeves get born 75 years too late for the great
Silent Movie Era?'' But the timeliest question is a good one: ``If
`Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace' doesn't make more money
than any film in history in the first 10 days, is it a failure?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Love, the managing editor of Rolling Stone, comes up with
the word for the tone of today's entertainment world: It's
``adolescentric.'' After all, teenagers will spend some $141
billion this year, and everybody wants a piece of that. Back in the
early 1990s, it took boomercentric advertisers a while to catch on
to the Generation X factor; but absolutely no one is missing out on
the new kids _ ``Echo Boomers, the Baby Boomlet, the Millennial
Generation, Generation Wired, Generation Y,'' whatever. Like it or
not, we're marching to a teen beat.
</P>
<P>
   Buried in the issue's ``Teen Hot List'' is a little piece called
``The Sell,'' which helps define what the magazine's cover heralds
as ``The New Teen Spirit.'' Unlike Generation X, today's teenagers
don't object to being marketed to _ as long as it's good marketing:
``And we all know what bad marketing looks like. It's either stiff
and lame or else too self-consciously hip. It features slang that
is so fifteen minutes ago. It talks down to teenagers. It fails to
recognize that a fifteen-year-old only wants to act and buy like a
seventeen-year-old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
