<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3047 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SPELL-BOS &LR;      05-19 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SPELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WONDROUS DESIGN, BUT A FLAT RENDERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE SPELL 
By Alan Hollinghurst 
Viking, 257 pp., $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan Hollinghurst's third novel, ``The Spell,'' has the formal
elegance of an 18th-century garden, but the story it tells is about
romps in the bushes. Nature always will burst through patterns of
order to claim its own. The amusing fascination of the novel lies
in the discrepancies between human nature and artistic design.
</P>
<P>
   Hollinghurst puts two couples through an intricate pavane. Robin
Woodfield, an architect, is trying to rebuild his life with a young
would-be actor named Justin after the loss of his lover to AIDS.
Justin invites his own ex-lover Alex down to the country cottage
for the weekend; during the stay, Alex meets Robin's young gay son,
Danny, and ultimately takes up with him (``Dan,'' his father says,
``you can't be serious!''). Drifting through the story is a teenage
handyman named Terry, the cheerfully slutty town hustler, who winds
up in just about everybody's bed as Hollinghurst explores the
nuances of the complicated relationships among his characters _
takers and givers, father and son, son and lovers, lover and
ex-lover _ and the strains of coupledom, which one pair survives
and another doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   A nifty little prelude and a postlude frame the story. In the
prelude we meet Robin during his student days, 20 years before the
principal events of the story. He's making a pilgrimage through the
Arizona desert to the ruins of a house designed by Frank Lloyd
Wright. Afterward, he stumbles into a bar, where he is about to
score with a cowboy when he makes a prearranged phone call to
London and learns he's going to become a father _ the first of the
book's many paradoxes and surprises. The postlude reunites most of
the principal characters, after a decent interval full of change
and stability, and they repeat an excursion to the brink of the
Dorset cliffs over the ocean _ but now there is a different sort of
brinksmanship, not the self-dramatizing kind but the kind that runs
through entire lives, as some of these characters have finally
realized.
</P>
<P>
   Hollinghurst builds his novel on contrasts, between youth and
age; between friendship and love, sex and romance; between city and
country, chamber music and club music; between natural states and
minds altered by drugs and alcohol. These contrasts generate gentle
humor, particularly when Hollinghurst deploys them in unexpected
ways and among unconventional people. He's also a witty, if not an
ostentatious, stylist, who describes Alex in a sex shop as standing
``amid the alien porn.'' The writer doesn't play favorites, and no
one has all the good lines _ and no one gets off easy.
</P>
<P>
   Readers of Hollinghurst's earlier novels, ``The Swimming-Pool
Library'' and ``The Folding Star,'' may, however, regret a certain
lack of density in this book _ deftly designed as it is, and full
of such entertaining set pieces as a scandalous but curiously
old-fashioned country-house party that brings all the characters
and conflicts together, like the second-act curtain of a play by W.
Somerset Maugham (``The Circle,'' say). Hollinghurst, like Proust,
is a novelist who happens to be gay rather than a gay novelist who
is in the business of writing gay novels. But this book does become
exasperatingly narrow in focus. ``Don't these people ever think
about anything other than their own emotional and sexual
gratification?'' we begin to wonder _ as we don't in pure farce or
romantic comedy. Hollinghurst's problem is that he has conferred
dimensions of depth on his characters that he doesn't plumb.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he enjoys some fun at the expense of Danny,
exemplar of the feckless young. ``Danny brought his big notebook
with him as usual, and his more secret plan was to try to write a
play about some of the people he knew on the club scene. . . . He
didn't envisage any technical obstacles to writing something
stageable and sensationally topical; he spent one morning planning
the guest list for the first-night party, and going over certain
points in the interviews he would give.'' But he also understands
Danny, or Alex comes to understand him. ``Danny would be a great
lover, that would be his career, though he knew next to nothing
about love, just as some great musicians knew nothing about music,
beyond their gift for making it.''
</P>
<P>
   While the other characters, unlike Danny, have jobs,
responsibilities, outside interests, and even ideas, we hear too
little about them as they move through their paces and places in
Hollinghurst's pattern. Something about Hollinghurst's other books
was unpredictable, but despite its cast of characters and louche
locales, ``The Spell'' remains curiously domesticated. It's a
romance, one may say in the book's defense. But Shakespeare knew
that romances were wild, and Hollinghurst doesn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
