<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCUSES FOR ALL `STAR WARS' NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today (May 19) is one of the most important days in postwar
American cultural history. A day as important, perhaps, as July 19,
1957, which must be around the time that Norman Mailer realized
that he _ and a generation of writers to follow _ could make more
money and achieve greater fame writing about themselves than
writing about the world around them. A day ranking in significance
with Feb. 15, 1987. That was when ABC television started
broadcasting its epochal, eerily prescient, seven-part series
``Amerika,'' about the Soviet takeover of America.
</P>
<P>
   Going to work or attending school is out of the question.
Workplace absenteeism alone is expected to run into the millions.
Massachusetts education officials stupidly scheduled their
notorious MCAS exams for this week. We can reasonably expect
several thousand ``incompletes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Commonwealth's own Brett Dewey gets it right on his
``Wookiee hooky'' Web site,
www.geocities.com/Hollywood/Studio/9203/: ``Skip Work, See Star
Wars!'' But to take the day off, you will need an excuse. Feel free
to borrow one of mine from this special Clip 'n' Save feature; I'm
into sharing.
</P>
<P>
   For schoolchildren: I took the day off to do astronomy research
for the MCAS.
</P>
<P>
   For gifted schoolchildren: We're reading Joseph Campbell's ``The
Hero With a Thousand Faces'' in English class, and I wanted to see
how the Jedi knights fit into Campbell's mythic schema.
</P>
<P>
   For Web-addicted schoolchildren: Harry (Knowles, Internet film
guru) told me to see it.
</P>
<P>
   For the sophisticated, albeit not totally credible, schoolchild:
I was attending Laurel Ulrich's lecture, ``Sheep in the Parlor,
Wheels on the Common: Needlework and Politics in 18th-century
Boston,'' at the Museum of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Public-sector employees: I'm owed a vacation day, I'm sure.
</P>
<P>
   Private-sector employees: I was working at home, I'm sure.
</P>
<P>
   Anglo-phonies' excuse: I was attending a memorial service
commemorating the 463d anniversary of the beheading of Anne Boleyn
(May 19, 1536).
</P>
<P>
   Anglo-phonies' excuse, Part Deux: I was attending a memorial
service commemorating the 64th anniversary of T. E. Lawrence's
death on May 19, 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Enough fiddle-faddle. The ``Star Wars'' situation is somewhat
complex. Because the movie falls far short of expectations _ yes, I
have seen it, at what my wife called a ``second-tier press
preview'' _ many citizens will need an excuse not to see the
capstone artistic creation of the American Century. Herewith, those
excuses:
</P>
<P>
   For PETA members: I can't bear to see Jabba the Hutt bite the
heads off those poor little lizards.
</P>
<P>
   For the overly sensitive: Jar Jar Binks's exaggerated Pimp Walk
is offensive to homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   For bibliophiles: I read the book (published May 3).
</P>
<P>
   For ``power'' computer users: I don't need to see the movie;
I'll download the 6 trillion-byte bootleg video from
copyrightinfringement.com.
</P>
<P>
   Theatergoers with a social conscience: I think it would be
better to use those 2,500 theaters to shelter Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   For scholarship students: I'm saving my grocery-bagging money to
see ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' 14 times.
</P>
<P>
   For cineastes: I couldn't miss ``Loony Tom the Happy Lover'' at
the Harvard Film Archive, a brilliant articulation of underground
filmmaker James Broughton's ``polymorphous, bisexual universe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3050 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-2ND &LR;      05-19 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (a and s coding)  
 BOSTON: ... Boston stadium.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On March 15, another key development occurred, not in New
England, but in Phoenix, where NFL owners voted to change league
policy to foster internal funding of stadium projects. Finneran
felt vindicated. And the door to bringing the Patriots back home
opened a little wider.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a key turning point,'' Finneran said
recently.``It meant the league might be willing to participate. And
it was a tacit acceptance of what the House had argued all along:
that those who stood to benefit from a new stadium, like the NFL
owners, also had to participate in funding it.''
</P>
<P>
   A month later, the Boston group -- now consisting of Kirk,
Monan, Boston Edison chairman Thomas J. May, Budd, and Connell --
began crafting an opinion piece to be published in the Globe. The
draft, articulating broad backing for keeping the team, was
circulated on Beacon Hill in advance so leaders would not be
stunned when they opened their papers April 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest is history,'' Kirk said. ``This thing just
unfolded.''
</P>
<P>
   The article triggered strong statements of support, most
importantly from Beacon Hill, and unexpectedly positive statements
from the mayor saying he was open-minded. Privately, though, it
soon became clear Menino still did not want a stadium in Boston, so
the group began focusing on Foxborough, the Patriots' base since
1971.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Birmingham, the Senate president and a former labor
negotiator, called Kirk at home, urging a face-to-face summit on
Beacon Hill the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I figured we might be able to get this done was
to all sit down in the same room and hammer it out,'' Birmingham
said. ``So that's what we proposed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It all came together, quite literally in the 11th hour _ on
Tuesday, April 27, at 11:35 p.m., to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   The state's power troika emerged from a three-hour meeting with
a plan that could upend everything the team planned and Hartford's
dream of becoming an NFL city.
</P>
<P>
   The seed planted by Kirk and Rooney nearly five months earlier
had sprouted in this cluster of leadership gathered in Birmingham's
cavernous office, paneled with Honduran Mahogany and draped in
patinated yellow and green fabric.
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the 12-foot antique table sat the House speaker,
Finneran. Birmingham sat at the other. Seated on blue-leather
chairs between them were Kirk, Governor Cellucci, Lieutenant
Governor Jane Swift, aides to all three political leaders,
stadium-expert Goodell, and another NFL executive, Neil Glat.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second night in a row the group had met in
Birmingham's office. The first evening, there was a lot of
posturing. By the second night, it was clear everyone was working
toward a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Except there was a sticking point: Finneran's demand that the
Patriots pay up to $2 million a year to cover some of the state's
costs for road, sewer, and other public infrastructure work
required at a new Foxboro Stadium. NFL officials balked, noting
that should be the state's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   A tense standoff ensued, and for a few minutes it looked like
the deal could die.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by the impasse, Cellucci, a strong supporter of a new
stadium for the Patriots, sided with Finneran. Still, NFL officials
insisted they couldn't agree to the payback language. To keep the
momentum of the talks going, Birmingham asked Kirk and the NFL men
to wait in another room while the three political leaders discussed
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   After about 30 minutes, they were invited back in, presented
with the the final plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a general feeling that this was it,'' Birmingham
said later. ``The deal was as good as it was going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Under the offer, drafted into the legislation that passed
Tuesday, Kraft would build the stadium, partially assisted by
low-rate NFL financing. The state would provide $70 million in
infrastructure improvements around Route 1. Further, Kraft would
grant an easement on his land, allowing the state to upgrade access
ramps and sewer lines on his private property.
</P>
<P>
   Several people involved in the negotiations claim credit for the
easement plan. But whoever promoted the idea, it broke the
stalemate by eliminating the land purchase component of the
Senate's last plan, which Finneran opposed, while preserving
infrastructure spending that the team deemed necessary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Massachusetts moved closer to a counteroffer, Connecticut
fell behind.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, on Thursday, April 29, a team of Patriots
consultants delivered a prognosis that put the Hartford deal in
critical condition: the stadium, they concluded, most likely could
not be ready by 2002, as promised, because it would take longer to
clear the site of the steam plant and scrub it of environmental
contamination. Under the stadium contract, that was enough for the
team to walk away without penalty, as long as it made the decision
by the upcoming Sunday, May 2.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft faced a choice: wait at least another year for the
Hartford stadium or take his chances in Massachusetts, where a plan
was now on the table but had not received full legislative
approval.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Kraft, his son Jonathan, and team executive Andy
Wasynczuk flew to Hartford to see if a third option was possible:
Would Connecticut extended the penalty-free deadline another month,
by which time a more definitive review of the site could be
completed?
</P>
<P>
   Rowland refused. Mostly, the governor couldn't believe the team
would really turn their backs on a free stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a game of high stakes poker'' said one person who was
in the room.``And I think the governor was calling the team's
bluff.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, furious and desperate, gave Kraft just 24 hours to
decide _ even though Kraft legally had several days to make up his
mind. The meeting ended. They all left the governor's office to
face a throng of reporters camped outside and issued sober, but
vague, statements about being committed to their ``goal'' of the
Patriots playing in Hartford by 2002. They shook hands as cameras
clicked and went their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a final parting.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants for both sides stayed up well into Friday morning,
trying to salvage the agreement, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the Krafts got a final consultants' report.
</P>
<P>
   With a void of good news, Robert Kraft retreated to his office
on the 34th floor of a Boston skyscraper to fax the formal
termination notice to Connecticut. He called Rowland as it was
being transmitted.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kraft and Wasynczuk left the room. It was a painful and
emotional conversation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, in Los Angeles promoting Massachusetts film
production, was chatting with renowned chef Wolfgang Puck, about to
make a cheese, tomato, and pepper pizza, when news of the stunning
about-face broke.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, Cellucci would be on the set of ``The Tonight
Show.'' Jay Leno, originally from the Boston area, gave a nod to
the governor during his opening monologue, asking him what was
happening with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The camera, beaming the program to some 6 million viewers, spun
around toward the audience where Cellucci sat smiling with his
thumb in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're staying,'' the governor shouted, ``in Massachusetts!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
