<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3056 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-BONANZA-BOS &LR;      05-19 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-BONANZA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS' A TOP BRAND, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inforonics wants a few good ``Star Wars'' fans. Looking to
recruit new workers, the tiny provider of ``e-business solutions''
will run help-wanted ads at some local theaters showing ``The
Phantom Menace,'' the new ``Star Wars'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   ```Star Wars' fans are our work force,'' says Inforonics vice
president Mark Pinsley, explaining the hiring strategy of the
Littleton, Mass. company.
</P>
<P>
   Set to debut May 19, ``The Phantom Menace'' is more than a
movie; it's a brand, a marketer's delight, a job recruiting device,
a Super Bowl of the cinema. Because it appeals to a host of
demographic groups, the movie is virtually certain to stir up a
merchandising frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies looking to exploit the hype that surrounds
the premiere of of the fourth ``Star Wars'' movie from George Lucas
are Hasbro, Taco Bell, Pepsi-Cola, and Lego.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is not to create hype; it's to control it,''
says Marty Brochstein, executive editor of the Licensing Letter, a
newsletter that tracks entertainment licensing deals.
</P>
<P>
   Many successful movies these days reach only a narrow segment of
the population. In 1997, it was teen-age girls who were largely
responsible for turning ``Titanic'' into a blockbuster. Two years
earlier, their younger sisters were wowed by ``Pocahontas,'' the
animated Disney film. But ``Lion King'' was a far bigger hit
because it impressed both girls and boys.
</P>
<P>
   `Star Wars'' is different. If Sir Thomas More was ``A Man for
All Seasons,'' then ``The Phantom Menace'' is a movie for nearly
all demographics.
</P>
<P>
   When toys inspired by the new movie went on sale earlier this
month, stores threw open their doors at midnight, not exactly
prime-time for the children.
</P>
<P>
   At the FAO Schwarz in Boston's Back Bay, it's been mostly adult
toy collectors who've been thronging the premises. Kids aren't
expected to start clamoring for the stuff until the movie debuts
and companies begin running ads for movie-related merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   To drive early sales, FAO Schwarz telemarketers called the
ever-growing number of adult toy collectors in its customer data
base. So far, light sabers and action figures of Darth Maul, the
movie's villain, have been the big hits with this crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's interested in the bad guy,'' says FAO Schwarz
spokeswoman Jennifer Picard. ``Darth Vader had such an effect on
people, and this guy is supposed to be worse.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the univeral appeal that sets ``Star Wars'' apart from
other toy fads, notes Toy Book publisher Jim Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Mighty Morphin Power Rangers from a few years ago?
Nearly 90 percent of Power Rangers toys were bought for a child
under the age of 8, he says. Not so with ``Star Wars.'' Adult
collectors account for about 75 percent of the early sales for
``Phantom Menace'' merchandise, he says. And the scramble that
these collectors touch off only adds to the movie's hype.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, ``The Phantom Menace'' will sell about $1
billion worth of toys this year. That's good news for Hasbro Inc.
of Pawtucket, R.I., which owns the licensing rights to the first
three ``Star Wars'' movies and which paid a hefty licensing fee for
the rights to make toys related to ``The Phantom Menace'' and the
two other movies that Lucas plans to make as part of his second
trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the life of the new deal, Hasbro is expected to pay $600
million in royalties to companies controlled by Lucas. At first,
plans called for Hasbro to share most of the toy market with
another company, Galoob Toys Inc. But partly to gain a bigger share
of the ``Star Wars'' toy market, Hasbro simply went out and bought
Galoob last year for $220 million.
</P>
<P>
   For Hasbro, the challenge is to sustain the ``Star Wars''
momentum for another decade; a short-term blowout around the
release of ``The Phantom Menace'' simply won't make the nut for the
world's second largest toymaker. To break even, Brochstein of the
Licensing Letter estimates Hasbro will have to sell $3 billion
worth of product over the life of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   One way to maximize future sales is for Hasbro to make exclusive
toy lines for various retailers. A few years ago, K-B Toys had
great success with an exclusive Han Solo storm-trooper line, says
K-B spokesman John Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro spokesman Wayne Charness says no exclusive lines are
planned this year. But don't be surprised to see them come out in
2000 and 2001, the interval between ``The Phantom Menace'' and the
scheduled release of the next movie in the trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to inspiration for toys, ``The Phantom Menace''
has ``incredible richness,'' says Charness, who notes that Hasbro
will introduce 200 new toys this year tied to the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way we could bring out all the fresh new product
from this movie in just a year,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Not all toys will be from Hasbro. Such is the beguiling nature
of the force that Lego Inc. has decided to enter into the first
licensing deal in its history.
</P>
<P>
   In the two decades since the release of the first ``Star Wars''
movie, toy companies have changed dramatically, and ``Star Wars''
may be one of the reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Once toy companies actually made toys. Now to a large degree,
they are marketing companies that manage merchandise licenses and
look to movies and TV for a boost. Today's toy companies are
``hitchhiking on Hollywood,'' says Babson College marketing
professor Kathleen Seiders.
</P>
<P>
   Given the synergies between the two industries, Boston
University professor Sue Parenio adds, ``You have to wonder which
came first _ the movie script or the marketing plan?''
</P>
<P>
   If Hasbro hopes to sell a ton of toys, PepsiCo Inc. looks to
move an ocean of soft drinks. Pepsi plans to distribute 5 billion
soda cans bearing the likenesses of characters from the new movie,
among them a ``special edition'' of Yoda cans.
</P>
<P>
   At e-Bay, the Internet auction house, reports already circulate
that a Yoda can will fetch $150, says Pepsi spokesman Jon Harris.
Pepsi isn't just putting pictures on soda cans; it's also enlisted
a Lucas company to create a special ``spokes-alien'' that will star
in its ``Phantom Menace'' commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Three restaurant chains once owned by Pepsi, KFC, Pizza Hut, and
Taco Bell, are also running promotions tied to the movie. Three
planets are featured in ``The Phantom Menace,'' and each restaurant
will be tricked out as one of planets.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time ever, the three chains will appear together
in a TV ad campaign, says Amy Sherwood, a spokeswoman for Tricon
Global Restaurants Inc., the parent of the three chains. On a TV
near you, expect to see Colonel Sanders and the Taco Bell chihuahua
frolicking to a ``Star Wars'' theme.
</P>
<P>
   According to Newsweek magazine, ``The Phantom Menace''
respresents a $2.5 billion marketing investment for Pepsi and
Tricon, but the two companies separately dispute that number.
</P>
<P>
   Could ``The Phantom Menace'' actually flop? After all, Hollywood
thought ``Godzilla'' would be a blockbuster, and Wal-Mart Stores
Inc. heavily promoted ``Prince of Egypt.'' Despite proven story
lines and big corporate tie-ins, neither movie lived up to advance
billings.
</P>
<P>
   According to editorial director Jill Bilzi of Playthings
magazine, the Internet helped croak ``Godzilla.'' When word quickly
spread among kids that the movie wasn't very good, ``Godzilla''
bombed at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, some observers have laid the blame for a would-be
blockbuster's failure to a marketing plan that simply overwhelmed
the movie's script.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Toy Story'' made a hash out of that theory. It created
roles for nearly every old toy in the play room _ Etch-a-Sketch,
Slinky, Mr. Potato Head. And still the movie was a surprise smash.
To this day, Mattel may regret that it nixed a star turn for Barbie
that was written into an early draft of the script.
</P>
<P>
   One of Lucas's key skills may be his knack for perfectly
balancing a movie script with a merchandising plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never a sense that the merchandising tail is wagging
the movie dog,'' licensing expert Brochstein says of Lucas. ``He's
a business man and he's a story teller.''
</P>
<P>
   A well-told story is no guarantee that a movie will also be a
merchandising hit, however. Consider the fate of the recently
animated version of ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame.'' Even Disney
couldn't make Quasimodo lovable enough for a mass audience.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other movies, ``Star Wars'' has a 22-year track
record of merchandising success behind it. That means ``The Phantom
Menace'' is ``as close to a sure thing as you can have'' in
Hollywood, Brochstein says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt it will be big,'' he says of the new movie
and the companies that look to cash in on it. ``The question is:
`Will it be big enough?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
