A3060 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-19 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN GET DAY IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Financial consultant Anne Kaspar had no idea that the lawsuit
she and seven other women filed against Merrill Lynch several years
go would help launch a nationwide backlash affecting the way bias
complaints now are resolved on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought there might be a few institutional changes, but we
never expected the lawsuit to have such an enormous impact,'' said
Kaspar.
</P>
<P>
   For years, stockbrokers, salespeople, and securities traders
have been required to take any dispute they had with their employer
to a hearing before industry arbitrators, rather than a jury of
their peers.
</P>
<P>
   But now, eight years after the US Supreme Court approved the use
of mandatory arbitration to settle employment discrimination
claims, some key players in the securities industry have backed
away from mandatory arbitration, while other firms are searching
for alternative ways to handle discrimination disputes.
</P>
<P>
   So far, The National Association of Securities Dealers has
dropped a mandatory arbitration clause from its U-4 form, the
application employees in the industry must use to register with the
Securities and Exchange Commission. And, starting this year, the
Boston Stock Exchange and the Chicago Stock Exchange exclude
certain discrimination claims from mandatory arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange announced this year that it would no
longer arbitrate employee discrimination disputes.But that's not
all.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Merrill Lynch ended its use of mandatory arbitration
to handle bias complaints, becoming the first company on Wall
Street to do so. The firm made its decision as part of a settlement
of the lawsuit filed by Kaspar. That complaint has since grown to
include some 900 women who came forward under a process established
by the settlement last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We changed our policy July 1 of last year,'' commented Bill
Holden, a spokesman for Merrill Lynch in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Jay W. Waks, who represents employers and chairs the
Employment Law Practice at Kaye, Scholer, Fierman, Hays &AMP; Handler
LLP in New York City, believes the shift away from arbitration by
the exchanges could pose serious problems for employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge jump, a huge shift, for both the New York Stock
Exchange and the National Association of Securities Dealers,'' he
said. ``To carve out an exception for employment discrimination
cases leaves a big problem for both employers and employees,'' he
said. ``Many employment discrimination claims are coupled with
traditional common law claims such as refusal to pay bonus or
intentional infliction of emotional distress or defamation. That
means some issues could end up going through arbitration and other
issues would be heard in court, creating more litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   For many employers mandatory arbitration has been a boon. Not
only does it limit lengthy and expensive court battles, but it also
reduces publicity that can seriously damage a company's reputation
and its business.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since the nation's highest court ruled in favor of
mandatory arbitration, thousands of companies have sought to have
sexual harassment and age, gender, and other discrimination claims
moved from the courts to private hearings for binding arbitration.
More than half a million Wall Street workers are still legally
bound by agreements mandating that they arbitrate disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Smith Barney found itself the subject of a suit in May 1996. The
92-page complaint alleged that at least one of the firm's offices
had created a ``boom-boom room'' where women were belittled by men.
The suit also said although established male brokers earned as much
as $200,000 per year, successful women brokers typically earned no
more than $100,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   After press reports about the Smith Barney and Merrill Lynch
lawsuits caught the public's eye, things began to change. The
National Organization for Women launched a national campaign in
which Smith Barney was targeted as a ``merchant of shame,'' major
television and news outlets interviewed women plaintiffs from both
lawsuits, and a handful of courts began outlawing the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Kaspar, the Lincoln, Mass. woman who joined Merrill Lynch in
August 1991, said both she and the firm had agreed that she would
be ``a million dollar producer within a certain amount of time and
that I would receive management support.''
</P>
<P>
   She claims she grew concerned when the firm gave her a
performance goal that was considerably higher than that of a male
colleague who had been hired around the same time. According to
Kaspar, she was expected to have more than $20 million under
management the first year and $250,000 in commissions. He was
expected to manage a $10 million portfolio and make $90,000 in
commissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a situation where you were penalized if you did not
meet these goals and objectives,'' said Kaspar. ``Being penalized
means management will not pay for seminars you need to attend, and
they will dock your pay by 25 percent. Once that happens, you
cannot recover without devine intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaspar complained. ``I went in and said, ``I can't take this
anymore,' '' she recalled. ``My manager turned his back to me and
said, `I can let you die here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Holden, speaking on behalf of the company, said Kaspar was
treated fairly. Clearly, Kaspar, now an independent financial
adviser, disagreed. In October 1995, she sued.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Questions, comments, story ideas? Contact Diane E. Lewis at
work(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
