<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG TIME COMING FOR ALPHA INDUSTRIES' STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The good news about Alpha Industries Inc. is that the Woburn
company's stock has broken into new high territory in the last two
months.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing news: The old Alpha stock high was recorded 19 years
ago, long before combustible company cofounder George Kariotis
would stage his ill-fated gubernatorial campaign against Michael
Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   Like a cryogenically sealed space traveler, Alpha stock has
continued to sail on for years at near-comatose levels. It didn't
really snap back or quite die out either. Think ``Lost in Space,''
without Dr. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the sudden and remarkable comeback: It might be
in your cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   After years of searching for a way to move from its defense
subcontracting past into more commercial markets, Alpha and its
business of supplying high-tech parts for cellular telephones has
driven revenues and the company's stock price. The company's
defense work now accounts for 10 percent of business and continues
to fade.
</P>
<P>
   Alpha shares have soared from 18 3/4 on April 5 to 42 7/8
Tuesday, a climb that made it possible for the company to schedule
a pending sale of 3 million new shares. (Chief executive Thomas
Leonard and other company officials, citing the stock offering,
declined to be interviewed.)
</P>
<P>
   But has Alpha stock gotten ahead of itself? Needham &AMP; Co.
analyst Ryl Ashley initiated coverage of Alpha on May 3 with a buy
recommendation and a 12-month price target of $43 per share. That
target anticipated 26 percent appreciation on a stock that had
already moved sharply higher, but it is just 12.5 cents short of
Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
   The Alpha components that have caught the attention of stock
analysts are semiconductors made of gallium arsenide, a combination
of gallium and arsenic molded into a wafer that is lighter and
nearly as strong as silicon.
</P>
<P>
   Alpha began working with gallium arsenide years ago in
connection with military contracts for communication and radar
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Today, digital cell phones are crammed with gallium arsenide
technology. Alpha uses the material to make switches inside the
phones, but more importantly it also manufactures power amplifiers
that improve transmission signals and extend battery life.
</P>
<P>
   Alpha's power amplifiers work inside Motorola's tiny StarTAK
models and its new ultra-small digital V-phones on sale now in
Europe and Asia and soon to hit the US markets.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's decision to boost production orders for StarTAK cell
phone chips in early April was the fuel that started the Alpha
stock rocket.
</P>
<P>
   But Motorola could be too much of a good thing over time. It is
by far Alpha's largest customer, accounting for 28.1 percent of all
revenues. Ericsson, the company's second-biggest account,
represents 8.2 percent of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Even Alpha fans like Ashley see the dangers of so much business
concentrated in a single account and what might happen if the
customer decided to go somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motorola is certainly the biggest part of their comeback story
and Wall Street will be very happy when they have another,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless communications accounts for only about half of Alpha's
business at the moment, but it's growing fast and accounts for the
lion's share of its stock valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless revenues are expected to double to $130 million in the
next two years. Its other two technical divisions are forecast by
some analysts to grow by about $5 million to $67 million over the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley justified her original stock growth forecast with a
valuation plan that assigned a relatively pokey 10 times earnings
ratio to Alpha's slower-growing business and a 45 times earnings
multiple to its wireless communication work.
</P>
<P>
   Alpha shareholders have already been rewarded for promise and
the company will surely gain too once it sells new stock at today's
lofty levels. Then it will have to deliver on the potential.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thud! Nextera Enterprises Inc. of Lexington, Mass., the
management consulting firm backed by the Michael Milken/Larry
Ellison venture Knowledge Universe, went public Tuesday and traded
down. Nextera shares fell 1 1/16 to 8 15/16 on its first day of
trading. The company raised $115 million in its initial public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
