<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ANTI-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S LOVE-HATE FOR US ENDURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ When President Clinton charmed his way through China
last year, praising the Chinese and pledging growing friendship,
the joke here was that he had unseated basketball star Michael
Jordan as China's favorite American.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after NATO's errant bombing of the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade, Clinton suddenly became Enemy Number One. The
state-controlled media and ordinary people alike denounced him as a
murderer and condemned the United States as a ``hegemonist'' power
intent on dominating China.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after four days, furious anti-American protests involving as
many as 400,000 people in 20 cities subsided. That is mostly
because authorities who first encouraged the rock-throwing
demonstrations decided to halt them. But it is also true that the
worst public vitriol seems to have drained away. Here in the
capital, calls to boycott American goods have gone largely unheeded
and Americans are walking the streets unbothered. Greatly
diminished are the angry taunts of a week ago, when numerous
Americans were chastised by strangers.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time the pendulum of Chinese public opinion
has swung radically against the United States, nor is it likely to
be the last. But while it will take time and considerable effort to
rebuild the damaged relationship between the governments in Beijing
and Washington, ordinary Chinese people's sentiments toward America
may be quicker to heal.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is both admired and resented here, reflecting
a love-hate relationship between the Chinese public and all things
American. To be sure, Chinese people are genuinely furious about
the bombing; almost anyone from laborers to professors believes the
attack was an intentional plot to bully their nation, and the
government has fed that belief by delaying news of Clinton's
apology. But while suspicion of all foreign powers runs deep in
China, true hatred of Americans is rare.
</P>
<P>
   There are many practical reasons for that. American investment
creates jobs and brings technology to China. The United States is
China's second-largest trading partner, and tourism by Americans
feeds millions of dollars into the economy.
</P>
<P>
   At a MacDonald's restaurant, filled Tuesday with its usual
lunchtime Chinese crowd, cashier Qin Lin reasoned that ``American
companies did nothing wrong. This has nothing to do with American
business or American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond economics, there are more subtle reasons for the
conflicted views of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feelings of nationalism and cosmopolitanism are very
complicated in China. A lot of China's problems in the last 150
years since the Opium War have come from weakness to the outside
world,'' said Shi Jinghuan, a professor of education at Beijing
Normal University. ``People want to learn high technology from
Western countries, but they feel unhappy when the country we most
want to learn from doesn't treat us the way we want to be
treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Much in the way that India feels disrespected and denied its
rightful place in world affairs _ prompting it to test nuclear
devices to prove its muscle last year, China has long felt put down
by foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese schoolchildren are taught that after 5,000 years of
proud history, a weak China was humiliated and colonized in the
19th and 20th centuries. Communist China, founded in 1949, was then
isolated and marginalized for decades, largely by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of pride mixed with inferiority runs deep; Chinese are
taught that their ancestors invented paper, printing, gunpowder,
and the compass, but that foreigners applied those inventions in
modern, useful ways. Belief in the superiority of Chinese
civilization, coupled with the shame of being subjugated by outside
``barbarians,'' has fed xenophobia and nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Technology and modern ideas are seen as the ticket to catching
up with the West. But adopting select concepts while retaining
``Chinese characteristics'' is not always easy, leaving many here
with feelings of envy and resentment.
</P>
<P>
   American products are best-sellers here; they are considered the
height of modernity, but evoke frustration that Chinese technology
and design has not matched America's. American television, movies,
and music are hugely popular and widely imitated, but are also
resented for sidelining traditional culture. American liberties are
admired and envied, but also suspected of feeding crime, divorce,
and a host of social ills more prevalent in the West than in a
nation that has been regimented and isolated for most of its
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really hate Americans. It's like love _ you can't
explain why,'' said a 29-year-old man who works for a US company.
``I felt embarrassed to shout `Down with America' this week. Ever
since the Open Door policy, America has become the symbol of
freedom, high technology, the good life, modernity, excitement. . .
. Some people spend many years waiting for a visa to go to the US.
So when we say we hate America, it's not really deep-seated.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, hatred of Japan, which colonized China and perpetrated
wartime atrocities, comes far more naturally to many Chinese than
anti-Americanism.
</P>
<P>
   In one protest in front of the US Embassy last week, a tired
student leader accidentally shouted, ``Down with the Japanese'' _
and her classmates automatically echoed the call. When she tried to
correct herself, one shouted, ``That's OK. The Japanese are worse.
Down with the Japanese!''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders have long stoked suspicion of foreign nations,
and the NATO bombing offered a perfect example of a supposed plot
against China. Meanwhile, allegations of Chinese misdeeds, such as
the theft of American military secrets, are not reported in the
press, promoting a one-sided view.
</P>
<P>
   In one of countless similar commentaries, the People's Daily
said Friday that Western powers led by the United States are using
``political, economic, military and diplomatic means to obstruct
and destroy China's development.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a powerful message, but as contact with foreigners and
access to the outside world expands, not everyone is buying it.
</P>
<P>
   Deng Zaoheng, 55, a housewife, said the bombing, though
horrible, hasn't turned her against the United States. ``We still
hope relations between China and the US will continue developing,''
she said. ``We need each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3070 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-2ND &LR;      05-19 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (a and s coding)  
 BOSTON: ... Boston stadium.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On March 15, another key development occurred, not in New
England, but in Phoenix, where NFL owners voted to change league
policy to foster internal funding of stadium projects. Finneran
felt vindicated. And the door to bringing the Patriots back home
opened a little wider.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a key turning point,'' Finneran said
recently.``It meant the league might be willing to participate. And
it was a tacit acceptance of what the House had argued all along:
that those who stood to benefit from a new stadium, like the NFL
owners, also had to participate in funding it.''
</P>
<P>
   A month later, the Boston group -- now consisting of Kirk,
Monan, Boston Edison chairman Thomas J. May, Budd, and Connell --
began crafting an opinion piece to be published in the Globe. The
draft, articulating broad backing for keeping the team, was
circulated on Beacon Hill in advance so leaders would not be
stunned when they opened their papers April 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest is history,'' Kirk said. ``This thing just
unfolded.''
</P>
<P>
   The article triggered strong statements of support, most
importantly from Beacon Hill, and unexpectedly positive statements
from the mayor saying he was open-minded. Privately, though, it
soon became clear Menino still did not want a stadium in Boston, so
the group began focusing on Foxborough, the Patriots' base since
1971.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Birmingham, the Senate president and a former labor
negotiator, called Kirk at home, urging a face-to-face summit on
Beacon Hill the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I figured we might be able to get this done was
to all sit down in the same room and hammer it out,'' Birmingham
said. ``So that's what we proposed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It all came together, quite literally in the 11th hour _ on
Tuesday, April 27, at 11:35 p.m., to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   The state's power troika emerged from a three-hour meeting with
a plan that could upend everything the team planned and Hartford's
dream of becoming an NFL city.
</P>
<P>
   The seed planted by Kirk and Rooney nearly five months earlier
had sprouted in this cluster of leadership gathered in Birmingham's
cavernous office, paneled with Honduran Mahogany and draped in
patinated yellow and green fabric.
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the 12-foot antique table sat the House speaker,
Finneran. Birmingham sat at the other. Seated on blue-leather
chairs between them were Kirk, Governor Cellucci, Lieutenant
Governor Jane Swift, aides to all three political leaders,
stadium-expert Goodell, and another NFL executive, Neil Glat.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second night in a row the group had met in
Birmingham's office. The first evening, there was a lot of
posturing. By the second night, it was clear everyone was working
toward a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Except there was a sticking point: Finneran's demand that the
Patriots pay up to $2 million a year to cover some of the state's
costs for road, sewer, and other public infrastructure work
required at a new Foxboro Stadium. NFL officials balked, noting
that should be the state's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   A tense standoff ensued, and for a few minutes it looked like
the deal could die.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by the impasse, Cellucci, a strong supporter of a new
stadium for the Patriots, sided with Finneran. Still, NFL officials
insisted they couldn't agree to the payback language. To keep the
momentum of the talks going, Birmingham asked Kirk and the NFL men
to wait in another room while the three political leaders discussed
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   After about 30 minutes, they were invited back in, presented
with the the final plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a general feeling that this was it,'' Birmingham
said later. ``The deal was as good as it was going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Under the offer, drafted into the legislation that passed
Tuesday, Kraft would build the stadium, partially assisted by
low-rate NFL financing. The state would provide $70 million in
infrastructure improvements around Route 1. Further, Kraft would
grant an easement on his land, allowing the state to upgrade access
ramps and sewer lines on his private property.
</P>
<P>
   Several people involved in the negotiations claim credit for the
easement plan. But whoever promoted the idea, it broke the
stalemate by eliminating the land purchase component of the
Senate's last plan, which Finneran opposed, while preserving
infrastructure spending that the team deemed necessary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Massachusetts moved closer to a counteroffer, Connecticut
fell behind.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, on Thursday, April 29, a team of Patriots
consultants delivered a prognosis that put the Hartford deal in
critical condition: the stadium, they concluded, most likely could
not be ready by 2002, as promised, because it would take longer to
clear the site of the steam plant and scrub it of environmental
contamination. Under the stadium contract, that was enough for the
team to walk away without penalty, as long as it made the decision
by the upcoming Sunday, May 2.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft faced a choice: wait at least another year for the
Hartford stadium or take his chances in Massachusetts, where a plan
was now on the table but had not received full legislative
approval.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Kraft, his son Jonathan, and team executive Andy
Wasynczuk flew to Hartford to see if a third option was possible:
Would Connecticut extended the penalty-free deadline another month,
by which time a more definitive review of the site could be
completed?
</P>
<P>
   Rowland refused. Mostly, the governor couldn't believe the team
would really turn their backs on a free stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a game of high stakes poker'' said one person who was
in the room.``And I think the governor was calling the team's
bluff.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, furious and desperate, gave Kraft just 24 hours to
decide _ even though Kraft legally had several days to make up his
mind. The meeting ended. They all left the governor's office to
face a throng of reporters camped outside and issued sober, but
vague, statements about being committed to their ``goal'' of the
Patriots playing in Hartford by 2002. They shook hands as cameras
clicked and went their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a final parting.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants for both sides stayed up well into Friday morning,
trying to salvage the agreement, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the Krafts got a final consultants' report.
</P>
<P>
   With a void of good news, Robert Kraft retreated to his office
on the 34th floor of a Boston skyscraper to fax the formal
termination notice to Connecticut. He called Rowland as it was
being transmitted.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kraft and Wasynczuk left the room. It was a painful and
emotional conversation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, in Los Angeles promoting Massachusetts film
production, was chatting with renowned chef Wolfgang Puck, about to
make a cheese, tomato, and pepper pizza, when news of the stunning
about-face broke.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, Cellucci would be on the set of ``The Tonight
Show.'' Jay Leno, originally from the Boston area, gave a nod to
the governor during his opening monologue, asking him what was
happening with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The camera, beaming the program to some 6 million viewers, spun
around toward the audience where Cellucci sat smiling with his
thumb in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're staying,'' the governor shouted, ``in Massachusetts!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
