<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PATRIOTS DEAL, ALL ROADS LED BACK TO FOXBOROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY AND MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It took just one day to debate and approve a bill that
will keep the New England Patriots in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's vote may never have happened if a couple of old
friends had not bumped into each other in a Washington hotel
ballroom last December _ an encounter that sparked a nearly
six-month campaign to keep the team from moving to Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner honoring Nobel Peace Prize winners David Trimble and
John Hume, Boston attorney Paul G. Kirk Jr., former chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, spotted his pal, Pittsburgh Steelers
president Daniel Rooney, an outspoken critic of National Football
League franchises leaving their home markets for smaller ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over and gave him a little tease about the NFL
referees'' making bad calls, said Kirk, one of more than two dozen
people interviewed for this story. ``He said, `Well, what are you
going to do about getting the Patriots to go back to
Massachusetts?' We talked about it a little bit, the dismay...''
</P>
<P>
   ``It did go from there,'' Rooney said, referring to the mostly
secret efforts that resulted in Tuesday's legislation being
forwarded to Governor Paul Cellucci for his signature. ``I will
admit that.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, at a meeting of a small group of NFL owners
in Chicago, Rooney listened as team owner Robert Kraft chronicled
the Patriots three-year quest for a new stadium. Blocked from
building in Boston itself, the team flirted with Providence while
Massachusetts legislators argued into a dead end over a proposal
Kraft and Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham had put together.
Then, Connecticut came acourting.
</P>
<P>
   Rooney was stupefied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know business guys in Boston,'' Rooney reportedly said, his
mind reverting back to his talk with Kirk. ``And I know they don't
want this to happen.... I really can't imagine they will let this
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Hartford looked like a done deal on Nov. 19, when Kraft
stood in the ornate Judiciary Room of Connecticut's Capitol,
signing a ``memorandum of understanding'' with Governor John G.
Rowland. The document was a plan to move the team from the one of
the oldest stadiums in the nation to a new one in downtown
Hartford, centerpiece of a $1 billion rejuvenation project for the
ailing insurance city.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, there with his son, Jonathan, had tears in his eyes.
Although he felt welcomed by the cheering crowd and pleased with
what would be the richest deal ever offered an NFL team, sadness
and disappointment at leaving his home state were also evident on
his face.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Dec. 15 _ days after the Kirk-Rooney encounter _ the
Connecticut General Assembly passed legislation authorizing $374
million for a stadium, public infrastructure, and maintenance of
the facility, where the state university's football squad would
also play.
</P>
<P>
   But Rooney and Kirk, longtime friends through Irish charity
circles, were already working the phones. The Steelers president
started with NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue, along with Roger
Goodell, the league's stadium expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I talked to Father Monan next,'' Rooney said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. J. Donald Monan, the chancellor of Boston College who
helped broker the FleetCenter deal, was a significant force among
the widening group of mostly Irish Catholic executives trying to
spread the faith that the Patriots could be saved for the Bay
State. He gave Rooney some names of people to call, including
advertising executive John J. Connors Jr. and industrialist William
F. Connell, both of whom would become part of the inner core of
civic leaders _ known as ``Operation Team Back'' _ rallying the
business community to purchase luxury seating if and when a new
stadium got built.
</P>
<P>
   Equally significant, Monan bestowed inspiration for what seemed
like an impossible feat at that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father Monan was very important, giving me encouragement that
it could be done. I have a lot of respect for him,'' added Rooney,
whose son attended Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk, soft-spoken, persuasive, and once considered for the NFL
commissioner's job _ which ultimately went to his friend Tagliabue
_ had also sprung into action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Paul Tagliabue. I remember saying, `You know, I'm
glad to be helpful, but no one wants to embark on a fool's errand.'
''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner assured Kirk that developing a Massachusetts
alternative would be worthwhile. And by Jan. 6, Goodell was in
Boston, where Kirk introduced him to the civic group in his
Sullivan &AMP; Worcester law office.
</P>
<P>
   Goodell, with a background in economics and business, was
responsible for getting stadiums built from Seattle to Tampa.
However, this deal would not be as easy as the rest.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Kraft's accord with Rowland prohibited the owner
from talking with another state. That meant Operation Team Back
would have to pull together a proposal without consulting the team,
something they insist they did to prevent exposing Kraft to a
lawsuit by Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Second, there was the seemingly intractable position of House
Speaker Thomas M. Finneran. The Mattapan Democrat refused to
compromise on Senate legislation last year offering as much as $20
million for land and $52 million for infrastructure improvements
around Foxboro Stadium, ultimately halting legislative action and
pushing a tired and frustrated Kraft into Connecticut's hungry
grasp.
</P>
<P>
   But as the son of Charles E. Goodell, the US Senator from New
York who replaced the assassinated Robert F. Kennedy, Roger Goodell
understood politics. And he knew navigating them would be key to an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   So at their first meeting, Goodell quoted local favorite Tip
O'Neill as saying: ``There's always a solution if you give other
people credit for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But many factors contributed to the turn of events, including
missteps and overconfidence on Connecticut's part and the NFL's
growing concern about franchises being lured to smaller cities with
stadium bait. Within a month of that state's approval for an
open-air facility, there were signs -- some public and some private
-- of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   At their January Super Bowl press conferences, Tagliabue and
Gene Upshaw, head of the NFL Players Association, made it clear
they weren't thrilled about the Patriots' proposed move. Hartford's
smaller television market would mean less broadcast revenue shared
among the teams.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Kraft was starting to hear that clearing the
Hartford site of a steam plant would be more complicated than
Rowland had let on.
</P>
<P>
   So he paid a visit to the freshly reelected governor.
</P>
<P>
   Behind closed doors at Rowland's gubernatorial mansion in
January, Kraft made it clear he was worried about meeting a 2002
season opening after already extending the original 2001 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   As a fire crackled in the background, Rowland looked Kraft in
the eye and said he was putting his best people on the project. He
said the state would meet the goal. Indeed, the young Republican
governor was so confident, he gave the team an easy escape: If, by
May 2, the team did not feel the stadium could be completed on time
and within budget, the Patriots could walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is a charming, big-picture guy who thinks the people
around him are competent enough to handle the details,'' one
Connecticut lobbyist said of Rowland. ``I don't think he was well
served and hasn't been for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some outside Rowland's inner core have been calling the
Connecticut site crew the ``Junior Varsity Squad,'' a well-meaning
group ill-equipped to handle a project of such complication and
magnitude. It took them months to figure out a way to clear the
steam plant -- responsible for heating and cooling most of downtown
Hartford -- and environmental tests had still not been completed.
</P>
<P>
   All of that made outsiders smell weakness with the deal even as
Rowland and Kraft remained publicly committed to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Boston group began quietly visiting key
officials, including Finneran and Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino,
who had vehemently opposed Kraft's previous plan for a South Boston
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
