<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-EXCHANGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS MAY SOON TRADE SLEEP FOR STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Coffee in hand, Mike Branham sits at the computer
at 5 each morning to scan the Motley Fool, Raging Bull, and other
Internet financial news sites. The CNBC stock ticker scrolls across
his television all day. At 1 a.m., he might wae up to check the
market news from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his round-the-clock attention to stocks, Branham and
other small investors can actually trade shares only 6 1/2 hours a
day, when the US exchanges are open. But with so many people now
playing the stock market, the two main exchanges, the New York
Stock Exchange and Nasdaq, are facing the reality that the
traditional trading day is just too short.
</P>
<P>
   Now, both exchanges, in the first of what could be profound
changes in the way stocks are bought and sold, are planning to add
extra sessions so that people can trade stocks before and after
work.
</P>
<P>
   And that is only one step in a coming revolution. Driven by a
huge boom in stock trading over the Internet, a handful of private
companies say they will offer nighttime and even 24-hour stock
trading on what are essentially private stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   For years, mutual fund managers, pension fund managers, and
other big-money players have been able to trade before the opening
bell at 9:30 a.m. and after the close at 4 p.m. As the
democratization of the market continues, the new private exchanges
promise to give the same power to the small investor.
</P>
<P>
   Late-night stock trading might seem like welcome news for
Branham and the millions of other Americans who have made the stock
market an important part of their lives. But many people are not
sure it is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would wreak havoc on my life,'' says Branham, a Houston
events planner and confessed ``equities addict,'' who is scaling
back after making 800 trades last year. The stock market ``just
about drove me nuts'' as it is. ``Nighttime trading,'' he said,
``would be overload.''
</P>
<P>
   Even less-active investors fear they will lose sleep if they
have to worry about their portfolios tanking in late-night trading.
``Right now, when the market closes you have time to eat dinner and
spend some time with your family,'' said Dennis Fortier, a former
Maine resident and product manager who now lives in San Clemente,
Calif. ``If it's a 24-hour thing, I'm not sure people will know how
to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, much of the financial services industry says
late-hours trading will be a big hit. Their evidence: The bull
market has pushed the volume of stocks changing hands each day to
record highs. And, more important, a huge number of those trades
are being placed by on-line investors using ETrade, Ameritrade,
Suretrade, and more than 100 other Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   These investors place their orders by computer to an automated
service center, rather than over the phone to a live broker.
On-line brokerages did not even exist in 1994. Today, an estimated
14 percent of all trades, or one in seven, start with an investor
hitting a few keys on a personal computer. Brokerages are opening
15,000 on-line accounts each day.
</P>
<P>
   Just as ATMs allowed banks to save money on tellers, on-line
brokerages can operate so cheaply that it is cost-effective for
them to stay open at night. Last month, Instinet, a 30-year-old
service that allows mutual fund managers and other big investors to
make after-hours trades, announced that it would open its doors to
small investors this year.
</P>
<P>
   Island, a private exchange that has become one of the largest
forums for trading Intel, Dell, and Amazon.com, already operates
from 8 a.m. to 5:15 p.m. and has boasted that it will stay open all
night by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The push for late-night trading is also driven by recent rules
changes from the Securities and Exchange Commission and by the
growth of financial news reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, when you came home at night and wanted to look
at your investments, you read the paper or looked at your
statements when they came in the mail,'' says Douglas Atkin, chief
executive of Instinet. ``And you really couldn't act on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Internet is full of financial news sites, giving
people the kind of analysis and statistical information that was
once restricted to brokers. CNBC broadcasts financial news all day
on television _ including earnings news and other reports that
companies tend to announce after the markets close.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 40 percent of all on-line orders come in after market
hours. Tremendous numbers of people are shopping, but the store is
closed,'' said Michael Satow, a former government securities lawyer
who cofounded IndivEx, an after-hours trading service that plans to
debut this summer. Its slogan: ``The market's still open.''
</P>
<P>
   Instinet, Island, and at least seven other private exchanges
already trade shares during the day, accounting for nearly
one-third of the trading in certain high-tech companies. Each
operates by its own rules, but they are fundamentally different
than the major exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   All trades on Nasdaq and some on the NYSE involve middlemen. On
Nasdaq especially, investors, through their brokerage firms, buy
stock from the middleman, who keeps a large inventory of a certain
stock or set of stocks on hand. When investors sell stock, the
middleman is the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The middleman, known on Nasdaq as a market maker, turns a profit
by selling shares for a little more money than the buying price.
For example, an investor might have to pay $78.50 to buy a share of
Microsoft Corp. at a given moment, but he or she could sell it back
at only $78.44.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the buying and selling price, called the
spread, can be as high as 5 percent or even more for some stocks.
That means someone who buys the stock must wait for it to rise 5
percent just to break even.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new exchanges say they will cut the middleman and
match buyers and sellers directly. This will lower the spread, they
say, and cut the cost of each trade.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody who wants to sell shares of Microsoft Corp. at $80, for
example, can post the offer on one of the new exchange services. If
someone else has already offered to buy at that price, the service
closes the sale. Or, if the only buyer on hand is willing to pay
only $78, the buyer and seller could be matched up to negotiate a
price.
</P>
<P>
   The reality may turn out to be something less. Some analysts say
that many buyers who look for a seller late at night will find
nobody around _ especially if he or she wants to buy one of the
less-popular stocks. Even now, the new exchanges cannot find a
buyer for every daytime sell order they receive, forcing them to
send those orders into the regular Nasdaq system to be filled by a
market maker.
</P>
<P>
   That is why some of the new services, at least to start, will
close shop at 9 p.m. or so and are limiting themselves to the most
popular stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the new services have the major exchanges worried. NYSE
officials have said they are in talks to buy one of the new
networks, or may build their own.
</P>
<P>
   The officials have also said that by mid-2000 or sooner, the
NYSE will add an early morning and evening session. Nasdaq might
add a four-hour evening session.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the new exchanges could present a formidable challenge
to Nasdaq, says Bill Burnham, who follows the brokerage industry
for Credit Suisse First Boston. In a recent report, he predicted
that the new services would soon dominate the trading of
high-volume, popular stocks, leaving the Nasdaq market makers to
specialize only in more marginal shares.
</P>
<P>
   For the NYSE, the boom in electronic investing might also
highlight the costs of its crowded trading floor. Exchange
officials say their system still gives investors the best price for
shares.
</P>
<P>
   But the 96-year-old trading floor is becoming one of the last of
its breed. The major European exchanges are all electronic. Sydney
Futures Exchange estimates that it will cut costs by 40 percent by
switching to electronic trading. Just last month, the Tokyo Stock
Exchange closed its trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York Stock Exchange is a dinosaur,'' said Richard
Roll, a finance professor at the University of California at Los
Angeles. ``These electronic systems are much more efficient.
There's no reason for people to be physically located on the floor
of an exchange. It's a waste of resources.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, investors seem to have mixed feelings about
the coming world of round-the-clock stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jarrett, a Providence, R.I. high school teacher, said he
would probably use an after-hours service because his job keeps him
from checking the markets during the day. Still, he added in an
e-mail exchange, ``I just think for everyone's sanity, the market
needs to have an opening and a closing every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
