<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ The split in the alliance grows as
Gerhard Schroeder, the German chancellor, forcefully notes that
Germany, opposed to ground troops, can veto their use. He also
slaps the U.S. by calling for an investigation of the bombing of
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, saying the defective map
explanation was insufficient. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Brussels) _ A news analysis on why the alliance
is fraying and whether the lack of a strong U.S. position on how to
conduct the war in Kosovo is a factor. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Berlin) _ As the G-8 meets on Kosovo, no
breakthrough is in sight. The new buzzword is ``synchronization'':
an effort to synchronize the withdrawal of troops with an end of
the bombing and a U.N. Security Council resolution to authorize
some kind of force. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje) _ At least two Albanians are killed in
an explosion in an Albanian market. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Belgrade) _ Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian
envoy, arrives in Belgrade, but without the Finnish president, for
talks with Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Belgrade) _ Developments: A few antiwar rallies
are held and some people are reported arrested; plus an attack on
an opposition party headquarters. By Carlotta Gall.
