   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:45 p.m., stocks were little changed.
The Dow Jones industrial average was up 4 points, the S&AMP;P 500 up 2
points, the Nasdaq composite down 5 points. European stocks were
higher, with London up 0.8 percent and Frankfurt up 1 percent. In
Asia, the Nikkei fell 1.53 percent, and the Hang Seng fell 1.77
percent. On the credit markets at midday, the 30-year bond yield
had slipped to 5.85 percent. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-HAULER-STRIKE (Detroit) _ The Teamsters Union has authorized
a strike against 17 car haulers. A strike would hurt the ability of
auto makers to ship cars at a time of strong demand. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-BUSINESS (Shanghai) _ When anti-American
demonstrations erupted in several Chinese cities 10 days ago,
executives at several American companies went into crisis mode and
evacuated their employees. While it may be too early to tell
exactly how the business environment will be affected, the
politically radical language that has dominated China's official
media signals a slowing of some reforms and greater uncertainty. By
Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ECON (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ Latin America's improving
economic outlook, fueled in large part by the recovery of Brazil,
the region's largest economy, is unlikely to be affected greatly by
the possible increase in U.S. interest rates that the Federal
Reserve hinted at Tuesday. If anything, rates in Brazil are likely
to keep falling. By Simon Romero.
</P>
