<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSITY-EXPANSION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE UNIVERSITY OF NEW YORK CAMPUS IN ALBANY SEES BIG GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CLAIRE HUGHES  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST GREENBUSH, N.Y. _ The State University of New York at
Albany's east campus here was an abandoned site just four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's undergoing explosive growth.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago a major expansion was announced by Albany
Molecular Research. On Wednesday the state Department of
Environmental Conservation (DEC) announced the relocation of six
laboratories to the site, adding 30 to 50 jobs to the 350 there at
18 organizations, university officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Taconic Biotechnology, a company on the campus for two years, is
also planning to grow by more than 50 percent _ to about 45
employees _ in a 17,500-square-foot space, said managing director
Todd Little. Taconic expects to be in the new facility within six
months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the university plans to establish within the next
month a center for gene studies on the east campus. The center will
collaborate on a project with Taconic and Albany Medical College to
manipulate genes in mice and study the genes' potential effect on
human health, said Albert Millis, a university biology professor
and co-director of the planned Center for Comparative Functional
Genomics.
</P>
<P>
   It will cost about $2.8 million to establish the center, Millis
said, and another $300,000 to $500,000 for the joint venture,
called a transgenic animal facility. The three partners will share
in the cost.
</P>
<P>
   The university has operated the campus in East Greenbush for the
last three years, when it purchased the 58-acre site with the help
of a $5 million state grant.
</P>
<P>
   The goal has been to develop the campus as a center that would
encourage collaborations between the school and businesses,
especially in biotechnology and pharmacy. The university's School
of Public Health, with about 300 students, is also located at the
site.
</P>
<P>
   The new DEC labs won't provide a net gain of jobs in the Albany
region but will consolidate facilities scattered throughout the
area.
</P>
<P>
   DEC scientists will support the agency's air, water and solid
and hazardous waste divisions and work on research initiatives with
staff from UAlbany's Atmospheric Sciences Research Center. DEC and
university scientists have worked together previously.
</P>
<P>
   Taconic's expansion is driven by growth in its technology
service division, Little said. The company is a subsidiary of
Taconic Farms of Germantown. N.Y. Taconic Biotech provides support
for Taconic Farms, which breeds laboratory rats and mice.
</P>
<P>
   The East Greenbush division's expansion would also support work
expected from the transgenic animal facility, Little said. The
joint venture expects to attract both contract work and research
dollars, Millis said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Albany Molecular announced it would build an $11
million, 25,000-square-foot manufacturing facility to produce small
batches of pharmaceuticals at the east campus. The expansion is
expected to bring 150 jobs to East Greenbush over three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
