<P>
   Eds: Adds KOSOVO-STRIKES, JOURNAL-KOSOVO, SAFRICA-CELLPHONES,
LYBRAND, BAXTER-COLUMN.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ Diplomatic efforts kicked into
even higher gear on Wednesday, signaling that all parties to the
Kosovo crisis were looking to some way to end the 2-month-old
bombing campaign without involving NATO ground troops. Developing.
(Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   w/ JOURNAL-KOSOVO _ KUKES, Albania _ In fiction, Casablanca had
Rick's American Cafe. In fact, Beirut had the Commodore Hotel bar.
Every war has its meeting place for spies, mercenaries, diplomats,
correspondents and drunks. Kukes has the Bar Amerika, a place so
bizarre you may think it's fiction, but indeed it is fact. In one
corner, a geurrilla fighter from the Bronx is about to join the KLA
at the front. In another, aid workers discuss their latest strategy
for delivering food aid, while the local mobsters at another table
openly brag about how much of it they've stolen. (Holmes, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moving in both International and Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-CELLPHONES _ JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Naomi Shaku
lives in the Ebony Park neighborhood on the east side of
Johannesburg, a development of tiny government-built houses whose
single rooms are smaller than a rich man's bathroom. These homes
were built to house people who previously lived in squatter camps.
These are the poor, people who have precious little in life. Shaku,
24, may not have much. But she does have a cell phone. And so, it
seems, does almost everyone else in South Africa. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-STATION _ WASHINGTON _ As the House debates a bill to fund
NASA on Wednesday, Rep. Mark Sanford, R-S.C., plans to offer an
amendment to cut funding for the proposed international space
station. (Schultz, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KIDNEY-FOR-COP _ ATLANTA _ When DeKalb County Assistant Police
Chief Melvin Ferguson was told he needed a kidney from a type O
positive donor, he remembered a bloody crime scene. The wounded
killer's blood type was O positive. By then, Larry Grant Lonchar
was on death row. He agreed to Ferguson's request for a kidney,
setting up an international debate over whether death row inmates
could allow their organs to be harvested and choose to die on an
operating room table rather than by lethal injection or
electrocution. Lonchar lost the debate and was executed. But one
day later, Ferguson received a kidney transplant from a woman whose
life he had saved when he was a young police officer. Ferguson died
Monday. But his donated kidney, said donor Gina Pittman, ``kept
right on working until his last breath.'' (McDonald, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ With the state GOP convention coming
up this weekend in Augusta, we reflect on last week's death of
Marguerite Williams, at 80-something. It was people like her who
wrote the checks years ago that kept the then-fledgling state
Republican party going, planting the seed money for today's
two-party system in Georgia. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
