<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-COMMENTARY-052     05-19 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-COMMENTARY-0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BARAK REVIVES RABIN'S LEGACY WITH ELECTION VICTORY, COMMENTS
 &HT;    With Photo Mug.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By DEBBIE LERMAN 
 &HT;    c.1999 Special to the Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ When the results of the 1996 Israeli elections came
in, just six months after Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin's
assassination, I cried.
</P>
<P>
   Two days ago, as I watched thousands of Israelis celebrating the
results of the 1999 elections in Yitzhak Rabin Square, I cried
again.
</P>
<P>
   It was in that downtown Tel Aviv plaza -- then called King's of
Israel Square -- that Rabin was murdered at a peace rally I
attended.
</P>
<P>
   Months later I was shedding tears of disbelief that over 50
percent of my fellow Israelis voted for Benjamin Netanyahu -- a
leader of the vicious campaign against Rabin and the Oslo Peace
accords.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Israelis, the 1996 elections hit me like a second
assassination: First we lost a beloved leader, then we lost the
chance to continue in his path -- the path of peace and true
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the ensuing three years of Netanyahu's government, Rabin
became a powerful symbol for me and many other Israelis. He
symbolized everything we wanted our country to be but felt it was
losing. During Netanyahu's term, the peace process was effectively
halted, the religious nationalists gained power, and the country
seemed to be moving more toward a theocracy than a liberal
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the slick, media-savvy Netanyahu, Rabin seemed more
and more like a dinosaur: coarse, short-tempered and heavy-tongued,
but a man of integrity and total devotion to his country. Netanyahu
seemed determined to make Rabin's era recede rapidly into ancient
history.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for Netanyahu, Rabin was anathema.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who continued to mourn Rabin took it as a personal
affront every time Netanyahu purposely failed to mention him: in
his victory speech just months after Rabin's murder; when he signed
the Hebron peace agreement in 1997; and then the Wye River
Memorandum last fall. Netanyahu's deliberate detachment from
anything Rabin-related made me and many Israelis feel completely
alienated from him as a person and a leader.
</P>
<P>
   For us, Ehud Barak's victory over Netanyahu in the prime
minister's race signifies a return to Rabin's way. Barak himself
emphasized his role as Rabin's successor in his victory speech in
Rabin Square after Monday's vote and again Tuesday at Rabin's
grave.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Yitzhak Rabin Square was the natural place for
celebrating Barak's victory. That's why tens of thousands of
Israelis came together there in a spontaneous outpouring of relief
and joy. That's why I cried when I saw on television the large
posters of Rabin they waved. The memory of Rabin that had been
trampled on and repressed for 3-1/2 years was finally redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before the crowd in the early hours of Tuesday, Barak
said, ``I came here to Rabin Square, to the place where our hearts
were broken, when a stone blocked the gate, just when we were about
to embark on a new era.''
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who had stood in the square years ago with Rabin now
hope that stone has been removed and the new era can begin.
</P>
<P>
   (Debbie Lerman is an American-born Israeli citizen, and
free-lance writer living in Jerusalem.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
