<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3128 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-BROADWAY20-COX     05-19 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BROADWAY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Parade' score a thrilling original
 &HT;    By Kathy Janich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first sound you hear is the rhythmic rat-tat-tat of a
military drum. Then a plaintive tenor _ a Rebel soldier _ sings
softly of the old red hills of home, a Georgia ``where honor lives
and breathes.''
</P>
<P>
   The song continues, but the scene changes. It's 1913, and the
Confederate Memorial Day Parade has begun. That hopeful soldier is
50 years older, his voice deeper and sadder.
</P>
<P>
   So begins ``Parade,'' the Alfred Uhry-Jason Robert Brown musical
that lasted only weeks but is now collecting plenty of
end-of-season accolades. The show portrays 1913 Georgia as a land
of dishonor, where a young Mary Phagan is strangled, where Yankee
Jew Leo Frank is railroaded for the crime and where any number of
Southerners find the pull of a private agenda more intoxicating
than the search for truth.
</P>
<P>
   Tough stuff for a musical? Yes, but as exciting as it is
devastating. ``Parade'' is one of the finest Broadway scores in
recent years, performed by thrilling theater singers and given
backbone by a chorus that can soar or sting or break into harmonies
so potent your eyes will moisten.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, in his Broadway debut, has crafted odes, hymns, marches
and more for characters who show cracks as well as courage. When
Lucille Frank (Carolee Carmello) spits out ``You Don't Know This
Man'' to a crowd of accusers, she fights to control her outrage as
she tells them how little they do know. When Leo (Brent Carver)
sings of being an outsider (``How Can I Call This Home?''), his
longing for Brooklyn where ``people look like I do and talk like I
do'' is urgent and unfulfillable. When reporter Britt Craig (Evan
Pappas) heralds ``Big News'' to the plinkety-plank of a barroom
piano, it's clear his thirst for booze long ago liquefied his need
for facts.
</P>
<P>
   This is a remarkable recording, one that gives lovers of cast
albums the chance to revel in a wholly original American musical.
Brown's is a grown-up score for those of us who want substance with
our razzle-dazzle and our brains engaged as our toes start tapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parade''
</P>
<P>
   Original cast. RCA Victor. 28 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathy Janich writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1442EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3130 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS20-COX     05-19 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of recently released CD's
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldgredge, Sonia Murray and Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Useful Music''
</P>
<P>
   Josh Joplin Band. SMG. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Poised for national attention with his third release _ and debut
for Shawn Mullins' home-grown label _ Atlanta singer-songwriter
Josh Joplin always has followed a decidedly untrendy muse. His
maturity is sharply evident, whether on the heartbreakingly
beautiful ``Far Away'' or in the wistful childhood memories evoked
by ``Dutch Wonderland.'' Much of the album focuses on failed
relationships, subject matter usually ripe for cliche. ``Useful
Music'' contains not a one. Joplin's melodic songs succeed because
he's able to articulate his confusion and sadness so openly that it
binds him to his audience. And Mullins' clean, spare production
lets those emotions ring more clearly. Jay Leno better make some
more room on his couch. ``Useful Music'' has the potential to put
Joplin there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard L. Eldredge
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Pimpin' on Wax''
</P>
<P>
   JT Money. Freeworld/Tony Mercedes. 14 tracks. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Look at your watch when you put this album on. And know that at
that hour, minute and second you experienced an Atlanta rapper's
entry into the West Coast territory of ``Pimpin' on Wax'': a debut
as serious as fuzzy dice, loud suits and stacks with fish in the
soles are silly. The former member of bass music's Poison Clan
(``Shake What Your Mama Gave Ya'') continues in the misogynistic
vein of his earlier cohorts. But JT Money takes hip-hop's often
one-dimensional ``pimpin' '' to more intriguing levels. On the No.
1 rap single ``Who Dat?'' Money steps aside and lets the equally
cocky Sole show women have just as much hustle. He steps up his
clear, gruff delivery to match the bounce of ``Watcha Want.'' And
then he steps over to a softer side, proving a poignant lyricist on
the bluesy ``Kite to Ya Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``The Life and Crimes of Alice Cooper'' Alice Cooper. Rhino. 81
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   The only crime this four-CD retrospective is guilty of is
box-set bloat. Few artists deserve to be so extensively
anthologized _ even the work of such durable rockers as Elton John
and Rod Stewart showed wear when stretched to such lengths. Alice
Cooper's career is particularly patchy. Discs three and four, which
chronicle the shock-rock pioneer's limp '80s and '90s output, are
virtually unlistenable. (Though it's a hoot to hear the 1980 Gary
Numan rip-off ``Clones'' again.) And the long-lost tracks that open
the set _ by Cooper's mid-'60s garage rock group, the Spiders _
should have remained lost.
</P>
<P>
   But sandwiched in between is some pretty choice stuff, including
fist-pumping classic rock staples (``School's Out'') and charmingly
theatrical set pieces (``Go to Hell''). Most shocking is how dated
it all sounds. In this age of Marilyn Manson, a necrophiliac anthem
such as ``Cold Ethyl'' is about as chilling as ``The Monster
Mash.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1442EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3131 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-POP20-COX     05-19 0298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slicker Jack Logan remains true to scruffy roots
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a singer is his songs, then the Jack Logan whom critics and a
healthy cult of fans came to know on his 1994 debut, ``Bulk,'' was
a laid-back dude in grease-stained overalls, with a six-pack of
cold beer within easy reach and a dogeared Flannery O'Connor
paperback in his back pocket. Not slick, but a refreshing reminder
that rowdy, three-chord rock could also aspire to thoughtfully
literate devices. Pop open ``Buzz Me In,'' and it's clear that our
working-class hero has experienced an upgrade: He poses in a dinner
jacket, clutching a bouquet as if greeting a prom date.
</P>
<P>
   It's a giggle, but an apt one. The album, recorded in 1997 and
finally rescued by Capricorn Records from Logan's former label,
applies studio gloss to the Winder songwriter's scruffy craft.
Kosmo Vinyl's production is too fussy at times, yet it does wonders
for Logan's sincere baritone, locking in the emotional grain of his
voice against an ever-shifting backdrop. Between offhanded nods to
the Rolling Stones (``All Grown Up'') and George Jones
(``Melancholy Girl,'' ``Pearl of Them All''), Logan luxuriates in
plush arrangements that buffer his slice-of-life lyrics with airy
vibes, breezy guitar and the stray, muted trumpet. Close inspection
reveals, however, that while the scenarios change, the singer stays
true. ``Your neck smells like peppermint,'' he declares in the
album's most inspired couplet. ``C'mon, baby, let me pay your
rent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Buzz Me In''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Logan. Capricorn. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
