<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-IMPOSTERS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Imposters' provides shipload of fun nostalgia
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Impostors'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   The folks who brought us the savory, bittersweet ``Big Night''
go flat-out silly in this homage to shipboard romances of the
1930s. Writer-director Stanley Tucci and Oliver Platt play
out-of-work actors who stow away on a luxury liner populated by
familiar types: the grande dame (Dana Ivey), her sad-sack daughter
(Hope Davis), a fascist ship's steward (Campbell Scott), the
activities director whom he covets (Lili Taylor) and even the
occasional melancholy European royal (Isabella Rossellini).
</P>
<P>
   Tucci and Platt get into various scrapes, parade around in
disguise and stumble upon a terrorist plot.
</P>
<P>
   The pratfalls and chases do wear thin after a while. But the
cast (including an uncredited Woody Allen) is so game and gung-ho,
their enthusiasm becomes contagious. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
