</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Cruise'' (PG) _ Get on the bus. Cruising takes on a
whole new meaning in this quirky, low-budget black-and-white
documentary. Timothy ``Speed'' Levitch is a loquaciously eccentric
tour guide for a Manhattan bus company. Levitch is a heck of a
character study; he can get irritating. But surveying his domain
from the top of a double-decker, he's a kind of inspired
performance artist. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Very Bad Things'' (R) _ When a stag party goes murderously
out of control, the groom-to-be and his pals (Jon Favreau, Jeremy
Piven, Daniel Stern and Christian Slater) go to great lengths to
cover their tracks. Even if it means killing a bunch of people, or
each other. This pitch-black comedy from Peter Berg is the sort of
sick-joke experience you'll tend to love or hate. Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Bent'' (R) _ The first third features some twisted fun in
its vision of gay bohemian life in World War II Berlin (that's Mick
Jagger in a dress, folks). But when it gets to the concentration
camps, the movie betrays its stage origins, and actors Clive Owen
and Lothaire Bluteau are competent but not riveting as would-be
lovers who meet behind barbed wire. Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Holy Man'' (PG) _ A mild comedy-drama that wastes Eddie
Murphy's talents as a New Age drifter who brings big sales and
enlightenment to home-shopping producer Jeff Goldblum and media
analyst Kelly Preston; he's their spiritual Lassie, leading them to
warm-fuzzy values. It's Hollywood's latest reduction of spiritual
values to ``give somebody a hug.'' And it's not even very funny.
Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``In Dreams'' (R) _ In what could be called ``Nightmare on Elm
Street'' meets ``The Eyes of Laura Mars,'' a psychic woman (Annette
Bening) is harassed in dreams by a child-murdering psycho. For an
hour, the movie is eerie and disturbing, but an overly long
encounter between Bening and the madman proves damaging. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie'
</P>
<P>
   THE VIDEO COLLECTOR
</P>
<P>
   Notable videos on sale
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster: ``Deep Impact,'' $14.95 VHS, $29.99 DVD.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
