<HEADER>
A3162 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR'S-VOCABULARY-PROB     05-19 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR'S-VOCABULARY-PROBLEM-OPED-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AIR' VS. `GROUND': NATO'S WAR OF WORDS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Commentary)   (This insightful 725-word ``separate buy'' commentary is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable
to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``k'' commentary news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By PETER HERRLY  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As bombs rain down on ``strategic'' targets while
Serbian forces empty Kosovo, public opinion in Britain, France and
the United States largely approves NATO's ``air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many of those polled feel that a ``ground
campaign'' will eventually be required. Most defense experts in the
three countries mirror those conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Kosovo has a vocabulary problem. The terms ``air''
and ``ground'' seem to offer a classic choice of military options.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they offer incomplete choices, fail to reflect accepted
U.S. or NATO military concepts, and thus blur _ perhaps fatally _
the search for a military solution of NATO's current dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   The saying that hope is not a method expresses that dilemma. A
single-dimension strategy based on the use of force to ``signal''
and ``punish,'' instead of decisive force used in all dimensions to
compel, leaves only the hope that all will come out right.
</P>
<P>
   There is a better choice. The campaign which offers the surest,
and in the long run a less costly, way to accomplish the alliance's
political goals _ surer than the hope-to-win choice of an air-only
effort, and leaner than a ``ground campaign's'' hundreds of
thousands of troops _ is the one already embodied in the
war-fighting doctrine of NATO and the U.S. armed forces: a truly
joint campaign in all dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   In the joint U.S. and NATO military doctrine published after the
Gulf War, the term ``air campaign'' was deliberately never used.
</P>
<P>
   The Gulf War had made clear two things about air power. First,
air power has so immensely matured as a military tool that air
interdiction is now conceptually the equal of land and sea maneuver
_ something that soldiers and sailors do not like to admit.
</P>
<P>
   But second, the use of air power, although essential to success
in modern warfare, is not alone sufficient to ensure such success.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of problems associated with ground campaigns as
well, problems which have kept that option off the table so far in
this war.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of significant numbers of casualties and extremely
difficult terrain, as well as completely inadequate ports and
infrastructure for large land forces, give pause to all but the
most fervent advocates of a land solution.
</P>
<P>
   But it is precisely the shortcomings of single-dimensional
solutions that a truly joint campaign is designed to avoid. The
superb functioning and capabilities of allied air power, and the
enabling power of allied naval forces, makes adding land combat
power to the equation much less costly and much more effective.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the military aim focused primarily on the occupation of
Kosovo and the repatriation of refugees makes the operation more
achievable.
</P>
<P>
   This also makes an extensive Serbian guerrilla movement less
likely, since there are relatively few Serbian civilians in the
province to nurture a guerrilla resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Given that aim, NATO can leverage its overwhelming power to
protect the introduction of land forces, using all the tools
available: light infantry, armored, motorized, airborne, airmobile
and special forces, plus operational maneuver from the sea.
</P>
<P>
   That mix of forces, relying on massive air and naval power,
means substantially smaller land forces.
</P>
<P>
   Once introduced, the simple existence of land combat power (if
only in Albania, where it should have been deployed before the
first bomb was dropped) should force the Serbs to abandon some of
their passive defense measures such as spreading out their tanks in
ones and twos.
</P>
<P>
   As the concepts that are supposed to guide future U.S. military
operations stress, synchronized land maneuver and air interdiction
create an agonizing dilemma for opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Concentrating will brutally expose Serbian forces to heavier
losses from interdiction. But if they stay hunkered down, their
passive measures to reduce losses to interdiction mean they cannot
effectively counter allied surface maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Single-dimensional operations are not the way it's supposed to
be done in the post-Gulf War era. It is not too late to start using
all the tools in NATO's bag. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Peter Herrly, a retired U.S. Army colonel, was the
principal author of the manual ``Joint Warfare of the U.S. Armed
Forces'' and a professor of strategy at the National War College.
He contributed this commentary to the International Herald
Tribune.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 725-word commentary from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
