<SLUG> BC-GOODKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWAN SONGS WE'D RATHER NOT HEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A previously unreleased song, believed to be the last record
featuring all four Beatles, will be out in late summer. The
three-minute, still-untitled song was recorded _ then supposedly
lost _ at the Abbey Road Studios during the 1968 sessions for the
Yellow Submarine album. It features John Lennon on lead vocal.
</P>
<P>
   ``No new work has been done on it,'' an unidentified source told
a British newspaper, ``but Paul (McCartney), George (Harrison) and
Ringo (Starr) have said this will be the last Beatles single.
There's nothing else left.'' &QL; 
``''_ Knight-Ridder Newspapers &QR;
</P>
<P>
   _A previously unreleased song, believed to be the last recording
made by the band America, will be out in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   The two-minute, still-untitled song was recorded _ then
supposedly lost _ in 1983 during a recording session. It features
Dewey Bunell on lead vocals; he is interrupted by bandmates Dan
Peek and Gerry Beckley. Peek shouts, ``Enough already! This is too
wimpy, even for us.'' Beckley adds, ``I'm fallin' asleep here. We
suck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No new work has been done on it,'' an unidentified source
said, ``but Dewey, Dan and Gerry have said this will be the last
America release. There's nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   _A previously unreleased tape of the members of the Amazing
Rhythm Aces simultaneously trimming their toenails, believed to be
the last recording made by the band, will be out in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-second, still-untitled segment was recorded _ then
supposedly lost _ backstage after a concert. It features Russell
Smith counting off, ``One, two, three'' followed by a loud
``CLIP!''
</P>
<P>
   ``No new work has been done on it,'' an unidentified source
said, ``but Russell has said this will be the last Aces release.
There's nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   _A previously unreleased tape of David Lee Roth screaming
obscenities at a hotel maid, believed to be the last recording made
by the original members of Van Halen, will be out in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-second outburst by the group's lead singer was recorded _
then supposedly lost _ after the maid mistakenly filled dishes in
the band's motel room with M&AMP;M's without removing the brown ones
first. It features Roth and the unidentified maid, who can be heard
crying in fear. The other members of the band can be heard cheering
Jordan on.
</P>
<P>
   ``No new work has been done on it,'' an unidentified source
said, ``but Eddie (Van Halen), Alex (Van Halen) and Michael
(Anthony) have said this will be the last release by the original
band. There's nothing else left.''
</P>
<P>
   _A previously unreleased 911 tape, believed to be the last
recording of K.C. and the Sunshine Band, will be out in late
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The three-minute, still untitled artifact was recorded _ then
supposedly lost _ at a Florida recording studio during the sessions
for 1982's ``All in a Night's Work.''It features bassist Richard
Finch frantically telling the 911 operator that his cat has been
killed in a grisly blender accident; bandleader Harry Wayne Casey
is then heard shouting over the laughter of the other band members
that it's ``just a joke, Richard _ that's homemade salsa.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No new work has been done on it,'' an unidentified source
said, ``but Harry has said this will be the last Sunshine Band
recording. There's nothing else left.''
</P>
<P>
   _A previously unreleased recording of John ``Bonzo'' Bonham
accidentally setting fire to his own hair, believed to be the last
recording made by Led Zeppelin, will be out in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-minute, still-untitled prank was recorded _ then
supposedly lost _ after a tape machine was left running during
recording of 1979's ``In Through the Out Door.'' It features
Bonham, after several dares by bandmates, dousing his head with
gasoline, then waving a lighter nearby. ``Holy (expletive),'' a
voice _ perhaps that of singer Robert Plant _ is heard saying. ``He
really did it!
</P>
<P>
   ``No new work has been done on it,'' an unidentified source
said, ``but Robert and Jimmy (Page) have said this will be the last
Led Zeppelin release. There's nothing else left.''
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
