<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3183 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALCOLM-X-DIARY-HNS &LR;      05-19 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALCOLM-X-DIARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALCOLM X FAMILY READY TO SUE TO STOP DIARY SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The family of Malcolm X is poised to sue to stop
the sale of the slain civil rights leader's diary by the
Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield auction house here on May 27.
</P>
<P>
   New York attorney Joseph Fleming, representing the heirs of
Malcolm X and his late wife Betty Shabazz, said Tuesday that his
inquiries so far indicate the diary was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   The red 146-page diary, worth an estimated $30,000 to $50,000,
was found in the left breast pocket of the suit that the
charismatic leader was wearing when he was assassinated Feb. 21,
1965, in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield received the book from a private
collector with whom it has often done business in the past, who in
turn bought it from a person who allegedly saved it from
destruction in the New York archives.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said the only way the diary could have found its way
into private hands other than by theft is if the file on the
Malcolm X case were purged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our understanding is that if there was a purging of the file
that all of it would have been purged, not any one or two items,''
Fleming said. ``There's no indication of any such purging or
disposition of the diary.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City archivist Kenneth Cobb said his office received
the Malcolm X file _ presumably including evidentiary material
introduced at the trial of his assassins _ in 1993 and hasn't
removed anything from it. ``Once it comes into the archives, it's
never purged,'' Cobb said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City district attorney's office, which had the file
for 25 years, has no information on how the diary got to the
auction block.
</P>
<P>
   ``The file has been out of our office for many years,'' said
spokesman Wayne Bryson, adding he did not know whether the diary
had ever been in the district attorney's possession.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming challenged Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield's assumption that
it received the document through legitimate channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are on notice that there is a clear indication that this
item was stolen. No matter how it got to Butterfield, it was
stolen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't resolve this in the next day or two, we will have
to go to court in California to enjoin the sale,'' Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shuken, Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield's general counsel,
said: ``We're continuing to determine the legitimate salability of
the property. As soon as we can get the information together, or
the properties come to an agreement, we'll make a decision about
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
