<SLUG> BC-OAKLAND-POLICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND TAPS OFFICER FROM TOUGH DISTRICT TO HEAD POLICE FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 and ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Mayor Jerry Brown tapped the young captain in
charge of East Oakland's toughest neighborhoods as the new police
chief with a mission to change his city's crime-ridden image.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Richard Word, 37, is a 15-year department veteran who has
reduced drug-related violence in the flatlands near the Oakland
Coliseum and the San Leandro border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to drop crime more than the national average,'' Brown
said Tuesday. ``Oakland suffers from a perception of high crime.
That perception will only go away with a dramatic drop in crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a onetime governor of California, said he wanted the
nation to see Oakland as a model for sensitive community policing
that respects every person in Oakland yet does not tolerate violent
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has handled one of the toughest districts in America in
East Oakland and he's done a good job,'' Brown said of Word. ``He
has that balance between being sensitive to the community but
driving crime down. That's a very difficult balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Word replaces Joseph Samuels, who was ousted in March after
Brown and City Manager Robert Bobb said the city's crime rate was
not dropping fast enough in this city of 370,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Word committed himself to a 20 percent reduction in crime in his
first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to work smarter. In my career, we've never had a
numerical goal'' of cutting crime, Word said. ``I see it as a
challenge for everyone in the department. But it's something I
believe we can deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   Crime has fallen in Oakland over the last several years.
According to national crime statistics released by the FBI this
week, Oakland's homicide rate last year dropped 27 percent, robbery
fell 23 percent and aggravated assault dipped 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, forcible rape jumped 11 percent and burglary and
motor-vehicle theft increased 3 and 4 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the improvement, Oakland's crime rate is still among the
highest of all major cities in California.
</P>
<P>
   Word said his priority is not only to change the reality of
crime in Oakland, but the perception as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My voice mail fills up with people who are talking about
fear,'' Word said. ``If people are afraid of crime, then there is
too much crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Word, a San Francisco native, is the department's second black
chief. He said he had no tolerance for brutality and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   His predecessor had sparred with the City Council over community
policing and overtime for officers. Samuels could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The department has only about 670 officers but Word hopes the
City Council will pass a new budget to increase the force to about
750.
</P>
<P>
   Word was valedictorian of his recruiting class at the Oakland
Police Academy. He was promoted to captain in 1997 after four years
each as a sergeant and lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   He completed college last year at age 36, after juggling
business classes at John F. Kennedy University in Contra Costa
County around his police work, graduating cum laude. He is working
on a master's degree in public administration from Golden Gate
University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
