<SLUG> BC-ALIEN-LIFE-SEARCHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOBEL WINNER TO HEAD NASA UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ NASA's scientific search for alien life now has
a world-famous director, a Nobel laureate.
</P>
<P>
   Baruch Blumberg, who won the 1976 Nobel Prize for physiology and
medicine, will be the new head of the space agency's Astrobiology
Institute based at the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Ames Research Center in Mountain View, Calif.,
space agency chief Daniel S. Goldin announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Best known for his work in developing the hepatitis B vaccine,
Blumberg is senior adviser to the president at Fox Chase Cancer
Center in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The search for possible life on Mars and other worlds has
attracted growing attention from NASA in recent years, and Blumberg
should bring ``powerful and committed leadership'' to the quest,
Goldin said. ``We are extremely fortunate to have a person of his
scholarship, experience and accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Blumberg gives the scientific search for alien
life something it has lacked for almost two decades, a leader of
Nobel Prize caliber. The last Nobel laureates to be major figures
in the field were the late Melvin Calvin of Berkeley and Joshua
Lederberg, formerly of Stanford. Lederberg played a central role in
the research from the 1950s to the 1970s and was a close associate
of the late planetary scientist Carl Sagan.
</P>
<P>
   The Astrobiology Institute was founded last year. It is more a
virtual organization than a physical one. Using computer networks,
it ties together researchers at NASA centers, universities and
other institutions. Its researchers study not only the possibility
of alien life but how life began and evolved on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people worldwide afflicted with hepatitis B has
plunged dramatically since Blumberg's discovery of the vaccine, a
NASA spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Educated at Columbia University, where he received his medical
degree, Blumberg later received a doctorate in biochemistry at
Oxford. He previously taught biology at Stanford. He and his wife,
Jean, have four children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
