<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3207 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0520-C     05-19 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM KUKES: THE BAR AMERIKA, LOVE IT OR LEAVE IT
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Yet again, someone has inadvertently tripped
over the parrot cage, sending it tumbling across the stone floor.
Feathers are flying and the birds are squawking.
</P>
<P>
   It is an almost nightly ritual. But the stereo speakers are
blaring an Albanian pop song at peak volume, so few in the crowded
outdoor bar seem to notice the distressed birds or the embarrassed
patron trying to set the cage upright.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations only really come to a halt, and then only briefly,
when the thunder of a distant explosion echoes off the walls, as it
does often here at the edge of the war over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In fiction, Casablanca had Rick's American Cafe. In fact, Beirut
had the Commodore Hotel bar. Every war has its meeting place for
spies, mercenaries and diplomats, aid workers, correspondents and
drunks.
</P>
<P>
   Kukes has the Bar Amerika, a place so bizarre you may think it
is fiction, but indeed it is fact.
</P>
<P>
   Its location near the heart of the Kosovo refugee crisis has
made it the prime gathering place in Kukes, a grimy little town in
northern Albania made world-famous as hundreds of thousands of
refugees from embattled Kosovo province descended upon it over the
past two months.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner of the bar, a volunteer guerrilla fighter from the
Bronx is about to join the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA, at
the front. In another, Irish aid workers discuss their latest
strategy for delivering food to refugees, while the local mobsters
at another table are overheard to openly brag about how much of it
they've stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are popular in Albania these days, and not just for
their dollars. We're seen as the savior, Uncle Sam come to drive
back the Serbs and win one for the ethnic Albanian refugees.
Perhaps like no other time or place since Korea, or the early days
of Vietnam, have such a poor people put so much faith in U.S. power
and moral authority.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the bar, Mushli Lleshi(CQ), a man who could pass
for Moammar Gadhafi's stunt double, has never been to America. But
a U.S. bank helped him secure his loan a few years ago to build the
place. So in tribute capitalism, he named it Bar Amerika.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, in a courtyard trimmed with hedges, there is cafe
seating with umbrellas advertising Coca-Cola. Inside is dark and
smoky, with the stereo blaring and a television usually tuned to a
satellite news channel. The menu is limited and a vegetarian's
nightmare -- chicken, beefsteak and lamb.
</P>
<P>
   During the meal, either the pregnant mutt or the one-eyed cat or
both will nose your leg, begging for food. A hen and her chicks
occasionally wander into the courtyard scratching and pecking for
scraps.
</P>
<P>
   Kukes is several miles from the border of Kosovo and the rumble
of explosions echo through the town day and night, forcing a brief
lull in the din at the Bar Amerika.
</P>
<P>
   The patrons soon return to their Heinekens and chatter, each
offering a different theory on what we all just heard -- the sonic
boom of a NATO warplane, incoming Serb artillery, outgoing Albanian
army artillery, or a rocket-propelled grenade from the nearby KLA
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Mounted on either side of the bar's courtyard entrance are
mortar shells, placed there by the owner soon after the joint
opened in 1997 and a bloody coup in Albania followed. They are a
reminder for others here in lawless, bandit-ridden northern Albania
not to mess with the Bar Amerika.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars and Stripes and an Albanian flag fly from the balcony.
And Old Glory drapes a model of the Statue of Liberty, which stands
behind the bar. Elton John's greatest hits, apparently one of the
few Western CDs in possession of the barkeep, play often. The song
``I'm Still Standing,'' is popular with the small crowd of Kosovar
Albanian refugees working as translators for the media and relief
workers.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent night, an Albanian-American from New York, Vasel
Lulgjuraj, stopped by with some friends from the KLA to celebrate
before he departed for the front the following day to join the
guerilla war against Serb forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was born in Kosovo, Lulgjuraj is all Bronx,
developing since the age of three a ``Yo, Vinnie!'' accent and a
New York state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I told 'em, 'Hey I been trainin' five friggin' weeks. Send
me to the front, or I'm goin' home' So, I'm goin' to the front,''
he told me, proudly displaying his KLA dogtags.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Army veteran trained with an M-16, he is now carrying an
AK-47.
</P>
<P>
   He's also carrying an attitude common to many of the foreigners
who crowd daily and nightly into the Bar Amerika, guerrillas or
humanitarians, journalists or U.N. bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I saw those women and children on CNN and I said, 'I
gotta get over there and help,''' said Lulgjuraj. ``Somebody's
gotta do something for these people.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Westerners who have come to the most remote and
destitute part of Europe, the Bar Amerika is a oasis from where
most of them have spent the day -- in the dusty and wilting refugee
camps, listening to heartbreaking tales from the victims of the
Serbs' ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   For journalists, Bar Amerika is not only a retreat, but also
part of the beat.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a reporter with experience at nursing your drink, you
can occupy a table on the bar's front courtyard and expect in the
course of an hour or so to see almost anyone you'd want to
interview.
</P>
<P>
   War and refugees have been very good for the owner of Bar
Amerika.
</P>
<P>
   Not so good, though, for his parrots.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
