<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3210 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-HYPE-TEX     05-19 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-HYPE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL EFFECTS CAN'T COMPENSATE FOR PLODDING PLOT AND SKIN-DEEP
CHARACTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'd hate to be a parent taking my kids to ``Star Wars: Episode I
_ The Phantom Menace,'' because every scene is loaded with
figurine-ready characters and objets d' hustle. The movie is bound
to inspire trips to Taco Bell and KFC for the toy tie-ins. If the
first ``Star Wars'' used ``Triumph of the Will'' to make a point,
then this one's about the success of commercialism. It's ``Triumph
of the Till.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no way that a movie as massively hyped as ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' could possibly live up to
expectations. ``Phantom Menace'' has received the kind of media
attention generally reserved for natural disasters, a category in
which some think this ``Star Wars'' prequel belongs. Several of the
set pieces are fun, such as a race involving pod racers (the craft
Luke Skywalker drove in the first ``Star Wars'') and a light saber
battle with Jedi Knights Qui-Gon Jinn (Liam Neeson) and the young
Obi-Wan Kenobi (Ewan McGregor) taking on the decoratively faced
Darth Maul (Ray Park). ``Phantom'' is crammed with events,
characters and story line, and yet it's often boring because it
manages to seem as if nothing's going on. It's a mile wide and a
centimeter deep.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, no one who's seen any of the previous ``Star Wars''
films _ and there are apparently several of you out there _ should
be shocked to note that ``Phantom'' is clunky and heavy on
portentous exposition. What might catch you unawares is that the
battle between Good and Evil _ the operatic struggle that made up
the first three films _ has been downsized for a skirmish over
trade treaties and taxation. These discussions are like an
intergalactic version of C-SPAN. If you're not as deeply concerned
with the politics of the Empire as are ``Star Wars'' devotees, then
the first 40 minutes will be like catching one of the later
episodes of ``Babylon 5,'' a phenomenon like walking into the
middle of an unsubtitled foreign film.
</P>
<P>
   The characters fall into two groups, grim-faced worriers or
slapsticky comic relief figures. ``Phantom'' could use a character
with the cheery bravado of Han Solo, or at least an actor like
Harrison Ford, with his matinee-idol brusqueness. You'd think Ewan
McGregor was hired for his roughneck charm, but as Obi-Wan, he's
fallen into imitating Alec Guinness' tony inflections. Guinness
radiated slyness, and McGregor's appropriation makes him seem
laminated. He's a humorous, physical actor, and while there's
dialogue alluding to his wild streak, his Obi-Wan talks as if he's
waiting for the afternoon tea trolley to roll around. But there's
not much anyone can do with lines like, ``I sense a disturbance in
the Force.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom'' squanders more acting talent than any movie in
recent history. Like McGregor, its other potential swashbuckler,
Neeson, intones his lines in a dead voice. He wears the horsehair
wig that Val Kilmer sported in ``Willow'' _ another George Lucas
epic that took its fable aspects too seriously. (Why is it that a
film that does such an admirable job in creating computer-generated
special effects couldn't hide the glue holding the wig to his
head?) It's no wonder that he thought about retiring from show
business after finishing this movie _ he doesn't get to do any
acting in it. Poor Natalie Portman, who has talent to burn, is
reduced to a bad kid actor as Queen Amidala. Her fakey royal accent
seems to suggest she's been reading too much of Jewel's poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Although had she given a deeper performance, the scenes with
Portman cruising 9-year-old Anakin Skywalker (Jake Lloyd, who's
standard kid-actor adorable) might have been disconcerting. They
will become the parents of Luke Skywalker and Princess Leia. Lucas
didn't bother to write a personality for Anakin or, for that
matter, anyone else. They're all archetypes from an aerosol can.
The actors are handled miserably _ having to act with
computer-generated images (CGIs) that were added later clearly wore
them out. Even Samuel L. Jackson's insolence has been tamed. He has
an extended cameo as Mace Windu, a member of the Jedi Council, and
his eyes burn like a light saber, but he barely gets a chance to
stand up.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the movie was created by computer, and this
includes a number of the characters, like Jar Jar Binks, the
amphibious character who becomes a sidekick to Qui-Gon and Obi-Wan.
His patois must've been influenced by Jamaicans, and his elongated
ears suggest dreadlocks. It's almost as if Lucas is trying to
counter the benign racism of the first ``Star Wars'' by showing
that not only do blacks exist in outer space, but black culture
does as well. At one point, a happy Jar Jar _ whose name is
reminiscent of Shabba Ranks (and whose movements were created by
dancer Ahmed Best) _ breaks into the Smurf, just so we know he can
get his freak on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom'' is certainly a movie created for kids, but that
motivation seems to eliminate filmmaking excitement. Don't expect
another bolt of the folklore ingenuity and the intersecting of
magic that made the first ``Star Wars'' an unusual occurrence.
Irony abounds. Director George Lucas pioneered a kind of movie made
of a number of scenes, instead of just one, that became a
video-game template. So when he falls back on it _ like in the pod
racing scene _ you feel as if you're watching an imitation of a
video game. And although computers have freed him to create
whatever tableau his mind's eye can envision, his imagination
doesn't quite seem up to it. The lighting on many of the CGI sets
has a one-dimensional flatness, as does the light on all of the CGI
creatures. You find you get a charge seeing the way the human
actors' flesh takes the light _ even the stadium-worthy satanic
makeup job on Darth Maul, which makes him look as if he hails from
the same galaxy as Mankind and Stone Cold Steve Austin. Your eyes
get bored taking the shiny similarity of the CGI stuff.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few good things about ``Phantom'' is that it doesn't
use any pop music for its score. It's touching to hear an
orchestral score played at THX-quality volume. Part of ``Star
Wars''' success was that it was a rock 'n' roll phenomenon: the
first superloud stereo movie, which really helped it draw the line
in the sand between parents and kids. And although it seems
visually stunted, the sound design is layered and detailed. And
everything that was furry and cute in the previous films is now
lizardlike and scaly _ the ``Jurassic Park'' influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' has a ghostly feel, though _ it doesn't quite
register. Who'd have thought that a movie that attracted so much
premillennial tension wouldn't have a single surprise in it? A lot
of the problem comes with making a prequel, but it's a bad idea to
combine blandness and grandiosity.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
