A3227 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-ZONIANS-TEX     05-19 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-ZONIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZONIANS ANXIOUSLY AWAIT U.S. TURNOVER OF CANAL ZONE TO PANAMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DIANE SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mayra Cernicek is filled with a deep sense of loss when she
hears reports from her Panamanian homeland. Relatives tell her that
jobs are declining and that the Americans are really leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Those reports are reminders that Dec. 31 _ when the United
States will relinquish control of the Panama Canal to the
Panamanian government _ is quickly approaching.
</P>
<P>
   For many Panamanians, that date will mark the triumph of a long
struggle for national pride. Lack of control of the Panama Canal
and the former Canal Zone _ a 50-mile-long community that was
inhabited mostly by American workers _ has long been an affront to
their sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   But the control may come at a cost for those who had grown
accustomed to the American way of life. Many Panamanians are
uncertain about how the Central American country will manage after
its 96-year relationship with the United States changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very worried and fearful,'' said Cernicek, who lives in
Southlake.
</P>
<P>
   Worries abound about economics, government corruption and
Panama's vulnerability against outside powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sad, because Panama is a strategic point,'' said
Guillermina Lovelace, a Panamanian living in Arlington.''It was
watched by the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The canal was built as a passage between the Atlantic and
Pacific oceans. For most of the century, cargo and passenger ships
have used the engineering marvel.
</P>
<P>
   Some Panamanians are concerned that Panama might be ill-prepared
to begin operating the canal, which the United States built during
the early 1900s at a cost of about $387 million.
</P>
<P>
   Panama's political unrest during the rule of former dictator
Manuel Noriega and many residents' mistrust of the government also
are sources of concern. Some believe that the canal will be
exploited, that corrupt officials will line their pockets and that
Panama's poor will lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope it's for the good of Panama,'' said James Gaugh, a
Panamanian who lives in Dallas. ``We know better.''
</P>
<P>
   Among nationalists, there is no question that Panama can rise to
the challenge. The transition should be seamless, they say, because
many of the laborers, engineers, electricians, administrators and
other employees who work on the canal are Panamanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are optimistic, and we believe that there exists an
awareness among Panamanians over the great responsibility we are
assuming when we take control of the canal,'' said Victor Avila, a
professor of Panamanian history at the University of Panama in
Panama City.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an old aspiration for Panamanians, who have fought
since the 19th century to the present to strengthen our national
identity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of transition are more obvious each day. The U.S. military
bases and government buildings that dotted Panama's landscape are
being dismantled. Today, Panamanians live in homes formerly
occupied by Americans who worked for the Panama Canal Commission.
Gorgas Hospital, where generations of Americans were delivered, is
now controlled by Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Balboa High School, which is operated by the United States for
the children of American canal workers and military personnel,
graduated its final class last week.
</P>
<P>
   As such U.S. landmarks stop operating, so ends a chapter for the
many Panamanians and Americans who built lives around the canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like it used to be,'' said Denise Smith, who lives in
the Canal Zone. ``People are sad because they have to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who is married to an American who works for the Panama
Canal Commission, is among the last residents of the
U.S.-controlled territory. Through the years, thousands of
Americans worked and lived in the Canal Zone. Many were descendants
of workers who left the United States during the early 1900s to
help build the canal.
</P>
<P>
   The Zonians _ as they came to be known _ administered and
maintained the canal in many capacities, from locomotive operators
to electricians. They also provided fire, police and medical
protection for the people who lived and worked in the Canal Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Many other Americans went to Panama as military personnel.
Panama also had a large population of West Indians, many of them
immigrants from Barbados and Jamaica who were recruited to work on
the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Palmer, a Panamanian who is visiting North Texas, used to
work as a nursing aide at Gorgas Hospital. She said many
Panamanians hope that a U.S. presence will remain after Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish they would stay,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Panamanians say the country has been undergoing a
transition since 1977, when the United States and Panama signed
agreements guaranteeing that control of the canal would be
transferred.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the change is difficult at first, some say, Panama must
gain national pride by taking over the formerly occupied Canal
Zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am one of the few people who think that it is important for
the country to go through this change,'' said Marcia Howell, a
Panamanian who lives in Lewisville.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the uncertainty is caused by the notion that only
Americans can run the canal, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a facade that people have grown to believe _ that unless
it is done by Americans, then nobody can do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Diane Smith is a native of the Panama Canal Zone. She graduated
from Balboa High School in 1987. You can call her at (817)
685-3801, or e-mail: dianesmith(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
