<HEADER>
A3255 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE20-COX     05-19 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With a little planning, potluck can be elegant
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Potluck or covered dish dinners have been part of the American
scene since the Pilgrims and their Native American neighbors sat
down together for that first Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   In times of celebration and sorrow or to mark any occasion,
friends and relatives, neighbors and co-workers can usually be
counted on to gather together, bearing pots, bowls and casseroles
brimming with food.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's ``going potluck'' just for the sake of having a
party.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, certain arbiters of style and taste declared
potluck parties declasse. Peggy Post in her book ``Emily Post's
Entertaining'' proclaimed that the potluck party ``does not take
the place of the party you truly give for your friends. As long as
you can afford to provide even the simplest food and drink, you
should accept the entire responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is changing fast.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that potluck cuts down the time and cost of throwing a
party, offers a greater variety of treats than one person could
possibly prepare and gives guests the chance to show off their own
culinary skills. Potluck parties meld beautifully with today's
lifetstyles.
</P>
<P>
   Premeditated potluck
</P>
<P>
   Though the definition of potluck suggests an informality where
guests will have to settle for whatever is available with little or
no choice, planned potluck may not be as much an oxymoron as you
think. With a little planning you can have a potluck party that can
be as elegant, opulent and certainly as much fun as any affair you
have been planning for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For valuable tips on planning a premeditated potluck see:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  vh0312.infi.net/columns/anderson/ca112796.htm
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  augustachronicle.com/stories/123098/fea124-2454.shtml
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  newattitudes.lifetimetv.com/recipes/frameset.shtml/green
</P>
<P>
   beans.html.
</P>
<P>
   You will learn about choosing themes, how to divide who will
make what, what to do about main courses, utensils, food safety,
potluck protocol and more.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for your specialty
</P>
<P>
   If you already have a specialty potluck dish that you have been
taking to parties for years, you may want to expand your
repertoire. Or if you are still looking for that signature dish,
the Internet has enough potluck recipe suggestions to keep you
experimenting for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For screenload after screenload of possibilities, see
SOAR.Berkeley.EDU/recipes/cgi-bin/webglimpse?query
</P>
<P>
   &QC; potluck.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The library staff at New Mexico Tech got so proficient at
potluck, they published an online cookbook that's filled with good
ideas at
</P>
<P>
   www.nmt.edu/(tilde)nmtlib/subject/cookbook.htmlmain.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Potluck Pickins at progressivefarmer.com/countryplace
</P>
<P>
   /0996/recipes/index.html offers an informative article and
plenty of recipe possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you want to contribute the recipe for your specialty to a
cookbook that benefits breast cancer research, see www.pridewear
</P>
<P>
   .com/potluck.html.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Feta Pasta Primavera
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: about 10 minutes
Refrigeration time: at least 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   1(9-ounce) package refrigerated cheese tortellini
</P>
<P>
   1cup hot water
</P>
<P>
   2cups broccoli florets
</P>
<P>
   1cup cherry tomatoes, quartered
</P>
<P>
   1cup thinly sliced carrots
</P>
<P>
   1cup crumbled feta cheese with peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1cup Italian dressing
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup sliced green onions
</P>
<P>
   Prepare tortellini according to package directions; drain and
place in medium bowl. Cover and refrigerate at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Place water in a large saucepan with a steamer rack over
medium-high heat and bring to a boil. Add florets to rack, cover
and steam 2 to 3 minutes or until bright green but still
undercooked. Remove from heat and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Remove tortellini from refrigerator and place in a large bowl.
Combine tortellini, broccoli, tomatoes, carrots, feta, salad
dressing and onions; stir gently until blended. Refrigerate until
ready to serve. _ From: ``What's Cooking, America'' by Linda
Stradley and Andra Cook (BookPartners, $21.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 387 calories, 11 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 60), 29 grams carbohydrates, 26
milligrams cholesterol, 578 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
