A3259 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP20-COX     05-19 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chiffon cake sure to recall fond memories
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Josey Debner of Roswell (Ga.) asked for a chiffon cake
like those she made 50 years ago. In response, Katie Martin of
Lawrenceville (Ga.) e-mailed this Orange Chiffon Cake recipe, taken
from a 1942 edition of the ``Woman's Home Companion Cookbook'' she
found in an antiques store.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Reser of Dunwoody (Ga.)sent a basic chiffon cake recipe
from a 1950 Betty Crocker edition, which includes several
variations that she used to send to her husband when he was in the
military.
</P>
<P>
   To make a basic cake instead of the orange flavor tested here,
use 2 teaspoons vanilla extract and 2 teaspoons grated lemon rind
instead of the orange zest.
</P>
<P>
   The publications' timing is certainly right for Debner. We hope
the recipes are, too.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Orange Chiffon Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: about 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 65 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 1 1/2 to 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups cake flour, sifted
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   5 egg yolks, unbeaten
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons grated orange rind
</P>
<P>
   7 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a sifter, combine flour, sugar, baking powder and salt. Sift
together into a medium mixing bowl. Make a well in the dry
ingredients and add oil, egg yolks, water and orange rind. Beat
with a spoon to mix well. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Pour egg whites into a medium bowl. Add cream of tartar. Whip
until egg whites hold very stiff peaks, stiffer than for meringues
or angel food.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually pour the batter over egg whites, gently folding with a
rubber spatula until just blended. Do not stir.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into ungreased 10-inch tube pan and bake 55 minutes. Then
increase heat to 350 degrees and bake 10 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Remove pan from oven and immediately turn upside down, placing
it so that it hangs without cake touching table (invert pan and
place tube over a glass bottle), until cool, about 1 1/2 to 2
hours. Turn up and loosen from sides and tube with spatula. Turn
upside down again, then hit edge sharply on table to loosen onto
storage plate.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 211 calories, 4 grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 37), 30 grams carbohydrates, 66 milligrams
cholesterol, 307 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe requests
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Rogers of Decatur (GA.) is looking for a poppy seed cake
_ either a poundcake or a layer cake _ and the special icing that
goes on it.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Send food news to Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. The
deadline is noon two Mondays before publication.
</P>
<P>
   Editor: Susan Puckett at spuckett(at)ajc.com. 404-526-5443.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant editor: Marcia Langhenry at mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
404-526-5418.
</P>
<P>
   Food and nutrition writer: Reagan Walker at rwalker(at)ajc.com.
404-526-5856.
</P>
<P>
   Food writer/dining critic: John Kessler at jkessler(at)ajc.com.
404-526-5452.
</P>
<P>
   More on dining
</P>
<P>
   Need help deciding where to eat? Every week in the
Journal-Constitution, look for features about restaurants in
Thursday's Food and Friday's Weekend Preview.
</P>
<P>
   Dial-a-tip: For more suggestions on where to eat in and around
Atlanta, dial 511 and enter code 3663. Each call costs 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet
</P>
<P>
   On Access Atlanta, find recipes, features and listings for
hundreds of restaurants we have reviewed or visited. It's all at
www.accessatlanta
</P>
<P>
   .com/living/food/.
</P>
