<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3263 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TERRINE-RECIPE1S     05-19 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TERRINE-RECIPE1STTAKE20-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pates: Think creativity, not complexity
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pates and terrines are so beautiful that many may be intimidated
by the thought of making them. Don't be.
</P>
<P>
   It can be a difficult endeavor involving special pans and
hard-to-find ingredients. But it also can be a fairly uncomplicated
and creative effort.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes we offer here are in the latter category. You can
make any of them in a standard size (6 cup or 8 1/2-inch) loaf pan.
Or try dividing the recipes into two or three mini-loaf pans for
slices that better fit onto small crackers and baguette slices.
</P>
<P>
   We offer a classic chicken liver pate, but for the most part we
choose recipes featuring vegetables to reflect the season. So go
ahead and layer the flavors, and then slice into summer.
</P>
<P>
   Step by Step: Gazpacho Terrine
</P>
<P>
   Hedgerose Chef Martin Gagne walked us through the steps of
creating Gazpacho Terrine.
</P>
<P>
   Lining the pan (below). Most pates and terrines require a pan
that has been lined with plastic wrap. For especially soft
mixtures, it's important to make the plastic wrap as smooth as
possible. Gagne said oiling the pan first and then lining with
plastic wrap will keep it from slipping as you build the terrine.
He puts his molds in the freezer until needed.
</P>
<P>
   Most pates and terrines require blending or grinding of
ingredients. After snapping off the bottom stems, Gagne throws a
whole bunch of cilantro into the blender to make the gazpacho.
</P>
<P>
   For the Gazpacho Terrine, Gagne mixes the gazpacho, chopped
cucumbers and peppers and the gelatin in a bowl set in ice. That
helps the mixture to thicken and chill, speeding the process.
</P>
<P>
   Once the mixture begins to set, he pours it into the mold. What
doesn't fit, he pours into smaller molds, or timbales. The mixture
can set and be ready to serve after 30 minutes in the freezer or
about 2 hours in the refrigerator. You can slice and serve from the
terrine or unmold it onto a chilled platter.
</P>
<P>
   1. Lining the pan. Most pates and terrines require a pan that
has been lined with plastic wrap. For especially soft mixtures,
it's important to make the plastic wrap as smooth as possible.
Gagne said oiling the pan first and then lining with plastic wrap
will keep it from slipping as you build the terrine. He puts his
molds in the freezer until needed.
</P>
<P>
   2. Most pates and terrines require blending or grinding of
ingredients. After snapping off the bottom stems, Gagne throws a
whole bunch of cilantro into the blender to make the gazpacho.
</P>
<P>
   3. For the gazpacho terrine, Gagne mixes the gazpacho, chopped
cucumbers and peppers and the gelatin in a bowl set in ice. That
helps the mixture to thicken and chill, speeding the process.
</P>
<P>
   4. Once the mixtures begins to set, he pours it into the mold.
What doesn't fit, he pours into smaller molds, or timbales. The
mixture can set and be ready to serve after 30 minutes in the
freezer or about 2 hours in the refrigerator. You can slice and
serve from the terrine or unmold it onto a chilled platter.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Gazpacho Terrine
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings Preparation time: 1 hour, 30 minutes Chilling
time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Hedgerose chef Martin Gagne demonstrated this terrine for us in
his restaurant kitchen. It's a fairly simple and delightful twist
on a summer favorite, gazpacho. When you slice it, it looks like a
mosaic.
</P>
<P>
   Our adaptation calls for powdered gelatin, which is readily
available in any grocery store. Gagne and many chefs prefer to work
with gelatin sheets, which can be found at specialty stores such as
Harry's Farmers Markets, because they are more tasteless and
colorless. You can substitute 16 gelatin sheets for the amount
listed below.
</P>
<P>
   For the garnishing oil, Gagne works with grapeseed oil, which
can be found at health food stores. Any other light, flavorless oil
can be substituted. This recipe is enough to fill an 8-cup mold. If
you have a 6-cup loaf pan, you can work with that and pour the
remaining mixture into smaller pans, molds or cups.
</P>
<P>
   4 1/4-ounce envelopes gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   4large red peppers, roasted
</P>
<P>
   2large cucumbers, peeled, halved lengthwise and seeded
</P>
<P>
   1large red onion, skinned and quartered
</P>
<P>
   5limes, juiced
</P>
<P>
   1cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1large clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   1pinch saffron
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons Tabasco (or to taste)
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   3large bunches cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups tomato juice
</P>
<P>
   Pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups grapeseed oil
</P>
<P>
   Coat an 8-cup terrine or mold with oil and then line with
plastic wrap and place in freezer. In a small heatproof bowl,
combine the gelatin and water and set aside. Clean and remove the
seeds from the roasted red peppers and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place two of the cucumber halves in a blender or food processor
along with the quartered red onion. Add the lime juice, olive oil,
3 roasted peppers, garlic and saffron. Blend or process until all
ingredients are fairly well-chopped.
</P>
<P>
   Add the Tabasco and salt to taste. Snap the bottom half of the
stems off one bunch of cilantro and throw into the blender whole
and process again. Then add the tomato juice (if your blender or
food processor has a small capacity, mix in a large bowl). Pour
gazpacho mixture into a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Chop the remaining roasted pepper and thickly slice the
remaining cucumber halves. Toss the pepper and cucumber in a small
bowl together with salt and pepper to taste and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the gelatin over simmering water, double-boiler style,
until just dissolved. Add the pepper and cucumber mixture to the
gazpacho mixture and then stir in the gelatin until well-combined.
Place this bowl into a larger bowl filled with ice or ice water and
stir, scraping the sides of the bowl until the mixture begins to
thicken and chill, about 5-7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the mold from the freezer. Pour the mixture into the
mold. Put the mold in the freezer for 30 minutes or the
refrigerator for 2 hours. Meanwhile, combine the remaining two
bunches of cilantro, bottom stems removed, and the grapeseed oil in
the blender and blend thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Strain this mixture through a strainer lined with several layers
of cheesecloth into a bowl or bottle. You will have about 1 cup.
When terrine has set, serve individual slices on plates drizzled
with the cilantro oil.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 299 calories, 3 grams protein, 29 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 89), 7 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 136 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Liver Pate
</P>
<P>
   With Fig Preserves
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 20 minutes Chilling
time: 5 hours
</P>
<P>
   A classic pate usually includes livers or liver in combination
with other meats. This one is simple, yet divine. And finally,
here's a good way to finish off last summer's fig preserves. If you
don't have any, check gourmet or specialty stores. But this pate
will work fine without the fig topping.
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup (1 stick) unsalted
</P>
<P>
   butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   2medium onions (about 3/4 pound), chopped
</P>
<P>
   1pound chicken livers, trimmed, patted dry and seasoned with
salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup tawny port
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup fig preserves, chopped fine
</P>
<P>
   Toast points or water
</P>
<P>
   biscuits as an
</P>
<P>
   accompaniment
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet over medium-high heat, melt 2 tablespoons
butter. Add onions and cook, stirring constantly, until they are
soft but not brown, about 8 to 10 minutes. Transfer to a food
processor.
</P>
<P>
   In the same skillet, melt an additional 2 tablespoons butter
over medium high heat. Add the chicken livers. Cook, stirring
constantly, for about 5 minutes, until they are firmed and cooked
through, but still pink in the centers. Transfer the livers to the
food processor with the onions.
</P>
<P>
   Add the port to the skillet, bring it to a boil and deglaze the
skillet, scraping up the brown bits, for 1 to 2 minutes. Add the
port to the food processor with the remaining 4 tablespoons butter,
the allspice, lemon juice and salt and pepper to taste. Puree the
mixture until it is very smooth, and force it through a fine sieve
into a bowl. Line an oiled 2-cup mold or pan with straight sides
with plastic wrap and pour in the pate. Chill, covered, for 5
hours, or until firm. The pate may be made 4 days in advance and
kept covered and chilled. Invert the pate onto a plate, discarding
the plastic wrap, and smooth the top and sides. Spread preserves on
the top and serve with the toast points or water biscuits. _ From:
Food.Epicurious.Com (Gourmet, December 1991)
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 55 calories, 3 grams protein, 3 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 57), 3 grams carbohydrates, 79
milligrams cholesterol, 7 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
