<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3267 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TERRINE-RECIPES2     05-19 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TERRINE-RECIPES2NDTAKE20- </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Asparagus and Shiitake Mushroom Terrine
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 1/2-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Assembly time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 8 hours
</P>
<P>
   This terrine is as delicious as it is impressive. When you slice
through it, the asparagus gives the effect of green polka dots. We
found it in ``Martha Stewart's Hors d'Oeuvres Handbook'' (Clarkson
Potter, $35). She calls for a 12-by-2 1/4-inch metal terrine pan.
We found one (but only one) at Williams-Sonoma. But we tried it in
a standard 8 1/2-by-4 1/2-inch loaf pan and it worked beautifully.
The recipe calls for labneh cheese, which is a Middle Eastern
yogurt cheese spread. The new Whole Foods grocery at Briarcliff and
LaVista roads carries it. But you can substitute any yogurt cheese.
</P>
<P>
   12medium shiitake mushrooms, stems removed
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4medium leeks, white parts finely chopped and greens separated
into leaves, well washed
</P>
<P>
   1small bunch thin asparagus, about 16 spears
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup labneh cheese
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Line metal terrine or loaf pan with
plastic wrap, leaving a 3-inch overhang of plastic on each side. In
a medium bowl, toss the mushrooms with 2 teaspoons of salt, the
pepper and 2 tablespoons olive oil. Arrange on a baking sheet and
bake until roasted and golden brown, 15 to 20 minutes. Transfer the
sheet to a rack to cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   While the mushrooms are roasting, heat the remaining olive oil
over medium heat in a large saute pan. Add the chopped leeks. Cook,
stirring occasionally, until softened and translucent, about 5
minutes; do not allow the leeks to brown. Transfer the leeks to a
medium bowl to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a medium pot of heavily salted water to a boil. Add the
asparagus and cook until tender, about 2 minutes. Transfer to a
colander and rinse under cold running water. Drain and set aside.
To the same pot, add the leek greens and cook until tender, 2 to 3
minutes. Transfer the leeks to a colander, rinse under cold running
water, and drain.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine the goat cheese, labneh, and remaining
salt with the sauteed leeks; using a rubber spatula, stir until
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the leek greens in the pan crosswise and slightly
overlapping, with the ends of the greens hanging over the edges.
Using a small rubber spatula, spread a thin layer of the cheese
mixture along the bottom of the terrine.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange 1 layer of asparagus over the cheese mixture; trim the
asparagus to fit. Cover with another thin layer of the cheese
mixture, followed by another layer of asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   Continue with another thin layer of the cheese mixture and a
layer of mushrooms. Repeat with 2 more layers of asparagus and
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Fold the overhanging leeks over the top of the terrine. Seal
with the overhanging plastic wrap. Place on a baking sheet, top
with a second baking sheet, and place a weight on top (a heavy
cookbook works well). Refrigerate overnight. The terrine may be
made 2 days in advance, tightly wrapped, and refrigerated until
ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   To unmold, unwrap the plastic from the top of the terrine, place
an inverted serving platter over the terrine, and quickly turn the
terrine over onto the platter. Gently remove the mold and the
plastic wrap. Using a serrated knife, cut the terrine crosswise
into 1/2-inch slices. Arrange a slice on crostini, toast points or
crackers, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 52 calories, 2 grams protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 59), 4 grams carbohydrates, 3 milligrams
cholesterol, 317 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Tricolor Vegetable Pate
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Assembly time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 8 hours
</P>
<P>
   This pate is about as easy as they come, and it makes enough to
serve a party. In fact, if you were really pressed for time, you
could buy the pesto sauce, too. If you want to achieve a nice
layered look when you unmold it, try setting it in the freezer for
about a half-hour, and then turn it out. Then allow another
half-hour to soften before serving.
</P>
<P>
   White bean layer:
</P>
<P>
   2(15-ounce) cans cannellini (white kidney beans), rinsed,
drained thoroughly
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon minced fresh oregano or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   2garlic cloves, pressed
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Red pepper layer:
</P>
<P>
   1(7-ounce) jar roasted red bell peppers, drained, coarsely
chopped
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup crumbled feta cheese (about 4 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   Pesto layer:
</P>
<P>
   2garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1cup fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1cup fresh Italian parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup toasted pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup low-fat ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   Fresh herb sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Sourdough bread slices
</P>
<P>
   Line 8 1/2-by-4 1/2-inch loaf pan with plastic wrap, overlapping
sides.
</P>
<P>
   For white bean layer: Mash beans in large bowl. Add lemon juice,
olive oil, oregano and garlic and blend until smooth. Season to
taste with salt and pepper. Spread bean mixture evenly on bottom of
prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   For red pepper layer: Combine peppers and feta in a food
processor and blend until smooth. Spread pepper mixture evenly over
bean layer in prepared dish.
</P>
<P>
   For pesto layer: Mince garlic in processor. Add basil, parsley
and pine nuts and mince. With machine running, gradually add oil
through feed tube and process until smooth. Mix in ricotta. Spread
pesto evenly over red pepper layer. Cover with plastic wrap and
refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   To unmold, invert onto serving platter. Peel off plastic wrap.
Garnish with herb sprigs and serve with sourdough bread slices. _
From: Food.Epicurious.Com (Bon Appetit, October 1993)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 167 calories, 8 grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 47), 15 grams carbohydrates, 10 milligrams
cholesterol, 261 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Ham and Zucchini Terrine
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Assembly time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   Lydie Marshall included this recipe in her book ``A Passion for
My Provence'' (HarperPerennial, $15). It tastes like ham salad
taken to a gourmet level. She recommends first-quality ingredients.
Go to the deli counter to get the ham and choose imported Gouda for
best results. The hardest part of this dish is slicing both the
zucchini and the cheese thinly and evenly. Use your sharpest knife
or best gadgets, like a mandoline.
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   3or 4 medium zucchini, unpeeled, and cut in 1/8-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1pound boiled ham, rind and fat discarded
</P>
<P>
   1/4pound lightly smoked ham, rind and fat discarded
</P>
<P>
   2eggs
</P>
<P>
   1large clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   7ounces imported Gouda cheese, cut in thin slices
</P>
<P>
   Bring several quarts of salted water to a boil. Add zucchini and
when the water comes back to a boil, cook for 2 minutes. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Oil a 6-cup loaf pan or terrine and
place overlapping slices of zucchini on the sides and bottom of the
pan. Refrigerate 15 minutes. Coarsely grind the hams in a food
processor. Add eggs, garlic and pepper; process until it makes a
fine paste. You should have about 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Place alternate layers of ham and Gouda slices in the loaf pan.
(If you have leftover zucchini slices, feel free to include layers
of those as well.) Sprinkle with freshly ground pepper. (The ham
mixture will probably provide enough salt.)
</P>
<P>
   Tap the pan on the counter to pack it down; cover with a double
layer of aluminum foil. Place the pan in a water bath and bake for
45 minutes. Set aside to cool. Refrigerate at least 4 hours before
unmolding.
</P>
<P>
   To unmold: Warm the blade of a knife. Gently pass the warm blade
between the loaf and the pan. Turn the pan over on a platter; hit
the bottom of the pan with the handle of the knife to dislodge.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 163 calories, 19 grams protein, 9 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), 2 grams carbohydrates, 95
milligrams cholesterol, 837 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
