<HEADER>
A3268 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TERRINE20-COX     05-19 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TERRINE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Picnicking with pate? Let your romantic side cut loose and
create one elegant spread
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring is luring us from our dinner tables to the porch, the
back yard, the park and the lakeside for fresh-air dining. And for
large family gatherings and neighborhood block parties, grilled hot
dogs and Mom's potato salad will do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   But for those open-air concerts under the stars or romantic
moonlit picnics for two, something more elegant is in order.
</P>
<P>
   So we borrow from the French, who fancy themselves romantics,
after all, to suggest pates and terrines. These portable mosaics of
flavors and colors are magnifique.
</P>
<P>
   Hedgerose chef Martin Gagne says that they are ideal to take to
Chastain Park Amphitheatre, where concertgoers are famous for their
elegant spreads. Gagne often offers pates and terrines made with
seasonal ingredients on his menus and has taught others how to make
them at the Wollaston Smith Culinary Center. The techniques, he
points out, can vary from simple to master-chef complex.
</P>
<P>
   A moment here on the distinction between pates and terrines.
``The Le Cordon Bleu Complete Cooking Techniques'' cookbook
(William Morrow, $40) defines pates as ``a smooth- or
coarse-textured mixture, traditionally made of meat and/or liver,
but can be vegetable or fish, seasoned and set in a mold.''
</P>
<P>
   And a terrine is ``a mold or the food contained within it, often
a pate-like mixture of blended ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   The terminology can be a little confusing, especially as you
stray from the truly classic pates of ground meats. But the beauty
of these lovely loaves is that they are so versatile.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne explains that ingredients vary regionally in France,
depending on what's good locally and what's in season. One region
may have great fowl, another abundant pork. He demonstrated for us
a vegetarian gazpacho terrine that's ``more South of France, sunny
and summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The home cook in France is likely to be adept at making pates
and terrines that involve the layering or blending of a few
well-chosen ingredients. They are more likely to visit a
charcuterie _ a deli that sells sausages and pates _ for the more
elaborate versions, such as galantine, which can involve such
skills as braiding long strips of beef tongue and pork fat and
removing the whole skin of a duck without tearing it.
</P>
<P>
   Whether simple or complicated, Gagne says the most important
thing to keep in mind is to use the best-quality ingredients
possible. And most require plenty of chilling time _ at least
overnight. Many hold up well for two or three days or even longer.
That makes pates and terrines an ideal appetizer, since they can be
ready and waiting while you concentrate on other courses.
</P>
<P>
   While the avid cook may want to invest in a terrine mold _
usually a long rectangle made of earthenware or metal _ the novice
will do well to begin with standard loaf pans.
</P>
<P>
   Inside we offer a quick and easy tricolor vegetable pate and a
more detailed but delicious asparagus, mushroom and leek terrine.
</P>
<P>
   For a Southern twist on the classic pate, we suggest a chicken
liver and fig preserves combo; for an artful take on ham salad,
there's a ham and zucchini terrine.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have a pate or terrine in the picnic basket, throw in
some crusty bread or round crackers, your favorite cheese and fruit
and maybe a cold summer soup. Add a bottle of dry rose or other
good picnic wine, and you've got the makings for a perfect outing.
Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constituion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
