<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECIPE EXCHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And from Mrs. Fields: Marlyse Lysa Bohon of Mansfield, Texas,
copied ``a wonderful recipe for a very fruity banana cake'' while
watching a Debbi Fields cooking show about a year ago. And of
course, now the recipe has gone missing. Here it is, from ``Mrs.
Fields I Love Chocolate! Cookbook'' (TimeLife, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE CHIP BANANA BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Yields 2 9-inch loaves
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 sticks (3/4 cup) unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups mashed bananas (about 8)
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs, well-beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mini semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Lightly butter two 9-by-5-inch loaf
pans. Line bottoms with buttered parchment or wax paper.
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, whisk together flour, baking powder and salt.
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, cream butter and sugar. Add bananas and eggs,
beating until well-blended. Beat in vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Add dry ingredients to banana mixture and blend well. Stir in
chocolate chips. Don't overmix.
</P>
<P>
   Pour batter into prepared pans and bake for 55 to 60 minutes or
until golden brown and a cake tester inserted in center comes out
clean. Set pans on a rack to cool for 15 minutes. Then turn out of
pans to cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per slice (each loaf cut into 12 slices):
250 calories, 10 grams fat, 39 grams carbohydrates, 4 grams
protein, 68 milligrams cholesterol, 172 milligrams sodium, 35
percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking for cash: The 50th anniversary of the Pillsbury Bake-Off
is scheduled for Feb. 26-29 in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   All four categories of the cook-off specify quick recipes,
usually with time limits on preparation. The Easy Weeknight Meals
category, for instance, requires that the recipe be prepared and
assembled in 15 minutes or less (not including cooking time) or
that the recipe be prepared completely in 30 minutes or less. And,
as always, entered recipes must use one or more products from a
list of Pillsbury, Hungry Jack, Green Giant, Progresso and Old El
Paso products.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, indeed, the grand prize winner gets a check for $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   The rules and entry forms are available by calling (800)
306-1111 through Sept. 30 or by checking the Bake-Off Web site at
www.bakeoff.com.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the updated recipe for the most-famous bake-off recipe
from 1966. (And it didn't even win the grand prize.)
</P>
<P>
   TUNNEL OF FUDGE CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 16
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   3.4-ounce package chocolate fudge pudding and pie filling mix
(not instant)
</P>
<P>
   6-ounce package chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Cake:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Glaze:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 teaspoons milk
</P>
<P>
   Filling: In a medium saucepan, combine 1 1/2 cups milk and
pudding mix. Cook as directed on package. Add chocolate chips; stir
until melted. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cake: Heat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour a 12-cup bundt
pan. In a large bowl, combine sugar, butter and shortening; beat
well until light and fluffy. Add vanilla and eggs; mix well.
Lightly spoon flour into measuring cup; level off. Add flour, 1/2
cup cocoa, baking powder, salt and milk to creamed mixture; beat at
low speed until moistened. Beat 3 minutes at medium speed. Stir in
walnuts. Reserve 2 cups of the batter. Pour remaining batter into
prepared pan. Spoon filling in ring on top of batter, making sure
it does not touch the sides of the pan. Spoon reserved batter over
filling. Bake for 50 to 60 minutes or until cake springs back when
touched lightly in center. Cool 1 hour. Remove from pan. Cool 1 1/2
more hours or until completely cooled.
</P>
<P>
   Glaze: In a small bowl, blend ingredients, adding enough milk
for desired drizzling consistency. Spoon over cake, allowing some
to run down the sides. Cut with a serrated knife. Best served the
same day; store remaining cake in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 570 calories, 30 grams fat, 68
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 80 milligrams cholesterol,
230 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
