u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      05-19 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN QUESTION &AMP; ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zucchini Blues
</P>
<P>
   Q. ``Last year, we had zucchini that had some kind of mushy rot
at the base of the plant on some stems. It didn't seem to interfere
too much with fruit production, but I'm wondering what caused it. I
looked for bug burrowing and didn't find any.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reader wrote: ``Last year, I had four zucchini plants in
my yard, each in a different location (one in a large tub). They
each yielded five to seven very large and delicious fruit. I
overcame a bout with slugs early in the season, but later my plants
all wilted and died. They received plenty of sun and water. My more
experienced gardening neighbor noticed that the main stems near the
soil were rotted. The fruit-bearing period lasted only about three
weeks. How can I prevent the same thing from happening this year?''
 &QL; 
A. These zucchinis, and many others every year, are the victims of
squash vine borer. The borer is actually the larva of a moth, which
attacks squash, cucumber and muskmelon and does exactly what its
name suggests. The adult moths have metallic-green wings one to one
and a half inches across and look more like a wasp than a moth. The
female glues an egg near the base of the stem, and once hatched,
the white and brown larva, which can grow to an inch long, eat its
way inside and upward until the plant simply collapses.
</P>
<P>
   If you are going to rush your zucchini seedlings into the garden
in a race to make that first zucchini bread, squash vine borers are
a menace. Sometimes, they can be prevented by loosely wrapping the
lower six inches of stem with aluminum foil. Or if a close look
reveals yellowish grains of fecal matter on the ground, or if a
shiny ooze is coming from an entry hole, you can use a razor blade
or sharp knife to slit the stem upward until you find the larva.
Remove and kill the larva, then bend the stem down and bury it so
that all the cut portion is below ground; new roots may develop,
and the plant may continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   But the best defense is to sidestep squash vine borers
altogether by starting seeds later, so that you are not
transplanting into the garden until after July 1. By then, the
adult moth has laid her eggs elsewhere, possibly in your neighbor's
garden. With the summer heat in full swing, your seedlings will
produce enough fruit to cover his unfortunate losses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twinkling Trees
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our apartment building has a lovely and spacious garden. The
pool terrace and a restaurant overlook it. The restaurant used to
have tiny clear lights on the trunks and lower limbs of four of the
large trees near the windows. Our landscape architect told the
management that the lights would kill or at least stunt the trees'
growth. How can this be? The Henry Villard Houses use many more
lights; Tavern on the Green uses them as well. The restaurant had
to take the lights down. The manager said he would like to put the
twinkle lights back. Is the landscape architect right?
</P>
<P>
   A. While I'm not a big fan of lights in trees, twinkle or
otherwise, they do not affect a tree's growth as long as they are
not wrapped too tightly. Unlike poinsettia, kalanchoe, Christmas
cactus and chrysanthemum, which require a certain number of hours
of total darkness to start flowering, trees are not photosensitive
to the level of light from even the gaudiest display. It's easy to
forget, however, that the wire connecting the lights will not
stretch as the tree's trunk and limbs grow thicker. Left unchecked,
wrapped areas can become girdled, which can certainly damage or
even kill them. Twinkle lights may not be part of the landscape
architect's grand vision for the garden, but if you can convince
him to bring back the lights, be sure that the wires are loosely
wrapped and checked every year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York 10036, or by e-mail to
gardening(AT)nytimes.com. Those of general interest will be
published. Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
