<HEADER>
A3282 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HYDROS-HANAUER-SPI &LR;      05-19 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYDROS-HANAUER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANAUER BACK IN HYDROPLANE COCKPIT JUST `FOR JOY OF IT'  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chip Hanauer doesn't need the paycheck, doesn't crave the
limelight and, with 58 career wins and seven unlimited hydroplane
national championships, doesn't have anything left to prove
professionally.
</P>
<P>
   So why is one of Seattle's most beloved sports figures returning
to the hydroplane circuit after a three-year absence?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just too good an opportunity to pass up,'' said
Hanauer, 44, who retired one race into the 1995 season after a bad
crash in Detroit. ``I wasn't looking to come back and in fact was
really enjoying not coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``So why now? For the joy of it. Now I'm doing it for the same
reason I started racing, I'm doing it just because I love doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Hanauer wavered on the invitation to join Fred
Leland's Miss Pico team. After a visit with Larry Wisne, who owns
the team's corporate sponsor Progressive Tool and Industries,
Hanauer was swayed to come aboard. But not until certain conditions
were met and commitments made.
</P>
<P>
   Firstly, Hanauer insisted on a one-boat team, not the multiboat
operation the team had previously tried. Secondly, even though
Hanauer is financially secure, he wanted to be paid on par with an
Indy car or NASCAR driver.
</P>
<P>
   A change in leadership atop the Unlimited Hydroplane Racing
Association was also a major deciding factor. Bob Gobrecht has
replaced Bill Donner as president and CEO of the sanctioning body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people there now are good, ethical and honest,'' said
Hanauer, who will compete in this week's season opener at Lake
Havasu, Ariz. ``They are making sacrifices for the good of the
sport, not taking from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the particulars of Hanauer's return. But make no
mistake, it's the big picture that truly motivates Hanauer. Racing
will be an element of his life now. It is no longer his entire
life.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when you endure a life test as Hanauer has.
</P>
<P>
   Three years before Hanauer's retirement from hydros, he noticed
a problem with his voice. When he talked it had a kind of raspy
tone _ as if he had just awakened. The condition degenerated to the
point in 1995 where Hanauer would physically strain himself trying
to utter words. He visited a dozen doctors around the Seattle area
who found no apparent physical explanation for the problem, causing
Hanauer to doubt himself and wonder if it really was all in his
head. It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The week Hanauer decided to retire from racing _ no longer
willing to chance serious injury in yet another crash _ he was
diagnosed with a form of dystonia, a neuro-motor disability that
interfered with the brain's signal to the voice.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor at New York's Mount Sinai Hospital finally had
delivered Hanauer an answer. No one wants to be diagnosed with a
serious medical condition, but at least now Hanauer had peace of
mind and a plan of action.
</P>
<P>
   Hanauer calls the frustrating ordeal the ``the darkest time'' in
his adult life. He said he felt dangerously close to an emotional
breakdown and reacted by isolating himself. There were days when he
would run errands and then come home, lie down on his couch and
sob.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had became very depressed because I couldn't figure out what
was happening,'' Hanauer said. ``I have spent the last three years
getting control of my health and the disease and learning to live
with it and manage it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a much greater appreciation for life now. In the grand
scheme of things, I'm glad I went through this. You take nothing
for granted anymore. I'm a much happier person now, much
easier-going.''
</P>
<P>
   In the three years since Hanauer began treatment for the
dystonia _ a series of injections four times a year _ he's learned
to play the guitar, climbed Mount Rainier, adopted a dog from the
Humane Society, traveled the world, read lots of books and made it
a point to watch the sun rise each morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've reinvented myself. People that knew me before,
then through the diagnosis and now see how happy I am, they worry
what racing will do,'' he said. ``And I needed to hear that
opinion, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in Hanauer's case, time away from racing was a
sabbatical, not a retirement. It allowed him time for a
self-assessment that has resulted in a complete change of mind-set.
Racing no longer represents a need for validation.
</P>
<P>
   He clearly still has that competitive drive. But he doesn't have
the greed, the obsession, the ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself I'd never live more lavishly than what I could
afford when I was teaching school right out of college,'' said
Hanauer, who lives in a two-bedroom house on a corner lot once
owned by his grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Buffett's latest novel, a ``A Pirate Looks at Fifty,''
sits on the coffee table amid several racing magazines. Three
acoustic guitars are lined up neatly along one wall. A small couch
and a stereo are the only other pieces of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   All these value adjustments, however, are not to say Hanauer
will be any less driven when he straps himself in the Miss Pico.
And his return is eagerly awaited by those participating in the
series. He is only four victories shy of the late Bill Muncey's
all-time win record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chip coming back, which is very good for the sport, will bring
a lot of attention and competition,'' said Miss Budweiser driver
Dave Villwock, the defending series champion.
</P>
<P>
   Villwock and Hanauer's former team, the big-budget Miss Bud
operation, will again be favored in the series. But truth be known,
Hanauer welcomes the challenging circumstances of his return on
Lake Havasu, Ariz., this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Miss Pico is coming off a subpar 1998 season _ a year so
disappointing the team even opted not to compete in the season
finale. The team's rebuilding project is more like a major
restoration, but Hanauer likes the renewed committment.
</P>
<P>
   It kind of parallels his own life.
</P>
<P>
   He said he already feels comfortable with the Miss Pico and
that's something he can't say about his experiences with the Miss
Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crew may not be as experienced or highly paid as those at
the Miss Bud, but if we fail now it will be technically _ not for a
lack of motivation, and maybe I need that to keep my own passions
up,'' Hanauer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a lot of fun when I was racing there (Miss Bud).
It just wasn't comfortable. When you're winning as much as we were
winning and still not having fun ... well, that tells you
something.''
</P>
<P>
   So while so many of the greats in other sports are stepping
aside, unlimited hydroplane racing is welcoming back _ with very
open arms _ one of its legends.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't win another race, I've still had a great career,''
Hanauer said. ``This is a whole new approach, it's kind of a grand
experiment. Some would say I have nothing to gain by doing this. I
look at it like I've got nothing to lose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
