<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROCCOLINI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENY BROCCOLINI HAS A BIG NEW TASTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a new kid in the produce section of the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   The name of this baby broccoli is broccolini, and it's being
marketed by Mann Packaging of Salinas, Calif. A hybrid of broccoli
and Chinese kale, the vegetable has a sweet yet more peppery flavor
than its treelike cousin. And expect to pay prices closer to those
for asparagus for this new boutique vegetable. The company says the
higher cost results from the intensive labor required to pick the
product. We suspect it may also have something to do with the
novelty factor.
</P>
<P>
   BROCCOLINI AU GRATIN
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch broccolini
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Dash of cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 egg white, beaten
</P>
<P>
   Paprika
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Spray a shallow 1 1/2-quart baking dish with nonstick cooking
spray. Arrange broccolini in even layer. In medium bowl, mix
together mayonnaise, Parmesan, lemon, cayenne and garlic; fold in
egg white. Spoon mixture over broccolini and sprinkle with paprika.
Bake until topping is puffed and lightly browned and broccolini is
crisp-tender when pierced with tip of sharp knife, 15-20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 166 calories, 16 grams fat, 3
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 14 milligrams cholesterol,
187 milligrams sodium, 85 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BROCCOLINI WITH CARIBBEAN CHILE LIME DIP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch broccolini
</P>
<P>
   Dip: Yields 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup pureed fresh peaches, mangoes or bottled mango slices
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons mango chutney, chopped finely
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped mild red chiles
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped seeded serrano chiles
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Drop broccolini into saucepan of boiling water; drain after 1
minute. Rinse with cold water. Chill if preparing ahead. Combine
all remaining ingredients for dip. Chill until needed and serve
with whole broccolini.
</P>
<P>
   To microwave: Line 1/2 pound broccolini in single layer in
rectangular microwave-safe dish. Add 1 cup water. Cover and
microwave at high power for 3 minutes or until tender-crisp. For 1
pound of broccolini, allow 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 56 calories, trace fat, 12
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 91 milligrams
sodium, 3 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LINGUINE BROCCOLINI
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches broccolini
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mini cherry tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   9 ounces fresh linguine, cut into thirds
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups fresh basil leaves (4 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coarsely grated Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   Drop broccolini into a saucepan of boiling water. After 3
minutes, drain.
</P>
<P>
   Drop linguine into saucepan of boiling water. Return to boil and
cook 1 minute. Drain and toss with a little vegetable oil. For
sauce, melt butter. Whisk in flour and cook until bubbly. Whisk in
wine and half-and-half and cook, stirring, until thickened. This
much may be made ahead. When ready to serve, heat sauce to a boil
in large kettle. Add tomatoes and basil and cook 1 1/2 minutes or
until limp. Add linguine and broccolini and heat, stirring with
large spoon, until hot. Add cheese, heat through and season with
salt and pepper to taste. Serve at once with additional cheese
and/or ground black pepper on top, if you like.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 859 calories, 53 grams fat, 68
grams carbohydrates, 25 grams protein, 49 milligrams cholesterol,
917 milligrams sodium, 55 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
