<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3301 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-FUTURE-0520-     05-19 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FUTURE-0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FCC: AOL-CABLE DEAL COULD SKIRT NEED FOR REGULATION
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- America Online, the nation's largest Internet
service company, could attain a high-speed conduit to consumers by
investing in the cable industry, Federal Communications Chairman
William Kennard suggested Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real feasibility,'' Kennard said, given America
Online's deep financial pockets. ``I've probably been more candid
than I should have been,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But America Online Chairman Steve Case, appearing with Kennard
at a congressional technology forum, said he knew of a better way
that a reluctant FCC could avoid re-regulating cable companies:
Force AT&AMP;T to open its high-speed, high-volume pipeline to America
Online and other Internet providers as a condition for approving
the telephone giant's pending merger with MediaOne Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not for regulating the Internet,'' Case said. ``But we
need to have some kind of light touch'' so access to high-speed
lines are not closed to companies like America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites offering complex graphics, audio and video content
require substantially faster transmission speeds than are possible
on modems hooked to ordinary telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief gatekeepers for high-speed service, Milo Medin,
founder and chief technology officer of cable partner At Home, said
America Online would be welcome as partner as well -- ``if it were
willing to hand over 75 percent of its equity.'' A host of such
cable firms, including Cox Communications, invested in the At Home
startup venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to fly,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   Medin said the At Home venture, now in its fourth year, has
motivated telephone companies to offer competitive high-speed
services to consumers in the form of digital subscriber lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without cable, you wouldn't see this kind of innovation,''
Medin said.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of rights that America Online seeks, Medin argued,
would ``unhinge the investment community'' and stifle innovation.
</P>
<P>
   At Home currently has some 500,000 broadband customers out of a
potential pool of 15 million cable-equipped homes in its reach.
</P>
<P>
   Taking yet another tack, F. Duane Ackerman, chief executive of
BellSouth, said when it comes to bringing high-speed Internet
access to consumers, too much regulation of regional telephone
networks poses a much bigger problem than any potential reassembly
of AT&AMP;T's once dominant system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not as concerned about what AT&AMP;T can do as I am about
what BellSouth can't do,'' Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the unregulated cable side,'' Ackerman noted, ``the course
for deployment is clear. A cable company can invest its money,
invent the technology, develop new products and services and serve
its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the phone side, the course is unclear. If we invest in
data, will we be required to unbundle elements and sell them at a
discount so our competitors can resell them without having to make
the investment? Will we have to establish a costly separate
subsidiary for data?''
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman noted that Atlanta-based BellSouth is already reselling
its broadband technology to other Internet provides, such as
Atlanta's MindSpring Enterprises, on a comparable basis to its own
internal costs.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Enterprises publishes the Atlanta Journal-Constitution and
holds controlling interest in Cox Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
