<HEADER>
A3312 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VACATIONBOOM-TEX     05-19 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VACATIONBOOM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS PLANNING MORE TRIPS DESPITE PRICE INCREASES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KATHRYN HOPPER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pack your bags. Everyone else is.
</P>
<P>
   This summer figures to be one of the busiest travel seasons
ever. Industry forecasts are predicting that more Americans will
hit the road than ever before despite increases in airline, car
rental and hotel prices.
</P>
<P>
   Vacationers plan to take 271 million trips at least 100 miles
from their homes this summer, a 4 percent increase from last year,
the Travel Industry Association of America said last week in its
annual forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business has been booming,'' said Jim Ervin, Fort Worth
regional manager of AAA Travel Agency. ``I'm kind of surprised. We
just had our biggest April ever.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to figure what's fueling the robust tourist
economy: low inflation and high consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But Ervin said millennium madness might also be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word in the industry is that next year will be even
busier, because it's the year 2000 and more people will want to do
something special,'' Ervin said. ``So some people are going ahead
and traveling this year to avoid the crowds next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Memorial Day weekend traditionally launches the summer
vacation season. This year, AAA and the travel association expect a
record 33.3 million Americans to travel during that holiday, which
would be a 4 percent increase over last year.
</P>
<P>
   PRICES ARE UP: With so many travelers out, it might be more
difficult to find good deals. Airlines expect to fill more than 80
percent of all seats this summer, said Tom Parsons, founder of the
Arlington-based Bestfares.com magazine and its Internet site,
www.bestfares.com, which track travel deals.
</P>
<P>
   Rising jet fuel prices are also likely to lead to higher air
fares, but 13 percent of Americans still plan to travel by air this
summer. That's a 3 percent increase over last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines are going to be very stingy on the cheap fares,
particularly to the West Coast,'' Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, rental car rates are rising. According to Abrams
Travel Data Services in Long Beach, Calif., rental car rates rose 5
percent last year and will jump 2 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel prices are also generally up compared with last year, but
some markets where hotel construction has outpaced demand might
offer bargains. Industry experts say Las Vegas and Orlando, Fla.,
have some of the best deals.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices have risen slightly nationwide in recent weeks,
but the Southwest has enjoyed a slight dip, according to AAA
reports. The average price of self-service, midgrade unleaded fuel
in the region fell by 0.6 cent since April to $1.17 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD DEALS STILL AVAILABLE: Despite rising prices, savvy
travelers can still find good deals. Parsons figures that the
airlines will turn to the Internet for last-minute sales to fill up
leftover seats.
</P>
<P>
   Most major airlines post weekend fare specials on an Internet
site or via e-mail. This year, airlines have broadened the deals to
include 10-day advance fares and some vacation packages.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the major carriers launched a Memorial Day sale
featuring round-trip fares as low as $58, Bestfares.com said. The
lowest fares are available for departure May 29 and return May 30,
but travellers can pay higher fares for May 28 departure and May 31
return. The sale requires a three-day advance purchase requirement.
Examples of round trips from Dallas/Fort Worth: $178 to Washington,
D.C. and $138 to Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons says other travel deals are out there but take time to
research. He suggests finding lodging specials by cruising Sunday
newspapers. Hotels also often advertise specials in cities where
they draw a lot of weekend tourists. For example, San Diego hotels
publicize special deals in Los Angeles newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth going to the local bookstore and reading the Travel
section for deals,'' Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggests looking into the airline package deals offered
to popular resorts. It's not unusual to find package deals for less
than the lowest round-trip air fare. That happened recently, he
said, in a Hawaii package that includes air fare and hotel for $600
_ $280 less than the lowest available air fare of $880.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be the best hotel, but who cares if you save more
than $200 on the air fare?'' Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas/Fort Worth fares to the West Coast are high because
there's not much competition. American and Delta, for example, are
the only carriers to Portland, Ore., from Dallas/Fort Worth
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   But Parsons suggests flying to Long Beach, Calif., instead of
Los Angeles. He notes that 21-day advance-purchase fares to Long
Beach have been running $318 round trip, vs. $465 to Los Angeles
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons said Dallas/Fort Worth air fares to the East Coast and
Florida are good, as low as $160 round trip to Orlando and $190 to
Boston, because of competition from smaller carriers. Additionally,
European fares are running 25 percent less than last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the troubles in Asia, a lot of carriers have
shifted more flights to Europe,'' Parson said. ``London will be a
good deal all summer long.''
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in Kosovo doesn't appear to be deterring European
travel. Ervin said he has had strong bookings to Europe,
particularly the United Kingdom, Ireland, the Netherlands and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Florida continues to be Americans' top vacation state, followed
by California, Hawaii, Colorado and Texas. New York, Nevada,
Arizona, Washington state and the District of Columbia were the
other top 10 destination states, according to the travel
association, which represents more than 2,000 travel-related
organizations, including tourism offices, visitor bureaus, hotels,
airlines and cruise companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is hot,'' said Parsons, who is doing Disney himself
next month. ``Everybody is offering low fares to Florida, so
everybody's going.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
