</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-BONES (Cambridge, Mass) _ After 70 years of study, the
bones of nearly 2,000 American Indians have been returned to their
descendants for burial in New Mexico. Harvard University handed
over the remains in the largest and perhaps most scientifically
significant transfer under a 1990 federal law that requires the
return of Indian artifacts. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3319 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-PRESCHOOL-ART-2TA     05-19 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PRESCHOOL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPING CHILDREN NAVIGATE THEIR WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MARGOT SLADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Educators think of them as social skills and generally try to
build them into what they call the ``early childhood learning
experience.'' Parents think of them collectively _ if at all _ as
the ability to get along with others.
</P>
<P>
   Such issues are generally confronted on a crisis-management
basis: dealing with the playground bully, with being the new
student in school, with sharing, intolerance, an argument with a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   The computer seems to figure into neither calculation. Since you
can't be social with a machine, it seems odd to build social skills
by using one. But in fact, the computer is a good tool for
youngsters to try out and try on a range of responses to real-world
social situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer is nonthreatening,'' said Arthur Pober, an
educational psychologist and child and family counselor who is
executive director of the Entertainment Software Rating Board. ``It
is not another child on the block who can physically confront your
kid. It is not a parental figure, who mandates certain conduct. It
can be neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the right kind of software, the computer can present
scenarios and characters that allow children to place themselves in
a predicament and then experiment with what might be appropriate
responses. But of course they will not actually experience the
consequences of even the most outrageous behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Educators and psychologists note that in social skills software,
parents are essentially looking for story-telling programs with a
twist: the program should provide at least two or three
opportunities for children to choose among different courses of
action and to see how those choices play out for themselves and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Children delight in being able to rewrite the scripts, trying on
different behaviors for feel, as was discovered by four youngsters
who tested the programs reviewed here.
</P>
<P>
   The most appropriate programs should identify the kinds of
situations children are experiencing or are most likely to
experience: making new friends, for example, adjusting to a new
sibling, resolving a playground conflict.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, the packaging should indicate the social skills
that the software explores; at most, it will outline the actual
scenarios used. Check the visuals, too: settings should be
attractive, while characters should look inviting.
</P>
<P>
   The language should be appropriate for a child's age.
Alternatives should be presented in written words, spoken words and
illustrations. Many programs on the market _ and all the products
reviewed here _ offer children the opportunity to have their
stories read back.
</P>
<P>
   The best software provides support material for parents:
suggestions for exploring the scenario, with and without the
computer, and the consequences of decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is that parents can act as their children's
counselors,'' Pober said, ``which in these sticky situations is
precisely what they are supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ROBERTO JOINS IN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sanctuary Woods/Theatrix; $22.49; Windows 3.1 and later, and
Macintosh 7.0; ages 3 to 6.)
</P>
<P>
   Think of Roberto, a hippo, as the stealth bomber of the social
skills set. The power and effectiveness of his story _ and of this
educational package as a whole _ sneaks up on you.
</P>
<P>
   The ``you'' in this case is, of course, grown-ups. Children who
tried this product appreciated its realism immediately. Its appeal
starts with a familiar story line told by a wise old goat
(literally). Roberto wants to join a game of hippoball, but the
other hippos in the pond tell him there is no room. So he must
consider strategies for getting into the game.
</P>
<P>
   His alternatives are presented in three ``thought balloons'' at
a time, with each balloon's option written, illustrated and voiced
aloud. And after the conventional ``Ask nicely,'' what intriguing
options they are, from pretending to cry so that the others will
feel sorry, to behaviors that parents might discourage, like
handing out popsicles as bribes, or getting angry and kicking a
tree.
</P>
<P>
   What may surprise adults is what does and doesn't work. Saying
``Please'' _ a grown-up's cure-all _ gets Roberto nowhere.
Pretending to cry drives the other hippos away. Handing out
popsicles or entertaining everyone with his one-hippo band earns
him merely a thank you and applause.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, getting the attention of would-be playmates by
grabbing the ball and deftly hitting it back wins Roberto an
invitation to join a hippoball team. So does outright deal-making
(answer my riddle or let me in) and performing a magic trick in
which Roberto cleverly lands himself in the pond.
</P>
<P>
   The software has got it right. Among children, saying ``Please''
doesn't work; it never did. Nor does acting the crybaby. Kicking a
tree only hurts your toe. But proving that you can be an asset to
the team or can contribute to a fun afternoon is a promising ploy.
So is opting out by playing with another friend. Invited into the
pool, Roberto politely declines, saying, ``I'm having too much
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The program's appeal for adults, and its value for children,
doesn't end there. The instruction manual shows parents how to help
their children explore their choices at the computer. What a shame
that neither the manual nor the box touts the Parents Guide.
</P>
<P>
   In easy-to-access computerized form, it provides explanations of
children's emotional development along with the nature and extent
of their problem-solving, decision-making, planning, prediction and
evaluation of outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   Here parents will find ``When the Computer's Off'' activities,
including daily routines in which children can exercise options and
parents can discuss outcomes (like choosing to wear light clothes
on a cold day). Parents and children can also use the software to
print the makings of masks and hand puppets and cards picturing
Roberto expressing his feelings _ the basis of other social
scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roberto Joins In'' offers other computer-based activities.
Youngsters can play hippoball or sing and dance with Roberto,
selecting among musical styles and instrument. But these are
peripheral to learning social skills, and while several 5-year-olds
found them to be initially entertaining, they judged them
ultimately boring.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTAIN KANGAROO: LIFE'S FIRST LESSONS, ADVENTURE No. 2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Knowledge Adventure; $19.99; Windows 3.1 and later, and
Macintosh 7.5.1; ages 3 to 5.)
</P>
<P>
   All right, so the allure of this product rests primarily with
its cast of characters. Many adults will wistfully recall a youth
spent watching the Captain, played by Bob Keeshan, and his crew.
Many children will know them from the current animated feature.
</P>
<P>
   But the packaging does little to signal that there is a
well-thought-out social skills program here. Instead, it emphasizes
how Captain Kangaroo will help children plan a birthday party for
either Moose or Bunny Rabbit, complete with balloons, streamers and
candles that can be blown out with the judicious click and release
of the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are other cute, if pointless, doodads in this nicely
animated program. But the heart of the matter is the Storybook
Corner, which offers several stories and ample opportunities to opt
for different courses of action; the Say Please, Please game, a
kind of Simon Says in which listening for ``please'' is central to
winning, and the Finish-My-Rhyme Board Game, where landing on a
clock card means finishing one of Grandfather Clock's rhymes _
invariably a poem about sharing, caring or being friends.
</P>
<P>
   The story-building component offers enough scenarios to keep
even adults busy trying out different responses. ``Trouble in the
Treasure House,'' for example, offers a choice between Bunny and
Joey being upset with each other and someone throwing a baseball
and breaking a window. In ``A Garden Story,'' helping Greenjeans
involves not following directions.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the Storybook Corner can backtrack to change a
decision. And although the results are often predictable, this is a
program for younger children (what is predictable for grown-ups is
novel to young children) and there are some surprises: when Bunny
picks all the carrots in Greenjeans' garden, children may learn,
for example, that he would have to work hard planting a new garden
the next day, or that it took him three days to cook and can all
that he picked. Such inventive problem-solving should inspire
parents and children to brainstorm responses to real events.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Kangaroo's Parent Tips appear on screen as carefully
labeled books on a shelf. ``Help, My Child Has Bad Manners'' is
brief and generally unremarkable _ until you come to the
recommendation that adults provide time and space for children to
``play, exercise, move around freely and make some noise'' _
recognition, perhaps, that good manners often means restraining
children's talk and movement. There is also the worthwhile reminder
that children are not perfect and that adults should not belittle
them.
</P>
<P>
   Other tips include suggestions for parent participation at the
computer and questions to put to children as they play: Did they
choose as a gift, for example, what they wanted or what they
thought Bunny or Moose would like? You get the point.
</P>
<P>
   This product offers a rich selection of parent-child activities
``Away From the Computer.'' My favorite is Everything in Its Place,
in which players cut out images from magazines and newspapers, then
draw a house on a piece of paper and practice putting things away.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring how easy it is to find things when they are put
back in an orderly manner, children are asked to find certain
objects. Now, if this lesson only worked in real life. ...
</P>
<P>
   CHOICES, CHOICES: ON THE PLAYGROUND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tom Snyder Productions; $99.95 classroom version; Windows 3.1
and later, and Macintosh 7.1; kindergarten through fourth grade.)
</P>
<P>
   It's a pity that this product is geared to classrooms and not to
individuals or adult-child combinations. Adults could also benefit
from the critical thinking process on which it is based: understand
your situation, set goals, talk about your options, make a choice,
think about the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the quality of the exercise, parents and teachers
should consider the Choices, Choices series of programs for their
schools. (On the Playground can be purchased at www.teachtsp.com or
by calling 800-342-0236.)
</P>
<P>
   The playground issue presented here seems simple: It's morning
recess and you and your friends have been planning to play a very
special game. You notice a youngster who is new to the school
watching longingly. With a head shaped like a triangle, he looks
and talks differently from everyone else. Should you invite him to
play? What will your friends think? Recess lasts only 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Children's voices are used to act out the simulation, giving it
a realistic air despite illustrations that are comic-strip-like and
static. There are opportunities for cooperative learning and for
discussing and ranking four goals: stay out of trouble, help the
new kid, stay close with your friends and have fun during recess.
</P>
<P>
   Completing the simulation requires working through a series of
decisions, choosing among three options at a time, and discussing
outcomes at length through the use of Consequence Cards. On one
side, each card wordlessly depicts a possible consequence of each
option. On the back are questions to help students think about what
they see.
</P>
<P>
   The simulation is wonderfully textured; no solution is
one-size-fits-all. Indeed, the same choices won't always yield the
same result. Like life, this program offers hard-won learning
experiences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
