<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER DESIGNED FOR GRANNY OFFERS A FRIENDLY INTERFACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By SHELLY FREIERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who is the person in the family who hasn't learned how to use
the computer either by writing notes at work or playing games after
school? It's grandma or grandpa, of course. But the computer
industry is turning its attention to this group of potential users.
</P>
<P>
   Hauser, a product development consulting company, says it has
come up with a way to make computers more accessible to older new
users, through a prototype design it calls a ``Generationally
Relevant Appliance for the Non-technical New user and a Yardstick
for the future,'' which, one suspects, was contrived to make
possible the tidy acronym, Granny.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a friendly face to design for,'' said Ron Pierce, a
vice president who is in charge of product development. ``There's
no friendlier face than granny.''
</P>
<P>
   The prototype by Hauser comes in a box made with warm colors and
a flat-screen monitor, but its main change would be in the
interface and controls. The interface would leave behind the
desktop environment, with its folders, mailbox, trash can and deck
of cards.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when users turned on the computer they would see a list
reminiscent of the pad next to the kitchen telephone: Birthdays,
Shopping List, Appointment Reminders and a To-Do List.
</P>
<P>
   The main part of the screen would have sections for topics like
Family, Medical, Services and Home. Selecting each of these
sections would call up more details, like, for example, a
subsection for each of grandma's three children and their children.
</P>
<P>
   The new computer would also move beyond the mouse and keyboard.
A remote control or voice recognition technology could be used to
make selections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things everyone knows how to use are the telephone and the
remote control,'' Pierce pointed out could be sent in handwritten
form.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a market for computers for older users? Ernie Stokes, a
retired computer programmer who teaches Windows, Microsoft Word and
using the Internet to people over 50 at the Sacramento Senior
Center in Sacramento, says yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a little practice to get students accustomed to the
icons and how to navigate between menus and submenus,'' he said.
Some users also have physical difficulties controlling the mouse,
Stokes added.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the concept behind GRANNY, explained Pierce, is that
when grandma or grandpa boots up for the first time, the computer
would ``interview'' them, asking about their ages, hobbies, where
they've lived and their family and friends. ``Then the computer
would configure the screen with the things that are meaningful for
the user,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other applications might include making it possible for an adult
child to put information into the computer from a remote location,
controlling the lights and heat in the house and even linking to
medical devices like a glucose reader for diabetics.
</P>
<P>
   The basic idea, though, is to hide all the power involved in
helping grandma and grandpa run their lives behind a simple screen.
Pierce compares the computer with home appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to develop it to the point where it doesn't require an
exorbitant amount of time to learn how to use _ no one has to learn
how to use a television or refrigerator.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
