</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS! CAMERA! KEYBOARD! 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Portable computers have come a long way since Compaq introduced
its inaugural model in 1982, an oblong, 28-pound suitcase with a
fold-down keyboard and 9-inch, black-and-white monitor.
</P>
<P>
   But as with all things electronic, portable computers have grown
to be something of a commodity. Manufacturers now are generally
able to differentiate their offerings only by choosing from among a
dozen or so variables that are available to all of them _ screen
sizes, processor speeds, memory, software and, of course, price.
</P>
<P>
   There are notebooks, or laptops; subnotebooks, and even smaller
companion computers meant to work as a desktop sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens when a company that comes from a different end
of the business has a look at this tried, true and even a bit tired
formula? You end up with the Sony Vaio Picturebook Computer, the
only portable I have ever encountered that might prompt a user to
brush his hair and check for shaving cuts before sitting down at
the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Sony, of course, is primarily a consumer electronics company. It
makes products people use to have fun. IBM, Dell and Compaq often
talk about how their computers will fit into your ``work station.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Sony's premiere products is the Playstation. And when you
first turn on the Picturebook, and the Vaio logo settles onto the
screen, the bywords it offers for this product line are
``creation,'' ``communication,'' ``entertainment.'' There's nothing
about ``increased productivity,'' a favored computer-industry sales
slogan.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only words that set this computer, which fits into the
subnotebook category, apart from its competitors. It's the little
eye that stares at you from atop the screen. It's a tiny digital
camera, built into the upper lip of the fold-down screen and lid.
It allows you to take digital pictures, store them instantly on
your hard drive and then paste them into a document or e-mail them
to a friend. Quick and easy. No fuss, no muss.
</P>
<P>
   When you're not taking a picture, the eye serves as a live video
camera, and the image is shown in a small window on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The little camera swivels 180 degrees so you can take pictures
of things in front of the computer or behind it. But if the eye is
pointed straight ahead, you'll see an image of yourself at work.
</P>
<P>
   This all by itself should sew up the market among narcissists
and megalomaniacs. And a woman on a long airline flight who wants
to fix her makeup before landing without waiting in the long
lavatory line can plop the Picturebook onto the tray table and
apply mascara live on camera. (Of course, a mirror would work,
too.)
</P>
<P>
   A timer function allows you to set the computer to take pictures
unattended, at a predetermined time. That brings to mind a variety
of possible nefarious applications. But surely there must be more
important uses.
</P>
<P>
   Evaluating this computer in the office one day, it attracted
scads of attention.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wanted to have a look. But after the initial
enthusiastic exclamations, the question everyone asked was, Who
needs it?
</P>
<P>
   Sony offers several example applications:
</P>
<P>
   You're at the hospital with your wife, who is having your first
child. As soon as the baby is born, you snap a digital picture and
e-mail it to your mother.
</P>
<P>
   You're an interior designer, and you visit a job site. You take
some digital pictures of the rooms and paste them into your sales
proposal, prepared right there in the Picturebook.
</P>
<P>
   You are a real-estate appraiser required to use photographs as
part of your evaluation of a home. Take the pictures, visit the Web
site where comparable sales are listed and then write the appraisal
_ all with the Picturebook.
</P>
<P>
   The camera is quite easy to use. There's a button just above the
keyboard labeled ``capture.'' Press it once, and the camera turns
on, throwing the live-action video image onto the screen. Punch the
capture button again, and the camera snaps a still picture _ or 60
seconds of live video.
</P>
<P>
   Sony has programmed in a digital sound effect that simulates the
sound of a camera shutter, just to reassure you that the computer
really has taken the picture. (Somehow, the grinding noise the hard
drive makes as it stores the image doesn't do it.) The still
picture, or video clip, is then thrown up in a separate window, and
from there you have the option to save it or e-mail it.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is undeniably convenient, but ease of use usually
comes with a price.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the Picturebook's camera has a relatively low
resolution: 640 by 480 at best. Most stand-alone digital cameras
now offer at least twice that resolution, meaning the pictures are
that much clearer. At 640 by 480, a level of resolution not quite
as good as a regular television picture, no one would mistake one
of these digital prints for a conventional photograph made with
film. The digital print will be fuzzier.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, anchoring the camera to the computer body is
convenient in some circumstances but undeniably limiting in others.
If you're taking a photo of a room, or of yourself, the computer
camera is handy. But to shoot a specific object or person not so
conveniently anchored requires a fair bit of awkward juggling of
computer and object.
</P>
<P>
   I found with some experimentation that for many photos it's
simply easier to take the picture with a separate digital camera
and then slip the disk holding the image into the computer. In
those circumstances, the Picturebook offers few advantages over any
other laptop, except that it does come loaded with all sorts of
photo-editing and related software.
</P>
<P>
   The computer itself is less than half the size of a regular
laptop. It's only 9.25 inches wide and 1.5 inches high, and weighs
just 2.5 pounds, making it quite easy to carry around. But the
small, somewhat crowded keys make touch-typing awkward. And using
the function keys, whose surfaces are only three-eighths of an inch
deep, is a careful, deliberate exercise, even for one with
average-size hands.
</P>
<P>
   The computer's specifications are competent but underwhelming: a
266-megahertz Pentium I processor, 64 megabytes of memory,
4.3-gigabyte hard drive, 56K modem and an unusually wide, but still
small, active matrix screen _ 8.25 inches by 3.75 inches. An
outboard, plug-in floppy disk drive is included; an outboard CD-ROM
drive costs $300 extra. The basic computer sells for $2,300.
</P>
<P>
   Just scanning newspaper ads, I saw that for this price, you can
buy any one of several faster, more muscular notebooks, from IBM,
Dell or others, and still have enough money left over to buy quite
a nice digital camera _ even a Sony Mavica, which uses regular
floppy disks as the storage medium and offers double the resolution
of the Picturebook camera.
</P>
<P>
   But then, if you take those with you to the office, you won't
find an eager, curious audience gathering around your desk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1630EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
