<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSE-CHESTNUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE CHESTNUT TREES: SPRINGTIME'S GREATEST SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I was in one of those down-at-the-mouth moods one
morning last week as my cab tore down Fifth Avenue, when a
horse-chestnut tree hailed me from Central Park. Its pyramidal
white blooms, like giant vanilla cones, rose high above the other
trees, and I could swear some kind of cosmic wink passed between
us.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you have ever seen a horse chestnut _ Aesculus
hippocastanum _ in bloom, you know how impossible it is to ignore.
It stands on the greensward like some king in full regalia: velvet,
satin, jewels, scepter, the tall magnificent bearing. That is the
horse chestnut all over.
</P>
<P>
   And this one had just given me a swift kick in the pants to wake
up and smell the wisteria (which is blooming now all over the park)
before spring was gone and I was dead, not to get too metaphysical
about it.
</P>
<P>
   My cabby hung a right on 59th Street, and I glimpsed another
tree, its bare dark branches full of giant purple cones. What  &UR; was &LR; 
that thing? I'd seen it years ago at Winterthur in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Then I remembered. Paulownia tomentosa, the empress tree, a
scraggly thing that looks as if it were masquerading as wisteria
without any leaves. There's something slightly dopey about it. Like
some high school kid who says, ``Everybody else blooms with leaves
on, but I'm just going to put out these big flowers and think about
leaves later.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, I went around the park with Neil Calvanese,
the vice president of operations at the Central Park Conservancy,
who seems to know just about every plant in the park. And as I get
older, I like knowing the names of things and their habits: not
only when they bloom, but what their little fruits look like, how
to identify them from their bark. It's the comfort of the familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't recommend the horse chestnut as a street tree,''
Calvanese said, as we stood admiring one north of Cleopatra's
Needle, near 83rd Street. I had just wished, longingly, that our
city tree pits were large enough for such giant shade trees. ``The
fruit on it is very big,'' he was saying, ``and in the summer, it
gets blotch disease and drops its leaves. But in a park like this,
it's a great tree. It has bold leaves, bold flowers and it's a big,
open spreading tree.''
</P>
<P>
   He spread his arms out wide, as if he were the tree, 60 feet
tall, feeling all that space around his branches. We walked up
close to one of its huge white blossoms to peer at this intricate
piece of nature's engineering: a 10-inch pyramid of florets,
splotched with red and yellow dots, to tempt bees. These
flirtatious flowers rise like torches out of enormous palmate
leaves, each as big as a church fan. This tree understands the
power of the sacred and the profane. I had the uncanny vision of
hundreds of virgins proceeding down the aisle toward their
unvirginal fates. A sort of Aguirre ripple in a pastoral park.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one heck of a flower,'' Calvanese said.
</P>
<P>
   We went on to a silver linden tree just north of the Hamilton
statue, which stands behind the northwest corner of the
Metropolitan Museum. From a distance, this 60-foot tree, which is a
good 30 feet across, looks like a giant lollipop, because its
canopy is so rounded. And up close, its fresh green leaves have the
same oval shape. Underneath, the leaves have a silver-gray cast,
and hidden beneath each one hangs a little chandelier of three tiny
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hardly noticeable,'' Calvanese said, reaching up to
show one off. ``Before you see a linden tree in flower, you usually
smell it. To sit under this tree in bloom . . . '' His voice
trailed off. ``The honeybees love them.'' He pointed out a
wonderful pair of silver lindens on the eastern edge of the Great
Lawn, and behind them, a tall pair of turkey oaks, their elegant
branches cascading with fresh green leaves.
</P>
<P>
   And if you are wondering what those fuzzy, white
caterpillar-like flowers are, dangling from the graceful trees with
dark branches and shiny narrow leaves, they are black cherry
blossoms, soon to turn to cherries and to be ravaged by squirrels
and birds.
</P>
<P>
   As for the empress trees, there's a beauty blooming in the
southwest corner of the park, near the Columbus Circle entrance,
and another by Cherry Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lanky tree,'' Calvanese said, ``almost like an
ailanthus in its coarse texture. But the flowers are very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   I kept silent next to the master. But they look like footlong
cones of purple cotton candy, if you ask me. Maybe God made this
tree for kids. The flowers are just the color of wisteria, which
smells better, and grows wild all over the place. And from a
distance, it's easy to confuse the two.
</P>
<P>
   But wisteria blossoms hang down, from green leafy vines (go sit
under the wisteria arbors near Strawberry Fields), and empress-tree
flowers poke straight out from bare branches, with nary a leaf in
sight. Just last year's seedpods, or rattles, dangling down like
old party decorations. Maybe I'm missing something, but this tree
could use a makeover.
</P>
<P>
   There is another spectacular horse chestnut near the corner of
85th Street and Central Park West. If it's finished blooming when
you get there, make a note to catch it next spring, and go lie
under the linden trees. Or the English hawthorne trees, those pink
and white beauties lounging around with the willow trees by the
100th Street pool. Now where did this pool come from? In 20 years,
I'd never noticed it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1637EDT &QL; 
