<HEADER>
A3335 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-E3-GAMES-NYT &LR;      05-19 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-E3-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING SOON (MAYBE) TO A SCREEN NEAR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles is no stranger to action sequences and special
effects. But for three days in May, the Electronics Entertainment
Expo put on a light show that was extreme even for Hollywood. The
sprawling behemoth that is the Los Angeles Convention Center was
packed to the rafters with video games _ CD-ROMs, console games,
handheld games _ peripherals and accessories of all descriptions,
as well as thousands of software developers, publishers, retailers,
investors and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   In the promotional maelstrom, the Littleton, Colo., shootings
lingered as an undeniable subtext. Congress has put popular
entertainment in the political cross hairs, and publishers and
developers are understandably defensive about being misrepresented
_ of the 1,900 titles on the show floor, only a small fraction were
the first-person shooters that have put video games in the pillory.
</P>
<P>
   Video game developers are skeptical about the political process.
``The video game industry spends no money lobbying,'' said Howard
Lincoln, chairman of Nintendo of America. ``Hollywood and the gun
industry spend lots of money lobbying. So who gets attacked?''
</P>
<P>
   But behind closed doors, with a thin layer of particleboard
between themselves and the slings and arrows of public criticism,
the major players in this industry are seriously considering the
issue of violence and interactive entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a responsibility to ask the question,'' said Greg
Ballard, chief executive of 3Dfx Interactive, speaking in an
interview; his company's graphics accelerator cards smooth out the
animation in computer games like Doom and Quake. ``Everyone can
formulate a different answer. But we at least have to ask the
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, thousands of screens blazed with the most dazzling
digital media ever produced and the promise of a spectacular
millennial holiday season. Here are the highlights:
</P>
<P>
   NEW CONSOLES All of the big console companies have new boxes in
the pipeline. The furthest along is Sega's Dreamcast, which has
already been released in Japan and goes on sale this September for
$199. It promises a superior game-playing experience, along with a
modem and a Windows CE interface for Web surfing.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo announced that its next-generation machine would be
based on IBM's 400-megahertz Power PC chip running custom-designed
DVDs _ the cartridge era is officially over.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest news by far is Sony's new machine, the
Playstation 2, scheduled for release in the fall of 2000. Prompting
double- and triple-takes, the demonstration screen (housed in a
large, sparkling pyramid) inspired reverent, jaw-dropping awe. The
visual experience blows away anything you have seen on a PC (it's
closer to the computer graphics in ``Toy Story''). And the game
platform is backward compatible _ all the old Playstation games
will work. Hallelujah.
</P>
<P>
   BASS FISHING It seems that no publisher's holiday lineup is
complete without a bass fishing title: Bass Landing for the
Playstation (packaged with a rod-and-reel controller); Field and
Stream Trophy Bass 3D; Wal-Mart's FLW Tour Professional Bass
Tournament for the PC; Bassmasters 2000 and Bass Hunter 64, both
for the Nintendo machine, and Sega's Bass Fishing, a very
impressive title for the forthcoming Dreamcast console. ``Just
think of it as underwater combat,'' a bystander said. ``With
fish.''
</P>
<P>
   PLANK SPORTS If there is any trend to rival bass fishing for
popularity, it is skateboarding and snowboarding. Thrasher magazine
is lending its name to a skating game, Skate and Destroy. So is
Barbie _ Mattel's Super Sports fits America's favorite plastic
princess with a pair of in-line skates. And yes, she can fall down.
</P>
<P>
   Infogrames' Supreme Snowboarding renders extreme snow sports
with visual panache. (The publisher is based in France, so cheeky
spectators took to pronouncing the title Su-PREHM Sno-bor-DEENG.)
Acclaim's Trickstyle took a science fiction approach, leaving
phosphorescent light trails behind high-tech hoverboards. On the
Dreamcast, you can snowboard at night.
</P>
<P>
   DO-IT-YOURSELF DESIGN Continuing last year's trend of custom
design features, this year's games provide even more opportunities
to tweak the software or make up new material. For young children,
there's software like Fisher-Price's Magna Doodle, which lets you
animate your screen scrawls.
</P>
<P>
   For their teen-age siblings, Agetec's Fighter Maker allows the
player to design combat characters. Coordinate individual body
parts, choreograph full-body movements, cut and paste motion
sequences together, and voila, home-brewed fighting moves.
</P>
<P>
   TITLES FOR THE CASUAL GAMER Not everyone wants a 3-D spectacle
that takes 40 hours. Some people want simple games that take 15
minutes. As computing moves into the mainstream, the latter are in
the majority, and publishers are racing to sell simple mass-market
games for $19.99 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro leads the pack with digital versions of classic board
games as well as low-bandwidth online games (Scrabble, Battleship,
Grandmaster Chess) that send and receive moves via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSIC TV SHOWS The licensing fiesta continues. South Peak
Interactive has taken particularly aggressive cracks at the
television pinata, and all the vintage goodies are dropping out:
more Looney Tunes titles, followed by the Flintstones and Scooby
Doo. And yes, the rumors are true. There will be a Dukes of Hazzard
racing game.
</P>
<P>
   SHEEP At every Electronic Entertainment Expo, there is one title
that stands apart for sheer oddity, and this year it is Sheep,
developed by Mind's Eye in Britain and published by Empire
Interactive. The back story is that sheep were put here thousands
of years ago to observe life on Earth, but they forgot what they
were supposed to be doing and just stood around eating grass.
</P>
<P>
   Your mission is to herd them back to Mount Mouflon so they can
be picked up by the Mother Sheep and go home (Dolly meets ``Close
Encounters'').
</P>
<P>
   Game play consists of herding the sheep through 16 levels, from
Whoppy's ice-cream factory _ if you're not careful, the sheep will
be sucked into mixing equipment and emerge as sheepsicles _ to a
large, doomed ocean liner where you have to herd the sheep into
first class so they can escape on the few remaining lifeboats.
</P>
<P>
   The bleating noises are superb, and the designers have used a
mathematical approach developed on the cutting edge of computer
science and artificial life research to model flocking, so the
sheep clump and stray with uncanny realism. Watch for Sheep in
September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
