<SLUG> BC-NEW-STAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANT OF RUNNING IS NOW A FILM STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While on a recent quickie trip to New York,
Haile Gebrselassie went for an hour run in Central Park, dined at a
restaurant serving his native Ethiopian food and rode a limo back
to his hotel.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice being a film star.
</P>
<P>
   At 26, being squired through America's signature city,
Gebrselassie was far removed from his upbringing in rural East
Africa, where he lived in a hut and worked the family farm under
his demanding father. An occasional flogging was the price he paid
for seemingly minor indiscretions related to his desire, his need,
to run. The father, Tedesse Haile, never saw greatness in the son.
Thankfully, others did.
</P>
<P>
   Never heard of Gebrselassie? Wave the white flag when it comes
to its pronunciation? (Geb-rah-sell-ah-see.)
</P>
<P>
   Don't feel bad. He's little known in the United States and
certainly never seen beyond the sports pages.
</P>
<P>
   But something interesting happened to Gebrselassie in the last
three years. He became the star of a Walt Disney Pictures movie,
written and directed by Leslie Woodhead, that's both a documentary
(in contemporary scenes), and a drama that faithfully re-creates
his youth. In that respect, it goes where neither of the two movies
about the late American distance runner, Steve Prefontaine, could
ever go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Endurance'' debuted in Ethiopia last fall and opens in this
country Friday. ``Everybody said it was wonderful,'' Gebrselassie
said of the film's reception in his country. ``They were happy
because it showed the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gebrselassie is the best distance runner in the world, at
5-feet-3-inches a giant in his sport. He established world records
for 5,000 and 10,000 meters in a brilliant stretch of running last
summer on the European track and field circuit and won the gold
medal at 10,000 meters at the 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   So is the best runner in the world now a movie star?
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit,'' Gebrselassie said in a telephone conversation
from New York.
</P>
<P>
   English is not native to Gebrselassie, but the language is a
virtual necessity for an international track star. He speaks in a
lilting accent that ratchets up an octave or two when the subject
excites him. Such is the case when he observes the opening scenes
of ``Endurance.''
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a sight, Gebrselassie with his little barrel chest
running like a metronome over the savanna, beside rivers and up
hills while songs with names like ``Haya Wolalome,''
``Medina/Zalesgna'' and ``Tigrigna'' give the movie a sense of
verisimilitude that the two Prefontaine movies never attained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depicted the life,'' Gebrselassie said. ``It was very
accurate. I enjoyed it. It depicted things about my life. It was
good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While hardship is the currency of the Third World and to
struggle is given, one of the most poignant moments of the movie is
when 7-year-old Haile absconds with the family radio (his father
was such a stickler he would remove the batteries and hide them
after using it) in order to listen to the exploits of famed
countryman Miruts Yifter in the 1980 Olympic Games in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   With the philosophy of ``each one, teach one,'' little Haile
received his calling listening to Yifter winning the 5,000 and
10,000 meters in an Olympic Games boycotted by many Western
nations. Ethiopia aligned itself with what was then the Soviet
Union and competed against the wishes of the United States because
of the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The running styles of Gebrselassie and Yifter, also
5-feet-3-inches tall, are similar, although the former has
finishing speed the latter could only dream of. Gebrselassie is
known for his brilliant smile in victory. Yifter's most prominent
feature was in profile: His elongated head formed a virtual outline
of Africa itself.
</P>
<P>
   Gebrselassie said he has met Yifter, now living an expatriate
life in Toronto, many times. ``I think we are a little bit similar,
yes. The tactics were the same. He's very good at the end (of
races). We have many similarities.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia has had other Olympic stars, though nowhere near the
volume of Kenya, Africa's true Fertile Crescent of running.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
