<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-DESIGN-NYT &LR;      05-19 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN NOTEBOOK: PRIMORDIAL EMBRACES MODERN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.C., Ky.)   (bl)  
 By MAC GRISWOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NUTLEY, N.J. _ I had never done a modern garden till I got
here,'' said Richard Hartlage, a garden designer and horticulturist
from Seattle, who is now working on his first two private gardens
in the New York area. ``I had teethed on Gertrude Jekyll.''
 &HT;    The gardens face each other from opposite sides of a quiet,
oak-shaded suburban street here in Nutley, and belong to a pair of
friends, Graeme Hardie and Silas Mountsier. At the moment,
Mountsier's garden is in heavy construction mode, loaded up with
contractors' vans, brick piles and serious pneumatic equipment.
Hardie's garden is more or less complete, and contrary to what one
may think, Gertrude Jekyll would be happy with it. After all, the
English gardener loved strong architectural settings and used dark,
lush colors as often as the pale palette that most gardeners assume
she always went for.
 &HT;    Jekyll or no Jekyll, the boldness of Hardie's garden is
startling in this placid town, only a 30-minute drive from New York
City.
 &HT;    ``I wanted primordial,'' said Hardie, an architect and
anthropologist who was born in South Africa and was the director of
research at the North Carolina State University School of Design
until he retired to Nutley in 1991.
 &HT;    Primordial is what he got: torrid plants, bold geometry, sensual
artworks, strongly contrasting textures, varied path surfaces and
striking changes of level, all in a 44-foot-square garden. For
entertainment, he can jump in the hot tub concealed in the wooden
deck, or collapse with a margarita on a terrace shaded in summer by
banana trees.
 &HT;    Most of all, Hardie, 54, can lose himself in contemplating the
cobalt wooden walls that enclose three sides of the garden. From
inside them, the neighboring houses, discreet whites and pale
grays, dim to a scrim against these blasts of blue. The choice was
inspired by the Majorelle garden in Morocco, Hardie mentioned in
passing, as if there were nothing outre in importing this ringing
color to Nutley.
 &HT;    Hartlage, 35, is no stranger to New Jersey, and so the plants he
has introduced survive, even though many look tropical. Born and
raised in Louisville, Ky., and a graduate of North Carolina State
University (where he studied ornamental horticulture and met
Hardie), he spent three years as the superintendent of horticulture
for the Morris County (N.J.) Park Commission, running the
Willowwood and Frelinghuysen arboretums. ``I don't stretch the
zones here the way you think,'' he said. ``I don't believe in
pushing the envelope that much.''
 &HT;    Most of the hardy perennials that shape the underlying structure
of the garden are mundane, he said. The magic comes from his choice
of strongly colored varieties, like the gold-hued tufted sedge. And
since real tropical annuals like canna and coleus demand an equally
flamboyant background, he said, he went for hardy shrubs with large
leaves, like the red buckeye or Japanese mahonia. A few are really
unusual, like the crazy-looking variegated Japanese form of devil's
walking stick, a stubby contorted shrub with long fringed leaflets
edged in silver. Without the strength and variety of these
plantings, the garden would collapse into itself, leaving nothing
but the blue walls.
 &HT;    For all of Hartlage's consummate plantsmanship and extravagant
color sense, his point of departure for this garden, as for the
others he has designed, was the space. The house, like any modest,
turn-of-the-century suburban house, stands squarely facing the
street. But the drive cuts a diagonal across the depth of the lot
as it heads for the garage. When Henry Clark, a New York architect,
pushed a glassed-in extension out the back of the dark old kitchen,
he aligned it with the diagonal drive, not the wall of the house.
The extension's trapezoidal roof, which plays with the two
geometries at work on the place, sparked Hartlage's imagination
when he first visited.
 &HT;    ``It was important to me that the garden end up making sense of
the architecture,'' he said. In his design, he juxtaposed the two
geometries, creating planting beds and paths in interlocking
patterns.
 &HT;    ``Every garden should be a journey,'' he said, ``and it starts
with you sitting in a chair with your eyes moving around the
space.''
 &HT;    Hartlage contends that most gardeners don't use enough
architecture to anchor their plants. ``I see this place as a game
in a box,'' he said. ``I learned that from being a flower arranger.
In competition, you're often given a box to work with, and if you
don't have the money to cover it lavishly with fabric or whatever,
the solution is to draw the focus inside, and then the box
disappears.''
 &HT;    Then Hardie explained what happened when the garden came
together, in 1998. ``How to get the house to look like the garden
was the thing,'' he said. A South African muralist, Andre de
Villiers, painted the front hall with hot-colored African patterns.
 &HT;    And Hartlage's influence is spreading. Across the street, along
Mountsier's drive but on a neighbor's property, Hartlage has carved
out an elliptical space by planting an aerial hedge of Japanese
snowbell trees that float above a trim hedge. Mountsier is paying
for most of the plants and gets to enjoy the borrowed view when he
heads his car into the garage.
 &HT;    On Hardie's side of the street, a rare white redbud tree (Cercis
reniformis Texas White) is the first adventurer on the other side
of his driveway. Hartlage's gardens  are  headed on a journey _ all
around the neighborhood. 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    THE JOURNEY BEGINS 
 &HT;    By MAC GRISWOLD  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The woody framework in the garden that Richard Hartlage designed
for Graeme Hardie includes Japanese devil's walking stick (Aralia
elata Variegata), giant reed (Arundo donax), eulalia grass
(Miscanthus sinensis Cosmopolitan), Japanese mahonia (Mahonia
japonica), red buckeye (Aesculus pavia) and tufted sedge (Carex
elata Aurea).
</P>
<P>
   He also uses vines, like crimson glory vine (Vitis coignetiae),
and larger plants, like purple smoke bush (Cotinus coggygria
Atropurpurea) and the Indian bean tree (Catalpa bignonioides
Aurea). These are coppiced, or cut annually to knee height.
</P>
<P>
   Banana trees (Ensete ventricosum Maurelii) are treated as
annuals. Hartlage suggests using big containers and fertilizing
with twice the recommended dosage of Osmocote, and then feedings
once every two weeks of liquid 20-20-20. ``Half the fun is seeing
them go from this little nothing to 15 feet in two and a half
months,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
