<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSEY OVER TO MIDLAND FOR MENUDO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texans like to boast a bit about their love for Mex-Tex food.
It's not every state, after all, where you can get an enchilada to
float in a lake of greasy cheese and scorching chili.
</P>
<P>
   There is a perverse pleasure to be gained from searing one's
palate with a coating of capsaicin. But there are limits.
</P>
<P>
   Menudo.
</P>
<P>
   Non-Hispanic Texans, for the most part, don't do menudo.
Especially the ones who consider it adventuresome to have sour
cream with their black-bean burrito.
</P>
<P>
   Menudo _ made with beef tripe and pigs' feet _ is way out of
bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying to get them to taste it,'' David Diaz,
president of Midland's Hispanic Chamber of Commerce, said of his
Anglo neighbors and their fear of menudo. ``We are still trying to
convince them it is good for you.''
</P>
<P>
   It would seem that Diaz has a hard sell to make, but on the
first weekend of next month, Midland will hold its annual Mex-Tex
Cook-Off, and more than 20,000 visitors will be seeking the tripe
stew. Really.
</P>
<P>
   The annual event was held at a nearby racetrack until this year.
Now it is so big, organizers have moved it to the downtown city
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Chili and fajitas will be available at the cook-off, but Diaz
says most of the folks will be there strictly for the menudo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come from all over Texas to try this food,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul Pitts, oil and gas editor for the Midland
Reporter-Telegram, is one Anglo who appreciates the taste of
menudo. He is one of the cook-off founders; he has won the menudo
competition several times, and he is an experienced judge, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a turnoff,'' he said of menudo's first impression.
``Anglos turn their nose up at it when they find out it is cow
stomach and pig feet. It is a conditioning thing. What eventually
changes their minds is when they experience it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitts does admit that his first encounter was at a wedding in
Tijuana and that he nearly gagged. ``I tried it again later that
afternoon and it didn't taste as bad,'' he said. ``I had it again
the next morning, and two weeks later, I was looking around for
places to buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has come to love it. ``You can taste all the flavors
simultaneously, or separately. It's just that kind of concoction,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Menudo has a reputation for curing hangovers, although some
folks insist they would rather have a headache than consume the
stew. It is generally a breakfast meal, although often served for
lunch. Most restaurants that sell menudo sell it specifically on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell it all during the week,'' said Phillip Lancarte of Joe
T. Garcia's and Esperanza's Bakery in Fort Worth, ``but the weekend
is our biggest time.'' Lancarte said the restaurant won first place
a few weeks ago at a contest on the north side.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his menudo customers are Hispanic, Lancarte said, but a
fair number of Anglos try it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just use the beef tripe,'' he said. ``We don't use the
pigs' feet. But the pigs' feet do give it a good taste. They are a
good ingredient.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, a hot bowl of menudo is topped with chopped
onions, jalapeno peppers, a little oregano and slices of lemon or
lime.
</P>
<P>
   At the Midland cook-off, however, it will be hard to win without
the pigs' feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proportions should be about two-thirds meat to one-third
hominy,'' Pitts said. ``It should never be half and half. And about
one-third of the meat should be pigs' feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitts said the stew should not be too greasy, but should have
enough grease to carry the flavor. The best method is to use real
posole (dried hominy). But if it's not available, canned hominy
will do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recipes are sometimes vastly different,'' he said. ``But
we never have any trouble getting a consensus on the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a standard menudo recipe for those who would like to
give it a try. It has been adjusted for use with canned hominy _
not the purist method, but the fastest.
</P>
<P>
   MENUDO
</P>
<P>
   Yields 10-12 cups
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 pounds honeycomb tripe cut into 1-by-1/2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 pigs' feet
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red chili powder
</P>
<P>
   2 cups drained hominy
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   Water to cover, about 3 quarts
</P>
<P>
   Accompaniments:
</P>
<P>
   Dried oregano leaves, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   Lime or lemon wedges
</P>
<P>
   Dried red chiles, crushed, or chopped jalapeno
</P>
<P>
   Flour or corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   In a kettle, combine the tripe and the pigs' feet with 3 quarts
of water and salt. Bring water to a boil and simmer mixture,
covered, for 2 hours, or until the tripe is tender but still firm.
From time to time, skim froth from the soup.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the tripe to a bowl and set aside. Add the 1/4 cup
chili powder. Simmer the pigs' feet for 1 hour longer, or until
they are tender. Transfer them with a slotted spoon to another bowl
and let them cool until they can be handled.
</P>
<P>
   Discard the bones and cut meat into 1-inch pieces. Return the
tripe and the pigs' feet to the broth. Add the hominy, onion and
garlic and simmer the mixture, covered, for 30 minutes. Serve the
menudo with accompaniments for individual tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 128 calories, 6 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 14 grams protein, 85 milligrams cholesterol,
529 milligrams sodium, 41 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
