<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-NUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'D GO NUTS MORE OFTEN IF IT WEREN'T SO PRICEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN MELTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pop open a bottle of Samuel Smith's Nut Brown Ale and find
yourself transported back in time to the little town of Tadcaster
in Yorkshire, England. Established in 1758, the Old Brewery
Tadcaster has been cranking out malty, well-rounded brews, from
stouts to pale ales, ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Nut Brown Ale is no exception. Deriving its name from the rich
color and slightly sweet, nutty flavor, this British ale is called
Old Brewery Strong Ale in Britain. They can call it whatever they
like: a rose by any other name ...
</P>
<P>
   At first blush during our tasting, this brew came off a touch
weak: good color, nice head, fresh bouquet. But the first few sips
revealed no complexity. Only as we let it rest for a few minutes
did the true essence reveal itself: a toasty yet sweet palate,
nicely rounded bitter finish with lingering malt on the tongue. And
once again, we encountered that most American habit of beer
ruination _ overchilling.
</P>
<P>
   Most domestic brews are pilsners, descended from brews made in
chilly areas such as Bohemia, where beer is naturally served very
cold. As a result, the inferior descendants, American mass-produced
beers, are served practically freezing because they are unpalatable
any other way, and intense cold also covers up their lack of
character.
</P>
<P>
   British beers, on the other hand, are best when served slightly
chilled. Again, consider the native climate of England. Samuel
Smith has been brewing for 241 years: There were no refrigerators
back then, just a cool cellar or a chilly stream to keep the stuff
fresh. But most taverns keep their imports at the same cryogenic
temperature as the American junk. Thus, most good Brit brews need
to defrost for a few minutes before sampling.
</P>
<P>
   OK.MDNM/, I'm finished ranting.
</P>
<P>
   Nut Brown Ale is widely available, thanks to a good marketing
plan from Seattle-based importer Merchant Du Vin. It's also a touch
more expensive than many imports currently gracing our neighborhood
booze barns. Quite honestly, I'm not sure it's worth it, what with
the availability of so many other fine brews at a buck or two less
per six-pack. On the other hand, it's a pretty cheap trip back in
time for a genuinely satisfying sip of history. Try one and see for
yourself..MDBO/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
