<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: FINDING, AND FIXING, LEAKS IN SINKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: How-to photo/graphic diagram is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sink leaks can develop in two places. The obvious leaks occur on
top around the faucets. Remedies usually require opening the faucet
and adjusting or replacing the valve components. Leaks can also
occur under the sink in the drain pipes. These leaks sometimes go
unnoticed if the pipes are enclosed in a vanity or cabinet. They
are not as obvious as the faucet leaks because the pipes do not
hold water under constant pressure, so the drips are not constant.
Drain pipe leaks only drip when water is flowing out of the sink.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the leak can be corrected by tightening or replacing a
slip washer on one of the joints. Usually, however, the drips occur
because one of the pipes has corroded and is no longer watertight.
If one pipe is corroded, the others will soon deteriorate, so it is
best to replace the entire drain assembly. While this may sound
complicated, it is an easy repair that any do-it-yourselfer can
make. And it won't take more than a couple of hours.
</P>
<P>
   It is usually dark under the sink so you will probably have to
rig up work light. Make sure the light is plugged into a grounded
circuit, preferably a GFCI, because you will be working around
plumbing fixture that offer an excellent ground.
</P>
<P>
   Start by taking a Polaroid photo of the drain assembly. These
will show you how the pieces fit together and guide you when you
install the new pipes. If you do not own a Polaroid camera, make a
pencil sketch.
</P>
<P>
   You do not have to shut off the water for this repair, the only
water in the drain pipes is a small amount of standing water in the
trap. Start by placing a bucket under the drain trap. Use a pair of
water-pump pliers (also called '' channel locks'')to unscrew the
two slip nuts that hold the trap to the wall waste arm and the sink
tailpiece. Remove the trap and dump the water in it into the
bucket.
</P>
<P>
   Next disconnect and remove the other pipes, including the waste
wall arm. This is the horizontal pipe that connects with the
drain-waste pipes in the wall. Usually the pipes are joined
together with slip nuts. Some of the connections will have rubber
washers. You should replace all the fittings, including the rubber
washers, even if they look good.
</P>
<P>
   Take all the parts with you to the nearest hardware store or
home center. It is a good idea to place a sign on the sink so no
one uses it while you are at the store. When looking for
replacement parts, make sure the diameter of the new pipes matches
that of the old. Don't worry about the length; some of the new
pipes will be much longer. You can cut them to fit.
</P>
<P>
   Many home centers and hardware stores stock replacement drain
kits that contain all the parts you will need to replace the entire
drain assembly. These kits are usually cheaper than the total price
of the individual parts. You may also have a choice between metal
drain pipes or plastic ones. Both plastic and metal drain pipes are
equally durable, but most do-it-yourselfers find that the plastic
pipes are easier to work with.
</P>
<P>
   Using your Polaroid photo or sketch as guide, loosely connect
the new parts together. Mark the pieces that are too long and need
to be cut. Plastic pipes can be cut with almost any handsaw,
although a saw with a fine-tooth blade will produce a smoother cut.
Use a hacksaw with a medium- or fine-tooth blade to cut metal
pipes.
</P>
<P>
   It is not absolutely essential to cut the pipes square, but
square cuts make a neater job and will give a better fit when you
join the pipes together. You can use a miter box to get a square
cut, or you can wrap masking tape around the pipe. The tape's edge
will provide a guide for a straight cut.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble the pieces slide the slip nut, followed by the
washer, over the unthreaded end of the pipe. Examine the washer
carefully to see if it is tapered. If so, the taper should face
away from the slip nut. This is important, because if the washer is
incorrectly mounted it will not seal properly.
</P>
<P>
   Install the sink tailpiece first, then the wall waste arm. The
trap is the piece that allows you the most latitude for adjustment
_ you can move it up and down or back and forth as needed _ so
attach this part last.
</P>
<P>
   When all the pieces are in place, hand-tighten the slip nuts,
then run water through the drain. Check carefully for leaks. If a
joint does leak, tighten the slip nut another quarter turn. If it
still leaks, take it apart to make sure that the washer is properly
installed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
