A3358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MBA-ENTREPRENEURS-NYT     05-19 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MBA-ENTREPRENEURS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE MBA'S FOREGO HEFTY SALARIES TO START OWN BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLES BOISSEAU   
 The Gainesville Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Earlier this month, Jon Lovoy graduated from
the University of Florida with a masters degree in business
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going to work at an established consulting firm or
big corporation like most of his classmates, Lovoy is going to work
for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Lovoy has launched a business that records and sells compact
discs for high school and middle school bands. He operates a
one-employee company, named Da Capo CD Productions, from his
apartment in downtown Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrifying,'' Lovoy said. ``All my friends are getting
these jobs that are guaranteeing them a salary, and me I'm not
guaranteed anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovoy, 27, is among a small but increasing number of MBA
graduates who are giving up $60,000-a-year-or-more salaries to go
into business for themselves. These risk takers are attracted by
independence and emboldened by their newly acquired business
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Arnie Heggestad, the Holloway professor of entrepreneurship at
UF, said an increasing number of MBA students say they want to
eventually start their own business. Most, however, will first work
for a company for several years, which, among other things, allows
them to pay off any student loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they start something within five years of leaving we've had
a success,'' Heggestad said of those MBA students who specialize in
the college's entrepreneurial track.
</P>
<P>
   Other MBA schools also report their graduates are looking to go
out on their own as the explosion of the Internet has caught the
attention of would-be entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   A student poll of this year's 880 graduates of the Harvard
Business School found that 343 say they plan either to launch
high-tech start-ups or join the venture capital firms that support
them to cash in on the Internet boom, according to a student poll.
That's triple the number four years ago. Also, the number of
graduates taking traditional consulting and Wall Street jobs has
dropped by nearly half, to 308.
</P>
<P>
   Of UF's 140 MBA graduates this year, only a handful plan to go
directly into their own businesses, said Melanie Parker, director
of career services for the MBA program. Those opting to take a job
will earn an average of $62,000, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Wizeman and Chris Duvall are two UF grads jumping right
into business. They areare in the process of starting an
Alphagraphics franchise in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Wizeman said he had several employment offers, including one for
more than $100,000 from an investment banking firm in New York.
Instead, Wizeman, who already was a certified public accountant
before going to MBA school, decided to roll the dice.
</P>
<P>
   The pair have raised $400,000, mostly through bank loans and
personal savings, to pay a franchise fee, a downpayment on rent and
for printing, computer and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the nature of the person. There are a lot of people who
are very happy working for someone else, and they will go that
route,'' Wizeman said. ``But I just feel two things: One, I can do
better, and two, I will just enjoy it a whole lot more, the whole
building process.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinnie Whibbs III, who graduated with a MBA degree last year,
spent the past year helping set up a for-profit biomedical research
company in Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Whibbs launched LocalSensations.com Inc., a
Pensacola-based Web site to link travelers with offbeat
restaurants, hotels and other attractions in various cities. His
minority partner in the business, graduated this month but decided
to take a job at a new business unit of American Express in Fort
Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's in the genes,'' Whibbs said of going into his own
business. ``Everybody in my extended family works for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Lovoy, he started his CD-production company last year
while still in the MBA program. In April, he won first place in an
annual business plan contest among UF MBA students.
</P>
<P>
   Lovoy's business works like this: High schools and middle
schools send in audio tapes of their concerts and other
performances. Lovoy records the tapes onto CDs, designs the artwork
and pays any required royalties.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming year, Lovoy expects his sales to jump more than
five-fold from current annual sales of about $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the independence this provides,'' Lovoy said. ``While
right now I'm making less money than probably my colleagues,
starting, my potential of making more is greater.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainsville (Fla.) Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
