A3365 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     05-19 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV06-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JUNE 6, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am going to pour a concrete slab for a patio outside the
back door to my home. I want this to be a rectangular shape with
perfectly square corners because I will be putting down a
foundation and eventually want to erect walls and a roof on this
concrete slab. When I set up the form boards, how can I be sure
that the corners will be perfectly square?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several ways to do this but the simplest method is
measure across each of the diagonals as shown here. If all the
corners are perfectly square (each measuring 90 degrees) the two
measurements will be equal. If the diagonals do not measure the
same, then adjust or move the form boards until they are equal in
length. The same method can be used to check if a room is square,
or to square up a wood deck.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a problem with condensation in our attic during the
cold winter months. Water forms on the rafters and drips down onto
the insulation, then it soaks through onto the ceiling below. The
building has louvered vents in the gable at each end of the attic
and these are always open. Do think more vents are needed?
</P>
<P>
   A: As a rule, good attic ventilation requires that there also be
adequate venting along the eaves at the bottom of the attic so that
air can flow in at the bottom and out at the top, therefore gable
vents alone may not be enough. For best results there should be
ridge vents along the peak, as well as continuous venting along the
eaves.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our house has cedar shingles on the outside and our builder
told us that this type of siding should need no stain. However, the
shingles are now faded and discolored looking and look as though
they should be stained. What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   A: Application of two coats of shingle stain is definitely
advisable _ for appearance sake, as well as for preserving the
shingles. This should normally be renewed every four to five years,
depending on weather and exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The gray grout in the tile joints of my ceramic tile kitchen
floor has been stained in a large area where some grease was
accidentally spilled _ and I like the darker look. I know I can
scrape out and replace this grout, but since I like the darker
look, is there any kind of stain I can use to stain or color the
rest of the grout to match this area?
</P>
<P>
   A: Any oil or sealer will darken the grout to some extent _ but
you cannot be sure this would match the grease-stained grout.
Unless you want to replace all of the grout, I would advise just
fixing up that one darker area by scraping out the old grout and
replacing it with new material to match the rest of the grout.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``TO SEE IF FORM IS SQUARE'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: When the diagonals match in length you know the corners
of the form are all perfectly square.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
