<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I've been trying to run Scan Disk on my C drive, but this
message appears: ``Scan disk has restarted 10 times because Windows
or another program has been writing to this drive. Quitting some
running programs may enable Scan Disk to finish sooner.'' I have no
other programs running and have even disabled the virus scan.
What's wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are a few troubleshooting things to try when you get
this particular message in Windows 95 or 98. First, press Control,
Alt and Delete simultaneously to call up the Close Program dialog
box. If there are any programs on the list except for Explorer and
Systray, close them with the End Task button; do not close Explorer
and Systray.
</P>
<P>
   And make sure your screen saver is set to None. To do this,
right-click on the desktop area and select Properties from the
menu. Click on the Screen Saver tab, pick None from the pop-up list
and click OK.
</P>
<P>
   Try running Scan Disk again. If you still get the error message,
restart the computer in Safe Mode to disable temporarily any device
drivers that might be interfering. If you're using Windows 95,
press the F8 key when you see the ``Starting Windows 95'' message
and pick Safe Mode from the menu. If you use Windows 98, hold down
the Control key as the machine reboots and pick Safe Mode from the
Startup menu.
</P>
<P>
   If Scan Disk still won't run after that, restart the computer in
MS-DOS mode from the Shut Down menu. At the DOS prompt line, type
scandisk and press Enter.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How much Web server space does an average person need to make
a Web site?
</P>
<P>
   A. That depends on what the person wants to put on that Web
site. Web pages consist of files stored on a Web server. If the
site is to consist of just a few pages of text and small images,
for a personal family history page or a home-business
advertisement, for example, you could probably get by with just a
few megabytes of storage space. Many Internet service providers
offer their users about two megabytes or more of free space on
their servers for personal Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   You usually won't get your own domain name for the site with a
basic setup through your ISP. If you have grand designs for a site
with all the latest technology, like video and audio clips,
animation, tons of images and interactive material, you'll need
more server space to accommodate the larger files. Your provider
may also limit the number of hits your page can get per month.
</P>
<P>
   If you have bigger things in mind, you should try to rent server
space from a Web host company. Most of them have pricing plans that
will allow for more server space, traffic and even a domain name of
your choice for your site. To search for an appropriate Web host,
try looking at the Yellow Pages section of the Ultimate Web Host
List (webhostlist.internetlist.com). The Directory
(thedirectory.org) also offers a state-by-state list of ISP's and
Web hosts.  &QL; 
Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
