<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV27-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE NEEDS AN EXTENDED FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, May 27) 
(DW) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades, author Kurt Vonnegut Jr., 76, has viewed having an
extended family as the antidote to much of what ails us _ a safety
net in a sometimes cold and capricious world.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1976 book ``Slapstick,'' Vonnegut proposed the idea that
everyone should be assigned one of a fixed number of middle names,
and everyone else in the world who shared that name would
immediately become their family, with the resulting joys and
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   When Vonnegut gave the commencement address last Saturday to the
134 new graduates of the Class of 1999 at Agnes Scott College in
Decatur, Ga., the author elaborated on this familiar theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met a man in Nigeria one time, an Ibo who had 600 relatives
he knew quite well. His wife had just had a baby, the best possible
news in any extended family. They were going to take that kid to
meet all its relatives, Ibos of all ages and sizes and shapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would even meet other babies, cousins not much older than
it was. Everybody who was big enough and steady enough was going to
get to hold it, to cuddle it, to gurgle to it, and say how pretty
it was, or how handsome. Wouldn't you have loved to be that baby?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Vonnegut proposed, the reason there are so many people
getting divorced these days also stems from the lack of extended
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freud said he didn't know what women want. They want a whole
lot of people to talk to. What do they want to talk about? They
want to talk about everything. What do men want? They want a lot of
pals, and they wish people wouldn't get so mad at them all the
time. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that when a man and woman got married, the bride
got a lot more people to talk to about everything. The groom got a
whole lot more pals to tell dumb jokes to. A few Americans, but
very few, still have extended families. The Navajos. The Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most of us, if we get married nowadays, are just one more
person for the other person. The groom gets one more pal, but it's
a woman. The woman gets one more person to talk to about
everything, but it's a man. When a couple has an argument nowadays,
they may think it's about money, or sex, or power, or how to raise
the kids, or whatever. What they're really saying to each other,
though, is: `You're not enough people!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Vonnegut, as is his way, crammed a lot of life's big issues into
one little speech. He talked about technology and dental floss and
CNN. He told people not to give up on books, ``their friendly heft,
the sweet reluctance of their pages when you turn them with your
sensitive fingertips.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked about Colorado and Kosovo and how revenge begets
revenge, which begets revenge, forming ``an endless chain of human
misery.''
</P>
<P>
   And he talked about how woefully insufficient computers are at
providing people with what they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't try to make yourself an extended family out of ghosts on
the Internet,'' Vonnegut said, with his characteristic smirk. ``Get
yourself a Harley, and join Hell's Angels instead.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
