<HEADLINE>
HEALTH CARE EXPERT SEES RISING INSURANCE RATES CUTTING BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As health insurance rates keep rising, workers'
benefits are sure to suffer, a health care expert says.
</P>
<P>
   The assertion came in the wake of a vote Tuesday by the
California Public Employees' Retirement System (CalPERS) to allow
health maintenance organizations to raise rates for its members by
an average of 9.7 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS members are state and local government agencies that
represent some 1 million employees and their dependents.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Boland, a health care consultant in Berkeley, Calif., said
the rate increases granted to several HMOs _ including an 11.7
percent rate increase for Oakland-based Kaiser Permanente _
``threatens the integrity of (workers') overall compensation
packages. ... A premium increase basically affects everyone:
employer, employee and dependents. This is bad news for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Boland said employers won't be able to absorb the additional
costs and will need to pass them along to workers. However, he
said, employers will do this at their discretion.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Boland said, employers will need to ``raise (health
care plan) co-pays and deductibles or cut back on other benefits
like raises and overtime. It's going to come out of the employees'
pocket, directly or indirectly.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Kaiser, which is CalPERS' biggest contractor,
Foundation Health Systems Inc. will be allowed to raise rates 9.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS let Kaiser raise rates by 10.75 percent for this year,
after refusing its original request for a 12 percent increase.
Foundation raised its rates with CalPERS for this year by 5.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Tuesday by the health benefits committee of CalPERS,
the second largest public buyer of health insurance in the United
States after the federal government, also affects insurers such as
PacifiCare Health Systems Inc., Aetna Inc. and Cigna Corp.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS, whose premiums rose an average of 7.3 percent this
year, is the first big purchaser of health benefits to set premiums
for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The increases for the year 2000 are the biggest for CalPERS
members since 1991, when premiums rose an average of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, premiums have dropped in five of the past eight
years. The latest increase will return most premiums to
approximately the 1991 level.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS said rising medical costs justified substantially
increasing rates for the second year in a row. According to Sheryl
Skolnick, a BancBoston Robertson Stephens health care analyst,
overall U.S. medical costs are expected to increase by about 4
percent to 6 percent this year and another 4 percent to 6 percent
in the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``This level of premium increase is necessary to adequately fund
our members' health care in 2000,'' said Margaret Stanley, CalPERS'
health benefits administrator, in her recommendation to the CalPERS
health benefit committee.
</P>
<P>
   Skolnick said, however, that large employers who negotiate their
2000 rates later in this year may be more resistant than CalPERS to
big premium increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``(If insurers) have as good a year as they seem to be having, I
think their employer customers are going to be looking at their
profit margins and saying, `I want some of my money back, thank
you,''' said Skolnick.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs are a form of health insurance in which insurers limit
their coverage of the cost for doctors, hospitals and procedures.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS said rates for its self-funded, preferred-provider
organizations, another form of restricted health insurance, will go
up about 7 percent in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
