<HEADLINE>
A BACKWATER THAT INSPIRED ART  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tiny Breton village of Pont-Aven, now synonymous with the
post-Impressionist school of French painting that formed around
Paul Gauguin before he left for Tahiti, might have remained obscure
if not for the tides.
</P>
<P>
   Tides in this part of Brittany are nearly as extreme as they are
in the Bay of Fundy. A century ago, ships that came into the harbor
at flood found themselves high and dry at low tide. As a result,
the sailors who brought wine and other goods and then loaded up
with flour from the mills near the Aven River needed cheap hotels
and boarding houses to stay in while they waited for the waters to
raise their schooners.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the 1860s, those hotels and boarding houses, run by
shrewd businesswomen, began to attract artists in search of rustic
country and colorful Breton costumes. Americans were the first to
come, such painters as Robert Wylie, whose ``Fortune-Teller of
Brittany'' is at the Corcoran Gallery in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Others like him, whose names mean little today _ Thomas Hovenden
and William Picknell, for instance _ went back and told friends in
Paris, 350 miles away, about what they had found at Pont-Aven.
</P>
<P>
   One of the French artists who went, Felix Jobbe-Duval, wrote
Gauguin in 1886 with these words: ``It's a little backwater, and
cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheap was the operative word, and Gauguin, struggling and
penniless in Paris, lost no time in coming. Indeed, it cost him
practically nothing to live in the little boarding house where
Marie-Jeanne Gloanec had put up some of those American artists next
to the stone bridge over the river that gave the town its name.
</P>
<P>
   Gauguin found inspiration in the Bois d'Amour, a wood along the
meandering banks of the Aven, the rows of whitewashed stone
cottages with slate roofs, the rugged granite churches in nearby
villages and the suffused light that seems to be reflected from the
sea, a riverbend away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work hard here, and with success,'' Gauguin wrote to his
wife, Mette Gad, shortly after he arrived. ``I am respected as the
best painter in Pont-Aven; true, that doesn't bring in a penny
more. But perhaps it will help in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   What Gauguin developed in Pont-Aven (``Pon-tahVENN,'' as Bretons
pronounce it) was a style that changed the history of French art
after fellow artists like Emile Bernard and Paul Serusier joined
him.
</P>
<P>
   Today people flock to the village, halfway between Lorient and
Quimper, vastly outnumbering the 3,000 natives, from mid-July to
the end of August, and on weekends all year round.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Heidi, and I first came on a hot July day a year ago to
see the excellent Pont-Aven Museum nestled next to the town hall, a
building that was once a hotel annex run by Marie-Jeanne Gloanec's
biggest competitor, Julia Guillou.
</P>
<P>
   We returned after the tourist crowds were gone in early
September to explore the museum and the village at greater leisure,
staying in one of the five rooms at the rustic but comfortable
Moulin de Rosmadec. Its restaurant, housed separately in the actual
mill, is also the best in town, with a Michelin star.
</P>
<P>
   Our room on the ground floor, on a narrow lane called the
Venelle de Rosmadec reached from the main square, was more like a
suite, with a spare sitting room with white modern tile floors and
country Breton furniture in dark wood. The small bedroom (with a
little space to spare and a double bed) was a bit dark because the
shutters wouldn't open. A picture of Franck Sebilleau, the owners'
son, taken before he and his brother Frederic took over the kitchen
from their father, Pierre, hung on the bathroom wall.
</P>
<P>
   Down the lane past a well, the restaurant is a converted
15th-century mill, a two-story granite structure on a narrow island
between the millraces that used to channel the river to the water
wheel. The dining room is a warm place with Breton ladder-backed
chairs, a huge fireplace with a wild boar mounted over the mantle,
and lead-paneled windows opening out onto the rushing river.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen is even bigger than the restaurant, which seats
about 50. In it we found Franck, 28, and Frederic, 34, getting
ready for dinner. Their grilled Rosmadec lobster, its dark-red
shell redolent of butter and lightly salted, with two sauces served
on the side, one tasting of lemon butter and the other of herbs,
was memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder, with the ocean a few miles away. Pierre Sebilleau
gets the restaurant's oysters from the little port of Belon, down
the coast, source of France's most renowned oysters. Later we had a
dozen Belon No. 3's for lunch with a half-bottle of Muscadet at the
Bar La Cabane in the small town; the bill was just over $20.
</P>
<P>
   But we had come for the paintings and the museum, which was
closed over lunch. It was built in a modern style by a local
architect in 1986, a hundred years after Gauguin's first visit,
with considerable support from the pre-eminent collector of art of
the Pont-Aven School, Samuel Josefowitz, an American citizen who
lives in Switzerland and England.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When we visited, the museum's two floors (roughly 1,800 square
feet) were largely given over to an exhibition of paintings by
Georges Lacombe, one of the Nabis, as Serusier called those
inspired by Gauguin's work in Pont-Aven, borrowing the Hebrew word
for prophet or seer.
</P>
<P>
   The Pont-Aven School was multinational, with Irish, Dutch and
German as well as French artists, and the village also inspired
many American painters. At the museum, until June 21, Roderic
O'Conor, an Irish painter attracted to Pont-Aven when Gauguin was
there, holds center stage with engravings, and from June 26 to
Sept. 27, works by other Irish artists join his paintings.
</P>
<P>
   There is a 10-minute slide show to orient visitors and place the
town in the context of the art produced here. The small permanent
collection includes photographs and manuscripts from the extensive
documentation center, with pictures of Marie-Jeanne Gloanec and
Julia Guillou and their famous customers, and explanations of what
work the artists did here.
</P>
<P>
   In Pont-Aven the artists of the school developed and refined the
style of broad swatches of pure color separated by heavy dark
outlines recalling the lead joints in medieval stained-glass
windows, leaving faces and other elements abstract rather than
realistically detailed.
</P>
<P>
   Painting, Gauguin thought, should have ``the right to dare
everything,'' and while there are only a handful of his works in
the collection _ ``Le Sabotier'' is the only oil painting _ there
are enough to give an idea of where this art was heading.
</P>
<P>
   Later paintings by others like Emile Jourdan, whose 1926
painting ``Larnot Chapel in Moonlight'' hangs here, show how long
the influence of the Pont-Aven School lasted.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the museum, just to the left before the main square, we
saw one reason why artists of that era kept coming _ the annex that
Julia Guillou built across the street from her hotel to cater to
them, now the town hall. ``Annex'' indeed; it is about the size of
a four-story public school, and on the fourth floor our guide
Annaig Kerlan pointed out the enormous windows Madame Guillou
installed for the huge studios, four of them, built into the place.
</P>
<P>
   Madame Guillou, who died in 1927, was not alone. Opposite Madame
Gloanec's former pension on the Place Paul Gauguin, above the
Galerie La Belle Angele, you can see where other ambitious
landlords and landladies enlarged dormer windows, the better for
painters to work.
</P>
<P>
   Annaig, who conducts short guided tours for the town tourist
office on the square, showed us how to walk to the Bois d'Amour on
the banks of the Aven, where Serusier painted his ``Talisman''
under Gauguin's direction. This abstract impression of the small
glade is considered the first Nabi work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tree, how does it look to you? It's green, isn't it?
Paint it green, then, the finest green on your palette,'' Gauguin
is said to have told him. ``And this shadow, rather blue? Don't be
afraid to paint it as blue as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``Lesson of the Bois d'Amour,'' as the painter Maurice
Denis recounted it, is the name of a pedestrian itinerary. We found
it on the way down from the Chapel of Tremalo, a steep walk of more
than half a mile into oak forest and cornfields to a weather-beaten
granite Gothic church.
</P>
<P>
   Here Gauguin found the 17th-century polychromed crucifix
depicted in his 1889 work ``The Yellow Christ'' (now in the
Albright-Knox Art Gallery in Buffalo, N.Y.) and a self-portrait (in
the Musee d'Orsay in Paris). The crucifix still hangs in the
chapel, which has been considerably restored.
</P>
<P>
   When we came back down into town, we were ready for a snack
before tackling the art galleries. Galettes de Pont-Aven,
irresistibly rich butter cookies, were originally made here from
flour produced by the mills. Two companies, Traou Mad and Penven,
dominate the trade today, packaging the cookies in tins decorated
with paintings that they sell in inviting outlets on the main
square and down the Rue du Port near the little harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Besides galettes in various shapes and sizes, we found the
kouign-amann (pronounced quinn-amen) cakes at the Boulangerie
Kersale, next to the Cafe des Arts on the main square, lived up to
their legendary reputation. A pizza-sized confection of sweet dough
baked with salted butter and topped with sugar crystals, it's best
sampled over coffee or tea in the back room of the boulangerie, or
perhaps with a glass of pommeau, a blend of apple juice and
Calvados.
</P>
<P>
   The galleries start just past the boulangerie. Paintings by
artists from the generation that came after Gauguin and Bernard and
painted here can often be found in the Galerie de la Poste, 10, Rue
General de Gaulle, and in the Galerie l'Atelier d'Ernest, 11 rue
Louis Lomenech.
</P>
<P>
   Pont-Aven is not just about the past, however. Caroline
Boyle-Turner, an art historian and Gauguin specialist, has been
running a summer program for young artists here called the
Pont-Aven School of Art, with credits transferable from the Rhode
Island School of Design in Providence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 70 students this year, and we've just bought the
Gloanec boarding house,'' she said. So the tradition begun by
Americans continues. A few never leave. Wylie is buried in the
Guillou family plot in the Pont-Aven cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to exploring the town, we made two enjoyable short
excursions; they can be done by car or bicycle. In the village of
Nizon, in the direction of Concarneau about two miles outside of
Pont-Aven, is the Romanesque Calvary or crucifixion monument that
Gauguin depicted in his ``Green Christ,'' which hangs in the Royal
Museum in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   About 15 miles away, in the coastal town of Le Pouldu, is a
reconstruction of the seaside boarding house run by Marie Henry,
the Buvette de la Plage. The steep cliffs and sand dunes are a
different world from the picture-perfect streets of Pont-Aven, and
Gauguin, Serusier, Meyer de Haan and Armand Seguin came here for a
change of scene in the summer of 1889.
</P>
<P>
   As the weather was bad and Marie Henry's company stimulating,
they stayed for weeks and decorated the walls and door panels of
the tiny dining room with their paintings.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gauguin and his fellow artists couldn't sell any of
their works, so couldn't even pay the pittance for room and board
in Brittany. Marie Henry kept small paintings and sketches from her
boarders in lieu of payment.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly grateful, Gauguin sued but failed to get some of his work
back in 1894. His landlady took even the door panels with her when
she finally closed shop, and the house was eventually remodeled and
altered beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, on the anniversary of Gauguin's arrival, the village of
Le Pouldu recreated the original _ which now constitutes the
left-hand side of Cafe de la Plage, 30 feet away _ with
reproductions and some authentic paintings by the famous
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   So, once again, the dining room looks as it must have a century
ago _ about the size of a child's bedroom and filled with tiny
wooden tables and scenes painted directly on the walls, doors and
even the window panes by the artists.
</P>
<P>
   There are also reproductions of such familiar originals as
Gauguin's 1889 portrait of himself with a halo, now in the National
Gallery in Washington. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   High-speed trains (TGVs) from Montparnasse Station in Paris take
about four hours to Lorient ($130 round trip, based on 6 francs to
the dollar), or Quimper ($142). Avis and Europcar have offices in
the Lorient station, Avis and Hertz at Quimper. The drive to
Pont-Aven takes about half an hour from either city. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Manoir de Kertalg, (33-2) 98.39.77.77, fax (33-2)
98.39.72.07, a 10-minute drive from Pont-Aven in Moelan-sur-Mer,
has nine rooms and a duplex apartment in a 20th-century manor on
the grounds of a 15th-century chateau occupied by the hotel's
owners. No restaurant. Continental breakfast, $10. The rooms,
carpeted with antique-reproduction furnishings and modern tiled
bathrooms, color television, and direct-dial telephones, looked
comfortable and cost $82 to $163; the apartment, $200. Open Easter
to early November. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   Le Moulin de Rosmadec in the center of Pont-Aven, not far from
the main square, (33-2) 98.06.00.22, fax (33-2) 98.06.18.00, has
menus at $27.50, $50 and $66, the latter starting with eight No. 2
Belon oysters or duck foie gras and including grilled Rosmadec
lobster and its two butter sauces, and dessert of Grand Marnier
souffle or crepes flambees. A la carte dishes cost from $20 to $48;
add $30 to $60 for a bottle of wine. The restaurant also has five
rooms in an adjoining building, all for $80. Breakfast $7.65.
Closed all day Wednesday and Sunday evenings except in summer, all
of February, and the second half of November. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things to Do
</P>
<P>
   The Maison Marie Henry, in Le Pouldu, is open from April 1 to
Sept. 30. Until June 1 opening hours are only on weekends and
national holidays, from 3 to 7 p.m. Hours are daily except
Wednesday from 3 to 7 p.m. in June and September and from 10 a.m.
to 7 p.m. in July and August. Tours, in both French and English,
begin at 3:15, 4:15, 5:15 and 6:15 p.m. and in July and August also
at 10:20 and 11:30 a.m. Entrance fee $4.15.
</P>
<P>
   The Pont-Aven Museum, Place de l'Hotel de Ville, (33-2)
98.06.14.43, is open daily from 10 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. and from 2 to
6 p.m., staying open until 6:30 in April, May, June and October.
Open 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. in July and August. Admission $4.15.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
