<HEADLINE>
MANY ARE FINDING THE NERVE TO MOVE TO ANOTHER ISP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (Eds: 3rd take has 2 optional sidebars: computer users' stories of
selecting ISPs and what to look for in an ISP) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider the Internet service provider. Depending on your online
habits, it can be the home of your familial interactions, the
envelope for your business memorandums, the conduit of your deepest
desires. It can get about as much intimate use as the lenses of
your glasses or the pages of a journal. It is the choice of a way
to view Web pages and to send e-mail, and as such it should not be
approached without proper introspection and circumspection.
</P>
<P>
   Or should it? For many Internet users, new and seasoned, that
choice depends on what start-up disk appears in a mailbox or cereal
box on any given day, which provider an employer chooses or which
program for an Internet service provider, commonly called an ISP,
shows up on a new desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the correspondence we've received, and its emotional
content, choosing an ISP seems to rank somewhere between selecting
a long-distance phone service and choosing a caterer for a bar
mitzvah,'' Dr. Dawn McGatney, a Maryland pediatrician and
Webmaster, said via e-mail. Dr. McGatney runs a site called
Compleat Guide to an ISP You'll Enjoy Using (dogwolf.seagull
.net/isp.html). ``But we hear from many folks who are now on their
fifth or higher ISP,'' she added. ``Once you switch one to two
times, it's obviously easier. There is a bit of fear of the unknown
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people have decided they would rather switch
providers than fight suboptimal service. As of January, 36.7
percent of home Internet users had changed their ISP's at some
point and lived to tell about it, according to the Strategis Group,
a Washington-based research company that studies patterns in
telecommunications use. It's not an easy decision, but taking that
step can be liberating, people who love their new Internet services
say.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the choice is formidable, with 4,500 Internet
services available across the country. According to Forrester
Research, America Online has 39.4 percent of all home accounts; its
17 million subscribers worldwide are a group larger than the
combined daily circulation of the top 20 daily newspapers. Other
large services, like AT&AMP;T, Earthlink, MSN and Prodigy, collectively
share 15.3 percent of the market, while small ISPs _ those with
less than 2 percent of the market, like Sprint, Erols and the local
Bell telephone companies _ serve 41.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Internet services compete fiercely for new Internet users and
for people who have been online for years.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is the 800-pound gorilla in the middle of the information
superhighway and the new user's magnet. Its simple-to-install
software and ubiquitous distribution are the keys to its success.
Andrew Shepherd, a Forrester Research analyst, said that as of
January, AOL had captured 54 percent of all users who had been
online for less than six months and half of all users who had been
online for less than a year. It has also garnered its share of
criticism, as have other large and small ISP.s, for slow service,
busy signals, the prevalence of spam and concerns about members'
privacy. But Kathy McKiernan, an AOL spokeswoman, said that the
company was experiencing its fastest growth and lowest turnover
rate ever.
</P>
<P>
   Another service provider, Earthlink Network, based in Pasadena,
Calif., is competing for customers by, among other things,
marketing its Get Out of AOL Free plan and offering promotions like
a free month of service or free setup. Earthlink can transfer
Favorite Places Web sites from AOL to a new browser and will send
e-mail to everyone in a new customer's electronic address book to
notify them of the change of address.
</P>
<P>
   Taking cues from AOL, Earthlink has created easy-to-use software
that features a friendly on-screen guide. ``She'll say: `Hi,
welcome to Earthlink. I'll walk you through step by step. Click
here,' but you can also shut her up,'' said a company spokeswoman,
Kirsten Kappos.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet providers, particularly smaller ones, win new
subscribers in more personal ways. Paul Budlong of Seattle, for
example, chose his small ISP, based in Seattle, after receiving
e-mail from someone who used it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the name,'' he said of Drizzle.com, and found it
appropriate to local weather conditions. He switched from a
provider in Portland, Ore., to Drizzle, which serves the Puget
Sound region. He was frustrated by his old service's busy signals
(it could take up to 20 attempts to get through) and ``complete
technomorons at tech support who were incapable of speaking plain
English.'' He found the smaller local provider to be more helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``They e-mail back, they call back, they explain things in
simple terms, they're friendly, on the ball and very patient,''
said Budlong, who has an old 386 computer with software that could
best be described as quaint. The support staff even downloaded a
huge program for him that would have taken him hours to do online.
``I went downtown, knocked on the door, and they didn't even charge
me for the disks,'' he said. ``It was very cool.''
</P>
<P>
   But the smaller ISPs are particularly vulnerable to mergers and
acquisitions, so they are less likely to remain stable.
</P>
<P>
   People who find an ISP they like might hesitate to rave about it
because that might encourage others to join and lead to busy
signals all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a friend who wouldn't tell anybody when he'd find an ISP
he liked,'' said David Cassel, editor of the AOL Watch newsletter,
which is distributed to an e-mail list of 42,000 readers. ``You
really want a small service no one has ever heard about.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The search for the perfect fit can be traumatic. While any other
company that hung up on customers several times a day could expect
a quick pink slip, an ISP is harder to dump. Switching providers
could mean forfeiting prepaid Internet service, spending hours
rejiggering modem strings and software interfaces, losing old
e-mail messages and printing new business cards and resumes with
the new e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 reason that folks stick with an ISP that they hate _
and they can get truly emotional on the subject _ is that they've
prepaid a year or two in advance and stand to lose hundreds of
dollars by leaving,'' Dr. McGatney said. ``The trick here is always
to read the ISP's terms of service before subscribing. Be sure that
the ISP offers a prorated refund for those who cancel early. The
No. 2 reason would be the pain of notifying all your friends that
you have a new e-mail address, though many ISPs will forward your
e-mail forever at no charge.'' Mail sent to a closed AOL account,
she said, bounces back with a note that the mail could not be
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Catlett, president of Junkbusters Corp., an online privacy
advocacy group in Green Brook, N.J., said switching often required
reconfiguring the user's computer. ``That's probably a traumatic
experience for many people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Sherman, a Web search guide at the Mining Co. site, said
some Internet patterns were hard to break. His parents started out
with AOL and resisted a move to Mindspring, he said. ``Even though
Mindspring is so easy, they were comfortable with AOL,'' he said.
``It's an inertia issue more than a branding issue.''
</P>
<P>
   When choosing a provider, a computer user should decide whether
one goal is to get broad-bandwidth Internet access, which allows
Internet connections at speeds faster than the current standard
consumer maximum, 56 kilobits per second on a conventional
telephone line. These faster access routes to the Internet have
many advantages: they can be open as long as the computer is on,
there is no waiting for dial tones, and there is little waiting for
Web sites to load.
</P>
<P>
   Internet service through a cable TV provider, which is available
in some places, can typically download one megabyte of data in less
than 8 seconds, compared with digital subscriber lines, or DSL
lines, at 15 seconds or a fast telephone modem, operating at 56K,
at two and a half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cable Internet service connects a house through the same wires
that carry cable television, with, in most cases, the cable company
acting as the Internet provider. DSL connects a computer to the Net
through existing phone lines but the computer must be within a
limited distance _ a few miles _ of a phone company switching
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can pretty much count on the fact that the larger ISPs are
in heavy-duty competition to roll out high-speed access,'' Sherman
said. ``The question is just when.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other questions are worth pondering: Where and how much?
Cable companies can now reach only about 23 million households.
Their Internet service costs about $40 per month, said David
Eiswert at the Strategis Group. DSL lines are available to about 6
million households for about $50 a month, compared with a cost of
about $20 a month for traditional dial-up services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is concerned about price,'' said Shepherd, of
Forrester Research. ``That's in some ways going to be one of the
things that allows dial-up ISPs to really fight off cable in the
short term. They're providing service at half the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people decide not to pay for any ISP and rely on free Web
services instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can take half-steps _ get a Geocities Web page and Juno
e-mail account and access the Web through a machine at work or the
local public library if they don't want dial-up service,'' said
Cassel, of AOL Watch. Juno, Hotmail and Alta Vista mail are
examples of free e-mail services that a user can log onto from a
computer at a public library or Internet cafe. Free Web pages are
available at sites like Geocities and Tripod.
</P>
<P>
   Many Web surfers, however, want Web access from home. Some
choose their ISPs based on particular needs _ a frequent traveler
might want to have access to the Internet service while overseas,
for example, or a biology buff might need a large space on the Web
to hold a special page on the naked mole rat. Other customers
choose a service like AOL because it provides something like a
roped-off section of the larger Internet for children.
</P>
<P>
   There can be some advantages in switching providers early and
often.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changing your e-mail address periodically and auto-notifying
the sender to the old address with a message is a great way to get
off of every spam list in the world,'' Dr. McGatney said. ``Each
time we've moved, our junk mail dropped to zero for the next
several months.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL SIDEBARS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   HOW THEY SELECTED AN ISP
</P>
<P>
   Don Ho
</P>
<P>
   Entertainer (through his Internet director, Christopher Soares).
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked a local service provider based on price, service,
tech support, dial-ups and personalized service, not necessarily in
that order, mind you. We were with a local company. One of the
partners, whom we started with, split and formed his own ISP called
Maikai.net (www.maikai.net). So now we're with them. Because I know
the service will remain excellent! We've found that the larger ISPs
are of little or no help when they're done setting you up with a
DNS.''
</P>
<P>
   Linus Torvalds
</P>
<P>
   Creator of the Linux operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had to choose; I've always gotten a free Internet
connection through my work (or my studies back when I was at the
university).''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Catlett
</P>
<P>
   President of Junkbusters, an online privacy advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I started using ISDN, Eclipse Internet was the
only ISP with ISDN-capable modems in my local calling area. Now
many others do, but I haven't bothered to shop around. Also, I like
the fact that they're comparatively small because of the rumors
that some of the big national ISPs are considering deals where they
sell details of their customers' surfing activities to
advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Isabel Wang
</P>
<P>
   Co-founder of ISP-Check (www.ispcheck.com), which helps computer
users find ISPs and Web page hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was with Bell Atlantic for a long time. They claim they
support 56K, but I was always connecting at 28, and there were busy
signals on weekends and evenings. I'd get kicked off every five
minutes. I switched to Starpower, which is good. It was really
easy. Most ISPs can set you up the same day or the same minute when
they have you on the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Pattiann Rogers
</P>
<P>
   Poet, whose ninth book, ``The Dream of the Marsh Wren, Writing
as Reciprocal Creation,'' will be out in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an article in a computer magazine that gave
Mindspring a very high rating. I couldn't always make connections
reliably on Compuserve so I switched to Mindspring because of its
rating and because I wanted service for a Web site. I've been with
Mindspring several years now and am satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO LOOK FOR IN AN ISP
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are finding your very first Internet service
provider or looking for the perfect one after seven false starts,
choosing an ISP is challenging. Here are some questions to ask when
shopping around:
</P>
<P>
   HOW COMMITTED DO I HAVE TO BE? Extra points go to providers
offering trial memberships. Beware of those that tie you down to
years of service if you want a good rate. Find out if you can get
money back if you switch later.
</P>
<P>
   CAN I GET CONNECTED? Try dialing the phone numbers of a
prospective ISP during peak times and make sure you hear a modem
screech (good) instead of a busy signal (very bad). Ask about the
service's user-to-modem ratio, and find out if there are any
guarantees about how easy it will be to connect to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   WILL MY ISP KEEP UP WITH TECHNOLOGY? Find out if your
prospective provider plans to offer broad-band technology like DSL
for speedier access to the Internet. If you are particularly fond
of playing games, shopping or trading stock online, make sure that
the service has sufficient bandwidth to accommodate those
activities easily. Talk to customer service or sales
representatives to see if the provider has partners for DSL service
in your area or plans such partnerships. Or find out whether you
could continue with the provider if you got a cable Internet
connection; some ISPs offer discounts on access for people gaining
access to the Net through cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   IS THE PRICE RIGHT? If you don't choose unlimited access, make
sure you can afford the often-steep hourly rates if you exceed your
monthly minimum. You should find out if the provider has hefty
setup fees.
</P>
<P>
   IS THERE FREE, 24-HOUR TECH SUPPORT? You will most likely need
it. To check out customer satisfaction with a provider, talk to
other people who use it. If you can't find someone offline, try
searching newsgroups online for comments from the Web world at
large.
</P>
<P>
   IS ACCESS AVAILABLE ON THE ROAD? If you need access while
traveling, your provider should have a wide range of local numbers
in the areas you tend to visit or offer 800 numbers. If you decide
on cable or DSL service, make sure that you can connect in other
cities through your provider when you are limited to a phone line
on the road. With Web TV, you have to take along your box unit to
get on line from the road.
</P>
<P>
   WILL I HAVE PRIVACY ON THIS ISP? You should ask if the ISP will
sell your name to marketers or bombard you with spam. It is also
wise to find out if you can post what you want on your Web page,
including commercial material, if applicable.
</P>
<P>
   They say that breaking up is hard to do, but there are ways to
soften the separation anxiety when changing ISPs. ``Don't get
wedded to your ISP,'' said Jason Catlett, president of Junkbusters
Corp., an advocate of online privacy. ``They should be a commodity
service, and you should be able to switch easily if they raise
prices or start invading your privacy.'' Catlett noted that e-mail
tended to tie people to their ISPs. He suggested breaking that link
by using an e-mail forwarding service (like Pobox.com, Ziplink or a
college alumni group that offers lifetime e-mail addresses). That
way you can keep one e-mail address, regardless of how many times
you change providers.
</P>
<P>
   _ TINA KELLEY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
