<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-CATEGORY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING THE CALL OF THE `LOON' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Like so many tales of hard-won literary fame, this one
begins with a lawn mower running over a bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been debating over the years the various scenarios for
the bird,'' said Eric Paul Johnson, who wielded the lawn mower 16
years ago. ``Was he deceased (already)? Was it a suicide?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Was he deaf?'' asked Mike Sortino. ``He didn't get out of the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, the bird's death was an inspiration to the
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, this struck me as hilarious,'' Sortino said.
Instead of merely laughing, he bolted to Johnson's room and pounded
out a satirical story about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The severed head was still on the lawn,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Under such grisly circumstances the ``Loon News'' was born. If
you haven't heard of the satirical newspaper, welcome to the club.
In its 16-year run, Johnson and Sortino, both Valley residents,
have handed out Xerox copies of the paper to anyone who wants them
(for a copy, write to 507 E. Campo Bello, Phoenix, AZ 85022, or
letters(at)loonnews.com via e-mail). A word-of-mouth kind of thing.
Yet despite its lengthy existence, circulation usually hovers
around 45. Depending.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we run out we do more,'' Sortino said. &QL; 
Committed pair &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But size isn't important, as they say. The great thing about the
``Loon News'' is Johnson and Sortino's never-ending dedication to
creating it.
</P>
<P>
   Sortino is a writer. Johnson too, though his real love is
cartooning, and his strip, ``Loon News: The Comic Strip!'', is
included in each issue. He is ``waiting for international
syndication of the comic strip and'' _ here Sortino joined in,
finishing the quote as a duet _ ``unending merchandising
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   To call the ``Loon News'' a free-form publication understates
the case considerably. The two switch editing duties, depending
upon whims and schedules (Sortino works at the Herberger Theater;
Johnson at Target), and fill the ``Loon News'' with whatever
strikes them as funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of like Dennis Miller's `Weekend Update,' '' Johnson
said, ``but with some music stories.''
</P>
<P>
   I laughed, but satire is like anchovies _ not everyone
appreciates it. But the real fun is the Loon state of mind.
Remember the ``clear'' craze? Pepsi Clear and all that? They
cranked out ``Loon News Clear,'' a one-page issue printed on a
transparent sheet. Then there was Loon Aid, their answer to Live
Aid, and, perhaps, most memorably, their sendup of Hands Across
America _ Hands Across Eric's Bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a disaster,'' Johnson said, noting that the only
participants were him and two cats. ``I wanted to raise $200,000. I
raised 75 cents.'' &QL; 
Life goes on &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There have been dark times, certainly, when one or the other or
both nearly gave up on ``Loon News.'' Moves, jobs and other
real-life hindrances have interfered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had asked me when I was 14 if I would be doing it at
30, I would have said `No' and called you a name,'' Sortino said.
``We've had so many `last' issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But they have soldiered bravely on, satirizing anything in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing we've learned is that you can't kill it,'' Johnson
said. ``No matter what you do, it keeps coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   They've added a staff member, Mychele Dee. She writes and takes
care of their new Web page (www.loonnews.com), and during our chat
they sounded optimistic about the ``Loon New's'' future. Actually,
they made it sound like they didn't have anything better to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seen all the TV shows,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, sort of, the two are as dedicated to the ``Loon
News'' as any artist is to his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a frustrated non-working writer, it's a good outlet for
me,'' Sortino said. Johnson concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of don't see the point of writing all these stories and
drawing all these 'toons and stashing it away in a corner and not
showing anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So they don't. Here's hoping they never do. &QL; 
 &QL;  Reach Bill Goodykoontz at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
