<HEADLINE>
ADVICE ABOUT SCHOOL VIOLENCE 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: I am a high school sophomore. I am very worried
about school violence such as the recent shooting in Colorado. I
have been watching the news and realize this could happen at my
school or any school. More incidents like this are now happening.
</P>
<P>
   I was walking to class yesterday and a guy followed me into
class wearing a black leather trench coat. It really scared me and
several other classmates. I talked to the teacher to see if she was
going to do something, but she said he hadn't done anything wrong.
She also said she was afraid to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   How can I let someone in the school know about this student and
not get my teacher or the student mad at me? I really feel that
someone needs to talk to him. I'm worried that more violence will
occur and more people will be hurt. I'm really scared to go to
school. I told my mom I was sick today and couldn't go. What can I
do to help our school? _ Scared.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Scared: You are voicing a fear that many students share.
The first step to resolve your fears and help your school is:
communicate. You were correct in talking with your teacher.
</P>
<P>
   You could also talk to school counselors or principals and voice
your concerns about the way this student is dressed and acting.
Your school administration can talk to the student and let him know
that his clothing does not necessarily involve him in such violent
activities, but that he may want to select different clothes during
this time.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes didn't make this incident occur; the actions of the
students involved and beliefs created the actions. The clothes only
hid the weapons.
</P>
<P>
   By communicating your fears, you will make more people aware of
the actions of students in your school, and they will be more
likely to help prevent future incidents. The old saying, ``It takes
a village to raise a child,'' means that everyone needs to take
responsibility for the future generation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a problem or concern that needs an answer? The Class
Acts Teenstalk panel _ headed by Kathy Pope, a counselor at a Texas
junior college _ is comprised of teenage students who care about
other students. Write to: Teenstalk, c/o Class Acts, The New York
Times Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
