<HEADLINE>
A BRIEF LOOK AT THE NEWS 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 c. 1999 Compiled from reports by The Associated Press and Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A HUG OF ACCEPTANCE
</P>
<P>
   Kelli Linton is trying to bring a stop to teen violence, one
person at a time.
</P>
<P>
   After two teens in a group of outcasts shot 12 classmates and a
teacher at a Colorado high school, Kelli decided to hug every
student at her campus.
</P>
<P>
   Under Operation Heart to Heart, Kelli created green cards that
read, ``You are loved and accepted. Pass it on.'' She has been
hugging classmates and handing them cards two at a time, one to
keep and one to give away with a hug of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is I want to let them know that I love them and that I
accept them no matter who they are or what they've done,'' said
Kelli, a junior at Fort Worth's Carter-Riverside High. ``It's not
just a one-week campaign or crusade, and it's not a hug-a-thon.
It's an ongoing thing. Once you get to know a person and find out
about someone, you'll find out that no matter what they look like,
they're still fun people. I want students to reach out to people
they don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATING MOM
</P>
<P>
   Nikki Melanson's flower artwork about how much she loves her mom
was painted into the ice at Fort Worth Outlet Square last week for
all to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Nikki, 12, a sixth-grader, was the winner of a Mother's Day
coloring contest among kids who go to child care through the YMCA
of Metropolitan in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Nikki and her pals and others at the YMCA had a skating and
pizza party recently to celebrate. Her artwork, enlarged to 10 feet
by 8 feet, was chosen from almost 100 entries.
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOMS
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 bills filed in the Texas Legislature would limit
teen-agers in some way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just happen to be at a time in our history where I think
teen-agers ... are feared much more than they have been in the
past,'' said Laurence Steinberg, professor of psychology at Temple
University.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the major pieces of legislation that are showing
potential for becoming laws this session include requiring minors
to tell their parents before they have an abortion; to have
parents' consent for body piercing; and to have adult supervision
during the first year of driving, with graduated driver licenses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
