<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Upstart Unveils Rival to the Game Boy &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With millions of Game Boys sold worldwide, Nintendo has
practically owned the handheld computer amusement market for a
decade. At the recent Electronics Entertainment Expo in Los
Angeles, SNK, a game maker best known for its presence in video
arcades, unveiled its effort to end Game Boy's reign.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Neo Geo Pocket Color, the 16-bit, processor-based
game machine is smaller, lighter and faster than Game Boy players,
SNK said, and it can display ``nearly three times as many colors as
Nintendo's Game Boy Color.''
</P>
<P>
   The Neo Geo system, housed in a sleek horizontal case (Game
Boy's case is vertical), is capable of rendering 146 colors
simultaneously on its 2.6-inch display screen, compared with Game
Boy's slightly smaller display, which can show 52 colors at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   The Neo Geo Pocket Color machines also have a thumb-friendly,
built-in joystick, rather than the four-point directional game
controller that Nintendo uses on its portable and console machines.
</P>
<P>
   Neo Geo Pocket Color machines will cost $69.95, $10 less than a
Game Boy Color. Beginning on June 1, they will be sold on line
through the company's Web site at www.snkusa.com and later in the
year in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Neo Geo games are available, with 10 more expected later
this summer, Ms. Sujishi said. At last count, Game Boy Color can
play 450 original titles, including those made for black-and-white
Game Boys.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeremy Schwartz, a senior analyst at Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass., is skeptical of any newcomer's chances of
dislodging Game Boy as a favorite among players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game Boy is so entrenched at this point, with so many people
making so many well-known game properties for it, these guys are
going to have a very hard time getting any widespread consumer
acceptance of it,'' said Schwartz, an expert on games. He said
there was a long trail of other gaming machines crushed by Game
Boys. ``They're the master,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Consultant Reports a Flaw In Ebay's Web Site Security &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nothing lasts for long on Ebay, the popular online auction
house, except, apparently, potential security flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cervenka, a consultant in Edmonton, Alberta, recently found
a bug that can redirect personal information _ including passwords
_ from the Ebay site (www.ebay.com) to his own computer. But the
company has not remedied the security gap.
</P>
<P>
   Cervenka found that by inserting bits of the programming
language Javascript into a description of an item for auction, he
could surreptitiously get the screen name and Ebay password for the
bidders on that item.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the site, I just decided to try a couple things
that are common, wide-open, potential security holes, and I was
surprised that everything I tried seemed to work,'' said Cervenka,
a member of Because We Can (www.because-we-can.com), an informal
organization of people with an interest in security.
</P>
<P>
   With an Ebay screen name and password, an intruder could place
unauthorized bids and start bogus auctions while impersonating an
unsuspecting victim. Similar security problems could exist with
online e-mail systems and chat sites, Cervenka said, where the user
has the ability to modify a Web site. When Cervenka sent Ebay
e-mail about the security problem, he said he received only a form
letter in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are certainly aware of the fact that if you use the
Javascript, that what he described can indeed occur,'' said Kevin
Pursglove, a spokesman for Ebay. He also said that the company
intended to continue allowing the use of Javascript because many
people use it to enhance graphics in their descriptions of auction
items.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Cervenka, he said, ``We do know that if someone
uses the script the way the gentleman suggests, and there were any
intrusion to an account, we have the ability to identify the
violator of that within an hour's time and move promptly to suspend
them from Ebay.''
</P>
<P>
   No such suspensions have occurred, he said, adding that bidders'
credit-card information remains inaccessible.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Kelley &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keeping `Star Trek' Alive As the TV Series Goes Dark &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also from Electronics Entertainment Expo: Fans of ``Star Trek:
Deep Space 9'' need not worry about losing track of their favorite
characters as the television series ends its seventh and final
season next week. The space opera, full of souls looking for peace
and redemption, can go on in the claustrophobic world of a new 3-D
computer game.
</P>
<P>
   Called Star Trek Deep Space 9: The Fallen, the CD-ROM-based
action game is part of a coordinated, two-year-long strategy to
extend the ``Deep Space 9'' franchise through computer games,
novels, comics and audio books.
</P>
<P>
   The game, which allows players to be any one of the show's three
main characters _ Sisko, Worf or Kira _ is a winner-take-all
adventure. Billions of lives hang on practically every mouse click.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the digital daring will have to wait a while. Though
the books will be published later this year, the game, the company
said, will not be on store shelves until early next year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where Miss Liberty Welcomed Huddled Masses, Now on CD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just as Ellis Island was the port of entry for millions of
immigrants, South Peak Interactive in Cary, N.C., is hoping that
its new CD-ROM, The Ellis Island Experience, will be the port of
entry for millions of computer users when it is released next year.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROM, created with the help of the History Channel and the
Statue of Liberty-Ellis Island Foundation, contains images of
hundreds of artifacts, newly released documents and photographs.
There are also three hours of audio from the Ellis Island Oral
History project as well as a 3-D virtual tour of the island and
lots of video. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Headset Offers Movie Sound Without Going to the Theater &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surround sound, a movie-theater-like audio experience, is
becoming increasingly popular in living rooms by way of
many-speakered home entertainment systems and personal computers
bearing speakers bigger than the computers themselves. But you no
longer need to be surrounded by a battery of expensive speakers to
get surround sound.
</P>
<P>
   At E3, Sony announced the availability of cordless stereo
headphones that create surround sound. The headphones, called
MDR-DS5000, work in conjunction with a small base transmitter that
produces a multidimensional sound that listeners hear not only from
side to side, but also from front to back.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the sound is a convincing illusion. But at $549.99,
the manufacturer's suggested retail price is real enough. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   V-Chip in New Televisions &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In just a few months, half of the new televisions sold in the
United States will be required by federal law to include a V-chip,
a device that enables parents to block programs from appearing on
their television screens.
</P>
<P>
   But there's just one problem: the rating system that makes the
V-chip possible has been out for more than a year, but it isn't
used by most parents. In fact, the number of parents using the
ratings has declined to 22 percent from 31 percent in the last
year. The figures come from a survey of 1,000 parents that was
conducted last month by the Kaiser Foundation and the Center for
Media Education.
</P>
<P>
   To Kathryn Montgomery, president of the center, the drop can be
explained by the lack of recent media coverage of the V-chip. She
said the survey also showed how much people needed to be educated
about the V-chip. ``It's all very new,'' she added. ``It's going to
take awhile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
