<HEADLINE>
ON CBS, IT'S NOT A FOUNTAIN OF YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS, the only broadcast network not infatuated with youth,
announced a fall lineup Wednesday that blends young actors with
older ones in its new shows, and mixes new shows and established
ones on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Network chief executive Leslie Moonves said that one highly
regarded new drama with a Mafia theme and a great deal of violence
had been kept off the schedule at least in part because of the high
school shootings in Littleton, Colo., in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the time to have people being whacked on the
streets of New York,'' Moonves told reporters before making the
network's presentation to advertisers at Carnegie Hall yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his staff had screened the pilot episode for the
show, called ``Falcone,'' a week after the Littleton tragedy, and
had ``cringed.'' Even though he characterized ``Falcone'' as ``a
very high-quality show, really very well done,'' he said, ``We felt
a responsibility not to put it on the schedule now.''
</P>
<P>
   At the presentation to advertisers, Moonves exuded confidence,
buoyed in part by news that his network had clinched first place in
total viewers for the season, which ends next week. But CBS will
finish fourth among the 18-to-49-year-olds, a group the other major
networks woo ardently because advertisers pay higher rates to reach
them.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves said CBS was striving to be ``bimodal,'' seeking shows
that appeal to younger adults without alienating CBS's loyal older
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, three new shows feature an older and younger actor
in key roles: Tyne Daly as the mother of Amy Brennerman's lead
character in ``Judging Amy,'' Betty White as the mother of Alfred
Molina's lead in ``Ladies Man,'' and Margaret Colin as a
middle-aged wife whose husband has been transformed by a freak
accident into someone 20 years younger, a covert government agent
(Eric Close), in ``Now and Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Moonves described the new schedule as ``a little bit aggressive,
but not at all messing with stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Saturday and Sunday rosters remain intact from this
season. All three news magazines remain, with ``60 Minutes II'' and
``48 Hours'' both getting potentially stronger lead-in shows ahead
of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago Hope,'' with Mandy Patinkin back as Dr. Geiger and
David E. Kelley promising to write more episodes, has moved to 9
p.m. Thursday, from 10 p.m. on Wednesday. It will lead into ``48
Hours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes II'' moves to Tuesdays at 9 p.m., preceded by the
popular ``JAG,'' and followed by ``Judging Amy.'' CBS switched its
midweek movie from Tuesday to Wednesday, where it will be preceded
by ``Cosby'' at 8 p.m. (moving from Monday) and, at 8:30 p.m., a
new comedy, ``Work with Me,'' starring Nancy Travis and Kevin
Pollak as married law partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of Queens,'' a solid performer this season, moves
backward 30 minutes to replace ``Cosby'' at 8 p.m. on Monday,
followed by ``Ladies Man.'' CBS's hit comedy ``Everybody Loves
Raymond'' remains at 9, followed by ``Becker'' and ``Family Law,''
another legal drama, this one starring Kathleen Quinlan as a lawyer
who starts a new firm after her partner-husband leaves her, taking
many clients with him.
</P>
<P>
   Two new shows will appear on Friday nights. ``Love or Money,''
at 8:30 p.m., is an ensemble comedy about a building superintendent
who falls in love with the wealthy heiress living in the penthouse.
``Now and Again,'' at 9 p.m., is the drama about the middle-age
insurance man suddenly transformed into a government agent with a
rebuilt body.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. Doctors'' and ``Promised Land'' were canceled; ``Candid
Camera'' is on hiatus and could return as a substitute if another
show does poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the CBS schedule:
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY: 7 p.m., ``60 Minutes''; 8, ``Touched by an Angel''; 9,
``CBS Sunday Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY: 8 p.m., ``King of Queens''; 8:30, ``Ladies Man''; 9,
``Everybody Loves Raymond''; 9:30, ``Becker''; 10, ``Family Law.''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY: 8 p.m., ``JAG''; 9, ``60 Minutes II''; 10, ``Judging
Amy.''
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY: 8 p.m., ``Cosby''; 8:30, ``Work With Me''; 9, ``CBS
Wednesday Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY: 8 p.m., ``Diagnosis Murder''; 9, ``Chicago Hope''; 10,
``48 Hours.''
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY: 8 p.m., ``Kids Say the Darndest Things''; 8:30, ``Love
of Money''; 9, ``Now and Again''; 10, ``Nash Bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY: 8 p.m., ``Early Edition''; 9, ``Martial Law''; 10,
``Walker, Texas Ranger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
