<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISS-APARTMENT-ART-2T     05-19 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISS-APARTMENT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SON'S DEBT OF HONOR: AT HOME WITH TONY HISS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the center of the mantel, there's an 8-inch wood
plaque bought in the gift shop at the federal penitentiary in
Lewisburg, Pa. The painted plaque shows the prison as it looks now,
and as it looked when Tony Hiss' father, Alger Hiss, occupied a
cell there, convicted of perjury back in the 1950s for saying he
didn't pass secrets to Whittaker Chambers, an admitted communist
spy.
</P>
<P>
   The plaque is the newest memento in the Hiss apartment, the same
two-bedroom walk-up on East Eighth Street that Alger and Prossy
Hiss rented in 1947, when they moved up from Washington; the
apartment where Tony Hiss grew up; the apartment that Hiss, now 57,
shares with his own son, Jacob, 7, and his wife, Lois Metzger, who
writes sophisticated novels for teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment, along with the prison cell, is a central
character in ``The View From Alger's Window'' ($24), a memoir by
Tony Hiss, due from Alfred A. Knopf in early June.
</P>
<P>
   From the cell, the view was of long ridges of dark woods, large
red barns and a blue house. On Eighth Street, the view from Alger's
window is, still, out the back.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenwich Village apartment overlooks a small courtyard,
facing south. ``The top half of this view is all sky _ a great,
arching, almost Western-sized sky,'' wrote the son, whose
reflections on urban design have appeared in The New Yorker, as
well as in nine books. Below the sky and neighboring rooftops,
``there's a forest-canopy view of a miniature orchard of 10
ornamental Japanese crab apple trees.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, crab apple blossoms, the deep rosy pink kind,
were pushing against the third-floor windows, frothing, as Alger
Hiss remembered them when he started writing letters from prison.
Only three a week (to seven approved recipients) were allowed and
each only two pages long. He filled the pages with a tiny scrawl,
punctuated by pen and ink sketches of the furniture in his cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of what is here is what they brought with them from
Washington, full of optimism,'' Tony Hiss explained. ``The desk,
the sofa, the piano, the table, the chair, the same green enamel
kitchen table where I read his prison letters when I was 11 and
where I read the same letters again last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The apartment is in a time warp. When the building's super
wanted to replace the toilet _ a period piece with a round (yes,
round) tank and a tiny brass lever in the middle that says,
``Push,'' the Hisses wrote to the landlord in protest. ``This
toilet belongs in the Smithsonian,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen, too, is a throwback, with the same 1940s white
enamel gas stove, shelves and sink. Only the refrigerator, covered
with Jacob's drawings, speaks of the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, look at this,'' Hiss said. ``It was in the closet, and we
hung it on the wall.'' It is the presentation copy of the preamble
to the United Nations Charter. His father was secretary-general of
the founding conference in San Francisco in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The memoir details the almost four years that Alger Hiss spent
in prison, from March 1951 to November 1954, the years when Sen.
Joseph McCarthy, R-Wis., raged, destroying, some say, the careers
of thousands of suspected communists and communist sympathizers,
before his own decline and demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alger went to jail two weeks before McCarthy made his famous
maiden speech,'' Hiss said. ``Alger's conviction really  &UR; created &LR; 
McCarthy, in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who are too young to remember the Hiss case, it was
the case that shook the nation. Books still stream forth, arguing
for and against Alger Hiss' guilt. Last Thursday, when a federal
judge ordered the grand jury testimony from the case unsealed,
legal scholars and historians lined up again, to ask, and to try to
answer the same old questions.
</P>
<P>
   Did Whittaker Chambers make up the whole story about Hiss'
passing government secrets? Did the government and an ambitious
young congressman, Rep. Richard M. Nixon, R-Calif., railroad Hiss
with questionable or manufactured evidence? Or was Hiss a Soviet
spy, with a hefty bank account hidden in Switzerland: a man who was
a truly great actor, as his accusers claimed?
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hiss' book does not argue the case, although he does cast
his father in a new light. ``This is the first time anyone has seen
the 445 letters that Alger wrote during the time he was in jail,''
Hiss said. ``In all these letters, there is not one that even hints
at any admiration for anything communist. Marx never comes up, only
Freud and, of course, Justice Holmes.'' (As a young man, Alger Hiss
clerked for the aged Supreme Court Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes.)
``Would someone who could write these letters be the evil spy his
enemies painted him as?'' Hiss asked.
</P>
<P>
   The letters will be a surprise to those who saw only the public
Alger Hiss, who, even in his son's view, projected a cold and
lawyerly aspect. They are wildly playful and supportive of his
young son, who was 9 when his father went to jail and 13 when he
came out; a son who, for the agonizing months of one trial, which
resulted in a hung jury, and then a second, was taken in by wealthy
supporters on Manhattan's Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought it wouldn't be pleasant for a kid,'' Hiss
explained. ``And of course, they assumed he'd be found not guilty
and we'd all be back together again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up very fast intellectually,'' he continued.
``Emotionally, I grew a lot slower.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he never thought of changing his last name _ despite the
occasional ``weird'' phone calls he still gets. And he never
thought of living anywhere but Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his son occupies what was his own bedroom, a large,
blue-walled cube overlooking the crab apples. Hiss and Ms. Metzger
hang out in the larger master bedroom, with a papier-mache volcano
Jacob made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this apartment,'' said Ms. Metzger, 43. ``I don't think
of it as Alger's, but I think of it as the Hiss family's.''
Referring to its basically unchanged 1950s hominess, she added:
``It's certainly not a shrine. We have the volcano, an ashtray that
Jacob made that says `No Smoking' on it _ he thought that was
really funny! _ a piece of the cow mosaic from the old Cookery
restaurant that Tony found on the street and Jacob's toy cars in
practically every room.'' She paused. ``And, yes, because it's full
of memories, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Metzger's most recent novel, ``Missing Girls,'' is a highly
autobiographical account of her own growing up in Queens, the
granddaughter of a Holocaust survivor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both survivors of something,'' Hiss said.
</P>
<P>
   On the mantel next to the prison plaque is a little oil painting
with a Christmas message painted into the bottom: ``Peace on Earth
to Men of Good Will,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of Father's sent it to him when he was in jail,''
Hiss said. ``Of course, you couldn't send a painting, so he turned
it into a Christmas card.'' The back is stamped by the censor who
let it through _ one of the tiny victories of prison life.
</P>
<P>
   The book tells of his father's effort to borrow a few books from
the prison library when his family came to visit. The books, Alger
wrote, ``would be chosen with reference to the interests of an
11-year-old and in each instance would be submitted for
examination.'' The purpose was ``to lighten the tedium of a full
two hours of unrelieved inactivity for a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hiss never knew of the request, or that it was denied,
until he started writing his memoir.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's a book I've been working on for 50 years,'' he
said. ``In another way, it's a book that began with the birth of my
own son, which allowed me to stop thinking of myself as the son and
to start thinking as a father. Then there was my father's death in
1996. I started to see things as a whole. Then the wonderful luck
that my mother had saved such a packet of letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was ``the generous offer of the prison system,''
allowing Hiss and his wife to visit Alger Hiss' cell before his
wing, the honor wing, was obliterated by renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``So here was a place that when I was a boy, he couldn't leave
and I couldn't enter,'' he wrote about his visit to the Lewisburg
cell late in 1997. ``Now I could stand in the spot where all the
letters came from. My father, looking for parallels, had written
that his room was almost as big as mine. It was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
