<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV21-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MUCH PRIVACY IS A CURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday May 21)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I think it's time that Americans accept the fact that we have no
privacy left and learn to enjoy living life in a fishbowl.
</P>
<P>
   Everything from our driving records to our credit history is
readily available to anyone who's interested. Our names, ages,
addresses, incomes, education and buying habits are all part of a
vast database that is swapped and sold like jelly glasses at a
garage sale.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I've read that if you have a person's social security
number and know his or her mother's maiden name, you can actually
become that person, which may or may not be a step up, depending on
whose identity you take.
</P>
<P>
   (I would personally opt for someone like Bill Gates, who some
people say I resemble in a bloated, splotchy sort of way, not just
because he is a multibillionaire but because he might know someone
who can debug my computer.)
</P>
<P>
   As far as I know, no one has tried, or shown any interest in
trying, to assume my identity. Whatever personal information of
mine that is out there is simply used by companies that want to
sell me something, preferably just as I'm lifting that first
succulent forkful of Hamburger Helper to my mouth at dinner time.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no way to stop these people. You could hire
goons to crack some heads, but it would be hard identifying the
proper heads to crack, plus there is no guarantee that there are
enough goons in the world to do the job. A better solution, it
seems to me, would be to offer the companies even more personal
information so they could better tailor their annoying phone calls
and mailings to my specific needs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the credit card industry seems to have acquired
information that portrays me as the kind of person who needs a
minimum of 62 credit cards. No matter how many times I tell them I
don't need any more credit cards, the calls and letters continue.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, I need to provide some additional personal information
to the credit card companies so they'll go bother somebody else and
leave me alone: My wife only allows me to carry one credit card and
she says she'll take it away if I ever use it. It seems to me that
you are wasting your time trying to give additional credit cards to
someone who uses them (it) for decorative purposes only. (This is
not entirely true. I have used my credit card to scrape bubble gum
off my shoe but this does not happen often and I think one credit
card is probably sufficient for the job.)
</P>
<P>
   I also get a lot of phone calls from people who want to
``spring-tune'' my air conditioner. I'm not in the heating and
cooling business, but I believe that one spring-tuning a year is
all the average air conditioner needs or deserves. If I accepted
the service offers of all the air-conditioning companies that call
me up, I'd have trucks lined up 12 deep, blocking traffic and also
requiring me to use my only credit card, which my wife won't allow
me to do.
</P>
<P>
   If it's not someone wanting to tune up my air conditioner or
send me another credit card, it's someone who wants me to sign up
for lawn care service. (I suspect my neighbor is behind this,
somehow.) I understand why lawn care companies might think of me as
a likely customer because my lawn - otherwise known as ``the
wasteland'' - looks like the aftermath of an experiment involving
napalm and Agent Orange. The only place vegetation grows is in the
cracks in the driveway. (Perhaps it extracts precious nutrients
from the oil stains, it's really hard to say.)
</P>
<P>
   My lawn would benefit from a lawn care service, no doubt, but
once you start down this path, it's hard to get off. How can I
justify watering, fertilizing, spraying and otherwise coddling my
lawn when my air conditioner is wheezing like a three-pack-a-day
smoker and my credit card is glowing like a hot coal?
</P>
<P>
   I'm offering this information not to gain sympathy (though
you're free to feel sorry for me if you wish), but to give the
businesses that have access to my personal file a clearer picture
of who they're dealing with, with the hope, of course, that they'll
be shamed into leaving me alone.
</P>
<P>
   If not, there's always the goons.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
