A3501 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERRY-UNION-HNS &LR;      05-19 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERRY-UNION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARM UNION SEEKS NEW ELECTION FOR STRAWBERRY WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Banking on a change of political climate since
its stunning defeat last summer, the United Farm Workers Union is
calling for a representation election at Coastal Berry Inc., the
nation's biggest strawberry grower.
</P>
<P>
   The UFW petitioned the Agricultural Labor Relations Board in
Salinas for the election on Monday, and the board must by law
schedule one on or before May 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that the atmosphere is more conducive to a free and
fair election this year than last,'' said UFW spokesman Marc
Grossman.
</P>
<P>
   Watsonville-based Coastal Berry employs some 1,500 workers and
farms 850 acres in Santa Cruz and Monterey counties and 330 acres
in Ventura County. The company's principal owner, venture
capitalist David Gladstone of Washington, D.C., is regarded as the
berry industry's most pro-union employer and has pledged in writing
to adhere to strict neutrality in the election.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1998, Coastal Berry workers voted 523 to 410 to be
represented by the Coastal Berry Farmworkers Committee, a group
which was, paradoxically, opposed to unionization and a vehement
opponent of the UFW.
</P>
<P>
   The UFW refused to participate in that election, asserting that
supervisors had created an atmosphere of fear and coercion that
made a fair election impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The Agricultural Labor Relations Board threw out the results of
that election without examining the UFW claims, instead ruling that
the election was invalid because 162 workers in Ventura County
didn't receive ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Coastal Berry has fired several of the workers who led the
opposition to the UFW's organizing campaign last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
