<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REPUBLICAN QUESTIONS HILLARY CLINTON'S N.Y. TRIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate's top Republican campaign strategist on
Wednesday questioned the propriety of First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton's New York trips at taxpayers' expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times is it appropriate for the First Lady to go to
New York?'' asked Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of the
National Republican Senatorial Committee, which coordinates all GOP
senate campaigns. ``Is the public in effect underwriting her
campaign?''
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton still undecided over a run next year for the U.S.
Senate seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
McConnell joined New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, whose campaign
aides have criticized the first lady's government-funded official
trips to New York.
</P>
<P>
   She has made eight such trips this year and is scheduled to make
another to New York City beginning Monday. Since each one is an
official trip in her role as first lady, Clinton travels with an
entourage of Secret Service agents and White House aides. The Air
Force jet that flies her around costs $836-an-hour to operate.
</P>
<P>
   A small percentage of these expenses is offset by political
sponsors who invite the first lady to appear at their events. But
the rest are financed by the U.S. treasury. McConnell argues that
since she reaps incalculable political rewards from such
appearances, it's unfair to ask taxpayers to foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested there should be some clear line between what is
reimbursable and what is properly charged to the government, but he
offered no specific solution.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was traveling Wednesday to the Southwest and her White
House press office did not respond to telephone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Malcolm, president of Emily's List and an adviser to the
first lady, called McConnell's comments a ``partisan shot made by
the leading Republican political leader in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm said McConnell is ``well aware there's a process by
which people in White House travel, and I'm sure he saw (then Vice
President George) Bush doing same thing (in 1988 during his
presidential bid) and never said anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Emily's List is a political action committee dedicated to
electing Democratic women who back abortion rights. In 1998,
Emily's List raised $7.5 million to help elect seven women
Democrats to the House and two to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell told reporters he hopes Clinton does choose to run in
New York. ``I think it will be a reinvigorating thing,'' he said.
``This will be a race that will rival the presidential race in
terms of interest across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   He joked that if the first lady decides to enter the race, ``the
best day she has will be the day before she announces.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the two prospective Republican candidates, Giuliani
and Rep. Rick Lazio, is ``intimidated'' by the prospect of facing
her, McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the first lady herself may prove to be the
main issue. ``Lots of the issues the Clintons have had to deal with
in the last eight years will be hashed out,'' McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   He was alluding to the Whitewater controversy, the Arkansas real
estate deal involving Bill and Hillary Clinton which Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr has been investigating since 1994. The other
controversy that he said Hillary Clinton may find hard to avoid is
the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal that nearly cost President Clinton
his job earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the fact that Mrs. Clinton has never lived in New
York will be a major issue, McConnell said. Giuliani has already
referred to her as a ``carpetbagger'' in speeches.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by email, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
