<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, May 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Isolated potent thunderstorms will erupt across parts of western
Kansas, western Oklahoma and western Texas Thursday afternoon and
evening as moist air rapidly rises along a dry line, which marks
the boundary between dry air from the Rockies and humid air from
the Gulf of Mexico. A jet stream disturbance approaching from New
Mexico will add further lift. Thus, a few storms may reach severe
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, clusters of showers and thunderstorms, some heavy,
will develop early over parts of the central Plains. Storms will
then migrate northeast toward the upper Mississippi Valley and
western Great Lakes later in the day. Heavy rain is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated storms are also possible in southeast Wyoming and
northeast Colorado as moist winds from the east behind a cool front
ascend the westward-sloping terrain. Late Thursday or Thursday
night, another batch of showers and thunderstorms will redevelop
over the central Plains as another jet stream disturbance arrives
from the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated heavy thunderstorms will flare within twenty miles of
the Atlantic and Gulf Coasts of Florida as humid air is lifted
along the leading edges of inland-moving sea breezes. Farther
north, rain will gradually taper off across eastern Maine and
extreme southeast New England as a sluggish trough of low pressure
18,000 feet aloft swings slowly toward the Atlantic. Clouds will be
stubborn in spots and may not break until late Thursday or Thursday
night. In the wake of the trough, a bubble of high pressure will
bring a clear, cool night to much of the Northeast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Sun-enhanced Rain &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes sunshine is necessary for substantial rain. On Tuesday
afternoon, a cold front arrived in western Pennsylvania after
partial to full sunshine had boosted surface air temperatures to
their maximums. The combination of solar heating and lifting by the
cold front resulted in heavy thunderstorms, which left as much as
three inches of rain in southwest Pennsylvania. After sunset,
storms started to weaken, and by the time the slow cold front
approached very dry central Pennsylvania, only very light rain
remained, barely settling the dust caused by a dearth of rain in
May.
</P>
</TEXT>
