<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3551 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMONDS-FOOD-AZR &LR;      05-19 1845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMONDS-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPOONFUL' AUTHOR FINDS FOOD SERVES TO HEAL, NOURISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Nina Simonds' research for her latest cookbook began
27 years ago with a nasty stomachache.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was way too yin,'' she says, explaining that her diet was
out of balance according to the Asian concept of yin and yang.
</P>
<P>
   For Americans who treat such maladies by tossing back a couple
of Tums, the idea that the foods she was eating while studying in
China could not only cause an upset stomach but cure it as well
might seem, well, foreign.
</P>
<P>
   But a traditional Chinese physician convinced Simonds that
antacids were not the answer. After a few days of eating more yang
foods such as rice congee, lamb with cinnamon and chicken soup, her
health returned.
</P>
<P>
   The almost immediate relief came as a surprise to a Boston girl
raised on her mother's hardy Jewish cooking _ dishes such as
``schmiggy,'' meatloaf frosted with mashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   As Simonds' cookbook, ``A Spoonful of Ginger'' (Knopf, $30),
suggests, food can indeed be both nourishment and medicine. It's a
philosophy that Asians have been practicing for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   And every good Jewish mother knows that chicken soup cures many
an ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Simonds, whose five previous cookbooks include ``Asian Noodles''
and ``Classic Chinese Cuisine,'' was in Phoenix recently for a
conference of the International Association of Culinary
Professionals.
</P>
<P>
   At age 46, she is in the prime of health, she says, feeling
invigorated by a diet that includes much Asian cuisine and a lot of
grilled vegetables and lean meats. She drinks green tea all day.
When her spirits need a lift, she cooks up a batch of chicken soup
with shiitake mushrooms, ginger and miso.
</P>
<P>
   While being interviewed, she sips tea and snacks on a banana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the body tells us what it needs,'' she says. ``It's
the big picture. It's regimen _ to prevent disease, to lengthen
your life and ensure good health.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Spoonful of Ginger'' is beautifully photographed. Many of
the black-and-white photos were shot during a trip across Asia that
Simonds took last year with her husband, recording company
executive Don Rose, and her editor at Alfred A. Knopf, Judith
Jones. Rose took photos of people in such countries as Malaysia,
Thailand, Laos, China and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes, developed over many years by Simonds and inspired
by Asian home cooking, are assigned to such chapters as Nourishing
Soups (Korean Clampot With Garlic Chives), Seafood (Yin-Yang Shrimp
With Hawthorn Dipping Sauce), Soybeans and Tofu (Fragrant Steamed
Pearl Balls), Poultry: Chicken and Duck (Chile Chicken With
Cashews), the Neutralizers (Wild Mushroom Fried Rice) and Sweet
Flavors (Two-Spice Vanilla Tapioca Pudding).
</P>
<P>
   The last chapter is titled ``The Kitchen Clinic and Herbal
Tonics.'' It provides recipes for teas, tonics and herbal remedies.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a book of gastronomic denial. There are pastries and
pancakes and spicy spareribs. And the recipes are not intimidating
to the Western cook. No grubs. No roasted roaches.
</P>
<P>
   Even the little golden triangles of fried tempeh look inviting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe people will eat food if it's just healthy,''
Simonds says. ``It has to taste good.''
</P>
<P>
   For too many Americans, especially women, food has become an
enemy when it should be a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the eating disorders, people have forgotten how
nurturing it can be,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling out of sorts? Try a Soothing Pear Congee.
</P>
<P>
   Depressed? Nothing boosts the spirits like Baked Black Bean
Shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Blood pressure soaring? Mix up a tonic of lonicera japonica,
chrysanthemum flower, mulberry leaf, crataegus and cirsium
japonicum.
</P>
<P>
   Simonds advises readers that her cookbook is not intended as a
medical text and that anyone with a health disorder should consult
a qualified health professional.
</P>
<P>
   But when Western medicine fails to cure the common cold, why not
cook up some Grilled Ginger Teriyaki Tuna, a Chinese remedy for
colds and flu?
</P>
<P>
   Simonds and her husband practice what she preaches, leaving them
generally free of illness and feeling energized. Simonds visits
Asia at least once a year, while Rose makes frequent trips to
London, where his company has an office. But they are home in
Salem, Mass., most nights, and try to instill good eating habits in
their 10-year-old son, Jesse.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the boy does not always follow their counsel. Mom concedes
she fixes him macaroni and cheese, and he doesn't like many
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   French fries rule.
</P>
<P>
   But Jesse doesn't eat many meats either _ a bit of chicken now
and then. He has never had a fast-food burger. Because he is
healthy, Simonds doesn't fret.
</P>
<P>
   As a culinary professional, she's often the hit of Jesse's
school. When she's out of the country, she faxes him messages to
share with his classmates. When she's in town, she's in his
classroom, cooking up specialities for holidays and special events.
</P>
<P>
   His school projects often involve the culture and cuisine of
other lands.
</P>
<P>
   Simonds says she enjoys using her special talents to enrich her
son's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of bringing what I do close to him.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wild Mushroom Fried Rice &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``A Spoonful of Ginger'') &QL; 
2 tablespoons corn or safflower oil
</P>
<P>
   8 cloves garlic, smashed lightly with the flat side of a knife,
and sliced thinly
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound fresh shiitake mushrooms, rinsed, drained, stem ends
trimmed, and caps thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound cremini mushrooms, rinsed, drained, stem ends trimmed,
and caps thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons rice wine or sake
</P>
<P>
   2 cups minced scallion greens
</P>
<P>
   5 cups cooked rice, chilled
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Heat a wok or large, heavy skillet over high heat. Add the oil and
heat until hot. Add the garlic and mushrooms and stir-fry for 1 to
2 minutes, until slightly softened. Lower the heat to medium high
and add the rice wine or sake. Partially cover and cook for 3 1/2
minutes, or until the mushrooms are tender. Uncover, add scallions,
and cook, tossing, to reduce the liquid by half.
</P>
<P>
   Add the rice, breaking it up with a spatula. Cook 2 to 3
minutes, until heated through. Add the soy sauce, chicken broth,
salt and black pepper, and toss lightly to coat. Add the cilantro,
toss to mix, and spoon the rice onto a platter and serve. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Makes 6 servings. Approximate values per serving: 420 calories, 6 g
fat, 0 cholesterol, 84 g carbohydrates, 6.7 mg fiber, 11 g protein,
706 mg sodium, 12 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vietnamese Lemon Chicken &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``A Spoonful of Ginger'') &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 whole roasting chicken, about 4 to 4 1/2 pounds, excess fat
trimmed away
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Vietnamese Seasonings: &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 lime
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk lemon grass, ends trimmed, tough outer husks removed,
and cut into 1-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 garlic cloves, peeled
</P>
<P>
   3 slices fresh ginger, each about the size of a quarter, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon crushed dried chiles or dried chile flakes
(optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Rinse chicken, drain and pat dry
inside and out.
</P>
<P>
   Remove peel from the lime and drop the peelings along with the
remaining ingredients of the Vietnamese Seasonings in descending
order into the feed tube of a food processor fitted with a steel
blade, while the machine is running (or into a blender). Blend to a
paste and rub the mixture inside the chicken and all over the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Working carefully with your fingers, make a small pocket under
the skin at the breast. Slip some of the seasonings into the
pocket, and use your fingers to spread it out evenly over the
breast. Cut the peeled lime and squeeze the juice inside the cavity
as well as over the chicken. Put the lime halves in the cavity.
</P>
<P>
   Place the chicken in a shallow roasting pan, breast side up, and
roast 1 1/2 hours, or until the juices run clear when the thigh is
pierced with a knife. Remove from the oven and cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, remove the lime from the cavity, and carve the chicken
into serving pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings. Approximate values per serving: 506 calories,
36 g fat, 163 mg cholesterol, 5 g carbohydrates, 0.7 g fiber, 39 g
protein, 153 mg sodium, 65 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soothing Pear Congee &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``A Spoonful of Ginger'') &QL; 
1/2 cup short-grain or Arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   5 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 recipe Poached Pears in a Cinnamon-Ginger Syrup
</P>
<P>
   Put the rice in a pot and, using your fingers as a rake, rinse
it under cold water to remove some of the talc, then drain it in a
colander.
</P>
<P>
   Put the rice, water and salt in a heavy saucepan with a lid.
Heat, uncovered, until boiling. Reduce heat to low, partially cover
pan, and simmer for 45 minutes, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the recipe for Poached Pears in a Cinnamon-Ginger Syrup,
but after poaching the pears, remove them with a slotted spoon and
cut them into 1/2-inch dice. Add the diced pears to the syrup and
then mix into the rice. Cook an additional 10 minutes. Mix, ladle
into soup bowls, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 to 10 servings. Approximate values per serving: 249
calories, 1 g fat, 0 cholesterol, 64 g carbohydrates, 4.6 g fiber,
2 g protein, 122 mg sodium, 3 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Poached Pears in a Cinnamon-Ginger Syrup &QL; 
(From ``A Spoonful of Ginger'') &QL; 
10 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cinnamon sticks
</P>
<P>
   8 slices fresh, unpeeled ginger, about the size of a quarter,
smashed lightly with the flat edge of a knife
</P>
<P>
   6 slightly underripe Bosc or Anjou pears
</P>
<P>
   2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
In a large pot, combine the water, sugar, cinnamon sticks and fresh
ginger. Heat until boiling, reduce the heat to low, and cook for 30
minutes so the flavors marry.
</P>
<P>
   Using a vegetable peeler or a paring knife, peel the pears, and
rub the outside with cut lemons to prevent them from turning brown.
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze the juice from the lemons and add along with the pears
to the cinnamon liquid. Heat until boiling and reduce the heat to
low, so the water barely boils. Cook, uncovered, for about 25 to 30
minutes, or until the pears are just tender. You can poke them with
the tip of a knife to test them. Remove and place in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer about 3 cups of the cooking liquid to a smaller
saucepan. (Discard any ginger and cinnamon sticks.) Heat until
boiling, reduce heat to medium, and cook about 35 minutes, or until
the liquid thickens slightly. It should be like syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the pears in serving bowls and pour the cinnamon-ginger
syrup on top. Serve. To serve cold, pour the syrup over the pears
in a large bowl, cover with plastic wrap, and refrigerate for
several hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings. Approximate values per serving: 314 calories,
1 g fat, 0 cholesterol, 82 g carbohydrates, 6.5 g fiber, 2 g
protein, 5 mg sodium, 3 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
