<HEADLINE>
SENATOR SAYS KOSOVO RECONSTRUCTION COULD COST $3 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The pricetag for rebuilding war-torn Kosovo could
go as high as $3 billion, the senator in charge of the subcommittee
dispensing foreign aid said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., whose Senate Appropriations
subcommittee on foreign operations oversees the $12.5 billion
foreign aid budget, told reporters that rehabilitating Kosovo once
the war there ends is just the beginning of a long-term U.S.
relationship with the Balkans. He cited nations such as Albania and
Macedonia, which have borne the brunt of Kosovo's refugee exodus.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how you felt about this war, there isn't any
question that once it's over, we've got a new obligation to a part
of the world we had not previously paid much attention to,''
McConnell said. ``I'm not angry about it. It's a statement of the
obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell did not put a price on long-term assistance to Albania
and Macedonia. But he estimated the cost of direct relief
assistance to Kosovo at $3 billion ``over a three-to-four year
period.''
</P>
<P>
   He said European nations such as England and Germany should
expect to pick up 75 percent of the cost. But he added that the
cost to the U.S. treasury will be substantial. This year's proposed
$12.5 billion foreign aid budget includes $600 million for aid to
the more than 800,000 ethnic Albanians driven from their homes in
Kosovo by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question that's not adequate even
for this year,'' McConnell said. ``I don't think there's anyone who
thinks the refugees are going to be back in Kosovo by next winter
in a position to lead any kind of normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the war ceases and an international force occupies
Kosovo, relief workers will face the task of essentially moving
refugee camps in Albania and Macedonia back into Kosovo, McConnell
said.
</P>
<P>
   With widespread destruction in Kosovo, there is ``no housing to
be in, even if we physically get (refugees) back into their
country,'' he said. ``This is just the beginning. We've got a huge
number of people to care for, and the United States is going to
play a substantial part of that role.''
</P>
<P>
   If Slobodan Milosevic remains in power, McConnell said, he does
not think American foreign aid should go to help Yugoslavia recover
from NATO's massive bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do inside Yugoslavia depends on the what the
government looks like once it's over,'' he said. ``If it's
essentially the same as it is now, my inclination would be to do
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
