<HEADLINE>
THE MOTHER WHO CAME OUT OF THE BASEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When she said goodbye to her baby girl, Suzanna Tatom was 16,
unwed and on her way back to high school.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't what she wanted. She was simply doing what she was
told. Besides, that's how it was back then. Getting pregnant
brought such shame to your family, you were practically forced to
have an abortion or put your baby up for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanna gave up her baby.
</P>
<P>
   Five months ago, she and 'Chelle were reunited. That's
important, because now Suzanna can come out of the basement. That's
different from the closet, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The basement is where birth mothers live when they give their
babies up for adoption, where they hide the shame and the anger and
the love they can't own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always loved her, and there's never been a day when I didn't
think about her or pray about her, and I always felt like part of
my heart was missing,'' Suzanna said.
</P>
<P>
   The very thought brings tears to her eyes, the same way the
anger and the lost years bring with them a longing for what might
have been.
</P>
<P>
   After giving her baby up, Suzanna returned to high school and
met Anthony Tatom, who would become her husband of 23 years.
Throughout the years, she said, she and Anthony made inquiries
about her baby. But it wasn't until two years ago _ after her
mother and both of Anthony's parents had died _ that Suzanna
determined she would not live through another birthday without
knowing her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day she passed away, I looked into the mirror and thought
how much I looked like my mom,'' Suzanna remembered. ``Then I
thought that there was someone out there who probably looked like
me.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 25, 10 days before her daughter's 23rd birthday, Suzanna
told Anthony that she was ready, and the couple contacted the
adoption agency. Because of confidentiality guarantees, the agency
would tell them only that 'Chelle lived in Texas. Then they heard
about TxCare, a statewide adoption resource and education
organization.
</P>
<P>
   TxCare located 'Chelle in Denton, and Suzanna narrowed her
whereabouts to the University of North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In November, they met at 'Chelle's boyfriend's apartment near
the campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I've found her and found that she had a good life,
she makes me feel I've enhanced hers,'' Suzanna said. ``So I'm
getting a little closer to forgiving myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanna Tatom felt a lot of anger for a lot of years. She wishes
that she had been stronger, that she had been assertive enough to
tell her family she wanted to keep her little girl, to say to hell
with what society thinks.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't. She was just a girl herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that, back then, society was telling us if we
kept our babies, we were being selfish and didn't love our babies
enough to give them a chance to grow up in a home with parents, and
we couldn't give them enough.''
</P>
<P>
   I've heard that argument before. It's the same one that says
women should have the right to abortions because unwanted babies
become abused babies.
</P>
<P>
   Society is like that. We make up our minds, and our judgment
becomes frozen in place, like ice. Listen to Suzanna, and the ice
runs like water again.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanna Tatom was 16 when she got pregnant, but she always loved
her baby. And even if she were too ashamed to admit it, she was
always a mother _ a good mother.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
