<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-NUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TASTE OF THE DARK SIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN MELTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I think I may have found the perfect dark beer: Diebels,
Germany's No. 1-selling dark beer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brewed since 1878 in Issum, Diebels is a balanced,
dry-malt-flavored nectar that registers a strong note on the palate
but finishes cleanly. It has none of the throaty aftertaste that
most casual beer drinkers find so problematic with most dark beers.
</P>
<P>
   The Diebels brewers make a point of saying it's brewed according
to ``Reinheitsgebot,'' the German purity law. Although it sounds
noble, it's actually an ancient law that prevents other countries
from exporting into the Fatherland, thus creating a monopoly that
keeps the German beer industry thriving. Even though the economic
need for such a rule passed eons ago, the Reinheitsgebot tradition
remains annoying _ which may be the point, come to think of it.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it makes any difference to me, one way or the other. As
long as I can find Diebels at some friendly neighborhood booze
emporium, I'm a happy swiller.
</P>
<P>
   According to its Web site, the family-owned Diebels brewery is
the leading brewer of ``altbier'' in Germany. Since
November/December 1995, (according to the German Association of
Consumer, Market and Sales Research), Diebels has held a share of
more than 60 percent of the German altbier market, which gives
Diebels the highest market share of any German beer.
</P>
<P>
   Whoop-de-doo. All I know is that from time to time, I have to
remind myself that this is a dark beer. I look at the deep, caramel
color and savor the tiny bubbles as I pour it cleanly into a
chilled glass. The head rises majestically, releasing the
brewmaster's art, then settles away quickly.
</P>
<P>
   With each swallow, the taste builds smoothly, with just a tiny
bit of sweetness, followed by the merest hint of malt on the
aftertaste. No doubt about it, this quixotic little brew is a
mystery. That's why it's so easy to have another.
</P>
<P>
   Diebels works very well with food, especially something with a
bite, like a spicy penne arrabbiata: The flavors of the brew and
the pasta dish mingle comfortingly, supportive but not
overwhelming. You may have to drive a little to find Diebels, but
it's worth the trip.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
