<HEADLINE>
TEST YOUR LITERARY KNOWLEDGE
</HEADLINE>
 QUIZ-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time for another geography lesson. Match these variably
well-known native fictions with the cities of their settings. You
pass with nine correct answers and earn an A with 12 right.
</P>
<P>
   Titles with their authors:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Advise and Consent'' by Allen Drury
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Bartleby the Scrivener'' by Herman Melville
</P>
<P>
   3. ``The Crisis'' by Winston Churchill
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Death Comes for the Archbishop'' by Willa Cather
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Dinner at Antoine's'' by Frances Parkinson Keyes
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Farewell, My Lovely'' by Raymond Chandler
</P>
<P>
   7. ``The Gay Place'' by Billy Lee Brammer
</P>
<P>
   8. ``Great Son'' by Edna Ferber
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Jennie Gerhardt'' by Theodore Dreiser
</P>
<P>
   10. ``The Late George Apley'' by John P. Marquand
</P>
<P>
   11. ``Linda Condon'' by Joseph Hergesheimer
</P>
<P>
   12. ``A Man in Full'' by Tom Wolfe
</P>
<P>
   13. ``McTeague'' by Frank Norris
</P>
<P>
   14. ``Mrs. Bridge'' by Evan S. Connell Jr.
</P>
<P>
   15. ``Native Son'' by Richard Wright
</P>
<P>
   16. ``A Simple Act of Kindness'' by Winston Estes
