<HEADER>
A3560 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHORAL-MUSIC-GIANT-TE     05-19 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHORAL-MUSIC-GIANT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHORAL COMPOSER FEELS THE DIVINE IN MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Composer Robert Young's success is based on the
principle that less is more.
</P>
<P>
   Although Young has published more than five dozen works, few
have been longer than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most frequently performed composers in America, Young
arrived at this enviable position by composing in a genre for which
there is much demand and constant need for new material: the short
choral piece.
</P>
<P>
   His latest compositions will be premiered Monday by the Fort
Worth concert choir Schola Cantorum, featuring conductor Gary
Ebensberger, at Bass Performance Hall in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Young, 76, says composing choral music is more than just
churning out four-part settings of poems. On the practical side, he
says he has a deep knowledge of what works for chorus _ and what
doesn't _ from his decades as a choral director at Baylor
University.
</P>
<P>
   But Young says his work reflects a spiritual side, too, arising
from his deep love of poetry and his belief in the ability of music
to take on the presence of God.
</P>
<P>
   Young was born and reared in California. He grew up in the
conservative, evangelical Free Methodist tradition, and he said it
gave him a sense of spirituality but left him feeling socially
isolated as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music was the one redeeming feature of my life,'' Young said,
remembering his high school years.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had not yet graduated when the Japanese bombed Pearl
Harbor in December 1941, he enlisted in the Marines. Assigned to
Honolulu in anticipation of another attack, he spent most of the
war in relative safety.
</P>
<P>
   His first experience as a conductor came when, because of his
interest in music, he was recruited to direct the music at a small
Baptist church in Honolulu. He went to the library, checked out a
book titled ``The Eloquent Baton,'' and learned basic conducting
patterns before beginning to work with a small choir.
</P>
<P>
   After being discharged from the Marine Corps in 1945, Young
applied to Oberlin College. He was accepted in spite of a poor high
school record. Midway through the first semester, he learned that
his admission had been a bureaucratic error. By mistake, his high
school had sent the impressive transcript of another student named
Robert Young.
</P>
<P>
   He was dismissed from Oberlin despite having a good record
there. A sympathetic music teacher recommended him to Otterbein
College, also in Ohio, where Young graduated with an excellent
academic record before going on to perform distinguished graduate
work at Northwestern University in Evanston, Ill., and at the
University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   During overseas study in Britain, Young researched his doctoral
thesis on Baptist hymnody of 1612-1800 and sang in the Royal Choral
Society in London. While singing with that ensemble during a
performance of Elgar's The Dream of Gerontius at the Royal Albert
Hall under conductor Malcolm Sargent, Young had one of his most
overwhelming experiences of what he calls ``the God presence'' in
music.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining ``the God presence'' in music is difficult, Young
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't be analyzed,'' he says. ``There's something else
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He cites, as specific and obvious examples, the Ninth Variation
from Elgar's ``Enigma'' Variations, the final three symphonies of
Mozart, the ``Agnus Dei'' of Palestrina's ``Missa Brevis'' and the
slow movement of Brahms' Piano Concerto No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, three years after completing his doctorate at USC,
Young accepted a position as choral director at Baylor. Shortly
after arriving on the Waco campus, he organized a select 16-voice
chamber choir that performed in the resonant marble lobby of the
Armstrong Browning Library, a building that houses this
hemisphere's most significant collection of memorabilia of Robert
and Elizabeth Barrett Browning.
</P>
<P>
   This ensemble provided the inspiration and the laboratory for
Young's exploration of choral composition, and his style was
largely inspired by the group. His music is overwhelmingly tonal,
colored by the chromaticism, occasional dissonance and close
harmonies that give modern choral music its richness. Although it
reflects the high level of expertise of the Baylor Chamber Singers,
it is music that a typical community, church or school choir can
conquer with a little work. Dissonances are carefully prepared and
approached, and each separate voice part is written to exploit the
range in which it sounds best.
</P>
<P>
   Although he never had formal composition lessons, Young relies
on a solid background in music theory and on information he gained
in classes with composer Halsey Stevens at USC. Beyond
craftsmanship, he relies on inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could mill these things out by formula,'' he says, ``but I
live with a poem a long time, until I identify with it. I go
slowly. ... It's not something you can put in a test tube.''
</P>
<P>
   No one goes into composition for the money, but Young's short
choral pieces have become notably successful; selection of some of
his works as required pieces at statewide high school events has
guaranteed heavy sales. Concert choirs in Albany, N.Y., and
Savannah, Ga., as well as Schola Cantorum in Fort Worth, have been
particularly notable advocates of Young's music, and a recording by
the Albany choir led to Young's selection in 1997 to compose a new
anthem for the installation of a high official of the Episcopal
Church at the Cathedral of St. John the Divine in New York. Young,
now an Episcopalian, had the privilege of receiving Holy Communion
at the New York church during the performance of his work.
</P>
<P>
   Young generally earns between $300 and $1,200 for a commissioned
work. Grateful for the many performances of his works by Schola
Cantorum through the years, he declined to accept a fee when
conductor Ebensberger approached him about composing a piece.
</P>
<P>
   The result of the commission is a short, three-page choral song
setting the poem ``Somewhere'' by Christina Rossetti, a
19th-century British romantic poet who has figured prominently in
Young's works through the years.
</P>
<P>
   Young officially retired in 1993 after 30 years as a full-time
faculty member, including one year of service as acting dean of the
Baylor School of Music in 1987-88. Currently, Young teaches one or
two classes in choral conducting every semester, directs the music
at St. Paul's Episcopal Church in Waco and spends a lot of time
composing at the house he shares with his wife, Betty, a counselor
at Midway High School in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
