<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY POP STARS PLAY THE BASS INSTEAD OF DALLAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, living in Fort Worth and wanting to hear well-known
musicians often meant making the hike over to Dallas venues such as
Starplex or the Music Hall at Fair Park. But the opening of Nancy
Lee and Perry R. Bass Performance Hall has reversed the flow of
concert-going traffic between Fort Worth and Big D _ at least
partially.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous acts _ including bluesmen Jonny Lang and Keb' Mo' and
jazz vocalist Randy Crawford _ have played the Bass instead of a
Dallas location, and traditional Irish heroes The Chieftains played
Fort Worth for the first time after the Bass opened.
</P>
<P>
   But the big news was Lyle Lovett's three sold-out nights in
November. Lovett had not played Fort Worth since 1992, and this
time he drew more than twice as many people as he had then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were bidding against several venues in Dallas, and it came
down to Lyle wanting to give it a try,'' said Jerry Thompson,
president of Promoterline/Caravan of Dreams. ``A lot of acts are
willing to play a smaller venue to give the fans a nicer
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it set a precedent; it changed the perception of the
ticket-buying public. People are more willing to drive here than to
other venues and pay a higher ticket price because they're willing
to pay for the amenities and the environment. The phone is ringing
off the hook with agents wanting to bring their acts here. The
hall's become a major player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lovett shows' success led to other performers playing at the
Bass.
</P>
<P>
   ``My artists love the building,'' said Garry Buck, vice
president of Monterey International, a division of the giant
Monterey Peninsula Artists booking agency, which books Lovett, Lang
and Keb' Mo.' ``It's great to have a building of this quality and
have a rock act able to play it. Keb' Mo' called me personally
after the show and told me he wanted to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass Hall's popularity is due to its reputation as an
artist-friendly hall with great acoustics as well as its
fan-friendly location, with restaurants and shops within easy
walking distance.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bongiovani, editor of ``Pollstar,'' says there is also a
certain curiosity factor at work: The hall is, after all, only a
year old. But he adds that the hall's good rep certainly helps
ensure long-term interest.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDUL/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
