A3566 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-FRASIER20-COX     05-19 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-FRASIER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Name game burns `Frasier'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an established natural law of television that the Crane men
of ``Frasier'' are funniest when they're not gettin' any. Frasier
(Kelsey Grammer) sputters, Martin (John Mahoney) grouses and Niles
(David Hyde Pierce) twists himself into a human paper clip.
</P>
<P>
   But as tonight's season finale proves, they can be funny when
they're gettin' plenty, as well.
</P>
<P>
   That's the unlikely scenario for this one-hour special,
sandwiched between a one-hour ``Friends'' finale and the season's
curtain for ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening finds Frasier back with Faye (Amy Brenneman), the
woman for whom the whole family pretended to be Jewish in the
Christmas episode. Marty is having sleep-overs with a lady friend,
and Daphne is still smitten with her fiance Donnie (does anyone
else not trust this lovey-dovey divorce lawyer, though?). That
leaves Niles alone again, naturally.
</P>
<P>
   But that changes when Niles takes up with Kit, a free-spirited
waitress at the Cafe Nervosa. Before you can sing that old Warren
Zevon song ``Poor Poor Pitiful Me'' (``She put me through some
changes, boy/ Kinda like a Waring blender''), Niles is smitten with
Kit and he's become a bohemian party boy, ludicrous in black
leather instead of his usual Armani.
</P>
<P>
   Frasier, meanwhile, keeps slipping up and calling Faye
``Cassandra,'' which turns out to be the name of the station
promotions director memorably played by Viriginia Madsen in the
Valentine's Day episode.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, none of this bodes well for long-term fulfillment for
the Cranes, which is as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Even a not-so-hot episode of ``Frasier'' is better than the best
work of most other sitcoms; like ``Seinfeld,'' these guys set the
bar very high for themselves. And stretching any sitcom to one hour
nearly always poses problems with pacing and with not quite enough
laughs over a little too long a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   So as ``Frasier'' heads into a summer of reruns, here's a tip:
Even if it's too hot to sweat, when they re-run that Christmas
episode, don't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   9 tonight on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
