<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3567 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-FANS20-COX     05-19 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-FANS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans find creative ways to make 'Star Wars' opening a holiday
 &HT;    By Bob Longino and Matt Aldag
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a day that in the minds of many ``Star Wars''
fanatics will live in infamy.
</P>
<P>
   Army Pfc. Dustin Sayes, 22, stationed at Fort Benning, felt so
strongly about Wednesday's opening of George Lucas' ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' that he spent three months
fashioning himself a Darth Maul costume.
</P>
<P>
   So there he stood Wednesday afternoon outside United Artists'
Perimeter Pointe theater _ all gussied up from horned head to
booted toe as ``Phantom Menace's'' red-and-black poster boy for the
Dark Side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so `Star Wars.' It had the right amount of phrases from
the original,'' said Sayes, who drove to Perimeter Pointe on
Tuesday night, watched the first post-midnight screening early
Wednesday, slept in his car and was up bright and early for the
theater's 10 a.m. Wednesday showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am gonna go see it a few more times,'' Sayes said. ``It is
one of those movies that is definitely re-watchable _ like the
originals.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of metro Atlantans saw the film Wednesday, many at
midnight screenings but some during daytime showings, playing what
the Internet has dubbed ``Wookiee Hooky'' from work or school (one
employment agency generously estimated that 2.2 million Americans
would skip work or schedule time off Wednesday to see the film).
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of seats were available for many of the daytime showings.
After all, ``Phantom Menace'' is playing at about 35 theaters in
metro Atlanta and North Georgia and more than 2,900 more across the
country. But the film also appeared to be on track to set a one-day
box office record, topping the $26.1 million tally set by ``The
Lost World: Jurassic Park'' in 1997. While Exhibitor Relations in
Los Angeles said it would not release initial dollar figures until
today, some Hollywood executives have predicted the film could
bring in as much as $45 million for its first day. Some expect it
will make up to $140 its first weekend, another record.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many tickets are sold, the $115 million ``Phantom
Menace'' is already a moneymaker because of advertising tie-ins.
For example, Hasbro, one of 75 licensees, paid nearly $400 million
for toy rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was frantic to get here because my dad took me to the first
showing of `The Return of the Jedi' and I wanted to do the same
thing for my stepson,'' said Kamaria Johnson, 25, who saw the film
with her husband, Leonard, 38, and his son Christopher, 9, at AMC's
North DeKalb Mall 16. ``I don't think it has to be good. It's about
recapturing the awe I had (with the earlier films) as a child or a
senior in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a drubbing by several national film critics, many local
moviegoers gave ``Phantom Menace'' a spirited thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked it a lot and can't wait for `Episode II,' '' said
Jason Awcock, 23, of Suwanee (Ga.), who emerged from seeing the
film with a big grin on his face at Regal Cinemas' new Hollywood 24
megaplex.
</P>
<P>
   But other ``Star Wars'' fanatics weren't exactly charmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I camped out for tickets for seven hours, and now I guess I
wish I hadn't,'' said Paul Herris, 26, of Atlanta. ``I was
disappointed. I was expecting a lot more. I thought George Lucas
would write it more maturely.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Phantom Menace'' has been the kind of cultural Force
most Hollywood movies never achieve.
</P>
<P>
   So far, fans nationwide have purchased a record 250,000 tickets
for the film off the Internet and online kiosks, according to
Atlanta's National Data Corporation. Other fans waited in lines for
hours or days _ and, outside Mann's Chinese Theatrer in Los
Angeles, sometimes weeks _ for tickets. One group of fans, led by
Chris Petersen, 29, of Jonesboro (Ga.), camped out in blow-up
rubber Darth Maul and Queen Amidala chairs for about 30 hours at
Perimeter Pointe to await that theater's first showing. They
already had tickets, but wanted to commemorate the original ``Star
Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad took me 22 years ago to the first film,'' said
Petersen, who returned the favor by taking his dad Tom Petersen, of
Fayetteville (Ga.), to a Wednesday showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the things I'm most excited about,'' said
Petersen, who took off work as a computer staffer for Clayton
County (Ga.) public schools in order to see the movie. ``He took me
and now I get to take him.''
</P>
<P>
   Some businesses, such as Atlanta's The Headline Group and
Macquarium declared the opening a holiday, both buying tickets for
all their employees.
</P>
<P>
   In Fayetteville, Garry Brannon of College Park (Ga.) has bought
four tickets for one of the Thursday night showings at the
Tinseltown 17 and will leave work at B&AMP;B Graphics early to take his
wife, Darla, and two kids to see ``Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're shutting the plant down,'' Brannon joked. He and Darla,
after all, aren't just the owners, they're the entire B&AMP;B staff.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing: Elizabeth Lee, Ralph Ellis
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino and Matt Aldag write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
