<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVELS HAUNTED BY ACTORS' FACES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does an enduringly successful movie or television mini-series of
a novel determine our perception of a compelling fictional
character? Are these imagined people forever more perceived as
different from what their creators might have intended?
</P>
<P>
   When readers sit down with ``Hannibal,'' the sequel to ``The
Silence of the Lambs,'' will they see in their minds Anthony
Hopkins and Jodie Foster? If they do, is that a plus or minus for
the reader and the writer who created the character in the first
place? Moreover, can a great actor steal a great character from the
writer?
</P>
<P>
   These questions are prompted by the forthcoming publication of
Thomas Harris' ``Hannibal'' (Delacorte Press) and Martin Cruz
Smith's just-published ``Havana Bay'' (Random House) in which the
ever complex and evolving Russian detective Arkady Renko from
``Gorky Park'' returns for the fourth time.
</P>
<P>
   Generally such questions can only be raised in literary
thrillers because the characters do return in book after book, and
their fictional persons have unconscious internal stories that not
only change and grow with each book but also are intricate enough
to force a collaboration between the writer and the reader. Readers
have to use the author's hints to create part of the novel for
themselves, rather like connecting dots to get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Another towering book character in serious thrillers _ one to
match the serial killer Hannibal Lecter and the FBI agent Clarice
Starling and Renko _ was George Smiley, now retired, probably the
greatest creation of John le Carre, the master literary spy
novelist. I say Smiley is retired because Sir Alec Guinness'
portrayal in the 1980 mini-series ``Tinker, Tailor, Soldier, Spy''
was such a triumph that the author said the actor ``took the
character away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing Smiley after Smiley-through-Guinness had entered the
public domain was very difficult,'' le Carre has said. ``In a sense
his screen success blew it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith had no such problem with Renko. While ``The Silence of the
Lambs'' won five Academy Awards in 1991, the screen version of the
best-selling ``Gorky Park'' in 1983 was unmemorable, and the image
of William Hurt, who played him in the movie, certainly doesn't pop
to mind when one sits down with a Renko novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that Arkady is almost safe even from me, let alone
from an actor at this point,'' Smith said. ``Renko seems to really
exist. He's braver and more intelligent that I am. He always sort
of does things reluctantly but he does them. He doesn't want to go
into dark rooms unnecessarily.'' The writer said that in a way
Renko was fortunate that there is no Hopkins in his life, but that
he, as author, was mindful that a great movie would strengthen book
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smiley was intelligent and intriguing and fun, and he and le
Carre were real intellectuals,'' Smith said. ``Arkady conceivably
could be happy as a schoolteacher. The careful reader knows more
about him than he knows about himself.'' True enough, but in this
latest novel Renko is shaken up, at the end of his rope, still
``trying to fix himself in the universe, as if he has some control
of where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris' sequel will go on sale on June 8, with a first printing
of 1.2 million copies, up from the 500,000 originally planned. It
is expected to be the big novel of the summer and there is a frenzy
in Hollywood to get the rights to produce the movie, and bring back
Hopkins as Lecter and Ms. Foster as Starling, Jonathan Demme as
director and Ted Talley as scriptwriter.
</P>
<P>
   Lecter, in all his evilness, has become almost a cult figure,
and to his fans the idea of anyone but Hopkins playing him is
unthinkable if not laughable. Such actor-character identification
is not uncommon. To many James Bond movie addicts there was only
Sean Connery. Nonetheless, all the post-Connery Bond movies
succeeded, probably because Bond, unlike Lecter and Renko and
Smiley, is a cartoon character.
</P>
<P>
   Harris never gives an interview. ( Smith happens to be a friend
of mine.) But Harris' publisher and editor, Carole Baron, said that
any impact that Hopkins and Ms. Foster would have on the reader of
the novel was not important to him. Harris never saw the movie in
the theater or on video, she said. ``He may have, I think he did,
recently catch part of it on television,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was thrilled the movie won all the prizes and would be
thrilled if Hopkins did it again,'' Ms. Baron said. ``He's a
realist, a very pragmatic, thoughtful person. We discussed the le
Carre comment and the issue of whether the character was co-opted
by the actor. Tom is confident that what he wrote is his, and the
rest of the world can do what it does about the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert B. Parker writes a different sort of action best seller
for Putnam's, with a more straightforward story, less complex than
the literary thrillers. Each is a textbook model of linear
narrative. The main character in his continuing troupe is Spenser,
private detective, one of the great creations of the genre, who has
appeared in 25 books. Spenser was played by Robert Urich on
television in 1985 although it was the actor Robert Mitchum he had
in mind when he started writing the books. There are plans for A&AMP;E
to produce five new Spenser movies for television, with Joe
Mantegna as the detective.
</P>
<P>
   Spenser is more violent and more complicated in the books than
on television, but also funnier, Parker said, adding, ``People say
to me, `I can't imagine anyone but Robert Urich when I read your
books,' but I cannot control beyond a certain point what people
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere George Smiley is growing roses. His admirers wished
that his wife would stop fooling around with other men, but le
Carre would not grant him that domestic peace. We recently learned
that Arkady Renko had been rooting around in Havana since we last
encountered him in Moscow in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But what has Lecter been doing since last seen in 1988 as he was
off to have a friend for dinner with a fine Chianti? His publisher,
Ms. Baron, would only say that he ``was pursuing his interests.'' A
scary thought.
</P>
<P>
   As for the author? ``He doesn't repeat himself. He takes the
whole story to new levels, and explores things of his own
imagination.'' That crafted, enigmatic answer will have to do until
next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
