A3578 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-BOS &LR;      05-19 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES SING A TEAM SONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ It wasn't a scream in the ear, more a tap on the
shoulder. Psst, the Buffalo Sabres quietly insisted on the eve of
their playoff series against the Bruins, we're not just Dominik and
the Dominos.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that they begrudged their resident rock star, Dominik
Hasek, any of his overwhelming acclaim. ``He's the best goaltender
in the world,'' said center Curtis Brown. ``Maybe the best player
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just that the public obsession with Hasek tended to obscure
the supporting cast, dismissed as so many Sabre spear-carriers.
``We have other things going on this team,'' coach Lindy Ruff
maintained.
</P>
<P>
   Do they ever. That's why the Sabres are going to the Eastern
Conference finals for the second straight year, having completed a
six-game burial of the Bruins with a 3-2 victory Tuesday night in
which all their considerable qualities _ resounding forechecking,
startling speed, aggressive defense, and yes, pretty decent
goaltending _ were on display. The undeniable conclusion was that
Hasek may be the major element in the Sabres' equation of success,
but he gets plenty of help. Anonymous help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just waiting for people to start listening to us,'' said
center Michael Peca, the team captain. ``We never steer from the
fact that Dom is No. 1 here. But we've got a lot of guys with pride
and character who come to play. As long as we know that in this
room, it's irrelevant what anyone else says.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the word spread far beyond the Sabres' locker stalls _
right into the Bruins' souls. Hasek's magic was needed only in
spurts; for much of the series, Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe was at
least his equal. Everywhere else, the Sabres were clearly superior,
and they were on the Bruins like an anvil most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some hidden talent that hasn't been exposed,'' Ruff
said in the wake of the clincher, which followed up a four-game
first-round sweep of Ottawa and created a Queen Elizabeth Way
conference finals against Toronto, 90 minutes and one international
border up the road. ``Now it's starting to get exposed. Dom is the
glue that holds us together, gives us a lot of confidence. But I
can't say enough about the Peca-(Dixon) Ward-(Vaclav) Varada line.
Curtis Brown played great. (Wayne) Primeau, (Erik) Rasmussen, the
timely scoring we got without (Miroslav) Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Sabres managed to rattle the Bruins even without
their lone 40-goal scorer, Satan, sidelined for the series with a
deep ankle bruise. In his absence, all the Buffalo soldiers
contributed.
</P>
<P>
   Peca in particular was a revelation. Renowned as the NHL's
premier defensive forward, he showed his 27 regular-season goals
were no accident as he tied Brown for the team lead in series
scoring with three goals and two assists. Beyond that, he, Ward,
and Varada harassed Boston's top line, anchored by center Jason
Allison, to the point of virtual invisibility. ``Our offensive
checking line,'' Ruff called the trio.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Primeau were two other unheralded two-way factors. And
even though a couple of Buffalo's subsidiary scoring threats, Stu
Barnes and Geoff Sanderson, didn't hit the net, their speed and
relentlessness created havoc for the Bruins and opened the way for
their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of our strengths,'' said Brown, ``because the
opposition doesn't know who to cover some nights.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense was a marvel, too. Jay McKee and Rhett Warrener kept
Hasek's turf essentially free of debris. Alexei Zhitnik (one goal,
four assists) and Jason Woolley (two goals, three assists) not only
were attentive in their own end but provided the pinching in the
Boston zone Ruff considered vital to make up for the lack of
sustained offense.
</P>
<P>
   And Zhitnik and Peca led an attack that smothered the Bruins
with concussive checking, even if Boston coach Pat Burns, relying
on his policeman's background, did decry Buffalo's behavior as
criminal, a futile effort to create a diversion and influence the
officiating.
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate aftermath of their triumph, the Sabres were
relatively subdued. That's because they have merely equaled last
season's achievement, when they lost to the Washington Capitals in
six games in the Eastern finals. Now they regard the job as only
half done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to win more now,'' said Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Last spring, Hasek was considered the Sabres' one
and only weapon. This time they have the domino effect going for
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
