<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN GOVERNOR DENOUNCES CORRUPTION, URGES ECONOMIC OPENNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A leading Mexican opposition candidate for
president said Wednesday that his country will never crack down on
drug lords or fix its economy as long as the ruling party remains
in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become experts in surviving crisis, but not in
stabilizing the economy for our companies,'' Vicente Fox Quesada,
governor of the central state of Guanajuato, told a gathering of
professors and congressional staff members in the Capitol Building.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Mexican government must balance its budget to
convince both domestic and international investors that the country
is stable. Fox, a manufacturer of cowboy boots and former Coca-Cola
Mexico executive, also embraced privatization of state-owned
industries and the opening of his country's economy to
international competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalization is not a threat to those who do their homework
and can compete,'' said Fox, whose state exports to more than 100
countries and has investors from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who has been campaigning nationwide for a year for the
presidential nomination of the conservative National Action Party,
or PAN, also defended the North American Free Trade Agreement,
saying it was ``key'' to Mexico's economic future.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Harris Poll, nearly three out of four Mexicans
surveyed said the 1994 trade pact, which seeks to eliminate trade
barriers between Canada, Mexico and the United States, has been
good for the United States while only 43 percent said it was also
helping Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's nationwide campaign has helped forge an early advantage in
opinion polls. He leads Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, the mayor of
Mexico City, who is the likely candidate of the left-leaning Party
of the Democratic Revolution, or PRD.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also leads all potential candidates from the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, including Interior
Minister Francisco Labastida Ochoa, who is believed to be President
Ernesto Zedillo's preferred choice.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has dominated Mexico's government for more than 70
years, but opposition parties have been steadily chipping away at
its power. The congressional elections in 1997 were a watershed,
with four opposition parties capturing 261 seats in the 500-member
lower house of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, in a shift away from political patronage and toward the
democratization that Zedillo has promised, this week announced that
it would hold a primary for the first time later this year to
select a successor to Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the PRI move to a primary, Fox said the Mexican people
will be looking for change in the 2000 presidential elections after
so many years under PRI leadership. ``Not even communism lasted as
long as the PRI,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   On the issues of drugs and crime, the governor said corruption
has become so endemic among state and federal officials that only a
new government could hope to root it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI has not done anything to stop corruption in 70 years
and they will not do anything in another 70 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said the most effective way to end corruption was for the
country to have ``full democracy'' in which all public officials
were held accountable to the people through elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people know a mayor or governor or any other official
has taken money, they will kick him out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each year the United States wrestles with certifying Mexico as a
partner in the war on drugs. And as a perennial part of that
process, critics cite rampant corruption in the government as a
reason not to extend the certification, without which Mexico could
lose some U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said improving the economy and reducing crime eventually
will be determined in large part by how well Mexico educates its
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need an education revolution in this country, for without
it little can be achieved,'' said Fox, who holds a bachelor's
degree in business administration from Universidad Iberoamericana
in Mexico City and a management diploma from Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Mexican government should guarantee every citizen
the right to attend high school and college. Currently, the average
Mexican has fewer than seven years of formal education, compared to
14 years for industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must ensure that every Mexican has the opportunity to move
forward,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address of mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
