<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-POET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN NAMES A LAUREATE OF POEMS, NOT SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Andrew Motion, a 47-year-old London poet, critic,
biographer and professor of creative writing, was chosen Wednesday
to become Britain's poet laureate, succeeding Ted Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Motion was seen as the most conventional of the many mooted
candidates, and his selection put to rest rumors alarming to
traditionalists that Tony Blair, the modernity-minded prime
minister, might bypass known writers in favor of a ``people's
poet.'' Sir Paul McCartney was one name mentioned in that context.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes held the post for 14 years until his death in October.
The job has in the past been a lifetime appointment underwritten by
a case of sherry and 100 pounds ($162) a year, but in a departure
from custom, Wednesday's statement from 10 Downing St. said that
Motion's appointment would be for 10 years and that there would be
an annual payment of 5,000 pounds ($8,100).
</P>
<P>
   The poet laureate is approved by the queen but chosen from a
short list by the prime minister. Past honorees include Tennyson,
Wordsworth, Cecil Day-Lewis, John Masefield and John Betjeman. The
first poet laureate was John Dryden in 1670, and although there is
no formal job description, it is understood to necessitate writing
verse about the royal family and on grand national and ceremonial
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Where many poets mentioned as candidates for the post balked at
this requirement, Motion had demonstrated his willingness by
writing, unbidden, a poem about the death of Diana, Princess of
Wales. The poem, ``Mythology,'' read in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``Your life was not your
</P>
<P>
   own to keep
</P>
<P>
   or lose. Beside the river,
</P>
<P>
   swerving under ground,
</P>
<P>
   your future tracked you,
</P>
<P>
   snapping at your heels;
</P>
<P>
   Diana, breathless, hunted
</P>
<P>
   by your own quick
</P>
<P>
   hounds.''
</P>
<P>
   He also marked the passing of Hughes, whom he greatly admired,
with verse.
</P>
<P>
   Glasgow poet Carol Ann Duffy said recently that if chosen she
would refuse to celebrate in verse the next royal event, the
marriage this summer of Prince Edward and Sophie Rhys-Jones. ``No
self-respecting poet should have to,'' she told The Guardian.
``There are so many more interesting things to do with the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Numbers of other poets let it be known that they did not want to
be considered for the post at all. When a reporter at The New York
Times called Craig Raine, an Oxford poet, last December to ask if
he was interested, he exclaimed, ``Oh God, no!'' and hung up the
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes became laureate only after Philip Larkin rejected it.
Though widely admired as a great poet, he was faulted to the point
of ridicule for much of the verse he composed in the position.
</P>
<P>
   Motion, who had made it widely known that he would like the job,
said Wednesday that he saw the post as ``an extremely complex and
interesting challenge for a poet.'' Speaking from Sydney,
Australia, where he was attending a literary festival, he said, ``I
think that I want to honor the traditional responsibilities, to
write poems about royal occasions and so on, but I am also very
keen to diversify the job, or at least make those poems part of the
wider national issues that I also want to write about.'' He said he
particularly wanted to promote poetry in schools.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a comment that he had been viewed as the ``safe''
choice for the job, Motion said, ``Everything I have done in my
life I have intended to reform, so I didn't really recognize that
description of me.'' He vowed that he would not write poems that
are ``merely sycophantic or sentimental.''
</P>
<P>
   Motion lives in Islington, the North London neighborhood where
Blair lived before moving to 10 Downing St. He studied at Oxford
and holds the creative writing professorship at the University of
East Anglia in Norwich. He has published nine volumes of verse,
written a well-regarded biography of Keats and won the Whitbread
Prize for his life of Larkin, the poet who declined the laureate
position.
</P>
<P>
   Though the post itself is not held in universally high esteem,
the race to see who will get it stirs broad interest, and official
odds are quoted at William Hill, Britain's biggest betting agency.
Besides Ms. Duffy, candidates making it onto the agency's lists
included Seamus Heaney, Derek Walcott, Wendy Cope, Benjamin
Zephaniah, James Fenton, Tom Paulin and Geoffrey Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial Wednesday welcoming the expected choice of
Motion, The Times of London called him ``a poet of quiet
understanding, gentle humanity and lyric force. His is a very
British body of work, bound by sea and salt flats, personal loss
and the national past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
