<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESERVATION-FLAG20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'STAR-SPANGLED BANNER' BENEFITS FROM PRESERVATION GRANT
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not the rockets' red glare, but a 90-year onslaught
of indoor light, air pollution and temperature change has the
original Star-Spangled Banner on its way to the Smithsonian
Institution's version of an intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning early next year, a team of museum conservationists
will undertake a meticulous inch-by-inch cleaning of the
30-by-34-foot woolen flag that inspired Francis Scott Key's famous
1814 poem.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration effort, which officials of the Smithsonian's
National Museum of American History say will take will more than a
year, was one of 62 projects named Wednesday to receive federal
historic preservation grants under the new ``Save America's
Treasures'' program.
</P>
<P>
   The grants were announced by First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
Other projects include preservation of the 1905 Wright Flyer in
Dayton, Ohio, restoration of historic Ebenezer Baptist Church in
Atlanta and stabilization of Fort Jefferson in the Dry Tortugas
National Park in Monroe County, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Smithsonian officials say cleaning the flag and re-exhibiting it
will cost $18 million before the job is finished.
</P>
<P>
   They say they are not trying to make the flag that flew over
Baltimore's Fort McHenry during the War of 1812 ``look like new.''
</P>
<P>
   But they hope that by scrutinizing nearly every thread in the
flag and cleaning it with dry cleaning solution and special vacuum
cleaners, they can stabilize it and arrest the deterioration that
has done a lot more damage than British troops did with their
rockets and bombs bursting in air.
</P>
<P>
   The work is being done in a special laboratory and has been
turned into another Smithsonian exhibit: the public can watch
conservators while they blot, vacuum and scrub.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to some stains, the wool has been weakened by
exposure to light and oxygen in the air, said Suzanne
Thomassen-Kraus, a museum conservator.
</P>
<P>
   Besides cleaning it up, museum officials have decided to remove
a linen backing that a team of Boston seamstresses hand-sewed to
the flag in 1914, seven years after the banner was donated to the
Smithsonian and 17 years before the song was officially named the
national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   A new backing material has not yet been selected.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
