<HEADER>
A3600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARTBREAKER-BOOK-REV     05-19 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTBREAKER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HEARTBREAKER:' FINGERNAILS, CAKE BOXES; THE FEAR IS EVERYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To get quickly into the mood of ``Heartbreaker,'' Robert
Ferrigno's fifth and latest noir crime thriller (after ``The Horse
Latitudes,'' ``The Cheshire Moon,'' ``Dead Man's Dance'' and ``Dead
Silent''), consider the character Armando.
</P>
<P>
   Armando is ``a slender sociopath from the Medellin slums with a
mouth like a kewpie doll, his hair a nest of braids tied with gold,
blue, and red ribbons, the colors of the Colombian flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Armando is ``what the South Americans called a dead boy, an
utterly loyal assassin, devoid of compassion or desire.'' His
favorite weapons are the tips of his right-hand middle and index
fingers, to the nails of which he has epoxied ``surgical-steel
chips sharp enough to shave with,'' and lacquered pink to match his
real nails. When he flutters his hands in the air his nails look
like ``flamingos taking off.'' When he flutters them close to his
victims they often bleed without at first understanding why.
</P>
<P>
   Armando, a bodyguard, is among the many unpleasant characters
who infest the plot of ``Heartbreaker.'' His boss, Junior Mayfield,
is one of the remaining ``good ol' boys'' in the Florida drug trade
not ``killed off or scared off when the South Americans moved in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cali cartel tortured informers with chain saws; Junior
threw a barbecue, sent the blackened head to the magpie's family in
a Baskin-Robbins cake box. The Cubans introduced Mac-10 drivebys;
Junior responded with a truck bomb that leveled Diego Ortiz's
mansion on Key Biscayne, killing Ortiz, his wife and children, five
servants, and eight bodyguards.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Junior wants to sic Armando on Valentine (Val) Duran, an
undercover cop who has been messing up Junior's business. To
protect his grandmother, Val has moved with her to Los Angeles,
where with nothing but the best intentions he has gotten himself
involved in yet another dangerous situation.
</P>
<P>
   Having fallen for Kyle Abbott, a beautiful marine biologist who
lives down the hall from him in his new apartment, Val gets invited
to the home of her rich mother and stepfather, Gwendolyn and
Charles Abbott II. There he meets Kyle's handsome playboy
stepbrother, Charles Abbott 3d, nicknamed Kilo for the kilogram of
marijuana the police once caught him with in his car.
</P>
<P>
   Kilo's date is Jackie Hendricks, a stunning redhead whom, it
turns out, he has hired to kill his stepmother (Kyle's mother) for
control of the family money she doesn't trust in his squandering
hands. When Val discovers this plot, he finds himself hunted not
only by Junior and the pernicious Armando but also by Kilo's and
Jackie's muscle, Darryl Dekker, an oversize psychopath with a mind
that seems to have been unhinged by ``a whiff of Saddam's nerve
gas.'' What is distinctive about Ferrigno's gripping action is that
as usual it is often set in a natural world whose appeal he makes
the reader vividly feel. When Val and Kyle first meet they walk
under a night sky that prompts Val to remark, ``My grandmother
would see a sky like this, and she'd say that it looked like God
had dropped stars across the night and not bothered to pick up
after himself.''
</P>
<P>
   At the denouement of their affair, they take a ride in the
motorboat Kyle uses for her research. ``Forty yards away the sea
burst into a huge plume that became a gray whale, then another and
another, the sea erupting with whales, drenching Val and Kyle with
spray. Val counted at least 11 or 12 of them breaching, adults and
calves cavorting in the twilight. Their boat rocked wildly, water
slopping over the sides, while he hung on, too overwhelmed to be
frightened. The whales were gone as quickly as they had arrived,
the waves returning to their choppy regularity. The night was empty
without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this a world, then, where every prospect pleases, and only
man is vile? Hardly. Among Val's quirky friends is Oscar, a lawyer
whose hobby is building a miniature golf course modeled on horror
movies. Kyle is not impressed. ``Horror movies are fake,'' she
says. ``I'm used to the real thing.''
</P>
<P>
   When she contemplates the fifth hole of Oscar's course, based on
``Invasion of the Body Snatchers,'' she describes a water beetle,
Dytiscus, whose larval form is equipped with hollow sickle-shaped
mandibles ``sharp as razors.'' With them Dytiscus impales creatures
that float by, ``maybe a mosquito wriggler,'' injects digestive
acid into them and pumps their dissolved insides out.
</P>
<P>
   `` `When Dytiscus is done, the wriggler is just an empty bag of
skin drifting off in the water.' Kyle grinned at Val in triumph.
`That's a horror show.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As Val remarks in another context, ``Mother Nature loves a
winner.'' When Ferrigno is done, most of his characters are empty
bags of skin, drifting off in the ether. Yet the reader is
altogether entertained.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HEARTBREAKER'
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Ferrigno
</P>
<P>
   307 pages. Pantheon. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
