<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUICK-REFURBISH-ART-9     05-19 1776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICK-REFURBISH-ART-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTANT HOME: READY, SET, DECORATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It had been a volatile week on Wall Street. On the
Big Board, trading was heavy; the Dow marched steadily toward 9000.
But last July, Carey Maloney and Hermes Mallea were busy
orchestrating their own big deals.
</P>
<P>
   The designers of M (Group) were reeling their Rolodexes and
flexing their shopping-arm muscles on behalf of Barry Gesser, a
single, 35-year-old hedge-fund manager, who had purchased a house
in Bedford, N.Y., and right before Memorial Day asked the designers
to ``pull his place together'' by the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted it done _ spare no expense _ in six weeks: 10
bedrooms, a pool house, stables, tennis courts and two three-car
garages _ overhauled, outfitted and furnished, right down to a
selection of clothes hangers.
</P>
<P>
   So, Maloney and Mallea were suited up for action, directing 25
painters as they hand-glazed the dining room pale robin's-egg blue
and white-washed the fences, flying in a suite of teak garden
furniture from California, selecting a hand-knotted rug from Doris
Leslie Blau for the living room, having the mint julep cups
monogrammed and overseeing 24 window washers.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the third week, I was wondering, What have we gotten
into?'' Maloney said. ``I would never do it again. We were just
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   When the opening bell dings on Wall Street these days, it's not
just the traders, brokers and the hedge-fund managers who are off
and running. Their architects and designers are on the move, too:
going to auctions, flying in French antiques, commissioning fine
woodworkers, paneling libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Million-dollar decorating marathons have become a fact of life
for many designers catering to the under-40 Wall Street set. This
new generation of getters and spenders is no longer satisfied with
Porsches and $1,000 bottles of Petrus, the traditional perks of the
bull-market trade.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mr. Darcy, Jane Austen's bachelor extraordinaire, these men
and women demand well-appointed manses custom-furnished, fully
curated (with the latest electronics, not art) and loaded with
personality. The designer's will do in a pinch. When Maloney and
Mallea asked Gesser's secretary for personal snapshots as a homey
touch, and none arrived in time, they filled his frames with
pictures of their chihuahua, Pancho.
</P>
<P>
   For trading-floor millionaires, speed is of the essence,
transforming decorating _ historically, a painstaking process of
soul-searching followed by shopping, finding, returning, picking
and waiting, then waiting some more for delivery of the goods _
into a homesteading steeplechase.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys took the ball and ran,'' Gesser said. ``I had
nothing to do with it. It was great.'' He had wanted a look that
would ``wow'' visitors but still be relaxed enough ``to have your
25-year-old girlfriend over to bounce a little bit on the
couches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We Wall Streeters want the best,'' he added. ``We want to buy
the right stuff, but we don't necessarily know what it is. So, we
turn to pros like Carey and Hermes. I saw that they'd done the
Bronfmans' place,'' he said, referring to Clarissa and Edgar
Bronfman Jr., ``and I figured if anyone knows what the right stuff
is, they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald O. Perelman's five-week renovation of the Creeks in East
Hampton, N.Y., has also become the stuff of legend for Wall
Streeters feeling the homing instinct. A local real estate agent,
Tina Fredericks, confirmed that the financier saw the
12,000-square-foot black stucco mansion on a Saturday, closed the
$12 million deal on Sunday and by Monday had more than 30
contractors working to get ready for the Fourth of July in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured that's what I wanted for July 4th, too,'' Gesser
said. ``I told them: `I don't care what it takes. Just do it.'''
His six-week project, he said, cost in the low millions.
</P>
<P>
   For the connoisseur consumer, spending clout used to mean being
able to buy the highest quality at any cost. Today, risk-taking
clients go for a different premium: they want high quality twice as
fast, leaving the design profession to do the sweating.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they want people to know they paid overtime to get it,''
Maloney said.
</P>
<P>
   While some design professionals say these clients' rapid-fire
decision-making and obsession with ``status details'' _ such as
getting Barbra Streisand's acoustician on the job _ are admirably
direct, others say they are overwhelmed just talking to the fresh
princes of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have done a seven-bedroom house from ground up, with
everything in it, between Labor Day and Memorial weekend,'' said
Carl D'Aquino, a Manhattan designer. ``I've done it twice, but I
don't like it. You have to be in war mode. You have to be in
condition. And your general contractor has to be big enough to
throw 30 people at the project.''
</P>
<P>
   For D'Aquino, a paneled library is often the most daunting
challenge. ``They all have to have a paneled library, but they
don't have any books,'' he said of a handful of Wall Street
clients. ``They don't even read magazines!'' He recalled moving one
bookless 30-year-old bachelor into a three-bedroom apartment with a
library. ``One day, he told me: `I bought a book today!' It stopped
me in my tracks. `Good! Which one?' I said. Well, he didn't know
the name of the book. He only knew that it was leather-bound with
gold lettering. It turned out to be Moby Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   An aura of impersonality often typifies the stir-to-dissolve
decor of young Wall Streeters, as might be expected when your
designer orders everything, down to the mood candles. ``They're
only interested in surface,'' lamented one designer, who requested
anonymity because he works with several trader clients. ``The '80s
Wall Streeters at least made an attempt to understand design. Now,
all they want is styled image.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is an impressive decisiveness. ``There's no playing
around,'' D'Aquino noted. ``If they like it, they like it right
away.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lyle Wilpon, 32, an investment banker, who admitted that he is
``compulsive about details,'' made that work for him. His designer,
Gary Mickelson, recreated the calming, beige-on-beige palette of
the Frick Museum in a new Park Avenue apartment _ ``to soothe
someone dealing with different time zones.''
</P>
<P>
   In a technique employed by many decorators working with
time-conscious clients, Mickelson relied on one furniture maker,
Todd Hase, to make practically all the furnishings. But the detail
that his client enthused most about was the Gracious Home tie rack
the designer installed in the closet. ``I got about 15 million
calls about the tie rack,'' Mickelson recalled. ``He counted the
prongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Obsession with detail doesn't mean a client is interested in
getting involved in the decorating process. Because Gesser didn't
want to shop, his designers took Polaroids of fabrics and antiques
and asked him to eliminate ones he couldn't live with. ``He never
knew for sure what he was actually getting,'' Maloney said, noting
that it took Gesser about a minute to select 40 pieces of
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The dining-room chairs were hand-built by Sotheby's Restoration,
a service offered by the auction house, which was able to copy
antiques in time. To avoid the prolonged vigil of waiting for
custom-ordered fabrics, the designers selected only materials in
stock. ``We didn't show him anything he couldn't have,'' Maloney
said.
</P>
<P>
   On July 3, the day Gesser moved in, there were 50 people
swarming over the place. The driveway had been regraveled 40
minutes earlier; the fences were still being painted as he passed
through the gate in his black Lincoln Navigator. A breakfast table
by the pool was laid out. The library shelves were stocked from a
local bookstore, Maloney said: ``Hermes did A to L; an associate
did M to Z, and I did biographies, garden and history. The books
humanized the place instantly.'' The designers even signed Gesser
up for membership in the Bedford Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that Gesser gave them enough money in advance to cover
the bills. ``We owed him money through the entire process,''
Maloney said.
</P>
<P>
   In a practice that seems to be increasingly common when dealing
with here-today (perhaps gone tomorrow) financing, Benjamin
Noriega-Ortiz, a Manhattan designer, asks for full payment up
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just too hard to get them to focus on writing checks,''
Noriega-Ortiz said. For one client, a single hedge-fund manager,
35, who did not want to be named, the decision to buy and decorate
an apartment did not come easily. ``I was having so much fun in
stocks that I didn't really want to take the money out,'' she said.
But once she decided to buy an Upper West Side duplex, she moved in
last May, contacted a designer and was settled in by that July.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in the middle of the day, she was sun-bathing in her
bikini on the balcony. A gold-embroidered Indian silk sari was
flung casually on a Brunschwig &AMP; Fils armchair _ one of the many
personal touches the designer provided a year ago that remained in
place.
</P>
<P>
   A sofa was upholstered in orange velvet with quilted gold silk
cushions. A regulation kitchen was hidden by a voluminous
Teflon-coated curtain. ``I did the whole place in the time it took
to order the fabrics from one source,'' Noriega-Ortiz said.
``That's three months. It had to look elegant and it had to be
instant.'' The artworks came mostly from one gallery in SoHo. ``It
took about 10 minutes,'' Noriega-Ortiz said. One piece, made from
sculptured wax, was being used to stow her Labrador's chew toys. A
price tag still dangled from an Italian-made leather desk chair.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the woman bought a 1763 country house in Connecticut,
and she says she plans to take things a bit more slowly. The thrill
of decorating has paled. ``For a while, I was into houses, then I
was into kitchen accessories,'' she said, describing the cooking
classes she took at home from a chef. ``Now, I'm into doing my own
hedge fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Gesser, too, has moved on. He has just put his house in Bedford
up for sale and is looking for a new place in the Hamptons. Maloney
and Mallea just couldn't say no to renovating his new multimillion
dollar town house on the Upper East Side. When the designers met up
with him in Bedford recently, they noticed that their photographs
of Pancho still filled his picture frames. A trusty friend to the
last.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
