<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3602 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NANKING-JAPAN-NYT &LR;      05-19 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NANKING-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY'S SHADOW FOILS NANKING CHRONICLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than a half-century after the Japanese invasion of the
ancient Chinese city of Nanking, a tense international literary tug
of words has flared over the Japanese translation of a bestselling
book in the United States, ``The Rape of Nanking,'' which was
scheduled to be published in Japan this year.
</P>
<P>
   The American publisher, Basic Books, and the Japanese company,
Kashiwashobo, ended months of wrangling this week by canceling
their contract for a translation of Iris Chang's chronicle of the
Japanese army's military atrocities in the Rape of Nanking, which
involved the systematic killing of 300,000 Chinese civilians and
prisoners in a city of fewer than 650,000 people in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   From Tokyo, Kashiwashobo's editor in chief, Hiraku Haga,
declared that he did not trust the book. ``It's biased, prejudiced
and like wartime propaganda,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the American publisher, John Donatich, issued a
statement expressing regret. ``The contract between us stipulated
very clearly that no modifications to the text or artwork of
Basic's edition be made without the author's consent,'' he said,
noting that the Japanese publisher and the author could not agree
on changes.
</P>
<P>
   Kashiwashobo had sought to add notes and eliminate photographs
in the book over the objections of Ms. Chang. She said she
suspected that those actions were motivated by threats from
right-wing Japanese organizations that challenge her description of
events. ``I think it is safe to assume that they were cracking
under pressure from ultranationalist groups,'' said Ms. Chang, who
lives in Sunnyvale, Calif., and whose immigrant Chinese parents
passed down stories to her as a child of the atrocities in Nanking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denial,'' she added, ``is an integral part of atrocity, and
it's a natural part after a society has committed genocide. First
you kill, and then the memory of killing is killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan has historically been reluctant to take responsibility for
wartime atrocities, and some prominent Japanese officials contend
that the incident in Nanking never happened. In recent years there
has been increasing pressure from left-wing historians and others
to explore that past. But mainstream politicians and education
officials still tend to play down that history, charging that the
West has exaggerated accounts.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time that publishers have dueled over
sensitive books that crossed borders. In 1997 Doubleday
successfully sued to halt the publication of a Polish translation
of an American biography of Pope John Paul II that had been heavily
edited by the Polish publisher to tone down some of the words of
the authors, Carl Bernstein and Marco Politi, and to remove
references to the pope's ill health, to Polish anti-Semitism and to
criticism of the Roman Catholic Church in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   With the increasing export of American books to other countries,
it is likely that there will more literary debates about books that
challenge sensitive views about local events. But so far such
arguments are relatively uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unusual,'' said Carolyn Savarese, vice president and
group rights director for the Perseus Books Group, which includes
Basic Books. ``In the 50 years that Basic has been publishing books
around the world, that has never happened before, and I think that
says a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Basic and Kashiwashobo initially struck an agreement to publish
``The Rape of Nanking'' in May 1998 despite interest from other
Japanese publishers, Ms. Savarese said. As part of that contract,
she said, Basic included the stipulation that ``no modifications to
the text of the original edition could be made without the author's
consent.''
</P>
<P>
   The hardcover version of the book, a stinging indictment of the
behavior of Japanese military in Nanking, was first published in
the fall of 1997 in the United States to general critical acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on diaries of soldiers, contemporary interviews and news
accounts from the time, Ms. Chang describes mass executions of
prisoners of war, the rape and killing of women, the burning of
homes and the hunt for young men who might challenge the military
in the future. And she tries to explain what motivated the
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Takokoro Kozo, who was a soldier in the 114th Division of the
Japanese army, is quoted in the book as saying, ``Women suffered
most,'' and adding, ``Perhaps when we were raping her we looked at
her as a woman, but when we killed her we just thought of her as
something like a pig.''
</P>
<P>
   After the publishers signed the contract for a Japanese version
of the book, the efforts to translate it faced problems almost
immediately. Ms. Chang received a letter from a Japanese literary
agency alerting her that several Japanese historians had declined
to review the translation, and that one professor had backed out
because of pressure placed on his family by ``an unknown
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Kashiwashobo started sending her letters seeking
corrections and annotations to material in the book after creating
a group to review her work. Haga of Kashiwashobo said in an
interview Wednesday that the issue amounted to a contract dispute,
and that his company was not responding to pressure from groups
that disliked the book. His company did request changes, he said,
but did not insist on them.
</P>
<P>
   Kashiwashobo, he said, did receive a faxed threat demanding a
halt to the publication of the book and was visited by members of
an organization that ``did not make a verbal threat, but basically
wanted to voice the concern that the book may influence the younger
generation.'' But he noted that his company was pressing forward
with plans to publish other titles that examine Japanese war
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But in e-mail correspondence quoted by Ms. Chang, Haga wrote,
``As we have indicated before, our publishing company is subject to
considerable attack and it's not an exaggeration to say that we
have put ourselves in a life-threatening situation in publishing
this book.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the author and the Japanese publisher would trade
letters debating suggested corrections and a proposal to eliminate
certain photographs, like one showing Japanese soldiers bayoneting
Nanking victims. Ms. Chang said she was told that the authenticity
of the photograph was questionable because the shadows of the
figures appeared too short for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Haga's correspondence indicates that he was also concerned about
the picture captions and wanted disclaimers that explained that
Kashiwashobo could not verify the authenticity of the pictures.
``If we publish the photos with caption translations exactly as
found in the original, we will surely be open for severe attack
from the right-wing conservatives, and we have no way to defend
ourselves,'' he wrote in November.
</P>
<P>
   With the termination of the contract, Basic Books announced that
it would seek another Japanese publisher. ``I want the Japanese
people to know the truth of the Rape of Nanking,'' Ms. Chang said.
``I want them to know a side of history that isn't properly taught
in school. Like it or not, this is a part of their history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOWER-THEATER-REVIEW-     05-19 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOWER-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THIS LIME TREE BOWER': A WEALTH OF AMBIGUITY, AN ECONOMY OF
WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ray, a hard-drinking Lothario of a college professor
in Conor McPherson's ``This Lime Tree Bower,'' is not a fancy
talker, at least not by academic standards. His sentences and his
words tend to be short, but they nonetheless summon entire
landscapes of sharp, conflicted sensations.
</P>
<P>
   Here, for example, is Ray identifying a crystalline moment of
guilt, as he recalls driving through the Irish countryside with his
steady girlfriend: ``Carmel beside me in a light print dress and my
mind wandering into different beds.''
</P>
<P>
   The image of the promiscuous mind is good, but it's that ``light
print dress'' next to it that makes this sentence fragment explode
with impressions, conveying both Ray's idealizing view of his lover
and the luxury he finds in feeling bad and lowdown. Just 15 words,
and you're securely inside someone else's head.
</P>
<P>
   McPherson, an Irish playwright still several years away from 30,
and the author of ``The Weir,'' the haunted tribute to storytelling
now on Broadway, consistently brings to blooming life what English
teachers were always telling you about economy of means in writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Lime Tree Bower,'' a story unfolded in alternating
monologues by three men, hasn't been done many favors by the
uncomfortable production that opened Wednesday night at Primary
Stages. But McPherson's language is potent enough to survive even
this sadly awkward rendering, and images and phrases from the work
take on their own proliferating existence in your memory afterward.
``These books knew how to be read,'' a character in ``Lime Tree''
says of his favorite detective novels. The same might be said of
McPherson's plays.
</P>
<P>
   In summary, the plot of ``This Lime Tree Bower'' brings to mind
those sweet-natured foreign films distributed here under the rubric
of ``quirky'' and ``life-affirming.'' It's a small-town
coming-of-age tale that features both an exotic introduction to sex
and an antic robbery at gunpoint that is pulled off by one of the
play's narrators. The victim of that crime is, of course,
dislikable and humiliated in ways that involve public nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are shadows in ``Lime Tree'' that movies like ``The
Full Monty'' don't begin to capture. McPherson uses words to create
both a buzzing sense of atmosphere and an equally vibrant silence
beneath that pulses with unanswerable questions. ``Lime Tree'' has
its elements of excessively cute eccentricity, but it also finds a
troubled ambivalence in each of its characters that is the province
of first-class literature.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a performance style to convey that ambiguity isn't easy,
as is unfortunately evidenced by this production, directed by
Harris Yulin and performed by T.R. Knight and Thomas Lyons, as
brothers on the edge of manhood, and Drew McVety as the college
professor who goes out with their sister. These three actors are
likable, eager presences, but you're often conscious of the sheer
effort they put into sustaining their accents and remembering their
long, rambling speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently the production feels pitched self-consciously in a
no man's land between a staged reading and fully realized
characterizations. What should be a rolling river of language
becomes instead something dry and fitful. Each actor, especially
McVety as the libidinous Ray, has his moments, and they are sure to
improve with time. For now, however, you often have to look past
the performances to find the gold in McPherson's text.
</P>
<P>
   Gold there definitely is. Though it uses multiple narrators,
``Lime Tree'' doesn't go for obvious ``Rashomon''-style differences
of interpretation. What McPherson aims for is both simpler and more
subtle, indirectly contrasting the senses of self and of sexuality
of the play's three characters, who are in different stages of
defining their personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, though stranded in sybaritic adolescence, is the most fully
formed. Joe ( Knight), who is still in school, retains a wondering,
waiting quality, while Frank ( Lyons), his older brother, has
reached the point of restlessness where he needs to bolt. The form
that restlessness takes is what gives the play its anecdotal shape.
</P>
<P>
   McPherson asks you to exercise a certain skepticism about what
you're hearing. ``The town was full of spoofers,'' as young Joe
observes, adding that his Italian father has warned him that Irish
people are just as likely as not to ``make something up'' when
something needs explaining.
</P>
<P>
   What a person fabricates, however, can be more illuminating than
a more straightforward recitation of events. And when Joe recalls,
in Gothic terms, his first vision of people having sex, its mixture
of repulsion and fascination rings resoundingly true.
</P>
<P>
   Joe is also the one who discourses on the pleasures of paperback
thrillers and westerns. He likes them, he says, because ``the
sentences were always short'' and ``the writers gave you the
facts.'' In contrast, he says, in the books he studied in school,
``nobody said what they meant and you had to work out what
everybody wanted.'' Then there are those rare writers like
McPherson, who seamlessly blend the virtues of both camps.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THIS LIME TREE BOWER'
</P>
<P>
   By Conor McPherson; directed by Harris Yulin; sets by Walt
Spangler; costumes by Debra Stein; lighting by Deborah Constantine;
production manager, Tina Fallon for Crux; stage manager, Marienne
Chapman; associate producer, Seth Gordon; general manager, Margaret
Chandler; artistic and administrative associate, Anne Einhorn.
Presented by Primary Stages, Casey Childs, artistic director. At
354 W. 45th St., Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: T.R. Knight (Joe), Drew McVety (Ray) and Thomas Lyons
(Frank).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
