<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOW-DO-WE-DO-2TAKES-N     05-19 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOW-DO-WE-DO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESSYE NORMAN AND BILL T. JONES CREATE A PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a moment in rehearsal, Bill T. Jones said,
when his partner Jessye Norman used her voice to say something
about herself that went beyond words and music. She started out
with an opera, slid into something jazzy and then ambled into a
land of soulful notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave me this look,'' Jones recalled the other day over a
lazy lunch in midtown. ``I think, that as African-American artists
working in very Eurocentric environments, it was her way of saying,
`I am in touch with who I am.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Norman, the soprano, and Jones, the choreographer and
dancer, are collaborators on a performance called ``How! Do! We!
Do!,'' which will have its world premiere Monday and will be
repeated next Thursday at City Center. The show promises to be as
provocative and hard-to-categorize as the artists: It is just the
two of them onstage, creating a mosaic of song, dance, poetry and
the spoken word in a series of tableaux with readings of Frank
O'Hara poems forming the narrative thread.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years I've been interested in Frank O'Hara,'' Jones said
of the poet, playwright and art critic. ``His voice is urbane,
passionate, cultivated, capable of deep lyrical flights and the
throwaway camp line.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he envisions ``How! Do! We! Do!'' as a poem open to
interpretation, an exploration of two personalities. At one point
Ms. Norman imitates a radio tuning into pivotal moments in modern
history, especially the civil rights struggle. Ms. Norman and Jones
do a dance that is meant to evoke both the travel of Africans to
the New World and the travels of all immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The vocal music will be both live and recorded and range from
Duke Ellington to Mozart to American spirituals to Schubert lieder.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is creating a new programming genre which
links the classical music world with the world of theater and dance
in Lincoln Center's New Visions series,'' said Jane Moss, vice
president for programming at Lincoln Center. Lincoln Center is
renting City Center for the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It defies categorization,'' Ms. Moss said. ``Hearing Jessye
Norman with Bill T. Jones is completely different from hearing her
in recital.''
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps fitting that O'Hara's voice informs the duet,
because he felt that poetry should be ``between two persons instead
of two pages.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides coming from different disciplines, Ms. Norman is
famously private and Jones is famously extroverted. She is a large
woman known as a diva. He has a dancer's body and is known for
using spoken language on the stage and addressing issues like
racism and AIDS in his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I needed a title that would hold whatever we do,''
Jones said of this latest endeavor. ``How! is how we became Jessye,
how we became Bill, how we became friends. Do! is a way of being in
the world that is action-oriented. We! is who we are together.
People will try to figure us out together, this man and this women
who have their level of reputation and notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Do! is movement-driven, text-driven, music-driven.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Norman said she saw the show as a chance to explore themes
that are close to her heart: the civil rights movement, the
anti-apartheid struggle, the moment Hank Aaron broke Babe Ruth's
major league career home-run record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to bring attention to certain social issues,'' Ms.
Norman said. ``I do movement and I'm very comfortable with it. The
first time, I was giggling the whole time and saying, `Bill, you're
not serious.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on the verge of singing,'' she said, leaning forward
with a mischievous twinkle in her eye. ``We put the flame out on
that idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The project started 10 years ago after they met and decided to
do something together. The show evolved with many conversations and
hours of listening to music.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who formed the post-modernist Bill T. Jones/Arnie Zane
Dance Company in 1982 with his companion and saw it reach
international prominence, has created dances for Alvin Ailey Dance
Theater and the Berlin Opera Ballet, among others, and
choreographed for opera houses, including the New York City Opera.
Zane died in 1988. These days the peripatetic Jones' is promoting a
new book of photographs by Zane called ``Continuous Replay: The
Photographs of Arnie Zane, 1970-1980.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Norman, who grew up in Augusta, Ga., started her career in
Europe and returned to the United States to become one of the first
major black stars of the opera world since Marian Anderson. Even
though her official biography does not even include her marital
status, her persona has received almost as much attention as her
voice.
</P>
<P>
   She has been quoted in articles as using the royal ``we,'' for
example, and is sometimes described as imperious. There was a
flurry of articles a few years ago about a lawsuit she brought
against a British magazine for telling a story about her being
trapped in a revolving door and being advised to go sideways. The
magazine quoted her as saying: ``Honey, I ain't got no sideways.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Norman said the other day that the story was old and may
have originally been about a German singer. She never said it, she
reiterated, even though she lost the lawsuit. She said that she
felt the fabricated comment was a slap at all African-Americans, a
way of saying that to be black is to exist in the vernacular.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he knew Ms. Norman was aware of the paradox of her
position in a Eurocentric world, a theme he has explored in works
like ``The Last Supper at Uncle Tom's Cabin/The Promised Land.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not on a soapbox with `How! Do! We! Do!,''' Jones said.
``I'm enjoying this moment with Ms. Norman. I heard the jargon of
the '60s, an ancient jargon that is about freedom and defining
oneself. I want to make an art that is multilayered and
intellectually satisfying but that is encouraging to me and those
like me.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole time right now, this whole discourse right now, is
about negotiating differences. Do we all believe we have something
to learn? This exists on the political level and it exists on the
social level. Ms. Norman and I are developing a language of how to
speak to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Ms. Norman said she loathed interviews because she was
fiercely private (``I find it amazing that people would actually
allow a photographer into their home to take pictures,'' she said)
and because so much written about her has been untrue. She said she
believed her art could speak for itself without people knowing
about her love life or her bathroom color scheme. She said she was
tired of the diva anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, people need to cultivate a mystique that is
comfortable for them,'' she said of her reputation. ``People write
things they think must be true or how they would be if they were in
my shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   In an hourlong interview, Ms. Norman laughed often and smiled
easily. This is who she said she is: ``not married, just happy'';
practices yoga, adores Toni Morrison and Duke Ellington, lives
modestly, never reads reviews (``It's not as if I'm going to get an
objective, helpful criticism''), allergic to pets, interested in
the spiritual and passionate about social justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``To work this way, to do something completely different, is a
strength, it's growth,'' Ms. Norman of the show with Jones, whom
she first met backstage at the Joyce Theater in Manhattan. ``I
learned to walk across a stage without teetering or tottering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of my career as a kind of wheel,'' she continued.
``There are spokes going in all directions. I just find different
directions all the time. I'm going to do more popular music, for
example.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In 10 years, I'll probably spend more time writing,'' she
said, adding that she was rereading ``Paradise'' by Toni Morrison,
a lot about Duke Ellington and the second volume of a book about
Eleanor Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compassion was the most natural thing in the world to her,''
she said of Roosevelt. ``I want to look at the connection of the
spirit to what it is that we do. I like the way that whole thing
invades my life. One can be hesitant to talk about these things
because the people who have been vocal about these things have not
turned out to be the people we thought they were.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not pie-in-the-sky spirituality that moves her, either,
said Ms. Norman, who supports the Girl Scouts, children's charities
and AIDS research. She said she cares about any issue that touches
on people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said ``How! Do! We! Do!'' strives to capture the spirit of
these two artists who are as concerned with their art as they are
with how people manage to make it in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The piece wants to be a bit mad, deeply felt,'' he said.
``It's a mosaic. These two people who are friends and two artists
who respect each other using all these forms and images and music
to talk about the present, the past and even the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
