<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3609 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECHAVESTE-$ADV23-COX     05-19 1817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECHAVESTE-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FROM MIGRANT WORKER, SHE ROSE TO KEY WHITE HOUSE ROLE
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 23.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Maria Echaveste was talking about patriotism in her
White House office, which is a short stroll from President
Clinton's desk but an odyssey away from the dusty cotton fields of
south Texas where her story began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work in this country to make sure that when you say
the word 'American,' it includes, in your head, all the things that
we are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can it be that even in Latino communities, if you're
talking among yourselves, you say 'los Americanos' as a shorthand
way of saying 'the other, the white Americans,' even though we're
all Americans? Somehow we've taken in that they're Americans; we're
Mexican-Americans,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know, excuse me, I'm really proud to be Mexican. I'm
really glad to know where I came from. But I'm American.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the White House deputy chief of staff personifies the
melting pot.
</P>
<P>
   Echaveste, 45, is ``sort of a one-woman band of diversity,'' the
New Republic noted. ``She's a Hispanic woman, a Jew, a corporate
lawyer, a Californian, a Texan, a New Yorker, a marathon runner,
and a gardener. Oh yes, she also knits.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing she's not, though, is a Southern good ol' boy _ which
helped get her hired by Erskine Bowles, the North Carolina
businessman who was serving as Clinton's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have very different backgrounds. That's another reason
why I wanted to bring her in,'' Bowles recalled. ``If you have
people with different backgrounds, people with different life
experiences, people from different cultures, people of different
races and genders, you're going to make a better decision than if
you just have 10 white guys sitting around a table.''
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of migrant farm workers, Echaveste has reached a
White House position never before attained by a Hispanic woman. In
the past six years, she has risen steadily through the
administration ranks _ from the Labor Department's wage and hour
administrator to White House director of public liaison to deputy
chief of staff. A cabinet position could be next. She has been
rumored to be a contender for secretary of education should Richard
Riley decide to return to South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she's at the highest position she's going to end
up at,'' predicted Bowles. ``If she decides to stay in the
administration, I think Maria is destined for a seat at the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Maria was the eldest of the seven Echaveste children. Their
parents had crossed the Rio Grande in the early 1950s to find a
better life, and Maria was born in Harlingen, Texas. Her father
couldn't read or write back then. He was taught by her mother, who
had finished the second grade. But they were bright and ambitious,
hard workers who earned their citizenship and moved to California
in search of higher wages.
</P>
<P>
   The children grew up following ripening crops across California,
picking cotton, strawberries, grapes, tomatoes and carrots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived out in the country on farms,'' recalled Rosa, the
middle child of five girls and two boys. ``We did not have a lot of
toys or material things. But Maria was really imaginative. We did
these elaborate shows and plays for each other. And we played
school. She was always the teacher, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   For almost longer than she can remember, books were central in
Maria's childhood. She spent as much time as she could in the
libraries of schools and agricultural communities.
</P>
<P>
   Books would open the door to a life beyond the aching backs and
merciless sun and endless fields and orchards. But her early
academic awareness wasn't the only reason that Maria was always the
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being the oldest child and having the responsibility of caring
for all the little ones, she had to grow up fast,'' said Carmella,
the third-born of the Echaveste children. ``Those experiences
interfered with her childhood. The term we use now is 'parentified'
_ a child expected to be a substitute parent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She definitely was a parental figure,'' agreed Rosa. ``If we
did anything wrong, we feared her reaction as well as our
parents'.''
</P>
<P>
   The patriarchal household stressed traditional Mexican and
Catholic values. At times, there was a culture clash between the
stern, Spanish-speaking father and his Americanized children. He
did not want his eldest daughter to go off to college, even after
she earned a scholarship to Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was angry,'' said Carmella, now a social worker in
Pasadena. ``My mother told her, 'go, and I'll work on your dad
while you're gone'.''
</P>
<P>
   With Maria leading the way, six of the seven Echaveste children
went on to earn college degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the guiding light,'' said Rosa, now an insurance
broker in southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the parents followed the example set by their
offspring and became avid readers. Refugio Echaveste advanced to
become a ranch foreman, joining the vast American middle class
before retiring and returning with his wife, Maria, to live in the
Mexican town of Jalisco where he was born.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   At Stanford, Maria Echaveste majored in anthropology and might
have gone on to graduate study and an academic career except for a
tight job market in her field. Instead, she spent a year in the
nation's capital interning with the U.S. Commission on Civil
Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Envisioning a government job, she earned a law degree from the
University of California at Berkeley. But instead of returning to
Washington, she became a corporate attorney in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed it immensely,'' she said, describing the challenge
of winning courtroom battles. And the practice was lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've added up how much money I've lost in the last six years
being in government,'' she said. ``It's a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, she married Stanley Schlein, a Bronx attorney. She
also converted to her husband's religion _ Orthodox Judaism. She
has since divorced but remained Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised a Catholic and had a very hard time with
Catholicism, which was the source of another battle with my parents
when I started not to go to church,'' she said. She considered the
religion _ ``the way it was in my house'' _ to be confining to
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very suffocating. You're someone's mother, someone's
sister, someone's daughter. You're not a person in your own
right,'' she explained. ``It's also very focused on the hereafter,
as opposed to now. And especially, I think, in a Mexican household,
there's a lot of resignation. It's 'whatever God wills'.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found Judasim to be much more life-affirming. This is our
time. It's about what you do every day, about how you use the
blessings that you have every day and what you do with this life
now, not what's going happen to you post-death.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, she became active in Democratic politics and served
as president of the city's Board of Elections. During the 1992
presidential campaign, she left her law firm to become the national
Latino coordinator for the Clinton team. Her White House position,
she concedes with a chuckle, is directly attributable to picking a
winning candidate.
</P>
<P>
   She joined the new administration and became wage and hour
administrator, a Labor Department position requiring Senate
confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   The job is powerful but obscure _ overseeing minimum wage laws,
child labor laws and the newly passed family medical leave act,
said Tom Glynn, a Boston hospital administrator who is a former
deputy secretary of labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could have been chief of staff for the attorney general,''
Glynn said. ``Given that choice, most people would have gone to the
Justice Department. But she was very committed to the issues
concerning working people. She ended up handling a lot of hot
potatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   She led a project that obtained $8 million in back wages for
poor workers who had been illegally underpaid by their employers.
And she pushed an anti-sweatshop crusade to press retailers and
clothes makers to improve the working conditions at the facilities
of their apparel contractors.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of Clinton's second term in 1997, Echaveste moved
over to the White House as public liaison director, responsible for
boosting support for presidential policies and initiatives. She
replaced Alexis Herman, who had been appointed secretary of labor.
</P>
<P>
   Among Echaveste's projects was the presidential initiative to
provoke a ``national dialogue'' on race relations to prepare the
nation for a future without any racial majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have criticized (the initiative) as an issue
that started out big and is going nowhere,'' she said. However, she
predicted that ``some years from now, what the president did by
putting this issue about how we relate to each other across racial
and ethnic and religious lines will be seen as the big deal it
really is.''
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1998, Echaveste was promoted to deputy chief of
staff. The job entails ``managing the White House,'' she explained.
Her duties have ranged from routine administration _ deciding who
gets raises _ to coordinating the State of the Union speech and
planning the Wye River summit to negotiate Mideast peace and the
50th anniversary NATO conference.
</P>
<P>
   The air war over Yugoslavia forced a drastic revision of the
original plans for a celebratory NATO summit, said Doug Sosnik,
presidential assistant for policy and strategy. At every progress
meeting, Echaveste had to keep pushing for changes, warning,
``people, read the paper,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like turning a huge ship around'' to produce a
successful session that was completely different from the
celebrity-filled gala initially envisioned, Sosnik said.
</P>
<P>
   Echaveste gets things done, said Bowles, her former boss.
``There are a lot of people in Washington, I found, who understand
policy. But I didn't find many who could translate that policy into
action. She's both a leader and a doer _ again a rare
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Echaveste said she is thankful for the opportunity to
work 12 hours a day, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to participate in some of the decisions that have
to be made around here is something that I take very seriously,''
she explained. ``It's not about the trappings of, 'Oh, I work in
the White House.' Or, 'Oh, I got invited to some fancy state
dinner'. Or, 'Oh, my goodness, I get to travel on Air Force One.'
It's about, 'Okay, you had a really interesting session on school
violence on Monday. Now how are we going to organize this into a
national campaign?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance to work on something that can make people's
lives better,'' she said. ``I hope that doesn't sound too corny.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
