<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3622 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      05-19 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IS A BOWL OF CELEBRITIES, AND WE'RE IN THE PITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Julia Roberts lifted up her arm to wave to the crowd
and, in turn, the world froze.
</P>
<P>
   It was the lead story on ``Inside Edition,'' ``Entertainment
Tonight'' and even, believe it or not, made the nightly news. The
newscasters gasped in horror and snickered in revulsion as the
photo of Roberts was flashed the screen for five haunting seconds.
</P>
<P>
   There, just beneath her cap-sleeved gown was not evidence of a
budding extra head; the expanding, flapping gills of a fish woman;
or even a tumor equivalent in girth and color tone to a ripe, juicy
melon. Nope.
</P>
<P>
   It was just hair.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts had the armpits of a ring-tailed lemur.
</P>
<P>
   One local newscaster's brain was apparently seized by a
brilliance bubble as she mentioned aloud, ``I bet she just forgot
to shave. She (begin ital) couldn't (end ital) have done that on
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Let me be the first one to explain: When you've got enough fur
sprouting from within a fold of flesh to clothe a badger, it's
really not something that slips your mind _ especially when it's
long enough to weave beads and brightly colored bits of yarn into
and makes noise when you walk. Take it from one who knows.
</P>
<P>
   I also know a story like that has (begin ital) got (end ital) to
be important when it disrupts coverage of Pamela Anderson's
silicone baggie reduction from the size of a monster-truck tire to
that of an 18-wheeler. I imagine the world is just relieved to know
that she can finally reach across that continental divide she calls
a chest and feed herself again.
</P>
<P>
   I guess if there's anything that can knock a big, fat boob out
of the spotlight, it's gotta be a hairy monkey armpit.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose now it will become the hip Hollywood ``thing,'' maybe
replacing the trends of lips pumped full of Fix-A-Flat or wearing
sheer dresses but no underpants.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all right by me. I don't need any excuse to throw
down my Lady Bic, I can be a lemming! I was just waiting for a
Hollywood's highest-paid actress to come along and say it was OK to
liberate our armpits from the heavy chains of razors and wax.
</P>
<P>
   Those who sent their follicles to an early grave via
electrolysis will become the jealous scourge, as women all over the
world raise their arms and shout, ``A pretty woman is a pretty
hairy woman!!'' After all, isn't it just another place where we can
place our diamond-encrusted bobby pins?
</P>
<P>
   If Julia Roberts can capture the attention of the WHOLE WORLD by
unveiling a beard in her pit, think of the hidden powers she
contains. Clearly, she alone has the ability to turn all of the
taboo behaviors into acceptable social icons. Why let the magic
stop here? Let's let it all hang out, sister-woman!
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'm happy to see Julia endorse something that my
mother considers barnyard animal hygiene. In fact, I'd like to see
her build a couple of more bridges to free humanity of tiresome
social restraints and dismiss notions of socially unacceptable
behavior. Because if Julia does it, it (begin ital) must (end ital)
be OK. Let's really give the media something to talk about!
</P>
<P>
   At her next premiere, I implore Julia to walk down that red
carpet with her left hand prying her panties out of the crack of
her behind.
</P>
<P>
   I beg her to be photographed wearing sandals that expose
toenails so long that they curl over and scrape the ground and can
shred flesh.
</P>
<P>
   I want her to tell a trashy tabloid or ``Good Housekeeping''
that, instead of washing her underwear, she simply turns it inside
out.
</P>
<P>
   I want her to admit to Barbara Walters that she eats chocolate
like it was a vitamin.
</P>
<P>
   I want to see her at the Academy Awards next year, talking to
Joan Rivers about her designer dress, when she lifts one hip,
concentrates so hard that her face gets all squished up, and pushes
out a poot.
</P>
<P>
   I want her to be on ``Oprah'' when she suddenly starts to squirm
and magically produces a bra from the cuff of her shirt sleeve as
she giggles and says, ``That just totally itched! Can I put this in
somebody's purse?''
</P>
<P>
   I want her to admit that she, too, in pursuit of a particularly
irritating crusty, has stuck her finger up her nose and then
examined it without realizing she was in a crowded grocery line.
</P>
<P>
   I want her to confess that when her left and right brain
communicate with each other, sometimes it gets broadcast out loud.
</P>
<P>
   I want her to insist that she's melted down her tweezer for the
war effort and is ``so over'' plucking old lady hairs from her
chin.
</P>
<P>
   But dangers lurk.
</P>
<P>
   All of this Julia Mania could cause a jealous backlash with
other flavor-of-the-season celebs. Out of spite, Pam Anderson could
shove a river raft into her torso; Camryn Manheim might throw a
perfectly good Twinkie away; and Calista Flockhart might consider
the unholy by picking it up and eating it. In front of people.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK. Julia Mania can be revived. It (begin ital) can. (end
ital) If you think the world froze when she lifted up her arms and
the camera spotted it, prepare for the apocalypse this summer when
she's spotted on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   In a bikini. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send comments about her column
to the Rep, P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or by e-mail to
laurienotaro(at)usa.net. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
