<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN OPPOSITION TO GROUND TROOPS MAKES CONTINUED AIR WAR LIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Despite some diplomatic progress, the NATO bombardment
of Yugoslavia is likely to continue at least until the end of this
month, a senior German official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Steiner, the chief diplomatic adviser to Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder, said that a minimum of two weeks would be needed
to overcome differences between Russia and the West, and to bring
the Yugoslav government ``to the level of vulnerability where it
will agree to our demands.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks, in a telephone interview, reflected a German
conviction that the NATO policy of bombing combined with diplomacy
will work if given time, and that using ground troops would be a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my view that we will not deploy ground troops in
Yugoslavia,'' Schroeder, a Social Democrat, said Wednesday in an
interview with German television. He was repeating a position that
he has forcefully taken this week as Britain has called for
preparation for the possible use of troops to force a military
victory in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The German view, critical because Schroeder has been
coordinating the European response to the war, reflects historical
and political factors that make Germany's position unique and
appear to limit NATO's options.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since World War II, the maxim that ``only peace'' would go
out from German soil has amounted to a mantra, repeated by
governments of the left and right alike. German participation in
the NATO bombardment of Yugoslavia therefore amounts to a huge
departure, after which ground troops appear as a step too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``By German standards, the change of policy has already been
extensive and radical,'' said Karl Kaiser, a political analyst.
``We have come a huge distance in a short time, and managed to
bring public opinion along. But for the government, ground troops
would be too much at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Public support for the war has declined to 51 percent from 61
percent a month ago, according to an opinion poll published last
week. The strong pacifist strain in German politics and opinion has
begun to resurface.
</P>
<P>
   As the tide of opinion has begun to shift, the Green Party,
junior partners in Schroeder's government, has become more forceful
in seeking an end to the bombing, calling last week for a pause in
air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting strains in the coalition are such that it appears
probable that any eventual NATO decision to use ground troops would
bring down the first ``Red-Green'' government of the modern German
state.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in the German position is that the main
opposition party, the center-right Christian Democratic Union, has
up to now supported the NATO bombing, opening the way for a
bi-partisan approach that would be reassuring to a country still
alarmed by the prospect of sharp internal divisions over a European
war. But the Christian Democrats, the party of former Chancellor
Helmut Kohl, has said it will oppose a ground war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not weaken on the military side, but equally we must
not change strategy that is making headway,'' Steiner said. ``We
have to be steadfast, with no mixed signals, and then perhaps in a
couple of weeks we will get where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Steiner spoke as senior officials from the Group of Seven
wealthiest nations and Russia met in Bonn to try to build on a
statement earlier this month that called for the deployment in
Kosovo of international ``civil and security presences'' and the
withdrawal of Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   The statement, issued on May 6, marked the first time since the
bombing began two months ago that Russia and the West had spoken
with a single voice. But it left open several contentious issues,
including the composition of any international force, the
circumstances in which NATO bombing would stop, and whether all
Serbian forces have to pull out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the meeting Wednesday, which was attended by
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, was not intended to
resolve all those issues, but was part of a process that would
still take some time and should eventually lead to a U.N. Security
Council resolution on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   One basic difference remaining is the Russian and Chinese
insistence that NATO's bombing must stop before a diplomatic
solution can be found. This demand is rejected by the United States
and its allies, which insist that Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic must first accept the deployment of a NATO-coordinated
international force and withdraw his troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Mayorsky, the Russian delegate to the Bonn meeting, said
Wednesday that peace depended on NATO stopping the bombing. ``The
Russian position, as before, is that a condition for such a
resolution is an end to the bombing of the territory of Yugoslavia
by NATO forces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. resolution would spell out the conditions for and
perhaps the broad composition of any international force. It would
in effect give such a mission the firm basis in international law
that critics have argued the NATO campaign lacks.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Steiner said the diplomatic efforts were focused on a new word:
``synchronization.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, diplomats are looking at the possibility of having
the beginning of a withdrawal of Yugoslav forces coincide with a
provisional halt to NATO bombing, the passing of a U.N. Security
Council resolution, and the start of a deployment of international
forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   This is a highly complex and time-consuming aim. But if
achieved, it might allow all sides to claim a bit of a victory and
so break the current impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy to the
Balkans, would raise that sort of possibility with Milosevic in
Belgrade on Wednesday. As for Western countries, they have decided
to coordinate their diplomatic efforts through the Finnish
president, Martti Ahtisaari, who may eventually travel to the
Yugoslav capital, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari comes from a country that is in the European Union but
not in NATO and, having worked on the conflict in Bosnia for some
time, is familiar with the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone from Washington to European capitals is agreed that
Mr. Ahtisaari will now be a central figure as the diplomacy moves
forward,'' Steiner said. ``He knows the NATO position and he shares
it.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But it remains open to question whether NATO will be able to
maintain its unity as that diplomacy moves forward at a modest
pace, and whether Milosevic can be brought to yield to demands that
still include the withdrawal of all Serb forces from Kosovo and a
strong NATO presence there.
</P>
<P>
   That question is particularly acute because Germany's history
insures that one option that might increase pressure on Milosevic _
the use of ground troops _ is highly unlikely to be adopted by
NATO. Or, if it were, Germany would remain on the sidelines, with
unpredictable repercussions.
</P>
</TEXT>
