</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIN ABOUT BUSH'S ROLE IN GOP GUN DEBATE TAKES LIFE OF ITS OWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To hear some people tell it, when Gov. George W. Bush says
``Jump!'' Republicans in Washington ask, ``How high?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Bush leads in the Republican presidential polls. Yes, he's
widely respected by Republicans in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But reports and rumors notwithstanding, Bush apparently was not
the moving force when Senate Republicans reversed course last week
and supported instant background checks for arms purchasers at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters Wednesday in Austin, Texas, that he received a
call from a Republican senator and expressed support for the
provision to require the background checks. Bush spokesman David
Beckwith said the call, from Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, came before
any Senate vote on gun-show checks _ not as Republicans were
deciding to do a U-turn.
</P>
<P>
   The phone call, however, has taken on a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   On ABC's Sunday interview show ``This Week,'' columnist George
Will quizzed Sen. Orrin Hatch, the Utah Republican who chairs the
Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator, it is rumored one of the reasons Republicans changed
their vote between Wednesday and Friday, I guess, is that there was
a call from Austin, Texas, from Governor Bush's operation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I know of,'' Hatch replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``No contact whatever?'' Will pressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Hatch said. ``Not that I knew of.''
</P>
<P>
   But the idea would not die.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the show, commentator William Kristol, editor of the
Weekly Standard, said: ``Well, the Republicans reversed themselves,
I'm told, under pressure from Austin from George W. Bush's aides.
Bush did not want to run as the party that had killed gun locks
..., the party that had legitimized gun shows. All that sort of
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith, in a chronology supported by Craig's spokesman Will
Hart, said Craig was on the Senate floor when Sen. Frank
Lautenburg, D-N.J., claimed Bush supported mandatory background
checks on gun purchasers at shows _ just as if the sale were at a
gun shop. Requiring a background check was part of a Lautenberg
proposal in competition with a measure by Craig.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Sarah Brady, George W. Bush, (Rep.) Henry Hyde, gun
manufacturers and gun dealers get behind closing a loophole, I
think everybody here ought to listen, and we ought to close it,''
Lautenberg said in Senate debate.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg spokesman Mark Nevins said Lautenberg's statement was
based on published reports of Bush's recently announced support for
background checks at gun shows and that the senator had not
contacted Bush or his office. Bush confirmed the point in a news
conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said that when Craig, who opposes mandatory checks at
gun shows, heard Lautenberg's statement, he went to a cloakroom off
the Senate floor and called Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said Bush and Craig discussed the bills. The spokesman
said Bush told Craig he would prefer the Republican's proposal over
the Democrats' but repeated his support for mandatory background
checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Hart said Craig apparently never referred to his conversation
with Bush during the ensuing debate.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said the only other contact between the Bush and Craig
offices on the gun-show point came last Thursday when he asked an
aide to phone Craig's staff and ask for copies of the two measures.
</P>
<P>
   But word of the Craig-Bush phone conversation _ apparently with
some embellishments _ made the rounds in the Senate cloakrooms.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Senate Republicans changed their minds and voted
Friday for the mandatory background checks, Bush's alleged role in
the switch was being set in stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably gives Bush more credit than he's due, but such is
the advantage of being a front-runner in a presidential race,''
said a Senate Democratic source.
</P>
<P>
   The spin about Bush's power amuses the governor and his aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Craig) call came before any votes at all,'' Beckwith
said. ``I tried to point that out'' to at least one national
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   By the weekend Bush's supposedly pivotal role and influence was
firming up as gospel on a nationally televised program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This juggernaut is getting mythic proportions,'' Beckwith
declared in mock triuphmalism. ``I mean, we can do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
