</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-BALLET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON BALLET HAS RAISED THE BARRE FOR TEXAS COMPANIES
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: Has sidebar, HOUSTON-STEVENSON (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Ben Stevenson was a young dancer touring with a
British company the first time he saw Houston, in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stayed at the Shamrock Hilton, which was a glamorous new
hotel then,'' he says. ``It was out in the country in those days,
and we thought we were in the wild, wild west.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he returned, two decades later, Stevenson was a
renowned choreographer and teacher who had just been named artistic
director of the Houston Ballet. And he began the work of turning a
small, regional company into one of the success stories of American
ballet.
</P>
<P>
   It's a story with plenty of lessons for the Fort Worth-Dallas
region. The rise of Fort Worth Dallas Ballet in the past decade,
and its successful weathering of last year's resignation of its
artistic director, are admirable. However, although the Fort
Worth-Dallas area is comparable in size to Houston, we still lag
far behind Houston's company in budget, company size and national
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston company has more than twice the annual budget of
ours and not quite twice as many dancers, with a reputation built
on national and international tours, and a repertoire rich in
lavish productions of old and new ballets.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Stevenson began touring nationally, staging new
productions of classics and substantial world premieres that have
become a part of the Houston Ballet tradition. New works that
Houston Ballet has premiered under Stevenson include ``The Snow
Maiden,'' ``Dracula'' and ``Peer Gynt;'' new versions of classics
include ``Romeo and Juliet,'' ``Cinderella'' and ``Sleeping
Beauty.'' A new full-length ballet titled ``Cleopatra'' will be
premiered next year. The company has appeared in Europe, in China
and at important U.S. venues, including the Metropolitan Opera
House in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Ballet success story began in 1976. Having risen to
a position of respect as a teacher and choreographer on both sides
of the Atlantic in the 1960s, Stevenson was without a job when the
Chicago company he worked for folded _ at the same time the small,
young company in Houston had announced it needed an artistic
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in New York told me not to apply,'' Stevenson says.
But instead, he made an ambitious proposal: He wanted to build,
over a period of decades, a genuine Houston-based company that
would not depend on guest artists.
</P>
<P>
   To his surprise, the board agreed. But that was only the first
obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio was a closet,'' he says. Prominent supporters built
a facility for him, which was followed in 1984 by the current
facility, a spacious, light-filled converted shoe factory near
downtown, supplemented by rehearsal space at the downtown Wortham
Center, where the company performs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two audiences in Houston,'' Stevenson says. ``The
ones who were loyal to the Houston Ballet, and the ones who wanted
to see guest companies. We have stood our ground.''
</P>
<P>
   But even success stories have moments of crisis _ or, in the
case of the Houston Ballet, budget problems. In 1995, the company's
long-term deficit reached $400,000; worse than that, the company
had to be ``rescued'' at the end of several seasons with intensive
fund-raising drives.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Director Cecil Conner arrived during the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that we couldn't do a year-end campaign every
year,'' Conner says. ``Instead of budgeting on the basis of `Here's
what we want to spend,' we realized we had to budget based on
`Here's how much money we have, how shall we spend it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part was cutting the corps from 56 dancers to 46.
</P>
<P>
   Under Conner, the long-term deficit has disappeared, and the
annual budget has returned to $11.2 million annually, close to the
pre-crisis level. Equally important, the endowment has reached $30
million, very close to the ideal endowment-to-budget ratio of
3-to-1. The subscription season was cut from seven to six
performances and the minimum number of performances dropped from
seven to six; the company discovered that by having fewer
performances, it could keep its income steady while lowering
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the dance boom of the 1970s and 1980s, we thought dance
would grow forever. Then, in the 1990s, everyone had to cut back,''
Conner says. ``Now, we know that growth is not the only criterion
for success.''
</P>
<P>
   No single element has been responsible for the success of the
Houston Ballet. The continuity of personnel on Stevenson's artistic
staff has been important _ he has staffers whom he has known since
his London days _ along with his devotion to building a school.
Now, Stevenson can say with confidence that there is a ``Houston
look'' in his company _ descended from but not exactly the same as
the British school of ballet he learned.
</P>
<P>
   New ideas in fund-raising have also been significant. Houston
Ballet supporters invented the ``Nutcracker Market,'' a
holiday-time boutique concept that has been picked up by other
companies, including Fort Worth Dallas Ballet. Houston's
``Nutcracker Market'' grosses $6 million annually in sales,
providing an impressive net profit of $1 million. And community
support has been crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Houston proves that a major ballet company can thrive in Texas.
The question now is whether Fort Worth and Dallas can match or even
exceed Houston's accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
