<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-STEVENSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET BEN STEVENSON, THE MAN WHO PUT HOUSTON ON ITS TOES
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: SIDER with HOUSTON-BALLET (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston Ballet Artistic Director Ben Stevenson is, like the
company he directs, a study in versatility, perseverance and
imagination, with a talent for taking advantage of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1936 in the British coastal town of Portsmouth, the son
of a bus driver and a florist, he started studying ballet at 7.
</P>
<P>
   His mother and sister ``were crazy about opera and ballet,'' he
says. Knock-kneed, he was encouraged to study dance by a doctor
whose daughter had cured a similar problem with ballet classes.
</P>
<P>
   But the ballet classes did more than cure bad legs: By 15, he
was good enough to win a government grant to go to London for
advanced study. There, his hallmark versatility emerged early on
when he was a member of the touring Ballet Arts Theatre company, an
outgrowth of the ``Ballet for Beginners'' TV program, and a dancer
in West End musicals. But classical ballet continued to call him
back, and he danced with the Sadlers Wells Ballet, the Festival
Ballet of London and the Sadlers Wells Opera Ballet _ as well as in
productions of ``The Boys From Syracuse'' and ``The Music Man'' and
other musicals of the era.
</P>
<P>
   While Stevenson was at the Festival Ballet in London, he
choreographed ``The Sleeping Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Sleeping Beauty'' was a success, a change of company
management put Stevenson out of work; a friend encouraged him to
visit New York. Within two weeks, his skills as a teacher of dance
were discovered; he became director of the Harkness Youth Dancers,
which eventually became the main Harkness Company, which
specialized in new ballets in a classical style. There, Stevenson
produced his first original ballet, ``Three Preludes,'' to music of
Rachmaninoff. The piece premiered with the company on tour in
Dallas, and has since become a part of the international dance
repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
