<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-TEN-COMMANDMENTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY BIRTHDAY -- TEN COMMANDMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RABBI ELI HECHT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, May 21, Jews worldwide will celebrate a
holiday called Shavuoth. The highlight of the holiday is attending
synagogue and listening to the revelation of God in the form of the
Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jewish tradition this event happened some 3,311
years ago on Mt. Sinai. The story is read from a hand-written
scroll called the Torah. Since the event took place 50 days after
the Jewish exodus from Egyptian slavery, the holiday is also called
Pentecost, meaning fifty.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the holiday marks the birthday of the Ten
Commandments and the Hebrew Bible called the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   Whether one believes that the special covenant between God and
the Hebrews was passed on to the church, called New Hebrews, or to
the Islamic religion, the Hebrew Bible remains supreme and
respected by all religions. It is the most influential book in
human history.
</P>
<P>
   Let me share the following story that took place in the year
800.
</P>
<P>
   There was a kingdom called the Khuzaria, which was situated
between old Turkey and Russia. Buland, the king of the Khuzaria
people, was a very spiritual person. However, his country was a mix
of many religions and pagans.
</P>
<P>
   One night the king had a dream and he was told by an angel,
``Thy way of thinking is pleasing to God, but not Thy way of
acting.''
</P>
<P>
   The dream caused the king to study many religions. After
concluding there were three main religions he invited
representatives of each religion to his palace. To each he told the
following: ``You must pick a different religion than what you now
practice.'' This was made under the threat of death.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian said, ``the Jewish religion is for me, their Bible
is the old testament.'' The Moslem said, ``I do not believe that
the Christian religion is a way of life. I do, however, believe in
the Hebrew Bible. It is the mother of religions.'' The Jew answered
``I am ready for death. It is the Hebrew Bible that I want and
nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   The king saw that the Hebrew Bible was respected by all
religions. Subsequently his entire nation embraced the Jewish
religion. The kingdom lasted two or three hundred years. Rabbi
Judah Halevi wrote a book in the 12th century describing the
episode, called ``The Book of the Khuzarai.''
</P>
<P>
   From this story we realize how respected the Hebrew Bible is by
all religions.
</P>
<P>
   In America's infancy we find the Puritans espousing the Hebrew
Bible. As early as 1650, the colony of New Haven used the Hebrew
Bible for its laws. By reviewing the writings of our early settlers
you will find that the leaders of the colonies studied and knew
Hebrew well.
</P>
<P>
   Our great Liberty Bell carries the quote from the Bible,
``Proclaim liberty throughout the land unto all inhabitants
thereof.'' Some knew a lot more about being Jewish in those days
than our present-day Jewish population. Our founding fathers wanted
religion to be part of our great republic.
</P>
<P>
   We all recognize that the Ten Commandments are the most
important instructions that God has given to the Jewish nation.
However, we must remember that there is no monopoly on the
commandments and their rewards. All nations are free to study and
observe the commandments.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all religions should celebrate the holiday of Shavuoth,
the birthday of the Ten Commandments, God's present to the world.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
