<SLUG> BC-PORK-AND-KOSOVO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING BILL HAS A LITTLE BIT FOR EVERYONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, D.C. _ Exit 66 in Box Elder, S.D., is a long way
from Kosovo, but it's close enough for government work, which helps
explain why an emergency spending bill for the war in Yugoslavia
includes a new highway interchange for the town of 3,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have larded the $15 billion spending package that is
sailing through Congress this week with similar narrow-interest
provisions. There's $100,000 for a new YMCA child care center in
Huntington Park, Calif. There's $1.5 million to buy water for a
parched lake in Arizona. There's $2 million for a study of a
proposed wood veneer plant in Ketchikan, Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which the House passed easily Tuesday and the Senate
is set to vote on Thursday, began as a straightforward effort to
pay for the air war and the damage left by a series of natural
disasters. But the must-pass legislation has become a handy vehicle
for lawmakers looking for a way to get pet projects on a fast
track.
</P>
<P>
   The spending package is expected to win final approval in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill has very little to do with busting Belgrade and a
great deal to do with bursting the budget,'' Rep. Lloyd Doggett,
D-Austin, said during House debate Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill earmarks $1.3 million to help prepare for a World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle, gives the city of Colorado Springs
$1 million for a new summit house at Pike's Peak and clears the way
for an $8 million forestry research center at Auburn University in
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the spending package say they demonstrated
remarkable restraint, given the temptations. About $12 billion of
the $15 billion bill is earmarked for defense. An additional $2.9
billion is dedicated to disaster relief. That left about $268
million for projects that fit neither category. It was that pot of
money that bankrolled most of the disputed items.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things that some people don't like. It depends
on where you're from and what you believe, I guess,'' said Sen. Ted
Stevens, R-Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it does, and if you're from Alaska, there's plenty to
like. As chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee, Stevens
made sure his state interests were addressed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the veneer plant, the spending bill includes $23
million to compensate Alaska fishers for losses they've suffered as
a result of fishing restrictions in Glacier Bay National Park.
Dungeness crab fishers are guaranteed ``fair market value'' from
the government for any crab pots and related gear they take out of
service.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a provision for reindeer that makes the animals
eligible for $70 million in livestock assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Santa in trouble?'' asked Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa. ``Is
there some reindeer emergency that I am not aware of that requires
millions of dollars?''
</P>
<P>
   Some congressional add-ons are aimed at helping private
interests battle the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., added a provision overriding the
Interior Department's objections to the planned Crown Jewel Mine in
his state. Environmentalists are livid because the mine operators
plan to use a cyanide solution to extract gold from Buckhorn
Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, added language extending a
moratorium against a Clinton administration proposal to increase
royalties on oil and gas produced on federal land.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also weighed in on more mundane items, including
naming a new Post Office in Tuscumbia, Ala., after former Sen.
Howell Heflin.
</P>
<P>
   But it is money that counts the most back home.
</P>
<P>
   In Box Elder, Mayor Glenn Baldwin was thrilled by the prospect
of $3 million to help pay for a new interchange on Interstate 90.
City officials want to shut down Exit 66 because it is in the
flight path of the B-1 bombers at nearby Ellsworth Air Force Base.
The new exit would be about a mile down the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Rene Brizuela, the executive director of the YMCA in Huntington
Park, said the $100,000 grant for his facility would expand a
preschool day care program from 50 children to 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need is here. There's no question,'' Brizuela said. ``I
don't know what relationship it has to Kosovo, if there is any
relationship between Kosovo and child care.''
</P>
<P>
   And fishers at San Carlos Lake, near Globe, Ariz., can't wait to
get more water in a lake that is in danger of drying up this
summer. The money will be used to buy water from another lake.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that pork is in the eye of the beholder, a grateful
sports columnist publicly thanked the measure's chief sponsor, Rep.
Ed Pastor, D-Ariz., for slipping it into the spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressmen are easy to criticize sometimes,'' Barry Burkhart
wrote in The Arizona Republic, ``but they're easy to love in this
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
