<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3644 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-TRADING-WORKPL     05-19 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-TRADING-WORKPLACE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET PORN; LATEST WORKPLACE DISTRACTION IS FOLLOWING STOCK MARKET
ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., N.Y., Wash.)  (Eds.: Please note that the (STAR) within parentheses has been used
in the 7th and last grafs instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(rk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Florida, a young dentist tracks stocks between patients,
sometimes even between an X-ray and a filling. In Washington state,
a freight-company manager logs on to a financial Web site for four
to six hours of his workday. A designer at a California
architectural firm gets so absorbed in the market that his
productivity falls 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The long bull market and cascading advances in technology have
combined to drive capitalism's main numbers game into the heart of
the American workplace, with millions of wage earners, managers and
entrepreneurs obsessing about Wall Street. Their obsession, in
fact, far eclipses the speculative 1920s, when elevator operators
and bootblacks were a chief source of what passed for information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago I would have never thought I'd be into doing
this,'' said the dentist, Norma Victores, 30, of Hialeah, Fla., who
follows the market on the Internet and has bought part of her
portfolio of 21 stocks and mutual funds online. ``I used to think
it was just for the big-timers.''
</P>
<P>
   While much of the early concern about workday Internet abuse
focused on pornography, the lure of the stock market has overtaken
it, some specialists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where employees are really wasting their time,'' said
Jonathan Penn, an analyst at Giga Information Group, a firm that
advises companies on information technology. ``I'd definitely put
that first,'' he added, ahead of sports, personal e-mail and chat
rooms, with pornography _ its sites now typically blocked _ further
down the list.
</P>
<P>
   The flick-of-the-finger ease with which office workers and
others can research, monitor and trade stocks _ often able to
return instantly to their assigned tasks _ is of rising concern to
employers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Media Metrix, a New York company that meters
Internet use much the way Nielsen does television, 22.8 million
Americans used Web sites on company time in March. About 25 percent
of all corporate Internet traffic, much of it surreptitious, is
considered unrelated to work. Some 8.2 million people visited Yahoo
Finance, CBS Marketwatch, Schwab, E(STAR)Trade and other financial
sites at work, up from 6 million just three months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market ``is becoming a huge distraction,'' said Victor
Woodward, a vice president at Content Technologies, which develops
programs to help companies create and enforce policies for Internet
usage. He said corporate demand for help in curbing stock-related
Web use had quadrupled in the past year as proprietors of gateways
add monitoring and other financial features as ``a way to draw in
eyeballs,'' which bring advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Online trades account for as much as 30 percent of all buying
and selling by individual investors, surveys show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that this is not a problem in the workplace,''
acknowledged Jill Munden, who oversees Silicon Investor, the
biggest financial discussion forum. She said that 50 percent of
site visits, which average 20 minutes each, come during regular
working hours and that ``you have to believe most people don't
divulge trades and research to their boss or co-workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for Charles Schwab , the broker accounting for more
than a quarter of Internet transactions, now averages 33 million
visits a day, up from 24 million in the fourth-quarter of 1998,
according to Daniel Hubbard, a spokesman. And actual transactions,
which take only a couple of minutes, are outnumbered 26 to 1 by
typically longer sessions for researching companies or mutual funds
or to review portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's busiest periods, Hubbard found, coincide with the
opening and closing hours of the New York Stock Exchange _ from
9:30 a.m. to 11:30 a.m and 3:30 p.m. to 4 p.m.. For many West Coast
investors, though, these might well not be work hours.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Dean Hatfield, a designer, for whom raking in
fast-stock-market money of between $5,000 and $15,000 a month for
much of last year began to threaten his day job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of billing, say, 37 hours during the week, as I should
have, I was billing perhaps 28,'' said Hatfield, who works at KRJ
Design in Burlingame, Calif. ``It became an issue because the
revenue just wasn't coming in.'' Hatfield's superiors took away his
Internet access, so now if he wants to go online he must walk to
another terminal, his activities easily visible. He likens it to
``getting your hands caught in the cookie jar.'' Now, he says, ``I
do it on the phone or from home _ but it's not day-trading
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   At American Fast Freight, a Kent, Wash., company that bundles
shipments into bigger units and then arranges for overseas
transport, the official in charge of computers, Jeff LePage, is
still struggling to find a way to ``put the kibosh'' on a
middle-aged employee who is routinely logged onto a financial site
for most of the working day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't really focused on this until it became chronic,''
said LePage, who now notices a gradual decline in the unit's
performance that he blames on the employee, a peer he is reluctant
to confront.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's John Alexandrou, a 43-year-old salesman in Foster
City, Calif., who said that for the past three years he has spent
30 minutes to an hour of working time a day on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adrenalin of trading options, that's got me completely
hooked,'' Alexandrou said, adding that the fraternity of on-the-job
market devotees is very large indeed, especially in Silicon Valley.
``You're not going to find very many people in this Valley who are
not distracted by the stock market,'' he said. He insisted,
however, that while he has suffered big losses on occasion, he
never fails to make his business quotas.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest concentration of Internet stock activity does
indeed seem to be on the West Coast, especially in the high-tech
community, where much of employees' pay is in stock options and it
is common for even those of low rank to have an equity stake.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
