<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3645 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-TRADING-WORKPL     05-19 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-TRADING-WORKPLACE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: equity stake.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course, while the Internet makes a lot of information
available to small investors that was once accessible only to
professionals, that does not mean all those investors necessarily
pay less attention to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Brown, vice president of MSI Consulting, a Seattle-based
management and marketing adviser to high-tech companies, says he
often spends less time tending to his portfolio in the mid-six
figures than when he used to phone orders to a broker, a process he
said can mean ``you've chewed up an hour of your day.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor has the government been able to discern much economic effect
from the presumed productivity loss caused by a distracted work
force. Growth in output per hour accelerated last year, and Michael
Harper, acting associate commissioner for Productivity and
Technology at the Bureau of Labor Statistics, guessed that the time
wasted by workers on the stock market was not unlike water-cooler
discussion of football or movies, and may even be a partial
substitute for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know whether they would be working _ or doing
something else'' if interest in the stock market should wane,
Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the market is seen as an increasingly serious time-eater
by many employers, who while having great technical ability to
monitor Internet activity, have only recently begun to do so in
earnest. A survey by the Society for Human Resource Management
found 76 percent of members not bothering as recently as 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, employees seem to have little trouble avoiding
detection from casual observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hide the day-trading quite easily,'' said Hatfield,
the California designer, a 36-year-old who for a time was making
more money trading than in salary. ``One second I was in
E(STAR)Trade,'' he said, referring to a popular electronic broker.
``And the next second I was doing design in AutoCad,'' a tool of
his trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
