<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNATIONAL SPACE STATION SURVIVES HOUSE TEST
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Despite its inflating cost and significant delays,
the international space station survived attempts in the House
Wednesday to scrap it.
</P>
<P>
   The NASA project avoided being terminated by a vote of 337 to
92. The House also rejected amendments to limit money for the
project and to exclude Russia from the station's international
partnership. The action came as the House considered a bill
authorizing NASA's future activities. A final vote is expected
today (THURSDAY).
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Next graph for Palm Beach Post; trim for other papers)
</P>
<P>
   Reps. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Ft. Lauderdale; Alcee Hastings,
D-Miramar; Mark Foley, R-West Palm Beach,; and Robert Wexler,
D-Boca Raton, voted with the majority each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think its a good deal for science,'' said Rep. Tim
Roemer, D-Ind., a House Science Committee member who moved to
eliminate the station. ``This project just doesn't live up to
NASA's past accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposed in 1984 by Ronald Reagan, the station originally was
projected to cost $8 billion to launch and maintain, while current
costs are estimated at $100 billion. The United States has invested
$20 billion in the project and still has $80 billion to go, said
Rep. Mark Sanford, R-S.C., a co-sponsor of Roemer's amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project is becoming ridiculous in its costs and time
overruns,'' Sanford said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., chairman of the House
Science Committee, said the space station is vital in developing
technologies and medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Roemer said the partnership with Russia cost the United States
more time and money in constructing the station. The administration
encouraged a partnership with Russia to save taxpayers $2 billion,
but instead it has cost the United States $4 billion, Roemer said.
He blamed the increased cost on numerous delays and Russia's
financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
