<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-HAULER-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE THREATENED BY TEAMSTERS WHO TRUCK NEW AUTOS TO DEALERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Teamsters' union is threatening a strike by
drivers against the trucking companies that carry new cars to
dealerships. Such a move would likely limit the selection of
vehicles available to consumers but would not affect the economy as
much as a strike at an auto factory.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers voted overwhelmingly earlier this week to authorize
their leaders to call a strike if a new national contract with the
trucking companies cannot be negotiated before the current
four-year contract expires May 31.
</P>
<P>
   This contract was concluded only after a 32-day strike in 1995
against the leading car-carrier company at the time, Ryder System
Inc. in Miami, and many in the auto industry are concerned that
another strike may be likely.
</P>
<P>
   With auto sales running at the fastest pace ever through the
first four months of this year, a strike could quickly disrupt
supplies to dealerships. ``Everyone would have a problem,'' said
Ford Motor Co. chief executive Jacques Nasser earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem would not be as serious as last summer's 54-day
strike by General Motors auto parts workers in Flint, Mich. That
strike forced GM to close virtually all of its North American
assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers were able to keep their factories operating during
the 1995 strike, shipping new cars and light trucks by rail
whenever possible and storing other finished vehicles in empty
lots. GM, the automaker most reliant on Ryder, continued shipping
cars by rail to its 50 regional distribution centers and invited
dealers to send employees to drive the new cars from the centers to
the dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   State laws allow vehicles to be sold as new even if dealers and
their employees have had to drive them to their point of sale.
Since the last strike, Ryder has sold its car-transport business to
Allied Holdings Inc., based in Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A strike could be much more significant for the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters and its new president, James P. Hoffa,
than for the auto industry. While the Teamsters now represent
workers in many industries, the union has its roots in the trucking
industry, where much of the organizing was done by Hoffa's father,
James R. Hoffa. Negotiations with the car-transport companies will
offer Hoffa his first chance to show whether he can negotiate
bigger gains for drivers than his predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   If negotiators for the Teamsters and trucking companies are
unable to reach a deal by May 31, the truckers would not
necessarily walk off the job immediately. Though the Teamsters have
threatened an immediate walkout, the union made a similar threat in
1995 but waited until September.
</P>
<P>
   Some auto assembly plants close for weeks at a time in June and
July to install new equipment for the building of the next model
year's vehicles. The Teamsters would be able to put more pressure
on the transport companies for a settlement if the union waits
until factories resume weekly production of hundreds of thousands
of new cars.
</P>
<P>
   If the drivers struck, dealerships would most likely run out of
popular models that are in short supply. Inventories are now lowest
for full-sized sport utility vehicles and pickup trucks and for
Japanese-brand minivans like Honda Motor Co.'s Odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   The Flint strike last summer led to layoffs of nearly 200,000
workers at GM and thousands of employees at its suppliers,
significantly slowing economic growth in the United States in the
second and third quarters. GM has still not fully recovered from
that strike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
