<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Thursday, May 20, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Stewart Slavin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   STAR-HOOKY (Los Angeles) _ Star Wars fans call in sick to
schools and businesses to stand in line for the best seats and for
the opportunity to finally satisfy their yen for the ``Phantom
Menace.'' By Jesse Hiestand. (Will move in the ``n'' California and
``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   with
</P>
<P>
   STAR-ANTI (Los Angeles) _ In a galaxy right here, on a street
corner not so far away, people live and work and shop with little
regard of the social phenomenon that is opening at a movie theater
near them. In fact, these are the people who couldn't care less
that ``Star Wars Episode 1: The Phantom Menace'' opened Wednesday.
By Gregory J. Wilcox.
</P>
<P>
   STAR-TIX (Los Angeles) _ The official record-breaking, first-day
totals for ``Star Wars Episode 1: The Phantom Menace,'' as told by
analysts and the studio that released the movie. By Dave McNary.
(Will in the ``n'' California, ``a'' national and ``f'' financial
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   ZEDILLO-VISIT (Los Angeles) _ Mexico's President Ernesto Zedillo
flies to suburban Burbank Airport and is greeted by Gov. Gray Davis
before the pair board historic railroad cars to travel to Union
Station in downtown Los Angeles. By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the
``n'' California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-CHANCELLOR (Los Angeles) _ Marshall Drummond, who was
president of Eastern Washington University for nine years and now
is administrator in Northern California community college
districts, was appointed chancellor of the L.A. Community College
District. By Robert Monroe. (Will move in the ``n'' California news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   HEART-NEED (Los Angeles) _ Elated at reaching her sister in the
Ukraine for the first time in 25 years, Lioudmila McDonald's joy
soon turned to grief. A niece she had never met needed open-heart
surgery to save her life, and only surgeons in the United States
had the necessary expertise and facilities. The doctors agreed to
donate their services, but now the teen-ager needs $8,000 to cover
other costs. By Steve Carney. (Will move in the ``n'' California
and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   BIKE-COMMUTER (Los Angeles) _ Fifteen years ago Geoff Stocker
was one of the few, the brave, the sweaty, who was bicycling to his
job at Cal State Northridge, where he serves as recreational sports
director. Today he still bikes to work. On Thursday, his dedication
to two-wheeled commuting will be celebrated as part of National
Bike to Work Day. By Yvette Cabrera. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-REFUGEES (Los Angeles) _ Thirty-two Kosovar refugees are
heading to Los Angeles, sponsored by relatives. The refugees, who
will arrive Thursday morning, will be living temporarily with host
families. By Michael Coit. (Will move in the ``n'' California and
``a'' national news files.)
</P>
