<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TECH-20-COX     05-19 1559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TECH-20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HI-TECH GAINS KEEP U.S. MILITARY COMMANDERS IN TOUCH WORLDWIDE
 &HT;    EDS: This story is also suitable for technology pages.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TASK FORCE HAWK, Albania _ During World War II, Gen. Dwight
Eisenhower sometimes waited for carrier pigeons to bring battle
dispatches from the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   During the Gulf War, Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf often got news from
the battle faster on CNN than from his own military communications.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lt. Gen. John Hendrix, commander of Task Force Hawk
troops in Albania, has tools of military communication that his
predecessors could scarcely dream of.
</P>
<P>
   And as he still prepares for a possible strike into Kosovo with
Apache tank-killing helicopters, the top U.S. commander is not the
only beneficiary of the military's great internet leap forward.
</P>
<P>
   Now even the 25-year-old captains working under Hendrix can call
up a classified bulletin board on their laptops that gives them
immediate access to operational orders and intelligence. Or they
can whip off a quick e-mail to their spouses or their bill
collectors, using an unclassified military internet system called
NIPRNET.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average captain here has more internet power in his or her
hands than a general did in the desert in Desert Storm,'' said Army
Maj. Doug Wolfe, 35, of Catasauqua, Pa., who is deputy
communications officer of Task Force Hawk.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the 24 Apache gunships and an assortment of artillery
rocket launchers, perhaps the most potent weapon the Army has
airlifted into Albania are 200 laptop computers and a plethora of
associated communications gear.
</P>
<P>
   For every 25 of Hendrix's soldiers, there is one
government-supplied laptop. All 200 have Ethernet cards or similar
devices so that they can be hooked in together in a military-wide
Local Area Network.
</P>
<P>
   Many, if not most, of the Army's current laptops have been
bought off-the-shelf from companies like Motorola, IBM, RCA,
Micron, Gateway, and Dell. The same is true of other communications
gear being used here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Army units in the field have been about eight to ten years
behind the civilian industry,'' said Lt. Col. Karla Torrez, 41, of
Cocoa Beach, Fla., the commander of the 32nd Signal Battalion from
Darmstadt, Germany. ``We are always evolving, just as they are.''
</P>
<P>
   In purchasing laptops for troops in the field, the Army
deliberately does not require any particular brand name. Instead,
it has been taking bids for standard laptops with some type of a
Pentium chip, plus at least 32 megabytes of memory. Some of these
``tactical'' laptops use Windows NT 4.0 as their operating system
while others use Windows 95, Windows 98, UNIX or
</P>
<P>
   Linux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I think there is also one Apple out here,'' said
Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
   When Hendrix first wakes up each morning inside his
camouflage-netted headquarters, he can immediately sit in front of
his own dedicated computer and fire off an e-mail to anyone in the
world. He can choose from two e-mail systems installed in his
laptop _ one for ``secure'' messages and one for ``unsecure.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Hendrix walks over to his command office, he has access to
another dedicated computer, this one also plugged into both secure
and unsecure internet networks.
</P>
<P>
   If Hendrix wants to dispatch a secret military message, he could
log onto the military's worldwide SIPRNET (Secure Internet Protocol
Network) system.
</P>
<P>
   This would allow him to send even highly secret information
almost instantly on a network designed to foil enemy eavesdroppers.
Using SIPRNET, he also can check for any overnight secret traffic
from his superiors in Italy, Brussels and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A SIPRNET message is first encrypted, using a super-secret
``key'' that has been certified to be immune to enemy eavesdroppers
by the U.S. National Security Agency. Then it is bounced from
Albania to somewhere outside the Balkans via a military satellite
to a downlink called the STEP site. From there, the message is
relayed to the rest of the SIPRNET, the
</P>
<P>
   military's secure turf within the internet.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix has a good many options if he wants a heart-to-heart
with his superiors thousands of miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can pick up a secure telephone and call them,'' said Wolfe.
``He can send them an e-mail note on secure e-mail. He can talk to
them securely via VTC (video teleconferencing). So he has a lot of
communications tools available to him that were not available to
Gen. Schwarzkopf back in Desert Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his subordinates, Hendrix is known to be a devotee of
management through secure video teleconferencing.
</P>
<P>
   After morning chow, Hendrix normally calls a transcontinental
staff meeting via secure VTC (video teleconferencing.) Hendrix sits
in front of a VTC terminal _ a laptop equipped with a microphone
and a small camera trained on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Back at his rear headquarters in Germany and other selected
points around the world, there are similar VTC terminals for
various generals, admirals and perhaps some civilians who have been
granted the right to participate in daily Task Force Hawk planning
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, there is often a second and a third video
teleconference. At least one of these regular meetings-by-video is
a top secret discussion run by Hendrix's G-2 (intelligence) section
that presumably includes the latest satellite imagery and other
data on what is happening in Yugoslavia and perhaps elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   This intelligence video teleconference takes place on an even
more secure military communications network that is known here by
its acronym, JWICCS.
</P>
<P>
   Though military communications have improved dramatically in the
last decade, everything isn't perfect here.
</P>
<P>
   The big challenge is trying to overcome the mountains of
Albania, which sometimes make it difficult for commanders to reach
the low-flying Apaches and their support helicopters as they scoot
through the valleys leading toward Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mountain terrain has caused problems here that we've
always talked about when we teach doctrine to Army units,'' said
Col. Torrez of the 32nd Signal Battalion. ``But to experience it,
you really recognize the challenge that a lot of our systems cannot
get over the mountains. And satellites become more of a requirement
than a luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the problem is that from World War II to the Gulf
War, the Army has run its battles mostly with walkie-talkies and
other forms of ``line of sight'' communications. In the mountains,
they don't work as well as they do in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   During Operation Desert Storm against Iraqi forces, one of the
most dependable battlefield radios was called ``Fox Mike'' _ the
military way of referring to a certain portion of the FM radio
band.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those (military radios using FM) have been improved since
Desert Storm,'' said Wolfe. ``There are not only improvements in
security, but also improvements in the radios. Back in Desert
Storm, most units were using old-model Fox Mike (radios). Now they
are using something called SINCGARS (Single Channel Ground Airborne
Radio System). It's a very good system.''
</P>
<P>
   Good. But not ideal for the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   To overcome the limitations of ``line-of-sight'' radios, the
Army also relies on a network of military satellites, some of them
called TACSATs. And then there is the high-flying
command-and-control plane called the ABCCC, which can fly high over
Albania with a ranking Army general and a staff of communications
experts aboard to help manage an Apache attack.
</P>
<P>
   It's taken some on-the-spot ingenuity, but the Army is figuring
ways to communicate on the ground despite the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though you need satellites to get over the mountains, you
can extend the range from your systems by taking the satellite into
a line-of-site system and breaking it off into potentially two
locations via line-of-site,'' said Torrez. ``So we are mixing the
systems.''
</P>
<P>
   As adept at communicating as the Army is today, the experts on
the scene from the Signal Corps are not claiming they can do
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are limits,'' said Torrez. ``The satellites are one. You
only have so much bandwidth available. And bandwidth is a common
term in the Signal Corps that is our constraint these days. The
more bandwidth, the bigger the communications pipe. The bigger the
pipe, the more you can pump through.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the technological advances of the last decade that permitted
the army to multiply its ``connectivity,'' the most important was
the widespread adoption of digital technology for satellite
communications, as well as a data-sending method called ``packet
switching.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have transferred from analog technology _ analog systems _
to digital systems and packet switching,'' said Torrez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Packet-switching assigns time slots to the transfer of data
and does it continuously,'' said Torrez. ``The basic analog
telephone circuitry was: 'I gave you 16 channels on a group. Once
you dialed and seized a channel, no one else could have it, whether
you used it or not.'
</P>
<P>
   ``With packet-switching and digital technology, we can give a
group of computers a channel to do packet-switching on, and they
will get a lot more information transferred.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
