<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3657 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-MINISTER-BOS &LR;      05-19 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MINISTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN PRIME MINISTER PICK EASILY APPROVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Just days after narrowly surviving an impeachment vote,
President Boris N. Yeltsin consummated his victory over parliament
Wednesday as his choice for prime minister sailed through an
unusually easy confirmation vote.
</P>
<P>
   One Kremlin aide called it an ``indisputable victory'' for
Yeltsin after the State Duma, the normally hostile lower house of
parliament, voted 301-55 to approve Sergei Stepashin, the former
head of police and internal security forces, as Russia's third
premier in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   But Duma leaders made it clear the vote was not a sign of
confidence that Stepashin, 47, who has no background in economic
administration, had the answers to the country's many economic
woes. The lawmakers were voting to prevent a showdown with Yeltsin
that some predicted could lead to bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators said they decided not to avoid further confrontation
with the volatile Russian president after failing to muster the 300
votes needed to begin impeachment proceedings against Yeltsin on
Saturday. And anyway, lawmakers said, Stepashin was not the worst
man for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he fires the right people and hires the right people and
his government lasts for more than three weeks, well, yes, he might
accomplish something,'' lawmaker Grigory Yavlinsky said of
Stepashin, in faint praise that echoed throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin shook off the less-than-enthusiastic reception and
thanked lawmakers for their support, which he said meant political
forces were ready put aside their disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are united by concern for our homeland for our people so
that our country may at last become normal, civilized, wealthy,
prosperous and great,'' Stepashin said after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the vote approving Stepashin ended, for now, a
government crisis that began last week when Yeltsin abruptly fired
the government of former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who was
popular both in polls and in the Duma. Yeltsin, despite his
frequent illnesses and 2 percent approval rating, has suddenly
reemerged as Russia's most powerful political figure _ again.
</P>
<P>
   It must be said that the aging, ailing Russian president is
probably the world leader in being written off and making
improbable political comebacks. But in his many catfights with the
Duma, the president has prevailed only in part because he is a
master of political brinksmanship, especially in comparison with
his main opponents in Russia. It is the constitution Yeltsin
imposed on Russia in 1993, first by dissolving parliament with
tanks and later by pushing through a highly suspicious referendum,
that gives the president the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   If the Duma had failed to approve Stepashin, the constitution
gave Yeltsin the right to keep naming him, or appoint someone more
radical. After the third vote, Yeltsin would have been able to
dismiss the Duma and set new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Had Yeltsin been impeached, he could not have dismissed the
Duma. But only one impeachment charge _ illegally waging war in
Chechnya _ came anywhere near success. Only a few deputies
Wednesday pondered the irony that the Duma nearly impeached Yeltsin
over Chechnya, but then approved Stepashin, who as head of Russian
counterintelligence played a key role in the early mishaps of the
war, which killed an estimated 80,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Duma grumbled that Stepashin's government will
probably be as short-lived as those of his predecessors, Primakov,
Sergei Kiriyenko and Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov, who led the failed
impeachment drive, said Stepashin's desire to serve was ``almost
even admirable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the new government has no guarantees that it will be able
to accomplish anything while the main destroyer is sitting in the
Kremlin,'' Zyuganov said during a remarkably brisk debate over
Stepashin's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov also expressed concern that Stepashin, loyal to Yeltsin
might choose ministers from the ``oligarchs,'' a group of financial
insiders personified by Yeltsin family friend Boris Berezovsky; and
the ``young reformers,'' a group led by former economic guru
Anatoly Chubais. Most Russians blame those two groups for the
country's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   However, only one lawmaker spoke out against Stepashin. ``Those
who vote for Stepashin will be voting to prolong the genocide
against our people!'' cried legislator Magarita Chistokhodova.
</P>
<P>
   But most Duma members figured that voting against Stepashin
would be voting to prolong the government crisis, and that the
lower house had nothing to gain from the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Ryzhkov, head of bloc that usually supports Yeltsin,
agreed. He compared Russia today to the last days of the Russian
empire, when an autocratic but unpopular czar drove the country to
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``In such a situation, who will give a red cent that (Stepashin)
will work for three more months,'' Ryzhkov said. ``We believe that
with the country half in ruins we need some sort of stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin said it would take him about a week to form a
government and immediately embarked on a two-hour meeting with
Yeltsin in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin was at work a day after Spanish officials caused a scare
Tuesday by saying the president had come down with acute bronchitis
_ something the Kremlin denied. The president made no public
statements, but made a point of appearing on national television
with Vladimir Putin, the head of state security, just to let
everyone know who was in control.
</P>
<P>
   In his address to the chamber, Stepashin pledged to deal harshly
with criminals and corruption, repeating promises that he has made
as interior minister. But he sought to play down speculation that
his nomination was a prelude to a crackdown on opposition parties,
rumors that have drawn comparsions to former Chilean dictator
Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not General Pinochet,'' he told the chamber. ``My name is
Stepashin.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin promised not to make major changes to the policies
pursued by Primakov, who was widely credited with calming the
political and economic crises that followed the collapse of
Russia's financial system last August.
</P>
<P>
   But Stepashin also said Russians expected ``concrete and
positive results from the government'' and he would provide them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
