A3665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-1STLD-W     05-19 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCERTAIN OF ITS PATH, UNITED STATES PROVIDES NO DIRECTION TO
ALLIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds, fixes to Schroeder, the umlaut being nontransmissable, in the
6th, 7th and 8th grafs; today to Wednesday in the 6th graf.)  (rm) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ As NATO wrestles with whether to dispatch combat
troops to Kosovo, there is no longer a unified NATO strategy about
how to win the war. And without Washington providing a clear
direction, Britain, Germany and Italy have begun to publicly
promote separate and conflicting plans.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been unable to quiet the unruly chorus
because it has not made up its own mind about how to bring the war
to a successful close. As Washington's allies lock horns over the
risks and advantages of a land campaign, President Clinton has said
only that he is not excluding the option.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is a committee that lacks a chairman,'' said Ivo
Daalder, the former director of European Affairs at the National
Security Council. ``There is a lack of direction because no one is
leading the way.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO's confusion is, no doubt, welcome news for President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia. From the start, his strategy has
been to ride out the air war, encourage divisions within the
Western alliance and try to negotiate a Kosovo settlement on his
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, events at NATO headquarters this week provided ample
evidence of dissension within the ranks. British Foreign Minister
Robin Cook started off the week by reminding the alliance that time
was running out for NATO's plan to return ethnic Albanian refugees
to Kosovo before the winter. He urged NATO to quicken the pace by
considering a land attack after Serb troops were weakened by
several more months of air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The British plan, however, was greeted Wednesday with
undisguised contempt by German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Under political pressure from pacifists in his coalition
government, Schroeder told a closed-door meeting of NATO
ambassadors that Germany wanted the air war to continue but would
not back a NATO ground attack. That was a significant statement
since there cannot be an allied land campaign without the approval
of all 19 NATO members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not participate in this specifically British debate on
war theories,'' Schroeder later said in caustic remarks to the
press. ``I am against any change in NATO strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was just the German view. The Italians have their own
political problems: leftists in Italy's government's coalition have
complained about allied air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the criticism at home, Italy has fashioned its own,
somewhat convoluted plan. It has urged NATO to impose a 48-hour
bombing pause after the United Nations Security Council agrees to a
resolution outlining the principles of a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   If Belgrade still balked, Italy says, NATO could restart its air
strikes and mount a land campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each country has to deal with its own domestic
constituencies,'' a senior Western diplomat said. ``Like everything
in NATO, this will depend on where the United States comes down.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressing question is whether air strikes alone will enable
NATO to attain its objectives. And if it does not, should the
alliance compromise with President Milosevic or raise the stakes by
sending in ground troops?
</P>
<P>
   Washington has yet to declare its hand, virtually inviting a
continuation of the noisy debate. Top Clinton administration
officials have said there is no allied agreement for a land
campaign without noting that Washington has done nothing to create
a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's indecisiveness recalls the
embarrassing round of diplomacy it conducted when it first began to
grapple with the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when the war in Bosnia raged, the White House developed
a plan to use air strikes against the Bosnian Serbs and to arm the
Bosnian Muslims. Instead of telling the Europeans that this is how
the allies needed to proceed, however, the Clinton administration
dispatched Secretary of State Warren Christopher to solicit the
allies view on the option.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans were surprised that the world's superpower was in
a listening mode and did not hesitate to rebuff the idea. It took
two more years, and countless lives, before the Clinton
administration insisted that the allies go along with its plan.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Washington is putting off the difficult decision on ground
troops for as long as possible in the hope that the Milosevic
regime, not NATO, will crack.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning preparations for a land war, Western officials
acknowledge, would be a wrenching decision for NATO under any
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But one diplomat added: ``It's hard to envisage the alliance
coming to terms with the issue until the leader of NATO is prepared
to make a decision,''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
