<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3671 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-BONES-2TAKES-N     05-19 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-BONES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 70 YEARS, REMAINS OF 2,000 INDIANS ARE BEING RETURNED HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ In what experts believe is the largest single
return of American Indian remains, the bones of nearly 2,000 Pueblo
Indians set out for home Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m., a 53-foot semi-trailer loaded with boxes of skeletons
began the long journey from Harvard's Peabody Museum, where the
bones have been stored and studied for more than 70 years, to the
ancient Pecos Valley site in New Mexico from where they were
excavated.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, from the New Mexican village of Jemez, the
descendants of the dead Pecos set out on a three-day foot trek to
meet them _ about 200 of them walking through the chilly mesa dawn
among rabbit brush and wildflowers, family dogs frisking at their
heels.
</P>
<P>
   The truck and the trekkers are to rendezvous Saturday for a
private mass reburial that tribal leaders say will cap a process
both solemn and full of the joy of rightful return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are real grateful, happy and proud that our ancestors are
on their way home,'' said Pete Toya, the war chief of the Pueblo of
Jemez.
</P>
<P>
   Since Congress passed the Native American Graves Protection and
Repatriation Act of 1990, skeletal remains and sacred objects have
been returned by museums to the tribes where they originated, as
mandated in the law.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 10,000 skeletons have been returned from possibly
100,000 stored at museums, estimated Thomas W. Killion, director of
repatriation at the National Museum of Natural History. His museum
alone has returned about 4,000 sets of skeletal remains, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But no single return has been as big as this one, and that is in
part because there has rarely been a Native American dig as big as
the Pueblo of Pecos excavation overseen by Alfred V. Kidder, an
archeological pioneer, from 1915 to 1929.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest collection in U.S. history, in terms of
material culture and human remains, from a single site
assemblage,'' said William Whately, the tribe's archeologist.
</P>
<P>
   Kidder went to the Pecos site specifically to lead a giant dig
that would help lay the foundation for modern archeological
techniques. The Pueblo of Pecos had been a significant southwestern
crossroads for half a millennium, one of the legendary cities of
gold sought by the Spaniards. But by the 19th century it had fallen
on hard times, and the remnants of its once-rich population
migrated to the Pueblo of Jemez in 1838 and effectively merged with
its people.
</P>
<P>
   Kidder set the standard for modern archeology when he excavated
the Pecos site, said James W. Bradley, an archeologist and director
of the Robert S. Peabody Museum in Andover, Mass., which has many
Pecos artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time that anyone went to major site and took
it apart stratographically _ sort of deconstructed it, and by
taking each of the layers off, understood the process by which that
site had been created,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kidder's finds, Bradley, said, turned into a kind of Rosetta
stone for the Southwest, providing critical clues about who lived
where when.
</P>
<P>
   The Pecos remains also provided valuable material for research
by physical anthropologists into how the early Indians lived; and
medical researchers took advantage of the statistical power offered
by such large numbers of skeletons to perform studies on
osteoporosis, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM) But times changed, and calls to redress the
wrongs done to Indians mounted. Soon after the repatriation act
passed in 1990, the descendants of the Pueblo of Pecos began to
discuss how to bring the remains home.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bradley at the Peabody Museum in Andover
contacted the tribe, as the law required, to let it know the museum
had material _ not skeletons, but masses of artifacts like pottery
_ that it believed it might be obligated to return.
</P>
<P>
   The pueblo's response was brief and to the point, Whately said:
``We know and let's talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Whately said the two sides treated each other all
along with the utmost respect. Soon, the other Peabody Museum, the
Harvard one with the skeletons _ formally called the Peabody Museum
of Archaeology and Ethnology _ joined the process.
</P>
<P>
   Though the talks were largely amiable, the return process was
fraught with deep emotion. In 1996, when a tribal delegation first
entered the Peabody Museum room where hundreds of their ancestors'
remains were stored, the pain was overwhelming, those present said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked into that room, and got together with our
ancestors, that was emotionally disturbing _ I shed some tears,''
Toya, the war chief, said. ``And then, being there for a couple of
hours, then, I guess, they told me that they were going back home.
And we've been working on it ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   As Whately described it, after a few minutes of sorrow ``every
single person in the room was overcome with a feeling of joy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the joy came to us it was a pretty clear indicator they
were telling us one thing and one thing alone: `We want to go
home,''' Whatley said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For all the descendants' happiness, the return of the bones hasa
downside for the scholars who can no longer study them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the bones' reburial meant a loss to researchers,
Barbara Isaac, assistant director and coordinator for repatriation
at Harvard's Peabody Museum said ``Yes'' _ but then qualified:
``Probably. We wouldn't know at this point what that research would
be. A great deal has already been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley at the Peabody Museum in Andover agreed that the bones'
return meant a certain loss to researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could additional work be done? Of course,'' he said. ``But we
are a culture of values, and one of our values is that you don't
exploit people.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all repatriations go so smoothly. Lawrence Hart, a Cheyenne
member of the federal review committee that oversees how the
repatriation act is carried out, said there are often disputes over
whether particular sets of remains can be positively identified as
coming from particular tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, the act is really being implemented well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Jemez Pueblo would surely agree. As the Jemez
Pueblo trek through the mesas and across the Rio Grande got under
way Wednesday, Stuart Gachupin, one of its coordinators, took a
break and exulted: ``We're happy that our ancestors are coming
home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1928EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
