<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-WRONGFUL-BOS &LR;      05-19 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-WRONGFUL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRONGFUL 23-YEAR IMPRISONMENT BRINGS $7 MILLION SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ For David Milgaard, hell at the hands of the Canadian
judicial system started in 1969 in his hometown of Saskatoon,
Saskatchewan, when a pretty young nursing aide was raped and
stabbed to death.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the assault suggested that Gail Miller, 20, was
the victim of a serial rapist who had attacked other women at
knifepoint, and police had an obvious suspect in a local man with a
long history of vicious sexual crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, for reasons that today appear almost sinister,
investigators focused on Milgaard, a 16-year-old possessed of a
wild streak _ but whose only prior brush with the law involved a
joyride in a stolen car.
</P>
<P>
   Their case against Milgaard was circumstantial _ he had been
placed in the same neighborhood. But it was the only case they
seriously pursued.
</P>
<P>
   Milgaard was charged, convicted and sentenced to prison. And
that's where his real nightmare began. He was sodomized by
cellmates, and abused by guards. He attempted suicide and made two
desperate escape attempts in his 23 years behind bars. On the
second of these, he was shot by Toronto police.
</P>
<P>
   All along, Milgaard was innocent of the crime. Not ``not
guilty'' by reason of some legal technicality. Truly innocent.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Milgaard's 30-year ordeal came to a close when he was
awarded $7 million by the Canadian and Saskatchewan governments. It
was the largest payout for wrongful conviction in Canadian history.
</P>
<P>
   ``After three terrible decades, it finally feels like it's
over,'' said his mother, Joyce Milgaard, who led the long battle
for exoneration.
</P>
<P>
   Milgaard, now 46, skipped the press conferences and apologies
from government officials to go camping in British Columbia with
his wife, Marnie. ``You can't really appreciate the horrors he's
survived,'' said lawyer Hersh Wolch, part of the volunteer legal
team that challenged the system on Milgaard's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Milgaard suffers from depression so severe he was recently
committed temporarily for treatment at a psychiatric hospital, and
rarely comments on the injustices that threw a boy into prison and
regurgitated him as a middle-aged man.
</P>
<P>
   ``No words can describe it,'' he told reporters two years ago
when a DNA test proved he was not Miller's assailant. ``I always
knew I was innocent. The hardest thing has been the waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The question shouldn't be: `How do I feel about
this?' The question should be, `How did this happen?' ''
</P>
<P>
   As part of an unprecedented federal and provincial deal with
Milgaard's family, Saskatchewan pledged to mount a public inquiry
into a case that has drawn international attention and tarnished
the image of Canadian justice.
</P>
<P>
   But observers give Canadian officials credit for finally making
an unequivocal apology to Milgaard and agreeing to the
extraordinary payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least Canadians still have the ability to blush,'' said
Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, the American former prizefighter whose
unjust conviction for a triple homicide in New Jersey was
immortalized in a Bob Dylan ballad and is the subject of an
upcoming film starring Denzel Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistakes like David Milgaard at least stir some sense of shame
among Canadians,'' said Carter, executive director for the
Toronto-based Association for the Wrongfully Convicted, who has
received neither apologies nor restitution for his own 20 years
behind bars in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The public inquiry into Milgaard's case is almost certain to
cause major embarrassment to Saskatoon police, whose behavior
appears to have gone beyond bungling and misjudgement to the realm
of conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Crucial files on suspects have vanished and evidence pointing
away from Milgaard was ignored. Incredibly, the police seeme to
have similarly shrugged off tips about the murder weapon and a
string of knife attacks against women that could not have been
perpetrated by Milgaard.
</P>
<P>
   The original suspect in the rape-murder, Larry Fisher, now 49, a
lifelong sexual criminal with seven rape convictions, has been
charged in Miller's death. He is scheduled to go on trial in
October.
</P>
<P>
   The nursing aide died from as the result of 12 stab wounds on
Jan. 31, 1969. The savage attack fit the pattern of Fisher's knife
assaults against women in Saskatchewan. Moreover, Fisher's own wife
refuted his alibi and told police that the paring knife probably
used in the attack was missiong from her kitchen on the day of the
killing. Police never followed up.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, prosecutors insisted on trying Milgaard for the case.
After the teenager's conviction, Saskatoon police files on Fisher
mysteriously vanished, and the prosecution's star witness was
killed in an odd hunting mishap.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Supreme Court of Canada overturned Milgaard's
conviction because of procedural errors, but urged Saskatchewan to
order a new trial. The province refused, but police and
prosecutors, in bizarre public statements, insisted that Milgaard
was guilty, and that even if he had been wrongfully convicted it
was just tough luck.
</P>
<P>
   That sance was abandoned only when DNA tests showed that semen
found on Miller could not possibly have come from Milgaard.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wrong of the most serious kind was committed,'' said
Saskatchewan Justice Minister John Nilson. ``How did a 16-year-old
end up serving 23 years for a crime he did not commit?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
