<HEADER>
A3676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAZI-DEPORT-500&AMP;ADD-N     05-19 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZI-DEPORT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. REOPENS CASE AGAINST ALLEGED NAZI DEATH CAMP GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, GERMANY, POLAND)  (js) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reopening a case that has haunted the Justice
Department for more than two decades, federal prosecutors went to
court Wednesday to try again to strip U.S. citizenship from John
Demjanjuk, a retired auto-worker from Cleveland who the government
charged was a Nazi death camp guard.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the civil complaint that could lead to Demjanjuk's
deportation was there any mention of the charge at the heart of the
government's original case in 1977 against Demjanjuk _ that he was
``Ivan the Terrible,'' the sadistic gas chamber operator who
slashed and beat thousands as he herded them to their deaths during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   That charge collapsed in a shattering defeat for the Justice
Department in 1993 after contradictory evidence emerged about
Demjanjuk's true identity and a federal appeals court subsequently
found that the Justice Department's Nazi-hunting unit, the Office
of Special Investigations, was ``reckless'' in failing to disclose
potentially exculpatory evidence in its files that another man
might have been the murderous Ivan of the Treblinka death camp.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the government brought a reduced but still searing
array of charges in the civil complaint filed in U.S. District
Court in Cleveland. The complaint retraced some of the lesser
charges in the original complaint accusing Demjanjuk of serving as
a guard at the Majdanek camp in Poland, the Flossenburg camp in
Germany and the Sobibor extermination camp in Poland, a
horrifyingly efficient operation that the Justice Department said
existed for the sole purpose of murdering Jewish civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the government complaint said Demjanjuk was a member
of an SS-run unit that took part in the mass round-up of nearly 2
million Jews in Nazi-occupied Poland who were killed in mass
shootings or in gas chambers.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department official said that the government revived
the case, which was officially overturned last year, in part
because of the seriousness of allegations about Demjanjuk's
activities at camps like Sobibor, one of only five extermination
camps in the entire Nazi network of wartime camps.
</P>
<P>
   The official said that the decision to go ahead with the case,
which was approved by Attorney General Janet Reno, might have
turned out differently had the review of the Justice Department's
action found that prosecutors engaged in ``intentional misconduct''
in identifying Demjanjuk as Ivan. ``But,'' the official said,
``that just wasn't the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Demjanjuk's lawyer, Michael Tigar, reacted critically to the
Justice Department's effort, saying that Demjanjuk was too ill to
survive another court battle and his family was nearly bankrupted
by the long legal fight against the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-two years ago they sued,'' he said. ``After 21 years of
litigation it was determined not only that they had the wrong guy
but that they had defrauded the courts. We hope it doesn't take
that long to demonstrate once again that the Justice Department is
wrong.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The case has stirred deep passions about Nazi war crimes
prosecutions and the ability of the government to try aging
defendants for acts committed more than a half century ago.
Wednesday, leaders of Jewish groups applauded the Justice
Department's decision to revive the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistake in the case to begin with was that the prosecution
was pinned totally on trying to prove he was Ivan the Terrible at
Treblinka even though there was evidence that he was a guard at
Sobibor,'' said Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean of the Simon Wiesenthal
Center in Los Angeles. ``I think they have a very strong case and
excellent shot at getting him deported from the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
