<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, May 20. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
PRINCIPAL-INDICTED (Phoenix) - In an unusual move, a grand jury has
indicted the principal of a Phoenix elementary school on child
abuse counts, accusing her of failing to stop abuse by a school
counselor. Principal Joanne L. Talazus is accused of seven felony
counts of child abuse and two counts of failure to report injuries
and neglect of minors. Talazus is accused of ignoring the conduct
of Ronald Maldonado Ruelas, 31, a Longview counselor. Ruelas was
indicted earlier on 23 counts of child molestation, indecent
exposure and sexual abuse involving nine victims. By WILLIAM
HERMANN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
KNIEVEL JUMP (Phoenix) - Advancer on Robbie's jump over the Grand
Canyon. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MCSTRATEGY (Washington) - Sen. John McCain's presidential campaign
provided us an exclusive inside look at his strategy for winning
the GOP nomination. Story will say that his campaign has targeted
New Hampshire, Arizona and South Carolina as the key early states
to grab early momentum and to bruise front-runner George W. Bush.
McCain is planning to delay buying ads until close to the primaries
and to instead rely largely on free media and on publicity from a
September book tour that will take him to all major media markets
(the book, said to be both emotional and patriotic,, is about the
family military history). McCain hopes to hurt Bush in New
Hampshire, then come home to Arizona, which was about to drop off
the map but is suddenly pivotal again because the Legislature has
opted to retain the early primary date. By JEFF BARKER. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HILLARY (Grand Canyon, Ariz.) - First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
visits the Grand Canyon to promote 70-plus miles of new bike and
hiking trails along the Canyon rims that will, in conjunction with
new light-rail and bus mass transit, help eliminate cars from the
park. By CRIS MOESER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Two years after being convicted of seven
fraud counts in a federal trial, former Gov. Fife Syminton, now a
full-time cooking student, remains free, waiting to learn his fate
from the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals. Unlike regular folks,
Symington didn't have to settle for the drive through lane of
fast-food justice. He's feasting on the full gourmet spread. By
E.J. MONTINI Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Julia Roberts lifted up her arm to wave
to the crowd and, in turn, the world froze. It was the lead story
on ``Inside Edition,'' ``Entertainment Tonight'' and even, believe
it or not, made the nightly news. The newscasters gasped in horror
and snickered in revulsion as the photo of Roberts was flashed the
screen for five haunting seconds. There, just beneath her
cap-sleeved gown was not evidence of a budding extra head; the
expanding, flapping gills of a fish woman; or even a tumor
equivalent in girth and color tone to a ripe, juicy melon. Nope. It
was just hair. Julia Roberts had the armpits of a ring-tailed
lemur. By LAURI NOTARO. Story moved in the `'L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SIMONDS-FOOD (Phoenix) - Nina Simonds's research for her latest
cookbook began 27 years ago with a nasty stomachache. ``I was way
too yin,'' she says, explaining that her diet was out of balance
according to the Asian concept of yin and yang. For Americans who
treat such maladies by tossing back a couple of Tums, the idea that
the foods she was eating while studying in China could not only
cause an upset stomach but cure it as well might seem, well,
foreign. But a traditional Chinese physician convinced Simonds that
antacids were not the answer. By BARBARA YOST. Story moved in the
``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
