<HEADLINE>
NEXT SEASON AT FORT WORTH DALLAS BALLET ... BALANCHINE AND A WORLD
PREMIERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ An ambitious, widely varied season,
including major works of Balanchine and a generous selection of
contemporary classical ballet, will characterize the Fort Worth
Dallas Ballet's first full season programmed under the leadership
of artistic director Benjamin Houk.
</P>
<P>
   Hired in June 1998, Houk inherited an already-planned season for
1998-99; the 1999-2000 season will reflect Houk's tastes and
ambitions for the company.
</P>
<P>
   However, Houk by no means returns to the Balanchine-centered
philosophy that dominated the company for 11 years under previous
director Paul Mejia, Balanchine works return to the programming in
a big way, with the major evening-length setting of ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream'' and the shorter ``Stravinsky Violin Concerto'' and
``Allegro Brillante,'' set to music of Tchaikovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights will be the world premiere of Trey McIntyre's
``Alice in Wonderland,'' and one American premiere, British
choreographer Graham Lustig's full-length ``Peter Pan.''
</P>
<P>
   One new piece by Houk, with title and subject as yet
undetermined, will also premiere.
</P>
<P>
   As in recent seasons, the company will present a full
subscription season of five full programs in Fort Worth at Bass
Performance Hall and a shorter subscription season of three full
programs in Dallas at Fair Park Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Performances:
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth season at Bass Performance Hall:
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 8-10: ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' by Balanchine, music by
Mendelssohn.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 12-14: ``Contemporary Classics.'' ``Allegro Brillante'' by
Balanchine, music by Tchaikovsky; ``Alice in Wonderland'' (world
premiere) by Trey McIntyre, composer to be announced; ``Principia''
(company premiere) by Kevin O'Day, music by Steve Mertlant.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 3-19: ``Nutcracker,'' by Houk, music by Tchaikovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 18-20: ``Baroque to Balanchine.'' ``The Moor's Pavane''
(company premiere) by Jose Limon, music by Purcell; ``Stravinsky
Violin Concerto'' (company premiere) by Balanchine, music by
Stravinsky; ``Pas de deux''from ``Don Quixote'' by Marius Petipa,
music by Minkus; new work by Houk.
</P>
<P>
   May 5-7: ``Peter Pan'' by Graham Lustig, music by Jack
Lanchbery.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas season at Fair Park Music Hall:
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 20-24: ``Nutcracker''
</P>
<P>
   March 3-5: ``A Midsummer Night's Dream''
</P>
<P>
   April 20-24: ``Peter Pan'' (American premiere) .MDBO/.MDNM/
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
