<HEADER>
A3695 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-RDP-HNS &LR;      05-19 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXS SENATE CLEARS UP GUBERNATORIAL SUCCESSION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The state Senate on Wednesday approved a
constitutional amendment making it clear how the offices of
governor and lieutenant governor would be filled if Gov. George W.
Bush is elected president next year.
</P>
<P>
   Senators also endorsed a constitutional amendment to allow
judges to order a former spouse's wages to be garnisheed for
overdue alimony.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures, which previously had won House approval, will be
submitted to Texas voters in November.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry would automatically fill a vacancy in the
governor's office under House Joint Resolution 44, the
gubernatorial succession measure. And the 31 state senators would
choose one of their own to succeed Perry as lieutenant governor
until the 2002 general election.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor presides over the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was approved, 28-1, with Sen. Mario Gallegos,
D-Galena Park, casting the ``no'' vote.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors said the change was necessary to clarify the current
line of succession to the governorship. It would require the
lieutenant governor to give up that post to become governor,
something that isn't clear in the present Texas Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos said he opposed the amendment because it could allow
``lame duck'' senators defeated in the November 2000 election to
help choose the next lieutenant governor before they leave office.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 political season not only will decide if Bush becomes
president but also will decide if Republicans can hold onto their
16-15 Senate majority.
</P>
<P>
   During debate on the succession measure last week, Democrats
unsuccessfully tried to add a provision that, in effect, would have
prohibited Republicans from promoting a GOP senator to lieutenant
governor if Democrats regained the Senate majority after the 2000
election.
</P>
<P>
   The wage garnishment proposal, which would strengthen a limited
alimony law that Texas has had for only four years, was approved
27-2.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the measure, House Joint Resolution 16, is
needed because alimony payments are difficult to collect without
the teeth that garnishment would provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no argument with the employer. There
either is a garnishment order or there is not a garnishment
order,'' said Sen. Chris Harris, R-Arlington, the sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, questioned the proposed
enforcement tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alimony has only been around in Texas for about four years.
The idea of putting employers in the middle of a financial fight
between a husband and a wife doesn't sound to me like a very good
idea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins and Sen. Mike Jackson, R-La Porte, voted against the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember that song, `It's Cheaper to Keep Her,'?''
quipped Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   State law already allows wages to be garnisheed for child
support.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature approved limited alimony in 1995 as part of a
welfare reform package.
</P>
<P>
   Alimony can be ordered from former spouses who have been
convicted of family violence offenses. It also can be ordered if a
marriage lasted at least 10 years and the former spouse seeking
payments is poor and disabled or is the custodian of a disabled
child who requires so much care the parent cannot leave home to
work.
</P>
<P>
   In other action Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   _ Senators approved 29-0 a bill to close a loophole in the Open
Meetings Act that allows governmental bodies to meet behind closed
doors for staff briefings.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, House Bill 156, must go back to the House for
consideration of Senate changes.
</P>
<P>
   Senators removed an exception that the House had added for the
Texas Transportation Commission. But they provided some
confidentiality for investment conferences involving trustees of
the Texas Growth Fund, a public, equity-oriented investment fund.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeff Wentworth, R-San Antonio, the Senate sponsor, won
Senate approval of similar bills in three previous legislative
sessions, only to watch them die in the House. This time, he waited
for the House to approve the measure first.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Senate gave final approval on a voice vote to Senate Bill
236, which would ban the execution of mentally retarded murderers.
The legislation by Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, now goes to the
House, where it faces a race with the clock in the days before
lawmakers adjourn May 31.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
