<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3696 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASSHALL-EFFECTS-TEX     05-19 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASSHALL-EFFECTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASS HALL CHANGES A CITY _ AND LIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A great concert hall can change the life of
a community the same way a great book or movie can change the life
of an individual.
</P>
<P>
   Reading Thoreau's ``Walden,'' seeing ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' _
or experiencing some other artistic adventure, be it Kubrick or
Hemingway or Handel _ made you a different person, made you see the
world in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in just one year, Bass Performance Hall has made Fort
Worth a different city and changed lives, on communal and
individual levels.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever one might say about David Schwarz's opulent design _
and it's just as easy to pick apart as ``Walden'' or ``Messiah'' _
he created a building that has made itself the heart of a community
like no other arts venue in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Sports facilities and shopping malls epitomize the communities
of Dallas (Texas Stadium, the Galleria) and Houston (the
Astrodome). The Capitol and the University of Texas are the heart
of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But since the Bass Hall was dedicated one year ago, the
community life of Fort Worth _ a dusty frontier outpost that was a
musical and cultural backwater within living memory _ has come to
be dominated not by educational, commercial, governmental or sports
facilities, but by an art museum and a multiuse performance hall.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell Art Museum and the Bass Performance Hall make Fort
Worth what it is. Just as the Kimbell functions as a home for the
finest visual arts of our civilization, so the Bass Performance
Hall functions as a ``museum'' for the finest musical and dramatic
accomplishments of Western culture. A serious concert artist will
perform in Chicago, New York, Boston, San Francisco or Los Angeles
_ and Fort Worth, before Dallas or Houston.
</P>
<P>
   What makes a hall great? Great acoustics and great ambience, for
starters. Acoustically, Bass Performance Hall is about as good as
possible. Great singers sound terrific there, and great orchestras,
such as the St. Petersburg Philharmonic and the St. Paul Chamber
Orchestra have proved that the room enhances the sound of a fine
ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Fort Worth Opera general director William Walker says,
``Bass Performance Hall and opera is a marriage made in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   As for appearances: Will we get tired of those 40-foot angels?
The jury is still out on that. The back of the building is dowdy,
the front bombastic _ but the ambience somehow works out to be more
than the sum of the parts. Approaching Bass Hall before a
performance, one almost always has the sense of being in a lively
urban environment. The journey from the entrances (grandly labeled
``portals'') to the interior can be confusing, but the visual mood
created by the stylish, purposely anachronistic interior _
particularly the beautiful blue dome _ makes a magnificent frame
for fine performances. You really feel that you're in a great hall,
a place where Verdi or Rachmaninoff would have felt at home.
</P>
<P>
   On a more subtle, political level, Bass Performance Hall
guarantees the domination of Fort Worth cultural life by the Bass
family for at least another generation. With the same patience and
etiquette with which they influence megacorporations and
presidents, the Basses subtly bend and direct orchestras, operas
and ballets. Boards and managers may make noise in public, but a
silent nod or shake of the head from a member of the Bass dynasty
is what really matters in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   It cost $61 million, raised from private, corporate and
foundation funds, to build the hall, which is now owned and
operated by the nonprofit, private Performing Arts Fort Worth. The
hall provides a principal performance venue for the Cliburn
Foundation, the Fort Worth Symphony, the Fort Worth Opera and the
Fort Worth Dallas Ballet, plus a home for some presentations by
Casa Manana.
</P>
<P>
   For all of those organizations, the building of Bass Performance
Hall has been a historical transition.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Symphony previously had offices and a rehearsal
facility in south Fort Worth and performed at Ed Landreth
Auditorium and Fort Worth Convention Center. Now, for the first
time, the symphony has administrative offices, performances and
rehearsals in the same place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a dream come true,'' says symphony Executive
Director Ann Koonsman.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the orchestra has experienced 15 consecutive
sellouts in the 2,050-seat hall; the biggest problem is persuading
ticket-holders who decide not to attend an event to call and turn
in their seats so that other music-lovers can attend. But turnout
for the 1999-2000 season, one year out from the excitement and
curiosity generated by the opening, will be the test of the hall's
long-term effect, Koonsman says.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Opera experienced such an immediate pressure for
more seats that it added a third performance of its third
production of the season, a first for the company. All three
productions next season will have three performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's expensive to produce an opera there,'' Walker said. ``But
we can handle the expense because of the public response.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker points out that the hall provides a perfect combination
of intimacy and grandeur for opera, and that the company can
produce operas with a subtlety and finesse that wouldn't work at
the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons have been learned. During the 1998-99 season, the
Cliburn Foundation presented attractions such as the Moiseyev Dance
Company and House of Blues. This year, the Cliburn Foundation will
leave such attractions entirely to Performing Arts Fort Worth and
concentrate on traditional recitals.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cliburn, which established itself as the world's leading
piano competition in less-than-elegant surroundings, can look
forward to presenting its 2001 competition in an environment with a
sense of place perfect for the enjoyment of great piano music.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a downside, too, for some of the smaller groups in
town, who now compete for funding and audiences with a
high-profile, high-prestige venue.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kreiman, executive director and co-artistic director of
Contemporary Dance/Fort Worth, a small modern-dance company, said
that she's ``excited that Bass Hall is presenting international
dance companies in Fort Worth.''
</P>
<P>
   However, ``as a small arts organization with an ambitious
community-based performance program, it has been difficult for us
to compete with Bass Hall for funds in the community,'' Kreiman
said. ``We don't have as prominent a profile.''
</P>
<P>
   On the upside, she said, ``It is our hope that activities at
Bass Hall will generate greater interest in live performing arts in
our community.''
</P>
<P>
   That would appear to be the case _ and not just with adults. Sue
Buratto, director of the hall's education program, says that 60,000
local schoolchildren have visited the hall. Next season, the
program will reach 70,000 students in grades one to seven.
</P>
<P>
   Bass Performance Hall's managing director, Paul Beard, says that
he has been perplexed by the audience response to a few of the
shows that Performing Arts Fort Worth presented in its subscription
series, particularly the St. Petersburg State Ice Ballet, which
drew a disappointing ticket response. But the group plans to
continue presenting the same number and type of eclectic
performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has been gratifying has been designing a building that
can present a variety of different events,'' Beard says. ``And to
see that it really works.''
</P>
<P>
   Principal supporters contended during the final phase of fund
raising that Bass Performance Hall would be the last great hall of
the 20th century. On a purely chronological basis, the wonderful
new orchestra hall in Seattle deserves that title, because it
opened in September.
</P>
<P>
   But Bass Performance Hall has achieved a historical aura and
connection with the outside world that very few halls have. With
continued community support, Bass Performance Hall can become
America's second Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDSU/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
