<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AN UNORTHODOX ELECTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Israel)   By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ehud Barak won a landslide victory in Israel
because of who he was not.
</P>
<P>
   He was not Bibi Netanyahu, a man of the right who angered the
right with the Wye accords, and then infuriated Israel's center by
backing away from that agreement to placate the implacable
hardest-liners.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was he Shimon Peres, a man of the left who was defeated
three years ago by Bibi because his policy of land-for-promises
threatened Israel's security and Jerusalem's unity.
</P>
<P>
   From now on, Barak will be judged on who he is. Because his
Labor Party lost seats in the Knesset, he must form a coalition to
govern. Our first indication of what sort of prime minister he will
make comes in his choice of partners.
</P>
<P>
   He could go left to the doves, the Arab and anti-religious
parties, plus the Russian immigrants. That would divide Israel and
provide no mandate for peacemaking. Won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   He could go religious to Shas, which snatched the mantle of
outsiderhood from the rightist Likud, and is now the third-largest
party. Shas wants money for its schools and day care; once bought,
it would be malleable on all else. Could happen.
</P>
<P>
   He could go right to the battered Likud. Bibi forthrightly
accepted responsibility for its defeat and stepped down. The acting
leader is Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, a sensible hawk whose word
is good, and who has been urging a broad-based coalition to make a
secure peace that most Israelis can live with. Should happen.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, like Bibi, is a bit of a loner. That can be a sign of
security. Six years ago, when he was army chief of staff, he was in
Washington and dropped by my Times office to introduce himself and
express his views _ unencumbered by aides, advisers, agents or
witnesses. That was impressive; he knew his stuff. (So why didn't I
make notes?)
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, when he was serving in the Peres Cabinet, an
Oslo II plan was presented that would hand over to Yasser Arafat
large chunks of the West Bank before final talks began. Barak
pointedly abstained. He agreed not to make his opposition public
lest it be ``misinterpreted.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibi Netanyahu as prime minister inherited that salami-slice
schedule and paid a heavy price in media support for interpreting
it narrowly. He was right: Unless Israel had a sizable portion of
land to hand over at the final settlement, all the focus would be
on the division of Jerusalem, and the talks would fail.
</P>
<P>
   Though gloating at Bibi's fall can be heard more in Tel Aviv,
Gaza and Washington than in Jerusalem, he will be remembered for
his wise slowdown of that land rush as well as a laudable
insistence on Palestinian reciprocity in combating terror. His
political ingratitude needlessly made enemies of his allies, and
their mistaken reaction to his necessary compromises brought him
down.
</P>
<P>
   The new prime minister has saddled himself with a self-imposed
deadline of withdrawing troops from the Lebanon buffer zone. If he
withdrew unilaterally, he would invite the Hezbollah up to the
border to harass northern Israel; if he withdrew as part of an
agreement negotiated with Syria, he might find the price to be the
Golan.
</P>
<P>
   I hope he does not make Rabin's mistake in assuming U.S. troops
would patrol a no man's land atop those Heights. Only Israel can
defend Israel's borders.
</P>
<P>
   Barak will also have to look inward at the division in Israeli
society between secular and ultra-Orthodox. (Black and white, too _
he made a nice reference to the inclusion of the Ethiopian Jews.)
That recalls the question asked by Jewish grandmothers the world
over whenever a great event takes place anywhere: ``Is it good for
the Jews?''
</P>
<P>
   This unorthodox election can turn out to be very good for the
Jews. The political deck has been reshuffled. A consensus about the
Palestinians is emerging. The weakness of the system that
encourages the birth of one-issue parties stands exposed, but the
other side of that coin is that the secular and religious parties
are competing out in the open.
</P>
<P>
   Where does this happen but in a creatively quarrelsome
democracy? Where in the Middle East but in Israel?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
