<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD ALLOW WHOLESALERS TO IMPORT PHARMACEUTICALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to combat soaring prescription drug prices, US Rep.
Bernie Sanders (I-Vt.) is introducing federal legislation Thursday
to let US retailers import drugs from other countries, where
wholesale prices tend to be much lower.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Sanders said, is to pass along lower prices to
consumers, particularly seniors. The legislation is co-sponsored by
Representative Marion Berry (D-Ark.) and Representatives Jo Ann
Emerson (R-Mo.).
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of prescription drugs is outrageously high,'' said
Sanders. ``There are seniors in this country who literally have to
make the decision between food and medicine. We have a national
crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' legislation is the latest effort in Washington to make
medicine more affordable for seniors. Senator Edward M. Kennedy,
Democrat from Massachusetts, has introduced legislation to add drug
coverage under the Medicare program. President Clintonhas suggested
using part of the federal budget surplus to pay for drug coverage
under Medicare, and is reportedly working on a proposal to be
released in coming weeks. And numerous lawmakers have said they
were drafting similar legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry is staunchly opposed to the Sanders
and Kennedy bills. They say the Kennedy bill would lead to
government price controls, while the Sanders proposal could lead to
the sale of potentially unsafe drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation raises a host of safety concerns that has the
potential to harm millions of patients,'' said Jackie Cottrell,
spokeswoman for the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of
America in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Sanders bill would allow retailers to buy drugs made in the
United States which are then exported to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Because many drugs are cheaper outside the United States,
seniors in Sanders' home state of Vermont often hop across the
border to Canada to buy their medications, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A survey commissioned by Sanders showed that the price for 10
commonly prescribed drugs are 81 percent higher in Vermont than if
they were purchased Canada, and 112 percent higher than in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally insane for people to be crossing the border to
buy drugs that are made right in this country,'' Sanders said.
``This is a probusiness, free trade proposal that will allow
consumers in this country to enjoy significantly lower prices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
