<SLUG> BC-LAW-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BINGHAM DANA TO MERGE WITH HARTFORD LAW FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Bingham Dana, in a deal that raises the Boston law
firm's global profile, said Wednesday it would merge with Hebb &AMP;
Gitlin, a Hartford law firm that recently snared the government of
Indonesia as a client.
</P>
<P>
   Bingham Dana, one of Boston's oldest law firms, has in recent
years been on a mission to expand its international practice,
notably by acquiring the Japan practice of a New York law firm,
Marks &AMP; Murase, in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hebb &AMP; Gitlin also has international clients, but the firm
gained prominence in London circles in the early 1990s when founder
Richard Gitlin acted as the US administrator in the bankruptcy
proceedings of Maxwell Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really good strategic fit,'' Jay S. Zimmerman, the
managing partner of Bingham Dana, said Wednesday about the merger.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to global practices, the firm's bread-and-butter
legal work in this country also fits, Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   The larger of the two firms, Bingham Dana has 325 attorneys and
a specialty in corporate finance for banking clients, while Hebb &AMP;
Gitlin, which has only 55 attorneys, has a similar standing in the
insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you look at convergence of these two industries'' _ banking
and insurance _ ``this is a natural for us,'' Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe, which is owned by The New York Times Co., is
among Bingham Dana's clients.
</P>
<P>
   On the international front, Hebb &AMP; Gitlin was hired early this
year by the Indonesian government to help its efforts to
restructure troubled corporate debt and lift the country out of the
economic troubles triggered by its currency crisis last year.
</P>
<P>
   To do this work, the merged firms plan to open an office in
Singapore, which will also help Bingham Dana better serve its
clients in Japan, Zimmerman said. The firms both have London
offices and plan to merge them, allowing them to more effectively
pursue clients in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``As our clients are consolidating into global institutions,''
Gitlin said in a statement, ``we made a strategic decision to
merge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
