<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Allied divisions over using ground
troops in Kosovo burst into the open Wednesday when Germany's
chancellor came to NATO and declared that his country would block
the alliance from fighting a land war. ``This is first and foremost
a German position,'' said the Chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder. ``That
position is also the present position of NATO, and the strategy of
an alliance can only be changed if all the parties involved agree
on it. I am against any change of NATO strategy.'' By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Brussels) _ A news analysis on why the alliance
is fraying and whether the lack of a strong U.S. position on how to
conduct the war in Kosovo is a factor. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Berlin) _ As the G-8 meets on Kosovo, no
breakthrough is in sight. The new buzzword is ``synchronization'':
an effort to synchronize the withdrawal of troops with an end of
the bombing and a U.N. Security Council resolution to authorize
some kind of force. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DESERT (Brussels) _ Hundreds of Yugoslav soldiers
deserted their brigade in Kosovo on Tuesday, defying their officers
and fighting through a military checkpoint to return their home in
Krusevac, to the north, NATO officials said Wednesday. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje) _ A powerful bomb exploded Wednesday
on a busy street in a crowded ethnic Albanian neighborhood here,
severely injuring two men and raising fears of more violence as the
huge influx of ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo continues. By
David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Belgrade) _ Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian
envoy, arrives in Belgrade, but without the Finnish president, for
talks with Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Belgrade) _ Developments: A few antiwar rallies
are held and some people are reported arrested; plus an attack on
an opposition party headquarters. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
