<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NANCE-FUNERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT AND SENATORS PAY TRIBUTE TO AIDE TO HELMS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Va.)   By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   McLEAN, Va. _ After the organist had begun playing and just
before the soprano soloist began singing ``Swing Low, Sweet
Chariot'' at Rear Adm. James W. Nance's funeral, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright was ushered down the aisle and seated in a front
pew next to Sen. Strom Thurmond.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sen. Jesse Helms, leaning heavily on an aluminum cane, came
through a side door and walked a few paces to sit with the Nance
family, across the aisle from Ms. Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Nance, Helms' childhood friend from North Carolina who came out
of retirement to become chief of staff of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, did not want an elaborate Washington funeral,
according to friends, and he did not get one.
</P>
<P>
   No prominent officials spoke, just the pastor, the Rev. Gary G.
Pinder; Nance's younger son, Andrew; and a granddaughter,
Catherine. The pallbearers and ushers were old friends, not
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   But the funeral was not a typical one for a congressional aide,
even one as senior as Nance, who was 77 and died on May 11 of
complications of myelodysplasia, a blood disease. The presence of
the secretary of state, other State Department officials, including
Barbara Larkin, assistant secretary for Legislative Affairs, and
two busloads of senators and staff members was a statement of
respect for the admiral and for Helms.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Helms,
the prickly and powerful North Carolina Republican whose moniker is
``Senator No,'' has held hostage various Clinton administration
nominees for ambassadorial and other foreign posts. Albright,
throughout her tenure, has taken pains to court Helms. She even
accompanied him to his home state in a 1997 visit.
</P>
<P>
   Nance worked at his Senate post until the week before he died,
even though in the last months he had appeared increasingly ill and
required weekly transfusions that he called ``in-flight
refueling.''
</P>
<P>
   A quiet, confident man who shunned the spotlight, he was a
formidable presence on Capitol Hill because of his unusually close
relationship with Helms. They grew up together in the Depression in
Monroe, N.C., and the senator prevailed on Nance, who had several
top commands in the Navy and who served on the White House staff in
the Reagan administration, to come out of retirement in 1992 to run
the committee's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Nance's sizable influence, said Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr. of
Delaware, the top Democrat on the committee, was grounded on the
fact that he was ``one of the few men or women'' who could say to
Helms, ``Enough, Jesse; slow down, Jesse; no, Jesse.''
</P>
<P>
   In a eulogy on the Senate floor on Tuesday, Helms called Nance,
who was known as ``Bud'' to senators and peers, ``a giant of a
man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved Bud Nance like a brother,'' Helms said, his voice
cracking. ``In my final conversation with him nine days ago, I told
him so. His voice, weak and raspy but nonetheless unmistakably
clear, replied, `I love you, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nance was buried on a hillside at Arlington National Cemetery.
As his coffin was placed in the ground, Navy fighters flew by in a
missing-man formation _ a V shape except for a missing plane in one
wing, the military's traditional salute to a fallen leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
