<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BURNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS OPTIMISTIC ABOUT BRUINS' FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The numbness had passed and coach Pat Burns was
feeling the sting of disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   His Bruins had been ousted from the Stanley Cup playoffs the
night before and yes, it did hurt, yes, he feels the Bruins were
the better team, and yes, there is reason to be optimistic about
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Burns hit on a wide range of topics Wednesday at the FleetCenter
_ the ups and downs of the season, injuries _ and was willing to
tackle any question thrown his way.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost any.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't discuss what was missing from this year's team and
what would be needed next year to take things to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get one thing straight,'' said Burns. ``I'm not going to
sit here and talk about what this team needs and what this team is
going to do. You can forget that. I'm not going to talk about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give me some time, you've got to give some time
to management and myself to sit down and go over some stuff and put
in some reports. If we're going to talk about what this team has to
do and will do, we're wasting my time and we're wasting yours.''
</P>
<P>
   With that out of the way, Burns talked about the differences
between the Bruins and Sabres, who won the Eastern Conference
semifinal series in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had some breaks. They had some good breaks at the right
time,'' he said. ``They had some bounces. We didn't have too many
bounces go our way. But I'm not saying it was just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played (Tuesday) night probably their best game of the
series. It was a non-error game that we just couldn't get through
and it was that close.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're down, 3-1 (in games), everyone knows it's
difficult to get through that. But the team stood up and fought
back and we fought back to the final buzzer. Nobody quit.''
</P>
<P>
   And that pleased Burns to no end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a season of ups and downs, which all seasons are,''
he said. ``I think every team in the NHL has them and we had our
share. In the final six weeks of the season everybody gave it
everything they could to try and get us in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting by the first round was tough. It was hard and we went
through the wall to get through it. The second round, we tried to
get through the wall but there was just a little bit missing. But
I'm very satisfied. I kept on saying I was proud of what the team
accomplished and I still am.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns indicated that Bruins fans may have even better days ahead
when asked if this is where he thought his team would be after his
first two years at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know those things,'' he said. ``It's easy to say at
this time we're at where we wanted to be and if we're not there I
could have said, `Well, we're coming there.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're on the right course, put it that way. The ship
was going the wrong way and now it's going the right way. I think
that's important and now we have to make sure that the right
sailors are on board and tying the right knots.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns warns, too, that neither the fans nor the players should
lull themselves into a false sense of security now that they have
some playoff experience and success under their belts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to say, `Now they've had enough (experience), turn
the light switch on and get the parade ready,' '' he said. ``No, I
don't think so. There's still a lot of things you have to go
through in a playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   ``To really make yourself, you have to learn, you have to be
ready to understand what it takes. Whether or not I can tell you
right now that they know exactly what it takes and there's going to
be no problem, well, I can't promise that. That would be stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, now that the Bruins are out of the playoffs and
there's no reason to keep injuries a secret, Burns detailed the
ills the Bruins faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jason) Allison was one guy who had a bad wrist for the last
part of the season. (Sergei) Samsonov had a lower rib and a lower
back that was really painful. Don Sweeney? An amazing individual to
go through what he had to go through. He had his ribs frozen every
single game and it would hurt twice as much the next day than it
did the day he played. Tim Taylor the same thing. Byron's (Dafoe)
back near the end started to tighten up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of things, but that's the playoffs. That's
what makes you get through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
