<HEADER>
A3736 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-CELLPHONES20-     05-19 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-CELLPHONES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta firm answers call for better phone service
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Naomi Shaku lives in the Ebony Park neighborhood on
the east side of Johannesburg, a development of tiny
government-built houses whose single rooms are smaller than a rich
man's bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   These homes were built to house people who previously lived in
squatter camps. These are the poor, people who have precious little
in life.
</P>
<P>
   Shaku, 24, may not have much. But she does have a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   And so, it seems, does almost everyone else in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   From the poor in makeshift shacks of corrugated iron to the rich
in their suburban mansions, from those riding in Mercedes and BMWs
to those traveling only on foot, cell phones are phenomenally
prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people here have cell phones,'' said Shaku,
gesturing toward her neighborhood of one-room, cement block houses.
</P>
<P>
   Her phone, she said, costs her about 200 rands a month, about
$30, and it's worth it. It allows her mother, who is caring for
Shaku's baby, to call her if the baby needs her, and it allows
people doing business with her mother's little store to call if
they have a question or a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has them,'' said Donald Keene, the state of
Georgia's trade representative in South Africa. ``I've never been
in a country where people use cell phones so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials routinely give out cell phone numbers. So
do business people and professionals. If a phone rings in a car
carrying several people, it often occasions a brief debate over
whose phone is going off.
</P>
<P>
   Is that mine? Yours? Bip-beep-beep-bip-beep-beep. No, I think
that's his.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons for the heavy cell phone use is that public
phones in South Africa are sparse and do not always function.
Besides, many poorer areas _ like Ebony Park, where Naomi Shaku
lives _ simply are not served by telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Shaku couldn't get a regular telephone installed in her house
for any amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   None of this has gone unnoticed in Georgia. Advanced Charger
Technology, which is based north of Atlanta, plans to introduce
soon in South Africa a new cell phone charger that recharges
batteries faster and more completely than existing ones, said Jody
Steinberg, the company's communications manager.
</P>
<P>
   What's the company's assessment of cell phone use in South
Africa?
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it to be explosive,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   And the potential is great not only in South Africa but across
the continent, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no infrastructure,'' she said. ``They will have
wireless before they have land lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaku did not speak of infrastructure, but she said essentially
the same thing: She has no other way to keep in touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only contact people have,'' said her friend, Esther
Mashubuku, also 24, as she leaned against the door of one of the
boxy little government houses in Ebony Park. ``We don't have
telephones here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
