<SLUG> BC-UNFUNDS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.N. Foundation awards $21 million to 11 projects
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The United Nations Foundation, the organization
created to disburse Atlanta businessman Ted Turner's 10-year, $1
billion gift to U.N. causes around the world, announced its fourth
round of grants Wednesday, giving $21 million to 11 projects which
range from providing birth control for Kosovar refugees to
protecting the environment of the Galapagos Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The board, which includes Turner and former Atlanta Mayor Andrew
Young, awarded the grants at a meeting last week in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The board is working to sharpen its focus, to avoid scattering
its resources too widely, said David Harwood, a spokesman for the
foundation. That process will continue at the board's next meeting,
in November, when members will award money almost exclusively to
projects dedicated to improving the health of children, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The board is also working to design projects that promote
cooperation between different U.N. operations, that leverage money
from the private sector, and that can be replicated elsewhere in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   In its 18 months of operation, the foundation has awarded $108
million. About a quarter of that has gone to children's health;
another fourth to protecting the environment; 35 percent to
population control and improving the lives of women; and 16 percent
to other U.N. causes.
</P>
<P>
   The grants announced Wednesday, each of which goes to one or
more U.N. agencies, are:
</P>
<P>
   _ $1,865,650 over three years to slow the spread of HIV and AIDS
among youth of southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.5 million over two years to support efforts to use the
media worldwide to help create a tobacco-free world.
</P>
<P>
   _ $3,999,850 to help protect the 5,000 native species of plants
and animals in the Galapagos Islands from harmful invasions of
non-native species.
</P>
<P>
   _ $2.6 million to support a U.N. partnership with an independent
body to recommend global policy on the future of large dams and
possible alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ $2 million to strengthen the U.N.'s monitoring of the global
environment and to supply better information to decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
   _ $370,660 to develop the production of energy by organic means
in rural India.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.5 million to help promote investment in projects that
generate energy without contributing to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   _ $5,206,000 over three years to strengthen reproductive health
programs in refugee and emergency situations.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1,777,835 over four years to promote ``micro-insurance''
systems for women in West Africa, in which a number of women would
contribute very small amounts of money to a health insurance pool.
</P>
<P>
   _ $700,000 to improve repro- ductive health among Kosovar
refugees, who are expected to give birth to 1,000 to 1,500 babies
per month.
</P>
<P>
   _ $365,000 to help the new director of the U.N. Development
Program, the U.N.'s primary agency dedicated to alleviation of
poverty, chart a new course.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
