<HEADER>
A3739 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-19 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN ARMY DESERTIONS RAISE NATO HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES RADIN AND COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ US and NATO officials said Wednesday that hundreds
of Serbian soldiers are deserting from the Yugoslav military in
Kosovo, raising the possibility that the two-month-long bombing
campaign is undermining discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Reports that 500 to 2,000 Yugoslav army reservists have deserted
in Kosovo have provided a badly needed boost for NATO, which has
come under attack for inflicting heavy, if accidental, casualties
on civilians. But other reports asserted that Yugoslav forces have
hunkered down along Kosovo's border with Macedonia, preparing for a
possible battle with NATO ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said Wednesday that
the deserters returned to towns in central Serbia to defend
relatives from a government crackdown on antiwar protesters. He
said most were going to Krusevac, where Serbian police are
reportedly using ``extreme measures against demonstrators''
protesting forced army recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This...is further evidence that (Yugoslav President Slobodan)
Milosevic's regime is beginning to crack,'' Rubin said. ``Belgrade
is feeling the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have now demonstrations in three different towns where
he's having to divert troops to go and try to quell these internal
demonstrations. These are the mothers and parents you saw
demonstrating in support of Milosevic just weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Serb officials said the soldiers in question were
reservists who returned to their homes after being withdrawn from
Kosovo last week.
</P>
<P>
   The reports of desertions took place as Russian and European
officials accelerated their efforts to find a diplomatic end to the
war in Kosovo. Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin traveled to
Belgrade Wednesday to hand-deliver the terms of a peace proposal.
While there were no reported breakthroughs Wednesday night,
Chernomyrdin's visit comes at a time when Serb authorities have
signaled that Milosevic is open to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   France, Italy and Germany said NATO's air campaign may be
bringing a change in Belgrade's position. ``Each day that goes by
see the chances of a settlement come closer,'' France's President
Jacques Chirac said at a French air force base outside Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always understood NATO's strategy to be a dual
strategy,'' said German Chancellor Gerard Schroeder. ``One element
is the military campaign ... to save people in Kosovo from being
killed, from being expelled. The second element of our strategy has
always been the search for a political settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy's Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema suggested sweetening the
deal by agreeing to Russian and Chinese demands that NATO pause its
bombing. At the same time, he assured that he wouldn't break with
the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   But US officials cautioned there will be no agreement until
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic capitulates to NATO's
demands. And key differences between Washington and Moscow over
NATO's role in the postwar Balkans could scuttle any peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Those differences were underscored by Chernomyrdin's insistence,
in Belgrade, that NATO halt its bombing. ``To stop everything, for
Milosevic, for all of us, it is very important to add that once
more they should stop everything,'' Chernomydin said during his
one-day visit. ``Most important is that the bombing stops, stop
killing people.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said there was agreement in Belgrade to work for
peace under the framework of a plan put forth by Russia and the
Group of Seven leading industrial nations.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, NATO bombs continued falling in Belgrade and
outside the capital. Tanjug, the Yugoslav government-controlled
news agency, said four people died when a factory was bombed in
Gnjilane, 25 miles southeast of Pristina, the Kosovo capital. Three
of the dead were women working in the factory cafeteria, Serb
officials said. The Serb Media Center said two inmates were killed
and several others injured when NATO bombed a prison in Istok in
northwest Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the bombing campaign to end the war has strained
the 19-nation alliance. Britain's renewed call for consideration of
ground troops in Kosovo set off an awkward public debate throughout
NATO over the introduction of troops.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, Italy and France _ who have been spearheading European
peace efforts _ publicly ruled out an invasion of Kosovo. President
Clinton, softening his opposition to a ground war, said Tuesday
that options remain on the table.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's Balkans envoy, Strobe Talbott,
appealed for unity in talks with the Group of Eight nations.
</P>
<P>
   The group is drafting the UN Security Council resolution that
would contain the elements of a peace settlement for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more accent there is on issues where we agree, the more
likely it is that one person who is not in on these meetings, Mr.
Milosevic, will get the right message,'' Talbott said.
</P>
<P>
   The G-8 plan calls for an immediate end to Serbia ethnic
cleansing campaign, the withdrawal of some 40,000 Yugoslav
soldiers, police and paramilitary groups, and the deployment of an
international peacekeeping force to oversee the return of nearly
800,000 ethnic Albanians to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   A transitional government, administered by the United Nations,
would be established to pave the way to a self-governing entity.
Any final agreement is also expected to demand that the Kosovo
Liberation Army end its offensive against Serbia and submit to
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   The State department sought to toughen its stance on Kosovo
Wednesday. David Scheffer, the US ambassador at large for war
crimes, said that a peace accord would not shield Milosevic or his
supporters from prosecution for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no deal to be cut,'' Scheffer said.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department source, speaking on condition of anonimity,
said a final peace agreement may deprive Milosevic of control over
Kosovo. ``We are looking at a (Western) protectorate for Kosovo''
in which Yugoslav forces would have even less control of border
crossings and customs than they would have had under the
Rambouillet agreement. Some sources say a reason no agreement to
avert the conflict was reached at the Rambouillet peace conference
earlier this year is that US negotiators refused to acknowledge
Serbia's sovereignty over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a deal can be struck, there remains considerable
opposition to the peace settlement from the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The G-8 formula is a retreat by the international community,''
KLA spokesman Visar Rekar said. ``It would be a tragic error to
leave him room for maneuver by suspending air strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, China's UN ambassador, Qin Huasun, said that Beijing is
``adamant'' in opposing any diplomatic settlement. But US officials
remain hopeful that China will not stand in the way of an agreement
that can end the war.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Radin reported from Washington; Lynch reported from the United
Nations. Globe London bureau chief Kevin Cullen contributed to this
report from Belgrade.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
