<HEADER>
A3742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-     05-19 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUIS LUYT: FIRST, FERTILIZER, RUGBY AND BEER. NOW POLITICS. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KLERKSDORP, South Africa _ In a field of professional
politicians, Louis Luyt stands out. There isn't another fertilizer
magnate turned beer baron turned rugby czar in the running.
</P>
<P>
   His slogan is ``We Mean Business.'' An American pollster working
here calls him ``South Africa's Ross Perot,'' and the word from his
spokesman is: ``As he says, Exxon has four times the GDP of South
Africa, and if Exxon can be run like a business, this country
can.''
</P>
<P>
   But ask Luyt what voters see in him, and he says bluntly,
``They're looking for a man.''
</P>
<P>
   A man?
</P>
<P>
   ``A man who will stand up to adversity. A man who will stand up
for their rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyt (pronounced late) entered the race for a parliamentary seat
only seven months ago, but he was already a household name _ not
always uttered in admiration _ and doesn't shirk from spending
money.
</P>
<P>
   He drew only 120 listeners to the civic auditorium of this
farming city Tuesday night, but pollsters say he is close to the 1
percent of the national vote that would assure his new Federal
Alliance Party of seats in Parliament after the election June 2.
</P>
<P>
   The party has a full list of candidates _ most of them
conservative white defectors from the National Party _ but it is
clearly a one-man bandwagon. All its posters show only his face _
the gray hair and narrow, slightly suspicious eyes of a millionaire
executive, the remarkably thick neck of a former rugby lineman _
and the word ``Vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's subliminal,'' Luyt joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking for a man'' may seem a fusty concept, especially
compared with the modern I-feel-your-pain ethos of American
politics, but to judge by the listeners arriving Tuesday night,
Luyt, 66, knows his audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a strong leader,'' said Ria van Wyk, a retired teacher.
``A good leader _ a go-get-'em type,'' said Henry de Korte, a
college student. ``Someone who could pull the country together,''
said D.P. Badenhorst, a retired farmer.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of the small crowd was black, as Luyt says 60 percent
of his supporters are _ which is surprising, considering that a
year ago, he was the embodiment of rugby's refusal to let the
government pressure it to put black players on the national team
before coaches judged them ready.
</P>
<P>
   The league forced Luyt to resign as its president because he
sued to stop a government inquiry into corruption and racism in the
sport and his lawyers forced President Nelson Mandela to spend two
humiliating days on the stand.
</P>
<P>
   But to blacks disappointed in the African National Congress
government, and particularly its failure to curb crime, Luyt has
some appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Africans, African men especially, like a man who is big and
strong, who has authority,'' said Nomavenda Mathiane, a black
reporter who watched Luyt campaign in black townships like Soweto
and Alexandra. ``They might not vote for Luyt, but they respect
him.''
</P>
<P>
   A black Klerksdorp resident, a 40-year-old storekeeper who
declined to give his name, saying he feared being attacked, came
because ``I read his manifesto _ fighting crime is his priority No.
1. My friends are disillusioned with the ANC, and most like Louis
Luyt.''
</P>
<P>
   On the issues, it is hard to describe Luyt's candidacy in
American terms because he calls himself a liberal. But he favors
chain gangs for criminals, the return of the death penalty, rapid
deportation of illegal immigrants, the establishment of a Christian
state, prayer in public schools and Parliament, an end to abortion
except in rape cases and merit hiring in preference to affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   Liberalism in South Africa is often about race; Luyt does not
defend apartheid and mocks the idea of a volkstaat, a separate
Afrikaner homeland. In 1988, seeking an end to the international
sports boycott, he defied the old apartheid government to meet the
African National Congress in exile and cut a deal to desegregate
rugby.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts his business prowess. A former captain of the
Orange Free State rugby team with degrees in law and business, he
founded Triomf Fertilizers, which he said became one of the largest
fertilizer companies in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, he founded Louis Luyt Breweries and captured 16 percent
of the market in one year. Since 1986, he has turned the
debt-ridden Golden Lions rugby team and Ellis Park, a stadium in
Johannesburg, into a franchise richer than all the country's other
teams combined _ an accomplishment that has endowed him with a
higher cash-to-humility ratio than George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about reports that he had spent 2 million rand of his own
on the race _ about $300,000 _ he scoffed. ``I spent 3 million last
week.'' He declined to name the total; ``my bank manager would kill
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He turned snide on being told a popular political analyst had
estimated he would spend $6 a vote to get 50,000 votes (``the
average rugby crowd,'' the analyst had cattily noted). He was
spending far more than ``that failed journalist turned political
analyst'' knew, he said, and would win 20 of the 400 seats in
Parliament _ a bold prediction, since polls he dismisses suggest he
might get four.
</P>
<P>
   Though sometimes bombastic for TV cameras, he is no
rabble-rouser. His subdued speech here was almost wistful for
``this beautiful land of ours'' that he said had been turned over
to majority rule too precipitously and was being mismanaged; five
more years of ANC government, he said, ``and you'll be sitting in
poverty wondering what might have been.''
</P>
<P>
   The applause was polite. At the end, he almost begged for
questions; no one had any.
</P>
<P>
   When Luyt declared his candidacy in October, he hoped to unite
all the opposition parties against the African National Congress,
which is expected to win the election handily. That union never
happened. But he doesn't regret the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike an endless American campaign, ``it hasn't been
miserable,'' he said. ``It's been expensive! But not miserable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
