<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ANC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA DEPUTY TRIES TO ALLAY FEARS OF ANC POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The African National Congress has
no plans to change the constitution if it wins a two-thirds
majority in the election on June 2, according to Deputy President
Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties have used the ANC's goal of a two-thirds
majority to try to mobilize voters against President Nelson
Mandela's party, saying a landslide victory would give it far too
much power.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the party has sent vague and contradictory signals
about what it would do with a two-thirds majority. Speaking to a
business seminar Tuesday, Mbeki was clearly trying to allay
concerns over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki said ``there is no substance'' to suggestions that the ANC
would try to curtail the power of provincial governments or rein in
independent watchdog agencies. He said his party was simply looking
for the ``biggest support possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls have suggested the ANC, which got almost 62 percent
of the vote in 1994, could get 67 percent this time, particularly
if there is a low voter turnout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-GA-MILITARYSPENDI     05-19 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-GA-MILITARYSPENDING20 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockheed Martin may cash in on part of proposed defense contract
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lockheed Martin's Marietta plant would build four
C-130J cargo planes under a defense spending proposal approved
Wednesday by the House Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The defense contract, valued at an estimated $252 million,
doubles the number of the planes approved by the Senate Armed
Services Committee last week.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal passed the committee 55-1, with the only dissenting
vote coming from Rep. Cynthia McKinney (D-Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   The contract is part of a sweeping budget request from the
Defense Department to spend $288.8 billion in the coming fiscal
year. That is an increase of $10 billion over what the department
was given this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the difference in funding for the C-130, the House
and Senate bills closely mirror each other. Both call for spending
at least $161 million on construction projects at military bases in
Georgia. Both also would spend $3 billion to build six F-22
fighters. The Lockheed Martin plant in Marietta is the assembly
point for the F-22.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force behind this year's spending increase is the
``vital need to improve our military preparedness,'' said Rep.
Saxby Chambliss (R-Ga.), a member of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was the need more evident than in NATO's war against
Yugoslavia, Chambliss said. Years of declining military budgets
reduced the nation's military resources to a dangerously low level,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The $15 billion emergency spending bill that passed the House
earlier this week will help, Chambliss said, but Congress should be
spending more in its regular budget to bolster the nation's
defense, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure our tanks and equipment are in tip top
shape,'' Chambliss said. ``We have got to be prepared for two major
theater wars to occur at any given time. I don't think this goes
far enough toward that goal, but it moves us in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to bring the military up to par, the Joint Chiefs of
Staff requested $32 billion in additional funds, Chambliss said.
This year's spending plan falls $16 billion short of that goal.
</P>
<P>
   The C-130J is an advanced version of a cargo plane that Lockheed
has been building for three decades. The aircraft is used by the
Air Force and the Marine Corps. This budget request would be for
the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best advertisement for the C-130s is CNN,'' said
Chambliss, noting how the planes are constantly seen in the
network's coverage of the war in Yugoslavia. ``It's the workhorse
of this war.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), whose district produces the C-130, said
he will work to make sure that the four aircraft ``remain in the
defense budget as it moves through the legislative process.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin is cautiously optimistic about the prospect. The
company has said that it would need 12 C-130s to maintain
production at its Marietta plant in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are encouraged by what we have seen so far, but there is a
long way to go,'' said Peter Simmons, spokesperson at Lockheed
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin is not the only Georgia winner in this year's
defense spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill calls for spending $3.6 billion on 15 C-17 planes,
which are assembled at the Boeing Company plant in Macon. And the
bill calls for $483 million in funding for a Joint Surveillance
Targeting Attack Radar System aircraft, which is based at the
Warner Robins Air Logistics Center. The bill allocates $46 million
in additional funds to go toward the purchase of another plane.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
