<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES FOCUS ON LITTLETON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)   (See also Congress-Guns)  (DW) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The school shootings in Colorado are so dominating
presidential politics that Dan Quayle took the occasion of the
seventh anniversary of his ``Murphy Brown'' speech Wednesday to
deplore the polluted culture he said had contributed to the
shootings. In the process, Quayle, a Republican candidate for
president, played down the role of guns in the Littleton killings
and emphasized personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overriding issue isn't really gun control, it's
self-control,'' Quayle declared in his speech, delivered in the
same San Francisco arena as his previous excoriation of Murphy
Brown, the television character who had a child out of wedlock. ``A
child who loves God, honors his parents and respects his neighbors
will not kill anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   A month after the worst school killings in the nation's history,
virtually all of the presidential candidates are incorporating the
shootings into their campaign speeches and shaping their public
events around the episode to help define their candidacies. For
many it has emerged as a chance to reflect on the state of American
society, its culture and its values.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate, Elizabeth Dole, has taken perhaps the most
dramatic tack, using the shootings to espouse an eye-catching
platform of gun control and to promote herself squarely with women
who vote.
</P>
<P>
   More typically, Quayle, the former vice president, has focused
his attention on the culture; Wednesday he blamed a liberal ``legal
aristocracy'' for judicial opinions that he said undermined
society.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who has spoken out repeatedly about the
killings since the incident on April 20, is to travel to Littleton
on Thursday to meet privately with the families of the victims and
to address the city. Gary Bauer, another Republican candidate for
president, plans a similar visit on Thursday to speak at a
Christian school in nearby Denver.
</P>
<P>
   One reason politicians are so focused on Littleton is the
public's continuing preoccupation with it. A new survey from the
Pew Research Center says that interest in Littleton among Americans
remains so high _ six in 10 are still paying very close attention
to it _ that ``the follow-up reports continue to rank among the top
news stories of the decade.'' Almost twice as many people are
absorbed in news about Littleton than are following the NATO
bombings in Yugoslavia, the poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mellman, a Democratic pollster, explained the preoccupation
this way: ``The problems of violence and discipline in schools have
been a preoccupation of the American public for a considerable
period of time, but those concerns have been inchoate, dispersed
and individualized. What Littleton serves to do is make it
concrete, give it specificity to make it real for people, and it
creates an imperative to act.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
