<HEADLINE>
EXPECT CHALLENGES IN SANTA ANITA CANYON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LANGTON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Twenty-five miles east of one of the world's
busiest intersections lies access to a mountain chain that can
resemble Colorado, with a little Pacific Northwest thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   Interlaced with hundreds of miles of trails and dirt roads, the
San Gabriel Mountains are a far cry from the San Fernando Valley
junction of the 101 and 405 freeways and a critical out for
Southland adventurers.
</P>
<P>
   Streams run year-round, and the higher elevations are laden with
snow each winter. Yet even in the lofty rugged peaks of the Angeles
National Forest, the summer heat _ and the air quality _ can become
oppressive. That leaves a precious few weeks between April and July
when the weather is neither too cold nor too hot to enjoy this
verdant backcountry getaway.
</P>
<P>
   One of the trailheads for mountain biking that is simplest to
reach is found at Chantry Flat Picnic Area above Arcadia. But
beware, access to the Upper Winter Creek Trail is about the only
thing that's easy about this route, which is described herein as a
9{-mile loop that also combines Zion, Sturtevant and Upper Falls
trails and winds through bucolic Santa Anita Canyon. An optional
6-mile out-and-back ride to Mount Wilson can be found, as well.
</P>
<P>
   These trails are not for the faint of heart or weak of leg. Not
only are they extremely narrow with severe exposure and rocky
granite outcroppings, many switch back sharply and can climb as
much as a thousand feet in a mile _ a standard to gauge extreme
steepness.
</P>
<P>
   Also be aware that the locals don't take too kindly to
irresponsible riders. There is a well-staffed volunteer mountain
bike patrol that will just as soon report your inconsiderate
behavior as save you from being lost or injured. But if you think
you can handle it, you will be treated to some of the most
exquisite singletrack in all of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been running and riding these trails for 15 years,'' said
volunteer patroller Laurence Johann of Sierra Madre. ``I feel like
I'm closer to God every time I come up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the most skilled and fit riders need attempt the route; all
trails noted are moderate to difficult, with some technical
sections. Other seasonable hardships can come into play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only does it get unbearably hot in the summer, there's the
rattlesnakes to contend with,'' said Long Beach patroller Guy
Hutton.
</P>
<P>
   From the picnic area parking lot at an elevation of 2,200 feet,
make your way up to the ranger facility and turn to the left of the
building past a large yellow gate marked ``Upper Winter Creek
Trail, 2N41.''
</P>
<P>
   Ride up the paved road for three-tenths of a mile to a trail on
the right that is flagged ``Upper Winter Creek Trail, Hoegee's Camp
2.5 miles, Mt. Wilson 6.5 miles.'' The trail climbs gradually, and
at 2.2 miles in begins descending more steeply, including some
tight, steep switchbacks. Within another four-tenths of a mile a Y
intersection is reached (2,625 feet); turn right. (The left fork
meanders up to Mount Wilson in some 6 miles, however it is
extremely steep and technical and not recommended; a shorter side
trip lies ahead.)
</P>
<P>
   Pedal on and soon ford Winter Creek, turning right after
crossing it to the next trail junction at the 2.7-mile mark. Our
course veers to the left onto the Zion Trail. (Staying to the right
takes riders to Hoegee's Camp and down Lower Winter Creek Trail
through several stream crossings to Chantry Flat; round-trip
distance for this loop option is about 5 miles.)
</P>
<P>
   The Zion Trail climbs steeply and gains 1,000 feet in 1.4 miles
to a junction with a short trail that traverses to the right a
short distance to the summit of 3,575-foot Mount Zion. Push on past
the juncture and descend a lush, fern-festooned trail dotted with
poison oak. The mile-long drop is narrow and exposed, so exercise
caution. At 5.2 miles in cyclists reach a T that is the Sturtevant
Trail (3,275 feet), near a spot known as Camp Sturtevant.
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive cyclists can turn left and ascend a difficult 3-mile
segment, which gains feet before reaching 5,710-foot Mount Wilson.
We turn right toward Sturtevant Falls.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 yards down the trail, turn left over a slight cascade
then up and over a small saddle. Continue past the Gabrielino Trail
that comes in from the left at a spot identified by a sign that
states, ``Chantry Flat 4 miles.'' Turning right, you will pass
through a series of picnic areas. Remain to the right of the stream
and, at 6{ miles in, take Upper Falls Trail (2,450 feet), which
rises from the canyon bottom, once again becoming rocky and
technical. At mile 8, the track drops steeply and again joins
Sturtevant Trail at the base of Santa Anita Canyon (2,050 feet). To
the left is renowned Sturtevant Falls; steer right onto the final
1{-mile section returning to Chantry Flat, and watch out for
hikers.
</P>
<P>
   At mile 9, Lower Winter Creek Trail runs in from the right
(1,800 feet); continue ahead over a bridge and climb the 400 feet
up a paved road back to your automobile. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
IF YOU'RE GOING...
</P>
<P>
   Chantry Flat Picnic Area and the outset of Upper Winter Creek
Trail are situated above Arcadia in the Angeles National Forest.
Drive east on the Ventura Freeway (134) to the Foothill Freeway
(210) east, exit at Santa Anita Avenue and turn left. The route
turns into Santa Anita Canyon Road as it ascends into the San
Gabriel Mountains. Parking is limited at the picnic area, so cars
may be left along the roadside.
</P>
<P>
   Be prepared to pay $5 for a one-day Adventure Pass, as required
by the U.S. Forest Service. Passes can be purchased _ on weekends
only _ at the site, or at nearby sporting goods stores. Some hearty
souls choose to park on residential streets and pedal the steep
3-mile stretch to the trailhead, which saves $5 but increases the
workout.
</P>
<P>
   Allow at least two hours to complete the 9{-mile loop, and
another hour or more if the 6-mile round-trip extension to Mount
Wilson is tackled.
</P>
<P>
   Maps: Mount Wilson 7.5-minute series topographic map, and Tom
Harrison Cartography's ``Trail Map of the Angeles Front Country.''
Some maps are available at Chantry Flat.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone: Angeles National Forest trails information line,
(626) 574-5200.
</P>
</TEXT>
