<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO POSSIBLE CANDIDATES WON'T RUN FOR MEXICAN PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Two influential governing party politicians
Wednesday ended weeks of mystery about their presidential
aspirations, declining to compete for the party's nomination
against Interior Minister Francisco Labastida Ochoa, who is said to
be President Ernesto Zedillo's choice.
</P>
<P>
   The two politicians' parallel decisions appeared to strengthen
the possibilities for Labastida, who announced on Tuesday that he
would resign to seek the governing party's nomination, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two men who announced Wednesday that they would not run were
Miguel Aleman Velasco, the governor of Veracruz, and Esteban
Moctezuma Barragan, the Social Development minister.
</P>
<P>
   Their simultaneous withdrawal added to the sensation that
Zedillo and his advisers have written a script casting Labastida as
the leading man for the nomination of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, even though the party will
select its candidate for the first time through a presidential
primary, instead of allowing the president to select the candidate
directly, as has been traditional.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida has recently attracted the backing of several PRI
governors, pro-PRI business executives and leaders of
PRI-controlled labor federations.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawals by Aleman and Moctezuma leave Labastida facing
only two significant rival candidates, Gov. Roberto Madrazo Pintado
of Tabasco and Manuel Bartlett, the ex-governor of Puebla. And
since Madrazo and Bartlett both draw their backing from the same
constituency of PRI traditionalists, they are likely to compete
mainly with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labastida benefits from the decisions by Aleman and
Moctezuma,'' said Alfonso Zarate Flores, the publisher of a
political newsletter here. ``This is part of a preconceived plan
I'd call political engineering. There's nothing spontaneous about
these events.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleman, whose father of the same name was president of Mexico
during the country's 1946-52 postwar boom, had run strongly in
recent opinion polls, solely on the basis of his legendary name.
Wednesday he said he wanted to stay on as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Moctezuma began his career in 1987 as an aide to Labastida, then
the governor of Sinaloa state. Referring to his former boss,
Moctezuma said Wednesday, ``I see the party already has someone who
represents the values I stand for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
