<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Folks like Williams put the Republican Party on map
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Marguerite Williams could be a handful, as more than
one Republican state chairman found out.
</P>
<P>
   So did Pat Robertson when he ventured onto the floor of the 1988
Republican National Convention on a peacekeeping mission to the
Georgia delegation and ran head-on into Williams, who gave him a
piece of her mind about the squabbles then going on between his
supporters and her candidate, George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Disaffected by that tumultuous intraparty battle, Williams in
later years gave money to Democrats Sam Nunn and Zell Miller _
heresy, in the eyes of some, for a former Republican national
committeewoman.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Williams, who died last week, deserves to be
remembered when the Republicans gather in Augusta this weekend for
their state convention.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the party's presidential candidates are slated to speak
to the Georgians this weekend _ not to mention NRA Executive Vice
President Wayne LaPierre, who'll be introduced by U.S. Rep. Bob
Barr.
</P>
<P>
   After they've sized up Lamar Alexander, Gary Bauer, Elizabeth
Dole and Alan Keyes, many of the Republicans will zip back to
Atlanta for Texas Gov. George W. Bush's presidential kickoff,
attended by the elder Bushes, George and Barbara, standing in for
their son.
</P>
<P>
   It is a relatively recent phenomenon for the Georgia Republican
Party to get this much national attention, and it wouldn't have
been possible without the presence, during the lean years, of a few
strong-willed, sometimes cantankerous people with checkbooks, like
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a venture capitalist for the Republican Party early
on, when there weren't a lot of people willing to write checks,''
said Rusty Paul, who's bowing out as state chairman this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Political generosity is not a natural trait of the well-to-do. A
lot of rich people make contributions because they feel they have
to, or on a whim.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many worthy causes, and many poster children more
appealing than politicians. Relatively few of the wealthy get
involved as much as Williams _ certainly not on such a long shot as
the Georgia Republican Party used to be.
</P>
<P>
   An heiress to the Maybelline cosmetic fortune, she was one of
the Thomasville Republicans, a small group, many with northern
connections, who formed one of the nodal points around which the
modern party has bloomed.
</P>
<P>
   The party has worked hard in the past few years to broaden its
base of contributors, from about 4,000 to 44,000, Paul said, and is
today much less dependent on a few key donors than it once was.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that 90 percent of the money to run the party came
from 10 percent of the contributors, he said. Now it's more like 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say a handful of the party's biggest contributors
aren't ``crucial at crucial times,'' as the chairman put it.
</P>
<P>
   More so for the Republicans. There are two sorts of currency in
politics: the kind that comes with being elected and appointing
people to boards and deciding where economic projects will be
located, and the more traditional variety provided by those with
the means and will to write checks.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Georgia Republicans accumulate more of the first kind
of currency, they will remain dependent on the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution political editor Tom Baxter
provides opinion, analysis and commentary in his column.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
