<SLUG> BC-PARK-CHURCH20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ebenezer Baptist restoration ensured
 &HT;    By Jennifer Ffrench-Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The money is now in the bank and the historic Ebenezer
Baptist Church is about to undergo a major overhaul that will
preserve it as part of Atlanta's civil rights legacy.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Park Service, which operates the 86-year-old building
that was home to the church that nurtured the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr., received grants totalling $1.2 million Wednesday to
continue the building's restoration.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton announced a $620,398 grant
from the federal government's Save America's Treasures Program. The
Ebenezer restoration was one of 62 projects in 24 states that got
grants totalling $30 million. The National Parks Foundation, a
nonprofit group that raises funds for park service projects, will
match that grant.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catroppa, superintendent of the Martin Luther King Jr.
National Historic Site, said the money will cover all the work
needed to preserve the building.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for the restoration, which will take about a year, will
begin by next week. The work will be done over two years. It will
preserve the interior and exterior of the building and its
furnishings and artifacts, and replace the building's electrical,
heating and air conditioning systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have a contractor on the site by April or May next
year,'' Catroppa said.
</P>
<P>
   Since assuming control of the building with a 99-year lease in
March, Catroppa said the Park Service has spent $153,000 to replace
a leaky roof. It is now well into a $35,000 restoration of the bell
tower, which is scheduled for completion by early June.
</P>
<P>
   Catroppa said the church will close to tours during some of the
work next year. ``There will be no way to avoid it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ebenezer's congregation vacated the 750-seat sanctuary for its
new $8 million Horizon Sanctuary in March.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1886, Ebenezer was the home church of the young King,
whose father was pastor from 1931 to 1975. King was co-pastor with
his father from 1960 to 1968. His funeral was held there after his
1968 assassination, and he is interred next door at the King
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
