<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON BUSINESSMAN SEEKS CONSTRUCTION ON NEW FOOTBALL STADIUM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ariz.)  
 
By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Concerned that another NFL team may move to Houston
without his involvement, businessman Bob McNair is trying to
persuade local officials to build a new football stadium without a
guaranteed franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Such a strategy didn't work in San Antonio, Texas, where the
Alamodome, which opened in 1993, remains without a National
Football League team.
</P>
<P>
   But McNair believes there is virtually no risk in Houston,
because the city has a strong enough market that it will eventually
attract a team _ through expansion or relocation.
</P>
<P>
   McNair said he should be the owner of a local team rather than
someone like Arizona Cardinals owner Bill Bidwell, whose team could
be looking for a new home after Mesa, Ariz., voters rejected a
stadium referendum Tuesday by a 60-40 percent margin.
</P>
<P>
   McNair said Wednesday he is willing to front a substantial share
toward a new stadium, which would all but guarantee his involvement
in a local franchise should Houston get one.
</P>
<P>
   If Bidwell or any other owner wanted to move his team to
Houston, said McNair, he would have to sell at least a 30 percent
managing share to McNair for playing in the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to get a team, one way or another,'' McNair said.
``It's not like San Antonio, which does not have the business
climate that Houston does. Houston has supported a team in the past
and will support one in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, McNair has been floating the idea among
public and private officials involved in plans for a $310 million
stadium the Harris County-Houston Sports Authority has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have said the stadium would be built only if Houston
got a team. But amid concerns that Houston could attract a bad
owner, especially one without local roots, they have been seeking
ways to give McNair more leverage in his efforts to get a team.
</P>
<P>
   Many worried privately about the Bidwell family owning a team in
Houston. Under the family's ownership, the Cardinals are one of the
league's most vagabond franchises, moving from Chicago to St. Louis
to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after the Cardinals left St. Louis in 1988,
officials there began trying to woo another team, and eventually
got the Rams from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The saga sounds similar to one in Houston. Work began on a
stadium plan almost immediately after Oilers owner Bud Adams
announced plans to move his team to Tennessee in three years after
he could not swing a deal here.
</P>
<P>
   County Judge Robert Eckels said Wednesday the concern about
ownership is a good reason not to rapidly dismiss McNair's idea of
building a stadium before Houston gets a team.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a good idea to start construction, Eckels said, if
McNair can promise his end of the bargain as originally planned,
predicated on Houston getting a team.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the sports authority would provide $195 million
toward construction of a stadium and McNair would pledge $50
million in cash and $1.05 million annual rent plus revenues on
parking and other items totaling $2.96 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that a Houston football team have a local owner
who gets along well with the local community,'' said Eckels. ``Bob
McNair does that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   County Commissioner Steve Radack said he has no problem with the
plan, as long as the county doesn't have to pick up any of the tab.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone wants to spend money building a stadium on county
property, it sounds like a good idea,'' Radack said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo officials have similar concerns
about building a new stadium without a guaranteed team.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal cut with the sports authority, the rodeo would
share the cost of building the stadium, including paying $1.5
million annual rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, we want a successful partnership with a known
quantity rather than with someone who has not shown a track
record,'' said rodeo president Jim Bloodworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't taken a position, but we would carefully watch who
our partner is. Bob McNair is not only a great individual, he's a
Houstonian.''
</P>
<P>
   But rodeo officials, concerned about duplicating the Alamodome's
woes, may not support construction of a new stadium without a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might be able to extend our exclusive agreement for 18
months to two years,'' said one rodeo source. ``But I doubt we
could go much further than that, because we need to spend money on
our existing home (Astrodome), and we couldn't wait much longer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under the original deal, McNair has exclusive rights to a new
stadium through Jan. 31, 2000. But he is worried that an existing
owner with stadium problems, like Bidwell, might try to get the
Houston stadium plan for himself.
</P>
<P>
   By getting the exclusive agreement extended, McNair would have
more leverage in convincing an owner to sell him a managing share
of the team.
</P>
<P>
   In March, McNair wrote Bidwell and eight other NFL owners with
stadium problems offering to buy a portion or all of the team.
</P>
<P>
   McNair said Wednesday he has since had only a cursory discussion
with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't talked since then, and we had nothing concrete to
say then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have not indicated what will happen to the team.
Besides looking at Houston, the team could examine moving to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, McNair said, the overwhelming defeat in Arizona
improves his chances of getting a team.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, owners in other troubled cities will decide a
little quicker about whether to stay or move to Houston. If they
don't move quickly, they could lose out to the Cardinals, McNair
said.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, he said, it puts pressure on the NFL to award an
expansion franchise to Houston instead of Los Angeles, which is
getting no closer to a commitment for public money for stadium
plans there.
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners, who recently awarded a conditional franchise to Los
Angeles, will meet in Atlanta next week to examine L.A.'s efforts
to come up with a financing plan to renovate the Municipal
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the climate in Phoenix, Los Angeles and Chicago, where
no public money is coming forward for a stadium,'' McNair said, ``I
am not sure the NFL wants to turn down such a good deal in
Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
