<HEADLINE>
GOP NIXES GORE-INSPIRED EARTH SATELLITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a real life ``Star Wars'' battle on Capitol Hill
Wednesday, House Republicans prevailed by deleting a project
inspired by Vice President Al Gore to put a satellite in orbit that
would give Internet users a live, round-the-clock view of Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans decried the $32 million satellite plan, part of a
$42 billion bill funding NASA, as unnecessary, while Democrats
charged that the GOP was politicizing the project and killing it in
an orchestrated effort to ridicule Gore, the party's front-runner
in the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Gore campaign viewed the force the Republicans
used to destroy the satellite funding as the sequel to their
trashing his claim of having invented the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The NASA funding bill, stripped of money for the so-called
Triana project, passed 259-168, with many Democrats _ including all
10 members of the Massachusetts delegation _ voting against the
overall measure.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats say they will push their colleagues in the
Senate to reinsert funding for the project. And the White House is
making noises about a veto if money for the Triana satellite
mission is not restored in the NASA bill, which also includes
funding for the space station and the space shuttle over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said Gore was trying to spend $32 million for a
project of limited value. They argued that Earth-viewing already is
available on the Weather Channel, NASA's TV channel and on some Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need it. We've already got it there. It's free. Why
spend the money on something that someone came up with in a
dream?'' said Jim Wilkinson, a spokesman for House Majority Leader
Richard Armey, who helped lead the opposition to the Triana
satellite project.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson mocked Gore for saying he awoke one morning in early
1998 with the idea of a live, high-definition-TV image of the Earth
available on the Internet 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Armey once dreamed about catching a 10-foot bass,''
Wilkinson said about his boss, an avid fisherman, ``but he didn't
wake up and call the Fish and Wildlife Service to force them to
spend $30 million to make it a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA is currently scheduled to launch the Triana satellite in
December 2000. Although some analysts have questioned the
scientific value of the mission, supporters believe it will address
fundamental questions about the Earth's climate. NASA officials,
who lamented the project's defeat, lauded its scientific and
educational merits.
</P>
<P>
   Once in orbit, the spacecraft would measure the amount of the
sun's energy that the Earth reflects back to space. Because
sunlight is the principal engine that drives the weather, the
mission would allow a more accurate measure for climate models of
how much solar energy the Earth absorbs. Internet users would get
continuous views of the Earth from space and the natural phenomena
that affect it.
</P>
<P>
   Representative David Weldon, a Republican from Florida, who
offered the amendment to kill the funding, suggested it was unfair
that NASA was laying off 600 workers at Kennedy Space Center at the
same time it was ``finding tens of millions of dollars to fulfill a
vision for the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Nichols, spokeswoman for House Minority Leader Richard A.
Gephardt, said Triana was a ``good political issue'' for
Republicans, since they have spent little energy doing other
legislative work. ``It's sort of silly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said Armey, a staunch Clinton-Gore critic who has
claimed credit for leaking Gore's boast about inventing the
Internet, ``has decided that his role in life is to try to be a
thorn in Mr. Gore's side.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson shot back: ``We've decided our role in life is to stop
bad policies and enact good ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore, referred to the House
Republican leaders as ``Luddites'' the group of early 19th century
English workmen who destroyed labor-saving machinery as a protest.
They have ``politicized Kosovo, Y2K efforts, hurricane reliefs,
farm aid, guns, and now even science,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a safety lock on the GOP to help protect the American
people from such blatant partisanship,'' he said. ``If the
Republicans were around 400 years ago, they probably would have
attacked Galileo as well.''
</P>
<P>
   And brushing off attacks on Gore's ideas, Lehane continued, ``We
recognize that the Republicans will stoop as low as possible in
their efforts to attack the vice president, as they did for six
years with the president. And now they are turning their guns on
the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all scientists agree the project is worthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any scientist who is saying they need it. This
is almost pure showmanship, and there's no science being
addressed,'' said Richard S. Lindzen, a professor of earth,
atmospheric and planetary science at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult to use video images of the Earth for
serious work evaluating climate changes or land use,'' Lindzen
said, because those rely on infrared scanning or other advanced
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the Triana proposal an example of NASA's ``shoving more
hardware into space'' to please politicians, Lindzen said, ``The
only thing this does is use resources and give you a Web site with
pictures, but I know of no one who is saying, `I need this for
science.' ''
</P>
<P>
   However, Boston University professor Farouk El-Baz, director of
the Remote Sensing Center, disagreed. He said the Triana images
could be ``of great significance'' in helping authorities monitor
forest fires, oil spills, dust storms, or other large-scale natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular satellite would not be able to focus on
particular areas,'' El-Baz said, but it could play a key role
giving researchers a new way to monitor macro-level changes on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scientific and research value is really in the timely
images of events as they are happening,'' said El-Baz, whose center
three years ago used satellite-imaging techniques to corroborate
that up to 1 million people attended the Nation of Islam's
``Million Man March'' in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Peter J. Howe of the Globe staff contributed to this report from
Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
