<HEADLINE>
SIMILARITIES TO BOSTON MURDER SEEN IN FLORIDA CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RIC KAHN AND DANIEL VASQUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Police in Hollywood, Fla., have asked the FBI to help them
investigate a grisly murder which has eerie similarities to the
unsolved slaying of Karina Holmer, a Swedish au pair whose severed
torso was found in a Boston trash container nearly three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the beaten body of Delia Lorna Mendez, a 34-year-old street
prostitute, was discovered in the parking lot of a pet supermarket
in Hollywood, Fla., Sunday afternoon, it sparked conjecture that
the killer could be the same one who murdered the 20-year-old au
pair because of the ways in which the victims were disposed of.
</P>
<P>
   Both women had been killed, then cut in half _ apparently with a
power instrument, possibly a circular saw _ then discarded in a
Dumpster. The Mendez murder was the first time a body had been
mutilated that way since Holmer's remains were found in a Fenway
receptacle in June 1996, Boston police say.
</P>
<P>
   Although police found both halves of Mendez's severed body,
Boston police said a Hollywood detective received three anonymous
tips alluding to the Holmer case. Hollywood police adamantly deny
that scenario.
</P>
<P>
   There are obvious differences between the two murders: The
victims are about 14 years apart in age; Mendez was a brunette who
was severely beaten and Holmer, a blonde, had been strangled;
Holmer's torso also had been cleaned and wrapped in plastic, unlike
Mendez' bloody body. The bottom half of her body was never found.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Mendez homicide could provide local authorities with
their most promising lead in finding Holmer's killer in the past
two years, Boston police said Wednesday they have no plans to send
detectives to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a body in Florida; we have a body in Boston. Other
than that, there is no connection,'' said Boston Police
Superintendent Donald Devine.
</P>
<P>
   From his home in Sweden, Holmer's father Wednesday expressed
disappointment with that conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a bit surprised if they don't show any interest'' in
checking whether the crimes are related, said Ola Holmer. He said
Boston police had not contacted him about the possible new
development.
</P>
<P>
   Florida authorities said they have not found evidence that the
murders are related, but have not ruled out that possibility.
``Everything's wide open,'' said Hollywood Police Lt. Chad Wagner,
but there are no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner said police questioned Michael Schulerman, Mendez'
boyfriend, and searched his home after he reported her missing. He
was then released. As part of the probe, Wagner said, police will
investigate whether Schulerman had any Boston connections.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida police said their detectives must first sift through
a mound of physical evidence found in the Dumpster before they will
know whether to bring Boston into the investigation. The cause of
Mendez's death has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Detective Paul Farrahar, head of Boston Police's homicide
unit, said Wednesday he plans to wait until Hollywood police finish
their preliminary investigation, and ``if sometime in the future it
seems appropriate to send our investigators there, we certainly
will. It's just too early to speculate on possible connections.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Florida police have asked the FBI to help them
narrow the scope of suspects. The characteristics of the crime will
be entered into a national database to match against other
incidents, and federal authorities will use those details to create
a profile of the possible killer, including occupation and
personality traits.
</P>
<P>
   Holmer's upper torso was found in a Dumpster in Fenway following
a night out downtown. Authorities determined that she'd been
strangled, then her torso cleanly severed. The rest of her body has
never been found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
