<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ALLISON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLISON REFUTES SINDEN CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Jason Allison hadn't heard the comments his boss,
Harry Sinden, made after Tuesday night's game in Buffalo. After
being eliminated by the Sabres in the Eastern Conference
semifinals, Allison boarded the charter flight home with his
teammates and management and experienced the same disappointment,
numbness, exhaustion, and frustration they all felt.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the Bruins center arrived at the FleetCenter for the
annual disbursement proceedings (re: meet the media, sign a ton of
souvenirs), he read the critical remarks made about him and
linemate Dmitri Khristich by the club's president/general manager
and it hit him like a slap in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said he thought his team was mediocre through too much of
the six-game series against the Sabres and that Khristich and
Allison were subpar at least in part because of the money paid to
them last fall when Allison was a holdout and Khristich went to
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Allison took issue with Sinden's comments is an
understatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to blame somebody for it,'' Allison said with an
edge to his voice. ``I can be happy with my effort. I played the
best I could. Maybe I could've played better but it wasn't from
lack of effort. That's his opinion, what he wants to say. It seems
like it's someone different's fault every year. How many years had
it been since they got out of the first round? With 10 different
coaches and 500 different players. It's my fault this time, I
guess. I'll take the blame. He must have seen something real bad
that I didn't notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said he was surprised and hurt by Sinden's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know it until I got here,'' he said. ``I played
hurt for him over the two years numerous times. This year, I had a
badly sprained wrist and I could've been out for a couple of weeks
or a month but we were in a playoff hunt and I didn't miss a game.
I did everything I could to play. I'm not blaming (the wrist) for
the playoffs. I'm just bringing it up because I don't know if the
approach he took was a very classy one.''
</P>
<P>
   That being said, Allison, who led the team in scoring with 76
points, said he knows that he had his moments through the season
when he wasn't his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed at different times during the year with my
play,'' said Allison, who had seven fewer points than last regular
season. ``I don't think I totally had a bad year at all. I don't
think I totally had a bad playoffs. I probably could've played
better. I still had pretty much my average for points I've had over
the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Allison, he was one of the Bruins' more reliable
forwards. There was only one time during the regular season when he
failed to score in four straight games. And part of Allison's
problem during the playoffs was that Khristich was invisible much
of the time and Sergei Samsonov was far less than 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, when it comes to cultivating warm and fuzzy
feelings, the Bruins will never be confused with Barry and Eliot of
Jordan's Furniture, who recently flew all their employees to
Bermuda as a gesture of thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Bruins and everyone else would argue that with
the salaries pro hockey players make, they can fly themselves and
everyone they know to Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Allison's point was that his play had nothing to do with his
salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comments about the money are ridiculous,'' said Allison,
who had 11 points in 12 postseason contests. ``If you look at the
money I made this year, compared to my numbers, I probably actually
overachieved in the league's salaries and I don't think anyone can
argue that point. For what he said, that giving the money changes
us, that's why we didn't play well, it's a crock. Maybe that's his
way of covering himself, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said coach Pat Burns tried to soften the blow of
Sinden's comments but from the sound of it, it didn't work all that
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him again and he said, `Don't let it bother you
too much,' '' said Allison. ``I said I won't. I don't think I
played badly this year or in the playoffs but I think I can reach a
higher level. He said, `You played good, don't worry about it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Try as he might, Allison couldn't hide his hurt. He said it
wouldn't affect his summer or anything else but it was clear that
he was trying to make sense of being publicly criticized. It was
equally clear he felt blindsided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why he said them,'' said Allison. ``It really
upset me that he was talking about the money. That's what it's
always about. It's always got something to do with the money. I
could've had four more points this year and he would've been paying
me an extra million dollars (an incentive clause for reaching 80
points) and then he could maybe say something, I don't know. To me,
it didn't make much sense. It seems he always has to fall back on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison ran the gamut from defiant to hurt to confused. He said
he didn't want to fan the flames of controversy but at the same
time, he felt the need to express and defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way they have a right to criticize players sometimes
because they're paying you and they are your boss and they have an
organization to run but sometimes they've gone about it the wrong
way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allison said he has significant plans this offseason to improve
his conditioning. He plays a lot of minutes, more than any other
forward on the team, and he said he wants to improve his skating
and endurance. He is planning to work with Olympic speedskater
Kevin Scott from Calgary for perhaps as long as a month. Skating
has been a knock on Allison throughout his career and he said he
wants to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I realized this year, if I'm going to play 22, 25
minutes _ I played 28 one game _ if you're going to be doing that,
you have to reach a totally other level of conditioning because
it's too tough,'' he said. ``You can't play your best if you're out
there tired all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that workload made him appreciate what Ray Bourque does
even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelieveable, he's a freak of nature,'' said Allison.
``That's genetic, too, with Ray. He works extremely hard but to be
at the level he's at, it's genetic, too. He runs and trains but he
cannot skate all summer and skate for three days and be in great
shape. I don't play a finesse game. It's down low, outmuscling
guys. That takes more energy than maybe some of the skilled guys
playing 20 minutes a game. I have to work for my ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said he wants to get better and is hoping that the sting
from Sinden's comments doesn't last. He said they had a domino
effect through the dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys other than myself are upset,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The most pointed of whom was Anson Carter, who had his own
contract squabbles with the team that led to a holdout last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset about it,'' said Carter. ``He has his own opinion,
obviously, he's the boss. But I thought Ally played well. Just
because of what he's being paid, he's being blamed due to his
salary. I'm sick and tired of money being a big issue of everything
that's being said around here. If something is said, it's always
about money. It's the root of everything that happens around here.
His numbers speak for themselves. The guys in the room know that
he's putting forth every effort and that he plays hurt so why would
you bring up the money factor? They make you think he's greedy and
he's not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
