<HEADLINE>
CBS TO INTRODUCE SIX NEW SERIES, MOVE FIVE OTHERS AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS on Wednesday said it will introduce six new series next fall
and shuffle five others on its prime-time schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The new series include three dramas featuring familiar names
like Tyne Daly, Dixie Carter and Kathleen Quinlan, and three
comedies with the likes of Nancy Travis, Sharon Lawrence and Betty
White.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule leaves Monday as a comedy-heavy night capped by a
10 p.m. drama. But ``Cosby,'' the linchpin of the network's Monday
night lineup the past two seasons, will move to Wednesdays at 8 in
the fall. ``The King of Queens'' will move from 8:30 into the 8
o'clock slot on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   Also relocating are ``Chicago Hope,'' to Thursdays at 9;
``Diagnosis Murder,'' to Thursdays at 8, and ``60 Minutes II,'' to
Tuesdays at 9.
</P>
<P>
   A summary of CBS's new series:
</P>
<P>
   Family Law. One-hour drama co-produced by Paul Haggis (``EZ
Streets'') about a motley group of lawyers thrown together by
unexpected circumstances, namely, the breakup of Lynn Holt's
marriage. Holt's husband takes their law practice with him, forcing
Holt (Kathleen Quinlan) to start over from scratch. Best character
name: Randi King, the new firm's divorce lawyer, played by Dixie
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Judging Amy. Hourlong drama based on the life of Amy Brenneman's
mother. Brenneman plays Amy Gray, a divorced mom who leaves New
York to become a judge in Hartford, Conn. Tyne Daly plays her
opinionated mother. Best character name: It's gotta be Amy.
</P>
<P>
   Now &AMP; Again. One-hour action-drama about a middle-age insurance
agent whose body is destroyed in an accident but whose brain is
unharmed. He lets the government transplant his brain into the
hunky body of Ben (Eric Close), but he has to agree to become a
government agent and give up his old life _ including his wife and
family. Best character name: Theo. No it's not Kojak incarnate.
Theo is Ben's controller, played by Dennis Haysbert.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies Man. Alfred Molina plays Jimmy Stiles, a guy surrounded
by women: his wife, his ex-wife, his two daughters, his mother and
his mother-in-law. Sharon Lawrence plays the current wife, Park
Overall is the ex, Betty White is the mom. Best character name:
Peaches, the mother-in-law. (Dixie Carter played her in the pilot,
but Carter has a leading role in ``Family Law,'' so the part is
being recast.)
</P>
<P>
   Work With Me. Nancy Travis and Kevin Pollak play a husband and
wife whose separate law careers become one when they join forces in
the same firm. Best character name: Sebastian (Ethan Embry), an
office assistant who's dating the other office assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Love or Money. Half-hour romantic comedy set in a posh Manhattan
apartment building. Cellar-dwelling maintenance man (Dash Mihok)
loves high-born kindergarten teacher (Paget Brewster). Swoosie
Kurtz and David Ogden Stiers play the billionaire parents. Best
character name: Puff Conklin (Judy Greer), the empty-headed sister.
</P>
<P>
   Here is CBS's prime-time lineup for the fall, with new series in
bold type (times are given are Seattle time):
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   7-8 p.m.: ``60 Minutes''
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Touched by an Angel''
</P>
<P>
   9-11 p.m.: ``CBS Sunday Movie''
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-8:30 p.m.: ``The King of Queens''
</P>
<P>
   8:30-9 p.m.: ``Ladies Man''
</P>
<P>
   9-9:30 p.m.: ``Everybody Loves Raymond''
</P>
<P>
   9:30-10 p.m.: ``Becker''
</P>
<P>
   10-11 p.m.: ``Family Law''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``JAG''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``60 Minutes II''
</P>
<P>
   10-11 p.m.: ``Judging Amy''
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-8:30 p.m.: ``Cosby''
</P>
<P>
   8:30-9 p.m.: ``Work With Me''
</P>
<P>
   9-11 p.m.: ``CBS Wednesday Movie''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Diagnosis Murder''
</P>
