<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB BLAST BADLY WOUNDS 2 IN MACEDONIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ A powerful bomb exploded Wednesday on a busy
street in a crowded ethnic Albanian neighborhood here, severely
injuring two men and raising fears of more violence as the huge
influx of ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo continues.
</P>
<P>
   One man was so badly burned by the powerful blast that he could
not initially be identified. Another had a leg torn off that landed
in a playground 30 feet from the scene of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   By evening, Macedonian government officials said they had made
no arrests in the bombing and had no suspects. The explosion
followed a series of increasingly violent rocket and grenade
attacks on French soldiers in the NATO contingent here.
</P>
<P>
   Residents and passers-by gawked at the debris from the
explosion, which destroyed a car and blew the glass out of nearby
store windows.
</P>
<P>
   Sali Tahiri, 32, a clerk in a nearby auto parts store who helped
rush the victims to the hospital in taxis, said the intent of the
bombers was clearly ``to destabilize Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a neighborhood where the inhabitants are mostly
Albanians,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the Slav majority in Macedonia and the sizable
ethnic Albanian community _ up to one-third of the country's
roughly 2 million inhabitants _ have been tense ever since
Macedonia won independence from the old Yugoslavia in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of nearly 200,000 ethnic Albanian refugees from
neighboring Kosovo over the past eight weeks has increased those
tensions markedly. The refugees complain of rough treatment and
discrimination from Macedonian police and officials; the Macedonian
government has stressed that it has sheltered the refugees despite
the antagonism, but insisted that many be taken to third countries
to prevent tensions from boiling over into violence.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia is home to a small Serb minority, and many of its
Slavs sympathize with the Serbs in fighting to retain Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of both the Macedonian and ethnic Albanian communities
here have called for restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Stevo Pendarovski, a spokesman for the Macedonian Interior
Ministry, said the bomb exploded at 1:30 p.m. in a mostly Albanian
neighborhood in northeastern Skopje. He said witnesses described
the bomb as a small package wrapped in plastic and tied with twine
or wire, placed in the center of a traffic lane. The blast felled
the two men as they crossed the street and blew the windows out of
a nearby shop and parked car.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's bombing campaign against Yugoslavia is broadly unpopular
here, and rocks have been hurled at vehicles belonging to NATO's
contingent in Macedonia for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Since late April, French soldiers stationed in northeast
Macedonia have come under more direct attack. The area is home to
most of Macedonia's small Serb minority, and is also the region
where three U.S. servicemen fell into Yugoslav hands in disputed
circumstances in late March.
</P>
<P>
   Two grenades were thrown from a passing car at a French sentry
outside a base at Kumanovo, but missed their target. On April 29, a
short-range anti-tank rocket fired at a passing French jeep in the
area also missed its target.
</P>
<P>
   On May 10, a rocket fired at a French heliport in Kumanovo
missed its target. Three days ago, another rocket was fired at a
small hotel in the area used as a French base, but also failed to
strike the building. A French jeep was seized and burned by angry
Serbs last month after a NATO vehicle broke down in a Serb village.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2058EDT &QL; 
