<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UFW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 UFW Wins `Company Unions' Dispute
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
About 18 strawberry growers and farm groups have agreed to stop
funding worker committees that served as rivals to the United Farm
Workers union, as part of a settlement of a UFW lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   UFW officials _ who had slammed the worker committees as
``company unions'' _ announced the settlement at a press conference
yesterday in Watsonville.
</P>
<P>
   They called it a victory for the union that comes just as the
UFW is preparing for a potentially critical election at Coastal
Berry Co., the state's largest strawberry grower.
</P>
<P>
   ``This confirms our warnings that strawberry growers have been
illegally repressing workers' right to organize by funding these
sham organizations,'' said UFW President Arturo Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a message that company unionism is illegal in
California,'' added UFW spokesman Marc Grossman.
</P>
<P>
   Growers, meanwhile, downplayed the actual impact of the
settlement. They pointed out that the specific worker committees
that sparked the suit no longer exist. Other parts of the
settlement, which include payment of attorneys' fees to the UFW,
were confidential.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committees (named in the suit) are long gone, out of
business, so nothing's at issue,'' said Terrence O'Connor, a lawyer
for the Western Growers Association, which took part in the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit and settlement dealt with the relationship between
strawberry growers and groups such as the now-defunct Pro Workers
Committee, an anti-UFW group that held a 5,000-person march in
Salinas in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The UFW had alleged that the worker groups were committing fraud
by claiming to be independent of employers. As the lawsuit
progressed, the union discovered evidence of $56,000 in company
payments to the worker groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We subpoenaed the committees' bank records, but they said they
lost them, so we subpoenaed the Bank of America,'' said the UFW's
Grossman. ``Every time we found a new canceled check (from a
grower), we added a new defendant.''
</P>
<P>
   A Santa Cruz Superior Court judge ruled last winter that two of
the growers had violated a section of the state labor code barring
agricultural employers from providing money to farm labor
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Those two growers have appealed the verdict. Meanwhile, about 18
others signed a settlement promising not to fund workers' groups in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Some growers said they hadn't done anything illegal but signed
the settlement to avoid a costly legal fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these guys just bought hats for their workers from the
organization, which isn't illegal,'' said O'Connor. ``But it's like
a nuisance lawsuit. If it costs $1,000 to defend but $500 to
settle, then you'll settle it.''
</P>
<P>
   The UFW has spent the past three years trying to organize
California's 30,000-worker strawberry industry. It faced a big
setback last summer, when workers at Coastal Berry voted for
representation by a rival group.
</P>
<P>
   But the state Agricultural Labor Relations Board overturned that
election on May 6, and the UFW has asked the state to schedule a
new election at Coastal Berry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
