<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHEON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Healtheon, WebMD Close to Merger
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Two health-related Internet companies _ Santa Clara's Healtheon and
WebMD of Atlanta _ confirmed yesterday that they are close to
merging into a new company that would be a dominant player in
online medical information and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, Intel and Excite are likely to invest a total of $500
million in the merged company, to be called WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon shares shot up $24.38 to $80.25 per share yesterday,
giving the company a market value of $5.7 billion. That's the value
analysts are giving the deal, since WebMD is privately held. Each
company would own 50 percent of the new one.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon stock has soared 70 percent since Bloomberg News first
disclosed the discussions on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which only went public in February, operates a Web
site where patients and health care workers can monitor insurance
claims and get and make referrals. Doctors also can use the system
to order supplies and check lab results.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD, formed in October, offers information and discussion
forums on medical topics.
</P>
<P>
   If consummated, the merged company presumably would create a
medical portal for one-stop shopping and information.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon chief executive Michael Long would be chairman and
chief operating officer of the merged company; WebMD Chief
Executive Officer Jeffrey Arnold would be its CEO. Neither side
would say where the merged company would be headquartered.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon's board has rubber-stamped the deal, and WebMD's
directors were expected to vote on the plan yesterday. An
announcement should come later this week, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is expected to invest $200 million in the new company,
and Intel, Excite and San Francisco's McKesson HBOC would put in
another $300 million, said sources close to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   While a health care portal sounds like an exciting concept,
trying to tame the unwieldy, fragmented medical profession is an
``enormous challenge,'' said Jack Staff, an analyst at Zona
Research, a market-research firm in Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industry with a tremendous amount of data changing
hands,'' Staff said. ``Healtheon needs the help of plenty of
software and Internet partners, folks like Microsoft, Excite and
Intel, to make all these applications work. It is a daunting
task.''
</P>
<P>
   Health care has lagged behind other industries in automating
paperwork. Most medical concerns still rely on antiquated computer
networks, and nearly one-fourth of the $1 trillion spent on health
care in the United States each year is wasted on inefficiencies and
poor communications within the industry, according to Healtheon.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon was founded by Long and Jim Clark, the entrepreneur
behind Netscape Communications and Silicon Graphics. Clark is
Healtheon's chairman and will continue as a board member of the
combined company.
</P>
<P>
   The 727-person company _ backed by the powerful venture capital
firm Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers _ last month announced plans
to acquire another rival, Mede America Corp., for $460 million in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Internet firms, Healtheon has yet to turn a profit.
The company lost $54 million last year on sales of $48.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD, which employs 182, is backed by DuPont Co., the biggest
U.S. chemical company, and McKesson HBOC, the nation's biggest drug
wholesaler. One source estimated the 7-month-old startup has less
than $100,000 in sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Profits have nothing to do with the ($5.7 billion) merger
value,'' one WebMD insider said. ``It's about being first in your
market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
