u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-630     05-19 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE NEARS VOTE ON GUN BILL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Ill., Md., N.J., N.Y., Utah, Vt.)  (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After several days of escalating feuds between
Republicans and Democrats, the Senate pulled back from the brink of
a partisan meltdown Wednesday night and seemed poised for a final
vote on Thursday on a juvenile crime bill that has become a vehicle
for several new gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the House, Democrats were emboldened by signs that
their Republican colleagues might be open to some new gun control
and said Wednesday that they would move on Thursday to introduce
gun-control amendments to two bills being completed in separate
House committees.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Steny H. Hoyer, D-Md., and Nita M. Lowey, D-N.Y., said
that they would offer, as amendments to a postal service
appropriations bill, proposals calling for mandatory background
checks on all buyers at gun shows and a raise in the minimum age
for legal possession of a handgun to 21 from 18.
</P>
<P>
   Both are measures that on Tuesday drew at least some support
from House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois. Hastert said he
personally favored background checks at gun shows and a minimum age
of 21 for handgun purchases, though not handgun possession.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee said Wednesday that
they would offer similar amendments to a juvenile crime bill that
also might come up for final revisions on Thursday, but senior
Republican aides said the measures were technically not germane to
the bill and would be rejected on those grounds.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Republicans and Democrats made significant
progress late Wednesday on combining and condensing pending
amendments so that they might be able to get to a final vote on the
bill by Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, had previously
said that if work on the bill was not completed by then, he would
be forced to put it aside for an indefinite period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., said Wednesday night that the
melding Wednesday of many pending amendments into a single package
to be offered by him and Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, had
significantly diminished the chances of that indefinite delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It removes an awful lot of obstacles,'' Leahy said Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was scheduled to vote on that package and four other
amendments, including one gun control measure, late Wednesday
night. Early Wednesday afternoon, the Senate passed three other
amendments to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   A provision of one amendment would institute financial penalties
for states whenever violent criminals released from the state's
prisons went on to commit similar crimes in other states. A
provision of another amendment would allow schools to use federal
education funds for security and safety purposes, like the purchase
of metal detectors.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate rejected an amendment that would create an additional
$340 million annually so that schools could hire more guidance
counselors, but it approved the creation of a National Commission
on Character Development to look into the effect of cultural
influences on good citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate took that step, Republicans continued to press
reluctant Democrats for an agreement on a time limit to finish work
on the bill, and even some Democrats suggested that colleagues on
their own side of the aisle were dragging their feet, more
interested in keeping alive a debate on gun control than in putting
the bill to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., said his colleagues were
struggling with conflicting desires to keep bashing Republicans for
the traditional resistance to gun control and to nudge those
gun-control measures already passed by the Senate toward law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a balance between the politics of letting them swing on
this stuff and actually doing some good,'' Biden said, referring to
Republicans. ``I, for one, would save them from themselves.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The gun-control amendment to be voted on would require that pawn
shops conduct background checks even on customers coming in to
reclaim their own guns.
</P>
<P>
   That requirement exists under current law but would have been
eliminated by a provision in a previous Republican amendment,
passed last week, that promoted mandatory background checks for all
buyers at gun shows. Democrats cited that provision as one of the
main reasons they planned to re-introduce a new version of their
own amendment requiring background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican attempt to address that concern with a new
amendment was aimed at making certain that moderate Republicans did
not break party ranks and pass the resurrected Democratic proposal,
expected to come to a vote early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is siphoning off votes, patching another hole in their
leaky boat,'' said Sen. Frank R. Lautenberg, D-N.J., the principal
sponsor of the Democratic gun-show proposal. ``It's a desperation
tactic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
