<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-NASA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$41 BILLION NASA FUNDING BILL CLEARS HOUSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A $41.2 billion funding bill for NASA cleared the
House on Wednesday, but not before lawmakers engaged in partisan
wrangling over the Triana satellite, an Earth-viewing project
initiated by Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which outlines spending priorities for the
space agency into the next century, includes $7 billion for the
U.S. share of the international space station through 2002 but not
a dime for Gore's satellite proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the measure, which would give the space agency
slightly more money than the White House requested over the next
three years, are $7.8 billion for space shuttle missions and $4.2
billion for earth science programs.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, approved 259-168 with most Democrats opposing it, now
goes to the Senate. The bill authorizes spending but does not
appropriate money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
All but one member of Texas' congressional delegation _ Rep. Lloyd
Doggett, D-Austin voted against it _ supported the bill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If it becomes law, the measure would prohibit spending taxpayer
money on TransHab, an inflatable habitat for the space station that
is being developed at Johnson Space Center south of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Space agency administrator Dan Goldin has said he would ask
President Clinton to veto the bill if the final version does not
include money to continue the Triana satellite project, which Gore
has said came to him in the middle of the night last March.
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned by the vice president, the satellite would be
stationed halfway to the sun and would beam high-resolution images
of Earth to anyone with a television or access to the Internet. The
project is named for the lookout on Christopher Columbus's ship who
first spotted the New World.
</P>
<P>
   NASA agreed to tackle Gore's project and has since determined it
would provide scientists with views of changing clouds, the
planet's vegetation canopy, major fires and weather systems
currently monitored by satellites in much lower orbits.
</P>
<P>
   By October, the beginning of the budget year, NASA will have
spent $41 million developing the satellite, which is due for launch
during a space shuttle mission in December 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused the GOP of targeting the project in an effort
to embarrass the vice president, the leading candidate for the
Democratic presidential nomination next year. Scrapping Triana is
``totally parochial, totally partisan,'' said Rep. Bart Gordon, a
Tennessee Democrat who sees the Senate as the best chance of
reviving Triana funding.
</P>
<P>
   When Republicans on the House Science Committee last week
deleted Triana from the space agency bill, the $33 million sought
by the administration was transferred into cancer and microbiology
research overseen by NASA.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Science Committee Chairman James Sensenbrenner,
R-Wis., defended the transfer, saying it would be better spent ``on
medical research than on funding the vice president's late-night
inspiration for a multimillion-dollar screen saver,'' for computer
users.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dave Weldon, a Florida Republican, led the effort to scrap
Gore's satellite, saying it was embraced by NASA bureaucrats at the
same time they were laying off 600 employees at the Kennedy Space
Center in his district.
</P>
<P>
   The Triana project is ``an insult to the working men and women
at Kennedy Space Center who were being laid off while NASA was
scrambling to find tens of millions of dollars to fulfill a vision
for the vice president,'' Weldon said.
</P>
<P>
   The House also rejected an amendment, offered annually since the
project began, to halt U.S. involvement in the international space
station project. Also failing to win House approval was a proposal
to put a cap on U.S. spending on the space station and to end
Russian participation in the 16-nation project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think its a good deal for science,'' said Rep. Tim
Roemer, an Indiana Democrat and perennial leader of the drive to
eliminate space station funding. ``This project just doesn't live
up to NASA's past accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republican Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, defended the space
station, saying it would be a mistake to scrap the project now that
two components have been launched and others appear on schedule.
``We cannot be afraid to fail. We cannot be afraid to experiment,''
DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's share of the space station costs have been increased by
about $5 billion by the failure of economically strapped Russia to
keep to the schedule its space agency and the 15 other nations
agreed to follow in developing, launching and assembling the
orbiting laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before approving the bill, House members turned back an effort
to transfer $100 million a year from the space station budget to
help pay for aeronautics research. The move to divert the money was
led by Virginia Reps. Herbert Bateman, a Republican, and Robert
Scott, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The two lawmakers represent parts of Hampton Roads, Va., where
NASA's Langley Research Center faces major funding shortages.
Seventy percent of the research at Langley focuses on aeronautics
research.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, NASA cancelled Langley's work on a high-speed
passenger jet that could travel from the U.S. to Asia in less than
five hours. Also scrapped by the space agency was Langley's
research into improve the safety, lower the cost and reduce the
environmental impact of current aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
