<HEADER>
A3784 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0520-C     05-19 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. SHOWS VIDEO, PHOTOS OF REFUGEE MASSACRE; DIPLOMATIC EFFORTS
PICK UP STEAM
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-TECH-0520; JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0520.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department showed spy photos Wednesday
that U.S. officials said prove the authenticity of a video-tape
documenting the alleged March massacre of 127 ethnic Albanian
civilians by Serb police in a village in northwest Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The video, shot by a refugee during a mass burial several days
after the alleged massacre at Izbica, contained graphic close-ups
of victims -- most of whom appeared to be elderly men -- whose
bloodied bodies, faces and clothing appeared to have been riddled
with bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government has denied the attack and dismissed the
video as a fake.
</P>
<P>
   But the landscape, buildings and even trees seen in the video
match hand-in-glove with the features shown on U.S. spy photos of
the village, providing what State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin
called ``conclusive proof,'' that the video is authentic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've ever been able to link video
evidence with overhead imagery,'' Rubin told reporters after
presenting the intelligence photos and matching them with excerpts
from the video. ``The Serbs have lied to the world about what
happened at Izbica.''
</P>
<P>
   As NATO strikes against Serb forces stretched into their ninth
week Wednesday, diplomatic efforts to end the conflict picked up
steam.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's envoy to the Balkans, former premier Victor
Chernomyrdin, met in Belgrade with Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic,
president of Yugoslavia, to discuss a possible end-game.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin was scheduled to return to Moscow on Thursday to
meet there with Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and
provide an update on Milosevic's latest thinking.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was
scheduled to discuss NATO's Kosovo strategy with British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the frantic shuttle diplomacy of recent weeks, Rubin
said a diplomatic breakthrough was not yet at hand, as Washington
and Moscow remain far apart over the key issue of how to put
together a credible international security force to police any
peace arrangement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving towards agreement, not away from agreement,''
Rubin said. ``But clearly, there are major gaps that remain.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its NATO allies have insisted on a large,
combat-ready peacekeeping force with NATO at its core to police any
truce in Kosovo, a province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant
republic. Russia -- which has close historical and cultural ties to
its Slavic cousins in Serbia -- has pressed for a more lightly
armed force under United Nations command.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has said he would accept only a civilian monitoring
regime and he has so far ruled out the presence of NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that two months of air strikes are grinding away at
Serb unity, Rubin said the United States had verified that at least
500 Serb troops abandoned their units in Kosovo on Tuesday in the
single largest instance of Serb desertion to date.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said most of the deserters left Kosovo to return to their
homes in the town of Krusevac. Earlier this week, police in that
town cracked down on what U.S. officials have characterized as an
anti-war demonstration involving some 5,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The Krusevac authorities used heavy-handed tactics, including
attacks on women and children, to put down the demonstration, Rubin
said. U.S. intelligence sources believe that anger over those
actions prompted Tuesday's desertions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic's regime is beginning to crack,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's impossible to independently verify the State
Department's version of events inside Kosovo. Serb officials
expelled journalists from the province after NATO air strikes began
March 24.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare and horrifying glimpse at the bloodshed that's
unfolded inside the tiny province, however, the National
Albanian-American Council released a video Wednesday containing
gruesome footage of victims allegedly massacred in late March -- on
the 29th, according to some refugee accounts -- in the village of
Izbica.
</P>
<P>
   The village is one of more than 70 communities throughout Kosovo
where Serb troops, police or paramilitary gangs have executed
ethnic Albanians since NATO air strikes began, according to refugee
accounts deemed credible by the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Izbica) is only a small part of the story,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are normally not cameras when these massacres take
place,'' he said, ``but clearly, war crimes are being committed.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees reaching Albania and Macedonia from Izbica in April
told human rights investigators that they were traveling through
the village in a convoy of tractors and farm trailers when they
were stopped by Serb police.
</P>
<P>
   Men -- most of whom ranged in age between 60 and 80 years --
were separated from women and children, according to the refugee
accounts, and forced to march off to a remote spot where a broad
field met a wooded slope.
</P>
<P>
   There these men -- 127, the State Department said -- were mowed
down by gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   On April 17, the United States released two-day-old intelligence
photos of Izbica showing three neat rows of graves that did not
exist in photos taken in early March.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, U.S. and NATO officials cited the photos as
evidence of a mass grave that supported the earlier refugee
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb government denounced the spy photos as a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   The video released Wednesday, however, shows civilians digging
graves with picks and shovels in an area whose terrain,
architecture and foliage matches identically with the features
illustrated by the intelligence imagery.
</P>
<P>
   The information is being turned over to the U.N. tribunal
investigating war crimes in Kosovo, and Rubin said it would weigh
heavily against the alleged perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have what we need, and what we think can provide a
compelling case,'' against Serb forces in Izbica, Rubin said.
``Ultimately that test will have to be met by the war crimes
tribunal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin would not detail the source of the imagery, but U.S.
spyplanes and satellites have been heavily photographing Kosovo for
months.
</P>
<P>
   The grisly video released Wednesday showed victim after victim
-- some with badly contorted limbs, one with a hand that appeared
to have been shot nearly off and another with the contents of a
shattered skull seeping onto the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The victims wore the simple garb of traditional rural folk --
threadbare sweaters, loose-fitting trousers and heavy shoes deeply
creased by use -- and nothing even remotely resembling military
attire.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, an elderly victim is placed in a grave, wrapped
only in a time-worn blanket, and dirt is shoveled onto the body.
</P>
<P>
   In footage at the scene of the alleged massacre, a white-haired
man describes the shooting. Serb police lined the men up in three
rows against the hillside and opened fire, said the man.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was on the last row, and as victims fell before him
he too fell to the ground. The man prostrated himself flat on the
ground, showing the camera how he lay still as bodies piled on top
of him. Then he crawled, like an animal, into the foliage,
demonstrating how he escaped after the Serb police had gone.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the man says that his own brother was killed, and he
breaks into uncontrollable sobs.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the video, rifle-bearing men in camouflaged
fatigues can be seen standing by as civilians dig graves. Rubin
said he assumed the military men were members of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, an ethnic Albanian group supporting independence
for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs regard the KLA as a terrorist group and have justified
their brutal campaign across Kosovo as an effort to destroy the
rebel organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't rule out that the KLA was there,'' said Rubin. That
would not excuse, though, the killing of elderly civilians, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A war crime is a war crime,'' Rubin said, ``and there is no
justification for a war crime.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
