<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3786 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0520-C     05-19 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. SHOWS VIDEO, PHOTOS OF REFUGEE MASSACRE; DIPLOMATIC EFFORTS
PICK UP STEAM
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-TECH-0520; JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0520.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department showed spy photos Wednesday
that U.S. officials said prove the authenticity of a video-tape
documenting the alleged March massacre of 127 ethnic Albanian
civilians by Serb police in a village in northwest Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The video, shot by a refugee during a mass burial several days
after the alleged massacre at Izbica, contained graphic close-ups
of victims -- most of whom appeared to be elderly men -- whose
bloodied bodies, faces and clothing appeared to have been riddled
with bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government has denied the attack and dismissed the
video as a fake.
</P>
<P>
   But the landscape, buildings and even trees seen in the video
match hand-in-glove with the features shown on U.S. spy photos of
the village, providing what State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin
called ``conclusive proof,'' that the video is authentic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've ever been able to link video
evidence with overhead imagery,'' Rubin told reporters after
presenting the intelligence photos and matching them with excerpts
from the video. ``The Serbs have lied to the world about what
happened at Izbica.''
</P>
<P>
   As NATO strikes against Serb forces stretched into their ninth
week Wednesday, diplomatic efforts to end the conflict picked up
steam.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's envoy to the Balkans, former premier Victor
Chernomyrdin, met in Belgrade with Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic,
president of Yugoslavia, to discuss a possible end-game.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin was scheduled to return to Moscow on Thursday to
meet there with Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and
provide an update on Milosevic's latest thinking.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was
scheduled to discuss NATO's Kosovo strategy with British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook on Thursday.
</P>
