<HEADER>
A3785 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROVIDIAN-SFCHRON &LR;      05-19 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Providian Shares Fall 14% on News Of D.A.'s Probe
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Shares of Providian Financial Corp. fell 14 percent yesterday
following reports that the giant San Francisco credit card lender
is under investigation by the city district attorney for possible
consumer fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Providian's stock plunged $17.19 to $106.94 in trading of 5.6
million shares, six times its average daily volume in the past six
months, after The Chronicle and KRON-TV reported the district
attorney's probe.
</P>
<P>
   Providian, the nation's ninth-largest credit card company,
specializes in lending to customers with flawed credit records.
</P>
<P>
   Before yesterday's plunge, Providian had been one of hottest
financial stocks on Wall Street, with shares more than doubling in
the last 18 months. Investors loved the company's knack for
extracting profits from customers other lenders regarded as
deadbeats.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Providian's stock was vulnerable precisely because
the company was such a high-flier, trading at prices much higher
than most financial stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Before yesterday's drop, the company's shares changed hands at
prices as high as 55 times earnings. By contrast, American Express
trades at about 25 times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Chamberlain, an analyst with Jefferies &AMP; Co. in Los
Angeles, said it isn't clear an investigation will result in
sanctions that will affect Providian's profits. ``Still, if `20/20'
does an expose of them, then it's an investment issue,''
Chamberlain said.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by complaints from consumers, the San Francisco
district attorney's office said Tuesday that it is looking into
whether Providian violated the law in the sale of credit cards and
collection of debt.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups have accused the company of such questionable
practices as failing to properly disclose fees and charges. The
company says that its actions are within the law and that it will
cooperate with any city investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3788 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVI-SFCHRON &LR;      05-19 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Levi's Teaming Up With Goo Goo Dolls
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Can the Goo Goo Dolls convince teens to wear Levi's?
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. of San Francisco thinks they can. The
jeansmaker is expected to announce today that it will sponsor a
concert tour this summer featuring the rock bands Goo Goo Dolls,
Sugar Ray and Fastball.
</P>
<P>
   The Levi's Fuse '99 tour will cover 43 markets, including
Shoreline Amphitheater in Mountain View. Levi's, which has devoted
up to half of its marketing budget this year to rock music
sponsorships, plans to make the Fuse tour an annual event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to really create a positive association for
the Levi's brand with the most current, most exciting music,'' said
Joe Townsend, Levi's music sponsorship manager. ``I want our target
(audience) to come in and have a really fun time courtesy of the
Levi's brand. If we pull that off, we will have done a really good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Levi's is hoping concert sponsorships will build a positive
association with teens _ something conventional advertising has
failed to do.
</P>
<P>
   But a local marketing executive said he is thinks teens may see
the tour as a heavy-handed sales job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Levi's needs to establish a brand identity that doesn't feel
like it's being sold,'' said the executive, who declined to be
identified because he does business with Levi's. ``They can't buy
brand loyalty in this age group.''
</P>
<P>
   A retailing executive said he doesn't expect the concerts to
help Levi's because he believes bad fashion forecasting is the
company's main problem. ``It's cool to sponsor a rock concert, but
do they have the items to sell?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's spokesman Jeff Beckman responded that sales for several
of the company's lines picked up in April.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Fuse tour, Levi's this summer is hosting
little-known rock groups at 35 outdoor amphitheaters around the
country on small stages, called Levi's First stages, built
specially for the acts.
</P>
<P>
   The Fuse events will start about 4:30 p.m. The afternoon will
include performances on the Levi's First stages in venues that have
them, and record-spinning by disc jockeys in a nearby tent. In the
evening, the three headline bands will play at the main
amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's will offer performers clothing to wear but won't require
that they wear Levi's clothes, Townsend said. Levi's signs will not
appear on stage, but the Levi's name will be on tickets and on
posters around the venue.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend estimates 750,000 people will attend the Fuse concerts.
</P>
<P>
   The headline bands ``are not a sellout package,'' but will
attract a good-size crowd of young people, predicted one industry
source.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3790 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-KHRISTICH-     05-19 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-KHRISTICH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINDEN COMMENTS ARBITRATION FODDER, KHRISTICH SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- From Harry Sinden's mouth to Dmitri Khristich's ears.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour after the Bruins' season ended, Sinden, the
team's president and general manager, voiced his dissatisfaction
with some members of the team. The notable exception was Ray
Bourque. The notable targets were Khristich and Jason Allison.
Sinden called Khristich ``a total, total disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon at the FleetCenter, the normally reticent
Khristich went on the counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't read it. I heard it,'' Khristich said. ``(Sinden)
just makes his ground for the arbitration. That's about it. No
normal person would say this the second day after a disappointing
loss, carve everybody. That's not how it's done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on the team was feeling like we accomplished a lot
this season. We made one more step compared to the other season. We
learn from our mistakes and hopefully we do better next season.
With that kind of attitude, we woke (Wednesday) and saw that in the
newspaper. Maybe he's got a different idea. Maybe he's just
(thinking about) making money. Maybe he doesn't care about how
we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Khristich was awarded a one-year deal worth $1.95
million through arbitration. He likely will face the same
salary-setting process this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to file till July 15,'' said Khristich's
agent, Larry Kelly, ``but rest assured we'll be filing.''
</P>
<P>
   If Khristich and the Bruins go to arbitration, the proceedings
promise to be contentious.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, arbitrator Claude Foisy split the difference between
what the right wing wanted and what the club was offering. After
watching Khristich's performance in the playoffs, the general
manager felt he did not get his money's worth. Sinden called the
three goals Khristich scored against Buffalo ``meaningless,''
adding that high-priced players were paid to produce in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Sinden's comments and Khristich's counterattack, the
sides seem far apart in appraising Khristich's value. The general
manager's criticism could translate into a trade sometime around
the June draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like he's got confidence in me,'' said the
forward, who scored a team-high 29 goals and finished third in
assists with 42 during the regular season. ``I don't feel like even
going to arbitration because we will have totally different ideas
about what we're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he wanted to be traded, Khristich said, ``I
wouldn't say that yet. That's just a first reaction. It's a long
summer and we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   His agent was similarly noncommital on the subject of a trade,
adding only that he expected it to be a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Khristich's frustrations as a Bruin go beyond recent criticism
from the general manager. The right wing struggled through
stretches of unproductive play. He failed to score in the last five
games of the season and managed just 11 points (3 goals, 8 assists)
over the final 17. Khristich lacked consistency and regular
linemates, though he successfully reunited with Sergei Samsonov and
Allison midway through the Carolina series.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian deferred comment on his play in the postseason, but
admitted he would have liked more ice time. He finished with three
goals and four assists.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Khristich carries Sinden's words with him or dismisses
them as an emotional first reaction may depend on the success of
summertime negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know to (be critical before arbitration) money-wise,''
said Khristich. ``They know to put people down. I spent last year
in arbitration. I've been to the meeting of that arbitration itself
and I heard all the stuff they had to say about me. I was a little
surprised it came so early (this time), just the next morning after
the series. But I think I could predict what he would say and
that's what he was going to say.''
</P>
<P>
   When dissatisfied general managers and disgruntled players
speak, predictions are easy to make. Some expectations will be met
this offseason. Someone will walk away disappointed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
