<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SOCSEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS AND WHITE HOUSE TRY TO BREAK SOCIAL SECURITY DEADLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Neb., N.H., Iowa, Texas)   (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan group of senators on Thursday will
propose a plan to deal with Social Security's looming problems
while there is tentative maneuvering at the White House and on
Capitol Hill to revive an issue that had seemed all but dead for
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the group of senators was polishing its plan, Rep. Bill
Archer, R- Texas, who heads the House Ways and Means Committee, met
with President Clinton on Wednesday to explore whether there was
enough common ground between the parties to move the issue forward.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said before the meeting with
Archer that the president ``wants to find a way to bring enough
Democrats and Republicans along so that we can solve this problem
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Archer agreed at the meeting that they would reach
out to congressional leaders, including Speaker Dennis Hastert of
Illinois and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri, to
see if there was hope for serious negotiations. Archer also said he
would schedule hearings on Social Security next month, his
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The philosophical divide between the parties about how to deal
with Social Security remains deep, and there is so little trust
between Republicans and Democrats that the chances of a deal on
such a sensitive issue before the 2000 elections seem remote.
</P>
<P>
   But some members of both parties said they want to try.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nobody goes first, nobody goes anywhere,'' said Sen. John
Breaux, D-La., one of four senators who plan to unveil a
legislative proposal on Thursday. The others are Bob Kerrey,
D-Neb.; Judd Gregg, R-N.H., and Charles Grassley, R-Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Their plan is similar to previous proposals supported by members
of the group, and calls for private investment accounts within
Social Security that would be financed by a portion of the federal
budget surplus. Workers would place into the account each year a
tax rebate equal to two percentage points of the 12.4 percent
payroll tax that finances Social Security, and could choose from a
menu of investment options including stocks and Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for an accelerating the planned increase in the
retirement age to 67 and a reduction in cost of living increases.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also has several new twists, among them a provision to
have the government match a portion of additional voluntary
contributions to the private accounts by low-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has two Democrats among its sponsors, the plan is
likely to be rejected by most Democrats, especially those in the
House, who are opposed to creating private accounts within the
retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's backers, though, said they hoped to create some
momentum by attracting enough support from members of both parties
to force a vote in the Senate Finance Committee, bring the bill to
the Senate floor and convince the leadership of both parties that
it is worth the political risk to insure the retirement system's
long-term health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
