<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-ARTIST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE ART MUSEUM CANCELS EXHIBIT OF MIKE KELLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ ``Stand by Your Artist'' is not the Seattle Art
Museum's theme song. For the second time in a little more than a
year, the museum has agreed to exhibit an artist's work and backed
off at the prospect of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Both times modern art curator Trevor Fairbrother chose the
artists, and both times he said he agreed with the decision to
renege. The first case concerned Seattle artist Erika Langley's
photos of strippers, and the second, occurring last week, concerns
a 1988 installation piece by Los Angeles artist Mike Kelley titled
``Pay for Your Pleasure.'' Kelley's piece was to be part of a group
exhibition, ``2000{,'' slated to open in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Kelley's, Langley's situation is insignificant.
Instead of canceling her show, the museum delayed it until it could
be hung in a gallery, deciding that its initial decision to place
the photos in a hallway was an error. School groups regularly tour
through the museum, Fairbrother explained at the time. If teachers
see a warning label on a gallery, they might choose not to enter,
but in a hallway show, the option isn't available.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley's piece was canceled, and canceled after Fairbrother got
a go-ahead from museum director Mimi Gates and told the artist he
was on board.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley is one of the most distinguished artists in his
generation on the West Coast. ``Pay for Your Pleasure'' has been
exhibited without notable protest at New York's Whitney Museum of
American Art, the Renaissance Society at the University of Chicago
and the Los Angeles Museum of Modern Art, which owns the piece.
</P>
<P>
   The problem in Seattle, Fairbrother said, is that protests came
in so far in advance of the exhibiton that the museum didn't have
time to present the reasons it wanted to show it. Gates wasn't
available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   First reactions came via the Internet. After hearing the museum
was looking for a piece of art by a criminal, a reporter working
for the Web site of the ``APB Serial Killer Bureau'' called
victims' groups and told them the museum planned to exhibit art by
a murderer and asked them what they thought.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Eakes, member of the museum and founder/president of the
Seattle-based Mothers Against Violence in America, said local talk
radio hosts called her and presented a one-sided view of the
controversy. ``I was told the museum planned to feature the work of
a killer,'' she said. While she is impressed the museum made such a
fast decision to cancel the show, she said she would like to hear
more about the exhibit and what the artist's perspective is. ``I'd
be willing to work with the museum to explore the issue. The media
presented (the artwork) as today's outrage. There should be a
complete discussion before ruling it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Fairbrother also blames the media. ``The press created a feeding
frenzy and so distorted the idea of Mike's piece that we had no
choice,'' he said. ``Both Mimi and I agreed to make this decision
for the good of the institution. In this climate, the piece
wouldn't have a chance of being fairly viewed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay for Your Pleasure'' is essentially a corridor along which
banners hang featuring the faces of famed philosophers and artists
in the Western tradition, from early Greeks to 19th-century poets,
along with quotes from each that flirt with the idea of the rule
breaker and the criminal.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the corridor is a painting by a criminal active in
the region. Hence, when ``Pay for Your Pleasure'' was in Chicago,
it included a crude painting of a clown by mass murderer John Wayne
Gacy. Had ``Pay for Your Pleasure'' opened at SAM, a painting by a
local criminal would have been used. Kelley's intent is to
juxtapose theory and fact, romance and reality, thus raising
questions about why violence is romanticized.
</P>
<P>
   David Beatty, director of public policy for the National Center
for Victims of Crime, in Arlington, Va., expressed regret in the
Serial Killer Bureau online article that criminals are glamorized
for their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, however, he said the reporter calling him didn't
explain the artwork but said the museum was going to feature work
of an infamous criminal. The reporter ``didn't tell me what the
artist was doing,'' he said. ``I told her, not having seen the
context or the specific presentation, I couldn't make specific
comments. With art, you have to see it first.'' That quote didn't
make it into the online story.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet article was faxed to Seattle's ABC affiliate, The
Seattle Times. The Times editorialized last Friday on the subject,
asking why the museum couldn't also exhibit the work of crime
victims. After talk radio stations began to log in, the museum
canceled the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if any of the people complaining had seen Kelley's piece,
Fairbrother shook his head. ``It didn't seem so,'' he said. He
added that timing was another crucial issue, since the subject of
violence is particularly sensitive after the slaying of high school
students in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Andrews, director of the University of Washington's
Henry Art Gallery, agreed. ``There's national anguish after
Littleton,'' he said. ``I understand that. I'm the father of a
16-year-old boy. On the other hand, what better time for a piece
that explores the nature of violence? The issue is intolerably
double-edged.''
</P>
<P>
   Susanne Ghez, director of the Renaissance Society at the
University of Chicago, said controversies of this sort distort art
and everybody loses. ``Kelley isn't rewarding criminals or
increasing their fame. He's framing a discussion in an aesthetic
context.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Reid, a Seattle curator and writer who has both written
about and exhibited Kelley, thinks the artist has been given the
art world equivalent of the bum's rush. ``Who needs Jesse Helms
when we have the Seattle Art Museum?'' he asked. ``Did the museum
make any effort to educate the public about this work? No. If the
museum doesn't have the guts to stand behind a strong work of art
when the squeeze is on, then it should go on pretending the 20th
century never happened. Seattle's not ready for Mike Kelley? What
are we, the wimp town of all time?''
</P>
<P>
   Helene Winer, co-director of Metro Pictures, Kelley's New York
gallery, said the artist is disappointed but doesn't want talk to
the press and be dragged into a controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say I'm against museums withdrawing shows based on
uninformed protests,'' she said. ``There is no argument about this
piece. It's very anti-violence and very clear about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Held, acting director of Seattle's Center on Contemporary
Art, said CoCA is working on the possibility of showing Kelley's
piece but can't say anything for certain. ``We'd be honored to do
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle gallery director Greg Kucera, who saw ``Pay for Your
Pleasure'' in Los Angeles, recalls it as a ``magnificent'' work.
``Kelley has the bad habit of getting under people's skins and God
bless him for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
