<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newsstands offering plenty of stock advice
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anybody looking for inexpensive but professional
advice need look no further than the newsstand in the next few
weeks. No fewer than five magazines devote cover stories to what
stocks and mutual funds to buy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Money (June) features its second annual Money 100 list of
``outstanding mutual funds that any investor can use to build a
smart, well-balanced portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine (June) looks at
individual stocks, offering suggestions for three kinds of
portfolios _ ``conservative, aggressive and in-between.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bloomberg Personal Finance (June) takes a different tack,
examining Wall Street's ``most loved and most hated stocks,'' and
``how savvy investors can play both lists.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual Investor (June) considers whether it is time to buy
``the comeback companies'' _ such as General Motors, AT&AMP;T, Seagram,
Kmart, Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mutual Funds (June) surveys mutual funds designed to ``beat
the Dow,'' but also looks at tech stocks and the new Roth IRA.
</P>
<P>
   And as a service to those who would like to do their own
trading, Business Week (May 24) is out with its guide to buying and
selling via the Internet, which it says is ``rapidly changing the
way we invest.''
</P>
<P>
   My kind of town
</P>
<P>
   Take your pick, wealthy neighbors or working neighbors. This is
what two business publications do in their annual surveys of
cities: the 250 richest towns in America, by Worth (June), and the
16 best places for business and careers by Forbes (May 31).
</P>
<P>
   No, none of the richest towns is in Georgia. The closest, and
also top-ranked, is Jupiter Island, Fla., where the median home
price is $1.7 million. Worth says six of the top 10 cities are in
California and the other three are in Colorado _ can you spell
Aspen?
</P>
<P>
   If you're not affluent enough to live in a rich town, check out
Forbes' 50 best cities to get a job. Seattle ranks first and
Atlanta 10th, with the usual suspects in between: Austin, Texas;
Dallas, Ventura, San Jose and Oakland, Calif.; Somerset, N.J.;
Denver; and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   What's money for, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   If consumer spending is what keeps the U.S. economy going,
there's every reason to think it will go for a long time, according
to U.S. News &AMP; World Report (May 24). A booming economy is making
most Americans wealthier, and spending, it seems, begets spending.
</P>
<P>
   Strategy &AMP; Business (second quarter), an upscale business
quarterly, takes this concept a step further and suggests that the
consumption of consumer goods in so-called emerging markets over
the next 10 to 15 years will rival spending by consumers in the
United States and other industrial nations. Companies such as
Coca-Cola and Colgate-Palmolive are already ahead in this emerging
market game, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
