<SLUG> BC-CHARTER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3 major firms remove Charter from referrals
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three major managed care networks, totaling 32 million
members, suspended patient referrals to Charter Behavioral Health
Systems' psychiatric hospitals, in the wake of a critical CBS News
report on suburban Atlanta-based Charter's facilities.
</P>
<P>
   MCC Behavioral Care, which covers 10 million members, United
Behavioral Health, with 13 million, and Managed Health Network,
with 9 million, each said Wednesday that they were conducting
investigations of Charter as a result of the ``60 Minutes II''
program last month.
</P>
<P>
   The segment, anchored by Ed Bradley, alleged dangerous
conditions, falsification of records and lack of employee training
in Charter psychiatric hospitals. The allegations included injuries
and two patient deaths. The program followed a yearlong CBS News
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Charter, which runs the largest U.S. chain of private
psychiatric hospitals, responded to the program with an
investigation of its own. The company denies systemwide problems.
</P>
<P>
   But even the part-owner of Charter, Atlanta-based Magellan
Health Services, suspended referrals to two Charter facilities in
North Carolina cited in the ``60 Minutes II'' program. Magellan _
the No. 1 behavioral health company with 64 million members _ has
conducted its own reviews of Charter hospitals. It recently resumed
referrals to one suspended hospital, in Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   Removing Charter from referrals could cause access problems in
some rural areas where the company is the sole provider, said Mary
Graham of the National Mental Health Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the community,'' she said. Major urban areas,
such as metro Atlanta, have alternatives to Charter, including
independent facilities and psychiatric services offered by general
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies suspending referrals are among the top five
managed care firms that specialize in delivering mental health and
substance abuse services to insurers and employers. MCC is a
subsidiary of Cigna HealthCare, and UBH is a unit of United
Healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people reviewing their operations, training records _
all aspects of patient care,'' said MCC spokesman Howard Drescher,
adding that the company has resumed referrals to most Charter
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Charter suspensions led MCC to make contingency plans to
send patients to other hospitals, Drescher added. ``In some
locations, Charter is the only facility _ or almost the only one _
to give these services,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The privately held Charter operates 91 facilities in 32 states.
Eleven are in Georgia, with six in metro Atlanta. Annual revenue
exceeds $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``MCC and UBH are doing audits, and as far as I know, the
reviews have been favorable,'' Karen Jenkins, a Charter
spokeswoman, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 2 behavioral health company, Value Options, said it
reviewed its Charter care but did not suspend referrals.
</P>
<P>
   California-based Managed Health Network stopped its Charter
referrals the day after the ``60 Minutes II'' program aired. It has
launched its own investigation, which includes site visits to
Charter hospitals, said Lisa Haines, a company spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just taking precautions,'' she said. ``We want to make
sure our members are in the best place to receive services.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Magellan tried to sell its stake in Charter to the
other 50 percent owner, Crescent Operating. That deal collapsed.
And Magellan still has its ownership on the block.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Office of Inspector General, which fights health
care fraud, is reviewing the allegations against Charter.
</P>
<P>
   A recent filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission by
Magellan said the OIG, the Department of Justice and other agencies
are conducting investigations of Charter facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Charter is trying to clean up its act,'' said Al Guida
of the National Mental Health Association. The quality of care in
private hospitals such as Charter's is better than that in a
state-run institution, Guida added.
</P>
<P>
   But parents should actively monitor the care of their children
in any hospital, Guida said.
</P>
<P>
   He condemned the broad use of physical restraints on psychiatric
patients, in Charter and other facilities. The CBS program began
with the case of a 16-year-old boy who died in restraints at
Charter's Greensboro hospital. Congress is studying legislation
aimed at limiting the use of restraints.
</P>
<P>
   Charter has questioned CBS' reporting tactics, which included
footage shot by a hidden camera worn by a social worker who worked
for eight weeks in a Charter hospital. Charter cited patient
confidentiality concerns in filing a motion for a temporary
restraining order to prevent the program from airing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
