<HEADER>
A3798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-FRANKLIN20-C     05-19 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-FRANKLIN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Power shift: Executive moves up at Southern
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Allen Franklin's appointment as Southern Co. president
is a major step in repositioning the company to compete in a
deregulated electric power industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the move leaves open the question of who will eventually
succeed A.W. ``Bill'' Dahlberg as chairman and chief executive
officer of the nation's largest power producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a period of time when the industry is going to change
pretty rapidly,'' Dahlberg said Wednesday after elevating Franklin,
president of Georgia Power Co., to Southern's No. 2 post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to stay ahead of it, rather than try to catch up to
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Southern announced that Franklin, Dahlberg's close
associate of two decades, would become president and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   David M. Ratcliffe, chief financial officer at Georgia Power,
will succeed Franklin as president and chief executive officer of
Southern's largest subsidiary. Both appointments are effective June
1.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlberg is turning over to Franklin the day-to-day operations
of Southern's five U.S. utilities: Georgia Power, Alabama Power,
Gulf Power in northern Florida, Mississippi Power and Savannah
Electric.
</P>
<P>
   An engineer by training, Franklin will also oversee Southern's
electric power generation unit.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlberg, who has held three titles of chairman, president and
chief executive since 1995, will now have more time to plot
strategy for his $11.4 billion-a-year company, which has operations
across the United States and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Franklin will be essential to preparing Southern
for the coming shake-up in the $200 billion-a-year electric utility
industry. Deregulation will inject competition into what has been a
monopoly enterprise, much like it has for telecommunications, the
airline and Georgia's natural gas industries.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin has been Southern's point man for deregulation and has
represented the electric utility industry in testimony on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Kuhn, president of the Edison Electric Institute, the
Washington-based utility industry trade group, called Franklin the
industry's ``principal leader'' in formulating strategy as chairman
of the group's restructuring committee.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin ``probably knows more about the proposals than anyone
in our industry,'' Dahlberg added.
</P>
<P>
   But Dahlberg said Franklin was not being designated as his
successor at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Succession challenge
</P>
<P>
   The process of selecting a Southern Co. CEO has been compared to
the anointment of a new pope by the Vatican's College of Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   When Dahlberg was named president in 1994, it was clear he would
eventually succeed Edward L. Addison as chief executive. The same
was true 10 years earlier when Addison was named as heir-apparent
to Alvin W. Vogtle Jr.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no puff of smoke rising from Southern's Peachtree
Street headquarters Wednesday. The announcement was made after the
boards of Southern and Georgia Power approved Dahlberg's decision,
and in advance of next week's Southern shareholder meeting in
Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we've used the position of president as a
transition job. This is different,'' Dahlberg said, noting that
Franklin will also serve as the first chief operating officer in
Southern's history, a ``full-time job.''
</P>
<P>
   That role needed to be filled, he said, because of the growth of
Southern's Southeastern utilities, which now have 3.3 million
customers, and the increasing complexity of the utility business.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin will take a hands-on role in shaping Southern's
strategy as the utility industry moves toward separate generation,
transmission and distribution functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need a president,'' agreed Edward J. Tirello, an analyst
with BT Alex. Brown. ``As the company expands, you need more top
management and someone who could be chosen as a successor if
something happens to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Dahlberg and Franklin are relatively close in age. Dahlberg is
59, and Franklin, 54. If Dahlberg serves through mandatory
retirement at 65, that would leave five years for Franklin to serve
until his own retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But Franklin could be a transitional figure in that role,
according to industry observers.
</P>
<P>
   A new crop of leaders is waiting in the wings, most notably Tom
Boren, 49, president of Southern Energy Inc., which oversees
Southern's growing unregulated businesses inside the United States
and in Europe, Asia and South America. Those operations have just
taken off in the last several years.
</P>
<P>
   Southern projects that the unregulated businesses overseen by
Boren will account for 30 percent of the company's profits by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   But Boren's future prospects could depend on the continued
success of ventures that are inherently more risky than the
regulated utilities that will no doubt continue to account for most
of Southern's profits.
</P>
<P>
   Boren was promoted Wednesday to the additional title of Southern
executive vice president, and it was made clear he will continue to
report directly to Dahlberg, not Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   Other up-and-comers include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ratcliffe, 50, whose new job at the helm of Georgia Power is a
traditional steppingstone.
</P>
<P>
   _ G. Edison Holland, 46, president of Savannah Electric.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dwight A. Evans, 50, president of Mississippi Power.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul J. DeNicola, 50, president of Southern Company Services,
the company's engineering arm.
</P>
<P>
   But Dahlberg said he has ``no idea'' who will succeed him.
``It's premature to think about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Southern's stock closed
Wednesday at $27.75, up 31 1/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
