A3799 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-BANKS20-COX     05-19 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-BANKS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Banks will be prepared, safe, industry officials say
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The safest place to keep your money during the early
days of 2000 won't be under your mattress or in that old shoe box
hidden in the back of the closet.
</P>
<P>
   It will be your bank.
</P>
<P>
   An overwhelming majority of the nation's banks and financial
institutions are prepared to handle business on and after Jan. 1,
2000, banking industry officials said during a news briefing on Y2K
readiness Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Spoth, deputy regional director of the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. in Atlanta, called Y2K preparedness a ``top
priority'' for the industry. He said the FDIC and other industry
groups have been working for years on plans to avoid major
disruptions in service. Since last March, every FDIC-insured
institution has been examined at least twice for Y2K compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give you an assurance that if your money is in a
FDIC-insured account, it is safe,'' he said. ``We do not expect
prolonged computer glitches that will prevent customers from
getting access to their money. There are few guarantees in life,
but the FDIC is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   By June 30, Spoth said, there will be a complete testing and
inspection of computer systems at FDIC-insured institutions. They
must have detailed contingency plans in place in the event of
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, preparations are ``right on track,'' said Steve
Bridges of the Georgia Department of Banking and Finance, which
oversees most of the state's financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   As of May 15, he added, no Georgia banks were found
unsatisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   But consumers must also do their part, the experts said,
including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Stay informed and read all the Y2K information your bank sends
you.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have questions, ask a bank official.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you bank online, make sure your computer is Y2K compliant.
Make records of your accounts on a backup disk.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have direct deposit, check with your employer about its
Y2K readiness.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep your bank statements and records of transactions.
</P>
<P>
   _ During the date change, take out as much cash as you would for
any holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be on the watch for scams and avoid giving out account
information over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
