<HEADER>
A3802 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-2TAKES-N     05-19 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER BOASTED OF TORTURING LOUIMA, WITNESS TESTIFIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take to move within 30 minutes.) 
(sw) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In surprise testimony that riveted jurors and
spectators, a police sergeant testified on Wednesday that the
officer accused of torturing Abner Louima boasted to him that he
had carried out the attack in a Brooklyn police station restroom.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant, Kenneth Wernick, said that Officer Justin A. Volpe
had taken him into the restroom and shown him a stick that Volpe
claimed he had rammed into Louima's rectum. Later, in another area
of the 70th Precinct station house in Brooklyn, Wernick said he
watched as Volpe pointed the stick at another officer's face and
said, ``Smell this. Smell this.''
</P>
<P>
   Wernick said Volpe then pointed the stick at him and demanded to
know if he could see feces on it. The sergeant testified in federal
District Court in Brooklyn that he saw nothing on the stick, which
he said was two to three feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Wernick's testimony, his first public account of the events, was
the most direct testimony yet linking Volpe to a reported act of
police torture that shocked the city.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking rapidly in loud tones, Wernick told of a conversation
with Volpe that took place after dawn on Aug. 9, 1997, shortly
after prosecutors say Louima was attacked with the stick by Volpe
while another officer on trial, Charles Schwarz, held him down.
</P>
<P>
   Louima, a 32-year-old Haitian immigrant, had been arrested in a
street melee outside a nightclub in the Flatbush section of
Brooklyn, and prosecutors say Volpe mistakenly thought Louima had
punched him in the disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   Wernick, who held the rank of officer at the time and is now
assigned to the Fifth Precinct in Manhattan, said the conversation
started with Volpe's telling him, ``I took a man down tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he took a stick and put it five or six inches'' into
Louima's rectum, Wernick testified, ``and took it out and put it by
his mouth and teeth area, kind of like he was showing it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant said Volpe continued his account by saying that he
had hit Louima on the genitals and that he had ``held his hand over
his mouth and told him if he told anybody, he'd kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You want to go into the bathroom and see the stick?'
'' the sergeant testified as Volpe, at the defense table,
alternated between watching him without expression, shaking his
head and writing in a notebook. Wernick said he last saw Volpe
holding the stick outside the station house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked outside by a large Dumpster and he held up the
stick,'' said Wernick, a burly, gray-haired man, holding up his
left arm to show how Volpe was holding the stick, as he sat on the
witness stand next to Judge Eugene H. Nickerson's bench. He did not
say what Volpe did at that point with the stick, which has never
been found.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked away,'' the sergeant continued. ``I didn't want to be
involved at any point.''
</P>
<P>
   But earlier in his account, when Alan Vinegrad, an assistant
U.S. attorney, asked the sergeant whether he had believed that
Volpe had committed the torture, the sergeant said he had not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Vinegrad asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, because I didn't think anybody would do it,''
Wernick replied. ``And if they did it, they wouldn't talk about
it.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
