A3804 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS &LR;      05-19 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPERS FLARE AS SENATE TABLES BILL TO PROVIDE MORE SCHOOL
COUNSELORS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate set aside a measure Wednesday that would
have funded the hiring of more school counselors in wake of school
violence in Littleton, Colo., as lawmakers worked to wrap up
consideration of a major juvenile-crime bill that includes
controversial gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   The vote of 61-38 to table the measure, offered by Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minn., followed an angry exchange between Wellstone
and Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, in which they
accused each other of not being serious about addressing school
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone's amendment, which called for spending up to $340
million to begin hiring thousands of school counselors in an
attempt to head off potential violence, drew an angry response from
Hatch, who accused his Minnesota colleague of offering the
amendment ``just to delay'' a final vote on the juvenile-crime
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, chief sponsor of the larger crime bill, also labeled the
Wellstone measure as little more than an attempt to ``throw money''
at a problem that can't be addressed properly by simply hiring more
counselors to deal with troubled youth in the nation's public
school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I resent the accusation that this is taking up time and
delaying this bill,'' Wellstone bristled. He went on to accuse
Hatch of being unwilling to address the problem of troubled youth
who may not have access to qualified counselors in their schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to be lectured by the senator from Minnesota
whose answer to everything is to throw money at it,'' Hatch shot
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very relevant to what we need to do to help kids
before they get into trouble,'' Wellstone continued. ``I'm
surprised that with all (Hatch's) good work (on other issues
related to helping troubled children) that he doesn't understand
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange, which verged on a shouting match between the two,
illustrated just how tense the debate over juvenile crime, and
especially gun-control issues, has become in the Senate as
lawmakers try to address the public outrage over the shooting and
bombing incident at Columbine High School last month that left 14
students and one teacher dead.
</P>
<P>
   The debate on gun-control matters also continued Wednesday as
Democrats sought to force a vote on an amendment that would close
what they contend are loopholes in a Republican bill passed last
week. That bill called for some buyer background checks at gun
shows. Democrats contend that the bill, which limits the check to
24 hours, really amounts to no check at all, and would allow
criminals to purchase guns on Saturday and pick them up on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a gun show on Saturday and you only have a 24-hour
check, guess what? There's no check at all,'' Sen. Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y., told his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said the Republican amendment adopted last week
resembled ``an elaborate Kabuki dance to make it look we're doing
something'' on gun control ``when we're really not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic amendment would extend the waiting period on guns
bought at gun shows and pawnshops to at least three days.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., and other opponents argued that
the proposal would allow the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms to impose a records-check fee on gun purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the amendment is expected today or Friday if senators
hold to an agreement to limit debate on other measures.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bickering over gun control and the Wellstone
measure, the senators did agree by voice vote to create a national
Commission on Character Development to study the impact of cultural
influences on violence.
</P>
<P>
   The commission will be made up of 36 members, whose job it will
be to present Congress with a list of recommendations in two years
that could lead to legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The measure creating the commission was sponsored by Republicans
who have been trying to turn the focus of the juvenile crime bill
away from gun control to questions about the impact of cultural
influences on youth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
