<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3805 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-COMMENT-BO     05-19 1507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR BRUINS MANAGEMENT TO REVIEW ITS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not all about Jason Allison and Dmitri Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   It's not all about the lack of moves in the front office and the
stranglehold on the payroll purse strings.
</P>
<P>
   It's not all about a team that appeared to lose the message the
coach was preaching, too often stood around like so many deer
caught in the headlights, allowing the Sabres to run over them.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Bruins closed shop Tuesday night because of all
those things, and for the next five months we get to see how, or
if, Mssrs. Harry Sinden and Mike O'Connell respond to all of it.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden immediately and predictably opened up the blame game
after the 3-2 loss in Buffalo, putting the finger on Allison and
Khrisitch for their postseason shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   He was right to the point.
</P>
<P>
   But he was right, only to a point.
</P>
<P>
   Khristich was abysmal, from the opening faceoff of Round 1. The
irony in Sinden's late-night lambasting is that it was Sinden who
telephoned Pat Burns, according to the coach, and encouraged him to
keep Khristich in the lineup when some in the media _ including
your faithful correspondent _ opined that Khristich should be given
the hook early in Round 1. Khristich not only kept his job, but he
was temporarily reunited with Allison as his center and Sergei
Samsonov on the other wing. He remained an empty sweater.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the stats show, no matter what he says,
Khristich's performance was indifferent and a debilitating drag on
the team as a whole. He showed some interest in contributing
defensively, but he was a non-factor when it came to making plays,
fighting for the puck (puleeeez), or even shooting. Sinden's torch
job guarantees that Khristich's 29 goals can be deleted from next
season's roster.
</P>
<P>
   The bet here: they'll trade Khristich's negotiating rights, even
prior to an arbitration hearing. The nightmare only could grow
worse if an arbitrator awarded him, say, $3 million _ a bump of
more than $1 million over his 1998-99 pay. What club would want him
then? The Bruins would be in the position of letting him go for
nothing _ exercising walkaway free agency _ and then they'd have
lost an asset, admittedly a dwindling asset, for nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   As for Allison, his postseason was a disappointment. He by no
means took a step toward becoming Boston's Bryan Trottier or Mark
Messier, the knighted center in charge of the offense. But he did
have a bothersome wrist (a lingering injury from late in the
regular season) and he also had, at various times over 12 playoff
games, Khristich as one of his wingers. When Allison was at his
best this season, it was typically when Khristich looked as if he
cared to play, got involved, became a factor.
</P>
<P>
   How effective could Allison be with Khristich in hibernation and
the diminutive Samsonov essentially his only wingman? To find that
answer, go try hanging a laundered shirt on the clothesline,
without using your hands. Like the results?
</P>
<P>
   Turning both Khristich and Allison into the sacrificial lambs is
a deceptive slaughter. To repeat what we've said here a number of
times: there just aren't enough bodies to get the job done. And
that's OK. This is a team that went rotten in the patch only two
years ago for all the reasons we've stated before: bad trades; the
failure to pay some roster players who became free agents;
unfortunate injuries; loading up with old guys; replacing `B'
players who commanded `A' money with `C' and `D' players who
commanded `D' and `F' money (i.e. cashiering Shawn McEachern for
Trent McCleary).
</P>
<P>
   To recover from that mess and get in the playoffs last season
was very impressive. To win a round this year was another important
building block. Five years after winning their last series, it
provided some of the players, the majority of whom weren't here in
'94, with some validation. Ditto for the fans, who never stop the
crusade down Causeway, no matter where the team finishes. Bruins
fans deserve their pavilion in the Fans Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Did anyone truly expect the Bruins, as presently constituted, to
make it to the Eastern Conference championships this spring? If so,
they weren't realistic in their roster-wide assessment of talent.
For instance, Allison could have had a great series and there still
probably wouldn't have been enough to move to the next round. It
wasn't like the Joe Thornton line took charge. And the Rob
DiMaio-Tim Taylor-P.J. Axelsson line is a gritty, courageous trio,
but checking lines alone don't win championships, they provide a
base for the bigger, more talented lines to get the work done.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden and O'Connell will be forced to spend this summer,
especially to keep Byron Dafoe, who will come in asking a minimum
of $3 million-plus a season. Taylor can walk as an unrestricted
free agent and, as such, likely will command a three-year deal
worth upwards of $5 million. If the franchise learned anything from
letting Dave Poulin and, to a lesser extent, Dave Reid get away,
then Taylor will get the dough. If not, he'll be somewhere else by
mid-July. The bet here: he'll take a hometown discount worth
slightly below $4 million over three years.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond spending to keep the necessary parts intact, Sinden and
O'Connell have to add to the depth up front and in back. This is a
team that is at least four legitimate NHLers away from getting real
in the playoffs. Perhaps one will come from college or the minors.
Maybe they can deal for another. On top of that, they should spend
to bring in some free agents, something they steadfastly refused to
do last summer and again at the March trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Management's refusal to beef up the lineup, via trades or
free-agent acquisitions, was equally as defeating as Allison's poor
showing. In fact, it was more defeating. To lambaste Allison for
the eventual collapse only underscores to the rest of the roster,
and anyone else who might consider coming here as a free agent,
that ultimately everything is the players' fault. Now there's a
vibrant workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most troubling of all in Round 2 was not the losing, per
se, but how the club lost. There were dead spots, not just in
talent, but in emotion. After a rousing Game 1 against the Sabres,
they came out with a stinker in Game 2. Two nights later, after two
strong periods, they again went dead in the third period, blew a
2-1 lead, and then played like emotionless zombies in Game 4.
Another rousing performance in Game 5 (at least for 40 minutes),
was followed by another near total dud in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that erraticism has to be traced to coaching. Either the
players weren't heeding Burns's message _ be it because they
stopped listening, they choked, or were just too beaten up _ or the
right message wasn't being sent. It could be a blend of all that.
The bet here: when the aches and pains began to suffocate them,
they stopped listening. Burns can be faulted for not finding a way
to fire them up, get them over the mental block, but a coach has
only so many tricks, so many devices. He teased it out of them for
Game 5. Two nights later, they looked and played as if beyond his
reach.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting, Scott Bowman's quote Wednesday in USA Today, after
his Red Wings were eliminated by the Avalanche Tuesday night: ``A
coach can't hide behind the fact that some players didn't play as
well as they could have because that's his job (to motivate
them).''
</P>
<P>
   If this group has stopped listening to Burns, we won't know that
until next season. By then, of course, there undoubtedly will be a
mix of some 30 percent new faces in the lineup, most everyone will
be healed, and he'll have a chance to recapture and take command.
For whatever reason, they didn't respond to him the last two weeks
the way they did over the last month of the regular season and the
first round of the postseason. They lost their pluck. Burns
couldn't get them to regain it.
</P>
<P>
   Did any other Bruin play like Ray Bourque, with his passion, his
will to win, his steadfast refusal to retaliate to some awful cheap
shots? Of course not. To ask anyone to play like Bourque, which is
what Sinden asked, is not realistic. It's unfair to Bourque and
unfair to his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque is a Hall of Famer, and there are very few of those, and
fewer all the time in this era that emphasizes skill and point
production over the basic courage it takes to play the game. The
day he retires, perhaps a year from now, it would be only fitting
that Bourque gets his own parade through the city's streets, a
Stanley Cup-like parade for someone who so richly deserves to have
his name on hockey's greatest team honor.
</P>
<P>
   When Sinden and O'Connell begin to perform their jobs the way
Bourque performs his _ in constant pursuit of perfection, never
putting the knock on management, the coaching staff, teammates, or
media _ then Boston once more truly will be the Hub of Hockey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3806 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRICE-FIXING-620&AMP;ADD-     05-19 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRICE-FIXING-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT IS REPORTEDLY NEAR IN VITAMIN PRICE-FIXING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Justice Department is expected to announce shortly that at
least two of the world's largest drug and chemical companies have
agreed to pay as much as $700 million to settle criminal charges
that they participated in a global conspiracy to fix prices in the
sale of vitamins, according to people close to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In what would be the largest settlement ever in a federal
anti-trust case, Roche Holding A.G. of Switzerland and BASF A.G. of
Germany are expected to plead guilty to charges that they were part
of a global conspiracy to set prices and divide up the world market
in animal and human vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   While the negotiations with the government could break down,
people close to the negotiations said that the case is expected to
be resolved as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Roche Holdings is expected to pay as much as $500 million to
settle the case and BASF is expected to pay about $200 million,
according to people who have been briefed on the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Rhone-Poulenc of France has been under investigation but is not
expected to be fined, partly because executives there are
cooperating with federal investigators, people close to the
negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman at the Justice Department refused to comment
Wednesday on the prospect of an upcoming settlement. And
spokespersons for the three companies would only say that they are
cooperating with federal investigators and seeking to resolve the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We refuse to confirm or deny any speculation regarding a
settlement,'' said John Gilardi, a spokesman at BASF in Germany.
``We are cooperating with the Justice Department investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Roche and Rhone-Poulenc issued similar statements.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in Dallas has been probing price-fixing
allegations in the vitamin market for more than a year and criminal
indictments are expected to be handed up as soon as Thursday,
according to people close to the settlement. Several executives
could also be charged.
</P>
<P>
   A number of class-action lawsuits have also been filed against
the European companies, alleging that over the past decade,
executives at the three largest vitamin manufacturers _ Roche, BASF
and Rhone-Poulenc _ and several smaller manufacturers and vitamin
blenders, met secretly and agreed to fix prices and carve up
territories in the United States and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Silver, an attorney at Boies &AMP; Schiller in Armonk, N.Y.,
said his firm filed one of the earliest class-action suits in 1998,
and then filed several more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawsuits have alleged illegal conduct by an international
cartel that deliberately targeted and severely burdened consumers
in the United States,'' he said in an interview yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not a settlement takes place, federal prosecutors and
a number of class-action lawsuits have charged a massive global
conspiracy that involved fixing prices of the sale of such common
vitamins as vitamin A, C and E, as well as niacin and other B
complex vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   The cases involve everyday vitamins that are sold in
supermarkets and drugstores as well as the bulk sale of vitamins
that are fed to animals to produce a leaner and more healthy stock.
</P>
<P>
   The federal investigation into collusion in the vitamin market
is considered one of the most important anti-trust cases under
review by the Justice Department. Just months ago, Joel I. Klein,
the assistant attorney general in charge of the anti-trust
division, said: ``Our investigation into worldwide conspiracies
involving vitamins is continuing. Those conspiracies have affected
billions of dollars of commerce in products found in nearly every
American household.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last March, Lonza AG, a Swiss vitamin manufacturer, and five
executives at other companies pleaded guilty to price-fixing in the
vitamin market and agreed to cooperate with the Justice Department
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Lonza, a much smaller player that specializes in B-complex
vitamins, agreed to pay $10.5 million to settle price-fixing
charges brought by the anti-trust division of the Justice
Department. In that case, the government alleged that between 1992
and 1998, Lonza officials met and exchanged sales and customer
information and colluded to set prices for vitamins in the
B-complex group.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, executives at Chinook Group, a Canadian
company and DuCoa, a company formed as a joint venture between
Dupont and Conagra, pleaded guilty to charges that they conspired
to fix the prices of animal and human vitamins and divided up
markets in the U.S. and elsewhere. Those executives could be hit
with fines of at least $350,000 and a maximum of three years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Departments crackdown on the international
conspiracy involving vitamins is part of a larger sweep that
involves collusion among a number of huge global companies.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, Hoechst AG, the German drug maker, pleaded guilty to
conspiring to fix prices in the food preservatives market. The
company agreed to pay a fine of $36 million. And in that same
month, the Justice Department settled the largest anti-trust action
in U.S. history when SGL Carbon of Germany agreed to pay $145
million to settle charges that it fixed prices in the sale of
graphite electrodes, which are used in the manufacturing of steel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
