<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACE OPPONENT LEAVES POLITICS, AIDING BARAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The politician considered the one truly principled
opponent of peace with the Palestinians suddenly stepped out of
public life Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Calling himself ``a cantor without a congregation,'' the
politician, Benny Begin, the ultranationalist son of the late
Menachem Begin, announced that he is quitting politics forever. His
no-concession National Union Party won just four seats in
parliament in Monday's election.
</P>
<P>
   Known as much for impolitic honesty as for his Bible-based
advocacy of Israeli sovereignty in the West Bank, Begin said he
would relinquish his own parliamentary seat and sever ties with the
party he founded. Few doubt his word.
</P>
<P>
   Though essentially symbolic, the public surrender of the chief
protest candidate of the far right would seem to bode well for the
newly elected prime minister, Ehud Barak, and his effort to
assemble a broad coalition committed to a negotiated peace with
both the Palestinians and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Barak still faces the basic paradox that has bedeviled prime
ministers here for a generation: To win support for peace accords
that permanently reshape Israel's borders, he must assemble as wide
a coalition as possible. But in stretching the boundaries of
government from the devoutly religious to the zealously secular, he
constrains his ability to make tough but essential policy choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is for a broad government, which means the politics of
inclusion,'' one of Barak's associates commented Wednesday night.
`` `Anyone is welcome, as long as they play by my rules.' But he is
not going to the lowest common denominator.''
</P>
<P>
   The suddenly altered demographics of Israeli politics make
coalition-building much easier.
</P>
<P>
   In final election results released Wednesday evening, parties at
least nominally supporting the basic outlines of the 1993 Oslo
land-for-security plan claimed all but 18 of the 120 seats in
parliament. The only declared opponents are Begin's party, two
Orthodox religious parties and a new Russian immigrant faction led
by Avigdor Lieberman, who once proclaimed that ``the only thing to
my right is a wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the anchors of the former coalition of Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu _ the ailing Likud, down to 19 seats from its
previous 34, and the giddily ascendant Shas, up to 17 from 10 _ are
officially committed to Israel's treaty promises.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, though dominated by ultra-Orthodox rabbis and often
associated with the hard right, has called for a swift withdrawal
from Lebanon and supported land-for-security tradeoffs in the West
Bank. Ultimately, as a party devoted to the craft of political
patronage, Shas is thoroughly domestic in its concerns, and largely
nonideological in its approach to security policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Shas' obsessive quest for control of local budgets and
constituent services, as well as the jailing of its leader for
corruption, could make Shas a problematic ally.
</P>
<P>
   The defeated Likud remains Barak's most important potential
partner on the right. Support from Likud for painful territorial
concessions _ the surrender of the Golan Heights to Syria, or the
turnover of small Jewish settlements to Palestinian control _ would
leave only a small religious-based minority as the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But with Netanyahu's abrupt resignation as party leader on
Monday night, it is uncertain where Likud now stands. Aspirants to
succeed him include Meir Sheetrit, the finance minister and
self-proclaimed peace advocate, and Ehud Olmert, Jerusalem's
ambitious mayor, who has infuriated Palestinians by accelerating
Jewish home building in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The ascendance on Tuesday of Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon as
Likud's caretaker leader does little to clarify Likud's direction.
The champion of Jewish settlements in the West Bank and architect
of Israel's ``security zone'' across the border in Lebanon, Sharon
is nonetheless both pragmatic and covetous of continued authority.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has pledged to withdraw Israeli troops from Lebanon within
a year, and to proceed quickly with the stalled withdrawals from
the West Bank. Then he must proceed with the highly charged issues
of the Golan Heights and the political contours of a Palestinian
state. Aides acknowledge that it will be difficult for the new
government to follow both paths simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, a Lebanon withdrawal presents the fewest
difficulties. Israelis across the political spectrum are anxious to
end a two-decade military engagement that produces steady
casualties but few tangible security gains. In Barak's first early
morning speech after his election victory on Monday, it was his
promise to get out of Lebanon that elicited by far the most
enthusiastic response.
</P>
<P>
   If he so chose, Barak could quickly form a core 54-seat
coalition of five centrist and leftist secular Jewish parties: his
own One Israel movement, with 26 members of Parliament; Meretz,
with 10, and three parties with six seats each: Yitzhak Mordechai's
Center Party, Natan Sharansky's Yisrael B'Aliyah and the fiercely
anticlerical Shinui faction. The addition of a two-seat breakaway
Labor faction and three small Arab-dominated parties would give him
a solid 66-seat majority.
</P>
<P>
   But the desire to build a Jewish consensus in favor of any
permanent peace settlement could exclude the Arab bloc, analysts
say. Right-wing Israelis would find any peace plan endorsed by
Arabs inherently suspect, while Israeli Arab leaders would come
under intense constituent pressure to bolt a government that
refused to compromise on Palestinian claims on East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are big issues, and to deal with them as a society we
need a government of national unity, with both Likud and Labor,''
Sharansky said before the election. ``We need to build bridges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
