<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS CRITICIZE RENO FOR MISMANAGING CHINA ESPIONAGE CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators at a closed-door hearing of the
Intelligence Committee Wednesday lashed out at Attorney General
Janet Reno for what they said was her failure to aggressively
manage the case of a suspected spy for China at the Los Alamos
nuclear weapons, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are responsible,'' one senator angrily told Reno in what
the officials described as a hearing punctuated with acidic
exchanges with the witnesses, who included FBI Director Louis Freeh
and Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder.
</P>
<P>
   Several senators repeated their conclusion that the Justice
Department and the FBI botched the security inquiry into Wen Ho
Lee, a nuclear scientist who worked for more than two decades at
Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was fired from his job for violations of security rules, but
he has not been charged with any crime. His lawyer has issued a
lengthy statement in which he steadfastly denied allegations that
Lee spied for China.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said they still have no hard evidence
that Lee passed any classified information to China.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Sen. Richard C. Shelby, R-Ala., said the
committee was deeply disturbed by how the Justice Department and
the FBI handled the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the actions or inactions, on the part of the FBI and
the Justice Department, is dumbfounding to a lot of us, baffling,''
Shelby said. ``But we'll just continue our investigation. This is a
very important case.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno has said that the Justice Department will review whether
the department or FBI mishandled Lee's case. Law enforcement
officials said Wednesday that she is close to naming the staff for
the inquiry but has made little progress in re-examining the case.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, senators reviewed the Justice Department's
decisions in 1997 to twice reject a request by FBI
counterintelligence officials to seek a search warrant authorizing
more aggressive investigative techniques from a special court
established by the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act.
</P>
<P>
   That law allows federal agents to clandestinely conduct searches
of homes, offices and computers, or install electronic listening
and video devices trained on espionage suspects under rules that
are less restrictive than search warrants obtained in criminal
cases through the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico
have said the Justice Department's refusal to seek a FISA warrant
deterred them from invoking a policy that allowed them to
spot-check Lee's computer without any court authorization, fearing
it might taint any future case against him.
</P>
<P>
   But that chain of decision-making left federal authorities
ignorant for almost two years that Lee had routinely transferred
into an unclassified computer network millions of lines of secret
computer codes used in the development of advanced nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department rejected the FBI's request for a warrant
because it was dated, vague and lacked current evidence to provide
a basis for a reasonable suspicion that Lee was a spy, law
enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials later appealed the rejection to Reno in an
informal meeting in which a number of China-related issues were
discussed, but the subordinates who reconsidered the decision
affirmed the earlier rejection.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials subsequently tried to catch Lee in what
counterintelligence officials described as a ``false flag''
operation in which agents posing as foreigners tried to lure Lee
into spying. But Lee, officials said, did not take the bait.
</P>
<P>
   At the Justice Department, officials said the FBI managers did
not aggressively present the case for a warrant as a top
counterintelligence priority and were unwilling to deploy the large
number of agents that would have been required for full-time
surveillance that might have produced evidence to justify a FISA
warrant.
</P>
<P>
   But FBI officials said the Justice Department took the case
casually and failed to understand the difficulties in obtaining
concrete evidence in a case in which the suspected espionage may
have begun years earlier, before any investigation started.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, the failure to act could have a
significant impact. When agents finally opened Lee's office
computer earlier this year, they discovered that he had transferred
files from 1983 through 1995, and officials have said there is
evidence that someone else examined the files once they were in the
unclassified system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
