</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET POLITICAL DONATIONS MAY QUALIFY FOR MATCHING FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Responding to burgeoning political activity on the
Internet, the Federal Election Commission on Thursday is expected
to bring presidential fund raising into the age of electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC is very likely to change its rules to allow political
contributions by credit card to qualify for federal matching
campaign funds, two commission members said in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the presidential contenders in 2000 have their own Web
sites, and many are using the Internet to solicit campaign
contributions paid by credit card. But so far, the FEC has allowed
matching money only for donations by check or other ``written
instruments'' because of concerns over fraud.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Democratic candidate Bill Bradley asked the commission
to expand the matching funds, which come from checkoffs on
taxpayers' returns, to online credit card contributions.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the commission, Robert Bauer, the Bradley
campaign's general counsel, argued that online donations ``broaden
the base of financial support for presidential campaigns and
encourage renewed public confidence in American democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign started its Web site Dec. 4 and a campaign
spokesman said it had received $30,000 in online pledges and had
enlisted nearly 15,000 volunteers. The campaign has hired its own
Internet consultant, Lynn Reed.
</P>
<P>
   The first $250 of each individual contribution to presidential
candidates is matched with taxpayers' money as long as candidates
adhere to the federal spending limits. In 2000, candidates who
abide by the spending ceiling of about $40 million in the primary
will be eligible for up to $16.8 million in matching federal money.
</P>
<P>
   Some FEC officials have been concerned that credit card
donations do not have the same level of documentation or security
as checks, the two commissioners said, but these reservations gave
way to a desire to encourage Internet political activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, I don't think we ought to put barriers in
the way of the use of the Internet for political contributions
unless there's a compelling reason to do so,'' said David Mason, a
Republican who serves on the six-member commission, which is evenly
divided along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Sandstrom, a Democratic commissioner, said that ``advances
in technology'' had made online credit-card transactions secure
enough to satisfy the agency's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The expected approval of matching funds for online credit card
donations is being watched by the presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``2000 will be a groundbreaking year for Internet campaigning,''
said Juleanna Glover, press secretary for Republican candidate
Steve Forbes. ``The Internet will be to the 2000 election what
television was to the Nixon-Kennedy election.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Glover said the Forbes campaign, which has had more than
400,000 visitors to its Web site, had relied heavily on the
Internet to recruit volunteers and for small donations. Forbes does
not plan to apply for federal matching funds so he will not be
affected by the commission's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC plans to review an array of Internet issues, the two
commissioners said, but decided to act first on the matching-funds
question because of the greater urgency. Other areas under review
are how and whether to value as political contributions the Web
sites operated by individuals that carry a candidate's messages and
Web links that connect voters from one Web site to a candidate's
site.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said it would be impractical for the commission to try to
broadly police the Internet. ``It's the frontier, the political
equivalent of the Wild West,'' he said. ``The commission ought to
stand back and learn a little more about what this medium looks
like before it begins to introduce new restrictions and create
broad policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Most campaigns update their Web sites daily and include video
snippets and text of the candidates' speeches and other political
news. Elizabeth Dole's site also offers revolving snapshots,
including one from her wedding day, as well as a memorial to
Leader, the Dole dog who died Feb. 28. The Dole campaign says it
has enlisted over 5,000 volunteers on its Web site and taken in
over $50,000 in pledges.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia Lundberg of Portland, Ore., gave $1,000, the maximum
allowed, to the campaign through the Dole Web site. ``The campaign
site provides a great way to get information without waiting to
watch the news,'' Ms. Lundberg said, ``and on my own time.''
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates are also raising money on the Web, although it
is still a small fraction of their fund raising over all. The Gore
campaign, which has raised more than $9 million, has drawn $17,000
in online pledges.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the presidential nominees both had Internet sites but
they were mainly bulletin boards containing basic biographical and
campaign information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
