<HEADER>
A3819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBOUR-LOBBY-NYT &LR;      05-19 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBOUR-LOBBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURSING HOME LOBBYIST FIGHTS MEDICARE CUTS HE PUSHED AS GOP CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Iowa, Calif., N.M., Ky., Ga., Ark., Ohio, Pa.)   (bl)  
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Republican national chairman, Haley Barbour
designed his party's campaign to cut the growth of Medicare. Now he
has taken on a new assignment. As a lobbyist for a dozen large
nursing home companies, he pleads with Congress for relief from the
law he helped write.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995-96, Barbour told anyone who would listen that Medicare's
explosive growth threatened to bankrupt the program. He worked hand
in glove with House Speaker Newt Gingrich on legislation to rein in
Medicare spending. Now he complains that Medicare is spending too
little.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underspending by Medicare for skilled nursing homes is having
serious effects in the real world,'' Barbour said in an interview
Wednesday. ``Close to 20,000 caregivers have been laid off. There's
concern that nursing homes will close. It's resulting in harm to
senior citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   People outside Washington might see some inconsistency between
Barbour's earlier support for Medicare cutbacks and his work as a
lobbyist now. But his advocacy raises few eyebrows in the capital,
where dozens of people pass through the revolving door between
government and industry every year, where politicians do battle by
day but share cozy dinners in the evening, where legislators can
switch their votes overnight because of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other recent chairman of the Republican National
Committee, however, Barbour shaped the party's agenda, and
influenced legislation, through frequent meetings with Republican
leaders on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour, whose four-year term as chairman ended in January 1997,
said Wednesday that he was retained by his nursing home clients in
April and had since discussed their problems with about 15 members
of Congress, mostly Republican senators.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Clinton administration could take steps of its own
to relieve the burden on nursing homes, without waiting for
Congress to act. But he has not talked to administration officials.
As a rock-ribbed Republican, he said, ``I'm probably not the best
person for that assignment.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., who served in the House for 20
years, said he was lobbying the administration on behalf of the
same group of nursing homes as Barbour.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour has not yet filed the required forms with Congress to
disclose the amount spent lobbying for nursing homes on Capitol
Hill. Asked how much he was being paid, he said, ``Not enough,''
and laughed.
</P>
<P>
   He confirmed that his clients included the Sun Healthcare Group
of Albuquerque, N.M.; Vencor Inc. of Louisville, Ky.; the Mariner
Post-Acute Network Inc. of Atlanta; Beverly Enterprises of Fort
Smith, Ark.; HCR Manor Care Inc. of Toledo, Ohio; Genesis Health
Ventures of Kennett Square, Pa., and Extendicare Inc. of Markham,
Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour said he saw no contradiction between his old and new
roles. The Medicare cuts, he said, have been much deeper than
either he or Congress expected under the entirely new method of
reimbursement established by the 1997 law. In the first half of the
current fiscal year, he noted, Medicare actually spent less than in
the first half of the prior year. In the last week, three of
Barbour's clients have reported quarterly losses, due in large
part, they say, to the Medicare cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's ironic,'' Barbour said, ``is that this administration
is spending so much less on Medicare than Congress intended when it
passed the Balanced Budget Act of 1997. It's the same
administration that in 1995 and 1996 constantly clobbered
Republicans'' for proposing Medicare cuts that have proved to be
less severe than those that have actually occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The nursing home industry has long been a potent force in
Washington and many state capitals. Alan Solomont, former finance
chairman of the Democratic National Committee, was chief executive
of the largest nursing home company in Massachusetts and just last
month was host at a Democratic fund-raiser attended by President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's political action committee, the American Health
Care Association PAC, made campaign contributions of more than
$900,000 in 1997-98, according to data filed with the Federal
Election Commission and tabulated by Public Disclosure Inc., a
nonpartisan research group.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour, a seventh-generation Mississippian, has been in and
around Washington since 1985, when he became director of the White
House office of political affairs under President Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   He blends his political insights with an exceptionally detailed
knowledge of health care policy. Like a true policy expert, he
refers to sicker people as ``high acuity patients,'' meaning that
they have acute illnesses. And he speaks knowledgeably of RUGs, the
``resource utilization groups'' into which patients are classified
according to their medical condition and need for care.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour suggests two specific ways to relieve the financial
distress of nursing homes: Medicare, he says, should provide a more
generous allowance for inflation, based on the market basket of
goods and services used by nursing homes. In addition, he says, it
should increase its payments for sicker patients.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour estimated that his clients were receiving an average of
$270 to $285 a day for each Medicare patient. By contrast, he said,
when the budget law was signed in 1997, nursing homes had been
getting $360 a day or more for each Medicare patient, and expected
to get $310 to $320 a day in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, chairman of the Senate Special
Committee on Aging, met recently with Barbour and has requested
more financial data. Before rushing to bail out any companies with
taxpayers' money, Grassley said, he wants to know whether they have
been mismanaged, whether they grew ``too large too fast'' and
whether they took on more debt than they could handle.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, he said, they must not solve their problems by
evicting patients or reducing the quality of care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
