<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DESERTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS OF YUGOSLAV TROOPS DESERT, SAYS NATO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Hundreds of Yugoslav soldiers deserted their
brigade in Kosovo on Tuesday, defying their officers and fighting
through a military checkpoint to return to their homes in Krusevac,
to the north, NATO officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers, mostly reservists from the 7th Infantry Brigade in
Istok, hurried back to Krusevac after hearing from radio broadcasts
that police there were suppressing anti-war protests by women and
children in the village, the allied officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said
``battalion-level units'' were leaving their posts in Kosovo. He
cited intelligence reports, but provided no specific evidence of
widespread desertions. He also dismissed speculation that what
NATO's analysts saw as desertions may be withdrawals of the
Yugoslav military or police units.
</P>
<P>
   The allies' account of desertion was one of a series of
anecdotes that NATO has circulated to suggest that the air campaign
has had a devastating effect on the morale of President Slobodan
Milosevic's forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the allied military commander, has said of
Milosevic: ``We're winning. He's losing. He knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, NATO has not met its principal goal: to force
Milosevic to withdraw his troops from Kosovo. The same troops that
expelled more than 800,000 ethnic Albanians from Kosovo are now
digging in to block a possible allied invasion force, according to
military analysts here.
</P>
<P>
   And the conscripts who bolted from Istok represent only a
fraction of the 40,000-member force in Kosovo, and are not
front-line troops. Allied intelligence officials offered no other
specific examples of mass desertions, despite NATO leaflets,
intended for dropping over Yugoslavia, that assert 13,000 have
deserted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
