<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYCHEM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Raychem Selling for $2.87 Billion
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Henry Norr &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Raychem Corp., a Menlo Park electronics manufacturer that employs
some 3,000 people in the Bay Area, will be acquired by Tyco
International Ltd. for $2.87 billion in cash and stock, the two
companies said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco, an industrial conglomerate that expects to have $22
billion in sales this year, is buying Raychem to strengthen its
position as a leading electronics supplier to the
telecommunications and automotive industries.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco has spent more than $25 billion in acquisitions in the past
two years. Just six weeks ago, it closed a $12.2 billion purchase
of AMP Inc., the world's leading manufacturer of electronic
connectors.
</P>
<P>
   Raychem will be incorporated into Tyco's Electrical and
Electronic Components division, the same organization AMP is now
part of. Raychem's products, such as its heat-shrinkable tubing,
are often used with AMP's connectors, according to Raychem
spokesman Scott Wylie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You end up with a broader, integrated product line, and we
know our customers like to deal with broad-gauge suppliers,'' Wylie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Raychem will continue to operate under its own name. The
company's chief executive, Richard Kashnow, will become a member of
Tyco's executive team and will remain responsible for Raychem's
operations, according to Wylie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some reduction in head-count as the companies
come together, but we just don't know the extent and nature of the
reductions yet,'' Wylie said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its executive team, the company's local staff
includes employees in manufacturing, research and development, and
sales and marketing. Worldwide, the company employs some 9,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   Raychem, founded in 1957, makes a variety of components sold to
other manufacturers. Products include fuses, wiring harnesses,
tubing and touch-screen terminals.
</P>
<P>
   In its last fiscal year, it recorded sales of nearly $1.8
billion, but net income dropped 46 percent to $131.5 million, a
decline company officials attributed primarily to economic
difficulties in Asia, Brazil, Russia and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco, which is headquartered in Hamilton, Bermuda, will pay an
estimated $2.87 billion for Raychem, based on Tuesday's May &LR; 
18 &LR; closing value of Tyco shares. The payment will consist of $1.4
billion in cash plus 16.1 million newly issued Tyco shares.
</P>
<P>
   The price amounts to $37 per share for Raychem, a 19 percent
premium relative to its closing price on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Raychem shareholders will be able to decide how much of their
payment will be in cash and how much in Tyco shares, within the
limits of the amounts Tyco has set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco shares closed yesterday at $93.50, up $4.13. Raychem
climbed $5.13 to $36.25.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is expected to close in about four months, Wylie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco is best known for its fire-protection systems and
electronic security systems, but its recent acquisitions have moved
it into such markets as medical products, plastics and adhesives,
as well as telecommunications. Tyco is No.1 in underwater
telecommunications systems. In a separate transaction yesterday,
Tyco also bought the undersea cable business of Telefonica SA,
Spain's largest phone company, for $280 million in cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2126EDT &QL; 
