<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3829 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-BROOKS-SPI &LR;      05-19 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BROOKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKEPTICAL TERRY BROOKS ENDED UP PLEASED WITH `STAR WARS'
NOVELIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ No, he didn't do it for the money.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Brooks makes much more money on his own books, including
his trademark ``Shannara'' series, than he was to be paid for the
novel based upon ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   And, no, he didn't do it for the sales.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks has had plenty of best sellers in the past, 14 in all
leading to overall sales of 12 million books, making him one of the
sure-bet successes among popular authors today.
</P>
<P>
   What ultimately convinced the 55-year-old West Seattle writer to
turn someone else's movie script into a novel, even though that
someone else was George Lucas, was the thought of who would be
offended and what might happen if he turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Star Wars' project was first proposed to me when I was on
the phone in a shopping mall with a bunch of children passing by,''
Brooks recalled this week, ``and I immediately thought that if I
turn this down, I'll never be able to explain it to my own kids.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brooks still was intensely leery about the project. He had
done a novelization of Stephen Spielberg's Peter Pan adaptation,
``Hook.'' It had been such a nightmare that Brooks, a proud
craftsman at the writer's trade, repeatedly had told anyone who
would listen that he would not do such a thing ever again. There
simply was not enough money anywhere to compensate for that amount
of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   He had never met with Spielberg or even talked to him, for one
thing, and there were so many script changes throughout the project
that Brooks, a meticulous outliner of his work, felt as though he
were trying to build a novel on a foundation of quicksand.
</P>
<P>
   So Brooks arrived in Northern California at Lucas' Skywalker
Ranch in a state of profound skepticism, even if he felt some
kinship with Lucas since both ``Star Wars'' and ``The Sword of
Shannara'' had been released in 1977 and the two shared the same
book editor. Brooks kept reminding himself that he was fully
prepared to walk away from the new project at the slightest hint
that it might be ``Hook Revisited.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lucas' staffers charmed him with their relaxed approach,
their openness and the way they immediately treated him as a
colleague. A four-hour meeting with Lucas himself only cemented
Brooks' decision.
</P>
<P>
   Right off, the writer told the originator of ``Star Wars'' that
he might not be the right person for his book project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that I thought I was an odd choice,'' Brooks
remembered from that initial conversation. ``I said, `I'm not a
science fiction writer, so if that's what you're looking for,
you've got the wrong guy. I do not write science fiction, I write
adventure stories. If you want a good adventure story writer, then
you've got the right guy.' '
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' agreement with that helped ease Brooks' fears, as did
Lucas' assertion that he wanted a novel that expanded on the film
instead of merely fitting into a ``Phantom Menace'' straitjacket.
And Brooks was even more impressed after he challenged Lucas'
proposal that much of the story be told in flashbacks, saying that
would not be his approach, that it would be ``poor writing.'' Lucas
deferred to his judgment after some spirited give-and-take.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks did most of the writing in the third-floor office of his
spacious West Seattle home, an office with brimming bookshelves
(including such literary authors as Cormac McCarthy and Alice
Hoffman), several pieces of glass art, its own fireplace, several
pieces of Darth Vader memorabilia given him by his daughter, and a
dazzling panoramic view of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Writing has indeed been very good to the attorney-turned-writer,
who has another another home on the Big Island of Hawaii where he
and his wife, Judine, spend about three months a year.
</P>
<P>
   The film script was his Bible as Brooks began the outline of the
novel's chapters, a technique he considers absolutely crucial to
creating an appealing story with well-developed drama and
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outlining,'' Brooks emphasized, ``is the most important stuff,
the hard stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' editors were just a telephone call away, eager to provide
whatever Brooks needed to craft his version of the story. There was
also a CD-ROM with 6,000 images from the film that could be checked
whenever Brooks was describing a character or a scene and wanted to
ensure its accuracy, plus ``reams of paper'' setting forth names,
people, plants, planets, ships _ all the insider stuff that legions
of ``Star Wars'' fanatics would one day be committing to memory.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks started his story at a time earlier than in the film, in
order to give greater insight into the character of Anakin
Skywalker, the 9-year-old slave boy and expert pod racer destined
to become archvillain Darth Vader. The book, as Brooks envisioned
it, would unfold at a slower pace than the film, with more time
devoted to developing background and motivation. There was also the
chance to hint at some of the action to take place in the next two
``Star Wars'' films, within Lucas' limits.
</P>
<P>
   The real challenge for the writer, who was working under a
120-day deadline, came from within.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of book is so much easier than doing your own work
that you can find yourself thinking of it as a lesser thing,''
Brooks admitted. ``So there is also a tendency to want to slip over
things and get through it. I had to keep reminding myself to expand
</P>
<P>
   what's there in the script, to provide more depth and to not be
careless.''
</P>
<P>
   What Brooks ended up writing is a straight-ahead adventure story
cast toward the widest possible audience. His ``Phantom Menace''
(Del Rey/Lucas Books, 324 pages, $25) is a solid piece of
commercial fiction that moves smartly from scene to scene, with
crisp exchanges of dialogue and a minimum of descriptive
flourishes. It is a book that seems to follow the naval maxim,
``Steady as she goes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt I had anything to prove with this book,'' Brooks
related. ``I just wanted to do the best I could do, which is
exactly what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Where his ``Phantom Menace'' has gone in the two weeks since
publication is straight to the top of every fiction best-seller
list, much to the delight of Brooks, who has had more than a
half-dozen books claim the second spot, but never had one take the
top.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' novel has been helped by the clever marketing ploy of
having four separate covers with four different characters from the
film (all the better to ensure quadruple sales to collectors), plus
the unprecedented hype building up to Wednesday's release of the
film. Brooks, who has seen the original ``Star Wars'' a dozen
times, attributes the publicity juggernaut to the years that have
passed since the last ``Star Wars'' film, which has led many to
want ``to recapture the feeling they had back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, an amiable fellow with a distinct sense of humor, has no
delusions about the novel's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a reflection that I'm a great writer,'' he said.
``It's a reflection of the `Star Wars' craze.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer has seen that craze up close and it has left him more
than a little bemused. His appearance at a ``Star Wars'' festival
in Denver, along with some of the lesser characters from the film,
drew 40,000 people who waited in lines for five hours for the
chance to buy merchandise or secure autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks signed autographs for seven hours one day, with only a
45-minute break to give a presentation. He has long had his own
legions of fans who crowd his readings and signings, but Denver was
an out-of-this-world experience for the writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This instead was more like being a rock star,'' Brooks
stressed. ``It made you wonder how anybody with that level of
public attention can keep their sanity. Actually, I came away
understanding why those people often seem to go nuts. And if I had
been a new writer, instead of someone well-established, I'm sure I
would have gone nuts, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
