<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL HAS ITS OWN STAR POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pssst! You on the couch over there. You have the
glazed look of someone who has seen way too many Philly Men of
Hoops replays or Phantom Menace trailers. Put that remote control
down and listen up.
</P>
<P>
   May we be candid? You need to be raised right out of your rut
and maybe even your seat. We've got just the thing. It's a viewing
alternative to both Star Wars, the one conceptualized by George
Lucas as well as the one supervised by David Stern.
</P>
<P>
   What is it? Why, only one of the best-kept trade secrets around.
The Phantom Menace script has nothing on the NHL postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hockey League. Doesn't ring a bell, eh?
</P>
<P>
   A pity, that.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Cup hockey has been playing for a while in front of cult
audiences in the sporting equivalent of art houses. All but four
teams have been killed off, but if you tune in now you can get up
to speed on all the remaining characters and story lines before the
grand climax.
</P>
<P>
   As far as plots go, the NHL playoffs have shared quite a few
similarities with the NBA's mega-production that has, as usual,
monopolized the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   You have a retiring superstar to replace and, for the first time
in three years, the promise of a new champion. You have a
controlling coach named Pat, a team that has excelled with a
gallery of interchangeable shooters, a dignified veteran in search
of his first championship ring, an experienced squad that strangles
the life out of its opponents and a team that just may have the
Force with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Pat Riley of hockey is the Toronto Maple Leafs' Pat Quinn, a
one-time coach of the Los Angeles Kings who is in his first season
with his fourth franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs are the feel-good story of the playoffs, or
would be if the principal characters were more accessible. Hockey
players generally are as congenial as professional athletes come.
Indeed, to depict them any other way borders on blasphemy.
</P>
<P>
   Or did, anyway, before the cantankerous Quinn instituted
security measures that surely were inspired by a visit to
Buckingham Palace. Reporters wishing to talk to a player no longer
can count on catching them at their dressing room stalls. Their
best bet is to go through a team official, who will try to track
the player down.
</P>
<P>
   That's no sure thing, given that the Maple Leafs' new arena, the
Air Canada Centre, has more dressing room exits than there are
choices in the electronic scoreboard shell game.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs, with their swarming offense, are as exciting to
watch as the Lakers. Too bad they are infinitely less quotable.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto will play the Buffalo Sabres in the Eastern Conference
finals. The Sabres are the Portland Trail Blazers of the NHL. They
spread the puck around the way the Trail Blazers do the basketball.
Buffalo's leading scorer, Michael Peca, has 11 points in 10 games.
Who needs a sniper when you have the league's best player, Dominik
Hasek, in goal?
</P>
<P>
   Hasek plays as if he has no spine. The way he flops around,
you'd think he was another of Lucas' computer-generated creations,
a hybrid of Jar Jar Binks or something.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Boston veteran Ray Bourque plays his position by
the book. In his 20 years in the league he has penned the chapter
on offensive defensemen. Bourque, like the New York Knicks' Patrick
Ewing, is a proud warrior who has yet to bag the ultimate team
prize.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's title hopes remain alive but Bourque's dream was snuffed
out by Hasek and Co. in the Eastern Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The only No. 1 seed to advance to the Final Four is also the
NHL's biggest bore. The Dallas Stars play defense like the Utah
Jazz. They don't beat their opponents, they win by attrition.
</P>
<P>
   How tedious are we talking? Dallas defenseman Derian Hatcher
cheerily admits, ``We take 60-goal scorers and make them 30-goal
scorers.''
</P>
<P>
   If J.R. Reid vs. Tim Duncan is your idea of a matchup made in
heaven, you'll dig Dallas vs. the Colorado Avalanche in the Western
Conference final.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche's opening-round series against San Jose was
delayed a few days to afford the city of Denver time to mourn the
dead in the Columbine High shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado dedicated its postseason to the victims and their
families, then went out and let San Jose tie the best-of-seven
series at 2 with an ugly 7-3 loss just a few miles up the road from
Littleton, the site of the school tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, goaltender Patrick Roy, who is playing like it's 1993
(if you're unsure what that means, ask a Kings fan), shocked his
teammates with a tongue lashing that got their collective heart
beating again.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight games since then, the Avalanche has outscored San
Jose and two-time defending Stanley Cup champion Detroit 35-13.
That's a take off from the tenor of a postseason that has seen the
outcome of 32 of 68 games pivot on one goal.
</P>
<P>
   The television ratings for the NHL playoffs are better than last
year but still far, far away from great. Perhaps all those Star
Wars fans who've been waiting in line the past few weeks to see the
Phantom Menace will morph overnight into raw Stars aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh. What gives rise to a galaxy far, far away if not
the imagination?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
