<HEADER>
A3832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVARD-PORN-480&AMP;ADD-     05-19 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-PORN-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD OFFICIALS LINK EX-DIVINITY SCHOOL DEAN TO PORNOGRAPHY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., Mass.)   (rk) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ In a case that has raised questions of
privacy and propriety on the Harvard University campus, university
officials said Wednesday that the dean of the Divinity School was
forced to resign last fall because pornographic images had been
discovered on his university-owned computer.
</P>
<P>
   The dean, Ronald F. Thiemann, a nationally prominent theologian
who had established a Center for the Study of Values in Public Life
at the school, was asked to resign by President Neil L. Rudenstine
after several people saw the pornographic images on his computer,
said the officials, who spoke on the condition that they not be
named.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard announced his sudden departure at the time, but there
had been no explanation until The Boston Globe reported the
existence of the pornographic material Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard officials familiar with the case said Thiemann made
little effort to hide the material, sometimes leaving it on his
computer screen in his official residence. At one point, Thiemann
even asked the computer department for more disk space for his
computer and requested a university technician to transfer the
pornographic files to the new drive, the officials related.
</P>
<P>
   The Divinity School's rules prohibit the personal use of
university computers outside the school's educational mission and
specifically ban the ``introduction'' of material that is
``inappropriate, obscene, bigoted or abusive.'' Thiemann is
currently on leave and Harvard has taken no action to revoke his
tenured professorship.
</P>
<P>
   Thiemann's lawyer, Charles Ogletree, a professor at the Harvard
Law School, said he would have no comment on accusations made by
university officials unless they were quoted by name, and he said
that some of the accusations were incorrect. Ogletree declined to
elaborate on which charges were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Ogletree also said there were ``constitutional issues raised''
when an employer intruded on the private life of an employee.
</P>
<P>
   After he resigned on Nov. 13, several divinity school professors
said, Thiemann told them he had medical problems, including
depression. Harvard officials said Wednesday that when the
pornography was discovered, they were concerned that the episode
might be linked to emotional problems.
</P>
<P>
   During Thiemann's 13 years as dean, the Divinity School rose
from the second-class status it long held next to Harvard's more
prestigious medical, law and business schools. In his 13 years as
dean, the school's endowment almost quadrupled to $245 million from
$64 million.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations against Thiemann left the school in turmoil
Wednesday. The acting dean, J. Bryan Hehar, called three separate
meetings with the faculty, administrators and students.
</P>
<P>
   Professors at the Divinity School declined to return phone calls
Wednesday or said they were told to refer media calls to Harvard's
spokesman, Joe Wrinn, the director of the Harvard News Office.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Richard J. Wood, the dean of the Yale University Divinity
School, said the case was complex, because many people keep
personal items on their business computers. He also said the
pornography did not involve children and was not illegal.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas W. Ogletree, a professor of Christian ethics at the
Yale Divinity School and a former dean there, said pornography
presented an ambiguous problem. ``You have both the emphasis on the
freedom of private expression and the concern, especially by
feminists, that pornography exploits women or children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Smedes, a professor emeritus of Christian ethics at Fuller
Theological Seminary in Pasadena, Calif., was more critical. ``We
in the clergy agree that pornography in society is on balance evil,
a great evil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thiemann is an ordained Lutheran minister.
</P>
<P>
   Students at Harvard Divinity School seemed to be more lenient on
Thiemann.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Smith, 24 , a second-year student studying ethics and
philosophy, said: ``Even if he is a Divinity School dean or
professor, I think that Harvard's action is a little extreme. The
kind of moral policing that we're having in our society is really
getting out of hand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
