<HEADER>
A3837 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-GREENS-TEX     05-19 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GREENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WINNING POINTS WITH GREEN MOVEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A shift in Gov. George W. Bush's environmental
platform is winning cautious praise from environmentalists, but
pro-business groups are expressing puzzlement and alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the top GOP White House contender, recently changed to a
greener position on global warming and has moved closer to
environmentalists on the issue of getting certain industrial plants
to reduce pollution levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very positive,'' said Neil Carman, clean air
director for the Texas branch of the Sierra Club, a national
environmental group. ``But Bush's environmental track record _ you
know, he's running on empty.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, business groups say Bush was on the right
track before, when he said that science is still out on global
warming. A spokesman for the American Petroleum Institute, for
example, said the group was ``surprised'' by Bush's new stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has sent a bit of shock wave through the
community,'' said Peggy Venable, spokeswoman for Texas Citizens for
a Sound Economy, which has fought curbs on greenhouse gases. ``It
is a wake-up call that many of us need to visit with the governor.
...''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he changed positions after meeting with advisers who
agree there is ``some warming, but disagree about its cause and
impact.'' Asked what the state should do about global warming, he
said: ``I presume reducing (nitrogen oxides) and (carbon dioxides)
will help.'' Both are considered greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
   The governor did not say who advised him on global warming. But
the head of the New York-based Environmental Defense Fund met with
Bush in late March and the two discussed the issue, officials with
the organization said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked him to try to get the best scientific briefing he
could from a broad range of scientists and evaluate the evidence
for himself, and not to rely upon what third parties were telling
him,'' said Jim Marston, director of the Texas Environmental
Defense Fund branch.
</P>
<P>
   He characterized the meeting with the Environmental Defense
Fund's chief executive officer as part of Bush's effort to ``reach
out'' to various groups and industries as he ponders a run for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers have theorized that Bush is trying to enhance his
environmental record in anticipation of a presidential match-up
with Democratic Vice President Al Gore, who has made environmental
issues a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sidestepped a question about Gore at a news conference
Wednesday, although he said the environment should be a major issue
in 2000. He told reporters that people ought to ask whether he has
improved air quality in Texas. Bush called that his top ecological
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have got to ask the question: Is the air cleaner
since I became the governor? And the answer is yes,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say the answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   Tom ``Smitty'' Smith, head of the consumer group Public Citizen,
said the Environmental Protection Agency recently rejected the
state's clean-air program for North Texas. The EPA action marked
the first time that federal officials have threatened any Texas
area with economic penalties for Clean Air Act violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the whole, he's had a pretty dismal record,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith applauded Bush's efforts to limit the scope of a
proposed nuclear waste dump, and he praised the governor's support
of legislation that would reduce industrial pollution, though not
as much as environmentalists want.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Bush has endorsed a provision in the electric
utility restructuring bill that would require utility companies to
reduce emissions at ``grandfathered'' industrial plants, facilities
that have been exempt from modern clean-air laws for more than two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had earlier supported voluntary efforts to bring
grandfathered plants under modern clean-air rules.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
