<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3838 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-NEWS20-COX     05-19 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-NEWS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans survive wait for `Phantom Menace'
 &HT;    By Hank Stuever
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You wonder if they'll miss one another, now that
it's over.
</P>
<P>
   By sundown Tuesday, a sort of giddy calm radiated from the
asphalt. The people who waited (and waited, and then waited) in
line to be the first people in the first screening in the biggest
and loudest movie auditorium in town, had all (almost all) been
home for a shower. Some had applied red-and-black Darth Maul
makeup. One girl _ alas, just one _ had the Princess Leia 'do.
</P>
<P>
   In the remaining hours before the midnight unveiling of ``Star
Wars: Epis_'' (must we really type it out for you one more time?),
they were just happy to have lived to see the final moment.
Thunderstorms Monday night ripped away most of what was left of
Tent City on the north face of the Metropolitan cinema, a 14-screen
mammoth in South Austin that, for a time, was their home. Together
they survived it all: rain, heat, KFC chicken wings and even the
obnoxious morning deejays who came by to ``interview'' them, only
to poke fun at their love lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of friends,'' said Logan Campbell, 21, in a
reflective state of mind, a Darth Vader mask pushed up over his
forehead, while all around him plastic lightsaber duels playfully
unfolded. ``We made a lot of enemies, too.''
</P>
<P>
   There were tensions about who was really first in line, and who
saved who a place. There always were. Campbell was always exactly
second, having camped out at the Metropolitan since May 1. In front
of him were Mark Okun, 20, and Brian Couch, 20, but somehow, in
life's crazy shuffle, Couch wound up a few places back.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell and his friends know what you're thinking, because
they've heard it on TV and they read it in a newspaper editorial
and more than enough people have yelled it at them from passing
cars: Get a life.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell says it wasn't like they were all here 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   OK, yes it was, only they did it in shifts, all the while having
a life. They managed to finish classes, work at least one job, go
to Lamaze refresher courses, get to kids' soccer games, follow
Kosovo, get to dialysis appointments _ just for a few examples.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have lives _ nice lives,'' said Gloria Okun, 48, who
waited with her son and daughter toward the front of the line for
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday it was evident that ``Star Wars'' was going to be a
reality after all. Film canisters were delivered in the morning and
a crowd of Starwoids went running for the deliveryman, just to look
at them. ``I said, 'Oh no, no, no! Don't ruin the movie!''' Gloria
Okun said. Before noon, theater management handed out 150 ``seating
passes'' to ticket holders who wanted first choice of seats at the
12:01 show. By nightfall, your self-worth was determined by whether
or not you had the assistant manager's initials on the back of your
ticket, enabling you to be among the first 50 or so fans let in. By
now, a couple of thousand people were lined up and cordoned off by
police tape, ready for four different wee-hour showings. It felt
like the biggest moment of their lives _ something between a bowl
game, a rock concert, a wedding and a spiritual revival. ``No!
Sleep! Til! 'Star Wars'!'' the crowd chanted.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there had to be police, and naturally, they were
serenaded with ``The Imperial March'' by the crowd. A petite,
shrill-voiced female officer lined up the 12:01 crowd one by one.
Mark Okun rested on a cement ashtray at the first place in line.
``It's almost here,'' he said. TV cameras zoomed in on him, and he
self-consciously removed his broken wire-frame glasses, fully aware
of this fleeting fame.
</P>
<P>
   After an almost ceremonial ticket-tearing, Okun, Campbell and
their friends chose seats in the center of the back row. The entire
theater screamed at everything: They screamed when the lights went
down. They screamed at the THX logo. But as those familiar yellow
words traveled across a sea of stars, there was a churchlike hush.
Already it was the best movie they've ever seen, whether it really
was or not.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, Campbell said the movie was ``a little slow,''
but he said it in almost a whisper. He was already thinking about
getting on with a life. ``So now what?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
