<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3839 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-REACTIONS20-     05-19 2241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-REACTIONS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans' praise for `Menace' not universal, but close
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ We asked fans to call in with their own reviews,
and here's what some of you said:
</P>
<P>
   It's everything I expected and more! I was amazed at the
diversity of the crowd at the 12:01 a.m. show _ young and old, male
and female, long-time fans and newcomers, all left speechless for
much of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The special effects, action sequences and comedy will satisfy
those just looking to be entertained. Long-time fans will find new
characters to love (and fear!), familiar faces in different
settings, and new questions to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   I know my opinion as a ``Star Wars'' fanatic is biased (my
sister and I have seen the first movie so many times we stopped
counting), but I saw ``Episode I'' with a nonfan friend who enjoyed
it, too. Basically, I'm ready for ``Episode II'' now. In the
meantime, maybe I'll see this one a few more times
</P>
<P>
   _ Angela Mullins, Oxford
</P>
<P>
   I saw the first showing of ``The Phantom Menace'' at the
Beavercreek Cinemas last night. The movie has everything a movie
needs and more.
</P>
<P>
   It is a little slow at the beginning but hey _ all great sagas
need a beginning, and ``Phantom'' is the perfect way to begin the
``Star Wars'' Saga. I'll be sure to go again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, it's a movie the whole family can enjoy together.
And that is something hard to come by in the world today.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jason Streiff, Beavercreek
</P>
<P>
   I just returned from seeing the first showing at 12:01. The
experience of being at the theater waiting for the movie to start
was half the fun. All three networks had reporters there, there was
a myriad of people dressed up. An entire battalion of Storm
Troopers escorted Darth Vader through the theater, as various Jedi
and an abundance of Darth Maul lookalikes roamed freely and posed
for pictures. There was even a balloon guy making lightsabers, and
Darth Maul's double-bladed lightsaber staff out of balloons for
people.
</P>
<P>
   The movie itself was absolutely amazing. ``The Phantom Menace''
had me on the edge of my seat for two hours. The movie will answer
so many questions and start to explain many things leading into the
``Star Wars'' we all know, but it will also leave you asking many
more questions. There are some who will pick it apart and
concentrate on all the effects or how things were done. I do not
believe these people will enjoy the movie as much. Sit back, allow
yourself to once again be engulfed into the world George Lucas
captured us with so long ago, and this movie will be everything we
have waited 16 years for.
</P>
<P>
   _ Zak S. Blom, Ohio State University student from Springboro
</P>
<P>
   What can I say that won't be said countless times? Well, in a
word, stunning. Who knew from watching the trilogy that George
Lucas was capable of such beauty? From the sweeping vistas of the
desert planet Tatooine to the underwater splendor of the Gungan
city on Naboo, nearly every moment took my breath away. Plot,
characters and believability aside (all of which I found equally
wonderful), this movie will surely be hailed as one of the most
visually stunning ever created. Now don't get me wrong, the story
was exciting, the characters were interesting to say the least. But
I will always remember my first true glimpse into George Lucas'
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Anne Shininger, Wright State University student from
Oakwood
</P>
<P>
   In 1983 Virginia (my wife) and I practiced law together in the
old Cooper Building at Second and Main streets in downtown Dayton.
That spring when the ``Return of the Jedi'' premiered, we closed
the office for the afternoon, left our 7-month-old daughter Lilly
at day care and went to the opening day showing at the Dayton Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly never forgave us for leaving her behind in 1983, so in
1999 there was no way she was going to miss the first day showing
of ``Episode I.'' She worked Virginia and me until we gave in to
the 16 years of ```Star Wars' Guilt'' and purchased tickets for the
6 a.m. showing at Showcase Cinemas in Huber Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Our kids went to bed earlier than on Christmas Eve, and when the
alarm clock rang at 5 a.m., they were ready. Lilly and her friend,
Katie Lesko (both sophomores at Chaminade-Julienne High School) and
my sons, Frank (seventh grade) and Marty (third grade) and Eddie
(prekindergarten), who are Corpus Christi students, piled into the
van and we blasted off to witness ``Star Wars'' history.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of room at the showing with just a few
``in-costume'' customers. The kids and I rated the movie,
``Great!'' ``Awesome!'' ``Well worth missing school for!'' ``See
again, Daddy!'' Virginia gave it a ``Good but needing a Harrison
Ford/Han Solo-type character.''
</P>
<P>
   My vote for best scene of ``Episode I'' is when Jedi master
Qui-Gon Jinn (Liam Neeson) introduces the boy, Anakin Skywalker (to
become Darth Vader), to the young Jedi, Obi-Wan Kenobi (will train
Anakin and be struck down by Vader). Now that's spine-tingling
entertainment. No special effects needed for that scene.
</P>
<P>
   We have photos of our family together in front of the Silverdome
for the 1994 World Cup and in front of the Olympic torch in Atlanta
in 1996, and now we have a family photo in front of Showcase
Cinemas for the opening of ``Episode I.'' What more can a Jedi
want-to-be father do for his children? (My wife says, ``Maybe
college?'')
</P>
<P>
   May the force be with you.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Gehres, Dayton
</P>
<P>
   I saw ``The Phantom Menace'' at 12:30 a.m. at Showcase Cinemas
in Huber Heights. I suppose that qualifies me as a ``die-hard''
fan, so you may want to take my comments with a grain of salt.
</P>
<P>
   I have never before been to a movie where the audience
applauded. At the very beginning, when the previews were over and
``Star Wars'' blazed across the screen, the theater erupted. It was
a very intense moment. After all the hype, all the waiting, we were
finally about to have it all unfold in front of us.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard that the reviews for ``The Phantom Menace'' have been
generally bad. I think all the hype was probably a bad thing for
this movie. People are going in expecting it to be this complete
knock-your-socks-off classic, and it's not. It's just a movie. Were
any of the original ``Star Wars'' films any different? The appeal
is not in any one of the movies by itself, but in the whole overall
story. I think people have lost sight of that.
</P>
<P>
   That being said, I would have to say ``Episode I'' is hard to
judge without the context of ``Episodes II and III'' _ the story
isn't complete. However, taken as it is, I feel it is a highly
enjoyable movie. The visual effects are stunning. The lightsaber
duels with Darth Maul are unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointment may arise from the fact that the film moves a bit
slowly. It's supposed to move slowly. ``Episode I'' is mainly
back-story.... The whole story couldn't be told in just one movie.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good film. People just need to remember that it's a
movie, and nothing more. It's a good story, and more importantly,
it's the very beginnings of a great story. It's entertaining. Kids
will love it. It's fun, and that's the most important thing of all.
</P>
<P>
   There are disappointing things, to be sure. The character Jar
Jar is a little irritating to have such a large role in the
film.... I was personally disappointed that Darth Maul won't be
sticking around for at least one more movie.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, I think the disappointments can be overlooked.
More than anything else, the ``Star Wars'' saga is supposed to be
fun, and Episode I fits that requirement quite nicely.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jonathan Williams, Troy
</P>
<P>
   Attended the 12:30 a.m. showing in Centerville this morning. We
sat in the theater for over three hours waiting for the film to
begin. There were a few costumed characters, a lightsaber here and
there. A loud cheer erupted when the 20th Century Fox logo finally
flashed on the screen, followed by complete silence when the words
``A long time ago, in a galaxy far far away'' appeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace'' does not quite capture the magic of the
first three ``Star Wars'' films. The audience identification with
the characters is not as strong, some of the scenes with young
Anakin are awkward and some of the alien characters' dialogue is
difficult to follow. However, the film is visually stunning. The
beauty of the palaces and underwater cities of Naboo, the pod race,
numerous lightsaber fights, and the climatic battle droid battle
all are spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   I could feel that the audience really wanted the film to succeed
_ I initially gave it a ``7'' (on a scale of 10), but as I have
thought about it today it's now at least an ``8'' and I intend to
see it again!
</P>
<P>
   _ Wayne Mathieu, a baby boomer from Beavercreek
</P>
<P>
   I wrote a poem, because I was unable to enjoy much of the
bright-eyed happiness in this movie because I have, in my years of
existence, grown too jaded, and this was kind of reflected by Lucas
in the explanation of ``magic'' in biological terms. And so I await
the more cynical portions of the trilogy eagerly (how sick is
that?):
</P>
<P>
   Midi-Chlorians
</P>
<P>
   pre-dawn blue.
</P>
<P>
   post-myth cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   gathering dew drops;
</P>
<P>
   something is missing
</P>
<P>
   in these explanations
</P>
<P>
   of magic.
</P>
<P>
   a myth mistold,
</P>
<P>
   or santa claus
</P>
<P>
   discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   i wish i could
</P>
<P>
   borrow your sight
</P>
<P>
   for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   something ended
</P>
<P>
   (long ago
</P>
<P>
   newly realized).
</P>
<P>
   awaiting the
</P>
<P>
   tragic
</P>
<P>
   catharsis.
</P>
<P>
   _ JR Brubaker, Centerville
</P>
<P>
   I went to the 4 a.m. showing. I was 6 when the original ``Star
Wars'' came out in 1977. The trilogy was a seminal experience of my
formative years, so I was very excited about seeing how the story
began. I'll give ``Phantom Menace'' a B/B-, good but not great. The
visuals and effects are outstanding and Jar Jar wasn't quite as
irritating as I feared, though he was definitely a minor annoyance.
He is indeed the love child of Roger Rabbit and Stepin Fetchit (as
one critic noted). The movie has about 1/1,000,000 of the emotional
resonance of the first trilogy as a whole, and maybe 1/10th of that
when compared to ``The Empire Strikes Back.'' But it's fun, and not
quite as juvenile as I expected. Lucas managed a pretty good
balance for young and older fans.
</P>
<P>
   I'm definitely looking forward to the next one.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brian Landa, Dayton
</P>
<P>
   I went to the 4 a.m. showing of ``Phantom Menace.'' Before you
think I'm crazy, I got off work at 3 a.m., so it was actually
pretty convenient. Regardless of the time, the showing still
appeared to be sold out, or at least very close.
</P>
<P>
   When the 20th Century Fox and Lucasfilm logos went up on the
screen, the audience cheered and applauded. I thought the movie was
simply spectacular. It is unbelievable how many special effects are
in this movie. It is hard to believe this didn't cost more to make
than it did. Every scene was exquisitely crafted. The story draws
many parallels to the original movie. Jar Jar Binks is not as
annoying as we were led to believe. He may have been difficult to
understand at times, and his humor may have been somewhat juvenile,
but he didn't drag the movie down.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, this was a fantastic production. I think it's safe
to say that ``Titanic'' will sink again under the weight of ``The
Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeffrey W. Reger, Kettering
</P>
<P>
   I didn't form an opinion about ``Episode 1'' before I actually
went to see it this morning. I didn't want to be disappointed if it
wasn't all that I'd hoped for it to be.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas outdid himself with the computer-generated scenes. He did
things he could only imagine in the past. He pulled off some
incredible scenes, namely the Podrace. The effects were everything
I could have hoped for them to be.
</P>
<P>
   I also think Lucas did a pretty good job of casting the
characters. All of the people seemed to fit their roles very well.
</P>
<P>
   One of the movie's only weak points was the acting in some of
the scenes. But to any avid ``Star Wars'' fan it won't make a hill
of difference.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, I would say the movie was a definite success. My
viewing pleasure was made complete by ``Boba Fett'' sitting just to
the right of me.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sarah in Beavercreek
</P>
<P>
   As a Cincinnati native now living in Florida, I got to
experience the Orlando side of ``The Phantom Menace.'' Ticket sales
down here were psychotic; our big multiplex had a line of more than
400 people. Opening night was a great experience, all the fans were
very friendly, and we all swapped stories about the previous three
and rumors about this one.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting thing about the film was that I think it is
the first great film I have seen that doesn't meet my expectations.
Everyone goes in with a preconceived notion of how it should be,
and then we feel slighted on the way out that it doesn't do
everything we want it to. We are the people this movie was not
intended for, it is intended for the wide eyes child who is looking
to be lost in a galaxy far, far away, and not a cynical older
person who can beat ``Star Wars'' Trivial Pursuit without missing a
question (me). So, when I break the shackles of that off, I find
the movie is fantastic. It knows it is part 1 of 6 (possibly 9),
and does a great job setting up the stories to come.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles Edwards
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
