<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 19, 1999 -- POP-RESTAURANT, 5-19 -- Ali
Tayar, right, with Roy Liebenthal, at Pop. The restaurant, which
opened in April, is much more than just a deafeningly hot eatery
with no sign in front. According to its menu, ``Pop is based on the
post-war social idealism and trust in technological innovation,
mass production and pre-fabrication. The author is Tayar, the
architect who conceived this 2,500-square-foot temple of
retro-contempo chic. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- May 19, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 5-19 --
Sometimes sink leaks can be corrected by tightening or replacing a
slip washer on one of the joints. Usually, however, the drips occur
because one of the pipes has corroded and is no longer watertight.
If one pipe is corroded, the others will soon deteriorate, so it is
best to replace the entire drain assembly. While this may sound
complicated, it is an easy repair that any do-it-yourselfer can
make. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SPOKANE, Wash. -- May 19, 1999 -- CIR-RUGGED-LAPTOPS-2,
5-19 -- Laptops aren't usually run through washing machines, but
this one passed the test. Such ``rugged'' laptops are tested in
high humidity in temperatures of 86 to 140 degrees. (Jeff Green/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SPOKANE, Wash. -- May 19, 1999 -- CIR-RUGGED-LAPTOPS-1,
5-19 -- To earn the description ``rugged,'' an Itronix laptop is
drenched in water while operating. Heavier (up to 25 pounds), more
costly (some models start at $8,000) and generally less technically
sophisticated, ``rugged'' models are to ordinary laptops what the
Hummer is to the family car. (Jeff Green/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- May 19, 1999 -- RETURNED-BONES-BOS,
5-19 -- Clockwise from left, Rubie Watson, Barbara Isaac and
Patricia Capone look over pottery at the Peabody Museum that will
be returned to the Pecos Indians in New Mexico. The tribe regards
the 1916 excavation by a Harvard archeologist, which took these and
other items, as a desecration of holy ground. (Janet Knott/Boston
Globe Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- May 19, 1999 -- BBA-SHAUGHNESSY COLUMN-BOS,
5-19 -- New York Yankee Manager Joe Torre, right, with Don Zimmer,
who filled in as manager while Torre was recovering from prostate
cancer surgery, Tuesday at Fenway Park. In Torre's honor during his
absence, Zimmer left the manager's office chair empty and refused
the front-row seat on the team bus and airplane when they
travelled. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DOUGLASVILLE, Pa. -- May 19, 1999 -- CIR-GOV-SITES-2,
5-19 -- Linda Scott-Aughtry resolved a delay in Social Security
benefits online. ``I quit school when I was in 10th grade,'' Ms.
Scott-Aughtry says. ``I've been working ever since. For me to go
into the computer and accomplish that, it really made me feel
great.'' (Sal DiMarco Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MADISON, Wis. -- May 19, 1999 -- CIR-GOV-SITES-1, 5-19 --
Robert Bickner received online help in genealogy research. ``With
veryl[:tle Y3fort R) ChVw t+$.Y,KV.HRHZY
