<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 05/19/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) TAMPA, Fla. -- May 19, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-ZIMMER, 5-19 --
Don Zimmer, left, and Stump Merrill in the dugout during a
pre-season game at Legends Field in Tampa. The 21 victories and 15
losses compiled during Zimmer's tenure as the Yankees' interim
manager will be applied to Joe Torre's career record, says Steve
Hirdt, the executive vice president of the Elias Sports Bureau.
(Jon Adams/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- May 19, 1999 -- GUATEMALA-DEATH-SQUADS,
5-19 -- A log book which, according to investigators, describes the
activities of a secret Guatemalan military unit that kidnapped,
tortured and executed Guatemalans during the early 1980s as part of
a campaign against leftists. Human rights advocates in Guatemala
and the United States say the log book is the most detailed
document about military abuses ever obtained from Guatemalan army
sources. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) SKOPJE, Macedonia -- May 19, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
5-19 -- Children looking at a damaged car after a bomb exploded in
Macedonia's capital Wednesday. Two men were badly wounded in the
blast, which took place in a heavily Albanian neighborhood of the
city. (Andrew Testa/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- May 19, 1999 -- BUTTERFLY-DANGER, 5-19 --
All around the country, farmers are about to finish sowing millions
of acres of a genetically altered form of corn that protects itself
from pests by producing a toxin in its tissues. But researchers
report that this increasingly popular transgenic plant, thought to
be harmless to non- pest insects, produces a wind- borne pollen
that can kill monarch butterflies. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- May 19, 1999 -- CONGRESS-GUNS, 5-19 --
Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., left, and Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla.,
discuss the juvenile justice bill in the hallway outside the Senate
floor Wednesday. After several days of escalating feuds between
Republicans and Democrats, the Senate pulled back from the brink of
a partisan meltdown late Wednesday and seemed poised for a final
vote on the bill, which has become a vehicle for several new gun
control measures. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- May 19, 1999 -- NY-CLINTON, 5-19 --
President Clinton speaks with Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
during ceremonies to unveil plans for a new $484 million
state-of-the-art train station Wednesday. The new Pennsylvania
Station, a model of which is seen in the foreground, will handle
about half a million passengers a day, more than New York's three
metropolitan airports combined. At right is Transportation
Secretary Rodney Slater. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) MILTON, England -- May 19, 1999 -- PSION-CELL-PHONES-2,
5-19 -- Workers pour over a circuit board at Psion's enterprise
computing division in Milton. By harnessing its Epoc operating
system to the next generation of wireless telephones, Psion and the
world's biggest mobile phone producers are taking aim at no less a
target than the Microsoft Corp. (Jonathan Player/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MILTON, England -- May 19, 1999 -- PSION-CELL-PHONES-1,
5-19 -- Andrew Clegg, managing director of Psion's enterprise
computing division, with a prototype sub-notebook computer which
uses the Epoc operating system, at the company's headquarters. By
harnessing its operating system to the next generation of wireless
telephones, Psion and the world's biggest mobile phone producers
are taking aim at no less a target than the Microsoft Corp.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) PROVIDENCE, R.I. -- May 19, 1999 -- BBO-PROVIDENCE, 5-19
-- In what has become a good-luck ritual, members of the Providence
Friars baseball team shake their hats. Last October, Philip Smith,
the school's president, announced that baseball, men's golf and
tennis would be eliminated from the varsity athletic program,
saying that the cuts were made in order to comply with gender
equity and proportionality structures set by the NCAA. (Bill
Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- May 19, 1999 -- QUICK-REFURBISH-3, 5-19 --
It only took Benjamin Noriega-Ortiz three months to decorate a
hedge-fund manager's Manhattan duplex. The bedroom has tea-washed
wallpaper and a silk bed drape, but the client sleeps in an
undecorated room upstairs. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BEDFORD, N.Y. -- May 19, 1999 -- QUICK-REFURBISH-2, 5-19
-- It took 170 experts to renovate Barry Gesser's house in just six
weeks. Carey Maloney and Hermes Mallea are the designers
responsible for starting Gesser's African mask collection. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BEDFORD, N.Y. -- May 19, 1999 -- QUICK-REFURBISH-1, 5-19
-- It took 170 experts just six weeks to renovate the Gesser house.
``These guys took the ball and ran,'' says Barry Gesser, a single,
35-year-old hedge-fund manager. Million-dollar decorating marathons
have become a fact of life for many designers catering to the
under-40 Wall Street set. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- May 19, 1999 -- BOWER-THEATER-REVIEW, 5-19
-- From left, Drew McVety, T.R. Knight and Thomas Lyons in Conor
