   (NYT9) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- May 19, 1999 -- RETURNED-BONES-BOS,
5-19 -- Clockwise from left, Rubie Watson, Barbara Isaac and
Patricia Capone look over pottery at the Peabody Museum that will
be returned to the Pecos Indians in New Mexico. The tribe regards
the 1916 excavation by a Harvard archeologist, which took these and
other items, as a desecration of holy ground. (Janet Knott/Boston
Globe Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- May 19, 1999 -- BBA-SHAUGHNESSY COLUMN-BOS,
5-19 -- New York Yankee Manager Joe Torre, right, with Don Zimmer,
who filled in as manager while Torre was recovering from prostate
cancer surgery, Tuesday at Fenway Park. In Torre's honor during his
absence, Zimmer left the manager's office chair empty and refused
the front-row seat on the team bus and airplane when they
travelled. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DOUGLASVILLE, Pa. -- May 19, 1999 -- CIR-GOV-SITES-2,
5-19 -- Linda Scott-Aughtry resolved a delay in Social Security
benefits online. ``I quit school when I was in 10th grade,'' Ms.
Scott-Aughtry says. ``I've been working ever since. For me to go
into the computer and accomplish that, it really made me feel
great.'' (Sal DiMarco Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MADISON, Wis. -- May 19, 1999 -- CIR-GOV-SITES-1, 5-19 --
Robert Bickner received online help in genealogy research. ``With
very little effort, I got the records I have been looking for,''
says Bickner, who is a professor at the University of Wisconsin at
Madison. ``I was so impressed that I sent a message back and said,
'Thank you for putting this very user-friendly feeling on things.'
`` (Andy Manis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 19, 1999 -- CIR-CHIP-ART-2, 5-19 -- A
refrigerator that nags is just one of the exhibits at New York
University's new-media art show. Most of the exhibitors were in a
course called physical computing. They were asked to create
interactive computer projects that do not require the use of a
mouse, keyboard or computer screen. (Philip Greenberg/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- May 19, 1999 -- CIR-CHIP-ART-1, 5-19 -- A
dancing toaster - one of the creations at New York University's
new-media art show. Most of the exhibitors were in a course called
physical computing. They were asked to create interactive computer
projects that do not require the use of a mouse, keyboard or
computer screen. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SEATTLE -- May 19, 1999 -- CIR-INTERNET-SERVICE-2, 5-19
-- Seated at left, Paul Budlong, a customer, with Will Dean of the
Drizzle ISP. Budlong chose his small ISP, based in Seattle, after
receiving e-mail from someone who used it. ``I liked the name,'' he
says of Drizzle.com, which seemed appropriate to local weather
conditions. (Larry Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) OAKLAND, Calif. -- May 19, 1999 --
CIR-INTERNET-SERVICE-1, 5-19 -- David Cassel is editor of the AOL
Watch newsletter. ``I had a friend who wouldn't tell anybody when
he'd find an ISP he liked,'' says Cassel, whose newsletter is
distributed to an e-mail list of 42,000 readers. ``You really want
a small service no one has ever heard about.'' (Dan Krauss/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MANHASSET, N.Y. -- May 19, 1999 -- CIR-PRESCHOOL, 5-19 --
With the right kind of software, the computer can present scenarios
and characters that allow children to place themselves in a
predicament and then experiment with what might be appropriate
responses. And all this occurs without actually experiencing the
consequences of even the most outrageous behavior. (Vic DeLucia/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
