<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAYTON, GONZALEZ EXPECTED TO RETURN FRIDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
ARLINGTON, Texas _ Royce Clayton is expected to be back at
shortstop and Juan Gonzalez in right field Friday when the Rangers
open a six-game road trip in Baltimore.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'd say Clayton is 100 percent and Juan is 99 percent,''
manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton is on the disabled list because of a muscle tear behind
his right shoulder. He played for Triple-A Oklahoma on a
medical-rehabilitation assignment Monday, and went 1-for-5 while
playing all nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez missed his seventh consecutive game yesterday because
of a strained right hamstring. He has been running on a treadmill
and in the Rangers' indoor pool to strengthen it. Crabtree pitching
well Tim Crabtree lowered his earned-run average from 8.44 to 3.07
with 92/3 scoreless innings in his past 11 appearances, including
21/3 innings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crabby's getting better every day,'' manager Johnny Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed reliever hit 97 mph on the Rangers' radar gun
Tuesday, the best for anyone on the staff this season. He had hit
95 six times. His slider also has been effective.
</P>
<P>
   Although his ERA was high before the scoreless streak, Crabtree
has had only two bad outings this year. He gave up a total of five
runs in two outings, April 7 and 22. He wasn't scored on in his
other 15 games. Double trouble There are two ways to look at the
Rangers' propensity for hitting into double plays.
</P>
<P>
   One is that you have to have a good offense to do it as
frequently as the Rangers, who have grounded into 47 double plays,
more than any other major-league team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way you can hit into a double play is if you've got
someone on base,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``When you hit hard
ground balls at someone with runners on base, you're going to get
double plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The other is that the Rangers aren't patient enough with those
runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes double plays are created when you swing at pitchers'
pitches,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the case with Ivan Rodriguez, who leads the
league by grounding into 11 double plays.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, with only four walks in 141 at-bats, tends to swing
at pitches out of the strike zone. Frequently those become hits;
the catcher has a .326 average. Sometimes, they become double
plays.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the double plays, the Rangers are fourth in the
league with 235 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is how many runs you score,'' Oates said.
``No, change that. It's where you are in the standings at the end
of the year.''
Dransfeldt back down Rookie shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt will stay in
Arlington when the team leaves Friday for the road trip to
Baltimore and Tampa Bay, and was told he will be optioned back to
Triple-A Oklahoma. The Rangers want to make 100 percent certain
that Clayton is ready before officially making the move.
</P>
<P>
   Dransfeldt earned rave reviews for his defense during his first
16 games in the majors but hit .189.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just getting this experience is important,'' he said. ``For
the first time in the majors, I'm pleased. I'm a little
disappointed in my offense, though.''
Briefly Ivan Rodriguez was back in the lineup for the day game
Wednesday after playing the night before. Catchers usually get a
rest during a day game after a night game, but Rodriguez played
because the Rangers are off Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McLemore, who left Tuesday's game in the top of the fourth
inning because of stiffness in his left knee, did not start
Wednesday. Oates said McLemore could have played, but decided to
use the off day to give him two days of rest. McLemore pinch-hit in
the eighth inning. Long-ball contest Wednesday, Tampa Bay's Paul
Sorrento hit the longest home run in the history of The Ballpark in
Arlington. The top 12: Player, Team Opponent Distance Date 1. Paul
Sorrento, Tampa Bay Texas 491 5/19/99 2. Jose Canseco, Texas
Seattle 480 6/13/94 3. Roberto Kelly, Texas Anaheim 456 6/13/98 4.
Dean Palmer, Texas San Diego 449 6/14/97 4. Mark McGwire, Oakland
Texas 449 7/5/97 6. Juan Gonzalez, Texas New York 447 8/22/98 6.
