A3856 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-2NDTAKE-     05-19 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: about it.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wernick said that Volpe, who is 27, also gave him a report on
the street melee that had led to the arrest of Louima and a second
Haitian immigrant, Patrick Antoine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said there was a big fight outside some club, they were
acting like animals,'' the sergeant said Volpe had told him. He
said Volpe reorted that ``he got punched in the face, chased a
couple of people and caught somebody, but wasn't sure if it was the
guy'' who punched him.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe is also charged with beating Antoine, who had not been
involved in the melee, as he walked on a street near the nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's laywer, Marvyn M. Kornberg is expected to begin cross-
examining Wernick on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wernick took the stand, Antoine testified. In addition to
giving his version of his encounter with Volpe, Antoine told the
jury of statements the officer had made to him as he took him to
the same stationhouse restroom where prosecutors say Louima had
been attacked shortly before.
</P>
<P>
   The statements, as recounted by Antoine _ who testified in
Creole through an interpreter, though he said he understood English
_ included an apology to Antoine for having beaten him in the
street and an admission by Volpe that he had been acting
irrationally that morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me why was I following this guy,'' Antoine said,
apparently referring to someone else Volpe and other officers had
been chasing near the melee when Antoine walked by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I did not know what he was talking about, that I
was just going home and that he beat me,'' Antoine continued,
adding that Volpe ``then said he's sorry, he was feeling crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Antoine testified, the officer ``told me he
was like somebody who was going crazy,'' and that ``when somebody
hits him, he hits the person back.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that after Louima was arrested, Volpe, Schwarz
and the two other officers on trial, Thomas Wiese and Thomas
Bruder, beat him in a police car before Volpe and Schwarz attacked
him with the stick in the restroom at the police station. All four
are charged with violating Louima's civil rights. A fifth defendant
in the trial, Sgt. Michael Bellomo, is charged with trying to cover
up the reported beating in the police car.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg, suggested in questioning Antoine that he had
misunderstood the officer's words during the conversation in
English. The lawyer also got Antoine to acknowledge that even
though he identified Volpe in court as the one who he said had
beaten him in the street, he had not had time to get a good look at
that officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
