A3863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANDS'END-AD-COLUMN-N     05-19 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDS'END-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: LANDS' END'S CYBERCATALOG IS FOCUS OF NEW CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Wis.)  (bl)  
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The longtime New York editor Lee Eisenberg said he felt as if he
were on Neptune when he first landed in Dodgeville, Wis., last
March to become the top creative executive for Lands' End Inc.
catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   So it is only appropriate that the first big advertising effort
under Eisenberg is promoting Lands' End in another realm. In
cyberspace, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The apparel company's entire ad budget through November,
estimated at $15 million, seeks to sell its Web site,
www.landsend.com, in a TV, print and Internet advertising campaign
created by Biederman, Kelly, Krimstein &AMP; Partners in New York. Even
its June catalog cover is devoted to explaining how its site works.
</P>
<P>
   Lands' End's effort to establish itself among the first direct
apparel merchants to offer a comprehensive and, most importantly,
``fun'' _ Web site. But it is hardly alone. While few if any in the
estimated $93 billion catalog industry are advertising their Web
sites in a big way, some 75 percent of all catalog retailers now
operate Web sites, according to the Direct Marketing Association, a
trade group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign comes after a disappointing fiscal year in which
net income dropped 51 percent, to $31.2 million, for the year ended
Jan. 29. The company attributed the income drop to product price
cuts paired with a dramatic increase in costly catalog
distribution. This year, as it increases its Web presence, it will
reduce the size of its catalogs and cut catalog circulation.
</P>
<P>
   For the first quarter, ended April 30, sales were up 7.8
percent, to $290 million, and net income was $6.5 million, up from
$5.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lands' End is hoping to get a strong position on the Web before
it gets more competitive _ ``which will be very soon,'' said Katey
Muldoon, president of Muldoon &AMP; Baer, catalog consultants in
Sugarloaf Key, Fla. Muldoon has done work for the Lands' End
competitor L.L. Bean. But just throwing up a Web site is not
enough. The key to getting the attention of consumers is to be
entertaining, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the Lands' End TV spots promote its Web site's singular,
service-oriented features such as a ``Suit Finder'' icon that shows
women the swimsuits that look best on their body type, and ``Oxford
Express,'' a tool to help men find the right dress shirt. Swimsuits
and dress shirts are both big sellers for Lands' End.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of eye candy,'' said Ken Krimstein,
Biederman's chief creative officer, in explaining the Web site
features, ``and there will be lots of these types of innovations.
It's part of the philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   The direct-mail industry is focusing on the Web as the wave of
the future for obvious reasons: Internet sales are exploding.
Lands' End said it had $61 million in Web site sales for the year
ended in January, up from $18 million, and some 20 percent were new
customers, which is important in the saturated catalog market.
</P>
<P>
   Industrywide, catalog sales on the Web have jumped from $6
million in 1993 to an estimated $9.4 billion today as more people
go online, according to the Direct Marketing Association, which
projects sales will explode to $36 billion within three years.
</P>
<P>
   The direct mail industry is also a natural fit for Web marketing
because catalogers already have the fulfillment and customer
service infrastructure to handle Internet sales, said Amy
Blankenship, an association spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense; they're doing the same things they have always
done in print,'' she said, adding that entire sections of its
annual conference this year are devoted to e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to promote the Web is that it is cheaper to sell
on the Web than to send out the estimated 250 million catalogs each
year that Lands' End distributes.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean the company is abandoning print, said
Eisenberg, whose career has included stints as an editor at Time
Inc. and as the editor of Esquire magazine. Eisenberg said his job
was to expand on Lands' End's already established reputation for
entertaining and thought-provoking content, whether that be on the
Web or in its monthly catalog. Writers new to the catalog include
the humorist Bruce McCall and the art critic Robert Hughes, and
Eisenberg said he was also working with the New York designer
Milton Glaser to develop some design ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Lands' End is already sort of a New Yorker of catalog companies,
offering features from writers ranging from Garrison Keillor to
William Least Heat Moon amid pages of products about warm woolens
and highlander twills. The articles are intended to entertain and
inform and are totally unrelated to Lands' End products.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Eisenberg said that given the demographic profile of
its customers _ who tend to be affluent and educated _ he saw the
catalog (and the Web site, where there is no space limitation) as a
place for great writing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a guest copywriter series where authors write about
Lands' End products has generated interest in the publishing
industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the January issue, in which the best-selling
author Elmore Leonard was featured on the cover and wrote about
Pinpoint shirts, touched off a wave of phone calls to Eisenberg
from publishers who wanted their authors to write for Lands' End.
Leonard wrote that his character Chili Palmer in ``Get Shorty''
(who was played by John Travolta in the film of the same name)
wears a silky cotton Pinpoint in his new book ``Be Cool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They know or intuitively realize that it's a great place to
promote books,'' Eisenberg said. ``It may not be Oprah, but it does
a similar thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his feeling of being in outer space, Eisenberg said he is
now seeing Wisconsin as home, and is moving his wife and two
children there in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't used to the wide-open space of the prairie, but as it
has greened up there, its beautiful,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
