<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-ITALIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOM ITALIA TAKES ITS CASE TO BIG FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Telecom Italia made a last-minute bid Wednesday to lure
big shareholders who are undecided about whether to accept a
hostile $65 billion takeover bid from Olivetti over a friendly
merger deal with Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   With two days to go before the Olivetti bid expires, Telecom
Italia's chief executive, Franco Bernabe, reached out to fund
managers and other big investors by conference call, promising to
share his company's wealth by spending more than $4 billion to buy
back 10 percent of its stock at prices as much as $3.70 a share
above the amount offered by Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   An Olivetti victory would likely wreck the marriage of Telecom
Italia and Deutsche Telekom, former government monopolies that
together would create one of the world's biggest phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe, though sounding at times pressed and on the defensive,
made clear that investors who had offered Olivetti their shares by
Friday would be ineligible for the Telecom Italia buyback, if the
Olivetti bid failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who tendered will not benefit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday night, Olivetti had obtained 474.6 million
common shares, or only about 9 percent of Telecom Italia, the
nation's stock market reported. But big institutional shareholders,
which own most of Telecom Italia and will determine the outcome,
are not expected to formally decide until the Friday deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Paolo Catalfamo, managing director in Italy for the Templeton
funds, said that barring some startling development, ``we will
accept the Olivetti offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Most other big investors declined to disclose their preferences.
But the possibility of an Olivetti triumph was reflected on the
Milan exchange, where Telecom Italia's share price closed up 4.25
percent, at 9.927 euros, or $10.52.
</P>
<P>
   Especially large quantities of stock changed hands, apparently
driven in part by speculators acquiring Telecom Italia shares
Wednesday at less than 10 euros to offer them to Olivetti before
the week's end for a guaranteed 11.50 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti, Italy's No. 2 phone service provider, stunned
investors earlier this year with its bold bid for Telecom Italia, a
company seven times its size. To deflect the bid, Bernabe has
resorted to a wide variety of maneuvers, notably the plan to merge
Telecom Italia into Deutsche Telekom in an all-stock deal that
values the Italian company's shares at $12.65, 46 cents more than
the Olivetti bid.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Olivetti have suggested that the percentage of
shares obtained by the Friday deadline may be higher than the stock
market statistics, though they have offered no firm evidence to
back that up.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti's chief executive, Roberto Colaninno, the quarterback
of the takeover attempt, said this week that the best holding for
Olivetti lay between 65 percent and 70 percent of Telecom Italia,
which he described as ``the ideal level between sustainability of
debt and full control of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   But an Olivetti adviser said that the ideal target might be
lower, at only 1 or 2 percentage points above 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti's bid consists of $12.19 a share _ 60 percent cash and
the rest in bonds and stock in Tecnost, an Olivetti subsidiary that
is being used for the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   While Lehman Brothers has advised Olivetti on the bid, other
investment banks, notably Chase Manhattan and Mediobanca of Italy,
have raised almost $24 billion in financing for the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The Olivetti adviser said that if the challenger obtained less
than 50 percent, but more than 35 percent of Telecom Italia,
Olivetti would make a decision on whether to proceed with its
takeover attempt by Tuesday, taking into account such issues as the
effect on the rating of its bonds by a low result as well as the
legal implications. ``The situation is fluid and complex,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe's conference call Wednesday appeared at least in part to
be in response to calls by fund managers for some gesture that
would make their loyalty worthwhile, such as a notably sweetened
offer from Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   But Deutsche Telekom's chief, Ron Sommer, has ruled this out.
Bernabe had hastily cobbled together the deal in hopes that
Deutsche Telekom would be the white knight to rescue Telecom Italia
from Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   That union, however, has faced criticism since it was first
announced last month. Telecommunications analysts have questioned
the strategic and competitive benefits of the merger plan. Some
Italian government officials have expressed opposition because the
company would effectively be controlled by the German government,
which still holds a majority stake in Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti opened its bid for Telecom Italia with a strong pitch
to individual investors in Italy, who hold about 10 percent of the
shares, through an extensive campaign of newspaper ads. But few
appear to have come forward to offer their stock.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 70 percent of Telecom Italia shares are held by
institutional investors, including large funds in the United States
and Britain, and both Olivetti and Telecom Italia consider them to
be the crucial vote casters.
</P>
<P>
   With many fund managers refusing to disclose their plans so as
not to tip the outcome, many other investors have said that they
will only decide on Friday _ to allow Telecom Italia time for
last-minute offers and to judge the general sentiment in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Dolmer, a fund manager at Standard Life Investments, the
asset management arm of Standard Life Assurance Co. of Britain,
said that ``we know our thoughts at the moment, and we know what
the bulk of the assumption in the market is,'' but that Standard
Life would wait until the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Just what impact Bernabe's offers Wednesday night would have
remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
   In the Telecom Italia conference call, Berardino Libonati,
Telecom Italia's chairman, repeated arguments that the Olivetti bid
violated the rights of holders of savings, or nonvoting shares, and
that Italian laws that limited shareholders to 3 percent when
Telecom Italia was taken public meant that unless Olivetti obtained
more than 50 percent plus one share, its voting rights would be
limited to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments by Libonati, a noted lawyer, suggested that unless
Olivetti secured a strong majority stake, the battle could shift to
the nation's courts. And, Libonati added, ``Any Italian lawyer can
tell you how long legal proceedings in Italy can last.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe said Telecom Italia would spend as much as $4.1 billion
to buy back as many as 720 million common shares, or 10 percent, at
a maximum $10.12 a share, and seek stockholder approval for a
second buyback at a maximum price of $15.90, if the Olivetti bid
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Telecom Italia had the means to afford such
generosity, Bernabe responded that with annual operating profit of
almost $12 billion, ``we don't lack the financial capacity to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But some fund managers reached in the conference call did not
appear impressed. ``Why are we here today?'' one asked. ``You could
have done this three weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Another fund manger accused Bernabe of punishing share owners
who decided to offer Olivetti their stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're penalizing shareholders who tendered,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
