<HEADLINE>
U.S. RATE HIKE CALLED UNLIKELY TO HURT LATIN AMERICAN ECONOMIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on interest rates in Brazil, Chile and Argentina
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual urchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ The possibility of an increase in U.S.
interest rates, as suggested by the Federal Reserve this week, is
unlikely to undermine the steady improvement in Latin America's
economic outlook, forecasters said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although fear of higher U.S. rates was partly responsible for
drops in Latin American stock markets, it was seen as a knee-jerk
reaction. More important, economists said, is the strengthening
momentum of Brazil, the region's largest economy, and the benefits
such strength can carry over to others.
</P>
<P>
   Reduced capital flows, the greatest concern facing Latin nations
if the Fed were to raise rates, did not fan fears at Brazil's
central bank, which continued cutting interest rates Wednesday,
this time to 23.5 percent from 27 percent. The reduction is the
seventh since January's devaluation of Brazil's currency, the real,
and reflects growing confidence at the bank that the nation can
withstand volatility generated from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new currency regime allows us to absorb external impacts
in a better way,'' said Octavio de Barros, chief economist here for
Banco Bilbao Vizcaya.
</P>
<P>
   De Barros contrasted the situation of Brazil with that of
Argentina, where a system that fixes the value of the peso to the
dollar limits the government's use of monetary policy to react to
foreign shocks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most analysts agree that Argentina is the Latin American
country most susceptible to an increase in rates in the United
States, since it borrows so much abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, the second-biggest Latin American country, is largely
shielded from a U.S. rate increase for the same reason as Brazil,
since the government mainly borrows on domestic bond markets. Yet
Mexico, with nearly 90 percent of exports going to the United
States, could be hurt by weaker U.S. demand for its goods.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, only about a third of exports from the Mercosur
trade bloc, which comprises Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and
Uruguay, go to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Countries such as Chile would be insulated from higher U.S.
rates, largely since they are considered safer investments by
debt-rating agencies, said Walter Molano, chief Latin America
economist at BCP Securities in Greenwich, Conn. And Venezuela,
which has sent mixed signals to investors since President Hugo
Chavez took office in February, is partly protected from a rise in
American rates because of recent increases in the price of oil, the
country's main export.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rise in U.S. rates would probably get lost in the detail,''
said Arturo Porzecanski, global head of fixed-income research for
ING Barings in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that an increase could end up hurting Argentina the
most, since the government there is so dependent on international
capital markets for its borrowing needs. ``More than 90 percent of
Argentina's debt is denominated in currencies they cannot print and
cannot tax,'' Porzecanski said.
</P>
<P>
   On Latin American stock markets Wednesday, Argentina's benchmark
Merval index registered the deepest decline, falling 4.3 percent,
partly because of rumors that it would scrap the system that links
the peso to the dollar. The government denied this.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, the Bolsa index dropped 2.1 percent. Here in Sao
Paulo, Brazil's financial center, the Bovespa index declined 1.2
percent. Stocks were also down in Chile, Venezuela, Colombia and
Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Latin American equities become less attractive to foreign
investors when interest rates rise in the United States because of
improved returns on securities such as U.S. Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   While Brazil's central bank showed Wednesday that there is ample
room for it to stoke a recovery, there are still concerns over the
country's dependence on foreign capital flows. For instance, the
estimate for this year's trade surplus has fallen to about $4
billion from $11 billion, an illustration that the currency
devaluation has not done as much as once hoped to increase exports.
And the ability to finance debt would be made more difficult if
American rates rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is an importer of capital so any increase in U.S. rates
is negative,'' said Jose Scheinkman, a professor of economics at
the University of Chicago. ``The only way to attack this problem in
a long-term way is for the government to curb spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Brazil has made substantial progress in narrowing it
budget deficit, before payments of interest on debt are taken into
account, President Fernando Henrique Cardoso was dealt a minor
setback this week in efforts to limit pension spending, when
congressional pressure led him to withdraw a decree creating a
minimum retirement age for some workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
