<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glavine overcomes rough spot
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Outside of some scrambling in the fifth inning, Tom
Glavine came away from Wednesday's 7-3 win over the Pirates feeling
pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had too many big pitch counts,'' said Glavine who threw 118
pitches in seven innings, allowed five hits and three runs in
earning his third victory of the season. ``My stuff was good, my
stuff was live. There was only one inning I didn't feel all that
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   After bouncing into two double plays in the first four innings,
the Pirates used a hit-and-run to start something in the fifth. Ed
Sprague lined behind Ozzie Guillen on the play, allowing Kevin
Young to advance from first to third. A ground-out by Freddy Garcia
was enough to tie the game 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   With two out, Glavine walked No. 8 hitter Keith Osik to bring up
pitcher Francisco Cordova. But Cordova lined the first pitch to
right to score Sprague. A flare by Abraham Nunez gave the Pirates a
3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine allowed only a bloop hit over the next two innings and
recorded two of his five strikeouts. That finish and a Brian Jordan
grand slam enabled Glavine (3-4) to walk off with the third win in
his last five starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an indication that I'm getting back on track _ I can
have a bad inning or bad hitter or bad sequence,'' Glavine said.
``That's a whole lot better than earlier in the year. I'm getting
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Adaptable
</P>
<P>
   Giving Walt Weiss a day off Wednesday afternoon following
Tuesday's night game, the Braves used Guillen in the leadoff spot.
His .152 batting average and .152 on-base percentage made him a
strange candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen, an admitted free swinger, said before the game he would
make an adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to see more pitches because I'm at the top of the
lineup,'' Guillen said. ``When you pinch-hit, the first good pitch
you see, you have to swing. I'll try to do the same things Walt did
the last couple days.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping to his word, Guillen found his way on base with a bloop
double to start the four-run rally in the sixth and took his first
walk of the season in the seventh. He scored two of the Braves'
seven runs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
