<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES20-     05-19 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air Jordan propels Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tom Glavine knew a little something about Brian
Jordan's stinginess with two strikes from when he pitched against
him when Jordan was a Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   But not until the sixth inning on Wednesday afternoon did
Glavine get an up-close and personal view of how Jordan takes
having an opposing coach instruct a pitcher to walk the man in
front of him to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan needed just one pitch from the Pirates' Francisco Cordova
to let his feelings be known with a grand slam to left, allowing
Glavine to take his third win of the season as Atlanta beat
Pittsburgh 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two months, Glavine has witnessed some of the
intestinal fortitude of his new teammate who, given the absence of
Andres Galarraga, has responded with a Braves-high 31 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing against him, I always liked the way he played the
game,'' said Glavine, now 3-4. ``But I don't think you get an
appreciation for how good a player he is until you play with him
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan had ripped the same type of pitch, a fastball, from
Cordova in his previous at-bat high into the left-field wind and
watched it die a slow death and fall back into play. But after
back-to-back hits by Ozzie Guillen and Bret Boone, Pirates pitching
coach Pete Vukovich's visit to the mound and the ensuing
intentional walk to Chipper Jones, Jordan took another crack at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always feel a sense of anger when you see that pitching
coach go out there and he's looking at you while he walks out there
and you know he's going to walk Chipper to load the bases to get to
you,'' said Jordan, owner of the Braves' first grand slam of the
year and a team-high 10 home runs. ``I'm just that competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The four runs gave Atlanta a 5-3 lead on the way to a three-game
sweep of the Pirates. It was the Braves' fourth consecutive win and
first series win after losing the last three series on the road.
Jones and Jordan have combined for 10 RBIs in the last two games
after combining for 11 on the nine-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones credits Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been our MVP so far,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
