<SLUG> BC-BBN-OLDPLAYER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    40-something players still key contributors in the majors
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At age 40, Mickey Mantle had been gone from baseball
for three years. Joe DiMaggio, too. Jim Palmer was in his first
year of retirement. At 40, Sandy Koufax had been retired for nine
seasons. George Foster was through at 37, and so was Dale Murphy.
At 37, Lou Gehrig was dead.
</P>
<P>
   By tradition, the major-leaguer isn't washed up by his 40th
birthday, but he's wearing a pretty good lather. The paradox is
that while baseball is a game of gained experience, the
over-experienced are a burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble with baseball,'' Frank Howard once said, ``is by
the time you learn how to play it, you can't play it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in 1999. A dozen players age 40 or older are still in the
majors and a 13th, Tim Raines, celebrates his 40th birthday later
in the season. Five years ago, only three 40-year-old players were
active, and one of them, Florida's Charlie Hough, was biding time
until getting a hip replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion, accelerated year-round conditioning programs and a
prevailing economic system have conspired to keep older players in
the game, and not just for decoration. The New York Mets signed up
Rickey Henderson (40) with hopes he would charge the club's
offense. The Atlanta Braves went looking for an affordable leadoff
hitter and found Otis Nixon (40).
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland A's, with six regulars owning two years of
major-league service or less, signed Raines, relief dinosaur Doug
Jones (41), starter Tom Candiotti (41) and outfielder/infielder
Tony Phillips (40) to wet-nurse the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds real good, and they've had that impact,'' A's
general manager Billy Beane said. ``But we're limited in our
resources. We get the best players we can with the amount of money
we have. That's probably closer to the truth. We stock both Pampers
and Depends in our clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the geriatrics on the field can be a challenge.
Henderson is on the DL with a sprained knee. Candiotti already has
missed a start because his knee wouldn't loosen up. Tampa Bay's
Wade Boggs, just 57 hits from the 3,000 mark, is on the DL (leg
strain) for the second time in two years. He went his first 16
seasons without ever visiting the DL.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing you've got to find out is how much fight's in the
dog,'' Boggs said. ``And in this one, there's a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but age also plots against them. With his average
against left-handed pitching at .211, Boggs (40) has platooned at
third base with Bobby Smith, delaying No. 3,000 until mid-August.
Left-hander Tony Fossas (41), pitching for his seventh team when
the Yankees called him up earlier this month, also might be out of
work soon, after allowing four runs in his first four outings. Gary
Gaetti (40), is hitting .174 for the Chicago Cubs, which could
prompt his second release within 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   But in general, the statistical return has been high. In
Baltimore, Harold Baines (40) leads the Orioles with 29 RBIs and is
hitting .333 with runners in scoring position. St. Louis' Willie
McGee (40) had been batting .326 before falling to .278, and while
Nixon's average is a dismal .181, he has scored 17 runs in the 33
times he has reached base, a startling 51.5 percent rate. In 1998,
NL runners scored 34 percent of the time they reached base.
</P>
<P>
   Raines and Phillips still pressure opponents from the basepaths.
Phillips was stranded between third and home, with Raines running
behind him, the night Seattle's Carlos Guillen shredded his knee
during the rundown. Since 1997, the season of his drug bust,
Phillips has drifted through five organizations, but he has amazed
the A's with his work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see why he's played as long as he's played,'' said
Oakland manager Art Howe, who was an active player in 1982 when
Phillips first reached the majors. ``He wants to get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Henderson, who is chasing the all-time records for runs
and walks. He needs 216 runs and 145 walks. After a lackluster
spring camp, Henderson has a .427 on-base percentage and has opened
eyes around the Mets clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope I'm still walking when I'm 40 years old,'' Mets
catcher Mike Piazza said. ``If anyone can carry you from a leadoff
spot, he can.''
</P>
<P>
   This 40s set is no anomaly. Until their retirements last winter,
Dennis Eckersley (44), Dennis Martinez (43) and Paul Molitor (42)
filled large roles. Players turning 40 next season include San
Diego's Tony Gwynn, the Yankees' Chili Davis and Texas' Mark
Morgan. Cleveland's Paul Assenmacher, the Mets' John Franco,
Baltimore's Cal Ripken, Anaheim's Charlie O'Brien and Atlanta's
Andres Galarraga are 38. All ensure a robust senior citizenship
into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just too much left on the table, if there is a season
or two of productivity they might have left,'' Braves general
manager John Schuerholz said. ``They wouldn't just be leaving the
chance to add to the back of their bubble-gum card. Now there's the
chance to fatten their portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
