<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKRAIL20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crawford has strong case for seeking to start
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Has Chris Crawford won back his spot in the starting
lineup?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll talk it over and make a decision then,'' Hawks coach
Lenny Wilkens said after Wednesday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   Bet Crawford will start and for a number of reasons:
</P>
<P>
   _ He practiced with the other four starters, a definite giveaway
under the Wilkens' system.
</P>
<P>
   _ He was playing very well before his shoulder injury in Game 2
against Detroit and had a career-high 26 points off the bench
Tuesday against the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Hawks are much more flexible when Ty Corbin, who scored
only two points Tuesday as a starter, comes out of the lineup.
Playing off the bench, Corbin gives Wilkens the option of spotting
him at big guard or small forward.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Crawford has to be up to the assignment physically
and he says he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little sore,'' he said after his first game in a week.
``That's to be expected. But I'm not limited in my arm movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, briefly a minor league pitcher in the Astros
organization, was asked if going 7-for-14 from the field and
9-for-11 from the foul line left him with the same degree of
soreness as, say, a nine-inning shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way,'' he said Wednesday, ``I couldn't pitch
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Car-pooling
</P>
<P>
   Dikembe Mutombo gave his friend and rival center Patrick Ewing a
ride back to the Knicks' team hotel after Tuesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Did they talk shop?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Mutombo said. ``In fact, Patrick hardly talked to me at
all. He was too busy talking to my little girl (Carrie, 2).''
</P>
<P>
   In the game, Ewing lost his temper after hacking Mutombo in the
head late in the third quarter and was hit with a technical foul by
referee Ted Bernhardt. Asked if he were surprised by Ewing's
reaction to an obvious infraction, Mutombo said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick was frustrated. You're in a playoff game and you want
to be part of it, but he was in foul trouble early so he didn't
play much minutes ((17). That's what it was, his frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   Transplants
</P>
<P>
   Grant Long said he was not upset by the strong support the
Knicks received Tuesday. ``The Knicks are sort of like the Dallas
Cowboys and the Cowboys are America's team,'' Long said. ``It's the
same way with the Braves because of cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere you go, there are New York fans. They're
transplanted here; they're transplanted everywhere. It's not
anything against our team. There are New York fans all across the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   A new view on Henderson
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Marmer, eye surgeon and team physician, now says that
surgery is not indicated for forward Alan Henderson's damaged left
eye. Henderson is scheduled to fly to Baltimore today for a second
opinion. However favorable the report, he is not expected to play
again this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
