<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks' repairs start with defense
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Hawks are in trouble. They know it. Their fans
know it. Unless the Knicks wear blinders, they know they have their
second-round playoff opponent on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's Game 2 at the Georgia Dome is one Atlanta needs to
win, and not because teams almost never come back from a 2-0
deficit in a seven-game series. It happens, but teams with thin
rosters like the Hawks don't exhibit terrible defensive play twice
at home and recover.
</P>
<P>
   Dikembe Mutombo said he could not remember the last time the
Hawks gave up 100 points. ``I don't know if we give up that many
points all season. That's how different this game was for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, going into the playoffs, the Hawks had not surrendered
100 points in their last 23 regular-season games. They allowed 100
points or more three times during the regular season and won all
three.
</P>
<P>
   After his team allowed 50.6 percent shooting, coach Lenny
Wilkens said bad offense can lead to bad defense and the Hawks were
guilty on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've got to get better coverage. You bang _ whatever
you have to do. We yielded not that many turnovers, nine, but we
gave up 15 points from those turnovers, and that's because we
didn't get back on defense. And bad shot selection had something to
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot to wonder about, a lot to fix before the Hawks
go back on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Why were the Hawks, in a playoff game, settling for the
one-pass-and-shoot scenario?
</P>
<P>
   Why was Grant Long, who went scoreless, so ineffective two
nights after leading his team past the Pistons with 26 points and
11 rebounds?
</P>
<P>
   Why did the coach wait four painful possessions into the third
quarter to call timeout when it was clear after two that the Knicks
had made an adjustment and the Hawks were out of kilter? They
eventually went from eight points ahead to eight behind.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, where was Chris Crawford when things were falling
apart? After scoring 20 first-half points, he did not come back to
the game until 4:47 of the third quarter, with the Knicks up 66-62.
And then, the Hawks did not run a post-up play for Crawford,
although he dominated Latrell Sprewell in the second quarter with
17 points.
</P>
<P>
   With 2,232 regular-season and playoff games under his belt,
Wilkens rarely feels compelled to explain himself.
</P>
<P>
   He said he held Crawford in reserve so the young forward could
make an impact on the game when he was needed. He said he took a
timeout at 6:38 of the third quarter and another at 5:08 because
that's when circumstances dictated that he call them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Crawford aside, not much the Hawks did was right against a
Knicks team that is playing at a much higher level since the roles
of Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston were intertwined late in the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Long noted that the playoffs have a way of melding diverse
personalities. ``You heard there aren't enough balls to go around
with Patrick (Ewing) and Sprewell, not enough minutes for Houston
and Sprewell. (But) they put it all together. In the playoffs, guys
come together for a common goal.''
</P>
<P>
   So what can Long do about it after shooting 0-for-6?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I've got to be more aggressive,'' he said. ``I
never got any great looks in the game, never any free looks. There
was always somebody in my face and you can't really get a rhythm
until you get some easy shots, maybe a shot where there's no one in
front of you.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need to step up. And if you've watched our team, you
know we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
