<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love or hate him, Sprewell excelling
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fairly or not, Latrell Sprewell's legacy was carved
out in the neck of P.J. Carlesimo about 17 months ago. He became
and will be forever more ``the player who choked his coach,'' a
symbol of violence and mayhem. But Sprewell wears it well.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was best for him to end up in New York with the
Knicks after the incident with his old Golden State Warriors coach,
for there the scrutiny is more prying than anywhere, if by the
sheer number of media people alone. And if Sprewell was going to
show his true self _ as a player and person _ why not do it where
it'll be documented to the utmost?
</P>
<P>
   What the examination has uncovered since joining the Knicks is
this: Sprewell's an amazing athlete who has the mental capacity to
withstand the vehement expressions of dislike around the league by
fans. The boos follow him in NBA arenas around the league, but he
obviously thrives in the situation rather than succumbing to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the type of person he is,'' Knicks reserve guard
Chris Childs said. ``He's seizing the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell scored 16.4 points off the bench this season for the
Knicks and is a reason the Knicks go into tonight's Game 2 of the
semifinals series with the Hawks ahead 1-0. His 31-point blistering
of Atlanta in Game 1 Tuesday might have been the effort that
solidifies his re-emergence as an All-Star guard.
</P>
<P>
   The performance was calculating, yet random, his creativity with
the ball and speed dominant.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, when he arrived in New York, Sprewell carried more
baggage perhaps than any player ever. Baggage so heavy there were
no guarantees he could reclaim his position among the NBA's elite
guards _ or that he could actually be an asset to a team with lofty
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, it's very hard to be immediately good after such
a long layoff,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``Secondly, you never
know about a player coming from a losing situation because they
develop bad habits. But he's there. I mean, he didn't play for a
year (suspension), had a major injury (heel), was with a new team
and all the scrutiny. It was so much more. I'm shocked he's this
good after being out that long. It's tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of his development has been recognizing when to express his
talent, which was a real adjustment coming from the Warriors and
with the desire to prove he can still do it. ``Not every possession
(on a bad team) is as important as with a winning team,'' Van Gundy
explained. ``(Sprewell will) think: `Maybe I'll take this shot
here' when you're down 15 points. Derek Harper _ and he was one of
the best we ever had in New York _ had the same problem coming from
Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Sprewell's scoring, explosiveness and aggression is
appreciated to an almost cult degree. He is the crowd favorite at
Madison Square Garden, which speaks for his performance more than
New Yorkers' kind nature. For sure, if Sprewell did not flourish,
he'd be booed there, too.
</P>
<P>
   But he has somehow turned those who hissed at the trade that
brought him there into his raunchiest supporters. That he has done
it after not playing NBA ball for more than a year makes his play
that much more remarkable. For point guard Charlie Ward _ the
Knicks' resident spirituality rock _ Sprewell's handling of the
scrutiny and his mostly stellar play on the court is about growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's grown from that whole experience at Golden State,'' Ward
said. ``A lot of people wouldn't be able to handle what he's gone
through. He's done a good job of being himself, of remaining
strong. It takes a mature person to learn from errors. He's taking
this opportunity to prove people wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
