<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTSOCCER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Manchester, Bayern revived
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last time anyone from Manchester United was seen
hoisting the European Cup, it was Bobby Charlton 31 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bayern Munich won three titles in a row culminating in 1976, but
then Franz Beckenbauer headed for America and the New York Cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   The respective dry spells for two of Europe's most legendary
teams have lasted so long that they have magnified the hype leading
up to Wednesday's championship match.
</P>
<P>
   The first Champions' League final not to include a defending
champion unfolds at massive Nou Camp Stadium in Barcelona (2:30
p.m., ESPN2), with both teams also trying to win triple crowns _
European, league and domestic cup titles.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, United captured the first leg by downing Tottenham
Hotspur in a 2-1 comeback for its fifth English Premier League
title in seven years. But before heading to Spain, United will stop
off at Wembley Stadium on Saturday to meet Newcastle in the FA Cup
final.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-day schedule is a grueling one for United, which will be
missing suspended captain Roy Keane and center forward Paul Scholes
and possibly injured defender Jaap Stam for Bayern Munich. But
counting United out has been premature, as shown by its rally to
beat Juventus in the semifinals and by a scintillating FA Cup
semifinal overtime win against Arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``My players proved that they have something that elevates them
beyond the rest,'' United manager Alex Ferguson said Sunday. ``This
club is not about egos, not about chasing records. It's about
maintaining success.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its dominance in England under Ferguson, United has been
haunted by the ghosts of 1968, when Charlton and George Best gave
coach Sir Matt Busby his only taste of European glory.
</P>
<P>
   Bayern Munich cruised to the Bundesliga title and will have time
to rest up before its June 12 German Cup final against Werder
Bremen. Striker Giovanne Elber, one of the top guns in Europe, will
be out, and French World Cup defender Bixente Lizarazu is trying to
come back from injury. The key to the German club's success has
been to shed some of the glamour, and a lot of the infighting, that
earned it the moniker ``FC Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has not been one quarrel on this team,'' said
38-year-old libero Lothar Matthaus, who was with Bayern Munich when
it last reached the European Cup final, in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Crabby Cragnotti
</P>
<P>
   Two days after his team lost its hold on the Serie A lead, Lazio
chairman Sergio Cragnotti was complaining of poor officiating in a
1-1 draw with Fiorentina. But is the tomato-sauce tycoon more upset
that his club might be missing out on its first scudetto in 25
years or the fact that its value on the Milan stock exchange
dropped by $22 million (6 percent) on Monday as a result?
</P>
<P>
   Cragnotti said the referee should have given a penalty kick to
Lazio's Marcelo Salas on Saturday. At the same time, a hat trick by
Oliver Bierhoff paced AC Milan to a 4-0 rout of Empoli and a
one-point lead over Lazio heading into the final weekend of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always hope people are acting in good faith,'' Cragnotti
said in an interview Tuesday with Gazzetto dello Sport. ``But there
are strange things happening, and I wouldn't want the usual mess-up
to happen this Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ronaldo was denied a penalty kick in a game down the
stretch as Inter Milan lost the title to Juventus. Naturally, Milan
boss Adriano Galliani lashed out at Cragnotti. ``I didn't know that
clubs that are listed on the stock exchange are entitled to
different treatment from the others,'' Galliani said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Milan travels to Perugia, while Lazio has a tougher
task, playing at Parma four days after the Cup Winners' Cup final.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia: League abandoned
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the Yugoslavian first-division season,
interrupted since March 24 because of NATO bombings, has been
called off. The federation will decide later this month how to
determine a winner and runner-up to send to the European Champions'
League next year. Partizan Belgrade had been leading with 66
points, two more than defending champion Obilic. Last week, UEFA
ruled that Yugoslavia's national team would not be allowed to play
home matches during Euro 2000 qualifying. A June 8 match against
Malta originally scheduled for Belgrade has been moved to Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Women: USA meets Brazil
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm is poised to make soccer history Saturday in what
should be a good test for the U.S. women, who meet Brazil in a
friendly in Orlando (7:30 p.m., ESPN2). Hamm needs one goal to
become the all-time international scorer after tying Italy's
Elisabetta Vignotto at 107 on Sunday against Holland. Brazil is a
potential Women's World Cup semifinal opponent for the U.S., which
completed its roster Monday with few surprises. In addition to
Hamm, 12 other veterans of the 1996 Olympic champion team are
included.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
