<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PARENTAL NOTIFICATION BILL OFF LINE FOR NOW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ An emotionally charged parental notification
bill for minors seeking abortions skidded off track Wednesday in
the Texas House but is expected to be back up for consideration by
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's fate still hangs in the balance, but backers insisted
it remains alive, even after enduring the infamous use of a
parliamentary procedure on House rules that killed a similar
measure last session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping for the best, expecting the worst maybe,'' said
Rep. Dianne Delisi, R-Temple, the House sponsor of Senate Bill 30.
When the bill returns to the House, it will be the third time that
body has been set to vote on the controversial issue.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic turn of events began after a proposal by Rep.
Patricia Gray, D-Galveston, to allow adult family members _
grandparents, aunts, uncles and adult siblings _ to be notified
instead of parents was shot down by a 77-68 vote. Opponents are
adamant that only a judge should be allowed to decide if there is
good reason n &UR; A
</P>
</TEXT>
