<HEADER>
A3893 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-BILL20-COX     05-19 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-BILL20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Point of order takes life out of parental notification bill
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For the second session in a row, a House
lawmaker wielding a legislative technicality may kill a bill that
would force doctors to contact the parents of an underage girl
seeking an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Harold Dutton (D-Houston) on Wednesday employed a maneuver
called a ``point of order'' to pull a parental notification bill
from the House floor, endangering a highly popular GOP measure with
less than 11 days before the end of the session.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton argued that the minutes from one of the State Affairs
Committee's hearings on Senate Bill 30 were inaccurate, a
contention House Speaker Pete Laney upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, committee members scrambled into a room just off
the House chamber to approve the bill again. Soon after, lawmakers
scheduled it for another floor debate Friday. The quick turnaround
highlighted the precarious position the bill is now in: House rules
mandate that it must by approved by that body by Tuesday, so any
delay _ or another point of order _ could bury it for the session.
``There is still life in it, but there is no additional room for
error,'' said Rep. Sylvester Turner (D-Houston). ``In this
legislative process, it is much easier to kill than to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutton said he'll try to raise another point of order before he
allows the House to vote on the parental notification bill he
derailed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to kill things around her twice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton's maneuver could jeopardize a measure that Gov. George W.
Bush hoped to point to as one of his legislative accomplishments
when he hits the presidential campaign trail next month. Bush, who
is anti-abortion rights, has already drawn fire from religious
conservatives for being less than strident on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion rights activists railed against Dutton's action as
a perversion of the political process. Last session, Rep. Debra
Danburg (D-Houston) used a technical objection to kill a similar
parental notification bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am frustrated beyond belief,'' said Bill Price of Texas
Right-To-Life. ``This is what causes people to drop out of the
political system. This is cynicism at its worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Price said Bush was involved in efforts to forge a compromise
bill in the last several weeks, but that he was ``disappointed with
the effort up to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Most members of the Texas House support parental notification.
But they disagree on the alternatives that should be available to
girls who don't want to tell their parents. One option, asking a
judge to waive the parental notification requirement, must be
included to make the measure constitutional. That safeguard is
designed mostly to protect girls who are being sexually abused at
home.
</P>
<P>
   But some lawmakers argue that many girls would rather endanger
themselves by getting an abortion from someone other than a doctor
than tell their parents or face a judge. Rep. Patricia Gray
(D-Galveston) offered an amendment to the bill which would have
allowed a girl to notify a grandparent, an adult sibling or an
adult aunt or uncle rather than a parent. The House rejected the
amendment on a 77-68 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton said he had agreed not raise the technical objection
unless the Gray amendment failed. Once it did, he let fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They live in a world where there are two parents at home _
kind of the old Ozzie and Harriet sort of thing,'' Dutton said of
those who oppose Gray's amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you live in a city where the little girl tells me her
mother died last year of AIDS, her father is in prison, now she's
being raised by her grandmother and there's never been any formal
proceedings to create a guardianship, what are we supposed to do
about that situation?''
</P>
<P>
   During floor debate on her amendment, Gray argued that it would
reduce the number of abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be party to a child having an abortion because
she feels she has no other option,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the amendment said a parent _ not an uncle in a
faraway city, an elderly grandparent or a 19-year-old sister who
just started college _ is the only one equipped to guide a girl
through a traumatic procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing with this is saying that a third party can
step in between a parent and their child without first having made
any showing whatsoever that there is something wrong with the
relationship between the parent and the child,'' said Rep. Phil
King (R-Weatherford).
</P>
<P>
   Though they were enraged by Dutton's maneuver, anti-abortion
activists expressed confidence that the House eventually will
approve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will come back, we will get this bill through. It will go
to the governor's desk,'' said Chuck Anderson of the Texas
Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson pointed out that 39 states have notification or consent
laws and that four-fifths of Texans want a parental notification
law, according to a recent Texas Poll. The poll did not ask about
alternatives to notifying parents.
</P>
<P>
   Kae McLaughlin of the Texas Abortion and Reproductive Rights
Action League described Dutton's maneuver and the two-day delay as
``nothing for me to get excited about.'' She said it would,
however, give her time to convince more lawmakers to vote for
Gray's amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our kids are safe _ we're not jumping up and
down,'' McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
