<SLUG> BC-LEVITZ-REBIRTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEVITZ TOUTS EXPANSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Today in 1st, 12th grafs refers Thursday.) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARITA, Calif. _ Levitz Furniture Corp. will kick off
what officials call a re-birth of the company today with the grand
opening of a Santa Clarita Valley store, the first expansion since
the company filed for bankruptcy in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The newest store sports an open layout and a new merchandise
mix. Both are meant to reposition the company, which analysts say
suffered because its furniture failed to keep up with customers'
tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a milestone,'' said Ed Grund, chairman and chief
executive officer of the Boca Raton, Fla.-based company. ``We think
this signals to the consumers, the vendors and ourselves that we
have the capability and wherewithal to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   The company chose a good time to expand.
</P>
<P>
   The furniture industry had record sales of $57.8 billion in
1998, said Jerry Epperson, an analyst with Wachovia Securities.
Sales this year are expected to increase slightly over that - &QC; evel,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new store _ the 64th in the Levitz chain _ has been open in
the Valencia Marketplace since April 10 and has already generated
significant interest, said sales manager Anthony Tapia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past 10 days we've sold $100,000 with no promotion at
all,'' he said. ``It's a very good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   The store's target is $400,000 to $500,000 in sales every month,
but Tapia said he is hoping for an average of $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   The success or failure of the roughly 20,000-square-foot Santa
Clarita store is especially important for Levitz. The company is
still in the midst of a Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization, and
it announced the closing of 27 stores late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The opening is part of a broader effort to grow the company
where housing markets are growing, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very bullish about Valencia,'' Grund said. ``We would
have actually preferred a larger store but it wasn't available and
we wanted to be here now.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's ceremony coincides with the official re-opening of the
company's Huntington Beach and Redondo Beach stores.
</P>
<P>
   The remodels are part of the company's effort to revitalize the
lagging chain by closing stores in weaker markets, revamping
merchandise mixes and changing the company's image.
</P>
<P>
   The first Levitz store opened in 1910.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
