<HEADLINE>
BALKANS TURN OUT TO BE CELEBRITY HOT SPOT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Christie Brinkley  &LR; is going to the Balkans, &LR;  to visit Sarajevo
with the USO-Department of Defense Operation Allied Force tour,
featuring Ford supermodels. Brinkley's agent said she'd be
``visiting the military bases, signing autographs, getting
handshakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley thus joins the ranks of celebrities, including
 &UR; Richard Gere &LR; ,  &UR; Vanessa Redgrave &LR; ,  &UR; Bianca Jagger &LR; , &UR; Roger Moore &LR; 
and  &UR; Joyce Maynard &LR; , who's been getting her name in the paper
elsewhere for selling the love letters of  &UR; J.D. Salinger &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Gere was one of the first to make the trip. ``We learned a lot
from Gere's visit,'' a Macedonian representative to UNICEF told the
Ottawa Times. ``The problem is the focus can end up on the
celebrity and the stir they cause rather than the problems of the
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore who came bearing toys that caused near-riotous excitement,
refused to be driven around and stayed at a simple hotel. Still,
said UNICEF worker  &UR; Enver Mehmeti &LR; , his visit didn't really help.
``These children don't even know who Roger Moore is because he was
James Bond such a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ First in line outside the Grand Ballroom of the San Francisco
Hilton Hotel yesterday, waiting to get into  &UR; Dan &LR; 
 &UR; Quayle &LR; 's Commonwealth Club address, was  &UR; Bill McCarthy &LR; . He said
he had already seen the new ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the former vice president, when we asked why Quayle was
there when he could have been at the movie, he looked a bit
stunned. ``Is it open?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nosing around in the education and psychology library at UC
Berkeley,  &UR; Martin Schaaf  &LR; came upon a copy of the Journal of Social
Behavior and Personality, which contained a paper on ``Author
Perceptions of Positive and Negative Editor Behaviors in the
Manuscript Review Process'' (or Why They Hated It).
</P>
<P>
   _ A sculpture of the head of &UR; Vladimir Lenin &LR; , which said was on
display outside the Red Square restaurant in Las Vegas, has been
stolen. Restaurant management said the crime was particularly
odious because ``We had planned to freeze the head in a block of
ice that would be carved into a table and displayed in our vodka
locker. We don't care who has the head, we just want it back.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Singing books: The Lyric Opera of Chicago is planning operatic
versions of  &UR; Arthur Miller &LR; 's ``A View From the Bridge'' and &UR; F.
Scott Fitzgerald &LR; 's ``The Great Gatsby'' next season, reports BBC
Music magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whizzes at Procter &AMP; Gamble aren't the only ones who have been
buying web domains with negative connotations. The  &UR; George W. &LR; 
 &UR; Bush  &LR; campaign owns bushbites.com, bushsucks.com and several more
raunchy ones. Also bought: bushwhitman.com, bushpataki.com and
several similar names.
</P>
<P>
   _ The proud San Francisco mother of a new Princeton graduate
forwards a Daily Princetonian story about the end-of-year discovery
by authorities of a hot tub one student had installed in his
60-square foot room.
</P>
