<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STICKING TO ISSUES PAYS OFF FOR PHILADELPHIA MAYORAL PRIMARY
WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ In winning the Democratic primary on Tuesday to
succeed Edward G. Rendell as mayor of Philadelphia, John F. Street
held tightly to his issue-oriented message in the face of personal
attacks that nearly defeated him.
</P>
<P>
   While other candidates in the crowded field used attack
advertising in their campaigns, Street tried to ignore the barrage
and managed to win by a slim margin over his most aggressive
opponent in the race, Marty Weinberg.
</P>
<P>
   Street, 55, who resigned as city council president to run for
mayor, captured 100,902 votes, 35.5 percent of the total, to 89,041
votes, or 31.3 percent, for Weinberg, an aide to former Mayor Frank
Rizzo who was making his first run for elective office.
</P>
<P>
   John White Jr., a former head of the city housing agency and the
state welfare department, finished third with 61,816 votes for 21.7
percent. Happy Fernandez, a former city council member and the
first woman to run a credible race for mayor of Philadelphia, won
17,952 votes, 6.3 percent. Dwight Evans, a state legislator, had
13,290, 2.7 percent, and Queena R. Bass.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer then 30 percent of the city's 980,000 registered voters
turned out, about the average level of participation for a
primaries in Philadelphia, a city of 1.47 million people, about 40
percent black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am enormously pleased about the way I conducted my
campaign,'' Street said Wednesday at a victory lunch with Rendell
and other city leaders. ``But as the winning candidate, I now have
to do what I can to bring the party together, not just for me but
for the city of Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Street's success on Tuesday flowed from his smooth
working relationship with Rendell, a popular Democrat who is barred
from seeking a third consecutive four-year term. Over the years,
they worked closely together, drawing back Philadelphia from a
fiscal abyss in the early 1990s with programs of economic austerity
that led to budget surpluses and urban renewal throughout many
parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   It came as no surprise that Rendell gave Street, one of four
black candidates in the primary, a hardy endorsement. But in the
November general election, Street will face a Republican opponent
who also played a major role in the city's turnaround, Sam Katz,
who ran unopposed on Tuesday. As an expert in municipal finance,
Katz, 49, was one of the first consultants Rendell sought out to
stabilize the city's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Katz ran unsuccessfully for mayor in 1991 and for governor of
Pennsylvania in 1994, and in a city where registered Democrats
outnumber Republicans by almost 4-to-1, it might appear that he has
a difficult task ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But aides said his campaign strategy for the general election
will be to attract Republicans and the considerable number of
Democrats who did not vote for Street in the primary, including
many black voters.
</P>
<P>
   It is a calculation that strategists for Katz helped bring about
through the unusual decision to inject him into the Democratic
advertising wars. Katz ran commercials that attacked the two
Democrats he least wanted to face in the fall, Weinberg and White.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the aides said, Katz preferred a showdown with
Street, whose political fervor through years as a black community
leader most sharply contrasted with his own.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster Street's chances in the primary, Katz ran
advertisements that questioned Weinberg's and White's credibility
and management skills.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Katz said in an interview, Street's close
relationship with Rendell provides him an opening to portray Street
as a status quo candidate who is resistant to bolder solutions to
the city's most intractable problems.
</P>
<P>
   As examples, Katz said, he favors school vouchers to offer
children alternatives to troubled public schools and a faster
reduction of the city wage tax as a means to stimulate economic
development. Street opposes vouchers and favors a slower reduction
of the wage tax.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to make his case that more drastic measures are necessary,
Katz pointed out that for all the progress in the Rendell-Street
years, the city has lost 150,000 residents and 40,000 jobs since
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg, meanwhile, focused most of his attacks on Street, the
campaign front-runner who won glowing endorsements from the city's
three leading newspapers _ The Inquirer, The Daily News, and The
Tribune, the last of which has a mostly black readership.
</P>
<P>
   Playing largely to the same middle-class and working-class white
voters who supported Rizzo, Weinberg used television commercials
that showed 18-year-old images of Street shoving a reporter and
throwing water in the face of a city council staff member,
Weinberg's way of suggesting to voters that Street might be too
unstable to lead the city government.
</P>
<P>
   Other Weinberg advertisements cited financial problems Street
once had, including the two times he sought personal bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Street did not respond in his commercials until
late in the campaign and then only to admonish Weinberg for
attacking him and injecting an element of race in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Street focused on issues like seeking more state
revenues to improve public schools and expanding economic
development as a way to aid some of Philadelphia's neighborhoods,
where residents are suffering from substandard housing, joblessness
and high crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of working together, Philadelphia has become a can-do
city, and it's important for us to continue that work,'' said
Street, who would become the city's second black mayor, after W.
Wilson Goode, who preceded Rendell. ``The first step is to make
sure we heal the wounds of the primary. I'm sure all the candidates
will do their fair share to bring the party and the city back
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
