<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ENVIRONMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATORS SEEKS TO BOOST BUSH'S ENVIRONMENTAL RECORD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ From improving Texas air quality to debating
whether to turn West Texas into a national dump for low-level
radioactive waste, the Legislature on Thursday is setting the stage
to establish Gov. George W. Bush's environmental record for the
2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bush) may not be able to win as an environmentalist, but he
certainly could lose if he can't show the soccer moms that their
kids are going to have clean air,'' said Tom Smith, state director
of 8`Y envi.K++W,[H95R4onsumer group Public Citizen.
</P>
<P>
   While the House debates two Bush-backed bills Thursday dealing
with the clean-up of grandfathered industrial plants built before
the passage of the 1971 federal Clean Air Act, the Texas Senate is
poised to debate a bill that would allow private companies to run
nuclear waste dumps in West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who may face environmentally oriented Democrat Al Gore in
the 2000 general election campaign, expressed concern Wednesday
about the nuclear waste bill.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he has always backed a compact with Maine and Vermont
because it limited how much nuclear waste Texas would take, but the
bill pending before the Senate would allow private operators to
accept federal Department of Energy waste from across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not want Texas to become the dumping ground for nuclear
waste,'' Bush said. ``I am concerned that our regulatory agencies
won't be able to control the amount of waste coming into our
state.''
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation also creates discomfort for Bush because one
of the companies pushing the bill, Pasadena-based Waste Control
Specialists, is owned by some of Bush's top campaign contributors.
Bush said he has not talked to his backers about the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The company's majority owner, Dallas investor Harold Simmons,
gave $35,000 to Bush's re-election campaign last year. Simmons also
is a major donor to the national Republican Party committees,
giving $465,000 during the 1996 and 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Another Waste Control owner is Kent Hance, a Bush friend who
donated $31,000 to the governor's re-election. And one of Simmons'
Dallas consultants, state Public Safety Chairman Jim Francis, is a
Bush friend and his 1994 campaign finance chairman.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush faced pressure last year on whether a state-run
low-level nuclear waste site should be located at Sierra Blanca,
Bush avoided the issue by saying the decision was up to his Texas
Natural Resources and Conservation Commission members. The TNRCC
killed the Sierra Blanca site.
</P>
<P>
   But if the nuclear waste privatization bill passes the
Legislature, the buck will stop on Bush's desk.
</P>
<P>
   Bush declined to say Wednesday whether he would veto any nuclear
waste bill that allows DOE waste to be imported into Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, Envirocare of Texas, wants a subcontract with
the Texas Low-Level Radioactive Waste Authority to run the compact
site which would have been located at Sierra Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bush's national political allies, former South Carolina
Gov. David Beasley was among Republicans in South Carolina,
California and North Carolina who lost statewide elections last
year largely because of their stands on environmental issues.
Beasley's opponent said he had turned South Carolina into a
``nuclear pay toilet'' by supporting a commercial radioactive waste
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Two bills before the House will spotlight Bush's role in
cleaning up grandfathered industrial plants.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supports one bill that allows the owners of such plants to
come into voluntary compliance with the Clean Air Act if they join
a state compliance program by 2001. He also supports an electric
deregulation bill that will require power companies to bring their
power plants into compliance with the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have protested the voluntary compliance bill
this legislative session, demanding that the compliance be required
and saying the bill is Bush's sop to industries that have put more
than $300,000 into his presidential campaign so far. Several
environmentalists have been arrested at the Texas Governor's
Mansion while protesting the Bush measure.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has contended that he is the first governor even to try
to bring the grandfathered plants into compliance. He said
Wednesday that the clean-air provisions in the electric
deregulation bill will substantially improve Texas air quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am for clean air in the state of Texas,'' Bush said. ``The
electric dereg bill, which will substantially reduce air emissions
in the state of Texas, is a very good piece of public legislation
and I intend to sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said clean air will define his administration's
environmental legacy in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to ask the question, is the air cleaner since I
became governor, and the answer is yes,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Texas has been fighting with the federal Environmental
Protection Agency since Bush has been governor over air quality in
the Dallas-Fort Worth area. And a recent report by the TNRCC
indicated that air quality in the Houston Gulf Coast area has
actually declined since Bush has been governor.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore has made environmental reform one of the
hallmarks of his government service this decade. Bush declined
Wednesday to discuss Gore, who faces a challenge for his party's
presidential nomination from former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley of New
Jersey. But the governor said he does believe the environment will
be an important issue in the 2000 contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The environment) should be an issue,'' Bush said. ``The
environment is incredibly important for America in the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   While there have been no specific legislative issues involving
global warming this year, Bush's position on whether global warming
exists has been changing almost as fast as the Texas weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science is still out on issues like global warming. We
need to gather enough data that if there are any public policy
decisions, we base them on science,'' Bush said March 11.
</P>
<P>
   But last week Bush said global warming exists: ``The last time I
wasn't certain of the science. I've had some briefings recently,
and I'm becoming convinced that the science proves there's global
warming.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
