<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3912 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FROG-FRENZY-TEX     05-19 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FROG-FRENZY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURRIN FROGS WILL SAVE FESTIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELIZABETH CAMPBELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Texas _ Lake Worth's frantic, frenzied effort to
find frogs is finally finished.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen frogs are scheduled to be flown in Thursday from
Rochester, N.Y., saving Lake Worth's 16th Annual Bullfrog
Festival's signature event, a frog race at 2 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, I really thought we would have to cancel the
races,'' said Judy Haas, executive director of the Northwest
Tarrant Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Haas and other volunteers canvassed Texas, Louisiana and other
nearby states for a bullfrog source for the frog festival in Lake
Worth, a Fort Worth suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Haas' daughter, Michelle Werthen, even made a leap at some
bullfrogs on the 16th hole of2the Rolling Hills Country Club golf
course in nearby Arlington, Texas. After a 2 1/2-hour expedition,
Werthen, 33, was left with mud-caked pants, little dignity and one
``bad-eyed'' frog.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber is paying $125 to Ward's Natural Science
Establishment in Rochester for the frogs. Bob Iveson, Ward's
biology production manager, isn't surprised about Lake Worth's frog
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The bullfrog population isn't declining, but there is a global
amphibian crisis as developments take over the ponds and puddles
that frogs favor, Iveson said. Ward's frogs come from Louisiana, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a pond becomes a parking lot, the habitat is gone
forever,'' Iveson said.
</P>
<P>
   Ward's mostly supplies frogs to schools for science classes, but
it also handles unusual requests and ships all over the world, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We guarantee live delivery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After a newspaper article last week about Lake Worth's frog
search, Haas said, she received several leads. Dan Burt, an
Arlington golfer, informed Haas about the frogs he encounters on
the Rglming Hills course.
</P>
<P>
   Burt gigged frogs while growing up and reckoned that his East
Texas know-how gave him the edge on any citified frog living on a
golf course. Gigging is usually a nighttime operation, but Burt
said the golf course frogs seemed so laid back that he figured a
daylight hunt would be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, he underestimated the jumpy critters.
</P>
<P>
   Burt joined Werthen and her husband, Cory, at the 16th hole
about 8 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Werthen, who said she waded knee-deep into the pond, described
her adventure: ``The frogs just looked at me and smiled as if to
say, `Catch me if you can.' Every time I'd get close, they'd jump
back in the water. I managed to sneak up on one and caught him.''
</P>
<P>
   That lone frog had impaired vision, Werthen said. Nonetheless,
she took it home, but the frog escaped from her apartment patio and
is on the lam somewhere in Hurst.
</P>
<P>
   Werthen has been recruited to take care of the irreplaceable new
frogs, and she promises to keep a closer eye on them.
</P>
<P>
   The six bullfrogs will be packed in plastic bags with water and
extra oxygen and cushioned in moss before they are put into boxes.
Werthen will store them on her patio in a prefabricated fish pond
with netting securely clamped across the top. She has gathered some
crickets for the frogs.
</P>
<P>
   Werthen said she hopes that Lake Worth High School will take on
the duty of repopulating Lake Worth with bullfrogs. That way, the
festival can use home-grown talent next year.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
