u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      05-19 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DISCOUNTS DISCORD FOR SAKE OF TALKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration Wednesday played down
the divisions among its NATO allies over the air war against
Yugoslavia, in what appeared to be a conscious effort not to
accentuate those differences as delicate talks for a peace
settlement were under way.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreements among allies occurred as the Russian envoy,
Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, presented the allies' demands on ending the
war to the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, in Belgrade. But
behind the scenes Cabinet members and even the president were on
the telephone trying to repair the breach.
</P>
<P>
   The split between Britain and the United States prompted a
90-minute telephone conversation on Tuesday night between Prime
Minister Tony Blair and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Blair was portrayed the previous day as being in favor of
sending ground troops into Kosovo, a move that Clinton had strongly
opposed. Blair's foreign minister, Robin Cook, said in Brussels on
Monday that NATO should be prepared to send an international
security force into Kosovo without the permission of Milosevic,
another position that the White House has opposed.
</P>
<P>
   During the first few minutes of their telephone conversation,
Clinton expressed his displeasure at the stories from London and
Brussels which exposed their differences, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The president asked Blair if he could ``please get control'' of
those who appeared to be speaking on his behalf, one official said.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's talk of ground troops also troubled Clinton because it
played into domestic politics here, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   By promoting a need for ground troops, Blair was inadvertently
allowing a comparison to be drawn between Clinton's reticence on
the issue and the stance of Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who favors a
ground operation and has criticized Clinton's failure to embrace
the option.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official explained that Clinton's remarks on
Tuesday, when he said he would not rule out ground troops, were an
attempt to publicly deflect attention from disagreements among the
allies on the subject, a White House official said.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's plea, the conversation with Blair concentrated
on policy and what moves the alliance should make, the official
said. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also expressed to
colleagues her frustration Wednesday at keeping the alliance intact
as it moved toward its ninth week of the bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia, one of the colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's main responsibility is to keep the allies in line; on
Tuesday and Wednesday she spoke by telephone to the foreign
ministers of Britain, France, Italy and Germany, said her
spokesman, James P. Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   The top issues she dealt with were the proposal by Italian Prime
Minister Massimo D'Alema for a bombing pause once the U.N. Security
Council adopts a resolution on Kosovo and the statement by German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder that his country would oppose a land
war.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official involved in the Kosovo policy
said the appearances of disarray in NATO were ``very disturbing''
because they served to prolong the war ``we're trying to bring to
an end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every sign of disarray'' could encourage Milosevic to wait out
the alliance as members showed fatigue, the official said. With
growing signs of discontent among his troops, Milosevic also
appeared to be hurting, but with his firm rule he has the luxury of
disregarding his domestic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety about the ambiguous signals from the allies was also
expressed on Capitol Hill, where Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., the
ranking member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, described
the situation within NATO as ``perilous.''
</P>
<P>
   Biden, who has argued since the war began that the future of
NATO depended on success in Kosovo, said he was concerned that as
the air war progressed, fatigue among some allies would mount.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern for the administration is the timing of the
growing divisions within NATO. Administration officials were
downplaying their expectations of what Chernomyrdin might achieve.
It was far from clear what tone Chernomyrdin adopted with the
Yugoslav leader, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian, whom the United States has chosen as the best
chance to bring Milosevic close to NATO's demands, has to decide
what he can sell to his pro-Serbian Russian audience at home and
may turn out to be softer in his tone than the administration would
like, one official said.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomrydin told Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, with
whom he spent time preparing for the encounter with Milosevic, that
he would use the agreement by the seven leading industrial nations
and Russia as his ``talking points,'' an administration official
said.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement, reached two weeks ago, provided a framework for
how to reach a conclusion to the war with Milosevic, but was short
on specifics.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO official familiar with the talks between Talbott and the
Russian envoy in Helsinki on Tuesday and Wednesday said the Russian
had not moved in his position opposing an international security
force with NATO command and control. Further, there was no
agreement on the complete withdrawal of Serb troops from Kosovo
which NATO says it wants, the envoy said.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin was also insisting that a bombing pause, which
Washington opposes, was necessary to test Milosevic's intentions of
withdrawing from the province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
