u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SECULARISM-360     05-19 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SECULARISM-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGER AT ULTRA-ORTHODOX REVIVES A PARTY IN ISRAEL
</HEADLINE>
   (With ISRAEL-POLITICS) 
(rk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ When Tommy Lapid left a successful career as a
political commentator and television talk-show host to head the
secular Shinui Party two months ago, it was limping along with
barely enough support to win a seat in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Israeli elections on Monday, after an aggressive,
one-issue campaign directed entirely against ultra-Orthodox
parties, Lapid's new, militant Shinui emerged with six seats,
riding a backlash among secular Israelis against the rising power
of religious parties allied with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raised the banner of secular rebellion,'' Lapid said in an
interview, taking credit for an electoral swing that also helped
another secular party, Meretz, win 10 seats in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are likely to join a new governing coalition led by
Ehud Barak, the prime minister-elect, but they face a strengthened
ultra-Orthodox camp, which has grown to 22 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Lapid, 67, has warned that he will not join a coalition with
ultra-Orthodox parties, and he has expressed interest in becoming
justice minister so he can fend off attacks on the judiciary by
ultra-Orthodox leaders angered by rulings they consider
anti-religious.
</P>
<P>
   In Lapid's view, such attacks are a part of ``an ultra-Orthodox
offensive aimed at civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Lapid was not always so liberal. During years of work as a
newspaper columnist, radio commentator and the host of the popular
television talk program ``Popolitica,'' he was given to
conservative outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   In one essay he inveighed against what he described as excessive
intervention by the Supreme Court in public affairs. In a
television program after a suicide bus bombing, he compared the
government of Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres to Jewish community
councils appointed by the Nazis to enforce their policies. He has
also grumbled against affirmative action programs promoting the
hiring of women.
</P>
<P>
   But on the issue of ultra-Orthodox influence in Israel, Lapid
has been a staunch secularist. In hard-hitting campaign ads, he
attacked what he called ``religious coercion,'' attempts by the
ultra-Orthodox to regulate public life in Israel according to
religious law.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This assault, as he sees it, reaches all corners of Israeli
life. The rabbis and political leaders challenge the authority of
the Supreme Court, contending that its rulings are anti-religious.
The Labor Ministry, controlled by the Sephardic ultra-Orthodox
party Shas, dispatches inspectors to enforce Sabbath closings on
shops. The Orthodox rabbinate authorizes marriages, supervises
burials and runs a network of kosher inspectors in restaurants and
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, Lapid says, ultra-Orthodox politicians have used
their position to extract generous state allocations for their
schools and institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have milked the state coffers,'' he said, accusing the
ultra-Orthodox of ``extortion.'' Outraged by such language, the
Orthodox leaders have compared Lapid's oratory to anti-Semitic
invective used by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   His high-profile style breathed new life into Shinui after he
was recruited by the party's only legislator, Avraham Poraz.
Running a single-issue campaign that depicted the ultra-Orthodox
parties as a threat to the secular Israeli majority Lapid attracted
growing numbers of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think Shinui would have won six seats by being
wishy-washy, you're wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An object of ultra-Orthodox rage, Lapid is now accompanied by
bodyguards. At his Tel Aviv apartment Wednesday afternoon, three
police officers arrived to check if he was safe. They were
responding to a message by an anonymous caller who said that Lapid
had been shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
