u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COCACOLA-FRAUD-NYT &LR;      05-19 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCACOLA-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRIBUTOR SETTLES FRAUD CASE AGAINST COCA-COLA ENTERPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Ga.)   (bl)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Maryland soft-drink distributor that sued Coca-Cola
Enterprises in federal court, accusing the bottler of fraud,
wiretapping and other tactics intended to drive the distributor out
of business, has agreed to drop the charges and settle its case.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Asman, a spokeswoman for Coca-Cola Enterprises, the
Coca-Cola Co.'s largest bottler, said the settlement terms,
completed Friday, were ``strictly confidential.'' But as part of
the settlement, the distributor, B.K. Miller of Clinton, Md., ``has
sold its Coca-Cola assets to Coca-Cola Enterprises and will no
longer be handling products of the Coca-Cola Co.,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with most settlements, there was no admission of liability
or fault on either side, and all claims were dropped,'' she said.
The case had been scheduled for trial Sept. 14 in U.S. District
Court in Greenbelt, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Mark London, a lawyer for B.K. Miller, confirmed that the case
had been settled but refused to give any details. The family-owned
B.K. Miller sold about 1.6 million cases of Coca-Cola products a
year, making it a significant customer of Coca-Cola Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for B.K. Miller filed the suit in 1997, but the case
first drew wide attention in January, when court papers were
unsealed at the request of The New York Times. The papers included
internal memorandums and documents filed by both sides that
provided an unusual public glimpse of some of the soft-drink
industry's business practices, including secret investigations of
distributors like B.K. Miller by Coca-Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   B.K. Miller's lawyers argued that Coca-Cola Enterprises wanted
to take over Miller's customers, which included vending accounts
and small stores. They cited a price increase for B.K. Miller,
followed by the bottler's shift in strategy to control more of the
vending business, a highly profitable segment of the soft-drink
industry.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the investigations, a private detective was found to
have filed false reports, which were submitted by lawyers for
Coca-Cola Enterprises to the court as evidence that B.K. Miller was
violating the Soft Drink Inter-Brand Competition Act, a 1980 law
intended to protect small bottlers. Telephone conversations
involving B.K. Miller employees were recorded without the parties'
knowledge, according to the complaint, and other companies were
told not to sell Coca-Cola products to B.K. Miller, because they
were told, the company had transshipped products in violation of
the law, that is, shipped products outside its designated
territory. Miller denied having done so.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Coca-Cola Enterprises countersued B.K. Miller last
November, accusing it of breach of contract, fraud and other
offenses in connection with the transshipping allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises was spun off from Coca-Cola Co. in 1986
and is a separate, publicly traded company, based in Atlanta. About
43 percent of its stock is held by Coke, its largest shareholder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0445 </DOCNO>
