<HEADER>
A3924 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-1STLD-WR     05-19 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURPRISE WITNESS SAYS OFFICER BRAGGED OF TORTURING A SUSPECT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Subs first 5 grafs for recasting and clarifications; combines
takes.)   (sw) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In surprise testimony, a police sergeant said on
Wednesday that the officer accused of torturing Abner Louima
boasted to him of carrying out the attack shortly after he said it
took place in the restroom of a Brooklyn police station.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant, Kenneth Wernick, said that Officer Justin A.
Volpe, using coarse language, told him in detail how he had rammed
a stick into Louima's rectum during the attack in the restroom of
the 70th Precinct station house in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he took a stick and put it five or six inches'' into
Louima's rectum, Wernick testified, ``and took it out and put it by
his mouth and teeth area, kind of like he was showing it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Aside from Louima's own account,  &LR;  Wernick's testimony, his
first public account of the events, was the most direct testimony
yet linking Volpe to a reported act of police torture that shocked
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking rapidly in loud tones in federal District Court in
Brooklyn, Wernick told of a conversation with Volpe that took place
after dawn on Aug. 9, 1997, shortly after prosecutors say Louima
was attacked with the stick by Volpe while another officer on
trial, Charles Schwarz, held him down.
</P>
<P>
   Louima, a 32-year-old Haitian immigrant, had been arrested in a
street melee outside a nightclub in  &UR; the  &LR; Flatbush &UR; section of
Brooklyn &LR; , and prosecutors say Volpe mistakenly thought Louima had
punched him in the disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   Wernick, who held the rank of officer at the time and is now
assigned to the Fifth Precinct in Manhattan, said the conversation
started with Volpe's telling him, ``I took a man down tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Wernick said Volpe then told him about using the stick against
Louima.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant said Volpe continued his account by saying that he
had hit Louima on the genitals and that he had ``held his hand over
his mouth and told him if he told anybody, he'd kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You want to go into the bathroom and see the
stick?''' the sergeant testified as Volpe, at the defense table,
alternated between watching him without expression, shaking his
head and writing in a notebook.
</P>
<P>
   Wernick said Volpe then took him into the station house restroom
to show him the stick.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in another area of the station house, Wernick said he
watched as Volpe pointed the stick at another officer's face and
said, ``Smell this. Smell this.''
</P>
<P>
   Wernick said Volpe then pointed the stick at him and demanded to
know if he could see feces on it. The sergeant testified that he
saw nothing on the stick, which he said was two to three feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Wernick said he last saw Volpe holding the stick outside the
station house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked outside by a large Dumpster and he held up the
stick,'' said Wernick, a burly, gray-haired man, holding up his
left arm to show how Volpe was holding the stick, as he sat on the
witness stand next to Judge Eugene H. Nickerson's bench.
</P>
<P>
   He did not say what Volpe did at that point with the stick,
which has never been found.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked away,'' the sergeant continued. ``I didn't want to be
involved at any point.''
</P>
<P>
   But earlier in his account, when Alan Vinegrad, an assistant
U.S. attorney, asked the sergeant whether he had believed that
Volpe had committed the torture, the sergeant said he had not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Vinegrad asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, because I didn't think anybody would do it,''
Wernick replied. ``And if they did it, they wouldn't talk about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wernick said that Volpe, 27, also gave him a report on the
street fight that had led to the arrest of Louima and a second
Haitian immigrant, Patrick Antoine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said there was a big fight outside some club, they were
acting like animals,'' the sergeant said Volpe had told him.
</P>
<P>
   He said Volpe reported that ``he got punched in the face, chased
a couple of people and caught somebody, but wasn't sure if it was
the guy'' who punched him.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe is also charged with beating Antoine, who had not been
involved in the melee, as he walked on a street near the nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's laywer, Marvyn M. Kornberg, is expected to begin
cross-examining Wernick on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wernick took the stand, Antoine testified, and in
addition to giving his version of his encounter with Volpe, he told
the jury about statements the officer had made to him as he took
him to the same station house restroom where prosecutors say Louima
had been attacked shortly before and where Sgt. Wernick said Volpe
had shown him the stick.
</P>
<P>
   The statements, as recounted by Antoine _ who testified in
Creole through an interpreter, though he said he understands
English _ included an apology to Antoine for having beaten him in
the street and an admission by Volpe that he had been acting
irrationally that morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me why was I following this guy,'' Antoine said,
apparently referring to someone else Volpe and other officers had
been chasing near the disturbance when Antoine walked by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I did not know what he was talking about, that I
was just going home and that he beat me,'' Antoine continued,
adding that Volpe ``then said he's sorry, he was feeling crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Antoine testified, the officer ``told me he
was like somebody who was going crazy'' and that ``when somebody
hits him, he hits the person back.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that after Louima was arrested, Volpe and
Schwarz and the two other officers on trial, Thomas Wiese and
Thomas Bruder, beat him in a police car before Volpe and Schwarz
attacked him with the stick in the restroom at the police station.
</P>
<P>
   All four are charged with violating Louima's civil rights. A
fifth defendant in the trial, Sgt. Michael Bellomo, is charged with
trying to cover up the reported beating in the police car.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg suggested in questioning Antoine that he had
misunderstood the officers' words during the conversation in
English. The lawyer also got Antoine to acknowledge that even
though he identified Volpe in court as the one who he said had
beaten him in the street, he had not had time to get a good look at
that officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
