<SLUG> BC-HOME-PUTTINGGREENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING AROUND THE HOUSE BECOMES MORE POPULAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Tommy Hale was never much of a lawn
fussbudget _ just dragged out the ol' mower once a week and gave it
a quick once-over.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, a particular patch of perfect green grass
governs his thoughts and spare time.
</P>
<P>
   Hale waters twice a day, mows three or four times a week and
fertilizes once a month.
</P>
<P>
   When all that's done, the 50-year-old construction manager putts
on his own professional-grade golf green behind his Mistletoe
Heights bungalow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're pretty delicate little guys,'' he said of the Tif 328
grass blades that he babies.
</P>
<P>
   Hale is among a growing number of golf enthusiasts willing to
spend thousands of dollars and countless hours installing and
maintaining quality putting greens in their own back yards.
</P>
<P>
   The professional golfers who tee off Thursday at the MasterCard
Colonial tournament in Fort Worth may never suspect that some of
the nicest greens around are tucked inside subdivisions, beside
lake houses and next to garden homes throughout North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Private putting grounds help golfers trim their handicaps _ and
give them a status symbol that makes owners of run-of-the-mill
swimming pools want to hide in the deep end.
</P>
<P>
   Outfitted with amenities such as sand traps and areas with
driving nets, the greens can cost as much as $20,000. Even simple
models installed by do-it-yourselfers run into the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   But the real costs sprout after installation. Caring for the
green can demand as much time, strategy and dedication as the game
itself. The prospect of daily coddling is enough to turn off some
potential putters.
</P>
<P>
   Or turn off their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to have to sleep with that mower when I
bought it,'' said Buddy Wisdom, a Granbury retiree who plunked down
$3,700 for a machine to shave his 2,500-square-foot green to
one-eighth inch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to almost have as much commitment to gardening as to
golfing,'' said Sam Peterson, farm manager of Gardner Turfgrass in
Tioga and Pilot Point.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said his company gets two or three dozen inquiries a
year from people interested in adding greens to their yards, but
only about a half-dozen go through with it. Another outfit, Thomas
Brothers Grass Co. of Granbury, says it sells sod to about a dozen
home putters a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really try to discourage them, but a good many people
think it's just like keeping their lawn,'' Peterson said. ``With
any turf grass, the shorter you cut it, there's a direct
correlation with depth of root system. That makes it more
susceptible to everything, insects and not having enough
nutrients.''
</P>
<P>
   Putters who pooh-pooh yardwork do have an alternative, and don't
call it Astroturf _ call it ``nondirectional synthetic nylon
putting turf.'' A Colleyville company that installs the stuff says
it is catching on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I envision in the future where these will be just as popular
as having a swimming pool in the back yard,'' said David Bowden,
owner of Bowden's Guaranteed Hydromulch and Sod in Colleyville. In
1992, Bowden's company formed a division, Eagle Putt, specializing
in synthetic greens.
</P>
<P>
   The product used is nylon, knitted into the backing rather than
tufted like most carpets, so it does not create an abnormal roll
for the ball, Bowden said. He still installs natural turf greens,
but he said the low-maintenance artificial turf has made home
greens more popular. His company does about a dozen a year, most of
them synthetic. Cost is about $6,500 to $20,000 either way, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a garden home, so I didn't want any grass. This was a
way to fill in next to my pool,'' said Don Allen, who hired Bowden
to install a 20- by 14-foot synthetic green in his back yard,
overlooking the 18th hole and clubhouse at Timarron Country Club in
the Dallas suburb of Southlake, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Purists may still want real grass, and some discover that they
like puttering around the yard as much as putting in it.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Allen never got a kick out a greenskeeping when he worked
at a golf course in high school. ``Man, I never want to mow another
green,'' he recalls thinking.
</P>
<P>
   But Allen, a professional drag racer who is no relation to Don
Allen, said he has come to enjoy tending the 1,200-square-foot
green he built behind his home in the Fort Worth suburb of
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   He fondly recalls renting a Bobcat to excavate the site, filling
it with a mixture of sand and peat, and then struggling to keep a
succession of grasses alive and thriving. The latest variety is a
coastal turf. He tilled 25 bushels of hair-thin sprouts into the
soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of relaxing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus,'' he added, ``it's helped my golf game a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   FOR YOUR INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   How to build a home putting green, according to Dwane Smith, sod
farm manager for Thomas Brothers Grass Co. of Granbury, Texas:
</P>
<P>
   Excavate the area down 10 to 12 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Install drainage pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Bury pipes under pea gravel, then sand.
</P>
<P>
   Contour the area with a variety of slopes so that not all the
putts are the same.
</P>
<P>
   Install sod or put down grass sprigs, choosing a variety
developed specifically for greens, such as Tif 328 or Mini-Verde.
</P>
<P>
   Top-dress with a quarter inch to a half-inch of sand to fill in
all the cracks and undulations.
</P>
<P>
   Water, fertilize and get ready to mow.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
