<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PALM PILOT WILL LINK TO INTERNET WIRELESSLY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J., N.Y.)  (rk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Untethering the Internet from desktop computers, the 3Com Corp.
intends on Monday to introduce the first version of its popular
Palm Pilot handheld computer that can tap into cyberspace using
wireless links.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of the unit, the Palm VII, could become a
milestone in the evolution of the Internet, allowing users to link
easily from cars or beaches. Though the Microsoft Corp., Psion of
Britain and other companies are trying to develop software to link
wireless phones to the World Wide Web, the Palm Pilot has already
come to dominate the handheld computer market in the United States
and enjoys a passionately loyal base of customers.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of the Palm VII will also bolster aspirations
by the BellSouth Corp. to remain at the forefront of wireless
communications. The Palm VII uses BellSouth's wireless data
network, which covers most big cities in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Though the new Palm Pilot does not provide phone calls, some
communications analysts and executives believe that will not prove
a huge hindrance. Most wireless phones that include data services
do not allow the user to talk and access the Internet at the same
time, because the screen is pressed against the user's cheek during
a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   3Com intends to make the new product, which will have a list
price of $599, available first in New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut. But people who buy the Palm VII in those areas will be
able to use it around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is now a seamless network,'' said Janet Boudris, senior
vice president for strategic marketing for BellSouth's wireless
data unit. ``So if you get on a plane in New York and get off in
L.A., the service will work seamlessly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palm VII uses a technology known as Web clipping, which
reformats Web pages to fit the Palm Pilot's screen. Among the
operations that have signed up to provide content to the new units
are Espn.com, for sports scores and information; Moviefone.com,
film schedules and reservations; United Parcel Service, package
tracking, and E-Trade stock quotes
</P>
<P>
   3Com initially wants to charge $9.99 a month for a basic package
of services, though a full complement could increase that to $24.99
a month or higher. Different price plans would also include
different numbers of wireless transactions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
