A3935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACHIAVELLI-CONFERENC     05-19 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACHIAVELLI-CONFERENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FOR A MODERN MACHIAVELLI 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The subject was Machiavelli's relevancy to Beltway
politics, and at first Rep. Henry Hyde listened far more than he
talked. He was strategically quiet in his own way, even when he was
praised as ``the great expert on the ruling couple's
Machiavellianism.''
</P>
<P>
   But finally, as conservative scholars and political operatives
teased him with notions of Machiavelli's 500-year-old hardball
political advice to princes and presidents, Hyde, the leader of the
House Republicans' failed attempt to purge President Clinton from
office, could no longer resist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Machiavellian pragmatism behind just about everything he
does,'' Hyde said, his tone more that of observing a universally
stipulated fact than of flashing an oratorical blade into his White
House nemesis. ``Machiavelli didn't have pollsters, interestingly
enough. This guy does, and he'll follow them slavishly without any
real principle or core conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Hyde, seeming amiable as ever, finally asked the one
question that he had for the Machiavelli forum at the American
Enterprise Institute, a decidedly partisan gathering where no one
was of a mind to defend Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would Machiavelli have approved of President Clinton's defense
in the impeachment, which was really spin?'' the impeachment
manager asked, wide-eyed with curiosity about whether expediency
should trump morality in political success.
</P>
<P>
   In a way the question hung in the air for the duration of the
90-minute forum Monday evening, lest even back-handed praise of
Clinton ever be uttered at such a gathering.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Michael A. Ledeen, the institute's resident scholar,
Reagan administration veteran of the Iran-Contra intrigues and
author of a new book on Machiavelli's modern utility, went for a
laugh line rather than a flat answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, Machiavelli was in favor of impeachment  &UR; and &LR; 
conviction,'' he insisted to general laughter.
</P>
<P>
   But then Ledeen offered what he rates as one of the ultimate
Machiavellian quotations in condemnation, if not praise, of the
Clinton presidency, citing the Renaissance master strategist's
analysis of why Italian princes failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought,'' Ledeen quoted, ``that it sufficed for a prince
in the writing rooms of palaces to think up a sharp reply, to write
a beautiful letter, to demonstrate wit and readiness in saying
words, to know how to weave a fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience, steeped in a kind of post-impeachment tristesse
that nags at the capital city, was hushed with delight as he
continued quoting: ``To keep many lascivious women around, to
conduct himself avariciously and proudly, to rot in idleness.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the audience merriment at that, Hyde, listening
carefully, seemed to withhold the ultimate political compliment
from the president _ that he had been triumphantly Machiavellian
across the past year of his sex-and-mendacity scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have mediocrities in positions of power,'' Hyde fairly
sighed in summarizing the problem of a contemporary political
establishment that, Democrats would point out, includes himself.
``Oh, I shouldn't say that,'' he added. ``We have  &UR; rhetorical &LR; 
mediocrities.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from an unabashed round of Clinton bashing, the forum
provided a glimpse at the folkways of this city's mutually grooming
political class, right and left, that could hardly be surprising to
Niccolo Machiavelli. ``Loved your piece,'' one conservative
polemicist said in greeting another star from the op-ed firmament.
</P>
<P>
   In belaboring the president, Ledeen did not find an entirely
open field for his thesis that ``Machiavelli is now, as half a
millennium ago, probably the most contemporary of all political
commentators.'' Irving Kristol, the neo-conservative patriarch,
smiled in cutting his friend off at the polemical pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for letting a bit of Machiavelli enter our souls _ but
not too much,'' Kristol said, conceding frustration at the ``mush''
of modern statesmanship but accusing Ledeen of going overboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much too nice to Machiavelli, who was one of the most
wicked men who ever lived,'' Kristol continued, cautioning modern
readers to take Machiavelli more literally than satirically in his
cunning prescriptions for wielding power and knifing friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``A real nasty piece of work,'' he said, comparing Machiavelli
with the Marquis de Sade in liberating general discourse while
taking credit for some larger sagacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realize that it's better to read him than to read the Charter
of the United Nations _ it makes more sense,'' Kristol maintained,
drawing laughter. Ledeen argued that Machiavelli, for all his
intriguing ways, was above all opposed to self-indulgent leaders.
</P>
<P>
   As the conservatives sought to come to terms with the man from
Florence and the one from Hope, the most shocking observation may
have been offered by former CIA Director James Woolsey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Machiavellian doesn't always mean cynical or relying on fear;
love can get the job done,'' the one-time spy master insisted,
citing George Washington's weathering a hard-times rebellion in the
Colonial Army by the sheer power of the troops' affection for him.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Hyde held out no such hope for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, we desperately need leaders,'' he said. Then again he
brightened in looking beyond Clinton. He cited a new bumper sticker
he saw in Texas. ``Nixon in 2000 _ he's not as stiff as Gore,'' the
Illinois congressman quoted with a big Machiavellian grin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
