<HEADLINE>
N.Y. TIMES CO. EXECUTIVE LEAVING TO PURSUE DEGREES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ariz.)   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stephen Golden, president of the forest products
group of The New York Times Co., announced Wednesday that he would
resign June 30 to pursue a law degree and a master's degree in
American Indian studies at the University of Arizona. Jennifer C.
Dolan, who has served as controller for the forest products group,
was named acting director.
</P>
<P>
   Golden, 52, has been a vice president of the company since 1990
and has additionally headed the forest products group since 1994.
He joined The New York Times as a reporter in 1966, leaving the
next year for a series of posts in radio and television. He
rejoined The Times in 1976, serving as a manager in several
departments.
</P>
<P>
   Golden is a member of the family that owns the controlling
shares of The Times Co. and is a first cousin of the chairman,
Arthur Sulzberger Jr. Golden's mother, Ruth S. Holmberg, is a
former director of the company and a sister of its chairman
emeritus, Arthur Ochs Sulzberger.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
