<HEADLINE>
FEBRUARY WINDOW KEY TO MCCAIN PRESIDENTIAL STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Sen. John McCain's presidential campaign has
developed a strategy that relies on wresting momentum from Texas
Gov. George W. Bush in the early New Hampshire primary, then
decisively winning McCain's home state of Arizona a week later.
</P>
<P>
   McCain aims to bruise Bush, the Republican front-runner, in New
Hampshire and beat him in Arizona. McCain then plans to shift his
focus to South Carolina, whose ``First in the South'' GOP primary
is expected to follow Arizona's by four days in February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's approach, revealed in interviews this week with members
of his campaign staff, appears to have little margin for error
because it pinpoints, by necessity, a very small window of time.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year of campaigning and fund-raising could come down to
three states whose primaries are expected to be held just 11 days
apart _ from Feb. 15-26. Strategists for McCain, who declared his
candidacy in April, believe he must mount a successful early
challenge to keep Bush from walking away with the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Although the dates won't be finalized until summer, the
candidates expect New Hampshire's primary to be on Feb. 15,
followed by Arizona's on Feb. 22, and South Carolina's on Feb. 26.
McCain aides said he will also concentrate on California's March 7
primary, assuming he is still a viable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa, a traditional early powerhouse in the presidential
nominating process, does not figure prominently in McCain's plans.
Although he insists he's not skipping Iowa altogether, McCain
apparently decided it wasn't worth it to painstakingly build the
county-by-county organization that is typically needed to turn out
Iowa voters on a cold winter's night.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Republican presidential primary, which had seemed on
the vergU S
</P>
</TEXT>
