<HEADLINE>
CSUN'S PRIETO LEADS BIG SKY HEPTATHLON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Brandi Prieto of Cal State Northridge was not
thrilled to be competing in the heptathlon at the Big Sky
Conference championships on Wednesday at CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was the rest of the heptathlon field.
</P>
<P>
   Prieto, a five-time Big Sky Conference triple-jump champion,
posted personal bests in three of the four events to finish as the
first-day leader with 3,088 points in the two-day, seven-event
competition. LaShaunda Fowler of Northridge is second with 2,920
and Hillary Merkley of Idaho State is third with 2,873.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can ask anybody I know and they will tell you I am a
triple-jumper who happens to do the heptathlon,'' Prieto said.
``This is not something I want to do for a long time. I was not too
enthused about it but I am learning to like it because I am
starting to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   The lanky 5-foot-10 Prieto took the lead from the start
Wednesday, posting the top marks in the first two events, the
100-meter hurdles (14.0 seconds) and the high jump (5-4\). Prieto's
time in the 100 hurdles shaved nine-hundredths of a second off her
previous best. She was only a quarter of an inch off her
career-best in the high jump.
</P>
<P>
   Competing in only her second heptathlon, Prieto also threw a
personal-best 32-11 in the shot put. The junior finished the
afternoon clocking 25.88 in the 200, dipping under 26 seconds for
the first time in the half-lap event.
</P>
<P>
   Prieto scored a conference-leading 4,710 points in her first
heptathlon last month at Azusa Pacific, but Wednesday's showing
placed her 210 points ahead of that pace. Prieto's objective was to
build a solid first-day lead to take pressure off the second day _
and the remainder of the meet.
</P>
<P>
   The heptathlon concludes today with the long jump, javelin and
800 meters. Competition in the meet, which runs through Saturday,
begins today with the decathlon at 10:45 a.m. The heptathlon starts
at noon.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the heptathlon, Prieto, who has provisionally
qualified for the NCAA championships in the triple jump with a Big
Sky record 42-11}, will compete in the 100 hurdles, long jump and
triple jump. Fowler is entered in the 100, 100 hurdles and long
jump. The two will also team on Northridge's 1,600 relay in the
Matadors' bid for its second outdoor title in three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when I PR in something, I immediately want to do
something better,'' Prieto said. ``I am just trying to beat what I
already had. Hopefully the points will come. I am not going to
worry about the 800 while I am doing the long jump. I m-H5ust
VkVW.Zk$9
</P>
