<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-BROTHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE'S BROTHER ACCUSED OF MAKING THREATS WITH A HANDGUN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A brother of Patrick J. Buchanan, the presidential
candidate and conservative commentator, will surrender to the
police on charges he threatened people with a handgun at the home
of a relative of a top State Department official, the Buchanan
family said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The family said Hank Buchanan, 61, who has a history of mental
illness, had checked himself into a hospital for treatment after
the incident on Sunday at the Northwest Washington home of Cody
Shearer, the brother-in-law of Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   Shearer issued a statement Wednesday saying he had received
anonymous death threats after being identified last week on the
cable-television program ``Hardball With Chris Matthews'' as the
man who tried to intimidate Kathleen E. Willey, a former White
House volunteer who has accused President Clinton of making an
unwanted sexual advance. Other media outlets repeated Matthews'
assertion.
</P>
<P>
   Shearer told the District Police that an intruder broke into his
garage on Sunday, slashed the tires on his cars, then waved a
handgun at two house guests who confronted him. The intruder fled
in a car parked nearby, and one of the guests noted the
license-plate number, Shearer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hank, through me, is fully cooperating with the authorities
and hopes to resolve this to everyone's satisfaction,'' said Tom
Buchanan, a lawyer who is representing his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Buchanan ran his own accounting firm but has had a history
of manic depression. ``He had been doing very well, and this is a
terrible setback,'' his sister Bay Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Shearer said he ``categorically denies'' any intimidation of Ms.
Willey, and Matthews apologized on Tuesday night for mentioning
him. ``I now regret not having spoken beforehand with him before I
mentioned his name on the air,'' Matthews told viewers. ``I should
never have brought his name up until we had vetted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Buchanan has visited his brother in the hospital and
will issue a statement on Thursday, Bob Adams, the candidate's
chief spokesman, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Willey has said that a man approached her outside her
Richmond, Va., home in January 1998, two days before she was to
give a deposition in Paula Jones' sexual-misconduct suit against
the president. The man asked her about her missing cat and her
children and noted that her tires had been slashed, she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Shearer said he was in California at the time, and has a
reputable witness to prove it _ former Secretary of State Warren
Christopher, who by coincidence sat next to him on a plane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
