<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3940 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-CEOS-SUMMIT     05-19 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-CEOS-SUMMIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTHA STEWART, OTHER CEO'S ALL BUSINESS AT MICROSOFT SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ A perfect question to ask decor and
entertainment doyenne Martha Stewart at Microsoft's third annual
CEO Summit, which began Wednesday at the company's headquarters
here, might have been:
</P>
<P>
   ``America needs to know: Just what do you use for wallpaper on
your PC?''
</P>
<P>
   But early in the question-and-answer period following the
summit's kickoff address, Stewart made it clear she wouldn't
welcome that frivolity. Like the other 100 or so company heads
gathered here from throughout the United States, the chairman and
chief executive officer of Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia LLC had
come to Redmond on business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wears a little thin when people constantly ask me (at
meetings like this) what we're having for lunch,'' she said. ``Our
e-commerce business is alive and well and thriving, and the
information I'm gathering here will help me add value.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and her colleagues, who collectively head companies
employing 6 million people, are spending three days exchanging
ideas on the role technology should play in their operations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other attendees: Larry Bossidy, chairman and CEO of
AlliedSignal Inc., Michael Dell, chairman and CEO of Dell Computer
Corp., Jacques Nasser, president and CEO of Ford Motor Co., and
Paul O'Neill, chairman and CEO of Alcoa.
</P>
<P>
   They said getting the right information quickly into the hands
of workers who need it remains a critical objective for business.
That goal will be addressed in sessions such as ``Turning
information into knowledge'' and ``Integrating strategy and
information technology'' during the summit.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the meeting's purpose to tout Microsoft's own
offerings, Microsoft Chairman and CEO Bill Gates stressed in his
keynote address. In fact, ``It's a checkpoint on our technology _
CEOs ask us why it isn't easier,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft technology did intrigue the participants, to judge
from the buzz. Attention centered on Digital Dashboard, a modified
version of the Microsoft Outlook e-mail interface that presents
workers on a corporate intranet (internal network) with a windowed,
customizable mixture of information.
</P>
<P>
   That could include a running stock ticker, icons for accessing
news items, specially categorized and ordered by priority for each
user or groups of users, and the ability to hear phone voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   It could also include key financial information clickable for
increasing layers of detail, real-time messaging, and the ability
to participate in virtual meetings complete with video.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those features can be made wireless and accessible
through palmtop computers. A wireless network tying together the
entire Microsoft campus is under construction, Gates said. In the
two buildings where it's already working, ``We can't get employees
to accept being moved, they're so into it,'' said Dan Leach, a
Microsoft spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   AlliedSignal's Bossidy said, ``We have dashboards, but they
aren't digitized yet. I'm gonna have a chat with our folks and find
out how far away we are from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Digital Dashboard can be created from Microsoft software in
existence today through advanced programming, said Jeff Raikes,
Microsoft's group vice president of sales and support.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also used the summit Wednesday to show off ClearType,
the replacement for the TrueType font system that the company hopes
will make electronic books a reality.
</P>
<P>
   This new font-rendering engine triples the clarity of type
displayed onscreen by controlling each of the three electron beams
making up each pixel, explained Bill Hill, who helped develop the
technology. Currently, the three beams can be controlled only as a
group. ClearType will be part of a forthcoming version of
Microsoft's Windows or Windows NT, although Microsoft won't say
which one.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is absorbing not just more attention but more money
at many companies, the CEOs said. Companies have typically spent
between 2 percent and 4 percent of their annual budgets on
information technology. But as electronic commerce, intranets and
e-mail become increasingly widespread within companies' operation,
``information technology is no longer discrete,'' so it's harder to
quantify that expenditure, said Ford's Nasser.
</P>
<P>
   The summit won't be all business. Some of the CEOs are rumored
to be dining at Gates' Medina mansion. Martha Stewart was probably
not asked to help cook.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
