<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY PROMOTES GRAND CANYON TRAIL SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 and STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND CANYON NATIONAL PARK _ With the Grand Canyon as a
backdrop, First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton on Wednesday launched a
73-mile network of trails designed to help end drive-by visits to
Arizona's premier natural wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Grand Canyon Greenway will ``reconnect us to
our own country,'' so that visitors will know ``what it looks like,
what it smells like.''
</P>
<P>
   She visited the South Rim as part of her ``Save America's
Treasures'' tour, which this week included a four-day swing through
the Southwest, with stops at Flagstaff's Lowell Observatory,
Bandelier National Monument in New Mexico and Mesa Verde National
Park in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of a national tour designed to help preserve important
cultural and historic sites. Clinton also is promoting her
Millennium Trails, a program designed to link communities with
trails for hikers, bikers, wheelchairs and people on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grand Canyon is a place that deserves our attention, our
resources, our stewardship,'' Clinton said on the lawn of the
historic El Tovar Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We imagine a network of miles of trails connecting every
community in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady cited efforts to preserve the nation's
``underground railroad,'' the South-to-North route of escaped
slaves; urban trails in Baltimore and New York City; and a trail on
the banks of the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Clinton announced 62 grants totalling $30
million for historic preservation, including money for: the Honanki
prehistoric cliff dwelling near Sedona, Mission San Jose near
Tumacacori, Theodore Roosevelt School at Fort Apache, and the Vail
Ranch House in Sonoita.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose our history, we lose our collective memory and we
endanger our future,`` Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   She was joined at the ceremony by Grand Canyon Superintendent
Rob Arnberger, who helped develop the Greenway project. He said the
trail system would help visitors better enjoy the sights of the
canyon, allowing them to smell pine trees instead of car exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will separate the park experience from the parking
experience,'' Arnberger said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Axelson, a trail designer confined to a wheelchair after a
rock-climbing accident, said the new trails will help enable him to
experience the beauty of the canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grand Canyon was always a place that I was a little afraid
to come to. This Greenway is going to provide a way for Americans
of all abilities to experience the `grand' in Grand Canyon,''
Axelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the $46 million trails project, which is
expected to begin later this fall, was funded through state,
federal and private grants.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with planned light-rail and electric-bus mass
transportation, the new trails will help eliminate cars from the
park.
</P>
<P>
   Cars in recent years have caused congestion, pollution and noise
along the canyon's scenic overlooks, which park officials and
visitors say degrades the experience of visiting the park.
</P>
<P>
   The trails would include bike racks, shelters, toilets, bridges
and tunnels that would minimize environmental damage and minimize
the need for any road crossings.
</P>
<P>
   The trails are planned to start at the Canyon View Information
Plaza, currently under construction at Mather Point, which would be
one of two light-rail transportation stations inside the park. The
other light-rail station would be at the Maswic transportation
center at Grand Canyon Village. Both would receive visitors who
would board outside the park at a light-rail station in Tusayan.
</P>
<P>
   The trails would run parallel to the light-rail system between
Mather Point and Tusayan. They also would run along the south rim
of the canyon: west from Mather Point to Hermit's Rest and east
from Mather Point to Desert View.
</P>
<P>
   Trails also are planned on the north rim, connecting Grand
Canyon Lodge, Point Imperial and Cape Royal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit also comes within weeks of an expected decision
by the U.S. Forest Service on a massive land trade just outside the
park's main entrance near Tusayan.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate anticipated growth in tourism, a Scottsdale firm,
Canyon Forest Village, wants to build thousands of hotel rooms,
restaurants and retail outlets. Along with a new natural history
museum and land for local housing, schools and other community
facilities, the project possibly would connect to the planned
light-rail system into the park.
</P>
<P>
   That plan, however, is contingent on the Kaibab National Forest
trading nearly a square mile of land to Canyon Forest Village. In
exchange, Canyon Forest Village would give nearly three square
miles of private land - former homesteads scattered throughout the
forest - to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Canyon Forest Village would include 1,270 hotel rooms and
270,000 square feet of retail space. It has been endorsed by
several environmental groups because water for the project will be
shipped by rail and pipeline from the Colorado River near the
Arizona-California border. It would have no effect on springs
inside the canyon.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service also is considering a plan to accommodate
future tourism that would not require a land trade. That plan is
proposed by a coalition of Tusayan businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
