</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-STANLEY-LETTER-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASH SOUGHT FROM BIG FIRM IN '98 LETTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARSTOW with JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, a leading securities firm
embroiled in a racial discrimination dispute with a former
employee, received a letter last August demanding a $15,000 payment
from a police informant who helped arrange a sting operation that
was about to result in the employee's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before Christian Curry, the dismissed employee, was
arrested last August for conspiring to plant evidence that would
bolster a discrimination lawsuit against the firm, the police
informant, Charles J. Luethke, sent a letter to Morgan Stanley's
legal department demanding a cash advance ``for services
rendered.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Curry, who is black, finally filed that
discrimination lawsuit, which included charges of false arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley denied any wrongdoing. But days after Curry's
arrest, the firm wired $10,000 into an account designated by the
informer, the Manhattan district attorney's office said this week.
Morgan Stanley also failed to disclose the payment to prosecutors,
which prompted the district attorney's office on Tuesday to dismiss
all charges against Curry and instead focus their investigation on
the informer and several Morgan Stanley officials.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley officials declined Wednesday to discuss details
of the $10,000 payment, saying they did not want to compromise the
continuing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that our conduct and the conduct of our employees
in this matter was entirely appropriate and legal,'' said Jeanmarie
McFadden, a spokeswoman for Morgan Stanley, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McFadden confirmed that Morgan Stanley received the Aug. 13
letter from Luethke, but she said that it did not accurately
describe his conversations with the firm. Luethke, a college
acquaintance of Curry, wrote a series of letters to the company
last summer in which he described his plan of helping Morgan
Stanley defend itself against a possible lawsuit from Curry. Four
months earlier, Curry was let go from the firm. The firm continues
to contend he was dismissed for expense account abuse, but the
dismissal came shortly after nude pictures of him found their way
into a gay men's magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Letters from Luethke to various employees of the firm do not
represent actual discussions between Morgan Stanley and Luethke,''
Ms. McFadden said, declining to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 13 demand for $15,000 was addressed to Carol Bernheim,
a lawyer for Morgan Stanley who handles employee relations.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, a copy of which was obtained by The New York
Times, Luethke asked Morgan Stanley to help him establish his own
business. ``In addition,'' he continued, ``I would like a cash
advance of $15,000 for services rendered to MS thus far. It would
be an unnecessary risk for my girlfriend and me to be in the New
York area when Christian is arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Luethke could not be reached for comment Wednesday, but on
Tuesday denied that he was paid by Morgan Stanley to inform on
Curry.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of his Aug. 13 letter to Morgan Stanley, Luethke
introduced Curry to an undercover police officer posing as a
computer hacker. The undercover officer told Curry that he could
plant bogus e-mail in Morgan Stanley's computer system to bolster
the discrimination lawsuit he was threatening. According to the
police, Curry paid the officer $200 and provided him with a fake
e-mail that contained racist and homophobic comments about him.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Curry intended to then cite bogus e-mail as
evidence of bigotry on the part of senior Morgan Stanley
executives. Instead, he was arrested August 20 and charged with
forgery, conspiracy and trespass of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Those charges were dropped on Tuesday, clearing the way for
Curry's lawsuit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Morgan Stanley Dean Witter regrets the decision on the part of
the district attorney's office to drop the charges against
Christian Curry,'' Ms. McFadden said. `` Curry's own criminal
attorney has conceded that Curry paid money to an undercover
officer to plant phony e-mail in our system to bolster a civil case
that he threatened to bring against the firm.''
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, filed in New York State Supreme Court, Curry
contends that the firm had ``a permissive and encouraging
environment'' for discrimination on the basis of race and perceived
sexual orientation. That climate extended to the executive suite,
the lawsuit contends. It names Phillip Purcell, chairman and chief
executive, John Mack, the president, and 12 other officials
including Ms. Bernheim at the firm as co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint details more than a dozen specific incidents of
reported discrimination. It states, for example, that immediate
superiors questioned Curry about why he wore a necktie bearing the
logo of Shinnecock Hills, an exclusive golf club in the Hamptons,
joking that Curry, as a black man, must have been a caddy, not a
full member.
</P>
<P>
   During a Christmas party, fellow Morgan Stanley employees
pressed Curry to wear an ``Afro wig'' and a pair of ``big lips'' in
order to poke fun at a black superior, the suit said. In another
reported incident, the suit contends that Curry was the only member
of an investment banking team excluded from a dinner at Le Cirque,
an upscale Manhattan restaurant, held to celebrate the closing of a
real estate finance deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McFadden of Morgan Stanley said the firm had not seen the
suit and had no comment on its specifics. But she said, ``As a
matter of policy, we do not tolerate discrimination or harassment
in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry, who said he was not gay, contended in his suit that after
pictures of him appeared in Playguy magazine, the firm decided to
dismiss him. Executives used expense account irregularities as a
``pretext'' for doing so, the suit says. The irregularities
included expenses incurred by Morgan Stanley clients at an adult
entertainment club, the suit says, adding that white bankers at
Morgan Stanley regularly charged the firm for client entertainment
as such establishments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
