<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HAWKS' MUTOMBO DOWNSIZES HIS DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As a child he dreamed of being a doctor, but when he
grew to be 7 foot 2, Dikembe Mutombo modified that dream. Now he
would build a hospital where doctors can save lives in his home
country of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the lofty dreams of this lofty man are being
hampered. He says he has been unable to raise nearly as much money
as he had planned because of the lockout, and also because of
apathy from his fellow players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought guys would be more generous _ maybe $100,000 from
some of them,'' the Atlanta Hawks' Mutombo said Wednesday. ``But I
would say maybe seven to 10 guys contributed a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Mutombo will practice his own form of medicine _
vigorous elbow therapy _ upon the visiting New York Knicks in the
second game of their playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as elbows go, I would say he is right near the top,''
said Chris Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   If Mutombo were not such a jovial adult off the court, it would
almost seem that he was drumming up business for some bone-setting
clinic. However, he is far from a goon or a hacker, and equates
himself most with Bill Russell, the great defensive hub of the old
Boston Celtics and, while far more social than Russell ever was, he
also holds strong opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire him for not forgetting where he came from,'' said
Dudley, who is also known for his charitable impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo sees the world from the perspective of an African man
whose family includes teachers and surgeons. He came to Georgetown
from Congo, formerly known as Zaire, speaking French as well as
several African dialects, and majored in languages and diplomacy,
even if his beliefs are not always diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year I took some guys to Africa, and they wanted to know
where they would stay,'' he said. ``They did not know we had hotels
in Kinshasa. I blame the school systems in America. They let people
choose what they want to study, so people do not know much about
the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   After four years at the John Thompson Institute for the
Vertically Gifted, he was ready to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very lucky,'' Mutombo said with his throaty accent. ``At
first I could make $3 million a year, and now I can make much more.
I realized that I could give money and it would be a tax exemption.
I wonder why other players do not do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, many players do give money to charity, but few seem
as openly involved in their causes as he is with the Dikembe
Mutombo Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it, everybody leaves the earth sometime,'' he
said. ``Most of us leave it from a hospital bed. I want more beds
in a region of 10 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hospital is supposed to be a $44 million project,'' he
added. ``The building is not so expensive, but the facilities cost
money. In my country, one out of 10 newborn children have a chance
to die. One out of 10 mothers have a chance to die. There is
tuberculosis and malaria. I'm trying to be part of the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he fears he may have to downsize his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lockout killed us,'' said Mutombo, who served on the
negotiating committee, along with Dudley. ``If we had 82 games and
started on time, I could have made appearances in every city, the
night before a game, to raise funds. But I never got a chance
because we could not plan it.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not mind saying he is also saddened by the lack of
response from his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe every professional player should have a better sense
of giving back to society,'' he said Wednesday. ``Look at how
people are suffering. We got our chance. We make a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night he will try to stop his friend, Patrick Ewing,
with Alonzo Mourning, the third member of the Georgetown
triumvirate, whose Miami team lost to the Knicks in the first
round, expected to be in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   There is the notion that both Mourning and Mutombo have been
deferential to Ewing over the years, perhaps internalizing
Thompson's frequent comments that ``Patrick comes first'' among the
equals. Ewing showed ferocity toward Mutombo on Tuesday night,
throwing a vicious elbow for his fifth personal foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I think he was just frustrated because of all the fouls,''
Mutombo said. ``Afterward, I drove him to the hotel. We did not
talk about the game. Actually, he was more interested in talking to
my little girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo is soft when he talks about his friends. His elbows
speak a language of their own, but they are supporting his dreams.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
