<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-HUMBLED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS' BACKCOURT LOSES A BIT OF LUSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mookie Blaylock was exhausted Tuesday night. Early in
the fourth quarter, the player entrusted to kick-start the Atlanta
Hawks' offense committed a turnover that led to a jump shot by
Allan Houston on the other end of the court. He did not bother to
run downcourt to play defense, and a minute later he asked to be
taken out of the game by coach Lenny Wilkens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just running wild and kind of got tired,'' said
Blaylock, Atlanta's point guard. ``That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Wilkens: ``That's what happened. I thought he got caught up
in a frenzy.''
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta had one distinct advantage going into its Eastern
Conference semifinal with the New York Knicks, it was its
swaggering starting backcourt. With their ability to score and
defend, the dogged Blaylock and the cocksure shooting guard Steve
Smith were supposed to present New York with serious matchup
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But with Blaylock out of kilter, Smith severely limited by foul
trouble in Atlanta's Game 1 loss and a corn-silk thin bench, the
Hawks are reeling heading into Game 2 on Thursday at the Georgia
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Smith picked up his fourth foul with 10 minutes 9 seconds to go
in the third quarter after putting his team up by 8 on a jumper
with 9 minutes left in the quarter. The Knicks proceeded to go on a
40-15 run.
</P>
<P>
   Without Smith's defensive intensity, it was no coincidence that
Houston scored 19 of his 34 points in that run. Smith finished with
25 points on 6-of-17 shooting and 12 of 14 free throws, but he
could not post up as easily after Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy put
Larry Johnson on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the challenges, and I'm going to take the challenges
no matter who I play against,'' Smith said. ``I think you
definitely have to get physical. Me having four fouls at the
beginning of the third quarter, I couldn't get physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the Hawks were trying to do on defense, he added,
``What did we do? Nothing. They hit every shot, they had too many
easy looks. We weren't physical with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Hawks were trying to paint their series-opening
loss as an aberration, a game in which they simply gave up too many
open shots and took poor ones on the other end of the court.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to wonder how aggressive Smith will be after his
foul trouble in Game 1, and how winded Blaylock is after playing
more than 40 minutes in Game 5 of Atlanta's victory over Detroit
and 38 minutes on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For all their critics, the defense of Charlie Ward and Chris
Childs took Tim Hardaway out of the first round. Now, they have
opposing players taking themselves out of games.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough, Latrell Sprewell and Houston combined for
65 points in the 100-92 victory. It was only the third time this
season Atlanta gave up 100 points or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``They present a big problem,'' Smith said of Sprewell and
Houston. ``They both can run and shoot. The thing is for us, when
Patrick went out of the game, they run more. We don't want Patrick
to get into foul trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing played only 17 minutes Tuesday, allowing the Knicks'
transition game to take over the proceedings. The matchup between
him and Dikembe Mutombo never materialized, giving way to a
high-octane offense unveiled by the Knicks against the league's top
defensive team.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo, Smith and Blaylock did not act Wednesday as if they had
a sense of urgency about Game 2, and seemed to be almost dismissive
about the way they played Tuesday. ``If it was Game 4, maybe then I
would be worried,'' Mutombo said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Smith, ``We definitely didn't want to give up homecourt,
but it's not like we don't think we can go into New York and not
win a game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
