<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     05-19 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A NEW FENWAY PARK OFFERS YANKS A LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since the Fleet Center replaced the Boston Garden,
basketball has never been the same where America's jockey, Paul
Revere, yelled ``The British are coming'' more than 200 years ago
</P>
<P>
   According to most of New England's current colonists, the Fleet
Center has no charm. Of course, the Celtics have no players and the
Bruins aren't much better, but in Boston, charm is more important
than a modern look. Something, anything, can be new in Boston, but
ideally, it somehow should look as old as the Old North Church.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, that is the thinking behind the Red Sox plan for a new
Fenway Park to be built across the street from where Fenway Park
has stood since 1912 and where a World Series flag has not been
raised since 1918. It's a plan that should be required reading for
the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Red Sox were cursed by Babe Ruth's departure,
they have not been able to beat the Yankees when it counts. But if
the Red Sox can create a new Fenway Park with the charm of the
original Fenway Park, the Yankees should be able to create a new or
renovated Yankee Stadium with the grandeur that has been Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The new Fenway Park would retain the charm of the Wall, alias
the Green Monster, in left field. It would retain what is known as
Pesky's Pole, the right-field foul pole struck by eight of Johnny
Pesky's career 17 home runs, or so he says. It would retain ``the
triangle'' in the center-field wall, alias Conigliaro's Corner.
</P>
<P>
   It would also retain the bullpens beyond right field, the manual
scoreboard and the green-painted ladder up the Wall to the screen
where Bucky Dent's homer landed to help the Yankees win the 1978
American League East playoff.
</P>
<P>
   In retaining the virtual dimensions that confronted the Babe,
Teddy Ballgame and Yaz, the new Fenway Park would retain, in a
word, its charm while curing the ailments of the old Fenway Park.
There will be no obstructed views and twice as many restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   When and if it opens in 2003, there will also be more and wider
seats, 44,120 (including 100 luxury suites and 5,500 club seats)
instead of 33,871, the better to help the Red Sox, along with city
and state politicians (most of whom seem to favor the plan), pay
for its proposed total cost: $545 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox plan to raise $350 million; the city and state will
be asked to supply $195 million in condemned land, two parking
garages and improved traffic patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Not that all of the current colonists like the Red Sox plan.
Many in the Fenway Park neighborhood want to renovate the old ball
park. Some politicians don't want to contribute taxpayers' money.
And even among those who favor a new ball park, some don't want a
replica of the Wall; it backfires more than it helps.
</P>
<P>
   The pro football Patriots had a hard time squeezing $70 million
in state funds before abandoning Hartford, but the Patriots aren't
the Red Sox _ and Foxboro isn't Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For all its potential problems, the Red Sox plan should be
examined by the Yankees, as well as by New York's city and state
politicians, in deciding Yankee Stadium's future.
</P>
<P>
   Every year for a few years now, George Steinbrenner has insisted
he will address the Stadium issue when the season ends. After all,
doomsday is approaching; the Yankees' lease at the Stadium expires
in 2002. But when next season arrives every year, as this one has,
he still hasn't addressed it.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Mets have addressed their stadium issue. They hope
to build a new ball park up the street from Shea Stadium, which
would be leveled. The new ball park would resemble Ebbets Field,
where the Dodgers played in Brooklyn before departing in Walter
O'Malley's covered wagon for Los Angeles after the 1957 season.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was talking about a new
Yankee Stadium on Manhattan's West Side, but maybe he realized it
was not only impractical (at a cost of $1 billion) but also
unnecessary. When last heard, the mayor was touting a football-only
stadium for the Jets in a West Side complex with a new Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   And for all the talk about a New Jersey stadium being built for
the Yankees, that has been a bluff. No money, no site, no plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees belong in the Bronx, and they belong there in a new
or renovated Yankee Stadium with better access roads. Just as the
Red Sox belong in Boston in a new Fenway Park across the street
from the original Fenway Park. And just as the Mets belong in a
ball park that resembles Ebbets Field.
</P>
<P>
   Charm counts in New York, too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
