<HEADER>
A3993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORNYN-MORALES20-COX     05-19 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORNYN-MORALES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cornyn says he won't sue Morales
 &HT;    By Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Attorney General John Cornyn said Wednesday he
will not pursue a fraud lawsuit against former Attorney General Dan
Morales, but he is considering filing suit against Houston attorney
Marc Murr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any intention of filing any kind of lawsuit
against Dan Morales,'' Cornyn said. ``I don't know of any evidence
that he benefited personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Cornyn accused Morales of fabricating contracts
to help his friend Murr pursue a claim for $260 million in legal
fees in the state's successful litigation against tobacco
companies. In the face of that accusation, Murr withdrew his claim
against the state. Previously, Murr asked a national arbitration
panel to require tobacco companies to pay his $260 million fee. The
panel awarded him $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn is not backing off his accusation about doctored
contracts. He said he is leaving Morales' fate in the hands of
criminal investigators, while he considers suing Murr to stop him
from collecting the $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the fact that these contracts were doctored, and while
we have defeated his claim for $260 million, he still got $1
million on those same doctored contracts,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has denied any wrongdoing, calling Cornyn a liar and
vowing to clear his name. He said Wednesday that Cornyn's motives
are purely political.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been evident to me from the outset that the objective
of this exercise was to inflict political damage, not to win in
court,'' Morales said. ``What they have been after are newspaper
headlines that they can use if and when I were to re-enter
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Murr, through his attorney, has denied wrongdoing. He could not
be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Austin attorney Roy Minton, who represents Murr, said he was
unaware that Cornyn was considering suing his client. He said he
was puzzled about why the attorney general would sue to stop
payment from tobacco companies to his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco industry made it very clear they were not paying
any money (to lawyers) that was going to be in a state treasury,''
Minton said. ``John (Cornyn) may take a different attitude. I'll
wait to see what they say.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales has defended his friend's role, saying Murr was his
personal adviser and helped him as watchdog and co-pilot for the
complex litigation. Morales also hired five private lawyers to bear
the costs of the litigation up front and represent the state
against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   When Murr lost his bid to collect more than $1 million from
tobacco companies, Cornyn attempted to prevent Murr from claiming
any of the state's $17.3 billion settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, on the steps of the federal courthouse in
Texarkana, where the tobacco litigation has been fought for more
than three years, Cornyn levied his allegation of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Cornyn said there was evidence that Morales
committed ``serious misconduct'' but that his office could deal
only with allegations of civil fraud _ not criminal fraud. He said
he already was cooperating with an FBI investigation into the
matter and also would be turning over evidence to the Travis County
district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, as a matter of practice, does not confirm or deny the
existence of investigations. Travis County District Attorney Ronnie
Earle's office, which has jurisdiction over allegations against
state officials, said last week it would wait to receive a
complaint from Cornyn.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Cornyn indicated he was not filing a criminal
complaint with the district attorney. ``Since the feds are so far
along, we have left it in their hands,'' Cornyn said. ``Certainly,
Ronnie Earle has the authority to request documents. We're just
looking for a signal from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve McCleery, who directs the district attorney's Public
Integrity Unit, said: ``This is a change in the attorney general's
position and the first we heard of it. We need to evaluate the
situation before commenting further.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said Wednesday his goal always had been to stop any claim
for legal fees against the state's $17.3 billion settlement. ``My
goal was never to go after Morales,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
