<HEADLINE>
KNIEVEL READY FOR CANYON MOTORCYCLE JUMP
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Robbie Knievel has things figured just right, he'll briefly
soar with the condors this evening.
</P>
<P>
   The motorcycle daredevil intends to jump a sliver of the Grand
Canyon and perhaps break his world-record leap of 233 feet. An
attempt late last month was canceled by foul weather, but sunshine
is forecast for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Television plans to broadcast the feat live to the East
Coast and, provided all goes well, on tape to the West Coast at 8
p.m. Arizona time. Fox is calling the spectacle the Robbie Knievel
Canyon Jump, instead of Death Jump, its name for the aborted April
29 attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Knievel, 37, got the approval of the Hualapai Nation to attempt
the stunt. It's set for approxi mately 5:45 p.m. at a remote
visitor center and airstrip known as Grand Canyon West, northwest
of Peach Springs on the Canyon's south rim.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters say the leap will take Knievel and his bike up to
2,500 feet above the Canyon floor. The jump itself is more than 200
feet, and Knievel hopes to break his own record. But there's more
to it than that.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he's recognized in many quarters as the greatest
motorcycle dare devil ever, the specter of his father, Evel, whose
spectacular jumps and crushing failures riveted the nation in the
1960s and '70s, still looms over him. If Knievel is able to pull
this off, he may have his place in the sun. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
