<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXYNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NETWORK RIVALRY MAY BE COSTING GALAXY HISPANIC FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ A battle between rival Spanish language
television networks Univision and Telemundo might be causing the
Galaxy to lose Hispanic fans, team officials claimed.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, with attendance at the Rose Bowl averaging only
15,456 through five games, signed a local television agreement with
Telemundo earlier this year to broadcast four games.
</P>
<P>
   Univision, the most popular Spanish station nationally and
locally, holds Major League Soccer's national Spanish broadcast
rights. But, because the Galaxy signed with a competitor, Galaxy
director of media relations Luis Garcia feels that Univision
virtually has boycotted the team locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time they (Univision) came out this season was when
Octavio (Zambrano) was fired and Sigi (Schmid) was hired,'' Garcia
said. ``They used to come out to practices all the time. Their
coverage of us following games is really short also. They don't do
anything more than a Channel 4 (NBC) or a Channel 2 (CBS) would do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think someone's journalistic integrity would be
taken away because we signed with a competitor,'' Garcia said. ``We
think that their (Univision) audience wants to be informed as to
what's going on with out team. It just hasn't been happening.''
</P>
<P>
   MLS vice president of player relations Ivan Gazidis said the
league is still working on a way for the Galaxy to sign former UCLA
striker Seth George, drafted by the team in the second round of the
1999 college draft.
</P>
<P>
   George is not with the 1860 Munich German club he signed with
after college, but the club still owns his rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``No progress ... Seth is under contract in Europe,'' said
Gazidis. ``We don't propose to pay a transfer fee. Right now we're
waiting for that situation to resolve itself, but we're hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said if the team's slump continues,
he'll have to change the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy lost 1-0 in a shootout Saturday to Tampa Bay, running
its record to 4-5. The Galaxy has scored a league-low five goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed for myself, the team, the players and for the
fans,'' Schmid said. ``(The fans) want to see goals. It's not for a
lack of trying. We're making improvement but if this goes on
another week we may have to shake-up the apple cart because
obviously something isn't working.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid didn't talk about any tactical changes for Sunday's game
at the Rose Bowl against New England, but he talked about future
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The starting lineup has stayed constant since I took over, but
we could try a formation change. Maybe go with five midfielders,''
Schmid said. ``I would also look at maybe putting (defender) Steve
Jolley back up front. He's played there before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a panic situation because I feel confident we'll
break out of this -- but again, you have to be ready for change.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid said the problem offensively is penetration and the
Galaxy's lack of size is hurting them up front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a player comfortable in the penalty box,'' Schmid
said. ``Welton, Cobi (Jones) and Clint (Mathis) are comfortable
running at people. But we need that type of player that wiggles
away from people with his back to the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been rumors that Welton has been pursued by other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no trades right now but there have been talks,''
Schmid said. ``There have been a few names thrown around but I
can't get specific.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Tampa Bay standout Alejandro Sequira and former Dallas
scorer Mickey Trotman have been invited to train with the team this
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
