<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY LIKELY TO FORM SENATE COMMITTEE, AIDES SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton has told friends in recent
days that she is likely to form an exploratory committee that would
allow her to raise money and pay bills associated with a Senate
campaign, several associates of the first lady said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion by Mrs. Clinton that she is, in the words of one
adviser, ``inching very close'' toward a critical step in her
decision-making process came as she has faced some criticism for a
flurry of trips to New York that were billed as official White
House business. An exploratory committee would allow her to raise
money to pay for visits that even her own supporters say have taken
a decidedly political cast, as more and more Democrats seem certain
she will run.
</P>
<P>
   ``An exploratory committee is being considered,'' said Marsha
Berry, the first lady's spokeswoman, by telephone on Wednesday
night from the Grand Canyon, where Mrs. Clinton was visiting. ``But
at this point, any talk of an actual announcement is premature.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if she goes ahead with an exploratory committee, several
associates of Mrs. Clinton said, she has still not made a final
decision to run for the Senate. One close adviser said on Wednesday
night that the first lady was still weeks away from making a final
decision even on the exploratory committee, though this adviser
said that such a step appeared increasingly likely.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Mrs. Clinton's remarks to associates are the latest
indication that she is moving toward what would be the
unprecedented step of running for the Senate from the White House.
What is more, the first lady has asked several trusted advisers to
give her the names of political staff and fund-raising experts in
New York who could help raise money for the exploratory committee,
should it be formed, the aides said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Mrs. Clinton has told her closest advisers,
including Harold M. Ickes, the former White House chief of staff,
and several other associates to begin making staff preparations for
a possible campaign for the seat being vacated by Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   ``She at least wants to be able to continue to consider it,''
said one adviser, after speaking to Mrs. Clinton on Monday. ``It's
not the same as making a decision to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Another close associate, who also spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said: ``I think she has concluded that being a senator
is something she wants to do. She is figuring out whether she is
prepared to make a decision that will consume the next 7{ years of
her life.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The prospect of Mrs. Clinton running for the Senate has stirred
great interest among her friends and Democrats, including a number
of political consultants who would like to work for her in a
campaign and who have in recent days been furiously trading
information _ or rumors _ about the first lady's intentions. Mrs.
Clinton is known for keeping her counsel, and thus there were some
discrepancies on Wednesday night in accounts of what she is doing,
even among people who described themselves as familiar with her
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   For example, two associates of Mrs. Clinton said the first lady
had gone so far as to instruct associates to move ahead with
forming an exploratory committee, with the intention of announcing
a decision sometime in June or early July. Two other people who are
close to Mrs. Clinton described those statements as overblown,
saying she in fact has still reserved the possibility of not making
the race in the end.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, pressure on Mrs. Clinton to signal some sort of
intention is growing. For one thing, aides to Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani of New York City, the Republican who is likely to run for
Senate next year, have questioned the trips Mrs. Clinton has made
to New York at taxpayer expense.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Nita M. Lowey, the Democrat from Westchester County who
has said she would run for the nomination if Mrs. Clinton does not,
is said by other Democrats to becoming increasingly anxious for
Mrs. Clinton to make a decision. If Mrs. Clinton runs, Ms. Lowey is
going to run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Mrs. Clinton goes ahead and forms an exploratory
committee, she still could back out of the race. As a practical
matter, though, such an announcement would be seen in New York as
approaching a definite decision and would almost certainly lead to
Ms. Lowey exiting the race.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, there is a growing consensus among Democrats in
New York, as well as Mrs. Clinton's friends, that she is going to
run. ``Do I think she wants to run?'' said James Carville, the
Democratic consultant. ``Yes. Do I think the president would like
to see her run? Yes. Do I know yet whether she has decided to do
it? No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
