<HEADLINE>
ON HOCKEY: A FINAL FOUR WITH MANY STORY LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE LaPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Colorado ended Detroit's Stanley Cup reign Tuesday night
in Joe Louis Arena, the teams formed the traditional handshake
lines and the Avalanche's Claude Lemieux extended his hand to the
Red Wings' Darren McCarty. But McCarty snubbed him. Through the
bitter four years of rivalry between their two teams, these two men
have epitomized the hard feelings and have contributed to some of
the bloodshed. McCarty has ignored Lemieux's hand before. Although
this series was not as mean-spirited as those in previous seasons,
McCarty was not in a forgiving mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's personal feelings, between us,'' McCarty told
reporters, cutting off further discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Of his emotions in general and of the feelings of his city,
McCarty said: ``This is Hockeytown and there's no more hockey. I
feel bad about that.''
</P>
<P>
   By losing Game 6 by 5-2, the Wings' cup streak stopped at two.
After winning the first two games of the second-round series, they
lost the next four in a stunning skid. Their problems started in
goal, where Chris Osgood was injured and Bill Ranford was
inconsistent, but the slump spread throughout the roster. The Red
Wings could not solve Colorado goalie Patrick Roy, who got stronger
as the series went on and gave up only seven goals in the last four
games. And Detroit could not stop Peter Forsberg, who scored twice
on Tuesday and now leads all playoff scorers with 17 points on six
goals and 11 assists halfway through the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit captain Steve Yzerman said, ``They got stronger and we
faded,'' and he added, ``Losing is a humbling thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Scotty Bowman, the Detroit coach, said, ``When you lose four
straight games, you can't say the other team was lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman has been ambiguous on the question of his return or
retirement from coaching at age 65. He has coached various teams to
eight cup championships, tied for the lead with Toe Blake, his
mentor in Montreal in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado, which won the cup in 1996, is the only recent champion
among the final four teams. The Avalanche will play the Stars in
the four-of-seven-game Western Conference finals, beginning
Saturday night in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars won the regular-season championship for the second
consecutive season and eliminated St. Louis in six games in the
second round. For the last three seasons, the Western finals have
produced the eventual cup champion, and that is very likely to be
the case this season. The only other previous cup winner still
around is Toronto, from the Eastern Conference, which last won in
1967, the last spring of the old six-team National Hockey League.
The Maple Leafs, now one of 27 NHL teams, will play the Buffalo
Sabres, beginning in Toronto on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The best chance for the Eastern winner to beat the Western
winner would be for the East series to end in four or five games
while the Western winner gets injuries and fatigue in a long series
of six or seven games. All this will become more clear in two
weeks. In the meantime, the third round should be interesting in
both brackets. Although Buffalo and Toronto are neighbors on
different sides of the international border, they have never played
each other in the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have stars in goal, the Sabres with Dominik Hasek,
the Leafs with Curtis Joseph. Both have captains who are premier
centers. Toronto's Mats Sundin is primarily an offensive attacker,
while Buffalo's Mike Peca is a two-way center who is considered
among the best checkers in the league. The Sabres reached the third
round last season before losing to Washington. Despite finishing
seventh among the eight Eastern seeded teams, the Sabres are
confident after eliminating Boston in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were just happy to get there,'' defenseman Jason
Woolley said, referring to the conference finals. ``This year,
we're not just happy to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be hard to get there for Game 1. The two cities are
about two hours apart by car. They get each other's television and
radio stations and fans travel to each other's rinks for games.
Toward the end of Tuesday night's 3-2 victory over the Bruins in
Marine Midland Arena, the Buffalo fans were chanting, ``We want the
Leafs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars and the Avalanche have also never met in post-season
play, not even when they were in their former locations of
Minnesota and Quebec. Both typify the league's migration of the
1990s, having left northern hockey cradles for the South and the
West. Curiously, the Stars are 5-0 at home in the playoffs while
the Avalanche is 6-0 on the road. Last season, the Stars reached
the conference finals before losing in six games to the Wings.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, the Stars are led by Derian Hatcher, a big captain
known for heavy hitting in the defensive end. Colorado's best
defenseman is probably Sandis Ozolinsh, a swift playmaker who
pushes the attack in the offensive zone. At forward, Mike Modano of
the Stars is in the prime of his career, but his supporting cast is
older and slower than the front-line personnel of Colorado. In
goal, Roy has more championship credentials than Ed Belfour of the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the Avalanche, Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said:
``They're going to have a lot of confidence from beating Detroit.
They've really got eight or nine world-class players. That's a lot
for one team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
