<SLUG> BC-NJ-GUN-LAWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURRED BY SCHOOL SHOOTINGS, NEW JERSEY LEGISLATURE PUSHES ANTI-GUN
BILLS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Amid growing public support for stronger gun
control laws, Republican legislators in New Jersey are moving
quickly on bills to require childproof trigger locks on guns sold
in the state and are considering a bill that would create strict
criminal penalties for parents whose children use their firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Partly in response to the school shootings in Littleton, Colo.,
the Senate Law and Public Safety Committee will hold hearings on
Thursday on seven gun control proposals, including the trigger lock
measure and one that would offer tax exemptions for gun owners who
buy locking gun-storage vaults.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial measure would require that all guns sold
in New Jersey after 2002 be equipped with so-called smart-gun
technology, which uses a computer chip to prevent anyone but the
owners from firing the gun.
</P>
<P>
   The trigger lock proposal, similar to one approved this week by
the U. S. Senate, has the support of Gov. Christie Whitman and the
legislative leadership and is expected to become law within months.
Whitman sent a letter Wednesday urging senators to support the
measure, saying, ``There is simply no good reason not to require
that all guns sold be accompanied by this popular, affordable and
effective safety device.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats have complained that the federal legislation,
which is awaiting action in the House, is likely to make New
Jersey's trigger-lock plan redundant. Instead, the Democrats want
to concentrate on the smart-gun bill.
</P>
<P>
   In direct response to the Colorado school shootings, a
Republican senator, Louis C. Bassano, is scheduled to introduce the
measure on parental penalties during Thursday's hearing. The bill
would expose parents to criminal prosecution if their children use
their guns and would set harsher penalties if the firearms are used
to commit a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Various gun bills have long been under discussion, but the
events at Littleton have aroused so much public concern that
legislators are ready to act on some of those bills, said Bassano,
who is a member of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative activity here is part of a wave of gun control
measures being pushed by governors and state legislators across the
nation, from a California bill that would limit handgun purchases
to one a month to a measure introduced by the governor of Delaware
that would require a background check for the sale of any gun, even
between private citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Democratic majority in the Assembly also passed
a parental responsibility bill earlier this month and is pushing
for a ban on assault weapons. But both measures face strong
opposition in the Republican-controlled Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates say the Littleton shootings have also
helped stopped the momentum of bills in several states where gun
lobbyists have sought weaker rules on concealed weapons and
background checks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
