<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS SQUABBLE ON GUN CONTROL MEASURES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate bipartisanship that led to Tuesday's
passage of legislation requiring handgun safety locks threatened to
dissolve Wednesday as Republicans and Democrats spent hours in
squabbling about how to tighten a variety of gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate put off a vote until Thursday on the most disputed
issue, whether to enact more restrictions against gun show
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear whether the disagreement over several
amendments to be voted on Thursday would result in the collapse of
the overriding $5 billion Juvenile Justice Bill. A vote on the bill
could occur Thursday if party leaders settle their differences.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Republicans joined Democrats in requiring that newly
purchased handguns have safety locks, the two parties were at odds
Wednesday over how to control the unlicensed sale of firearms at
gun shows. The issue was whether a Republican-authored proposal to
require background checks on purchasers at gun shows, approved last
week after the GOP originally rejected a similar proposal, was
filled with new loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   A proposal offered by Senator Frank Lautenberg, Democrat of New
Jersey, was characterized by Democrats as closing a Republican
loophole that allowed certain gun show dealers to sell their wares
without performing background checks on purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy delivered an impassioned floor speech
in which he accused Republicans of ``making a mockery'' of gun
control by allowing high-volume dealers known as ``special
licensees'' to sell at gun shows without conducting background
checks.
</P>
<P>
   In some of the most incendiary language used in the debate,
Kennedy said it was ``wrong for the Senate to whistle past the
graveyard of Littleton,'' a reference to last month's mass shooting
at Colorado's Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Jeff Sessions, an Alabama Republican, wondered what
all the fuss was about. Sessions said that there is no loophole,
contending that Kennedy was mistaken to think that some dealers
would be exempt from the background check requirement. Moreover,
Sessions said, the proposal offered Wednesday by Democrats would
make practically no difference in combating crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gun stuff is just show,'' Sessions said at a press
conference, charging that Democrats were more concerned about
politics than crime-fighting.
</P>
<P>
   On another issue, Kennedy urged passage of an amendment that
called for retention of a current law that calls on the states to
make an effort to determine why there is a disproportionate number
of incarcerated minorities and to develop intervention strategies.
</P>
<P>
   The Juvenile Justice Bill would change the wording of current
law to replace the reference to ``minorities'' with a phrase that
says states should study why certain ``segments'' of the population
are disproportionately incarcerated. Kennedy, emphasizing that
current law has not resulted in the release of anyone, said the new
language was too vague and would say that ``Congress will look the
other way while minority youths are confined at disproportionately
high rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Orrin G. Hatch, the Utah Republican, argued against the
measure, saying, ``What's your solution, to let them out of jail,
crack cocaine distributors? Is there an argument that white crack
dealers get away with it because they are smarter or protected?''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday voted 52-48 to table, or kill, the
measure. The Senate also tabled a proposal to add $3 billion to
afterschool programs.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on Wednesday tried but failed to reach a compromise
with Democrats on a proposal to regulate gun sales at pawn shops.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's debate came as the Senate prepared to vote on the
overriding Juvenile Justice Bill, which would pour $5 billion into
fighting juvenile crime. The five-year bill includes $450 million
per year for drug testing and detention centers, $435 million
annually for juvenile crime prevention, $75 million in state
grants, and $40 million for research of juvenile crime programs.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Wednesday, Senator Thomas Harkin, an Iowa Democrat,
threatened to tie up the bill due to his objection to a proposal by
Senator Bill Frist, Republican of Tennessee. Frist proposed ending
what he called a loophole in existing law that allows students with
disabilities to bring a gun to school without being subject to his
state's law that requires a one-year expulsion for anyone bringing
a firearm to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the law stands, local school authorities have to jump
through hoops to remove a dangerous special education student who
brings a gun or bomb to school,'' Frist said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But Harkin said Frist's amendment would backfire, since it would
expel a student with mental or physical disabilities and provide no
alternative education to a person who may need it the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids with disabilities haven't been shooting anybody,'' Harkin
said, referring to the eight school shootings in the last 39
months.
</P>
<P>
   With Harkin threatening to filibuster the matter, Senate leaders
agreed to put off a vote on the measure until Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
