<HEADLINE>
STARS' KEANE SAYS FACING FORMER TEAM NOT IMPORTANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
IRVING, Texas _ Mike Keane has watched the media swarm move around
the Stars' locker room this season _ stopping at Derian Hatcher
when the Stars played the Phoenix Coyotes, camping out in front of
Brett Hull when the St. Louis Blues were the opponent, harassing Ed
Belfour when the subject of the Detroit Red Wings arose.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And yesterday, he saw the crowd stop in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I don't know these guys any better than anyone else,''
said Keane, who played with the Colorado Avalanche from 1995-97.
``You've got the wrong guy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way of the media shuffle, though, and it looks like
Keane will have to live with being a story line for the Western
Conference finals. He won fhe Stanley Cup with the Avalanche in
1996, and his smiling visage hoisting the silver chalise still is
visible on the NHL's ``Cup Crazy'' commercials that
</P>
<P>
   air on television. He's also one of Avalanche goalie Patrick
Roy's good friends. Keane and Roy played together for seven seasons
on the Montreal Canadiens before the two were traded to the
Avalanche in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Keane will get a chance to beat Roy, one of the hottest
goalies in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me how to beat him,'' Keane said, laughing. ``I'm
not a goal scorer.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is a competitor, and Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said he
expects to see Keane have a similar motivation to defeat his old
teammates to that of Brett Hull with the Blues. Like Hull and the
Blues, the Avalanche allowed Keane to walk away a free agent in
1997. Keane signed with the New York Rangers and was later traded
to the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good player for them, and he's a good player for
us,'' Hitchcock said. ``I think there will be \Rsome motivation\S;
he's been a good player when he plays against them. He has some
friends on the other side, but for Keane this is the playoffs and
everything takes a back seat to the war.'' \Nsubheds:Flu bug The
Stars allowed eight players to miss practice yesterday because of
injury, illness or fatigue. Defenseman Shawn Chambers missed while
rehabilitating a knee injury, and Pat Verbeek and Jamie
Langenbrunner rested sore knees. Joe Nieuwendyk, Craig Ludwig,
Richard Matvichuk, Ed Belfour and Grant Marshall also missed
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said some players have flu symptoms,
but he would not say which ones. Nieuwendyk said he definitely had
been hit by the flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling it right now, but it's getting better,'' he said.
``I expect to be at practice'' today.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers' availability for Saturday's Game 1 is in question, and
Tony Hrkac is out with cracked ribs. Hitchcock said he expects
every other player to be ready. \Nsubheds:Line swap Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock had Brett Hull practicing on a line with Mike Modano and
Jere Lehtinen yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   After moving Hull from line to line for the final three games of
the Western Conference semifinal series with the St. Louis Blues,
Hitchcock said yesterday he expects to start the conference finals
with Hull on the Stars' top line.
</P>
<P>
   Hull dished out the game-winning assist to Modano in Game 6
after rejoining the top line.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
