<SLUG> BC-NY-LOST-BODY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY LAWSUIT SAYS HOSPITAL LOST TRACK OF BODY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael McClester disappeared one winter day in 1992
after being taken to a Bronx hospital in an ambulance. Hospital
officials told his family that he had been treated and released, so
they started searching for him.
</P>
<P>
   McClester, 36, had battled drug addiction for years, so his
family looked for him in his old haunts and even made regular
visits to the local police precinct and Police Headquarters to look
at pictures of unidentified dead men.
</P>
<P>
   But eight months after he vanished, McClester's family said they
learned that their worst fears about his fate paled against the
reality of what had happened. Michael McClester had died at Jacobi
Medical Center on Dec. 16, 1992, the day he had arrived, and his
body had been effectively lost through a series of bureaucratic
mix-ups. The city had buried him in a pauper's grave even as his
family hounded police officials to help find him.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of a suit McClester's family filed against the city,
which operates the hospital, seeking $10 million in damages, is
scheduled to begin Thursday in state Supreme Court in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, his relatives spoke to reporters about their painful
search for McClester and the agonizing discovery of how he died
alone and was unceremoniously buried among the city's poor and
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son was respectable,'' said Nancy Moore, McClester's
71-year-old mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not pick up a bum on the street. His dress was
impeccable and his apartment was always neat. In fact, he was
fussier than me. It eats me up that they just threw him like a
piece of garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Moore said she has a recurring dream in which her son cries
out to her, ``Ma, how could they do that?''
</P>
<P>
   Her eyes welled up with tears and she said she wished she could
have seen her son once more before he was buried. ``I could've said
`goodbye,''' she said. ``I could've been a mama.''
</P>
<P>
   The family has since moved McClester's body to a private
cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Bade Goodman, a spokeswoman for the city's corporation
counsel, declined to comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Moore, a retired special education rehabilitation worker,
said she was in Florida when her son vanished, so she had her older
son, Cedric McClester, led the search. Both she and the elder
McClester said that at first they were not overly alarmed because
Michael McClester had vanished twice before, to enroll in drug
rehabilitation programs.
</P>
<P>
   Cedric McClester, 56, said his brother had started experimenting
with heroin as a teen-ager but had managed to mask his drug
problems for years. He said his brother had been a maintenance
worker at Bronx Lebanon Hospital for several years and also sang
with various bands at local clubs.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that his brother had tested positive for HIV
and had gone on disability about a year before his disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Cedric McClester said that on Dec. 16, 1992, police notified the
family that Michael had been admitted to Jacobi _ for treatment of
respiratory problems. He said he called the hospital and was told
repeatedly that his brother had been treated and released.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, Cedric McClester said he went to the
local police precinct repeatedly and looked through piles of
photographs. McClester, a former Democratic district leader from
Harlem, said he also called on friends elsewhere in the Police
Department to help search other hospital and prison files.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on Aug. 31, 1993, a relative received a letter from the
Social Security Administration stating that Michael McClester's
disability benefits would be terminated because he had died on Dec.
16, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The family later learned that Michael McClester had died in the
hospital's emergency room and that the hospital had sent a telegram
notifying next of kin to a nonexistent address in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   His body was kept in the Bronx morgue for more than a month, but
his picture was never sent to the Police Department's Missing
Persons Bureau. Eventually, the body was released for burial with
others that were unclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an alarmist or one to cry racism, but I believe he was
treated so callously because he was black and because he was HIV
positive,'' Cedric McClester said. ``And it's my feeling that this
kind of negligence hasn't been corrected. This has got to stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
