<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ZIMMER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMMER JUST BEING ZIMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The 21 victories and 15 losses compiled during Don
Zimmer's tenure as the Yankees' interim manager will be applied to
Joe Torre's career record, said Steve Hirdt, the executive vice
president of the Elias Sports Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is based on ample precedent, and, Hirdt added, ``We
always try to look for reasons to give it to the man who was hired
to be manager.'' The logic is sound, but in this season's first 36
games, the Yankees belonged to Zimmer; they were in his control,
and their collective mood often reflected his, in one of the most
unusual chapters in the Yankees' history.
</P>
<P>
   Torre encouraged Zimmer to be himself, and he was. Zimmer pushed
the successful development of the reliever Jason Grimsley, allowed
Derek Jeter tremendous freedom to blossom as a hitter and propelled
the Yankees to a 20-10 start, even while in tremendous pain from
his right knee. Zimmer also created a couple of avoidable
controversies, and when the team began to slump last week, his
anxious competitiveness _ fueled by his desire to win for Torre,
his close friend _ could not have helped an intense group of
players who needed to relax.
</P>
<P>
   When Torre returned as manager Tuesday afternoon, the Yankees
were in first place in the American League East; even George
Steinbrenner, the principal owner, who engaged in a mild feud of
silence with Zimmer, said it would be hard to ask for anything
more. With Jorge Posada, Chuck Knoblauch and Paul O'Neill _ pivotal
Yankees who struggle to feel good about themselves _ mired in deep
slumps, Torre's comeback is perfectly timed.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer did not want to be a manager again. At 68 years old, he
loved being Torre's bench coach, loved being at the park with
friends, playing bridge with Joe Girardi and O'Neill and Scott
Brosius. His personality played off Torre's perfectly: Torre was
quiet while Zimmer hollered encouragement from the dugout, and you
could barely tell when words passed between them, their lips hardly
moving.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre's prostate cancer was diagnosed and Steinbrenner
almost literally dragged Zimmer _ bad knee and all _ out of his bed
to manage. Zimmer acknowledged immediately that he had taken on a
no-win situation: After going 125-50 in winning the World Series in
1998, the Yankees would begin the 1999 season with two significant
differences, Roger Clemens instead of David Wells, and Zimmer
instead of Torre. If the team lost, Zimmer would be blamed.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, they won, to Zimmer's delight and relief. When they
picked up their first victory of the season April 6, Zimmer's hands
were shaking when he spoke to reporters in a strained voice, and it
was apparent there was great pressure on him. There would have been
pressure on anybody in this situation, and Zimmer was not immune.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees swept Texas and Toronto during a five-game homestand
that ended April 25, improving their record to 12-5, and Torre was
plotting his return. But even through the success, Zimmer's tenure
wasn't seamless.
</P>
<P>
   In the weekend before the regular season began, Zimmer publicly
chastised Steinbrenner for his meddling in the handling of pitcher
Hideki Irabu, which forced the owner to retreat into silence.
Eventually, Steinbrenner's refusal to speak to him gnawed at
Zimmer. On one hand, Zimmer wanted Steinbrenner to let him manage
the team, as Torre had told him to do. On the other hand, Zimmer
wanted Steinbrenner to appreciate the job he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   The plane trips exacerbated the pain in Zimmer's right knee, and
on April 28, the day after a long trip, he and the first-base
coach, Jose Cardenal, engaged in a brief shouting match in the
dugout during a game in Texas. ``You want to manage this team?''
Zimmer yelled, as if Cardenal had challenged his authority.
</P>
<P>
   His emotions simmering, Zimmer decided after that game to call a
team meeting and tell his players that he would retire after the
Yankees' game the next night, that Torre was coming back. He
tearfully thanked them and walked out, leaving a clubhouse of
stunned players to exchange confused glances.
</P>
<P>
   But Zimmer had not discussed his plans with Steinbrenner, or
Torre, or anyone. When he called Torre later that night, he
discovered that Torre wasn't feeling strong and had no intention of
coming back immediately. Many of the Yankees came to believe that
Zimmer had simply reacted to his pain, the frustration over a loss
and his exchange with Cardenal.
</P>
<P>
   Torre and Zimmer met with the news media together before the
Yankees' game April 30, and the change in Zimmer was apparent. With
his friend at his side, Zimmer smiled broadly, he was relaxed and
comfortable, and when someone asked Zimmer a question about Torre,
his voice grew husky and his eyes became watery.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
