<HEADER>
A4099 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ZIMMER-NYT &LR;      05-19 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ZIMMER-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BOSTON: became watery.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The losing began May 12, against Anaheim, and after the Yankees
were shut out again the following night, Girardi _ one of a handful
of players who had been told by Torre to watch over the team _
called a players-only meeting and began complaining about a lack of
effort, specifically mentioning at least one teammate's failure.
Zimmer walked in to hear this and said the same sort of thing to
Girardi that he had said to Cardenal: You're calling a meeting? Do
think you're managing?
</P>
<P>
   With that, Zimmer broke up Girardi's gathering, even though he
is probably closer to Girardi than to any other player on the team.
(The frustrated feelings did not linger. In a meeting called by
Zimmer the next day, apologies were expressed.) But the Yankees
continued to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer's ability to end the slump was hampered by the Yankees'
poor bench; rather than shake up his lineup or use pinch-hitters
for some of his slump-ridden players, Zimmer was saddled with the
third-string catcher Mike Figga.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Zimmer fought hard to keep Clay Bellinger, a
journeyman utility player whose primary skill _ versatility _ is
much better suited to the National League. Zimmer's son had been
involved in the drafting and signing of Bellinger years ago, and
like his son, Zimmer respected how hard Bellinger played, how he
approached the game, and he wanted Bellinger on this team.
</P>
<P>
   After their fifth straight loss last Saturday, Zimmer yelled
aloud in the clubhouse, angry that a television reporter had
misrepresented what Zimmer had said while asking a question to
Jeter. It was something that Torre never would have done during a
tense time, but then, as Zimmer has said repeatedly: ``I'm not Joe.
I'm going to be myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After Torre returned Tuesday, Zimmer avoided reporters, saying
he didn't want to talk, that he was back to being a bench coach.
Torre decided against thanking Zimmer in front of the players,
knowing Zimmer would break down. The gratitude was inherent anyway,
Torre said. Everybody on the team knew what he had contributed;
everybody knew how much pain he had endured and how loyal he was to
Torre.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went far and above the call of duty,'' pitcher David Cone
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer was headed out of the clubhouse before Tuesday's game
when Steinbrenner _ a longtime friend _ walked up and draped an arm
around his shoulder. ``We need you, pal,'' Steinbrenner said, and
Zimmer dropped his head, ducking from his emotions once more. His
task complete, ultimately appreciated, it was as if Zimmer were a
youngster sheepishly looking around for some rocks to kick at,
someone in the clubhouse said.
</P>
</TEXT>
