<HEADLINE>
IN NERVOUS HARTFORD, POLICE CHIEF DENIES HE EXPECTS A RIOT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD _ In a city on edge, even a purchase order can be
provocative.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the Hartford police chief, Joseph F. Croughwell
Jr., acknowledged that his force included some racist officers, he
found himself trying to explain why the department was stocking up
on pepper spray and smoke bombs while residents were waiting
tensely for a prosecutor's decision about whether to charge a white
officer who fatally shot a black teen-ager in the back.
</P>
<P>
   The purchases, Croughwell said in an interview Wednesday, were
routine and not in preparation for unrest over the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But residents in the bleak North End neighborhood where the
shooting took place are wondering why an armored personnel carrier,
usually kept in a police yard, was sent rolling through the streets
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   And why about 45 officers were given riot training last week.
</P>
<P>
   Those things, too, were just the normal course of business, the
chief said. ``I can see how people would add one and one and get
four,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said all the preparations were just coincidental,
Croughwell said he was concerned about what could happen after the
prosecutor decided whether the April 13 shooting of Aquan Salmon,
14, was justified. He said he had begun a series of brainstorming
sessions with his commanders about demonstrations that could
follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect a riot,'' he said. ``I really don't. But if we
have one, we have to be prepared for that. This training we're
doing now, it was not developed because of this. It was not
implemented because of this. But it's fortunate that we have it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be people who will try to try to exploit the
decision, either way that it goes,'' he said. ``We could have
incidents. There could be some people who get very angry with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of the purchases, the armored vehicle and the riot training
swept through the North End Wednesday. ``They're bringing out the
tanks,'' said the Rev. Henry L. Price, a black leader.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents speculated that the information was spread to
intimidate them. Others said they thought the police were trying to
stir things up. ``People on the inside are looking for people in
this community to validate their fear,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers are unhappy, too. Several said they were frustrated by
the increased scrutiny they have faced since the shooting. They
said that feeling now extended to their off-duty hours, since the
chief, in a news conference on Tuesday, urged white officers not to
attend parties or dinners unless black or Hispanic people were
present.
</P>
<P>
   The officers' bitterness can be seen in a poster promoting a
benefit for Officer Robert Allan, who shot Aquan and said later
that he thought the teen-ager had a gun. ``Shoot? Don't Shoot?''
the poster says. ``Damned If You Do. Dead If You Don't!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
