<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-WORLDCUP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999 WOMEN'S WORLD CUP: BEAUTIFUL GAME TAKES FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was so little news media and public interest in the U.S.
victory at the inaugural Women's World Cup of soccer in 1991 in
China that few people even knew the United States had a team, much
less the best team on the planet. The players kept their friends
and relatives informed by sending faxes, which were distributed
like chain letters, the equivalent of technological smoke signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one met us at the airport, there were no ticker-tape
parades,'' said the star forward Mia Hamm, laughing. ``One of our
sponsors took an ad out in the papers to let people know we had
won.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, the Women's World Cup is coming to the United
States, from June 19 to July 10, and the 16-team tournament carries
marquee billing as the largest sporting event ever held exclusively
for women. There will be no need to send faxes, or even e-mail,
because all 32 matches will be televised by Disney-owned ABC, ESPN
and ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup will serve, in large part, as an affirmation of
the gender-equity gains made since the passage of Title IX, the
1972 federal law that prohibits discrimination in the providing of
athletic opportunities for women. Those gains were most visibly
reflected in the gold-medal success by American women in
basketball, soccer and softball at the 1996 Summer Olympics and the
start up of two professional basketball leagues, one of which has
since folded.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the World Cup will celebrate the explosive growth
of soccer for women in the United States, where 7.5 million female
players are registered, according to a recent survey by the Soccer
Industry Council of America, a trade group. In suburbia, where the
game flourishes, girls' soccer has become as popular as sport
utility vehicles. Hamm is the most recognized and accomplished
player in the country, male or female. She makes commercials with
another University of North Carolina graduate, Michael Jordan, and
she has her own signature Barbie Doll, along with 107 career goals
in international play, 30 more than the Brazilian legend Pele.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets sales have reached 388,000 _ more than three times the
112,000 sold for the 1995 Women's World Cup in Sweden _ and
organizers believe they can eventually put a half-million
spectators in the seats by selling out the 77,716-seat Giants
Stadium for the American and tournament opener and the 92,542-seat
Rose Bowl for the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan was to play the tournament at small stadiums
on the East Coast. But the American women won the Olympic gold
medal playing before 76,489 spectators at the University of
Georgia, which persuaded organizers to place the Women's World Cup
coast to coast in some of the same cavernous football stadiums that
played host to the men's World Cup in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show that we're excellent soccer players _ smart,
tactical, fit, fast, athletic _ and we have everything the men's
game has, '' said U.S. forward Tiffeny Milbrett. ``We want
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Soccer's world governing body, known by its initials as FIFA, is
counting on sparks from this World Cup to kindle a brush fire of
interest in women's soccer around the globe, where female players
are facing the same cultural barriers American women faced two
decades ago. There is also hope that the Women's World Cup will
generate a top-flight professional league in the United States in
2001, the way the men's World Cup did, but plans are proceeding
cautiously amid much uncertainty about a league's commercial
viability.
</P>
<P>
   While there is ambitious optimism about the Women's World Cup,
the tournament is not without risk. The success of the World Cup is
largely tied to the success of the American women. Fortunately for
the organizers, the Americans are favored to win with their
wide-open, attacking style, unlike the dreary American men, who
finished dead last in the 32-team 1998 World Cup in France.
</P>
<P>
   But the disparity between the best teams and the rest could
result in some less-than-entertaining mismatches. The Japanese, for
one, played so deferentially in a recent game against the United
States that they were outshot, 35-0, in a 9-0 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said they did not have the time or money to build the
recognition of stars from other countries. And the scramble for
television viewers has been complicated by the National Basketball
Association lockout, which could extend the NBA finals to June 29.
</P>
<P>
   Should the American women not reach the final, the World Cup is
not very likely to transcend the base of suburban interest _ the
grass-roots soccer community, soccer dads and moms and their
teen-age and preteen girls _ to which the event is being primarily
marketed. An unlikely early exit by the United States could result
in largely empty stadiums and vacant interest by the American
public. But, through clever packaging requirements, organizers have
sold an average of 14,000 tickets for non-U.S. games in the first
round, including 30,000 for a doubleheader in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capturing the imagination of the American public is something
we'd like to do,'' said Marla Messing, the president of the Women's
World Cup organizing committee. ``Millions are not aware of the
Women's World Cup. To reach out is important. If it is only about
the U.S. team, I wouldn't consider that a success. We're looking
for more balance than that. But we'd be foolish to think the
non-U.S. games will attract as much attention as the U.S. games.''
</P>
<P>
   The competitive side of the tournament would be compromised if
China withdrew in the wake of NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy
in Belgrade, Yugoslavia. The fast, technically exquisite Chinese
finished second to the Americans at the 1996 Summer Olympics and
have beaten them twice in the three meetings since late March.
</P>
<P>
   So far, organizers said they had received no indication that
China might pull out; to the contrary, they surmise that the
Chinese could make a stronger political statement by defeating the
United States on its home turf than by withdrawing in protest.
There is some concern, however, about whether the Chinese and the
North Korean teams will have trouble securing visas from the closed
U.S. Embassy in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not say definitely we will come and I did not say we
will not come,'' Zhao Gin Fu, a foreign-affairs official in the
Chinese soccer federation, said from Beijing. ``Up to this point,
there is no such problem that we will not come.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
