<HEADLINE>
ONLINE PHARMACY DRUGSTORE.COM FILES FOR IPO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN COOK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Just three months after filling its first
prescription, Bellevue, Wash.-based drugstore.com Inc. has
registered with the Securities and Exchange Commission to raise as
much as $67.5 million in an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   The filing comes in the wake of major changes in the online
pharmacy business. On Monday, CVS Corp., one of the nation's
largest drugstore chains, purchased Seattle-based Soma.com for $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This market segment is moving very fast,'' said Gail Bronson,
a senior analyst at IPO Monitor and a startup specialist based in
Palo Alto, Calif. ``So an IPO is absolutely critical (for
drugstore.com).''
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen companies are attempting to crack the online
pharmacy market, from traditional chain drugstores such as
Wal-Mart, Rite Aid and Walgreens to start-ups such as PlanetRX,
RX.com and Express Scripts Inc.'s yourPharmacy.com.
</P>
<P>
   The market for prescription drugs, over-the-counter-drugs,
health and beauty aids and vitamins is estimated to be close to
$230 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore.com, which sells more than 15,000 health and beauty
products on its Web site, is aware of the competitive threats. ``If
we fail to attract and retain a large customer base and our
competitors establish a more prominent market position relative to
ours, this could inhibit our ability to grow,'' the company wrote
in its filing statement.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore.com recorded 687,000 unique visitors in the month of
March making it one of the top 50 e-commerce sites, according to
Web site tracking service Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   Although competition abounds, drugstore.com's filing for a
public offering gives it a temporary advantage over online
upstarts, Bronson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is an excellent move by drugstore.com,'' she said.
``First-mover advantage is very valuable when you are a dot-com
trying to capture the imaginations of investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronson added that the public offering would help drugstore.com
establish its brand name. ``It will help them become equated with
the entire market segment so when anyone thinks of pharmacies or
health and beauty they think of drugstore.com.''
</P>
<P>
   The filing provides the first financial snapshot of
drugstore.com. For the fiscal year ending April 30, the company
recorded a $10.2 million loss on revenue of $652,000. Since the
company was started last summer in the garage of chief executive
Peter Neupert, drugstore.com has lost $17.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company, now with 170 employees, has funded operations
through private financing totaling $57.2 million. Major backers
include Amazon.com, which in February took a 46 percent stake; the
Silicon Valley venture capital firm Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP;
Byers, with 28 percent; Paul Allen's Vulcan Ventures, with 9
percent; and Starbucks Chairman Howard Schultz's Maveron Equity
Partners, with 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Neupert, who was recruited to lead the company by
drugstore.com founder Jed Smith and Kleiner Perkins, holds 7
percent of the outstanding shares.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Soma.com, which operates its own fulfillment center in
West Chester Ohio, drugstore.com relies on third party vendors to
fill and distribute orders. While this saves the company money on
infrastructure costs, it also could pose a serious threat to
business if the current vendors RxAmerica or Walsh Distribution
cancel their contracts, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   RxAmerica, which supplies about 85 percent of drugstore.com's
prescriptions, is a joint venture operated by Albertson's and Longs
Drugs, both of which are potential competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the stock sale will be used for sales and
marketing, possible acquisitions and other general corporate
purposes. The lead manager of the offering is Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore.com, which plans to trade on the Nasdaq stock exchange
under the ticker symbol DSCM, did not disclose the number of shares
it plans to offer or the date of the stock sale.
</P>
<P>
   The company refused to comment, citing Securities and Exchange
Commission regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
