<DOCNO> NYT19990519.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WOMEN-WORLDCUP-2N     05-19 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-WORLDCUP-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: not come.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Globally, women's soccer is most securely positioned in the
United States. But the sport is also well established in the
egalitarian societies of Scandinavia, particularly Norway, the
defending World Cup champion; in China, where sport serves
propaganda purposes and the failure to win the 1991 Women's World
Cup at home caused a temporary shutdown of the women's program; in
Germany, which produced the 1995 Women's World Cup runner-up and
has a professional league, and in Japan, which features the world's
most highly regarded professional league, though several teams have
failed and foreign players have been dropped as a result of the
Asian financial crisis, according to World Cup officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Latin American countries such as Brazil and Mexico, which
have powerful men's teams, the women's teams have qualified for the
World Cup, although they continue to battle stereotypes that
American women once did _ that soccer is a man's game and that
female players are somehow unwomanly.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil holds a national club championship for women and its
women's national team shares with its men's team the powerful
corporate backing of Nike. Support for the Mexican women's national
team, however, is in such infancy that the World Cup squad is
expected to feature seven to nine Mexican-Americans who played
collegiately in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fighting the myths and prejudices that women's soccer
felt in the U.S. in the '70s,'' said Andrea Rodebaugh, the captain
of the Mexican team who played at the University of California at
Berkeley. ``That there are sports for boys and sports for girls and
that soccer is not for girls, not feminine. Now, I think that macho
attitude is dying down.''
</P>
<P>
   Australia, which finished 12th out of 12 teams at the 1995
Women's World Cup, is now providing the national team with an
annual budget of $900,000 with the goal of winning a medal at the
2000 Summer Olympics, which will be held in Sydney. Africa will
field two teams in the World Cup, Nigeria and Ghana. In Nigeria,
interest is sufficient to sustain a magazine called Female
Football. Ghana, which calls its team the Black Queens, so
astonished China with two close matches earlier this year that the
official Chinese news media reported that the Ghanaian players had
gained tremendous fitness by climbing coconut trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have mango trees, too,'' Wolanyo Agrah, the general
secretary of the Ghanaian soccer federation, said with a belly
laugh. ``We ran on the beach for endurance, but that could be a
joke, the coconut trees. The Chinese were amazed at the stamina and
speed of our girls.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the cultural appeal of women's soccer is
as important as its athletic appeal. The Americans are such
pioneers _ missionaries is the word used by coach Tony DiCicco _
for suburban girls that the players' appearances at post-game
autograph sessions bring a shrieking frenzy described by co-captain
Julie Foudy as a ``Beatles concert-slash-slumber party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want these girls to know that they can play at the highest
level,'' said midfielder Kristine Lilly, who is playing in her
third World Cup. ``We didn't look up to on the national team
because there wasn't one. We didn't wait for autographs because
there wasn't anyone to wait for.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Shick, 15, drove with several friends from the Poconos in
Pennsylvania to watch the American women play a recent tuneup match
against China at Giants Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J., the site
of the tournament-opening doubleheader on June 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather see girls play,'' she said. ``I can relate to the
girls. We can aspire to be like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from their skills, the American women said they believed
they held a cultural edge over many teams because women are
expected to succeed in any endeavor in the United States. The
American women are paid an average of $30,000 to $40,000 by the
U.S. Soccer Federation, they have been in a training camp for
nearly six months and most have endorsement deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not second-class citizens like women in some other
countries,'' said goalkeeper Briana Scurry. ``Our personality is,
we go after it. Other teams are aggressive, but there is a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in the Netherlands, which fields one of the world's
best men's teams, the women did not qualify for the World Cup and
are able to practice only two days a week while holding full-time
jobs. Michelle Akers, who will be playing in her third World Cup
for the United States, said she attended a soccer forum in Egypt
several years ago, and that the men seemed uncomfortable when she
played in an otherwise all-male pickup game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked me to play, but I was definitely a freak to them,''
Akers said. ``I almost got into a fistfight. Men were sliding into
me, one guy shoved me. We've come a long way, but we've got a long
way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in the United States, the 1999 Women's World Cup has drawn
nowhere near the financial support that the men's World Cup did in
1994. The organizing committee's overall budget of $28-$30 million
is about one-tenth of the budget for the men's World Cup and the
organizing committee's share of corporate sponsorships is $6
million, compared with the $40-plus million for the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``That World Cup is 80 years old; this one is nine,'' Messing
said. ``A budget of $28 to $30 million for a women's sporting event
is substantial. We are not ashamed of our budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Trecker, the editor of Kick magazine, said he believed
that organizers had made a mistake in portraying the 1999 World Cup
more as a women's event than an international sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very difficult to be convinced at this point that
this is a major world event,'' Trecker said. ``I don't see any
evidence that the world cares.''
</P>
<P>
   If this familiar skepticism and risk place tremendous pressure
on the American players to temper the doubts by winning the World
Cup, it is a situation in which the team has thrived for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said when we started this World Cup, `You can't do it
on a big stage, you can't do it in big stadiums, you won't draw,'''
said Foudy. ``Tell us what we can't do and we'll do it. We love
these types of obstacles. This is the opportunity for us to show
the world our sport and what we've done with it. Women's athletics
needs to know it can put on a big event and be successful. The
hardest part is they don't want to take the risk. We were fortunate
enough that we had great backing to take the risk.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
