<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG CASES AGAINST CONTRERAS BROTHERS FALTER IN MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Efforts to prosecute the Amezcua Contreras
brothers, whom American authorities say rank among the world's
largest producers of illegal methamphetamines, appear to be
collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Amezcua, who is 33 and has been imprisoned here for nearly
a year as the United States attempts to extradite him on
trafficking charges, won a victory early Wednesday when Olga
Sanchez Contreras, a federal judge, declared the proceedings
unconstitutional. Mexico's Constitution prohibits the extradition
of Mexican citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Amezcua's lawyer, Everardo Rojas Contreras, said the order
would block further extradition attempts against his client. It was
not clear how long Mexican authorities could continue to hold Jesus
Amezcua after the judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate case, Jesus Amezcua's younger brother, Adan, who
is 29, was freed from a federal prison Wednesday after an appellate
judge threw out trafficking and other charges against him. Adan
Amezcua had been imprisoned since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mexico's attorney general declined comment
Wednesday on either case.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration, Thomas
Constantine, Wednesday called the release of Adan Amezcua ``a
disappointing development.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said the DEA was still studying the decision in the
Jesus Amezcua extradition case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
