<SLUG> BC-GOVT-WEB-SITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY TO PROCEED WITH SERVICE THAT SEARCHES FEDERAL DATA BASES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Northern Light Technology Inc., whose new fee-based
service for searching federal government data bases fell victim to
a bureaucratic bungle this week, said Wednesday that it would begin
the service with or without the Clinton administration's backing.
</P>
<P>
   The service was designed in a joint venture of Northern Light
and the Commerce Department's National Technical Information
Services to give Internet users an indexing tool for quick
searches.
</P>
<P>
   But just hours after it was disclosed at a news conference on
Monday, senior Commerce Department officials, who said they had
been unaware of the project, announced that they were halting the
fees pending a review of whether it conflicted with the
administration's policy of unrestricted access to government
information.
</P>
<P>
   David Seuss, Northern Light's president and chief executive,
said Wednesday that the company would offer free two-week trials of
the service while administration officials completed a review.
</P>
<P>
   A government spokesman, Morrie Goodman, said, ``We think it's
absolutely fine that they're offering the service for free,'' but
added that if the company instituted fees without administration
approval, ``we will have to rethink our partnership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
