<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN CHANCELLOR THREATENS TO VETO LAND WAR BY NATO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 17th graf starting: D'Alema is to meet, etc., to make it U.N.
Security Council resolution, etc.) (rm) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Allied divisions over using ground troops in
Kosovo burst into the open on Wednesday when Germany's chancellor
came to NATO and declared that his country would block the alliance
from fighting a land war.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is first and foremost a German position,'' said the
chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder. ``That position is also the present
position of NATO, and the strategy of an alliance can only be
changed if all the parties involved agree on it. I am against any
change of NATO strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   In blunt, caustic remarks at a news conference, Schroeder
derided Britain's position that the allies should consider a ground
force even without a peace agreement if NATO bombing pounds
Yugoslav troops to the point where they can offer only scattered
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not participate in this specifically British debate on
war theories,'' Schroeder said in response to a question from a BBC
correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   After fending off several similar questions, the chancellor
snapped, ``I have said everything that is to be said on this
particular issue and you will not get any more out of me if you go
on pestering me.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany has long opposed sending its own troops into combat in
Kosovo. But the threat from Schroeder to veto any ground force
without a settlement is new, and he sought to put more weight
behind his words by emphasizing that he was also speaking as
chairman of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's reservations about the course of the war in Serbia
were reflected by a vote on Wednesday in the Italian parliament,
committing the government to seek a halt in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   But though the debate in Rome was long and passionate, the
resolution does not bind Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema to lessen
Italy's longstanding support of NATO policy. Still, D'Alema
welcomed the resolution, and the vote was a clear sign of the
growing domestic opposition to the war that is bedeviling Italy as
well as other European governments that are generally committed to
the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference here, even before he took questions,
Schroeder insulted the United States: He implicitly challenged
Washington's official explanation for the bombing of the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade _ that target analysts relied on a faulty
street map _ by renewing his demand for a formal NATO inquiry into
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats here say Schroeder, who just returned from China, was
angry that a trip he had long planned to herald his chairmanship of
the European Union was transformed into an official apology for the
embassy bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-member alliance is at a critical crossroads: As time runs
out to prepare hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians to return
to their homes before winter, the allies are badly divided over the
timing and conditions for the use of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley K. Clark, NATO's military commander, on Wednesday
flew to Washington, where he is expected to brief Defense Secretary
William S. Cohen and Gen. Henry H. Shelton, the chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, on the military options, including both a
peacekeeping force and a land war.
</P>
<P>
   NATO originally envisioned a peacekeeping force of 28,000
soldiers, including 4,000 Americans. The allies' current thinking
is that they will need perhaps 50,000 troops to help police and
rebuild devastated villages in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   No country favors a full-scale invasion against organized
Yugoslav army resistance. But Britain insists that NATO must act
now to prepare for a possible ground attack against battered
Yugoslav troops, an environment military analysts call
semi-permissive.
</P>
<P>
   Greece, however, is urging the allies to suspend bombing for 48
hours as an incentive for President Slobodan Milosevic to
negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution passed by the Italian Parliament on Wednesday
urges a similar suspension, moving a step closer to a unilateral
cease-fire than D'Alema has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema is to meet the NATO secretary general, Javier Solana,
here on Thursday. Italy opposes sending ground troops now but has
left open the possibility of doing so if Belgrade balks at a peace
deal set up by a U.N. Security Council resolution. But the wording
of the Italian resolution was so ambiguous that it did not close
any options for D'Alema.
</P>
<P>
   NATO members are split largely because the United States is
sitting on the fence.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said on Tuesday that ``all options'' remained
open, but on the same day Schroeder contradicted him, saying that
sending in ground troops without a settlement is ``unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO diplomats whom Schroeder addressed in a closed meeting
before the news conference said the chancellor stressed the same
theme of maintaining the air attacks and diplomatic campaigns, but
made his points in more muted tones.
</P>
<P>
   American diplomats here said Schroeder's remarks were directed
more at his domestic audience than at the international community.
Thus it is unclear whether Germany would carry out its threat to
block a NATO force if the alternative were outright failure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion in favor of the air war has been slipping in
Germany at the same time that pacific strains in German politics
are resurgent.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party, a junior partner in Schroeder's government, has
become more vocal in opposing the bombing, leading to fears that a
severe split could bring down the fragile coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Milosevic wants to divide NATO. Belgrade's insistence
that it is willing to reach a diplomatic accord only exploits the
allied bickering over the dual-track strategy of diplomacy and war.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats from the seven leading industrial nations and Russia
met in Bonn Wednesday to work out draft language for a United
Nations Security Council resolution. The officials were briefed by
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbot, who had met for two days
with Finnish and Russian leaders in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian envoy, Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, on Wednesday flew to
Belgrade, where he demanded a halt in the air strikes and then
immediately went into a meeting with Milosevic. On Thursday, Talbot
and President Martii Ahtisaari of Finland are to meet Chernomyrdin
in Moscow to review the diplomatic approaches.
</P>
<P>
   But the alliance has staked out tough conditions for Milosevic
to meet before the air war ends, leaving NATO with little
negotiating room. One condition, for example, is that Milosevic
withdraw his 40,000 troops from Kosovo before the allies halt the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said Wednesday, however, that Germany would support a
compromise between that position and the Italian plan to suspend
bombing for 48 hours after a Security Council resolution was
approved.
</P>
<P>
   The allies may also have to sacrifice a possible indictment of
Milosevic for war crimes to negotiate a deal that ensures the
refugees' return before winter. ``That is such a primordial
objective of such primordial importance that all other
considerations fall by the way for a certain amount of time,''
Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters later, NATO's civilian spokesman, Jamie P.
Shea, insisted that the allies remained united in their goals and
opposed to any compromises of their key conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to offer any carrots,'' Shea said.
</P>
</TEXT>
