<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REPRESSION IN PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, May 20:
</P>
<P>
   For most of its history, Pakistan has been ruled by military
dictators. In the last 10 years, however, Pakistanis have managed
to break from their authoritarian traditions and enjoy the freedom
of elections and free speech. Now this trend is in peril, with the
arrest this month of a respected and outspoken journalist, Najam
Sethi, by the military's intelligence branch.
</P>
<P>
   Sethi's detention has brought justifiable condemnation from
human rights groups. The government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
says the army has authority to police acts of sedition and that
Sethi had ``suspected links to foreign intelligence agencies.'' But
no evidence has been presented. What appears to have rankled the
government, in fact, is a speech Sethi gave in India recently,
warning of the collapse of institutions in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   According to Amnesty International, Sethi's arrest has been part
of a pattern of intimidation and threats against critics, including
other prominent journalists and opposition spokesmen. Last week,
the chief judge of Pakistan's Supreme Court set up a panel to hear
a challenge to the arrest. Pakistan must urgently review this case,
stop trying to crack down on dissent and make it clear that its
civilian government, not the army, is in charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
