<HEADER>
A4124 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-RACING-SAFETY-NYT     05-19 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-RACING-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CARS MAY STILL FLIP, BUT THE TETHERED TIRES WILL NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just weeks after three spectators were killed when parts of a
race car were ejected into the stands, the second fatal incident
involving fans in nine months, Championship Auto Racing Teams is
taking steps to make the grandstand a safer place.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with next week's Motorola 300, CART will require its
teams to attach the cars' front wheels and other upright parts
(i.e., brake assemblies and bearings) to the chassis with a
high-strength tether. This ropelike device, which is made of
synthetic fiber, should prevent the wheels from being severed from
the car, thus preventing them from becoming deadly projectiles. The
technology was first applied by Formula One, Europe's premier
racing series, this season.
</P>
<P>
   In both instances where spectators were killed _ the first at
CART's U.S. 500 in Michigan last year and the other at the Indy
Racing League's VisionAire 500 in Charlotte, N.C., earlier this
month _ the carnage was caused by speeding wheels and suspension
parts that had become detached from the cars' chassis during a
crash and were then catapulted into the stands. Three people were
killed and several others injured at each of those races.
</P>
<P>
   ``These tethers are designed to keep the wheel and other
suspension parts captive during high-impact crashes,'' said Kirk
Russell, CART's vice president of competition. ``We've been looking
at wheel retention for many years and we're going to be doing all
four wheels eventually. But right now, parts supply is a problem as
we're doing all this very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell also said that even if the tether does break, the
velocity of the wheel would be reduced, whatever direction it might
fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Indy Racing League, the country's other major open-wheel
racing circuit and CART's rival, is considering similar changes but
has not announced a decision. Several recent reports suggest that
the IRL does in fact plan the use of tethers in the near future,
possibly for next week's Indy 500. There could be an announcement
next Thursday, the final practice before the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're vigorously studying those possibilities,'' said Ron
Green, an IRL spokesman. ``But not until we're convinced that we've
found a safe solution. When there is, we'll have an announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   It is believed that the IRL is not yet convinced tethers are
safe until further testing is completed. One concern is that the
tethers can become dangerous to the drivers, as they might cause
the wheel to sling-shot into the driver's head if not joined at the
right points.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said that CART has closely followed Formula One's
experience with the tethers and has concluded that the drivers are
not put at greater risk. ``The tethers will be installed so that
they don't allow the wheels to come toward the drivers,'' he said.
There have been incidents in Formula One racing when wheels have
come detached during crashes this season, however, none caused
injury.
</P>
<P>
   CART will adhere to Formula One's rule book, which mandates:
``In order to prevent a wheel becoming separated in the event of
all suspension members connecting it to the car failing, cables
must be fitted which connect each wheel/upright assembly to the
main structure of the car. Under such circumstances, the design of
the cable must be such that no wheel may make contact with the
driver's head. The cable must be flexible with a minimum diameter
of 8 mm.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the tethers, the IRL's biggest promoter, Speedway
Motorsports Inc., announced plans to increase the height of the
catch fences at its tracks, which should provide the fans with more
protection from detached wheels and other flying debris. The
additional fencing, which will be installed at Texas Motor
Speedway, Lowe's Motor Speedway and three SMI owned tracks among
the 11 where the IRL races are held every season.
</P>
<P>
   The move was prompted by the incident earlier this month at
Lowe's Motor Speedway at Charlotte, where three spectators were
killed and eight injured by a disconnected wheel and suspension
parts during a race May 1. The projected cost to increase the
height of the fences is between $1 million and $1.5 million,
according to SMI president H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler. The work will
begin at Texas Motor Speedway, the site of the IRL's Longhorn 500
on June 12.
</P>
<P>
   The fences at most of SMI's IRL tracks are currently 15 feet
high with 3-foot-long overhangs along the top. Wheeler said the
fences where spectators are seated will be raised to 21 feet and
topped with 6-foot-long overhangs. Wheeler said that based on the
evidence available to investigators, it would have been unlikely
the wheel could get past the new fence and its arched overhang.
</P>
<P>
   And while slowing the cars _ a CART car can reach speeds of 230
mph _ has been addressed at certain tracks, Russell said that these
changes require major changes. CART is looking at the possibility
but is not ready to consider any drastic changes, Russell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
