<HEADER>
A4126 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENSEMBLE-THEATER-2TAK     05-19 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENSEMBLE-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAWAKENING THE ART OF ENSEMBLE IN LONDON  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Benedict Nightingale is the chief theater critic of The Times of
London.  
 By BENEDICT NIGHTINGALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Liam Neeson, Juliette Binoche, Kevin Spacey, Nicole
Kidman, Ewan McGregor, Stacey Keach and, right now, Cate Blanchett
as a truculent ex-spy in a revival of David Hare's ``Plenty'': in
the last year or so, the London stage has come to look like a
stalker's den or autograph hound's lair, so marked is the fashion
for embellishing productions with Hollywood faces.
</P>
<P>
   But the odd small voice has been heard, asking what has happened
to the principle of ensemble acting, and that little chorus has
recently been joined by a large voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work can be the star, the company can be the star,''
declared Trevor Nunn, director of the Royal National Theater, in
March. And he has proceeded to prove his point with warmly received
revivals of Shakespeare's ``Troilus and Cressida'' and Leonard
Bernstein's musical version of Voltaire's ``Candide.'' These are
the opening offerings in a special season that by late summer will
consist of six plays, involve some 50 actors and run concurrently
with the other productions at the National.
</P>
<P>
   Is this really such a surprising event? After all, the National
began life 35 years ago with a smallish ensemble led by Laurence
Olivier. His successor, Peter Hall, briefly experimented with
mini-companies presenting mini-seasons organized by Alan Ayckbourn,
Ian McKellen and others.
</P>
<P>
   But under the National's last director, Richard Eyre, casting
was mostly ad hoc, and to a large extent it remains so under Nunn.
The regular program at the theater this summer includes revivals of
Noel Coward's ``Private Lives'' and John Osborne's ``Look Back in
Anger,'' Hanif Kureishi's new ``Sleep With Me,'' and Martin
Sherman's ``Rose,'' a one-woman play with Olympia Dukakis as a
Jewish-American survivor of persecution in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But when Nunn took over the National in 1997, he found himself
nostalgically remembering running the Royal Shakespeare Company in
the late 1960s and early 1970s, when its turnover of actors was far
less rapid than it is now. The idea of a ``democratic, libertarian,
egalitarian company presenting plays of great diversity,'' a
``group of actors working and progressing together, with give and
take,'' still struck him as an ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's a bit early to be talking of pure repertory and
egalitarian ideals, especially since 50 is a large number, company
members can obviously not act together in every play, and nobody
can yet be sure of the permanence of the enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   But Roger Allam, a stunning Ulysses in ``Troilus,'' will also be
seen in ``Money,'' Edward Bulwer-Lytton's play about Victorian
finance, and Gorky's ``Summerfolk.'' Simon Russell Beale, who
brilliantly doubles as Voltaire and Pangloss in ``Candide,'
appears in those plays, too. And those four, along with ``The
Merchant of Venice,'' are being staged by Trevor Nunn, John Caird
or, in the case of ``Candide,'' John Caird ``assisted by Trevor
Nunn.'' Only ``The Darker Face of the Earth,'' by the American poet
Rita Dove, which joins the repertory in July, has a different
director, James Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn and Caird were the team that brought the world not only
``Les Miserables'' but the RSC's celebrated ``Nicholas Nickleby.''
The imaginative simplicity that won such admiration for their
staging of Dickens marks their current productions, too. In Nunn's
revival of ``Troilus'' in the amphitheater of the Olivier, Greeks
in plumed helmets battle Trojans in Oriental robes on a red-gravel
circle backed by a plain timbered wall.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Candide'' in the same auditorium, the circle has become
black and shiny, and John Napier's decor consists of a series of
oak chests that are used, playroom-style, as boats, horses or
whatever else Voltaire's globe-trotting demands. Though each
production lasts more than three hours, neither can be faulted for
epic size, fluency or pace.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two, ``Candide'' has attracted more attention, mainly
because of its reputation as the masterpiece that began by
flopping, the classic that has always been a work-in-progress. It
would take the combined skills of a 19th-century textual scholar
and a 21st-century computer wizard to work out who contributed what
changes to the show between its Broadway opening in 1956, through
Harold Prince's vaudeville version in 1973 and Jonathan Miller's
1988 production for the Scottish Opera to Caird's current
refashioning of the text.
</P>
<P>
   The National program lists no fewer than six lyricists,
including Lillian Hellman, Dorothy Parker, Richard Wilbur and
Stephen Sondheim, the last two of whom have done extra work for the
National revival. I can't say who rhymed eat, sweet and greet with
spirochete for the song in which Dr. Pangloss justifies his
syphilis as part of God's plan; but I can report that it is
Sondheim who now asks Candide to sing, ``Though of noble birth I'm
not/ I'm delighted with my lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Candide is, of course, the innocent Westphalian whose faith in
Pangloss' philosophic credo, that ``All's for the best in the best
of all possible worlds,'' is tested by witnessing and enduring
evils galore, from the atrocities of war to the Lisbon earthquake.
And the main problem his adventures pose a would-be librettist is
that, as Wilbur once put it, they come in ``a one-joke novel that
goes on for 30 chapters.''
</P>
<P>
   How can you bring narrative coherence, consistency of tone and
dramatic variety to a picaresque satire that presents
disillusioning events galore? How can you accomplish that and keep
faith both with wry, dry Voltaire and with a rich, tuneful score
designed for the great fun house, Broadway?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that you can't, not altogether, and Caird's
production, which does not flinch from embracing sad deaths and
jokey resurrections, the horrors of the Inquisition and the
serenity of Eldorado, might be summed up as
ironical-comical-tragical-pastoral. His contribution to the
``Candide'' archives is to give us extra helpings of Voltaire's
story, Voltaire's arguments with Enlightenment optimism and, for
that matter, Voltaire himself.
</P>
<P>
   It is the constant presence of Russell Beale's formidable
Frenchman, exuding curt, incisive authority and acerbic compassion
as he paces and narrates, that gives the evening its unity and
moral stature.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Russell Beale is matched as a performer only by Russell
Beale. His face, shoulders and body sag, and suddenly he is a
droopily ingratiating Pangloss, earnest and self-important, when he
is arguing that God created noses to keep spectacles in place,
increasingly desperate and panicky as he convinces himself that the
same benign deity ordained his own sickness, torture and execution.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel Evans, his head jerking forward like a fledgling just
emerged from its egg, his vowels equally tentative and nervous, is
a splendidly susceptible Candide. And if Denis Quilley is too
genial for Pangloss' philosophic opposite, the arch-pessimist
Martin, the cast is as consistent as a company needs to be.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the singing is as professional as we now expect from a
theater that recently presented a near-definitive ``Oklahoma!''
Alex Kelly brings wit as well as a fine soprano voice to Candide's
corrupt love, Cunegonde, transforming ``Glitter and Be Gay'' from a
coloratura set piece into a hilarious sendup of avarice and
hypocrisy, in which she sensuously bathes in jewelry while boasting
of ``How bravely I conceal the dreadful shame I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   But though Bernstein's score embraces everything from tango to
martial music to church liturgy, the beat tends too often to become
the upbeat. The contrast between that and the horrors unfurling
onstage sometimes reinforces the evening's ironies; but, myself, I
would have preferred more Kurt Weill and less jaunty Sullivan among
Bernstein's influences.
</P>
<P>
   Only an auto-da-fe, with impassive prelates orchestrating the
chant for blood that rises from a smoky red swirl of jubilant
Spaniards, has the full harshness the original novella invites.
Similarly, it is odd that so faithful an adaptation as this ends
with Bernstein's soaring salute to the joys of building houses,
chopping wood and cultivating gardens, and makes no mention of the
fact that, though Candide's long pursuit of Cunegonde has ended in
marriage, she has become quarrelsome and hateful.
</P>
<P>
   Caird has taken an impressively large step toward giving us both
Bernstein and Voltaire _ but I'm not sure the tortuous history of
``Candide'' has yet reached a definitive close.
</P>
<P>
   Until World War I came to demolish any lingering faith in
chivalry, ``Troilus and Cressida'' was hardly ever seen on European
stages. But now that most people feel equally unromantic about sex
and love, it is hardly ever off them.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn's revival is the fourth I have reviewed in the last three
years, and the sparest and most direct. Nothing but disenchantment
is likely to occur in and outside this desolate Troy and, of
course, nothing does. Peter de Jersey's passionate Troilus is
betrayed by Sophie Okonedo's Cressida, a shallow extrovert who
ventures way out of her emotional depth and morally drowns.
</P>
<P>
   Dhobi Oparei's big, dignified Hector is sneakily slaughtered by
Raymond Coulthard's slick, sneery Achilles. And Nunn's ``Troilus''
ends, as Shakespeare's original didn't, with Cressida alone and
rejected on the battlefield, rouge smeared over her beaten, baffled
face, while gunfire splatters offstage.
</P>
<P>
   This addition to a text that otherwise sticks with swords,
shields and Shakespeare isn't Nunn's main surprise. He has also
cast white actors as the invading Greeks and, although Cressida's
Uncle Pandarus is played in camp, twittering style by a pink-hued
David Bamber, the besieged Trojans are black.
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to argue with this. Isn't it odd that a British
theater that has often and effectively asked us to blind our
imaginations to actors' color should so emphatically ask us to
notice it? Isn't it doubly strange when Shakespeare emphasizes
that, far from being a racial conflict, the Trojan War was a
harebrained quarrel within the same ethnic family? Yet at least
minority actors are getting opportunities they would not normally
expect, even at the National.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, their response is testimony to the British
theater's skill-in-depth and energy-in-breadth. But there is one
performance that virtually every reviewer has acclaimed, and it
comes from a white Greek. Ulysses seems a limited and limiting
role, partly because the character has a justified reputation for
being cerebral and sly, partly because he delivers the long
speeches that make the play intellectually challenging.
</P>
<P>
   But Roger Allam, uniquely in my experience, suggests that every
wile, every argument, emerges from a deep frustration and anger at
the war's endlessness. He brings heart and stomach to a
traditionally heady part.
</P>
<P>
   Is Allam's redefinition of Ulysses the finest piece of acting
that has recently materialized in London? Maybe. But admirers of
Miranda Richardson in Wallace Shawn's ``Aunt Dan and Lemon'' at the
Almeida and Sheila Gish in Tennessee Williams' ``Suddenly Last
Summer'' at the Comedy might think otherwise. So might fans of Cate
Blanchett, star of the movie ``Elizabeth,'' in Jonathan Kent's
revival of ``Plenty'' at the Albery.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever your feelings about the didactic thrust of a play that
traces the political disillusionment and personal decline of a
woman who finds fulfillment as a British agent in Nazi-occupied
France, you must admit it reinforces Hare's reputation for writing
strong, interesting roles for women.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Blanchett's Susan Traherne is stronger and more
interesting than either Kate Nelligan in the 1977 premiere or Meryl
Streep in the movie version. She looks like some majestic alabaster
statue, and her despairing husband often finds her chilling to the
touch; but inside the sleek translucence there are fierce, even
feral feelings.
</P>
<P>
   This is a woman who, as she says, ``Likes to lose control,'' a
destructive idealist, a rebel unable to do anything about the
conformism she despises except rage and rave and smash her
possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Blanchett gives us the elegant aloofness and the violence,
plus the odd, humanizing moment of bewilderment and vulnerability.
You can see why others love her. You also know why they fear her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-99 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
