<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4128 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUILLIARD-MUSIC-SCHOO     05-19 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUILLIARD-MUSIC-SCHOOL-3TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUILLIARD TRIES TO NURTURE WELL-TEMPERED ARTISTS  
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How do you get to Carnegie Hall? Practice hard, for
sure, but take care, too, that your mental and spiritual
development keeps pace with the physical and technical, to produce
a well-rounded individual and artist.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch; the old joke collapses like a souffle. Yet those, more or
less, are the directions the Juilliard School is giving to young
musicians, dancers and actors hoping to find their way to Carnegie
and other prestigious stages. How thoroughly these ideals may have
permeated the cold, angular spaces of the big marble block of a
school at the northern end of Lincoln Center, or the superheated
psyches of artists, whether teachers or students, is debatable, but
such, at least, is the stated policy.
</P>
<P>
   The architect of that policy, Joseph W. Polisi, who has been
president of the school since 1984, seems, in any case, little
given to humor. Charged with responsibility for 730 highly gifted
young artists, Polisi, at 50, earnestly and carefully discusses the
route the institution has traveled of late and where it may be
headed, obviously taking his job seriously indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quiet revolution,'' he called the changes, in response to the
characterizations of Joel Sachs, the contemporary-music specialist
(``permanent revolution''), and Stephen Clapp, who has been the
dean of the school since 1994 (``evolution'').
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the process, the path has not always been smooth, and
several longtime faculty members and administrators were left by
the wayside at various stages. Yet if the school has come to
reflect Polisi's personality at all accurately, it shows a deep
humanity at base, for the hallmark of his tenure has been an
evident concern for the physical, psychological and social
well-being of the students, perhaps best exemplified by
construction of the school's first dormitory, in the 29-story Rose
Building nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a different feel,'' Polisi said recently. ``I wanted
a place as wonderfully rigorous as it has always been in the values
and standards of the profession, but I also wanted an atmosphere
that was constructive and welcoming, in which it was safe to take
chances and form a very precise focus within a holistic approach.
We have consistently pushed the idea that we want young people to
grow intellectually as well as artistically.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not ever thus. For much of its 94 years, Juilliard, which
just finished its school year after triumphantly announcing ``the
largest capital campaign in the history of performing-arts
conservatories,'' was long the very model of the competitive,
hothouse environment of the old-line conservatory, where students
sought to develop the technical virtuosity that would insure a
great solo career (or so they thought), and cared about little
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Mennin didn't want a well-rounded student at all,''
Andrea Olmstead said of Polisi's immediate predecessor, who died in
1983. ``He wanted experts.'' Ms. Olmstead, who taught music history
at Juilliard from 1972 to 1980 and now teaches at the Boston
Conservatory, has written ``Juilliard: A History,'' a book
scheduled for publication by the University of Illinois Press this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Polisi would surely deny that Juilliard students' level of
technical expertise has in any way suffered from the heightened
emphasis he has placed on the liberal arts. The offerings are still
not extensive, short of the school's joint-degree program with
Columbia University, nor are the requirements.
</P>
<P>
   And although some teachers of performance feared at the outset
that any such initiatives would encroach on their students'
valuable time for practice and rehearsal, many now point out that
the brightest and most committed young performers are precisely the
ones likely to seek added stimulation in other fields of endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brains, and the use of them in different ways, is not
necessarily an enemy to musical talent,'' said Joel Krosnick, who
teaches cello at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Another powerful argument for change can be found in the
radically altered circumstances of the outside world, which can no
longer be ignored. Although the severity of the crisis facing
classical-music institutions, especially, may in some respects have
been exaggerated, grand isolation is no longer an option.
</P>
<P>
   With music education largely banished from the schools and
potential audience members indulging other demands on their time,
energy and finances, musicians must look to the future not only of
their careers but also of their profession.
</P>
<P>
   Juilliard now offers a course in ``The Business of Music.''
Polisi himself has taught ``American Society and the Arts'' or a
similar course since 1989. Even Dorothy DeLay, the renowned violin
teacher, who has trained any number of celebrated soloists and will
be joined on the faculty next year by her most famous pupil, Itzhak
Perlman, has instituted programs training students to teach others
and to handle their own concert management until they get their
professional feet on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few students will earn enough money as soloists to live
on,'' Miss DeLay said, acknowledging a growing reality that
conservatories have been slow to admit.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Miss DeLay's programs are among several that stand to benefit
from the campaign announced last month to raise $100 million over
five years. Nearly half of the money, $48 million, is intended for
scholarships. Juilliard now has to compete not only with
conservatories _ notably, the Curtis Institute in Philadelphia,
which offers free tuition for all 167 of its students _ but also
with universities offering stipends to performers much the way they
do to athletes.
</P>
<P>
   John Weaver, an organ teacher, cited the case of a promising
student who bypassed Juilliard and accepted an $8,000 stipend to
attend Yale University, Polisi's alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   With $51 million of the campaign already raised at the time of
the announcement, some new programs are already going ahead. For
one, all doctoral candidates, some 20 students, will receive full
scholarships starting in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Another major component of the campaign is $24 million allotted
to improve faculty compensation, which is famously low. ``I don't
know whether you can infer how pathetic salaries are compared to
university scales,'' said Milton Babbitt, who teaches composition
at Juilliard and has taught at Princeton University.
</P>
<P>
   The school appears to be in good financial health, with an
annual budget approaching $44 million set against an endowment of
$435 million. Virtually everyone credits Polisi with being an
excellent provider. Indeed, while some were fearing early on that
Juilliard was turning collegiate, with its rah-rah spirit and
liberal-arts thrust, it seems instead to have been turning
corporate and political, for good or ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe is an excellent politician,'' Sachs said. ``Not that he's
in it for political purposes, but he knows how to use politics to
serve the purposes of a great school.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Ewazen, a composer on the faculty, suggests that given all
the school's disparate divisions, departments, factions and
temperaments, Polisi's job may be the third-hardest in the world,
after the two commonly cited: president of the United States and
mayor of New York. Still, most faculty members seem to feel that
they, like the students, can get his attention when they need it.
Make a good case for a program, many say, and Polisi will soon get
behind it.
</P>
<P>
   That was Sachs' experience when he founded Focus, an annual
festival of contemporary music. (And those who say, as some do,
that Polisi can produce financial backing but not ideas, might note
that by Sachs' account, the two men arrived at the title Focus
independently, on the same morning, seemingly at the same moment.)
</P>
<P>
   Such was also the experience of Daniel Druckman, when he
introduced programs to give the percussion department greater
visibility, and Michael Czajkowski, when he expanded the music
technology program, in which all music undergraduates, using an
array of computers, now try their hands at electronic notation,
synthesis, sampling and recording.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff is so pervasive in the music business that we can't
have them leave here ignorant of it,'' Czajkowski said. ``They
don't have to like it, but they have to know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the harpsichordist Albert Fuller, who teaches
a course in historical performance, reports that he enountered a
brick wall when he proposed a broader program in early music: ``Joe
Polisi said, `I don't ever get input from the faculty,' so I sent
him a 20-page document. He told me that putting in early music
would be as difficult as turning around an aircraft carrier in the
Panama Canal. In the long run, historical understanding will
triumph, but, boy, it's a tough battle, and I've given up the
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   When such specialized subjects as early music, non-Western music
and jazz are raised, explanations usually fall back on size. They
would involve more students, more classes. And although Fuller
finds that the attitude ``bigger is better'' still prevails at
Juilliard, Polisi has in fact been scaling student enrollment down,
from 950 when he arrived to 730 this year. Pianists and violinists,
especially, have been cut back.
</P>
<P>
   Such actions are responses not only to an increasing awareness
of declining demand and opportunity in a glutted market worldwide
but also to an unhealthy pressure on the building, which was
designed for a mere 450. Still, Polisi says that 730 is a good,
workable number for the future. (The present number comprises 244
graduate students, all in music, and 486 undergraduates: 339 in
music, 79 in dance, 68 in drama.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to do anything that we can't do really well or
that we can't relate to everything else,'' Polisi said recently of
early music and world music. He even added to the heap, pointing
out that Juilliard has never had a choral program, either. But when
it came to jazz, he grew intriguingly evasive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could we talk in three months?'' he asked, going on to report
that he and the trumpeter Wynton Marsalis, who is a Juilliard
faculty and board member in addition to directing Jazz at Lincoln
Center, have given a lot of thought to the matter.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Marsalis, for his part, said, ``There definitely should be a
jazz program, and it's close.'' Given Polisi's concerns about
overcrowding, might there be some connection here to Jazz at
Lincoln Center's future space in Columbus Circle? ``No,'' Marsalis
said. ``Jazz at Lincoln Center will help administer the program,
but it will be at the Juilliard School.''
</P>
<P>
   When Polisi is not lending support to a new initiative, he is
said by many to give the faculty a free hand. ``We have a deal,''
Sachs said. ``I can program anything I want as long as he's allowed
to hate anything he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Polisi was, like his father, a professional bassoonist before
taking administrative positions at the Yale School of Music, the
University of Cincinnati College-Conservatory and the Manhattan
School of Music. The skepticism that greeted his arrival in 1984
undoubtedly stemmed in part from the fact that he was young (36)
and lacked credentials to rival those of composers who preceded
him, Mennin and William Schuman.
</P>
<P>
   A certain skepticism persists in some quarters. ``The change is
not all that great,'' said Babbitt of the Polisi era. ``I'm
enormously fond of Joe personally, but it was the move to Lincoln
Center that really changed attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet here, too, Polisi played a role. When Juilliard moved to its
new building in Lincoln Center in 1969, it nurtured some
ambivalence. Older faculty members spoke with nostalgia of the
lovable old building farther up Broadway, which now houses the
Manhattan School of Music. In addition, the gloomy entry opened
onto 66th Street, facing discreetly away from Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   Only in 1991, when Polisi had an expansive new entry built above
65th Street, opening onto Lincoln Center Plaza, did the marriage
seem complete. ``It was symbolic,'' said Eve Shapiro, who teaches
in the drama division. ``Suddenly there was light and vitality in
the building, and I feel that about Joseph Polisi's arrival.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pivotal construction project was surely the dormitory,
in 1990, which Polisi carried out in collaboration with Nathan
Leventhal, the president of Lincoln Center. Since all first-year
students are required to live there, and since music, dance and
drama students are mingled within each suite, it instilled a sense
of unity and common purpose to the campus for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   (On other floors, the dormitory houses students from the
American School of Ballet.) Students from the different divisions
became friends and attended one another's performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dormitory is Joseph Polisi's biggest contribution to the
school,'' said Ms. Olmstead, the Juilliard historian. ``It was the
dream of every previous president.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rose building is also home to an array of health services,
mental as well as physical, instituted or greatly expanded by
Polisi. This year, in addition, Don Greene, a sports psychologist,
was hired to conduct classes dealing with performance anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   As a frequent visitor to the school in recent weeks was
constantly reminded, there is more to Juilliard: the evening
division (which this writer attended through much of the 1970s),
the pre-college division, and the Music Advancement Program, for
students in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately the continued reputation of the school rides
primarily on its stars: students like Brian McWhorter, an excellent
trumpeter from Portland, Ore., working on his master's degree, who
seemed ubiquitous over a few recent days: performing part of a
Berio ``Sequenza'' in Sachs' 20th-century performance class,
playing the offstage trumpet in a rehearsal of Beethoven's
``Leonore'' Overture No. 3 with the Juilliard Symphony and
composing electronic music in Edward Bilous' film-scoring class. He
and other students seemed positively to revel in the variety of
pursuits available to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juilliard is more than I had hoped,'' said Masumi Per Rostad,
a violist from New York who won the school's concerto competition
this year and just received his bachelor's degree. ``I've been
having a great time, and it isn't at all like `Nothing but the
Best.'''
</P>
<P>
   The reference was to a gossipy earlier book on the school,
``Nothing but the Best: The Struggle for Perfection at the
Juilliard School,'' by Judith Kogan, from 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juilliard does not care how old its students are,'' Ms. Kogan
writes with typical, mildly amusing overstatement. ``Juilliard does
not care whether they can tie their shoes, crack an egg or boil a
pot of water. Juilliard does not care whether they can screw in a
light bulb, mend a fence or feed a cat. Juilliard does not seem to
care whether they can put an English sentence together either.
Juilliard cares about whether they can do one thing: perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, times change, and millenniums can do strange things.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
