<HEADLINE>
S.S. WEISGLASS, 70, INVESTMENT BANKER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla.)  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephen S. Weisglass, the executive managing director of Conifer
Securities, a San Francisco investment banking firm, died on Sunday
at his home in Miami. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was lung cancer, according to a statement
from the Owen Cheatham Foundation, a nonprofit organization headed
by his wife, Celeste, who survives him. Weisglass served as vice
president and treasurer of the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   A native of New York, he became president of Ladenburg Thalmann
&AMP; Co., a New York brokerage firm, in 1979. In 1986 he was named
Ladenburg's vice chairman. He left the firm seven years later, when
he went into semiretirement and moved to Miami. Prior to joining
Ladenburg, Weisglass worked for Bear, Stearns &AMP; Company.
</P>
<P>
   Weisglass was a graduate of McGill University in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by two stepsons, Kenneth
R. Kennerly of Jupiter, Fla., and Owen C. Kennerly of San
Francisco, as well as two step-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
