<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-19 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIE'S-AUCTION-NY     05-19 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIE'S-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDS SET FOR 11 ARTISTS IN CONTEMPORARY SALE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bidding was fast, furious and often surprising at
Christie's sale of contemporary art Wednesday night. Records were
set for 11 artists, and works often exceeded their high estimates
many times over.
</P>
<P>
   The sale totaled $9.5 million, just above its $9.4 million high
estimate. Of the 46 works offered, 41 sold.
</P>
<P>
   Energy ran high in the crowded Rockefeller Center salesroom as
bids rose. ``There was a totally new spirit in the salesroom last
night,'' said Philippe Segalot, head of Christie's contemporary art
department worldwide. ``The room was filled with many new bidders
and a few new buyers.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the sale, experts said a majority of buyers were
seasoned 20th-century collectors fighting for the chance to buy
works by younger artists. As it has for the last year, the auction
house confined its offerings in the contemporary art sale to works
from the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bidders had to fight. Among the hottest offerings was Robert
Gober's ``Untitled (Leg With Candle),'' a 1991 sculpture of a
section of a leg made from wax, human hair, leather, cotton and
wood. After a long, slow war among several unidentified telephone
bidders, as well as Anthony d'Offay, the London dealer, and Simon
de Pury, a Geneva private dealer, the sculpture eventually sold to
Segalot's telephone bidder, for a staggering $794,500, nearly twice
its high estimate of $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   During the bidding Segalot was seen looking up at a sky box
where Francois Pinault, owner of Christie's, was sitting. Many
people in the audience said after the sale that they could see the
two speaking. The Gober price was a record for the artist, topping
the $552,500 paid at Christie's in November.
</P>
<P>
   Another high price, though not a record, was paid for
Jean-Michel Basquiat's ``Self-Portrait as a Heel, Part 2,'' a 1982
painting depicting the artist with a face like an angry African
mask. Estimated at $400,000 to $600,000, it sold to an unidentified
telephone bidder for $772,500. Another Basquiat, ``Untitled''
(1987), brought a strong price, too: $552,500, right in the middle
of its estimate of $400,000 to $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   One of the evening's biggest casualties, though not
surprisingly, was Robert Ryman's `Signet 20'' (1965-66), an
all-white painting in thick horizontal strokes. Its estimate of
$1.5 million to $2 million was too high, and the work had been at
auction only a few years ago. Nobody was willing to pay more than
$1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Final prices include the auction house's commission, 15 percent
of the first $50,000 plus 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not
reflect commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Three bidders were determined to buy Andy Warhol's ``Untitled
(Rorschach Series),'' from 1984. The black-and-white painting sold
to an unidentified telephone bidder for $684,500, more than twice
its high estimate of $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many times collectors ignored estimates and just kept bidding.
For Christopher Wool's ``Untitled (Fool),'' from 1990, in which the
artist used letters as imagery, five bidders engaged in a serious
bidding battle. It finally sold to Thea Westreich, a Manhattan
dealer, for $420,500, seven times its high estimate of $60,000. The
price was a record for the artist.
</P>
<P>
   Another record was set for Richard Serra. ``Sign Board'' (1969),
a thin sheet of hardened lead propped up, was estimated at $100,000
to $150,000. Larry Gagosian, the New York dealer, bought the
sculpture for $431,500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
